<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-YANKEES-CO     10-27 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-YANKEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves lose Game 3 to Yankees 6-5 in 10th
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chad Curtis hit a solo home run in the bottom of the
10th inning Tuesday night, lifting the New York Yankees to an
improbable 6-5 victory over the Braves and a 3-0 lead in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' will try to close out their second straight Series
sweep tonight at Yankee Stadium, with Roger Clemens opposing the
Braves' John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves started Tuesday night by jumping to a 5-1 lead and
ripping into the notion that this World Series was over. Trouble
for them was, the Yankees didn't stop fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees saw the Braves offensive uprising and upped the
ante. After Atlanta's 12 hits produced a 5-1 lead, the Yankees
answered with their first four home runs of the series.
</P>
<P>
   The New York hitters took aim at the shallow right-field fence
at Yankee Stadium on homers by Chad Curtis, Tino Martinez and the
game-tying two-run shot from Chuck Knoblauch in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the 10th, Curtis homered to left field off Mike
Remlinger to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter Tom Glavine pitched valiantly despite feeling
weak from the after-effects of the flu. He gave manager Bobby Cox
the seven innings he had requested. The Braves led 5-3 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox sent him back out for the eighth inning and watched him
surrender a first-pitch single to Joe Girardi and fall behind
Knoblauch 2-0. Knoblauch then hit a drive to right that sent Brian
Jordan sprinting for wall. Jordan got a glove on the ball at the
top of the fence but it bounced out and over for the game-tying 5-5
home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who'd scored five runs off Yankee starter Andy
Pettitte, were stifled the rest of the way by the Yankee bullpen.
They managed only three hits off Jason Grimsley, Jeff Nelson and
Mariano Rivera and failed to score from the sixth through the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Their most painful failure was in the ninth after Bret Boone led
off with a single, his fourth hit of the game. But pinch runner
Otis Nixon was thrown out trying to steal second, Chipper Jones
struck out and Brian Jordan grounded out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, not too happy about being benched in Game 2, doubled his
first three times up, giving him for in a row counting a pinch-hit
double in the ninth inning of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   He set the tone for a rejuvenated Braves offense, which had had
seven hits in 58 at-bats (.121) in the first two games. They came
back with seven hits in their first 15 trips to the plate on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Their two hits off Pettitte in the first inning equalled their
hit total against Yankees starters Orlando Hernandez and David Cone
in each of the first two games. Seven of the nine hitters in the
Braves lineup were hitless coming into Tuesday night's game. By the
time Walt Weiss singled to right field in the fifth inning, all
seven of those batters had collected hits.
</P>
<P>
   And this was against Pettitte, who was the Yankees best pitcher
in the second half of the season with a 3.84 ERA to go along with a
9-4 record. He had won both starts of this postseason, allowing
only three earned runs in 14 2/3 innings in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine was trying to use the eighth start of his World Series
career for a little payback for his seventh. His last World Series
start had come in Game 3 of the 1996 series against the Yankees,
the first of four consecutive losses by the Braves that saw their
2-0 disintegrate in the third World Series loss of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   He was cruising toward doing just that when Curtis, hitless in a
dozen career at-bats against Glavine, stepped to the plate in the
fifth inning. Glavine had retired 13 of the last 14 Yankee batters,
but grooved a fastball come over the heart of the plate, and
watched Curtis turn on it to cut into the Braves lead 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez got in on the act with a homer to right field two
innings later.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
