<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-1STLE     10-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE WAR OVER PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 6th graf (bgng `The second school...') to add comparison with
less moderate Republicans.) (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to make sense of the current foreign policy debate
in America, think of it like this: The key to the 20th century is
not the three world wars (I, II and the Cold War) that punctuated
it, but rather how we designed the peace that followed these wars.
The peace of Versailles was mishandled. The peace after World War
II was well managed. Remarkably, what Republicans and Democrats are
still debating today is how, and how much, America should shape the
post-Cold War peace.
</P>
<P>
   In 1919 and 1945, notes Fareed Zakaria, managing editor of
Foreign Affairs, ``America wanted to change the world, and the
world was reluctant. But in 1999, the world is eager to change _
along the lines being defined by America _ but now America is
reluctant.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if you look at the world that has developed since the
end of the Cold War, ``it is based in many ways on our ideas, our
values and our products _ yet we are ambivalent about recognizing
this world as our child, so we behave at times like deadbeat
dads,'' argues the political scientist Robert Pastor, whose new
volume, ``A Century's Journey: How the Great Powers Shape the
World,'' is an extremely thoughtful examination of great-power
politics.
</P>
<P>
   This U.S. ambivalence derives from the fact that while America's
victory in the Cold War was decisive _ it eliminated any
ideological alternative to free-market capitalism and any
superpower alternative to U.S. power _ it was not complete. America
did not occupy the countries it defeated in the Cold War, a la
Germany and Japan. Therefore our ability to reshape Russia or China
is limited, and their ability to obstruct us _ either by their
weakness or their strength _ still exists.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, you can see three schools forming in the U.S.
debate. First are the ``Nutty and Energetic Republicans.'' This is
an unholy alliance of old Cold Warriors, extreme isolationists and
unilateralists, and outright fools. What binds them is a belief
that America today is overwhelmingly powerful, therefore it can
preserve a post-Cold War peace either by ignoring the world or
acting unilaterally upon it. Because they are so focused inward,
these people spurn the United Nations, even though it is ready to
do our bidding and share our burdens.
</P>
<P>
   The second school is the ``Serious but Timid Republicans,'' who
actually offer an intelligent critique of the Clinton approach to
post-Cold War peace but are often outshouted by the GOP nuts. They
agree the United States should spread free-markets, engage China
and confront tyrants like Saddam Hussein and Slobodan Milosevic.
But this group's critique of the Clinton team is that it has relied
too heavily on multilateral approaches and treaties rather than on
hard-headed U.S. power, and that it has focused far too much on
smaller problems _ Haiti, Ireland and the Balkans _ and mismanaged
the big ones _ Russia, China and arms control.
</P>
<P>
   The third school is the ``Serious but Lazy Democrats.'' These
are the Clintonites. They have the right instinct _ that the
post-Cold War peace should be focused on sustainable globalization.
They understand that today's system of globalization greatly
benefits the United States, because it is our ideas, products and
people that are being most globalized. Therefore, the way to build
a post-Cold War peace is by using U.S. power to keep this system
stable, by using U.S. leverage to widen the circle of democracies,
and by using U.S. prosperity to widen the group of people who
benefit from globalization. They also understand that we can't
manage such an integrated system alone, and if we try we will
stimulate a coalition against us.
</P>
<P>
   But while they have all the right convictions, the Lazy
Democrats have the courage of those convictions only about half the
time. In Kosovo, they stuck to their guns; they did the same with
Nafta. But in April, when a deal to bring China into the WTO was
possible, they walked away because they didn't want to fight with
congressional Democrats and had not prepared the ground in advance.
Same with the Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Test Ban Treaty, WTO, U.N. dues, all failed,'' said
Pastor, ``because the nutty Republicans and the serious ones came
together. Unless the President forms a new coalition between the
serious Republicans and serious Democrats, America will not be able
to forge a post-Cold War peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
