<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-N     10-27 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YANKEES COME OFF THE MAT TO TRIUMPH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT27,31,32,37,38,39,40,42,43,44,45 _ are being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre was not sure whether he would play Chad
Curtis in Game 3 of the World Series on Tuesday night. Maybe it was
a better idea to start Ricky Ledee instead; Curtis, after all, had
not had a hit in 13 career at-bats against the Atlanta starter Tom
Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis started, however, slugged a home run off Glavine in the
fifth inning, and when he led off the 10th _ two innings after
Chuck Knoblauch had tied the game with a two-run home run off
Glavine _ Curtis slammed a game-winning home run off Mike
Remlinger, to give the Yankees a 6-5 victory and a commanding lead
of three games to none in the four-of-seven-game World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will now have four chances to clinch their 25th
championship and their third title in four years. No team has ever
rebounded from a 3-0 deficit in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Yankees' 11th consecutive World Series victory, one
shy of the record.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' John Smoltz will pitch Game 4 on Wednesday night
against the Yankees' Roger Clemens, who lasted two innings in his
last start, in Game 3 of the American League Championship Series.
Clemens was injured in that game, teammates say, most likely
hurting his back, and only Clemens _ who approaches baseball and
pain the way a middle linebacker might _ knows how that might
effect him on Wednesday night; he would not discuss the injury on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger relieved for the Braves to start the bottom of the
10th. Curtis fouled off a pitch, took a ball high, then ripped a
pitch over the wall in left field. Curtis threw up his arms as soon
as he made contact, and his teammates burst from the dugout to
greet him, while Remlinger and the other Braves walked off the
field disconsolately.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine had been scratched from his Game 1 start because of a
stomach virus that ultimately robbed him of about five pounds.
Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox said before the game that he hoped to get
``seven good innings'' from Glavine, and Glavine delivered that,
allowing only five hits; the Braves led, 5-3, after seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   There had been signs that Glavine was losing his stuff _ Curtis
homered in the fifth inning, after 14 hitless at-bats in his career
against him, and Tino Martinez homered in the seventh _ and both
Remlinger and John Rocker were warming up as the eighth inning
began. But Glavine had averaged about 10 pitches an inning and Cox
stuck with him, who with Smoltz and Greg Maddux has been the heart
of the team for the last decade. The Braves needed to win on
Tuesday night and Cox entrusted the lead to Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Girardi lined a single to the opposite field _ a hitting
adjustment made by both teams _ and Knoblauch came to the plate as
the potential tying run. He had hit the ball hard twice in three
previous at-bats. Cox stuck with Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   And Knoblauch bashed a high drive to right field, where the
Braves' Brian Jordan ran back toward the wall. The 56,794 fans at
Yankee Stadium stood, many Yankees leaped out of their dugout to
follow the flight of the ball into the right-field corner. Jordan
jumped, reached back over the fence, the ball went into his glove _
and then dropped out, bouncing into the stands. Home run. Knoblauch
soared around the bases, the game tied.
</P>
<P>
   Cox then called on Rocker, who was jeered heavily by fans, and
Derek Jeter blooped a single to center. Paul O'Neill, who had not
executed a bunt in his seven-year tenure with the Yankees, tried to
drop a bunt, popped up and stood at home plate momentarily, angry
at himself. Seeing this, the Braves' Brian Hunter allowed the ball
to fall, then threw to second to start a double play; because of
his failure to run out the play, O'Neill was thrown out at first.
The game was tied into the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera relieved, Bret Boone singled and Otis Nixon
pinch-ran. He tried to steal second, but Girardi threw him out,
celebrating with a pump of his fist, and justifiably so. The last
time a runner had been thrown out stealing with Rivera pitching was
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took extra batting practice Monday, each hitter
getting about 50 swings and a chance to linger in the cage and
focus on specific adjustments. Cox watched them swing and said he
thought his hitters gained confidence from the extra session.
</P>
<P>
   But practicing and applying are two different matters entirely,
and hitters from both teams were faced with similar adjustments on
Tuesday night. Both Glavine and Andy Pettitte pitch in the same
manner, attacking the outside corner when facing right-handed
batters, throwing low and outside time after time. Hitters often
stubbornly try to pull those pitches to left field and wind up
chopping ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment that right-handed hitters from both teams tried
was to punch or drive the ball to the opposite field, and the
Braves _ whose aggressiveness often overcomes them _ executed this
adjustment exceptionally.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams reached out and dumped a single to right field
leading off the game, before Bret Boone ripped a line drive to
right field; Boone's drive created a divot in the padding of the
right-field fence, only a foot or so from the top of the wall, and
Boone had a double, with Williams stopping at third. The Braves
mustered three hits in the first 17 innings of the World Series,
and they had two right away on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones grounded to third, and as Williams started home,
Scott Brosius, the Yankees' third baseman, reached out to field the
ball, intending to throw to the plate. It appeared as if he would
have nailed Williams easily. But Brosius dropped the ball, and from
his knees his only play was to throw to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte labored to keep Atlanta from scoring more runs in the
inning, at a cost of 26 pitches, and it was as if the early Braves'
hits made him tentative, which happened to him often in the first
four months of the season. Of the first 19 batters Pettitte faced
in this game, he threw a ball on the first pitch to 11, falling
behind in the count right away. Pettitte twice faced Walt Weiss,
the Braves' weak-hitting No. 9 batter, and both times Pettitte fell
behind in the count, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied the score in the bottom of the first, using the
adjustment, driving the ball to the opposite field: Jordan failed
to catch Knoblauch's line smash, the ball dropping out of his
glove, and O'Neill punched a game-tying single to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Boone again drove a double to the wall in right-center field
leading off the third inning, advanced to third base on a ground
ball and scored when Jordan slapped a single to right. Andruw Jones
blooped a single to left, and when Jose Hernandez pulled a double
into the left-field corner, Jordan and Jones both scored. Braves 4,
Yankees 1.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte took off his hat and wiped the sweat from his brow, and
Jason Grimsley was throwing in the Yankees' bullpen. Pettitte
didn't seem long for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   After Gerald Williams hammered a triple off the center-field
wall _ it appeared Bernie Williams misplayed the ball at the fence
and probably should have caught the ball _ Boone hit his third
double, into the left-field corner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
