<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PARAGUAYAN TO BE OUSTED
</P>
<P>
   In his first foreign policy announcement as president-elect,
Fernando de la Rua advised former Gen. Lino Oviedo of Paraguay,
exiled in Argentina since March when he was accused of
masterminding the assassination of his country's vice president,
that he will no longer be welcome. Oviedo's presence has caused
serious diplomatic friction.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: LEADER TIED TO CAMPAIGN INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   A criminal court judge has ordered President Jamil Mahuad to
testify in an investigation into allegations that contributions to
his election campaign last year were diverted and has also issued a
writ for the arrest of Ramon Yulee, who was Mahuad's campaign
treasurer. The actions were taken after a prominent banker, jailed
since July on charges that he had misused bank funds, said a
donation of $3.1 million that he made to Mahuad's run was never
declared.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: PRISON CHIEF FIRED
</P>
<P>
   The director of the country's largest prison was dismissed after
news reports that Marxist guerrillas in custody at a jail in Bogota
have been allowed to hold military exercises and political
indoctrination classes. Television footage showing members of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia engaged in such drills led
to a national outcry.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TALKS REOPENING
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. George J. Mitchell returns to Belfast Wednesday to
complete his effort, now in its eighth week, to break the stalemate
over guerrilla disarmament blocking progress in carrying out the
peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: CRAXI AILING
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Bettino Craxi, now a fugitive from justice
in Tunisia, was in intensive care in a Tunis hospital after
suffering from heart trouble. Craxi, 65, a Socialist whose career
collapsed under a wave of corruption scandals in the early 1990s,
went into exile in 1994. In 1996 he was convicted by Italy's
highest court of illegal financing of political parties.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: TANK COMPROMISE
</P>
<P>
   German leaders have reached a compromise on the delivery of a
Leopard II battle tank to Turkey. In a concession to the Greens,
who say the delivery breaks coalition agreements not to send
weapons to countries with questionable human rights records, the
Krauss Maffei Wegmann company will be allowed to deliver one tank
with a special precision cannon to Turkey for a year's test run.
Turkey is seeking to buy around 1,000 tanks worth about $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: U.S. MONEY SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak said at a news conference with Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen that Israel was not only counting on
promised U.S. financial aid to carry out the Wye River peace deal
but also ``already spending this money.'' During the U.S.-brokered
talks in Wye, Md., President Clinton pledged $1.2 billion to Israel
but Congress has since rejected the appropriation. ``We are working
with the Congress'' to secure the aid, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: 2 KEY APPOINTMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Barak made two important and long-awaited
appointments. He picked David Ivri, the national security council
director and a former air force commander, as ambassador to
Washington. And he appointed Oded Eran, ambassador to Jordan and a
veteran diplomat, to head the final status negotiations with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: 4 PAKISTANIS SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   The army said it had repelled Pakistani infiltrators in Kashmir,
killing four soldiers. Such incidents are not unusual in the
mountainous terrain near the Line of Control, but this was the
first report of serious fighting since a military coup in Pakistan
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: U.S. TALKS TO REOPEN
</P>
<P>
   High-level talks between External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh
and the U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott will be
resumed in the next few weeks, the Indian government announced.
Those talks, largely about India's nuclear weapons abilities, were
derailed by political instability in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: WARNING ON ARMS
</P>
<P>
   Combatants voluntarily disarming under a peace agreement to end
an eight-year civil war were warned that they must surrender their
weapons to receive a $300 cash incentive. Since disarmament began
last Wednesday, some rebels arriving at a disarmament camp near
Freetown have not brought their weapons, claiming they had been
confiscated. A West African peacekeeping force leading the
disarmament process fears that the rebels may be hiding weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
