<HEADER>
A9543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-MONAHAN-NYT &LR;      10-27 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MONAHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 MSGR. JEREMIAH MONAHAN, 65, NEW YORK ARCHDIOCESE'S CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Msgr. Jeremiah P. Monahan, who as chancellor of the
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York served as steward of the
church's secular affairs, including financial matters, construction
projects and administration, died Monday at a hospital in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor, who was 65, entered the New York Weill Cornell
Center of New York Presbyterian Hospital on Monday complaining of
chest pain. Results of an autopsy were not available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, the archbishop of New York, who is
recuperating from treatment for a brain tumor, issued a statement
saying, ``At 7 o'clock in the morning he shared breakfast with
those of us of the archbishop's residence in which he lived; at
about 10 o'clock at night we learned of his death.''
</P>
<P>
   Monahan had been chancellor since 1997, working in a post
O'Connor described Tuesday as bearing ``the enormous
responsibilities of guiding the financial and administrative
support of this vast archdiocese, one of the largest and most
complex in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zwilling, the spokesman for the archdiocese, said, ``He
oversaw the nearly 1,000 people who work in the Terrence Cardinal
Cooke Catholic Center, the administrative headquarters of the
archdiocese, and had the final say on any human resources policies
affecting employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the 413 individual parishes control their budgets, ``he
oversaw every departmental budget and set policies to make sure
that the money was administered properly and efficiently,''
Zwilling said. Annual revenues are about $545 million; expenditures
about $527 million.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Manhattan, Monahan was educated at Cardinal Hayes High
School in the Bronx, Cathedral College Seminary in Manhattan and
St. Joseph's Seminary in Yonkers. He was ordained by Cardinal
Francis Spellman in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Though he served as pastor of several churches in the city and
suburbs early in his career, he spent most of it as an educator,
first as an English teacher at Cardinal Hayes High School in the
Bronx and then as its dean of discipline. He was revered for
opening up the world to students who knew only their tough
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 he became principal of Cardinal Spellman High School,
also in the Bronx, where he made his mark as a fund-raiser, among
other things.
</P>
<P>
   He became a monsignor in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor is survived by three sisters, Patricia Paoli of
Manhattan, Agnes O'Donohue of Burbank, Calif., and Catherine
Lessuck of Port Reading, N.J., and a brother, Andrew Monahan of
Yonkers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLEMENTE-NYT &LR;      10-27 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEMENTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLEMENTE AND THE WEIGHT OF GESTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, October
27:
</P>
<P>
   There is always something disembodying about the hours spent in
an art museum. The substantive world rises up around you in bronze,
marble, porcelain and wood, in the interlaced texture of paper, the
rough surface of paint. And yet it is all held at a distance,
intangible except to the eye. Even abstract painting makes a
gestural appeal to the body, which nearly always goes unanswered by
the viewer. Deep taboo is what keeps you from fondling a Brancusi
or running your fingers over the strands of pigment that wind
through a Pollock. If you like, you may face Ingres' portrait of
Ferdinand-Philippe-Louis-Charles-Henri, Duc d'Orleans, now visiting
the Metropolitan Museum in New York, and try to capture in your own
posture the hauteur of that regal left arm. But you may not even
think about rubbing the frame.
</P>
<P>
   The place where a sense of disembodiment strikes hardest right
now is the Guggenheim Museum and its retrospective of Francesco
Clemente's work, which will hang until Jan. 9, 2000. It is always
tempting to impute a feeling of disequilibrium to the works being
exhibited at the Guggenheim. Usually it is just the architecture
talking, the viewer's feet and legs grappling as they ramp uphill
or down while the eye, with the paintings for reference, tries to
sort out the true geometry of the place from its inherent spiral.
</P>
<P>
   But something else is going on too. From the ancient global
archive of figural representations, Clemente draws on a vision of
the body in which its mass, so to speak, is its momentum, the
weight of the flesh reduced to gesture. He rarely suggests the
dimensionality _ the rotund worldliness _ that is so much a part of
Ingres' work. Space is not the context in which Clemente imagines
the human figure. The body no longer stands apart from its world,
towering into the foreground like the subject of one of Ingres'
remarkable portrait-drawings _ Charles-Francois Mallet, for
instance, who seems to loom halfway out of the frame. Instead,
Clemente's paintings invoke the body's apertures, the places where
we are ported into the world or the world into us. The eye is still
foremost among those apertures, but not as singly graced as it once
was.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the viewer is admitted to Clemente's sensory, mythic
dance only by eye. We stand there, gazing, resolved in our own
foreground, more like Ingres' Mallet than like the entwined,
gold-leaf figures in ``Usary of Love'' or the synoptic, caged beast
in ``Unborn.'' But the strength of Clemente's work is not only its
material prodigiousness and the near-surfeit of symbolic relations.
It is also its ability to make the viewer feel naked and clothed,
feral and aloof at the same time, poised on weary bones before
another painting and yet caught somehow in an elemental embrace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
