<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE BACK ON SCORING TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After going without a point for four games, Luc
Robitaille appears to have regained his scoring touch.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, whose drought came after being named the first NHL
Player of Week of the young season, has goals in two consecutive
games and nine for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Against San Jose on Sunday, Robitaille scored his fifth power
play goal, tying him with the Sharks' Owen Nolan for the league
lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period Tuesday against Washington, Robitaille
redirected a blast from the point from Aki Berg to cut the Capitals
lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was classic Robitaille, positioning himself in front of the
net and poking it past goalie Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I've ever seen Luc score a goal beyond two
feet,'' Kings coach Andy Murray said with a grin. ``He is a scorer.
Period. He can smell them.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in close to the opposing net can take its toll
physically. After several off years, Robitaille has improved his
conditioning the past few seasons and responded with 39 goals in
1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be pretty grinding in there,'' Robitaille said. ``It
became clear that if I was going to stay in there, I had to do
something. The other teams are getting bigger all the time. But the
work has paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's goal was the 526th of his 14-year NHL career.
Sunday, he passed Bryan Trottier for 21st place all-time. He did
not score his ninth goal last season until Nov. 10, the Kings 15th
game.
</P>
<P>
   __ What's in Storr: Goaltender Jamie Storr made his first start
in nearly three weeks and gave up a short-handed goal in the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings defense stiffened in the second and Storr didn't
face a shot for the first 11 minutes of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Watching closely was the Kings goaltending consultant Don
Edwards, who worked extensively with Storr during the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been very helpful for me,'' Storr said. ``He is not
only a good guy and a good coach, he is a friend who is very good
at making adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' role with the team has changed dramatically since last
season, when he was a full-time assistant for former coach Larry
Robinson. Edwards said the adjustment often has been difficult but
said he does not regret turning down assistant offers last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter is in high school and I didn't feel like I wanted
to do that to the family,'' said Edwards, who lives in El Segundo.
``I like working with these guys. They like to hard work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
