<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHERE HAVE YOU GONE, MELVIN MORA? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Watching the 1999 Atlanta Braves morph into the 1998
San Diego Padres in this World Series, I cannot help but think
about Melvin Mora, the overnight sensation, after nine years in the
bushes, who became the Mets' surprise weapon in the last weeks of
their season.
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves were blowing their lead on Tuesday night, and
losing to the Yankees, 6-5, on Chad Curtis' homer in the 10th
inning to fall three games down in this now terminal World Series,
my thoughts meandered to what the World Series might have been like
if Senor Mora were roaming the outfield, wherever Bobby Valentine
needed him.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't Mora and the other Mets have done as well the Braves
have done? On Tuesday night the Braves had a 5-1 lead with a
pitcher, Tom Glavine, just getting over a debilitating flu. Bobby
Cox let Glavine pitch into the eighth, by which time the Yankees
had tied the score on three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Since being leveled Friday night, Glavine had barely begun to
eat. Soup and crackers may not be the right diet to face the Bronx
Brutes. Then there is the question of whether Glavine's illness
threw off Greg Maddux and Kevin Millwood, both of whom had to move
up their starts by a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're logging a lot of innings by this time of year,'' Cox
said on Tuesday night. ``You're not getting much sleep. But you're
not tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday night, there was still the possibility that
the Braves would bounce back. After all, the Yankees had lost the
first two games of the 1996 World Series at home _ and have now won
11 straight World Series games. No team has ever come back from a
3-0 deficit in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have never got untracked. Watching balls whisk past
and under and through the double-play combination of Ozzie Guillen
and Keith Lockhart Sunday evening, I felt the Mets' middle
infielders would not have given the Yankees a seven-run head start.
</P>
<P>
   The manager needed some runs Sunday, so he benched Walt Weiss to
get Guillen's bat in the lineup. But with all due respect, I came
down with a serious flashback to the mid-80s when Davey Johnson
would stick Howard Johnson at shortstop instead of Rafael Santana,
thereby throwing off the entire Mets defense. Ever since, I have
taken the position that shortstop is too important a position to
tinker with.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss was back on Tuesday night, and so was the regular second
baseman, Bret Boone, contributing three doubles and a single, but
it is quite possible that the Yankees are simply too good, what
with their patience, their key hits, their base running, their
resourceful starters, their fine tandem of catchers. Just
everything.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are not perfect _ as the movie said, there's no
perfection in baseball _ but they do enough things right that it
has been a pleasure to watch them. Then again, the Braves were
comatose at home, and there's no excuse for that. Maybe the series
with the Mets took something out of them, although that is not
supposed to happen in a sport of technique rather than a sport of
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night there was the scenario of Yankee fans meeting
John Rocker, a marriage made in heaven or some otherworldly place.
The Yankee fans began chanting at him the moment he went to the
bullpen. He never responded, and got the Braves out of trouble in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees going ahead by three games, I can't help but
think the Mets would have given the Yankees a better fight in those
first two games in a pumped-up Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   I was originally concerned about a Subway Series (in our New
York grandiosity, we capitalize it), but maybe it would not have
been so bad, after all.
</P>
<P>
   I had been afraid of fighting in the aisles of the stadiums,
given the thuggish behavior of New York fans toward Boston and
Atlanta visitors in the first round. But even an 80-20 split in the
two New York stadiums would have neutralized the tough guys who
preyed on lone Braves and Red Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night I didn't happen to see anybody beating up on
Braves fans. But then again, I didn't see anybody brave enough to
wear Braves garb. It's not worth dragging out the regalia on
Wednesday night. The Yankees and their fans can smell victory.
They've got their Chad Curtis. Baseball fans can only dream of the
better series that might have taken place with Melvin Mora _ that
reincarnation of Mickey, Willie and the Duke roaming the outfield
in a Subway Series. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
