<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES GO DEEP, NEAR REPEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Braves manager Bobby Cox expected Tom Glavine to
pitch seven strong innings last night.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that twice before the game, and he was right.
Glavine was sufficiently recovered from the flu to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cox got greedy, and it will likely cost him the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine gave up a game-tying two-run homer to Chuck Knoblauch in
the eighth inning, and Chad Curtis smacked a 10th-inning home run
off Braves reliever Mike Remlinger, lifting the New York Yankees to
a 6-5 victory in Game 3 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling,'' Curtis said. ``I don't think I've ever
hit a walk-off \Rgame-ending\S home run in the regular season.
Somewhere between second and third, electricity was running through
my legs. Rounding third, seeing my teammates at home plate in a
World Series, it was special.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis hit two of the four home runs that allowed the Yankees to
erase the Braves' 5-1 lead and go up 3-0 in the Series and close in
on repeating as world champions. As the Braves remember from the
National League Championship Series, no team in major-league
history has ever lost the first three games of best-of-seven series
and came back to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big one to lose,'' Cox said. ``We were on our way
to getting right back into this. We lost a tough one in Game 1,
too. We could have been up 2-1 rather than down 3-0.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, threatening to pump some life in the Series, led 5-1
through four innings. But the Yankees stayed close, getting solo
home runs from Curtis in the fifth and Tino Martinez in the seventh
to make it 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, working with economy of effort, had thrown only 72
pitches through seven innings, a low number for starting pitchers,
and given up five hits. But he was also coming back from the flu,
which forced the Braves to scratch him from his Game 1 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Glavine was throwing great,'' Cox said. ``I know
everybody is going to ask me why I left him, but he didn't want to
come out. I asked him, and he said no. \RPitching coach\S Leo
Mazzone said he was throwing great, Tommy said he was throwing
great and I thought he was throwing great. We thought he would
breeze through the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Joe Girardi led off the eighth with a single to
right, but Cox, even with closer John Rocker ready in the bullpen,
stayed with Glavine. Knoblauch took two balls, then hit a high fly
ball down the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   Braves right fielder Brian Jordan got back to the wall near the
314-foot sign and made a leaping attempt. He did get his glove on
it as he reached over the wall but he couldn't hold it. The ball
popped loose for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pop-up,'' Glavine said. ``It wouldn't have gone out of any
other park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I hit it in Yankee Stadium,'' Knoblauch retorted. ``I
was just trying to hit it hard. I got good wood on it and hit it
far enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker got the Braves out of the eighth and through the ninth
inning. But Yankees closer Mariano Rivera also pitched two
scoreless innings, giving Curtis his chance against Remlinger in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   He made good by blasting a 1-1 pitch over the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge what he did tonight,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``We're not home run hitters, but sometimes those things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, perhaps helped by extra batting practice on Monday's
off-day workout, went to work early on Yankees starter Andy
Pettitte, hammering him for five runs in 3 2/3 innings. Bret Boone
had a three doubles and Jose Hernandez also had a two-run double,
giving the Braves a 5-1 lead
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down 5-1, and it was a little quiet in our dugout,''
Torre said. ``Then Chad hit one out and things picked up. We don't
quit. We're grinders. We play nine innings. The highest compliment
I can give this team is they play nine innings. When you do that,
good things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine looked sharp enough to keep that from happening. He did
it for seven innings. The eighth inning did him in. The Braves will
have a whole winter to ponder that.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
