<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     10-27 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPROTS COLUMN: FOR YANKS, A CLOSER WHO IS TAKEN FOR GRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before he warms up in the Yankee bullpen, Mariano
Rivera picks up a lead ball that weighs between two and three
pounds. Holding it in his right hand, he swings it around and
around, across his body, up and down for a few minutes. It makes a
real baseball seem lighter and smaller. And to the hitters he faces
after arriving at the mound, it's as if he were throwing that lead
ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves discovered that on Tuesday night when Rivera spun the
last two innings as the Yankees won, 6-5, in the 10th inning on
Chad Curtis' second homer for a 3-0 bulge in a World Series that
could end on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Panamanian right-hander known as Mo has posted numbing
numbers in this post-season: 7 appearances, 11 innings, 9 hits, 0
runs, 9 strikeouts, 1 walk, 0.00 earned run average, 5 saves, 2-0
record.
</P>
<P>
   Counting his last 28 appearances in a regular season in which he
had 45 saves and a 1.83 era, he has not allowed a run in his last
412/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the various positions a baseball team must fill in
assembling a winning team, a bullpen ``closer'' is the most
coveted. Without a quality closer, no team can expect to preserve
enough victories to win a division, a pennant or a World Series.
And of all the current closers, Rivera is so good now that he seems
to be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``How hard he throws, how much command he has of his stuff is
probably the thing that makes me feel good about him,'' Manager Joe
Torre said when asked about Rivera's attributes. ``I've had Lee
Smith, John Wetteland and Tom Henke, sometimes ball one, ball two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so different from that type of reliever, and yet he has
the ability to strike you out,'' Torre continued. ``From last year
to this year, he has learned to get people out without worrying
about striking them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera is what Goose Gossage was to the Yankees of two decades
ago with his flaming fastball, what Joe Page was to the Yankees of
half a century ago, what Bruce Sutter was to the Cubs and the
Cardinals with his split-fingered fastball, what Dennis Eckersley
was to the Athletics with his virtually perfect control.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tributes to Derek Jeter and Orlando Hernandez
lately, Mariano Rivera is arguably the most indispensable Yankee,
the closer who slams the door on even the thought of a ninth-inning
uprising. And at a slenderly muscled 6 feet 2 inches and 170
pounds, he does it with such seemingly effortless consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is the one who gives me the strength and power,'' he said
when asked to explain his success. ``Then I just throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded that dozens of other major league pitchers have
similar strength and power but don't use it nearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you have to have something special,'' he said. ``I think
I do. Maybe I do, but I don't know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's coaches and teammates know what it is, what they call
great mechanics: his being able to not only get maximum speed and
control out of his windup, release and follow-through, but also
being able to repeat those mechanics game after game, week after
week, month after month.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's got a loose wrist,'' Tony Cloninger, the Yankees'
bullpen coach, said. ``He gets a lot of his speed and movement at
the last minute with that wrist snap.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, who doesn't throw a curveball, has three different
fastballs in his arsenal: a two-seam fastball that moves in on
right-handed batters, and two cut fastballs to left-handed batters,
one that moves in, one that moves in and down. He throws an
occasional slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remembers what I told him the first time I ever saw him in
the Instructional League,'' Cloninger said. ``That the most
important pitch is strike one.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rivera walked the first Red Sox batter to face him Sept. 11
in Fenway Park, it was the first time he had walked his first
batter in more than a year, since July 9, 1998, at Tampa Bay. In 69
innings during the recent season, he walked only 18 while fanning
52.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's warming up,'' Cloninger said, ``he wants to know who
the hitter is and what the count is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera usually doesn't arrive in the bullpen until the fifth or
sixth inning. Until then, he stays in the clubhouse and watches the
game on television, especially how the opposing batters are
reacting to pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I get ready mentally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the bullpen, Rivera begins exercising with the lead ball
and enjoying the byplay of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just sits there and laughs at me and Allen Watson getting
on each other,'' Jason Grimsley said. ``But when it's time, he's
ready. He's turned his arm into a thunderbolt. He's as consistent a
pitcher as you'll find. No matter how he feels, he's the same
pitcher every time.''
</P>
<P>
   And being the same pitcher is all the Yankees ask.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
