<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     10-27 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DEATH, warmed over, in many ways can be more painful, even less
acceptable, than during the initial shock wave. At Champions Golf
Club, there was no relief from the news that Payne Stewart had lost
his life in a plane that flew itself for four hours, then spiraled
out of the sky from 40,000 feet and crashed in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was on his way to Houston, via Dallas, to compete in a
field of 30 for the PGA's Tour Championship. When someone dies,
even someone famous and well-liked, the world can't retreat to an
attic. Several of the players showed up at Champions for their tee
times Tuesday, some dutifully facing the TV cameras and tape
recorders, still groping for the right words, trying to share what
they felt.
</P>
<P>
   They were still lost in disbelief on this, the day after the
long, eerie, tragic flight to nowhere. They were trapped in that
empty, interior place where thoughts go to hide.
</P>
<P>
   John Huston had just left the driving range. The bill of his cap
was low enough that it almost touched his sunglasses. ``It's a dark
day,'' he said, unmindful of the brilliant sunlight and cloudless
sky, ``a tragic day. Playing today (in the pro-am), that would have
been difficult. Payne will be in our thoughts all week, but when we
get on the golf course, second nature will take over.''
</P>
<P>
   People grieve in their own way. The death of one of the world's
great golfers, at 42, was unspeakably sad. But speaking is part of
the grieving process. Phil Mickelson recalled late Monday how
Stewart had beaten him in this year's U.S. Open with a 15-foot putt
that was historic. Mickelson's wife was expecting their first child
at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pulled me aside,'' said Phil, ``and put his hands on my
face and said, `You're about to become a father, and it's the
greatest thing you can imagine.' For him to think about me at a
time when he just won the biggest event in golf is amazing and says
a lot about the person he was. He just had a lot of class.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mickelson appeared at the club early Tuesday morning, he
strolled out the back of the clubhouse, and his eyes swept the
scene in front of him: a few players taking practice swings at the
driving range, a small contingent of curious, early-arriving fans
milling around. Then he did an about-face, walked back to his car
and drove off. Sometimes nonverbal communication says more than
words.
</P>
<P>
   The players expressed their concern and sent their prayers to
Stewart's family _ his wife, Tracey, and his two children, Aaron
and Chelsea. Davis Love III issued a statement. Jim Furyk could not
be consoled, could not get his mouth to work.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the readers and viewers who are not necessarily
addicted to golf may be troubled by the constant references to
Payne and the ``five others who were killed.'' The other passengers
_ Robert Fraley, Van Ardan, Bruce Borland and the pilot and
co-pilot, Michael Kling and Stephanie Bellegarrigue _ were friends
of his. They, too, left families and friends and futures.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that we cherish our heroes, especially those
who have that precious blend of talent and style. What was there
not to like about Payne Stewart, the only player on the tour who
honored the game's past by wearing knickers, or plus-fours, and a
cap whose heyday was in the Roaring Twenties?
</P>
<P>
   A classy name, classy attire, classy guy.
</P>
<P>
   We knew him, or felt as if we did. Born in Missouri, he was an
SMU graduate and therefore a product of the Texas golfing pipeline.
We noted his victories _ 11 PGA tournament titles, including three
majors _ and his five Ryder Cups. His fans suffered with him as he
went eight years with only one win, in the 1995 Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were arrangements to change, schedules to keep.
</P>
<P>
   In the half-light of the Champions dining room, Jackie Burke,
one of the club's founders and the winner of the 1957 Masters, sat
at a table that had become his command post. He barked orders to
his assistants: Call the University of Houston; see if their band
can be here Thursday morning at 7:15 for a memorial service. See if
they have bagpipes or know where to get them.
</P>
<P>
   Burke was trying to organize a ceremony on the putting green as
an alternative to having the players fly to Orlando, Fla., and back
to pay tribute to Stewart. I asked Burke if he had ever gone
through a calamity of this sort before or during a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   He nodded. ``In 1966,'' he said, ``when Tony Lema and his wife
died in a crash. Tony had left the PGA Championship in Detroit for
a private outing (in Indiana). There was a cocktail party on the
patio, and the pilot wanted to show the guests she had Tony Lema in
her plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``She banked the plane and never came out of it, went into a
dive and crashed right on the golf course. Have I been through it
before? Yeah. But it doesn't get easier with experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
