<HEADER>
A9563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-27 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ You see a first-inning fly ball sail into the gap in
right-center field and somehow bounce off the right fielder's
glove.
</P>
<P>
   Any other team, and you're thinking, ``Lucky bounce.'' But with
the Yankees, that's just the way it always seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   You see the starting pitcher, Andy Pettitte, struggle mightily.
The lefty from Deer Park has nothing on this night, absolutely
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He gives up 10 hits in barely more than three innings, putting
his team in a 5-1 hole and making it look as if the Atlanta Braves
will get a free pass back into the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Any other team, and you're thinking, ``Not tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had it,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Yankees, there is only a collective shrug in the
face of such long odds. And then there is a parade of Yankees
relievers stepping up to the rubber and looking practically
All-Century. That's just the way it always seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   You see nothing offensively from them against Braves starter Tom
Glavine _ not so much as a hint of a rally against an ace pitcher
who clearly has his ace stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in trouble,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   But you see them keep coming. You see them swinging the bats
until somehow they scratch out a solo home run in the fifth inning
and another in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Any other team, and you're thinking, ``Too little, too late.''
</P>
<P>
   But then in the bottom of the eighth with Glavine still painting
the corners, Chuck Knoblauch gets another fly ball to sail deep
into right field _ the same player bouncing the ball off the same
fielder's glove and this time bouncing it over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Cox called it ``a Yankee Stadium home run.''
</P>
<P>
   And you know that's exactly what it was. The ball needed to
travel 314 feet to tie the game and make Knoblauch a hero. It went
314{, and Jordan's glove did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it had a chance,'' Jordan said. ``It kept
going. I thought I had it, and then I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Any other team, and the impossible bounces, the impossible
comeback, would seem too unreal. But with the Yankees, that's just
the way it always seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   After Knoblauch's tying home run, the 56,794 fans at Yankee
Stadium had to know what would come in extra innings. A hero.
Somewhere, there would be a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cox said he felt the game slipping away and felt nervous in
the 10th inning. And why not? Cox was himself a Yankee in the
1960s. He knows how it always seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always somebody you don't expect,'' Cox said. ``You never
know where it's going to come from with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   This time it came from the tiniest Yankee, left fielder Chad
Curtis, who stands 5-10 going on 5-8 and hit only five home runs
all year.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally. That's just the way it always seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis smashed the ball off Braves reliever Mike Remlinger,
flicking his bat into the air when he felt the ball blast off it
and into the New York sky. The crowd roared. Braves left fielder
Gerald Williams didn't even turn to give chase.
</P>
<P>
   Gone. Players flooded out of the Yankees' dugout and onto the
field. A stream of New York's finest sprinted onto the field even
before Curtis finished rounding the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The ball sailed over the left-field fence, then over the
original brick fence Babe Ruth built all those years ago that is
now some 430 feet away from home plate. Naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get a base hit,'' Curtis said. ``It just
went. I don't even remember going around the bases. I've heard
people talk about tingling at Yankee Stadium, but I've never felt
it before. When I was running between first and second base, I felt
electric.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball sailed over the hallowed monument park behind left
field, bouncing between shrines dedicated to Mickey Mantle and Yogi
Berra. Naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone stood. Everyone cheered. The booming sounds of Frank
Sinatra singing New York, New York began echoing off the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a night that you're going to be able to look back on
someday and think, `Wow,''' Torre said. ``Sometimes these kinds of
things just happen. I'm amazed, and yet I'm not amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. It's October. It's Yankee Stadium. It's the World
Series. It's just the way it always seems to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
