<SLUG> BC-RODEO-BULL-RIDING-CHAMP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULL RIDER CODY HART RANKS AMONG SPORT'S BEST _ AT 21
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Texas _ On a spring day earlier this year at his
wooded ranch, Cody Hart saddled an unbroken colt.
</P>
<P>
   That move brought a sharp rebuke from his petite wife, Shawna.
``I told him that it was stupid, that those colts were idiots and
they can be as bad as a riding a bull,'' she said. ``I told him
that it wasn't worth getting hurt over a $300 colt.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't want him to risk a needless injury that might spoil
her husband's commanding lead in the world bull riding title race.
After she put her boot down, Cody Hart wisely decided to postpone
his bronco busting until after the 1999 Professional Bull Riders
Bud Light Cup Series season.
</P>
<P>
   For Hart, that intense focus has proven to be the right choice.
He will enter the organization's $1.5 million World Finals,
scheduled tomorrow through Sunday at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center in
Las Vegas, with the world title clinched.
</P>
<P>
   Hart has a 1,805.5-point lead over seven-time world all-around
champion Ty Murray of Stephenville. The most points that can be
earned at the championship are 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   As Hart competes in four preliminary rounds and a potential
final, Shawna will be cheering him on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the world that motives me any more than my
wife and bull riding,'' Hart said. ``My wife is one of the main
reasons that I'm where I am as a bull rider. If I need someone to
lean on or a shoulder to cry on, she's there. She's like the
American Express card, I don't leave home without her. And bull
riding: I've loved it since I was knee high to a grasshopper.'' A
prodigy Hart, a spunky 5-foot-7, 145-pound cowboy, has $238,048 in
season earnings. If he fares well at the finals, he could finish
the year with more than $500,000, an unheard of sum for rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   The record earnings for any rodeo association is $300,213, a
milestone Chris Shivers reached last year. Hart will break the
record even if he is disqualified in every round at the
championships. For starters, he will receive $85,000 for winning
the cup series after finishing with the most points from 28
regular-season shows and the Las Vegas finals.
</P>
<P>
   At 21, Hart has dominated the 1999 tour, winning a record six
regular-season cup series shows. The feat is comparable to Tiger
Woods winning pro golf's 1997 Masters Tournament in his first full
year, then dominating most fields each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a Bud Light Cup show is like playing the 18th hole at
the Masters and you have to birdie to win,'' Hart said. ``Riding in
the final round is like having a 12-foot putt to win and you sink
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Woods, who began golfing at a young age, Hart has prepared
to be bull riding's kingpin since he mounted his first calf at age
3. From there, he ascended to 700-pound steers in elementary school
and onto 1,000-pound bulls in junior high. When he entered high
school, Hart made the transition to entering bull riding shows that
featured world-class athletes, including Murray and four-time world
champion Tuff Hedeman.
</P>
<P>
   Hart and older brother, J.W., 24, also a high-profile bull
rider, competed on a tour dubbed as Super Bull. As the two brothers
slapped down their entry fees at the bull pens, Cody Hart craved
taking on the maddest bulls on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 15, Hart mounted the feared world champion bull
Bodacious, in Wichita, Kan. ``You really had to be 18 to enter, and
when I told them I was 17, they said it was close enough. But when
I drew Bodacious they said it would be too dangerous. Then, J.W.
got in the office \Rwith officials\S and threw a fit. And we
convinced them that I could handle the situation.'' Hart stayed on
for several jumps and walked away unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Hart finished high school, he had mounted more than
his share of horrific bulls. At 18 in Alexandria, La., Hart
conquered the world champion bull, Red Wolf, a beast that had
fatally stomped Brent Thurman at the 1994 National Finals Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   As Hart lowers himself onto a raging bull in the coffin-shaped
bucking chutes, he knows he's asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you nod your head, you'd better mean business,'' he
said. ``All it takes is getting a hair off of your timing and
you're in trouble.'' A bullish competitor Bull riding has been a
highly profitable business for Hart, who has qualified for the past
four PBR world championships and has accumulated almost $500,000 in
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two years on the circuit, Hart grabbed attention by
qualifying for the PBR world championships' final round at 18 and
pocketing $145,541 at 19. Last year, he earned $73,108 after being
sidelined with nagging injures.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, Hart has dominated, winning the season opener
in Salt Lake City in December and never looking back. The defining
moments of the season were Hart's three showdowns with Moody Blues,
last year's top bull in the PBR. Hart topped Moody Blues three
times on three tries (Columbus, Fort Worth and Houston). In Fort
Worth in March, Hart received $10,000 for mastering the rapid-fire
spinner in a winner-take-all match. Had the bull won, the money
would have been handed to owner Terry Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's only setback was missing three weeks after suffering
clavicle injuries after a September wreck in Laughlin, Nev. But he
missed only one cup series show (Calgary, Alberta). Hart clinched
the title 1 1/2 weeks ago after finishing in the money at the last
regular-season show in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the finals, Hart has outpointed Murray, 9,845.5 to
8,040.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Cody realizes the significance of what he's
done,'' Murray said. ``Just to win one of these shows is a big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Dunn, the 1998 world bull riding champion, said Hart exudes
confidence: ``Ever since I first saw Cody ride, I knew that he
would be one of the great ones. He's cocky, and every great bull
rider that I've seen is cocky, at a young age. He's not afraid to
get out over the front of a bull and take him on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart said mental preparation is a key to success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning in bull riding is about 90 percent mental. Your mind
has to be right. You can't be hung up on having trouble at home.
You can't be thinking about some good-looking girl in the stands
and you can't be thinking about going to the bar after the rodeo
when you're about to ride.'' d nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
