r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX     10-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' IRVIN HAS GENETIC SPINAL CONDITION THAT CLOUDS RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Michael Irvin's already uncertain return to the
Cowboys from an Oct. 10 spinal injury has been clouded by a genetic
condition called ``cervical stenosis,'' or a narrow spinal canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike was born with a different-looking spine,'' Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones said yesterday. ``How does that impact any decision he
might make? To me, I've heard more discussed about what he was born
with than I have about any damage'' incurred from the spinal
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has played his entire career with a narrow spinal canal,
but the condition puts his spinal cord at risk because one hit can
jar it. In 1986, Green Bay cornerback Tim Lewis and Houston Oilers
linebacker Frank Bush retired finding out they had narrow spinal
canals.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Irvin's condition, Jones said, ``Yes, I'm
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a possibility that there is not going to be a
definitive conclusion,'' Jones said. ``They're addressing
everything. I don't see this as necessarily totally decided by
whether or not the swelling goes down. Right now, I don't know if
that's the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's cervical stenosis was initially revealed along with
swelling in his cervix when Irvin had a magnetic resonance imaging
exam after being knocked out of the game Oct. 10 in Philadelphia.
Irvin, 33, now faces something more than a healing process from a 2
1/2-week-old spinal contusion. He faces a career decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has a narrow spinal canal. ... Some people have it,
some don't,'' Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said. ``This obviously is
part of the concern. There are still more questions that need to be
answered over the next several weeks. The only thing that has
changed for him, really, is the time that has gone by since the
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Cowboys has talked about a timetable or even if the
Cowboys' all-time leading receiver will return. Jones said he
couldn't answer that. Irvin was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin is scheduled for another MRI tomorrow at the Dallas office
of spine specialist Dr. Drew Dossett. X-rays taken at Dossett's
office Monday showed nothing that wasn't already known in terms of
his genetic condition.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery is not an option, Jones said. He also pointed out that a
second medical opinion is available to Irvin, if he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   No one has advised the 12-year veteran to retire, Irvin said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's injury occurred when he awkwardly fell headfirst into
the Veterans Stadium artificial turf as he was being tackled on
what appeared to be a routine slant pass over the middle. He
immediately lost feeling in his extremities and couldn't move his
hands or legs for more than 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was taken by ambulance to a downtown Philadelphia trauma
center where an MRI showed swelling in two places of the spinal
cord, along with the narrow spinal canal. Roster moves Fullback Tim
Lester, who was signed the second week of the season, and
linebacker Nate Hemsley were cut yesterday. Robert Thomas is
expected to be the starter at fullback, and linebacker Lemanski
Hall was signed to replace Hemsley. The Cowboys also activated
fullback Ryan Neufeld from the practice squad. The moves were
related to trying to improve the special teams. Former Cowboys
linebacker Jim Schwantz worked out but was not signed. Schwantz
made the Pro Bowl as a special-teams player with the Cowboys in
1996. \Nsubheds:Teague doubtful Free safety George Teague's neck
sprain is more extensive than first thought when it occurred Oct.
18 against the New York Giants. Teague is expected to practice this
week for the first time since the injury but isn't expected to play
Sunday in Indianapolis.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
