<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNLIKELY YANKEE SMASHES A GAME ENDING HOME RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chad Curtis knew the ball was leaving Yankee Stadium,
which would turn him into a World Series hero and put the Yankees
within one victory of winning their second straight championship.
Curtis knew it was gone. Everyone knew.
</P>
<P>
   So Curtis coolly flipped the bat to the ground, raised his two
fists high like Rocky Balboa and trotted and floated around the
bases. When Curtis crossed home plate with the winning run in a
6-5, 10-inning victory over the Atlanta Braves, there were two
dozen Yankees waiting to smother him. They lifted him in the air
and Curtis felt he never wanted to come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you get one,'' Curtis said. ``That hit the sweet
spot of the bat. It was a rush. I can't say I ever felt that
before. Rounding the bases, I was kind of tingling. I've heard
people talk about that, but I've never felt it before. I was
tingling.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre hustled over to find Curtis after his second
homer in the game, leaned in close to his reserve outfielder and
told him that he had given himself the sort of baseball memory that
he would never forget. Curtis made his first World Series start on
Tuesday night, and Torre wanted to remind him about what he had
just accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional thing,'' Torre said. ``I told him, `You
had a heck of a first World Series game, young man.' That's a game
he'll look back on. That's a game he'll always remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis was an unlikely hero, but in some ways, he was a likely
hero, too, because the Yankees are a very deep team. Still, Curtis
did not even play during the four-game Series sweep against the San
Diego Padres last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I felt like I was more of a congratulator than a
celebrator,'' Curtis said. ``I came into this year telling myself:
last year I played the whole regular season and didn't play in the
post-season much. I told myself that if it totally turned around
this season and I contributed in the post-season, I would be more
happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Curtis' homer showed why the Yankees are so special.
Someone will do it. If it is not Paul O'Neill or Derek Jeter, it
can be Curtis. On Tuesday night, it was Curtis who drilled a 1-1
changeup from Mike Remlinger into the dark night and helped
continue a dissemination of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That says a lot about our team,'' O'Neill said. ``There are so
many people in here who are happy for Chad. We know what he's been
through. Those hits could make Chad Curtis' whole year. When you
hit a walk-off homer in the World Series, that's something he's
going to remember for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for Chuck Knoblauch. When Knoblauch's fly ball
drifted toward the right-field fence in the eighth, any ardent
Yankee fan had to think about Jeffrey Maier, for Knoblauch's ball
looked a lot like the shot Jeter stroked during the 1996
post-season, the one a 12-year-old Maier interfered with to help
the Yankees prevail against Baltimore
</P>
<P>
   But there was no fan interference in the cozy right-field corner
at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday night. Brian Jordan had enough
difficulty trying to corral Knoblauch's shot without any fans
involved. Jordan retreated to the fence, lined up the ball, leaped
and thought he had the ball. But as Jordan stretched his glove over
the fence, the ball tipped off the webbing of his glove, somehow
popped out and tumbled free for a dramatic two-run homer that
evened the score, 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it was going to get further in the seats, but I
know Jordan is a tremendous athlete and a great outfielder,''
Knoblauch said. ``I was hoping it would get far enough; luckily it
bounced the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   The score remained tied until Curtis opened the 10th off
Remlinger, Atlanta's third pitcher. Curtis started the game despite
being 0 for 13 in his career against Tom Glavine. But he homered
off Glavine in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger moved the count to 1-1 against Curtis, and then he
tried to throw a changeup. Curtis destroyed it. ``I don't think
I've ever done that in a regular-season game,'' Curtis said,
referring to a game-ending homer. ``To do that in a World Series
game, it felt great. It just felt great to hit that and to come
home and see my teammates waiting there to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   After Curtis' homer, NBC asked him to do an on-field interview
with Jim Gray, who had angered several players because of the
forceful manner in which they felt he interviewed Pete Rose after
the all-century team ceremony before Game 2 in Atlanta on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis let Gray ask him a question, then told him the Yankees
were unhappy with his treatment of Rose, waved to the camera and
jogged away. He did other television interviews on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something the team decided to do,'' Curtis said. ``The
team said we needed to do something after the way he talked to
Pete. It was a pretty special night for Pete.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday night was a very special night for Curtis. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
