<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYNE STEWART'S RELATIVES, FRIENDS RECALL HIS YOUNGER YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 MEMORIES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD,Mo. _ The simple one-story house where pro golfer
Payne Stewart spent his boyhood radiated with sunshine and laughter
and stories Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and friends stopped by to tell Stewart's mother and
sisters how sorry they were that he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But the long hugs and the hand-holding were overshadowed by
tales of fun and the vibrant memories of the boy, the teen-ager and
the man who loved to joke and pull pranks, have a good time and
just be nice to people.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and five others were killed Monday when the private jet
in which they were flying crashed in a field near Mina, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   In Springfield, Stewart's family and friends sat outside on the
backyard deck, a beautiful blue sky above them, as Bee
Payne-Stewart and her daughters, Susan Daniel and Lora Thomas,
reminisced.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel remembered how one time little Payne and a neighbor girl
stayed home while Mom ran to the grocery store. Spaghetti was
planned for dinner, and the noodles were cooked. Payne and the girl
grabbed the noodles and threw them all over the kitchen wall. When
Payne's mother got home, she asked them what they thought they were
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Payne told her that the best way to tell whether spaghetti
noodles were really done was to see whether they stuck to the wall
when you threw them.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas remembered the day the telephone company workers were in
the neighborhood installing telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   They had dug some deep holes, and the neighborhood children
decided to put little Payne, the youngest of the bunch, into a
hole. He was too little to climb back out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so mad at those boys for putting him in there,'' Thomas
recalled, gripping her hand into a fist, but laughing too at the
memory of little Payne, stuck with no way out.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about how Payne would have friends over and always
challenge them to golf-putting contests in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever wanted to do it, because Payne always won,''
Thomas said, and the three laughed, their hearty laughs echoing off
the other houses in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Stories. Laughter. Memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just loved the outdoors, and he cooks everything,'' Thomas
said, speaking of her brother as if he were there, sitting outside
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked to hunt and fish and canoe,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Their energetic brother even loved to snorkel and scuba dive and
watch movies, any kind of movie, and listen to music, any kind of
music. He was constantly busy, never slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   It had been like that when they were growing up in this
middle-class section of Springfield. Dozens of rambunctious kids
lived nearby, and they spent their time playing outside _
basketball, football, baseball and the made-up game of just
throwing a ball over the house to whoever was standing in the front
yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke so many windows,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   They remembered Payne the teen-ager, driving around in the
army-green Volkswagen Beetle he got as a hand-me-down from his
sister, Lora.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tell him the floorboard was all rusted out and it
didn't have a heater,'' Thomas said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel jumped in: ``And he went driving through a mud puddle,
and the water splashed up and got all over him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than once,'' Thomas added, sending them into laughing
spells again.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took that awful car to college at Southern Methodist
University in Texas on a partial golf scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He roomed with a millionaire, and he started acting like he
was a millionaire,'' his mom recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we weren't millionaires,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go down there and straighten him out,'' his mother
recalled, nodding knowingly and wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't making the grades,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made him go to summer school,'' Payne-Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   As they reminisced, Larry Edgar, who grew up with the Stewart
children in the neighborhood, came out on the deck to talk to the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, were you one of those boys who put Payne in that post
hole?'' Thomas asked him in mock anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying,'' Edgar said, shaking his head and looking at
the ground, yet with a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed as he told the story of how the neighborhood boys got
little Payne in big trouble with his mother once: ``We had a club,
and for Payne to be in the club we made him wait till Bee called
him three times before he went home.''
</P>
<P>
   More laughter. More smiles. More memories.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's mom and two sisters went to Boston last month to watch
him play in the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   They had a wonderful time, bonding with each other and
witnessing the grace and determination that was Payne Stewart on
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to kiss him every morning before he went out to play,''
his mother recalled, her eyes misting behind blue eyeliner and
gold-framed glasses. ``We were good kissers.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll always remember the last time she spoke to her son.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sunday night. Stewart had missed the cut for last
weekend's National Car Rental Classic in Orlando, Fla., so he had
been able to see his son, Aaron, play football. Aaron had made a
great catch, and Stewart was proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `See, everything works out for the best,' ''
Payne-Stewart recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She paused. She looked at her daughter Lora, her eyes pleading,
her lips pursed together so she wouldn't cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then he boarded that plane. So everything doesn't always
work out for the best, does it?''
</P>
<P>
   (A memorial service for Payne Stewart will be held Friday at
First Baptist Church of Orlando, Fla., where Stewart attended
services and where his children go to day school.
</P>
<P>
   In Springfield, a memorial service is scheduled for noon Monday
at Second Baptist Church.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
