<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING BUDGET SURPLUSES TO PAY DOWN NATIONAL DEBT IS JUST ANOTHER
SCAM 
</HEADLINE>
 DEBT-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The good news is Washington apparently will use future budget
surpluses to pay down the national debt. The bad news is the
process isn't likely to reduce the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   While many Americans equate lowering federal debt with
responsible government, what's shaping up here is just another
accounting scam. What seems to be evolving is a situation in which
political gridlock will result in budget surpluses going to pay
down the publicly held portion of the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by The New York Times characterized the portion of
the Treasury debt held by the public as ``the most important
component,'' but the process isn't likely to reduce the Treasury's
actual overall indebtedness. The debt won't shrink because most of
the anticipated budget surpluses will be the result of excess
Social Security payroll tax receipts.
</P>
<P>
   The scam part has to do with the fact that there are two kinds
of national debt. Nearly 60 percent of the $5.6 trillion national
debt is composed of marketable securities held by individuals,
financial institutions and foreign governments. This is marketable
debt, traded just like corporate and municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is mostly debt owed to trust funds. The trust funds
were created as parking places for surplus revenue from taxes
levied for specific purposes such as Social Security, highway
construction, airport improvements and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting device used is an interest-bearing nonmarketable
security to be redeemed by a budget appropriation when the money
needs to be spent for its intended purpose. What the trust fund has
is basically an IOU representing a claim on the Treasury. There's
no real money involved; the cash has been spent and an unfunded
liability was created in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, if Social Security surpluses are used to pay down
publicly held debt, this debt component indeed declines. On the
other hand, the debt owed to future Social Security beneficiaries
will rise by a like amount.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement wouldn't even be a new policy. This is exactly
what has been happening since Washington began enjoying budget
surpluses thanks to excess Social Security revenue. It happens well
out of public view, but the Treasury has been rolling over maturing
issues regularly in amounts less than the securities being
redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a modest shrinkage of publicly held debt. At
the same time, however, the nonmarketable debt owed the trust funds
has been growing even faster than the public debt is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Some may pretend this isn't spending, but what else do you call
debt service? Some may even applaud because government is replacing
debt owed to others with debt ``we owe ourselves.'' This isn't
quite true. We're replacing it with debt we owe our children and
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   If you have any doubt as to whether this arrangement improves
the debt situation, you can track progress most days by monitoring
the small type in this business section under the headline,
``Government finances.'' Make a notation of the total public debt
on the first of each month for the next year. The first and last
numbers on the list will tell you all you need to know about
Washington's latest fiscal dodge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9582 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-1     10-27 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YANKEES COME OFF THE MAT TO TRIUMPH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout; story is now an added starter on
The New York Times front page)   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT27,31,32,37,38,39,40,41,42,43,44,45 _ are
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre was not sure whether he would start Chad
Curtis in Game 3 of the World Series on Tuesday night. Maybe it was
a better idea to start Ricky Ledee in left field instead; Curtis,
after all, had not had a hit in 13 career at-bats against the
Atlanta starter, Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   But Curtis started, and slugged a home run off Glavine in the
fifth inning, the first blow in the Yankees' comeback from a 5-1
deficit. And after Chuck Knoblauch tied the game in the eighth
inning with a two-run home run, Curtis ended the game in the 10th
inning with his second home run, off the Braves' Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' 6-5 victory over Atlanta at Yankee Stadium gave
them a commanding 3-0 edge in the four-of-seven-game World Series;
no team has ever come back from a 3-0 deficit to win in the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who have won 11 consecutive World Series games,
need one more victory to clinch their 25th championship. The
Braves' John Smoltz will pitch Game 4 against the Yankees' Roger
Clemens on Wednesday night, with the Yankees seeking their second
consecutive World Series sweep and their third title in four years.
``Every time we've had a chance to close it out, we've always
closed it out the next game,'' reliever Jeff Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves seemingly had full control of the game after four
innings. The Atlanta hitters had made a terrific adjustment against
the left-hander Andy Pettitte, driving his outside pitches to the
opposite field and knocking him out of the game after only three
and two-thirds innings; Pettitte had allowed 10 hits and 5 runs
and, Torre said later, the Yankees' dugout was very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine had not been able to pitch Game 1 on Saturday, as
scheduled, because of a stomach virus, and he had lost a few pounds
and felt weak. Before Tuesday night's game, Braves manager Bobby
Cox had said that he hoped to get ``seven good innings'' from
Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   But the veteran left-hander gave him much more than that,
needing just 40 pitches to get through the first four innings. The
Yankees, too, were trying to drive the ball the other way against
Glavine, but his fastball was sinking and they were not getting
many good swings and everything seemed to be going along so
smoothly for the Braves. Win Game 3 and then Smoltz would have a
chance to tie the series for Atlanta in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre came out to relieve Pettitte and hand the ball to
Jason Grimsley, Torre said _ as he always does to a reliever when
the Yankees are trailing _ ``Hold them here and get yourself a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the field, Knoblauch and shortstop Derek Jeter kept
repeating these words to each other. Hold them. Hold them here.
We'll come back. Curtis led off the bottom of the fifth inning and
drove a pitch into the right-field seats, and there was life in the
Yankees; the lead was down to three runs. Glavine rolled along,
into the seventh, and then Tino Martinez smashed a home run. Braves
5, Yankees 3.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Yankees batted in the eighth, Remlinger and the
Braves' closer, John Rocker, were throwing in the Atlanta bullpen.
Glavine had given Atlanta seven good innings, as Cox had hoped. But
Glavine, who along with John Smoltz and Greg Maddux have been the
heart of this team for the better part of the decade, wanted to
continue. His pitch count was low; he assured Cox he felt fine.
``He was throwing great,'' Cox said later. ``He didn't want to come
out of the game. I asked him if he was tired and he said no.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi led off the inning and lined a single to left field.
Knoblauch was next, having hit a line drive off the glove of right
fielder Brian Jordan in the first inning _ an error, according to
the official scorer _ and later hit a double. He was comfortable
against Glavine, that was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Cox stuck with Glavine, who threw a pitch down and in to
Knoblauch, Knoblauch's favorite hitting zone. And Knoblauch bashed
a high drive to right field, where Jordan ran back toward the wall.
The 56,794 fans at Yankee Stadium stood; many Yankees leaped out of
their dugout to follow the flight of the ball into the right-field
corner. Jordan jumped and reached back over the fence, and the ball
went into his glove. And then it dropped out, bouncing into the
stands. Home run. Knoblauch soared around the bases, the game tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so happy, I wanted to lift him up and carry him,''
Bernie Williams said later. ``But I realized we still had to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Cox spoke of the home run bitterly. The Braves' manager
always will believe the Yankees won the 1996 World Series because
an umpire prevented one of his outfielders from reaching a crucial
pop fly, and he spoke of Knoblauch's home run with only slightly
less disdain. ``We basically got beat with the pop-up,'' Cox said,
referring to Knoblauch's home run. ``It was a Yankee home run. We
got beat with a 315-foot home run. You get a 315-foot fly ball and
it's an out in my book.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's good luck, Knoblauch said later, ``We'll take it every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   There was good feeling in the Yankees' dugout after that, David
Cone said later. The game was tied, Mariano Rivera was pitching.
They just needed a run. Bret Boone led off the ninth inning with a
single and Otis Nixon entered the game as a pinch-runner for the
Braves, to steal second. But Girardi threw out Nixon, pumping his
fist, for this was no small feat. It was the first time since 1996
that an opposing runner had been thrown out trying to steal against
Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker shut out the Yankees through the ninth inning, and as the
Yankees came to bat for the 10th inning, Remlinger relieved for the
Braves. Curtis was to lead off, and in his mind, he went through
his game plan: Just try to hit the ball up the middle. Don't try to
do too much with the pitch. Do something small and start the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   All night, some of the Yankees' reserves had been predicting
home runs, Ledee and Luis Sojo and Jorge Posada all calling shots
for their teammates. Posada had predicted that Knoblauch would hit
his home run, and had been right.
</P>
<P>
   As Curtis stepped in, nobody said anything. Before this game
began, after all, Curtis had not hit a home run since Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis fouled off a pitch. Remlinger threw a high fastball, and
Curtis stepped out. Nelson was in the trainer's room, his arm in an
ice pack, watching on television, and in the opposite corner of the
clubhouse, Jason Grimsley was watching on television.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger threw a changeup, and Curtis swung and hit the ball on
the air and flipped his bat away, and in the clubhouse, Nelson and
Grimsley knew what those in the dugout realized when they heard the
contact. Home run. Unbelievable. A home run. Curtis threw up his
arms at first, then ran around the bases, his face devoid of
expression, his mind apparently overcome by thoughts. ``I don't
remember anything,'' he said later, when asked about his trip
around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   He reached home plate and descended into a sea of happy
teammates, all of them one victory away from one more World Series
title, the last in a century covered with pinstriped championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
