<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBO-SERIES-YANKEES-BRAVE     10-27 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ON THE BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
 BBO-SERIES-YANKEES-BRAVES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of all the things the Atlanta Braves expected to
encounter in New York, this had to be the strangest.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know better, you'd almost say it was Southern
hospitality, at least until well after dark, when this city _ and
the Yankees _ turned rude again, just when the Braves thought they
might settle in for a nice stay.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Chad Curtis, a part-timer who hit just five home
runs all season and made his biggest noise when he complained about
teammate Derek Jeter laughing during a brawl with Seattle, all but
doomed the Braves to another long winter when he hit his second
home run of the night in the bottom of the 10th, giving the Yankees
a 6-5 win over the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was between second and third that I felt like there
was electricity going through my legs,'' said Curtis, who couldn't
recall ever hitting a game-ending home run in the regular season.
``Coming around third base, seeing my teammates waiting at home
plate in a World Series game, was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, winning their 11th straight World Series game, one
short of the record set by the Ruth-Gehrig Yanks, have a
three-games-to-none lead, with Roger Clemens in place to finish off
the Braves, who are in danger of losing the World Series for the
fourth time in five tries this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me at the start who would be the star of the
Series, and it's always somebody you don't expect,'' said Braves
manager Bobby Cox, who said he was surprised during introductions
to see how short Curtis was (generously listed at 5 feet 10 inches)
compared with his brawnier teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that last one was really crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis's blast was the second walkoff home run of the postseason
by the Yankees, who beat the Red Sox in Game 1 of the ALCS on
Bernie Williams's 10th-inning homer off Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still amazed, yet not amazed,'' manager Joe Torre said of
another Yankee comeback. ``We play nine innings.'' Or, in this
case, 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who had not homered in winning two games in
Atlanta, stole a page from their storied Bomber past with four home
runs to overcome a 5-1 deficit. Chuck Knoblauch tied the score with
a two-run homer in the eighth off lefthander Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, previously noticed for his wacky throws and wackier
penchant for being in the middle of the postseason's most
controversial plays, hit a fly ball that caressed the top of Brian
Jordan's glove before falling into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Cox called it a ``Yankee Stadium home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's response? ``I'm glad I hit it in Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, in his flu-weakened state, held the Yankees at bay
until the eighth, one more inning than Cox had projected him to
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis hit a first-pitch home run to make it 5-2 in the fifth,
and Tino Martinez hit another first-pitch homer to make it 5-3 in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's third pitcher, Mike Remlinger, started the 10th in
place of Public Enemy No. 1, John Rocker, the reliever who warmed
up to vulgar chants but threw two scoreless innings in relief of
Glavine. Curtis was the first batter faced by Remlinger, who joins
a couple other Braves relievers this decade who have given up
crushing World Series home runs: Charlie Leibrandt, beaten by the
Twins' Kirby Puckett in the 11th inning in a Game 6 triumph in
1991, and Mark Wohlers, who gave up Jim Leyritz's Series-turning
blast in Game 4 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the day had started out so pleasantly for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Cox, who spent the pregame hours walking the streets of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in New York so many times this year,'' Cox said,
``that some of the people I'm starting to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised how many people, because we are on TBS and
national television, with the Yankees and all the playoffs, people
do recognize you and they're very nice. They're all very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes Yankee starter Andy Pettitte, who allowed Atlanta
hitters to save face.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, whose total of seven hits in the first two games was
the weakest output since the '66 Dodgers, slapped Pettitte around
for 10 hits and five runs in just 3 2/3 innings to seize their 5-1
lead. Two batters into the game, the Braves had as many hits as
they'd had in the first 15 innings in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams singled, took third on Bret Boone's double, and
scored Atlanta's first run on Chipper Jones's infield out.
</P>
<P>
   Boone opened the third with another double and scored on a
single by Jordan, the cleanup man's first hit of the Series. Andruw
Jones followed with another single, his first Series hit, and both
came home on a double by Jose Hernandez, a shortstop by trade who
was making his first appearance as a DH.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Gerald Williams tripled over a leaping Bernie
Williams and scored on Boone's third double. The Braves' second
baseman became the first player since Brooklyn's Jim Gilliam to
double three times in one Series game. But Boone was erased
attempting to steal third, which may have cost the Braves a bigger
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to steal third all night on Pettitte,'' said
Cox, defending Boone's decision. ``I think he changed arms (as he
dived into third). I thought he'd be in there easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone had a fourth hit, a leadoff single in the ninth off closer
Mariano Rivera, then was replaced by pinch runner Otis Nixon. But
Nixon was erased attempting to steal on a strong throw by Joe
Girardi, Chipper Jones went down swinging on a full count, and
Jordan bounced to short.
</P>
<P>
   Three Yankees' relievers _ Jason Grimsley, Jeff Nelson, and
Rivera _ combined to shut out the Braves on three hits over the
last 6 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The win went to Rivera, who has five saves and a victory in
seven postseason appearances.
</P>
<P>
   He has thrown 10 scoreless innings in this postseason, and
hasn't allowed a run in 41 2/3 innings dating back to July 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
