<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBO-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN-BO     10-27 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS HAS CHANCE TO MAKE IT A CLEAN SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 BBO-SHAUGHNESSY COLUMN-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pitching in the theater of hatred that was Fenway
Park 11 days ago, that was tough. This should be relatively easy.
It's merely a chance to clinch the last World Series of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens will be working on 10 days rest, and 13 years of
restlessness, when he takes the mound against the Atlanta Braves in
Game 4 of the World Series Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It's said that there are no second acts in American life, and
nothing Clemens does can erase the haunting memory of a World
Series played in this same city 13 years ago when he was 24 years
old. Hardball historians, like Dealey Plaza buffs, still try to
reconstruct events of Game 6, the night Clemens left with a 3-2
lead after seven innings, about an hour before a seemingly harmless
grounder rolled between the feet of a onetime batting champ who
eventually would move his family to Idaho to escape infamy.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Bill Buckner, Clemens is dogged by what should
have been his finest moment. He was 24-4 in 1986, MVP of the
All-Star Game, MVP of the American League, the Cy Young Award
winner, and the winning pitcher in the seventh game of the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken 13 years and two family moves to get back to this
stage, and Wednesday night he gets the ball for the fourth _ and
possibly final _ game of the World Series. He has the chance to be
the guy in the picture standing on the mound when the Series is
won.
</P>
<P>
   The ring is all that eludes him. He's got the five Cy Youngs,
the 3,000 strikeouts, the two 20-strikeout games. He's going to
land in Cooperstown and over the weekend he sat with Willie Mays,
Ted Williams, and the ghost of Babe Ruth, recognized as one of the
30 greatest ballplayers of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is still reeling from his poor performance and rude
reception at Fenway Park, where he was routed by the Red Sox in a
13-1 loss to Pedro Martinez. He lasted only two-plus innings and
was mercilessly hooted when he was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to pitch well Wednesday night or his Hall of Fame
plaque could be eternally tarnished. He's in danger of being
remembered like the late, great Wilt Chamberlain _ as a dominating
numbers guy who could not win the big one. Clemens has two wins in
11 postseason starts, and none of the failures were more celebrated
than the embarrassing third-inning KO at Fenway this month. This is
the legacy he lugs to the Yankee Stadium mound. A Game 4 shutout
would change everything.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has been consistent only in his stubborn denials that
'86 is forgotten, and that the Saturday massacre in Boston was no
big deal. Baloney. He's too proud. He's still stung by his former
manager's accusation that he took himself out of Game 6 in '86. And
his family was deeply wounded when he was hooted out of the Hub 11
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about '86, he said, ``The controversy that's behind it. I
talked to Peter Gammons a week ago. Until he mentioned it, it
wasn't even a concern of mine. He said about John McNamara. So it
makes _ that was three years ago. So, again, this is here and now
it's a whole different situation. So that was the furthest thing
from my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame your humble columnist for the syntax in that
paragraph. It's Rogerspeak, word for word, right off the
transcript. A bag of words, spilled onto paper as only Clemens can
do it. And it's more baloney.
</P>
<P>
   In a rambling interview with the national media, he told a
couple of delightful stories about conversations he had with Ted
Williams when he was a young Soxer in Winter Haven (Ted told him,
``I know I can hit your fastball'') and took a not-so-veiled shot
at the Red Sox when he spoke of Yankee loyalty to ex-players:
``Great opportunities for me to talk to gentlemen and definitely
older players. You know, again, they welcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The Sox never did.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had a mediocre season for the Yankees (14-10, 4.60) in
1999. He was the No. 3 starter in the first two rounds of the
playoffs and pitched seven shutout innings in the Division Series
clincher against Texas. Then came the Boston disaster, and he's in
the Al Nipper No. 4 spot Wednesday night. Imagine a team so deep
that it plucks a pitcher from the All-Century team for the fourth
game of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the stage in Fenway was probably more than Roger could
handle,'' conceded Yankees manager Joe Torre. ``Unfortunately, he
couldn't pitch the way he'd like. Tomorrow will be a special day
for Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To finally be here in this situation is just really
exciting,'' said the Rocket. ``It's an awesome feeling to have this
chance again.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why he got himself traded to a city he hates. He wanted
a ring. He wanted to pitch in the big games at least one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night he returns to the World Series. The biggest game
of them all. He can win the Fall Classic all by himself. It's a big
game. Almost as big as a playoff game against Pedro Martinez at
Fenway Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
