<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS COME ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After plodding along for two periods Tuesday
night, the Kings scored twice within 33 seconds midway through the
third to defeat the Washington Capitals 5-2 in front of 13,169 at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Audette had two goals, including the Kings' final goal
that blew open a game that was close most of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings now have won two straight since first-year coach Andy
Murray blasted the club after a 6-3 loss to Phoenix last Friday.
The team is 2-1-1 on the homestand, which ends Thursday against
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake brought his team and the crowd back to life when he
broke the tie with 11:44 left in the game. Blake, who leads all NHL
defensemen in scoring, took a slick pass from Ziggy Palffy at the
point and beat Caps goalie Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute later Bryan Smolinski slipped through the
Washington defense, took a pass from Audette and fired the puck
over Kolzig's right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   When Audette scored the third goal of the period three minutes
later, the Kings had a victory for goaltender Jamie Storr, who had
played only one period in the team's first ten games.
</P>
<P>
   Storr, who allowed two goals in the first period, had an
otherwise quiet night. The Capitals had just three shots on goal in
the second period and just 17 for the game.
</P>
<P>
   But he showed no ill effects from a tender right groin that
forced him out of an Oct. 7 game in Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stephane Fiset is expected to return to the net Friday,
the Kings now have two solid contributors in goal.
</P>
<P>
   They also got three goals and eight points from their second
line, which was benched for the final six minutes of Friday's game
against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   With one game left on the homestand, the team has only played
well in spurts. Unlike their season-opening seven-game road trip,
when they went 4-2-1, the Kings had not put together a sustained
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Murray knew his team did not play well in the third period of
Sunday's 4-3 victory over San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   But after Tuesday's pre-game morning workout was cancelled, the
Kings came out sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Although they lead the league on the power play, their man
advantage backfired with 8:31 left in the first period when
Washington scored a short-handed goal.
</P>
<P>
   With just 10 seconds remaining in a holding penalty by Ken Klee,
Kings defenseman Garry Galley lost the puck to Peter Bondra at the
blue line. Bondra, perhaps the league's fastest skater, swooped
down on Storr and fired it over his left shoulder to give the Caps
a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Calle Johansson made it 2-0 less than three minutes later when
he scored a power play goal in front of Storr on a pass from Jan
Bulis. Although the Kings have been behind by two goals this
season, they have never trailed 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who passed Bryan Trottier on Sunday with his 525th
goal, cut the lead to 2-1 when he redirected a shot from the point
by Aki Berg. It was Robitaille's ninth goal, one behind
league-leader Brian Savage of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   It gave the Kings a spark, which carried over to the second
period. They held the Capitals without a shot for the first 11
minutes and tied the game at two on Audette's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kings had just five shots in the period, Audette
made his count. With 12:14 left, Glen Murray took a shot from the
point that sailed wide but right to Audette. The second-line
right-winger had a wide open shot at the goal and easily beat
Kolzig.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS &LR;      10-27 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ A four-run lead with Tom Glavine on the mound is no
match for the mystique of the New York Yankees, and apparently
neither are the Atlanta Braves.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nights like Tuesday can make even the most cynical among us
believe the Yankees are indeed a team of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   That something special that makes the Yankees, well, the
Yankees, manifested itself in dramatic fashion in a 6-5
come-from-behind Game 3 victory over the Braves, who are a game
away from elimination in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who took the mound on the heels of a bout with the flu,
made few mistakes in a gutsy effort. But when he did err, the
Yankees made him pay, clawing back into the game with three home
runs, then winning it with a fourth _ Chad Curtis' solo shot deep
to left field off Braves lefty Mike Remlinger in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was special,'' said Curtis, who also homered in the fifth
inning. ``I've never hit a walk-off homer. I've heard people talk
about tingling, but I had never felt that before.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I certainly felt some electricity running through my body
as I rounded second base, and then seeing my teammates waiting for
me at home plate was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch's game-tying two-run homer in the eighth
preceded Curtis' heroics.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Yankee mystique comes into play.
</P>
<P>
   On some nights and in some ballparks, Braves right fielder Brian
Jordan might have pulled Knoblauch's ball back into play. But as if
little Jeffrey Maher _ the unsuspecting hero of the 1996 American
League Championship Series _ were there to give it a helping hand,
the ball glanced off Jordan's glove and over the wall for a home
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got beat with a pop-up to right field,'' Braves manager
Bobby Cox said. ``It was a Yankee Stadium home run. The ball went
315 (feet), and it was a home run. That's the way it is here. The
last one was tagged, but I didn't even think (Knoblauch's homer)
was close to the wall. Three hundred and fifteen feet is an out in
my book, but that's not the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Knoblauch responded: ``I'm glad I hit in Yankee
Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees can clinch their second World Series title in as
many years with a victory tonight behind five-time Cy Young Award
winner Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly not your average pitcher,'' Cox said of
Clemens. ``This was a big one to lose. We were going to get right
back in this thing. We could easily be up 2-1 (in the best-of-seven
series) instead of down 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we're down to where you really have to run the table. It
would have been nice to win tonight's ballgame. But we've still got
our rotation intact. We've swept teams before, just not in the
World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have; in fact, they did it last season, and they
have won 11 consecutive World Series games dating to 1996 when they
won Games 3, 4, 5 and 6 to close out the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves aren't going to just give up,'' Yankees manager Joe
Torre said. ``I expect them to come out fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' rally overshadowed a comeback of sorts for the
Braves' offense, which awoke from a deep sleep with 14 hits,
including 10 off New York starter Andy Pettitte, who allowed five
runs in 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Braves only three innings against Pettitte to equal
their hit total for the first two games (seven). Gerald Williams
and Bret Boone opened the game with back-to-back hits, and Williams
scored on Chipper Jones' grounder to third. The Braves managed only
two hits in 14 innings off the Yankees' starters in the first two
games of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees halted the Braves' momentum, if only for a moment,
scoring a first-inning run of their own on Paul O'Neill's
opposite-field single. But Atlanta proved its first-inning
exhibition of actually putting runners on base was no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Boone led off the third with the second of his three doubles and
scored on Jordan's single to right. Braves designated hitter Jose
Hernandez capped the third-inning spree with a two-run double.
Boone's third double drove home the Braves' fifth run in the fourth
and made him the first player to hit three doubles in a World
Series game since Brooklyn's Jim Gilliam did it in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went quiet for a while after O'Neill's first-inning
single, collecting just two hits in the next 14 at-bats, including
the first postseason homer of Curtis' career. Curtis, who was
almost left off the World Series roster, belted a solo homer over
the right-field wall with two out in the fifth to cut the Braves'
lead to 5-2. Tino Martinez's seventh-inning solo homer pulled the
Yankees within two.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were down 5-1, it was a little quiet in the dugout,''
Torre said. ``The highest compliment I can pay to our team is that
we don't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest blow was Knoblauch's deja vu homer in the eighth.
The Bellaire High School product also hit a game-tying homer off
San Diego's Donne Wall in Game 1 of the 1998 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a pattern, I hope it continues (tonight),'' Knoblauch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Second-guessers questioned whether Cox left Glavine in the game
too long, but the Braves manager defended his pitching choices,
which included two innings by closer John Rocker sandwiched between
Glavine and Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Glavine was throwing great,'' Cox said. ``He didn't want
to come out. I asked if he was tired, and he said he was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yankees' bullpen shut out the Braves on four hits
over 6 innings. Mariano Rivera worked the final two innings for the
victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
