<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-BOMBING (Undated) _ A close look at the U.S. decision to
attack pharmaceutical plan in Sudan's capital, Khartoum, in
response to the bombings of the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania. A Special Report by James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OBESITY-HORMONE (Undated) _ In 1994, researchers discovered
leptin, a hormone that seemed to make fat mice slim. The following
year, to much fanfare, it was announced that humans made leptin
too, raising hopes that the hormone might do the same thing for
people that it did for the mice. But on Tuesday, the first
published clinical study of leptin finds that the substance is not
the weight loss panacea that obesity researchers had hoped for. By
Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LUNG-TEST (Gaithersburg, Md.) _ A new lung cancer screening
test looks so exciting that patients are starting to demand it and
hospitals are starting to advertise that they have it. But there is
a problem: no one has shown that finding lung cancers early with
the test actually saves lives. So the National Cancer Institute is
bringing a group of experts together on Tuesday to ask whether the
government can seize this historical moment in time, before the
test becomes so widespread that it is impossible to assess it, and
start a large study to see if it works. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-TONE (Washington) _ For the first time in more than a
decade, the fight for the Democratic presidential nomination has
triggered a fierce competition for the loyalties of its once
embattled liberal wing. And the catalyst for the struggle is
clearly Bill Bradley, who has consistently positioned himself to
the left of his lone rival, Vice President Al Gore, on a wide range
of issues, from gay rights to health care to child poverty to
criminal justice. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-IMAGE (Nashua, N.H.) _ The vice president, newly energized
by his opponent's viability in New Hampshire, has refashioned his
approach to voters, meeting in small groups, walking the streets,
shedding his huge entourage along with his reserve, making like a
regular guy. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIVACY _ President Clinton will soon propose sweeping
new federal regulations to protect the privacy of billions of
medical records and will assail Congress for failing to enact any
safeguards, administration officials said Tuesday. Exclusive. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Intel and Microsoft are added to the
Dow Jones industrial average _ the first Nasdaq stocks to be
included. Home Depot and SBC are also added to the 30 stocks that
make up the Dow, the most closely followed market barometer.
Chevron, Goodyear, Sears and Union Carbide are getting the boot.
The changes take effect on Nov. 1. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-NETWORKING (Undated) _ Janet Tiebout Hanson had been one
of just a few women professionals at Goldman, Sachs, where her male
colleagues had honed networking over the decades into a science.
But women like her who left, staying at home with their children
for a few years, later found their Rolodexes out of date and their
skills rusty. Why not, Ms. Hanson mused, jump-start the networking
process for them? So Ms. Hanson created an organization two years
ago called 85 Broads, a playful reference to the firm's location on
85 Broad Street. ``The reason I can do this is that I made it out
of Goldman into a successful entrepreneurial experience,'' Ms.
Hanson said. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
