<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TAKE 3-0 SERIES LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time the New York Yankees extended a World
Series winning streak to 11 games, Babe Ruth stood at home plate,
gestured with his arm in front of him, and hit what history knows
as the ``Called Shot'' home run.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, 67 years later, the Yankees ran another Series
winning streak to 11. Their method was no less extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis led off the bottom of the 10th inning with his
second home run of the night, giving New York a 6-5 victory over
the Atlanta Braves and a 3-0 lead in the World Series. No team in
baseball history has overcome such a deficit to win a postseason
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit a walk-off home run,'' said Curtis, a
journeyman who didn't even play in last year's World Series. ``And
I've heard people talk about tingling, (but) I've never felt that
before. I think somewhere between second and third I felt like
there was electricity running through my legs.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer, off reliever Mike Remlinger, was Curtis' second of
the night, and he knew it was gone as soon as he connected. He
flipped the bat as the ball sailed over the fence in left-center,
raising both arms in the air. As the Yankees streamed from the
dugout to greet him, police officers _ some on horseback _ streamed
from the bullpen area to ring the field.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no trouble, only joy for the Yankees, who can
complete a sweep in Game 4 Wednesday night. A win would give them
12 Series victories in a row, tying a record they set with sweeps
in 1927, '28 and '32.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, the eighth-place hitter, bats right-handed and started
because the Braves pitched a left-hander, Tom Glavine, who was
mostly brilliant Tuesday night. Glavine was scheduled to start Game
1, but flu-like symptoms pushed him back. He lost seven pounds _
although he re-gained some of it _ and manager Bobby Cox expected
only ``seven good innings.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he got. But because the Yankees were aggressive,
Glavine had thrown just 73 pitches through seven and he told Cox he
was strong enough to start the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're typically a team that takes a lot of pitches and works
the count, so the pitcher gets deep into his pitch count,'' Glavine
said. ``Right from the get-go, they seemed to swing early in the
count. That's fine. I don't mind a team that's doing that, as long
as I'm making my pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   He was from innings 2 through 7, when Glavine was so free of
trouble he worked from the stretch to just two batters. Curtis and
Tino Martinez hit solo homers to narrow the Braves' 5-1 lead, but
Glavine appeared in control as he began the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Then Joe Girardi smacked his first pitch for a leadoff single.
And on a 2-and-0 pitch, Chuck Knoblauch hit a game-tying two-run
homer off the glove of leaping right fielder Brian Jordan, near the
314-foot corner. As Cox put it, ``We got beat with a pop-up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he hit it out at first,'' said Jordan. ``If I
did, I probably would have timed (the jump) better. Once I knew the
ball was over the fence, I thought I could knock it back. I thought
I had it. I thought it was a sno-cone catch.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker, the New York scourge who was booed heartily in
pre-game warm-ups and serenaded with an expletive as he warmed up
in the bullpen, came on in relief. Derek Jeter led off with a
single _ extending his postseason hitting streak to 17 games _ and
Paul O'Neill followed by popping up a bunt that Brian Hunter let
drop. It turned into a double play because O'Neill didn't run,
grimacing and then sprinting for first, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker worked a scoreless ninth before Remlinger relieved him in
the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees overcame a rough start by Andy Pettitte, who allowed
five runs on 10 hits in 32/3 innings. But the Yankees bullpen was
tough.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley worked 21/3 scoreless innings. Ex-Mariner Jeff
Nelson followed with two more. Closer Mariano Rivera, whose 0.39
earned-run average is the best in postseason history, worked
another two.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera fell to his knees in celebration after Game 4 last year,
when the Yankees clinched the championship against San Diego. He
could repeat that scene Wednesday night unless the Braves can
recover.
</P>
<P>
   Said third baseman Chipper Jones in a somber Braves clubhouse,
``We have to try and save face.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
