<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9596 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     10-27 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-CENTURY ARM HAS SHOT TO SHOW IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now it's on the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   A World Series that is all but locked up and in the books has
just a little juice left in it. It's all about the Yankees and
their daunting postseason win streak after their 6-5, 10-inning
victory over Atlanta Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, the 1999 Braves are the 1998 Padres _ a team the
Yankees swept out of October without mercy, without care. That is,
the Braves will be the Padres if Roger Clemens can handle it _ this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, for Game 4, Clemens will make his first World
Series appearance since 1986, opposing Atlanta's John Smoltz. It is
his latest, best chance to create a new postseason image of himself
_ one fitting a five-time Cy Young winner whose (OK, questionable)
selection to the All-Century Team this week all but mandates that
the Rocket deliver now, in October, when it matters.
</P>
<P>
   And now this: A chance for the Rocket to dump a bunch of that
baggage he has dragged around with him since leaving Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that baggage he has carried into this season with the
Yankees, when he struggled, didn't seem to fit in and went 14-10.
He didn't look like the Roger Clemens the Yanks thought they were
trading for back in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Clemens said of what awaits him
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting comment from a guy who has one postseason win in
nine career starts and, worse, whose last start during the American
League Championship Series was an unmitigated nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago at Fenway, there was the 13-year Boston star
Clemens, all alone on the mound he used to own, in the direct line
of fire of the rabid Red Sox fans whose loud, taunting chants of
``Roger, Roger'' might still be echoing between Harvard Square and
Boston's Back Bay.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clemens the ex-Sox hero vs. Boston's new adopted son,
Pedro Martinez. It was the undeniable heart of the ALCS, and
Clemens, barraged by boos and jeers and Boston hits, just plain
crumbled _ as anyone with any shred of emotion would have, given
the weight of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the moment facing Clemens during Game 4 won't feel
like he's toting a Steinway grand piano out to the pitching rubber.
</P>
<P>
   It will only feel like a baby grand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have complete confidence in Roger Clemens,'' Yankees
designated hitter Chili Davis said Tuesday night, when it was clear
the Yanks' 3-0 lead put the burden of an Atlanta clampdown on
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows we're leaning on him. He came here for this. He came
here to win a World Series. What better situation than this?''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   This is Yankee Stadium, a place Clemens used to love to play in
even as a Red Sox. Clemens has had a career-long habit of walking
by Babe Ruth's monument out behind center field and wiping a little
sweat on Ruth's brass replica each time he walked out from the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the newest Yankee has a chance to close down the Braves and
end a long, empty chapter of his own stellar career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tomorrow will be a special day for Roger,'' Yankees
manager Joe Torre said. ``Coming to Yankee Stadium in that Yankee
uniform, there will be a lot of emotion, but there won't be a lot
of baggage. I think that will help him probably focus a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Torre has to hope it helps Clemens focus.
</P>
<P>
   A power pitcher whose chronic ailment has been that he gets so
worked up, Clemens gets so overwrought before most starts that he
can't control his cannon arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (what he does on the mound) is emotion. That's why he
has five Cy Young awards. There's a lot of fire in his belly,''
Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an interesting week for Clemens. After getting raked
in Boston in Game 3 of the ALCS, he has had to wait until Game 4 of
the Series to get his next start _ a situation that doesn't sit
well with his superhyped demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he had a few things to keep himself occupied. While
killing time in Atlanta during Games 1 and 2, Clemens was part of
the All-Century Team ceremonies, having been voted one of the top
30 baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trip, he said, being next to all the old-timers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tremendous. I don't look at myself in that way by any
means. But it means a lot to be around the guys I watched and
really admired. Every time I see Ted Williams, I get choked up. And
the words Ted has for you, they always relate back to hitting in
some way,'' Clemens said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   It is a moment Clemens said he'll never forget. But Clemens has
had more than his share of unforgettable baseball moments, some
like his 20-strikeout wonders and others less pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was in 1986, when he started Game 6 of the World
Series, walked off the field with a lead and then sat in the dugout
and watched the infamous Bill Buckner play that allowed the Mets to
come back and beat the Sox in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was years ago. That was a whole different situation. This
is here and now, so that was the last thing on my mind,'' Clemens
said, trying to forget.
</P>
<P>
   But who would be surprised if some of those memories flashed
before Clemens' eyes this evening, with so much on the line?
</P>
<P>
   The last time Clemens started a World Series game was long ago,
with turmoil and a few failures taking place since.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, in the Bronx, Clemens starts a game in the
World Series again. The Yanks up 3-0. They know what they want and
how to get it. It's just up to Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, his first ring hangs in the balance, riding on
his arm. What a chance.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
