A9619 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS2-LADN-WRIT     10-27 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS2-LADN-WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX A POSSIBLE AT POWER FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ From aging A.C. Green and John Salley to injured
Travis Knight and sometimes-gimpy Robert Horry, the Lakers' options
at power forward are multiple, if somewhat lacking in reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, coach Phil Jackson might throw another free agent
into the mix, but until then he'll take a look at a less
conventional alternative: Rick Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-7 Fox is a natural small forward, but he has the weight
(242 pounds) and muscle to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think playing Rick Fox at the four (power forward)
is better than any of the alternatives that I've had so far,''
Jackson said Tuesday, prior to the Lakers' 95-73 exhibition loss to
the Phoenix Suns at Thomas and Mack Center. ``Even though we give
up a lot of (height) defending the basket, he is a body that can
keep himself between the basket and the player, will box out and do
some things that we need done. We still need to look at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did, using Fox at power forward for the first eight
minutes of the second quarter and most of the fourth. Fox held up
defensively but struggled on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Horry, out the prior two games because of knee problems, started
the game and played 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson likes Fox's work at the position, it could save a
roster spot. It also will ensure the Lakers don't rely too heavily
on the 36-year-old Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to use A.C. for 30 minutes a game and burn him
out early in the year,'' Jackson said. ``I think he's a big
advantage for us coming off the bench and his infusion of energy is
good for us. From that standpoint, I'd like to use him to stabilize
the second unit. He has good knowledge of our offense. And then use
a little more speed and size perhaps (in the starting lineup) in
Robert Horry, if it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is also ready to take on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a position that I'm afraid of or suspect that I'll
live there the whole season. But I welcome it,'' he said. ``Just
getting on the floor, I'm OK with regardless of where it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Warming Rice: Glen Rice played his best game of the
exhibition season, scoring 21 points on 6-of-13 shooting, with four
3-pointers. The timing was perfect; Jackson was outwardly concerned
about his sharpshooter's slow start, particularly with Kobe Bryant
expected to miss the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need scoring from Glen. We need a couple guys to help Shaq
(O'Neal) out in scoring . . . because we're not going to get 100
points too often right now with the lineup we've got,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tidbits: O'Neal, who hadn't made consecutive free throws in
any game this exhibition season, did it three times Tuesday and hit
7 of his first 8 foul shots in the game. He finished 12 of 17 from
the line but made just 7 of 22 field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson decided to give veteran Ron Harper a day off and started
Brian Shaw in his place. Derek Fisher, suffering from flu-like
symptoms, was limited to 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   __ Housewarming: The Lakers will practice at Staples Center for
the first time today. Jackson wants his players to get accustomed
to the new arena before their home opener next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Staples Center is a massive cavern,'' Jackson said, ``and
to play inside of a place like that is a big change for players
that are used to compact courts. There's going to be some things
that are great homecourt advantages, but it's going to take us a
while to get used to it too. And the fact that we're sharing it
with another team in town is significant. It's not really our
homecourt. It's going to have to be something we make our
homecourt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
