<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSE BACKS CLINTON PLAN TO BAN INTERNET TAXES  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Seldom do House Republicans and President
Clinton agree on anything these days.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the House voted 423 to 1 to endorse a key White
House objective heading into a new round of global trade talks next
month: a worldwide ban on Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has little substantive effect, merely voicing a ``sense
of the Congress.'' But it signals a GOP embrace of what could prove
the most far-reaching policy of the Clinton administration, which
has set out to make the Internet a ``global free-trade zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible to me that we can have essentially a unanimous
vote on such a sturdy policy of no taxes in America or around the
world on e-commerce,'' said Chris Cox, the conservative Newport
Beach Republican who sponsored the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious White House agenda, first outlined two years ago
as a ``Framework for Global Electronic Commerce,'' amounts to a
free-market manifesto calling on governments to forgo regulation
and taxation of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the Internet has such explosive potential for
prosperity, it should be a global free-trade zone,'' Clinton
declared at the time, ``a place where government makes every effort
first ... to do no harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who also authored last year's Internet Tax Freedom Act that
imposed a three-year moratorium on domestic Internet taxes, said in
an interview that the idea is one area where he fully agrees with
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the administration's Internet policy was developed
by former White House policy guru Ira Magaziner, who devised the
complex health care plan that nearly sank Clinton's first term and
helped usher in the GOP congressional majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is undoubtedly the case that Ira learned from the health
care task force how not to develop a legislative program,'' Cox
said, calling Magaziner's Internet framework ``an excellent
product.''
</P>
<P>
   But since Magaziner left the White House, Cox said, no one is
clearly in charge of Internet policy, and the administration has
not ``shown sufficient support for a permanent ban'' on e-commerce
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``However the administration thinking may be developing on this,
it is opaque,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshevsky
sharply disagreed, saying top officials ``are strongly on record''
advocating ``duty-free cyberspace. It's one of our strongest
messages and one of our firm commitments for the new round of
negotiations. We would take issue with anyone who says that we
haven't made that abundantly clear.''
</P>
<P>
   At Clinton's urging, the World Trade Organization, the group of
135 countries whose trade ministers will meet in Seattle, already
agreed in May 1998 to a moratorium on electronic transmission
taxes, such as the recent U.N. proposal for a so-called ``bit tax''
on e-mails and other electronic data sent over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. idea was quickly shot down, and it is widely expected
that that WTO moratorium will be made permanent.
</P>
<P>
   But once talks get beyond simple transmission taxes, the issues
surrounding Internet trade become hotly controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to handle the problem of digital products'' in the
Seattle talks, Barshevsky said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   These can include Internet-downloaded software, movies, stock
trading, banking and professional services such as law,
architecture and consulting _ areas where the United States has a
commanding export advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormous field, and WTO rules with respect to
digitized content are not clear,'' Barshevsky said. Rules on
patents, trademarks, copyrights and other intellectual property
sent over the Internet also have to be clarified, she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Aaron, the undersecretary for international trade at the
Department of Commerce, warned last week that the European Union
has made its support for the tax moratorium contingent on nine
other items that ``could pave the way for duties in the future,''
including labeling all electronic deliveries as ``services,'' to
permit trade restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The area of Internet content is even murkier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French and Canadians are already arguing that cultural
industries should be exempt'' from any moratorium, including music,
television and movies, said Tim Bennett, vice president for trade
at the American Electronics Association.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Local Taxes Possible
</P>
<P>
   Even if national governments forgo e-commerce taxes, their own
localities may not. U.S. state governors continue to press hard for
the authority to impose sales taxes on interstate e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Cox issued a blunt warning to the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce, which was established by his legislation.
``It's an advisory commission; it will only give us advice,'' Cox
said. ``So the real question is what would happen if they
recommended taxing the Internet, and I can tell you the answer: It
would die a horrible death in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   While no country imposes taxes on e-commerce, Cox maintained
that governments will try. ``Birds fly, fish swim, and government
taxes and regulates,'' Cox said, adding that his domestic
moratorium demonstrated that it is easier to prevent taxes than to
roll them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal has been to occupy the field with a policy
prescription that says this is off limits,'' he said. ``If we had
waited until this became pandemic, then the forces of the political
status quo would have overwhelmed us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
