<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-ECONOMY28-CO     10-27 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ECONOMY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY: INTERNET ECONOMY TO TOP $500 BILLION IN 1999
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The booming Internet economy has grown ``at an
astounding rate'' of 68 percent since last year and is on track to
generate $507 billion in revenue this year, University of Texas
researchers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the overall economy grows at (an annual rate of) 4
percent, we'd say it's 'hot,' `` Anitesh Barua, associate director
of the Center for Research on Electronic Commerce at the
university's Graduate School of Business, noted Tuesday. He is the
co-author of the study along with the center's director, Andrew
Whinston.
</P>
<P>
   While the Internet makes up only a small part of the nation's $8
trillion economy, the study suggests it has surpassed such
traditional sectors as automobiles telecommunications and
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers,'' Barua said in an interview here, ``suggest
that we are finally seeing some of the payoffs from having built
out the Internet infrastructure _ and it's still going strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid rise was led by electronic commerce, whose revenues
rose 127 percent from $16.5 billion in the first quarter of 1998 to
$37.5 billion in the same quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the Internet accounted for 2.3 million
jobs in the first quarter of 1999, up from 1.5 million a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing these increases even though we do not as yet
have widespread use of broadband Internet technology,'' Barua said.
``Nevertheless, the commerce layer (of the Internet) is going
through the roof, and that's a very good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not suggesting that all of the security hurdles have
been overcome,'' he added. ``But the fear of the unknown is by and
large gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The next big online breakthrough may come through expanded use
of ``smart'' telephones, the Austin-based researchers suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are familiar with wireless devices and will use them to
buy things on the Internet, schedule their flights and so forth,''
said Whinston. ``To many people, it's something that doesn't seem
to be a computer. It's more like a telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Whinston and Barua compiled their results by observing 3,400
U.S. companies that generate all or part of their revenues from
Internet products or services. Some of their data was gleaned using
reports from research companies, financial reports and the Web
sites of 350 of the largest firms.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's findings update an initial report issued in June and
paid for by Cisco Systems. That study found the Internet accounted
for $301 billion in revenue in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shapiro, an undersecretary at the U.S. Commerce
Department, said the Internet is growing so fast because ``it is a
potentially incredibly efficient way to reach an enormous market.''
</P>
<P>
   He viewed University of Texas study as a useful, if broad,
measure of current trends. Both the Census Bureau and the Bureau of
Economic Analysis _ arms of the Commerce Department _ produce
measures of e-commerce activity that track closely with the Austin
results. The department plans to issue its first measure of
e-commerce retail trade early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers divided the Internet into four layers:
infrastructure, applications, intermediaries and commerce. They
view the interplay of these layers as the Internet ``ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   All four layers exhibited strong growth since early 1998. Total
revenue from the infrastructure and applications layers came to $63
billion in the first quarter of this year, while the intermediary
and commerce layers contributed $55 billion.
</P>
<P>
   After correcting for overlapping factors, the study pegged
Internet revenues in the first quarter at $108 billion, a 68
percent leap from the prior year.
</P>
<P>
   As defined by the researchers, the Internet economy is made up
of companies that generate all or part of their revenues from
Internet-related products and services, such as Cisco, Dell
Computer Corp. and IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   To this group, they add both pure Internet sellers such as
Amazon.com and eToys.com and the cyberspace business of such
traditional companies as L.L. Bean and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The complete updated 95-page study is available on line at www.
internetindicators.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
