<HEADER>
A9754 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-ROCKER-HOMETOWN28     10-27 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-HOMETOWN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Call this school Rockerville
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ In Jim Turner's worn leather wallet is a ticket
stub from John Rocker's first game in a Braves uniform, from spring
training on March 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carry it around just to remind me that dreams can happen,''
says Turner, Rocker's old high school baseball coach at First
Presbyterian Day School.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, hand-lettered banners around the 746-student campus
heralded the school's most famous graduate, a former pitcher for
their very own Vikings: ``LET'S ROCK(ER) THE WORLD!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker attended the school from first grade, earning A's and B's
as well as respect as an athlete before graduating in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been real excited about watching John and thinking
that we've had a part in his life,'' principal Joe Childs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous every time he gets up there,'' said Lyn Wiggins,
Rocker's former English teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neat,'' said Harris Lee, a senior and a Vikings shortstop
and pitcher. ``I go to the same school. He always comes down in the
offseason to give us tips.''
</P>
<P>
   Rashad Eldridge, also a senior ballplayer, once got into some
trouble he doesn't want to discuss. Rocker heard about it and
confronted the center fielder on one of his visits to Macon. ``He
got in my face yelling and letting me know I have potential to be a
high draft pick and don't let that go to waste. I took that to
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, dreams can happen. Turner, a high school baseball
coach for 17 years, once dreamed of playing professional ball
himself. He made it as far as Class A for the Cincinnati Reds. Now,
he admits to living a little through Rocker. On Saturday, he
traveled to Atlanta to watch Rocker in the first game of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The $150 ticket was a gift from Rocker to the coach, who stopped
by the Braves' dugout and flashed Rocker an encouraging hand signal
the two men understand as ``too legit to quit.'' ``See ya after the
game,'' Rocker called. But afterward reporters crushed around
Rocker, and Turner had to get back to Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's father coached Little League, and one of the fields in
Macon is named after him. So, little John Rocker played on that
Turner Field long before he stepped onto Atlanta's. ``The kids
didn't want to play catch with him because he threw so hard,''
Turner said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have much control,'' remembered Chris Wilson, a
friend who was in Rocker's graduating class and now teaches
physical education at the school. ``So you knew that if he hit you,
it was going to cause you some pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in elementary PE, he was very intense,'' said Childs, who
taught that class to young Rocker. ``He was the type of kid who
would get upset if his team lost in kickball. He did not take
losing gently.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, in high school, Rocker's coaches told him to walk a
player. Rocker didn't want to; he wanted to strike him out. No,
they said. To which, Turner said, Rocker replied something like:
``Then let me just hit him, so he'll earn first base.'' He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching Rocker in high school had its rewards and trying
moments. Turner routinely disciplined him for throwing his helmet
and made Rocker do ``pickups,'' scrambling one way and then another
for the ball. ``He'd get up into the 300s probably by the end of
the season,'' Turner said. ``He probably holds that record, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Turner tried to set Rocker straight was after the
ballplayer made national news for cursing the Mets and their fans.
``I wasn't real pleased about it,'' Turner said. He met Rocker in
the Braves' locker room the night the team won the championship
series. ``We talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Turner, a fatherly presence with his players who teaches
Bible classes, isn't all disciplinarian. He is profoundly proud of
Rocker and pointed out that the school has retired his No. 21
jersey _ and the mitt his teammates used to catch his pitches. They
are encased in glass in a busy corridor.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Turner was wondering if he should travel to New York.
He's never been to New York, and the idea ``sort of scares me,'' he
said with another laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the man has a ticket to dream. ``John on the mound
getting a save for the seventh game _ that would be my dream,''
Turner said. ``I'm sure it's his dream, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Young Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
