<HEADER>
A9755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-NUTS28-COX     10-27 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NUTS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The nut gallery
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Maybe the squirrels have the right idea
stocking up on nuts and seeds during the fall. After all, we've got
holiday baking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But think outside the shell for a moment. Savories as well as
sweets benefit from a crunch, and a flavor that's unique. Where
better to get it than from a food that's good for you, as well as
tasty?
</P>
<P>
   Nut-crusted fish and shellfish star on many menus. Nuts
accentuate stir-fry dishes. Try them tossed in a pasta salad or hot
pasta dish, or sprinkle some on top of a cream soup for texture
(hazelnuts marry well with potato soup; pecans perk up pumpkin
bisque).
</P>
<P>
   Nuts sometimes get a bad rap for their high oil content, but
they're packed with protein and beneficial acids. They taste great
with no additives, so you're not munching on empty calories. And
what about that oil? Nutritionists agree it's healthy _
plant-based, with no processing _ and the amount normally used in
recipes is slight.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're stuck on the old favorites, such as walnuts, pecans
and almonds. Look at the variety the nut bin offers today: black
walnuts from Virginia, pine nuts from Italy, hazelnuts from Oregon
and pistachios from the Middle East. Move over to the seeds, and
discover sunflower and pumpkin seeds roasted in different oils for
additional flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Fall is typically the nut harvest in America. Our holidays are
rich with nutty foods such as pecan and walnut pies for
Thanksgiving, cinnamon-nut filled rugalach for Hanukkah or nutty
fruitcakes at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   American cooks have long enjoyed a variety of nuts. Black
walnuts found their way into Colonial recipes; chestnuts were
abundant up until this century and pecans covered the Southern
states.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, the almond, walnut and hazelnut trees were
harvested by cooks during the gold mining era.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii is still the main producer of macadamias. America's
mainland cooks weren't so familiar with them until Debbie Fields
added them to chocolate chip cookies and popularity boomed.
</P>
<P>
   Pine nuts, or pignoli, joined our pantries during the Italian
food craze. A renewed interest in classic French dishes
reintroduced us to Europe's beloved hazelnut. Chestnuts also pop up
occasionally on haute menus. Look for them to be the nut darling of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Home cooks can learn from the chefs who not only chop nuts, but
grind them into nut flour or nut pastes, or toast, roast and fry
them to add to dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Use these tips when working with nuts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Chop them fine when using as a coating, to keep them from
falling off during cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use care when chopping with a food processor _ the nuts can
quickly turn to flour or paste.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add a teaspoon or two of flavored oil to nuts when grinding to
make a nut butter that's delicious as a spread for cooked fish,
chicken or pork.
</P>
<P>
   _ Baking with nuts? Toss them with flour or cinnamon-sugar to
keep them suspended in a batter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toasting nuts before chopping will bring out their best
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   _ All nuts contain oils. To preserve their flavor, they should
be kept refrigerated or frozen. Nuts can become rancid over time
and if exposed to heat.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list that can help you match dishes to nuts, but note
that any nut can be substituted for any other in a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Almonds: Toasting brings out their slight cherry-like flavor.
Makes a delicious nut butter. Classic dish: Green beans amandine.
</P>
<P>
   Cashews: The fruit of this nut is considered a delicacy in the
Caribbean islands, where they grow readily. Cashews are typically
served with stir-fried chicken, but also are delicious toasted,
ground and used as a coating for fish. Make a nut butter to spread
on asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnuts: The English are masters at this meaty nut's use; they
candy them, make them into sweet pastes and serve them roasted.
Delicious with cheese and served with port.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnuts (also called filberts): Coffee drinkers and chocolate
connoisseurs know that hazelnuts mix with bitter, dark flavors.
Sprinkle them over mashed turnips and parsnips, or add them to
spiced carrots and cinnamon-flavored sweet potatoes. Top a pumpkin
pie with lightly toasted, coarsely chopped hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Macadamias: These sweet nuts are so oily, they're sinful. It's
hard to find them without salt, but you can wash them off to toast
them and chop fine for a fish or chicken coating. Crush them well,
and coat shrimp with the nuts and coconut for a tropical flavor, or
make them into a nut butter.
</P>
<P>
   Story from The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
