<HEADER>
A9756 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-NUTS-BOX28-COX     10-27 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS-BOX28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More nutty ideas
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Pecans: The workhorse of the nut family.
Pecans are an oily nut, perfect for toasting. They go into any
cheese dish or any spicy Cajun mixture as well. Chicken or catfish
coated with these are becoming classics on Southern menus. Try a
pecan-cornmeal cake to serve under ham or shrimp at brunch.
</P>
<P>
   Pine nuts: These can go into salads or in hot pasta dishes right
out of the package. Toasted, they're a fine substitute for pecans.
Biscotti made with pine nuts is the perfect accompaniment to
espresso.
</P>
<P>
   Pistachios: The drier quality of this nut makes it ideal for
salads and in dishes where toasting isn't needed. Its green color
is a plus for presentation. Add them to a curried chicken salad
with apples or sprinkle them on top of hummus for a Middle Eastern
twist.
</P>
<P>
   Walnuts: Along with pecans, one of the most versatile nuts. To
some, however, walnuts have a slight bitter flavor. Pair them with
sweeter or saltier foods to overcome this. They toast and fry to
perfection, and their earthy flavor sets off greens, onions and
leeks. Walnut butter works on roast pork that's been cooked with
cranberries, or duck with oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Story from The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
