<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9757 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-NUTS-RECIPES28-COX     10-27 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS-RECIPES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nuts add crunch, flavor to many dishes
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Want to get nutty with your recipes?
Here are some ideas.
</P>
<P>
   HAZELNUT-VEGETABLE PIE
</P>
<P>
   1cup fresh broccoli, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1cup cauliflower, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2cups fresh spinach, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2green pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   1cup cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   1cup coarsely chopped hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1cup biscuit mix
</P>
<P>
   4eggs
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pre-cook broccoli and cauliflower until almost tender (about 5
minutes). Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Mix broccoli, cauliflower, spinach, onion, green pepper and
cheese and put into a well-greased 10-inch pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   Top with hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Beat together the milk, biscuit mix, eggs, garlic salt and
pepper; pour over hazelnuts and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 400 degrees for 35 to 40 minutes; let pie stand 5
minutes before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   PORK ROAST WITH APPLE PISTACHIO DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   4pounds boneless loin of pork
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon powdered ginger
</P>
<P>
   1cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   3tart apples, peeled, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   5cups dried bread cubes
</P>
<P>
   4eggs
</P>
<P>
   1cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup pistachio nuts
</P>
<P>
   Remove pork from refrigerator one hour before roasting.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the loin of excess fat and rub surface with salt, pepper
and ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a shallow roasting pan that will hold the roast with no
more than 3 to 4 inches of space between the roast and the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Don't use a rack.
</P>
<P>
   Roast for 25 minutes at 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Add onions and roast 5 to 10 additional minutes, until onions
are lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Add wine, diced apple and bread cubes to the onions in the pan
and roast for 25 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs and milk together and stir into mixture in roasting
pan. Stir in nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Roast for additional 25 minutes or until pork is done.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes from ``The Book Of Edible Nuts'' by Frederic Rosengarten
Jr. (Walker and Company, New York)
</P>
<P>
   JADE BROCCOLI WITH PECANS
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2cups peeled and shredded broccoli stalks (from about 3
pounds broccoli)
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4very thin slices prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1/2 tablespoon of butter in a small skillet over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pecans and saute until lightly browned, 2 to 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a plate to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Steam the broccoli until just tender, about 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain well and toss with the remaining 3 tablespoons butter and
the salt.
</P>
<P>
   Mound the broccoli on plates or in bowls and sprinkle the pecans
on top.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the slices of prosciutto alongside and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Best American Recipes 1999,'' Fran McCullough and
Suzanne (Hamlin Houghton Mifflin Company, Boston - New York)
SAFFRON PASTINA WITH CURRANTS, PINE NUTS AND MINT
</P>
<P>
   For the saffron dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon crumbled saffron threads
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the pasta:
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1pound tiny pasta (pastina)
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup dried currants, soaked in hot water until plumped, then
drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Orange flower water (available where bar mixes are sold)
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint sprigs or leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Pomegranate seeds for garnish, optional
</P>
<P>
   To make the saffron dressing: In a small bowl, combine the
saffron and oil and let stand for about 15 minutes to soften the
saffron.
</P>
<P>
   Add the garlic, lemon juice, cumin, turmeric, sugar and salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Mix well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot, bring 4 quarts water to a rapid boil over high
heat, then stir in the 1 tablespoon salt.
</P>
<P>
   Drop in the pastina and cook, stirring frequently, until tender
but still very firm to the bite.
</P>
<P>
   Drain well, then transfer to a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add the dressing, stir to mix well, and set aside to cool to
room temperature, occasionally stirring the pastina to coat
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Toast the pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pine nuts, drained currants and chopped mint, parsley
and cilantro to the pastina and stir to mix well.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, transfer to a serving bowl or platter, sprinkle
lightly with orange flower water and garnish with mint and
pomegranate seeds (if using).
</P>
<P>
   Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NUT-CRUSTED CHICKEN PINWHEELS WITH FETA CHEESE AND PINE NUTS
</P>
<P>
   2boneless, skinless chicken breast halves, about 1 1/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   2ounces feta cheese with basil and sundried tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup pine nuts, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup walnuts, toasted, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup light or regular mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable spray
</P>
<P>
   Slice chicken breasts horizontally to butterfly. Pound thin
between two sheets of plastic wrap, using meat mallet or bottom of
heavy skillet. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Mix feta cheese with garlic and finely chopped pine nuts. Spread
mixture evenly on flattened chicken breasts. Beginning at one long
side, roll chicken breast tightly, securing with one pick if
needed. Repeat with remaining chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   Coat chicken breasts with mayonnaise, and roll in toasted
walnuts, coating well.
</P>
<P>
   Spray cookie sheet with vegetable spray and place chicken
breasts on sheet. Bake at 450 degrees for 20 to 30 minutes, or
until juices run clear. Remove and let sit for 10 minutes before
slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Slice, in slight diagonal, for pinwheel effect.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3 to 4 as main meal or makes 8 appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from ``75 years of All-Time Favorites,'' Better
Homes and Gardens, Merideth Publishing, 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS SPROUTS WITH MUSTARD-SEED DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   1pint fresh Brussels sprouts, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons honey-mustard
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon mustard seeds, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon Italian dressing or vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Cook Brussels sprouts in boiling water to cover, about 20
minutes or until slightly softened. For best color, do not cover
pot. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Mix remaining ingredients and drizzle over sprouts just before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Basic vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup vinegar or freshly squeezed lemon or lime juice, or a
combination of vinegar and citrus juice
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon freshly ground pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl or jar with a cover, combine the vinegar or juice,
sugar, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk well or cover and shake to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the oil and whisk or shake until emulsified.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, mix the ingredients in a blender.
</P>
<P>
   Use immediately or let stand at room temperature for up to
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: To make walnut vinaigrette, use sherry vinegar or red
wine vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Add about 2 tablespoons finely chopped toasted walnuts and 2
tablespoons minced shallot or fresh chives.
</P>
<P>
   Use 2 parts walnut oil to 1 part high-quality vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
   From ``James McNair's Favorites'' by James McNair (Chronicle
Books, San Francisco)
</P>
