<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN28-COX     10-27 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guru: Shoppers will beat path to your adore
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ True story. Appliance dealer consults a
marketing guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comparison shopping is killing my bottom line,'' he complains.
``After I give a customer my best price, how do I keep them from
going to another dealer to beat it?''
</P>
<P>
   The guru, Tom Feltenstein, founder of the Neighborhood Marketing
Institute of Palm Beach, thinks it over and gets back to the
client: ``Give your shopper two pints of Haagen-Dazs as they leave
the store. They'll have to get home before it melts in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Tom Feltenstein who advised a small furniture
dealer what to do when two larger furniture stores built next door
to him on either side: ``Put up a huge sign that says 'Enter Here.'
``
</P>
<P>
   Also the same Tom Feltenstein who keeps writing books chock full
of relentless good advice, advice so upbeat, life-affirming and
spiritual that you could just upchuck. No, I didn't say that. And
if I did, I didn't mean it. Look, I read every word of ``Life!
Making it Work for You,'' which Feltenstein published in 1990, and
recommended it at the time. And now that the author has come out
with ``Uncommon Wisdom'' (Lebhar-Fridman Books, $29.95 in
hardcover, available through www.amazon.com), I concur entirely
with Dr. Patch Adams, who wrote in a jacket blurb:
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not God, but the financial world surely projects that
message. (Feltenstein's) suggestion is that life's true wealth is
measured in things far more soulful than property.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are 500 ways of saying that goodness and mercy and the
joy of combat can coexist in the same bosom, Feltenstein has found
them. Indeed, when my review copy of ``Uncommon Wisdom'' fell open,
the first words I saw were:
</P>
<P>
   ``Make money. Have fun. Be ethical. These are the three keys to
a successful business career. They were given to me years ago when
I first took a job with a very large hamburger chain headquartered
in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The hamburger chain was McDonald's and Feltenstein was its head
of marketing in the 1970s, leaving to work for Burger King before
finally starting his own consulting company in Palm Beach in 1983.
Today he has 20 employees, hundreds of clients and speaks 100 times
a year.
</P>
<P>
   And he has a message: ``Be kind. In your personal life and your
business life, kindness is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   To cite one example: If you own a restaurant, give all your
employees business cards. Your dishwasher shops, gets his or her
hair cut, meets new people. Why shouldn't he or she enjoy the
pleasure of producing a business card and recommending the employer
when introductions are made?
</P>
<P>
   Kindness improves the bottom line. And if kindness alone doesn't
transport you to the next plateau, it does worlds for this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere in our upbringings, our schooling, our careers,''
laments Feltenstein, ``are we taught to appreciate, to value, to
enjoy, even to love the plateau.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, this is uncommon wisdom, and you can take only so
much of it before you drive to Tom Feltenstein's offices in the
Palm Beach Towers, corner the author in his office and ask him:
</P>
<P>
   Where do you get all this stuff? Do you have a real job or do
you just spend the live-long day jotting down grand thoughts as
fast as you can think them?
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the usual questions Feltenstein fields from
clients, so he smiles tightly and it's five seconds of mental
rummaging before he comes up with just the right morsel of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only teach what you need to learn,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   I reward him with the blank stare this answer deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Feltenstein, a trim 60, bespeaking 30 years of pre-dawn runs,
rocks back in his chair and attempts to explain a life spent in
search of enlightenment while knocking them dead in the Darwinian
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was very metaphysical, a Christian Scientist, and I
have been a searcher on the path my whole life. I read constantly,
but no fiction. Usually self-improvement books, philosophy and
marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   During the McDonald's days, Feltenstein was already wedded to
his belief that nice guys can finish first, but there were times it
was a tough sell, even to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I discovered running in the '60s and meditation. I
had a sign on the door, 'I just need silence for 30 minutes.'
Nobody challenged me because I worked long hours in a heady,
exciting, hip business. I can honestly say I had no setbacks, no
serious illness, nothing to forge me.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his marketing savvy, even the right ad campaign was only
a foot in the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years ago I finally realized that I could bring in
millions of customers, I could put lines around the block. But I
couldn't get them to return unless the employees had self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   And with this epiphany, Feltenstein saw into the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mass marketing is dead. In the future, employers will discover
their internal customer, their own employees. If you treat your
employee as you treat your customer, invest some of your
advertising money in your employees, you will learn the secret of
building repeat business. Now you will have a chance if Wal-Mart
opens up next to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Feltenstein said, quality is a given. Price is
important, and so is service, but the one thing customers are
looking for are businesses that make them feel adored. Saturn has
learned this. So has the Ritz-Carlton. So has the restaurant with
the sign that says ``Ask us for our worst table,'' and then rewards
the patron with a half-price meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kindness,'' repeats Feltenstein, ``is the answer. It begins
with the people who work within your four walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: ronwiggins(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
