A9762 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-BINDI28-COX     10-27 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BINDI28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That karma-hither look
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Has body glitter lost its luster? Do
henna-decorated hands make you want to suppress a yawn?
</P>
<P>
   Bindi may be the answer to your adornment doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   The art of decorating the face and body with colored paints,
powders and jewels, bindi is this year's mendhi, the practice of
henna painting that hit celebrity hands a few seasons back. Think
of bindi as a painless alternative to tattooing and piercing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to decorate their bodies, but they don't want to
do it permanently,'' says Deidra Lynch, an artist with
Orlando-based Henna People.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Gwen Stefani was one of the first performers to get
starry-eyed over bindi, which in its simplest form has been used in
India to signify marriage. Madonna was briefly stuck on the trend,
and Boy George sported bindi during September's fashion shows in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   And a sure sign that a fad has hit the mainstream: Women's
publications start policing it. October's Allure magazine takes
LeAnn Rimes to task for wearing bindis that are the same size as
her earrings. (The three most important rules about bindi:
Proportion, proportion, proportion.)
</P>
<P>
   Do you dare try the look yourself?
</P>
<P>
   First, a few definitions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bindi _ Self-adhesive gemstones, typically worn on the
forehead and between the eyes. The cyclops-style accessory
originates from the red dot worn by married women in India.
</P>
<P>
   _ Body jewels _ Bindis applied to areas other than the face,
including in the belly button.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kumkum _ Made from flower petals, kumkum powder makes the
designs that often surround bindi. They are applied with stencils.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bindi paints _ Colorful paints that are used similiarly to
kumkum.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle Publishing just produced a Bindi Body Art Kit ($24.95)
that contains six washable body paints, 25 reusable stickers and a
booklet of step-by-step instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Henna People sells its bindis over the Internet
(www.thehennapeople.com) and provides an assistance line to talk
bindi wearers through tricky applications.
</P>
<P>
   Four Henna People artists traveled to 39 cities with Lilith Fair
last summer. Artist Lynch told the concertgoers she bindi-ized:
``People are going to smile at you all day, even if they don't know
you. It's like magic dust or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bindi Dos and Don'ts
</P>
<P>
   _ Do keep it in proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each person has to decide that,'' says Deidra Lynch, an artist
with the Orlando-based Henna People. ``Americans have just started
wearing this, so who's to say what's wrong and what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't wear bindis below the neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people try to wear them on their chest or arms, that's
when they lose them,'' Lynch says. ``You'll have a lot fewer
problems if you stick to wearing it above the neckline.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Do match your makeup and clothing to the bindi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark-colored bindis need dramatic makeup,'' writes Beth
Margetts in her Bindi book, part of Tuttle Publishing's Bindi Body
Art Kit. ``Glittery jewels need shimmer and shine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Do choose a bindi that complements your overall look,
``whether hippie chic, glamour puss, minimalist, party girl or
urban street,'' Margetts writes.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: stacisturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
