<HEADER>
A9763 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-UGA-GRANT28-COX     10-27 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GRANT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Dog unleashed: Grant erupts both ways
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athens, Ga. _ Georgia coach Jim Donnan could not resist a little
``I told you so'' after Charles Grant's performance Saturday
against Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs freshman, who plays defensive end and running back,
had a big day on both sides of the ball against the Wildcats. On
offense, Grant carried the ball three times for 44 yards and scored
two touchdowns. On defense, he had seven tackles, five tackles for
loss and three sacks.
</P>
<P>
   The performance earned Grant SEC Defensive Player of the Week
honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most overrated players in the country,''
Donnan said sarcastically. ``At least, that's what everybody keeps
telling me.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan had recently encountered some criticism for over-hyping
Grant and placing unrealistic expectations on the 6-foot-4,
265-pound native of Colquitt. Despite Donnan's early lauding, Grant
didn't get his first start at defensive end until Saturday and saw
only limited playing time in the first five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's been on my derriere ever since I made that little
comment about being excited about him,'' Donnan said. ``But anybody
who's seen him can tell you, that guy's special.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant showed against Kentucky what all the fuss is about,
proving himself both a dominating pass rusher and an explosive
runner. He made his presence known immediately with two
first-quarter sacks and a 1-yard touchdown run. In the fourth
quarter, he ignited the sellout crowd of 86,117 at Sanford Stadium
with a 42-yard TD run on which he leaped over two defenders at the
line of scrimmage, broke a tackle, then outran a defensive back for
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he ``had fun'' playing offense but was most proud of
his defensive performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting all those sacks, that's what I really liked,''he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs were having trouble pressuring opposing
quarterbacks before Saturday. They came into the game with just 12,
last in the SEC, before getting 11 against Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The question becomes, what took Georgia so long to start Grant?
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rushing the quarterback) is the basic talent, the basic skill
that you need. But, obviously, you have to play within the
system,'' said assistant head coach Joe Kines, who oversees
defensive ends. ``They call something in the huddle and it means
something to (Grant) now. You look back at Champ (Bailey), this was
about the time he started to start. . . . It was just a matter of
time. He's right where he needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant doesn't begrudge the coaches for the time it took him to
fulfill Donnan's prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came in, I didn't know too much about
defense,''he said. ``The coaches made sure I knew everything I
needed to know before they turned me loose. I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kines has worked overtime to keep his star pupil humble, which
hasn't been easy considering he's as impressed as anyone with
Grant's unique abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``God's certainly given him a good set of tools,'' Kines said.
``But it's like I told him: `The only thing we can deal with is
today's practice. Let's concentrate 100 percent on getting better
today, and everything else will take care of itself.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for all the praise Donnan heaped on his early on, Grant just
shrugs and smiles
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider that hype,''Grant said. ``He was just telling
it like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get no argument from Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
