<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9764 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GARY-COOPER28-COX     10-27 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARY-COOPER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For daughter of Gary Cooper, dad was half of incredible family
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was a few years ago that Maria Cooper
Janis began thinking seriously about her father again. Rocky
Cooper, her mother, had a stroke that had taken away her speech,
and one way for mother and daughter to be together was to go over
the family scrapbooks.
</P>
<P>
   The Scotch tape had dried out, and many of the photographs were
loose, so Maria and her mother resealed the photos and wrote
captions for them, with Rocky writing the names of all the people
Maria didn't recognize.
</P>
<P>
   But so many of them were obvious _ there was Hemingway and
Picasso and Ingrid Bergman and Robert Capa, in places such as Paris
and Brentwood and Sun Valley. And, reticently looming over them all
was Maria's father, Gary Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was assembling all this material,'' says Janis, ``and it
started me thinking about the sweep of history and the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Gary Cooper Off Camera'' (Abrams), part
coffee-table book, part biography, part essay on the idea and the
reality of Gary Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be able to tell how it was from my point of view,
and what our family life was like. And the issue of who Gary Cooper
was in an era when fame and fortune makes people go so crazy. He
was the top man in his field until he died, he became an American
icon, and he never lost his sense of values. His sense of
proportion about life, and his priorities were always pretty darn
clear. I wanted to tell that story: that you can have all the
goodies of life and still maintain a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Cooper was the most gravely beautiful of all male stars,
with a moral power that made him the supreme object of
contemplation for directors as varied as Frank Capra, Howard Hawks,
Cecil B. DeMille and Fred Zinnemann.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was the quiet American _ strong and resolute, capable of
doubt, incapable of cruelty. It was the gentleness that set him
apart from actors such as John Wayne and James Stewart, who could
be aggressively harsh. In contrast to them, Cooper was solitary and
shy, with a terrible anxiety at the heart of his personality.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was not a man who brought the office home with him. In
fact, he almost never talked about acting. ``To the extent that
rehearsing would have meant him pacing around his room muttering to
himself or emoting, that was not his style,'' his daughter said.
``He dropped that when he left the studio. Paradoxically, he was
still very much that person you saw on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   The man his daughter describes had a pantheistic connection to
nature, deriving from his childhood in Montana, and would rather go
fishing or hunting than make a movie. At the same time, he was no
bumpkin; educated in England _ his father was a judge _ Cooper knew
art, knew fashion, knew and adored women.
</P>
<P>
   As described by his daughter and virtually everybody who ever
crossed his path, Cooper was an enchanting man, sweet, mild and
unpretentious. But he was also lugging something around with him,
something heavy _ he aged very quickly, was periodically troubled
by ulcers and other manifestations of a nervous disposition, and
died young, at 60.
</P>
<P>
   What was was eating him?
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd always get uptight when he was working. He smoked a lot,
tried to give it up, but never quite could. He was of the school,
if you had a personal problem, you went out alone and figured it
out for yourself. I'm sure he had things that bothered him, but he
felt that you ought to be able to handle it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper loved to read history, didn't care much for fiction, with
the exception of Don Quixote, which deeply appealed to him, and
which he occasionally circled around the idea of playing. His
daughter remembers that, just about the time he was overtaken by
cancer, he was searching for someone to do a screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really terribly funny. He didn't tell jokes, but he had
a very wry, sharp sense of humor, and it filtered in and out of
everyday conversation. His take on things had a very humorous
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was only married once, but his marriage survived stresses
that would decimate most relationships. He was, of course, among
the most attractive men of any era, and was relentlessly pursued by
women. Usually, he allowed himself to be caught.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, in the late '40s, he left his family for several
years while he lived with actress Patricia Neal. But after a couple
of years, he came home and never left again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my parents basically loved each other very much. And
they both respected each other a hell of a lot. When the going got
rough, she did not play the self-pity victim part. She got her act
together, and said, 'I'm gonna live my life for a while.' She did
not sit home and turn to the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``At those times, you have a choice; you can go inside and pull
in, or discover yourself, and gain confidence. She was a great
starter of projects, tremendous imagination, always coming up with
a new project, a new group of people. She was a generator.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was diagnosed with cancer in 1960; after a period of
remission, it came roaring back. He looked at his options. The only
aggressive treatment was cobalt, with terrible side effects. Cooper
said the hell with it, and settled down to die.
</P>
<P>
   So many kids of famous people find it hard to make the
transition to some kind of reality when the light from a great star
fades away. How do you top an act that consists of Gary Cooper and
Ernest Hemingway, that makes everything else seem pallid?
</P>
<P>
   Yet Maria Cooper Janis has been married for nearly 35 years to
the pianist Byron Janis and is well-known in theatrical and
literary circles as one of the sanest, most delightful women
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that goes right to my parents. They put in my mind
from day one what the difference was between false values and the
real thing. They told me right up front, when I was 10 years old,
that life doesn't owe you a goddamn thing. And then they
embellished that by telling me that whatever you want, you have to
earn it, work for it, make your own choices. It's not going to come
to you by divine right.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back on it, we had a very normal family life. I
had a nanny but I had a lot of time with them. We did a lot of
things together; when he wasn't working, we did things together;
sports, athletic things, museums, just hanging out. That was the
norm for me. A couple of times a week, my mother would take me to
the beach, we'd throw sticks into the ocean, walk with the dog. If
Poppa wasn't working, he'd be there. You don't have to go to
Disneyland and spend hundreds of dollars. It's a question of giving
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: scotteyman(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
