<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making a few celestial observations
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ One of my most vivid memories is of sitting
under the stars in Big Bend National Park, more than 20 years ago,
miles away from light pollution, lying flat on my back and staring
goggle-eyed at a sky that one sees all too rarely when living near
a city. My college buddy and I got into this weird riff about how
maybe the whole cosmos was a celestial planetarium in God's
library/study, that what we were seeing wasn't really light years
away, and maybe we were all in miniature _ lots of little
Lilliputians running about with our self-importance and sense of
worth.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe you had to be there_ young, foolish, under the
influence of cheap Mexican beer and unformed minds. Still, the
stars never fail to fascinate me, much like classical music does. I
rarely have a clue what I'm looking at or listening to, but most of
it engages the mind, though not enough for me to go to the effort
to learn more about it. One has to compartmentalize .
</P>
<P>
   So last week's trek to the Stephen F. Austin observatory was a
welcome field trip to a jewel hidden in these Piney Woods. I did a
story for the newspaper a couple of decades ago on the observatory,
the last time I visited. It was impressive then and even more so
now.
</P>
<P>
   The outing was planned by the Grand Poobah of our Nacogdoches
Tennis and Adult Beverage Porch and Deck Club (NTABPDC). He runs
the physics department at SFA. Our tennis group has been getting
together most every Thursday night for seven or eight years to play
what we call old men's doubles tennis. That's somewhat of a
misnomer since there are a few female members who generally try not
to humiliate us graybeards too often _ just enough to keep us
humble. We have a rigid schedule: 90 minutes of tennis that is not
intended to raise one's pulse rate any more than, say, trying to
dash to the car in the rain, followed by 90 minutes of socializing
at a member's house, done on a rotating basis, with the schedule
carefully organized by the above-mentioned Grand Poobah. The man is
a genius at organization, and likely will serve as Grand Poobah for
life.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to the observatory, we chowed down at a fish fry,
the fish coming from a recent non-tennis outing by some members to
the Gulf Coast. I am unwilling to fish, not liking hooks, cleaning
fish or getting seasick, but I'm powerfully fond of eating fish.
You catch it, I'll eat it. That's my motto.
</P>
<P>
   Just after dark, we headed north to the observatory, tucked in
behind the experimental beef farm for a tour conducted by Norm
Markworth, the observatory director, who got a free meal out of the
deal in exchange for conducting the tour.
</P>
<P>
   The observatory boasts a 15-inch telescope, the largest between
McDonald Observatory in West Texas and the East Coast. Markworth
and associates helped build it. There are two other domed
observatories, and a concrete pad with stands for smaller
telescopes. Students had already set up the telescopes oriented
toward stellar attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Markworth first gave a fascinating tour of the sky above,
pointing out constellations with a flashlight that served
surprisingly well as a pointer. He admitted something I've always
wondered about. Hardly anybody sees a bull when they look at
Taurus, or a scorpion, or any of that stuff, save maybe the Big and
Little Dipper. Makes me wonder what those Greeks were smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Through the smaller scopes, one got an amazing glimpse of a
crescent moon, the craters crystal clear. For the first time I saw
Saturn and its rings outside of a photograph, and a hazy view of
Jupiter and one moon that I could pick out. On a computer screen
hooked to one of the big scopes, you could track an asteroid
discovered by an SFA astronomer.
</P>
<P>
   It was beautiful, eerie and fascinating all at once. That cosmos
I once watched while lying in the desert in Big Bend still may be
all one giant planetarium _ God's practical joke _ but that doesn't
make it any less interesting.
</P>
<P>
   I walked out the other night and stared at the sky, trying to
pick out the constellations Markworth pointed out with such
admirable ease. I live far enough out of town to have a decent view
of the sky, though nothing like at the observatory. I spotted the
Big Dipper after first finding the North Star. I'm still hunting
that danged scorpion.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel,
Nacodoches, Texas. E-mail: gborders(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
