<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Only good snakes are dead snakes
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I killed a snake in the yard the other day.
Guess that explains why the dogs were dancing around on their hind
legs and holding up their petticoats.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few days, they had been urgently trying to tell me
about the snake, but I thought they just wanted to come in the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Snakes, as you know, are all six feet long until they are killed
then they tend to shrink. This one shrank to about three feet.
</P>
<P>
   I follow the philosophy that the only good snake is a dead
snake. I probably ended up killing a snake that only eats fleas and
other snakes, but in the heat of the moment, I didn't take the time
to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked later if it had a triangular-shaped head. If a
snake has a tringular-shaped head that means it is either poisonous
or non-poisonous, I forget which.
</P>
<P>
   When I got around to looking at it, its head was shaped more
like a pancake from where I had been hitting it with the flat side
of a hoe.
</P>
<P>
   Is it me or is it the snakes? We just don't seem to get along.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of summers ago, I decided to clean out a storage
cabinet at an old lake house, and get rid of all the busted fishing
tackle, cans of rusted bolts and nails and an old black garden hose
that was rolled up in the back corner.
</P>
<P>
   I was up to my elbows in the cabinet pulling out junk and was
just about to grab that black hose when it started moving.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I started moving.
</P>
<P>
   I got as far away as I could as quickly as I could and wiped a
cold sweat off my forehead. To this day I still shiver at the
thought of that snake lying in wait for me to grab it.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I had composed myself and found a lethal weapon, the
snake had disappeared. I had violated the most sacred law of the
lake: Don't let a snake get away alive.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't about to go looking for a snake I didn't want to see in
the first place, so I closed the cabinet and put thoughts of
cleaning it up out of my mind.
</P>
<P>
   As for that snake I killed the other day, I like to think it was
the same one at the lake. It took him two years to track me down
and now the score has been settled. Snake, 0. Hoe, 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News,
Lufkin, Texas. E-mail: emurray(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
