<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pastor-ized: Minister's skills yield heavenly results
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Ohio _ He's the genial pastor winemaker of Miami County,
but right now, he's standing in the middle of his back yard,
frowning, rain pelting his cap, his thumb and forefinger stroking
his chin.
</P>
<P>
   There's no deep, ecclesiastical debate going on in the mind of
this Episcopalian rector. Mel Schlachter is trying to decide
whether to put his newly crushed red wine blend into an oak barrel
or a 60-gallon plastic container. He's weighing the advantages and
disadvantages. The plastic wins. That decision behind him,
Schlachter moves on, directing a dozen friends in their various
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a year, Schlachter's back yard and basement near downtown
Troy turn into winemaking heaven. He and a group of wine-enthusiast
friends gather to help with the crush of the current year's grapes
and to bottle the fermented fruits of last year's labors. The
friends take home full bottles of wine for their troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Schlachter _ who with his wife, Barbara, is co-rector of Troy's
Trinity Episcopal Church _ has been doing this for nearly a quarter
century, first in the state of New York State and for the past
dozen years in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do this because I love wine and I love social occasions,''
Schlachter said.
</P>
<P>
   That becomes immediately apparent early in the festivities, when
a couple arrives and stands for a moment empty-handed while others
are holding half-full glasses. ``Hello! You need some wine to
gladden the heart and strengthen the spirit,'' Schlachter says,
directing them to glasses and opened wine bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, though, the mood turns a bit more task-oriented, and
Schlachter starts giving orders, asking folks to retrieve buckets,
barrels and bags of sugar. Volunteers begin pouring containers of
fermenting grape ``must'' _ the juice, skins, stems and seeds of
crushed grapes _ into the top of a small wooden press. The
burgundy-colored liquid pours out the bottom into buckets and is
transferred to the 60-gallon plastic container for further
fermentation. The bucket brigade is halting at first, and there are
a few minor spills, but then the volunteers develop a choreographed
rhythm, and only a few drops find the garage floor.
</P>
<P>
   One of the helpers, Corie Schweser of Troy, looks at her
purple-stained hands still wet with wine and sneaks a finger into
her mouth. ``I've been doing this for six or seven years, and it's
a lot of fun,'' Schweser said. ``There's something about making
your own wine. And it makes for great conversation with the rest of
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, when she opens a bottle of wine that she played a part
in creating, the wine tastes just a little better, Schweser said,
noting how her cuticles were stained a bit darker than the rest of
her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Schlachter, overseeing others working the press, catches some of
the partially fermented juice in a glass, tastes it and nods his
head approvingly. Then he offers it around. The liquid _ a blend of
grape varietals Chancellor, Chelois and Leyon-Maillot _ tastes
sweet and tart at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Schlachter brings in most of his grapes and juice from New York
State, but has also made wine from Ohio grapes. Contest judges
think he's doing a pretty good job of it: Schlachter has won a slew
of awards for his wines, including a blue ribbon and a red
(second-place) ribbon for two wines he entered into the 1999 Ohio
State Fair, and a third-place finish in a national American Wine
Society wine judging last November.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the winemaker has decided against bottling last
year's cabernet sauvignon (''It needs more time in barrel to
soften'') and a Champagne-style sparkling wine (''I haven't been
able to get the yeast going . . . if we try to bottle it now, there
wouldn't be any bubbles'').
</P>
<P>
   But, he promises his volunteers, the sparkler should be ready by
New Year's Eve, in case anyone wants to ring in the new millennium
with a champagne toast.
</P>
<P>
   Several people smile and nod, as Schlachter turns his attention
to another vat of gently bubbling liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: markfisher(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
