<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's wrong with a little celebrating?
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hats off (perhaps I should say pants off) to
Matthew McConaughey for heeding most of coach Mack Brown's
suggestions to University of Texas football fans.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is fond of telling the Longhorn faithful to be loud, wear
orange and stay late.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the 29-year-old UT fan and movie star got two out of three
right early Monday morning when police busted him after finding him
dancing buck naked at home in Tarrytown, Texas, while playing the
bongos, according to a police affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey was being loud. Police came to his house around 2:30
a.m. to check out a loud music complaint. He was staying late. I
suspect McConaughey, who hangs out on the sidelines at UT games,
was still celebrating UT's big Saturday win over previously
third-ranked Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   If he was nekkid, however, he couldn't have been wearing orange.
</P>
<P>
   But two out of three ain't bad. I think Brown should give
McConaughey a plaque. Better still, UT regents should light up the
tower orange in his honor _ especially when you consider the guy
had to spend the night in jail after being arrested for allegedly
resisting the officers when they stuffed him in the patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you can't play bongos naked in your own home, is
this really a free country? I spent two years in the Army so that
Americans would be free to play the bongos naked at home.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering why a man of McConaughey's stature
lets himself get in a position like this. I mean, why would a guy
dance nekkid in his house at 2:30 in the morning while another guy
is standing there clapping?
</P>
<P>
   Simple. It's Nebraska's fault.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger the victory, the crazier a serious football fan
becomes. If UT had beaten, say, Rice, McConaughey probably would
have had his pants on when the police arrived to take him to jail.
You just don't take your pants off for beating Rice. Heck, you
don't even play the bongos for Rice.
</P>
<P>
   It works like this: If you beat Florida State, Tennessee or
Nebraska, it's acceptable to take off your pants. But a man of
dignity doesn't remove his pants after defeating SMU, Rutgers or
Bowling Green.
</P>
<P>
   The only time I have leg-wrestled anyone in the '90s was on the
floor at a party in Dallas after UT beat Oklahoma several years
ago. If UT had beaten Tulane, I wouldn't have gotten that drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another disturbing aspect of this case. Police said they
entered McConaughey's home after they saw a bong sitting on the
coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   What are the police doing going into somebody's house because
they see wacky tabacky equipment? If the cops barged into an Austin
home every time they saw the Zig-Zag man smiling at them, this town
would be like the final SWAT team raid scene from the movie ``The
Blues Brothers.'' It would be just ``hut hut hut hut hut'' all over
town.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, police came to McConaughey's Tarrytown house to
answer a complaint about loud music from a neighbor. If McConaughey
had the smarts to live in South Austin, instead of Tarrytown, this
might not have happened.
</P>
<P>
   In South Austin, the neighbors probably would have simply
hollered out the window for McConaughey to turn it down. Or they
would have brought their own bongos over and joined him.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
