<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9769 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN28-COX     10-27 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding a home, and love
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When he was 8 years old, Tony's father dropped
him off at the doorstep of Montgomery County Children Services.
``You aren't wanted,'' he told his son.
</P>
<P>
   That was half a lifetime ago for Tony, who turned 16 Tuesday,
but he will never forget that day. ``I was mad,'' he recalled. And
hurt. And scared.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Tony has been in the custody of Children Services,
where he is among 60 children waiting to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   He recently appeared on Wednesday's Montel Williams Show about
young men and women who were abandoned by their parents. Another
Ohio youth, a 14-year-old from Trotwood, also appeared on the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Caseworkers have prepared Tony for the possibility that the
publicity will spark interest in adoption.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years in foster care, Tony has mixed feelings about
that. He is settled comfortably into a foster home, the
postcard-perfect 120-year-old Brookville farmhouse of Betty and Jim
Terrill. As a ninth-grader at Brookville High School, he loves
playing basketball for the Brookville Blue Devils _ an enthusiasm
that helps him to keep his grades up. He's active in the youth
group of the Brookville First Church of the Nazarene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has fit right in,'' Mrs. Terrill said. ``But he's a good
kid. That's a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his peers, it's not a disadvantage not to come from a
traditional family. ``Nobody talks about their moms and dads,
anyway,'' he said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   But there are times it still hurts not to be with his family.
</P>
<P>
   When Montel Williams interviewers asked, ``What's the hardest
day of your life?'' the answer was easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My birthday,'' he said. ``That's the day your mom had you, and
you're supposed to be with your mom, and not with somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony continued to visit his mother occasionally until two years
ago, when Children Services gained permanent custody. Two years
ago, Tony came to live with the Terrills.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Tony was very quiet, and didn't pay much attention to
the Terrills. ``He figured if he ignored us, maybe we'd just go
away,'' Mrs. Terrill said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't. And Tony hung in there, improving his grades and
adjusting beautifully to his new life in Brookville.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising, given his history, that Tony came to the
family with protective armor, Mrs. Terrill said: ``I think he felt,
'If I just act like they're not there, I won't have to face moving
again. So let's just pretend there's nobody here but me.' That way,
he wouldn't have to face new rules, or fears about fitting in. It's
really scary for these kids, to be put in a new home all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, Tony opened up. ``He's determined to do better with
his life; he doesn't want what he has left behind,'' Mrs. Terrill
said. ``He has shown people he has been able to come out of the
lifestyle he was brought up in and will contribute a lot to
society. He's very thoughtful of the feelings of others.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Terrills are concerned, Tony has a home with them
until he's an adult. The couple keeps in touch with some of the
many children they've fostered in the past 17 years. ``He'll be
welcome here just like our own children,'' Mrs. Terrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony is representative of many ``older'' children who enter the
system. After the age of 10 or so, it becomes increasingly
difficult to place children in adoptive homes, said Ann Stevens,
public information coordinator for Montgomery County Children
Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope for adoption no matter how old the child is,'' Stevens
said. ``They need a sense of belonging, a family to call their own.
Because once they're out of the foster care system, it becomes more
difficult to hold onto permanency for that child. Where do you go
for the holidays? Who do you call when you need help?''
</P>
<P>
   So Tony went to New York City last week, to talk about what it's
like to grow up without a family. It was his first trip to New York
_ ``It was big,'' was his pithy review _ and he seemed both pleased
and overwhelmed by the unaccustomed attention. During the Montel
Williams taping last week, Tony tried not to look at the four or
five cameras pointed his way.
</P>
<P>
   He was showered with gifts. Luggage. A new computer. A Chicago
Bulls jersey. Best of all, a one-day basketball camp with the
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Brookville High School was abuzz with the news of his impending
stardom. How did that make him feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Special,'' he said. ``Usually, none of the upperclassmen
notice you. But older kids were coming up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   What resilience children have, you can't help thinking, when you
look at him, with his copper hair, freckles, shy manner and
disarming Huck Finn grin.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being 8 years old and being told by your father that
nobody wants you.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being 10, and ``too old'' to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what it takes, then, to turn into a good kid. A normal
kid, who loves basketball and alternative music.
</P>
<P>
   What do kids need, I asked Tony, if they're put in the situation
you were in?
</P>
<P>
   ``Courage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. They'll need courage.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll need a home.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
