<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MILNER-COLUMN28-COX     10-27 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting to the bottom of the `cowboy mystique'
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ The cowboy's life has been described in many
different, very different, ways. Movies probably more than any
other medium have shaped our images of how American cowboys looked,
acted, talked and worked. Generally, the movies, as well as most
popular fiction, drew ruggedly romantic pictures of cowboys and
cowboy life. Along the way, however, have been a few portraits that
were closer to the truth _ that cowboy life was hard, unrewarding
in the usual sense of the word, backbreaking hard work, sweatier
than romantic, and lonely. Very lonely.
</P>
<P>
   So, why have men over the years persisted in being cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   John R. Erickson, a real cowboy who attended Harvard and has
been known mainly as the creator of the ``Hank the Cowdog'' books
has written realistically about the cowboy's life and its allure.
One of his best on the subject is titled ``Panhandle Cowboy,''
first published in 1980 and now re-released in hardback by the
University of North Texas Press with a foreword by Larry McMurtry.
</P>
<P>
   If you have any interest in good writing and Texas history and
folklore, don't pass this one up.
</P>
<P>
   In his foreword, McMurtry compares the cowboy life, as described
by Erickson in his book ``Panhandle Cowboy,'' with the life of
desert Arabs. ``Their best qualities,'' McMurtry writes, ``are
forged in extreme conditions. Enrich or suburbanize a Bedouin or a
cowboy and taste, vigor and sense of art are soon lost. Keep them
out where the winds blow, the sands storm, and the animals resist
all reasonable effort and they remain superb workmen, alert,
humorous and subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson's book is regarded as a classic description of cowboy
life. His observations about the Crown Ranch in particular and the
cowboy lifestyle in general, are filled with humor as well as
pathos.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``Along about five o'clock in the afternoon, when we
were so sore and exhausted we wanted to drop in our tracks, we kept
ourselves going with nothing but pride and stubborness and will
power. We taunted each other. We teased. We invented and bellowed
lunatic songs at the top of our lungs. I offer the following as an
example of our doggerel. This verse, one of many which spring from
our fogged brains, celebrated the villain for whom we were working,
ranch owner and trail boss Lawrence. Ellzey:
</P>
<P>
   ``The trail boss's orders inspire us with fear.
</P>
<P>
   He don't pay no wages but he furnishes beer.
</P>
<P>
   Two six-packs a month and a kick in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Yippie-ti-yi-yo, what am I don' here?''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was raised in Perryton in far West Texas. After his
undergraduate work at the University of Texas in Austin he studied
at the Harvard Divinity School. Since returning to his native
state, he has made his living on horseback and writing. As
mentioned above, he is the author of the nationally popular Hank
the Cowdog series, books my teen age grandson has loved since he
was a mere tyke. He also has written a number of non-fiction books
about cowboy life and times and a book titled ``Cowboy Fiddler in
Bob Wills Band'' with Frankie McWhorter. He lives with his family
on his ranch in the Texas Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
