<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9771 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-RAC-HORSE-NOSESTRIPS2     10-27 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-NOSESTRIPS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horses wearing strips win some, lose some
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A winner by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   That long-used racing term has taken on a new meaning, just in
time for the Nov. 6 Breeders' Cup at Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   The company that developed Breathe Right nasal strips for humans
has introduced similar strips to be worn by thoroughbred horses
when they train or race.
</P>
<P>
   After tests at Kansas State University, the manufacturer of the
strips claims they will reduce the amount of energy horses use in
breathing while racing or training.
</P>
<P>
   The Flair strips, placed across the horse's nose, will improve
the flow of air and cut back on bleeding in the lungs, a common
injury to horses, claims CNS Inc., the Minnesota manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   With nose strips, two horses racing as favorites won 10 days ago
at Remington Park in Oklahoma. But the novelty of the new equipment
got the attention of bettors at Keeneland last weekend when long
shots with the adhesive nose pieces won at odds of 33-1 and 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too early to tell if they are making any difference,''
said Dr. Al Smollin, veterinarian for trainer Ralph Ziadie at
Calder. Two horses from Ziadie's barn have raced wearing the
strips. Neither won. During the past 30 days, five Calder horses
have worn the strips in races. All five lost.
</P>
<P>
   The strips will be permitted in the Breeders' Cup, said Calder
steward Charles Camac. As horses are saddled, trainers must notify
track officials if their horses are equipped with Breathe-Right
strips.
</P>
<P>
   There are no indications in the track program or the Daily
Racing Form that horses are wearing the strips. To find out,
bettors must come to the walking ring before the race to see for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Thus is the hard-worker among handicappers better informed,
although it may not lead to a reward at the mutuel windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is always trying to find something new to make the
horses run faster,'' said Chuck Streva, Calder track oddsmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at Gulfstream, one trainer had a blanket over a
horse in the starting gate. For a while, everybody wanted
aerodynamic silks for the jockeys. There's always something going
on. And then you never hear from it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Breathe Right hires jockeys Pat Day and Corey Nakatani to wear
the strips. To introduce the innovation among horses, five-strip
packages were sent to 500 trainers, said Gus Fenton, the CNS Inc.
product development chief.
</P>
<P>
   The strips, 4 inches wide and 6 inches long, are designed to
last for one day and usually come off as the horses are washed.
</P>
<P>
   The strips are being allowed in Florida, Kentucky and Oklahoma.
It was announced that they would be permitted in New York races,
but that has been delayed. ``We need to find out more about their
effect,'' said Terry Meyocks, president of the New York Racing
Association. California has withheld approval of the strips, too.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, strips are permitted during morning workouts.
Reports are scheduled to be made to the NYRA in December outlining
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they hold up in cold weather or hot weather or come off
in the rain or during the race?'' asked Meyocks. ``Will the horses
inhale more dirt deeper into their system? There is a lot we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to go crazy and think it's a panacea,''
Bernie Hettel of the Kentucky Racing Commission told the Lexington
Herald-Leader. ``I don't want people to think that it enhances a
horse's performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this,'' said Smollin, the veterinarian. ``If a horse
wearing one of the nose strips wins a race early in the Breeders'
Cup, by the time the last races come around, every horse with a
saddle on will have a nose strip on too.''
</P>
<P>
   John Crittenden writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
