<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-GROSSADS28-COX     10-27 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GROSSADS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commercials on cutting edge of bad taste
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Never in the history of Madison Avenue has humor been
so over the top _ or under the bottom. Words and images that a few
years ago never would have seen the light of America's living rooms
are suddenly showing up in all manner of TV sales pitches.
</P>
<P>
   In a new ad for Amstel Light beer, three guys in lab coats stand
around a brewery, scratching their heads. One pipes up: ``We didn't
know light beer is supposed to suck.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ad extols the virtues of Brut deodorant: ``Brut has been
considered an effective treatment for erectile dysfunction. Side
effects could include being hit on by models, and increased sexual
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Georgia Department of Transportation has gotten in on
the bad act with an ad to promote car pooling. The commercial ends
with a car horn covering up a profanity in the last line: If the
driver weren't stuck in gridlock he ``wouldn't feel like ----.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies bankrolling these campaigns, and the agencies
producing them, say the ads are in tune with the times, and the
off-color humor makes ads memorable. After Clinton-Lewinsky, Jerry
Springer, shock radio, why shouldn't we have shock advertising?
</P>
<P>
   ``Things become more permissive,'' says Steve Davis, vice
president of marketing at Heineken USA, who signed off on Amstel's
campaign. ``I suppose we could have written the ad as, `We didn't
know light beer isn't supposed to taste very good.' But who would
have remembered that?''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is partially responsible for the new in-your-face
attitude. Cyber start-ups will do virtually anything to get
attention. That includes _ as one company's commercial did _
shooting a gerbil out of a cannon.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial for Beyond.com features a middle-aged guy who,
freed to work at home, walks around the house naked. He even grills
in the back yard _ naked.
</P>
<P>
   Another spot, for E-trade, features a hunky guy who is the kept
lover of an older, ghoulish woman. His face twisted in disgust, he
rubs her bunions. Then comes the pitch: ``E-trade. Be Your Own
Sugar Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Marian Salzman, who follows trends for Young &AMP; Rubicam, says
it's no surprise that Internet companies are on the cutting edge of
bad taste. Since they're start-ups, they have no reputation to
tarnish, but they need to be heard in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have very little to lose, except time,'' says Salzman.
</P>
<P>
   The raunch factor goes beyond dot-coms, however. There's the
phallic-themed Kia SUV ad, for instance, which talks of cars in
sexual terms _ a woman soothes the male driver of a competitor's
SUV as if he were impotent _ and ends with a ``size matters'' joke.
And there's the campaign urging car-pooling by the Georgia DOT.
</P>
<P>
   Dull directives had been ineffective in the past, so Atlanta
agency Turner Fernandez Turner came up with ``Johnny the lonely
commuter.'' He's stuck in traffic, fuming, while a hippie guitarist
sings his scatological song.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the best way to get that message across was humor
like in the old-fashioned Warner Bros. cartoon, the character
Yosemite Sam,'' says Vicki Gavalas, director of communications for
the DOT. ``He gets angry and frustrated and wanting to say things
he can't say _ just like commuters do stuck in traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial has aired for three weeks. Gavalas says people
who like the commercial outnumber detractors almost two to one.
</P>
<P>
   If a child asks what that bleeped word is that almost rhymes
with ``grip,'' the DOT official suggests: ``Tell them `grit.'
That's what I told my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffry Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
