<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, October 28, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Pete Rose, late of the Cincinnati Reds,
is a hero for our confused, disparate times. (Rosenfeld, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ John R. Erickson, a real cowboy
who attended Harvard and has been known mainly as the creator of
the ``Hank the Cowdog'' books has written realistically about the
cowboy's life and its allure. One of his best on the subject is
titled ``Panhandle Cowboy,'' first published in 1980 and now
re-released in hardback by the University of North Texas Press with
a foreword by Larry McMurtry. If you have any interest in good
writing and Texas history and folklore, don't pass this one up.
(Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ One of my most vivid
memories is of sitting under the stars in Big Bend National Park,
more than 20 years ago, miles away from light pollution, lying flat
on my back and staring goggle-eyed at a sky that one sees all too
rarely when living near a city. So last week's trek to the Stephen
F. Austin observatory was a welcome field trip to a jewel hidden in
these Piney Woods. (Borders, Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I killed a snake in the yard
the other day. Guess that explains why the dogs were dancing around
on their hind legs and holding up their petticoats. (Murray, Lufkin
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When he was 8 years old, Tony's
father dropped him off at the doorstep of Montgomery County
Children Services. ``You aren't wanted,'' he told his son. That was
half a lifetime ago for Tony, who turned 16 Tuesday, but he will
never forget that day. Ever since, Tony has been in the custody of
Children Services, where he is among 60 children waiting to be
adopted. He recently appeared on Wednesday's Montel Williams Show
about young men and women who were abandoned by their parents.
Caseworkers have prepared Tony for the possibility that the
publicity will spark interest in adoption. After eight years in
foster care, Tony has mixed feelings about that. (McCarty, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELS0-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Hats off (perhaps I should say
pants off) to Matthew McConaughey for heeding most of coach Mack
Brown's suggestions to University of Texas football fans. Brown is
fond of telling the Longhorn faithful to be loud, wear orange and
stay late. Well, the 29-year-old UT fan and movie star got two out
of three right early Monday morning when police busted him after
finding him dancing buck naked at home while playing the bongos,
according to a police affidavit. If you can't play bongos naked in
your own home, is this really a free country? (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIGGINS-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If there are 500 ways
of saying that goodness and mercy and the joy of combat can coexist
in the same bosom, Tom Feltenstein has found them. And the
marketing guru has a message: ``Be kind. In your personal life and
your business life, kindness is the key.'' The one thing customers
are looking for are businesses that make them feel adored.
(Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
