<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1028-     10-27 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1028-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA1028: Beggar's Night can prove tricky in rural
areas
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. A sig/locator map is available.
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKVILLE, Ohio _ In the northwest corner of Montgomery County,
where corn and soybean fields seem to go on forever and driveways
are sometimes a half-mile long, the simple-seeming task of
collecting a little Halloween candy can be a major challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we'll do what we do every year _ we'll climb into
the car and take our daughters Kady, 9, and Kourtney, 12, to
Lewisburg so they can do their trick-or-treating,'' said Randy
Engle, of the nearly 20 mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   Engle's wife, Ieshsa, stocks up on candy every October, just in
case a few trick-or-treaters should happen to find their way to
their rural doorstep. ``But they never do, because we live in the
boondocks, so we end up eating the candy ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the rural areas around Dayton, it has become a Beggar's Night
tradition for kids from the country to travel to nearby towns to
get candy and other goodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear stories all the time about parents who drive their
children (all around this area), so they can trick-or-treat,'' said
Debi Correll, location administrator for Land O' Lakes, a feed and
grain elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Correll didn't have to worry about Halloween candy when she was
growing up in North Dayton. ``We lived in a regular neighborhood,
so going trick-or-treating was just a matter of going
door-to-door,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In several small communities _ including Brookville and
Phillipsburg _ police and firefighters take to the streets to
dispense candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trick-or-treaters come into town from all over the area,''
former Phillipsburg Fire Chief Bob Woolf said. Woolf, 58, who grew
up on a nearby farm, said he didn't know what trick-or-treating was
until he got married and moved into town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never went out looking for candy on Halloween because I was
too darned busy working on the farm,'' he added with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Trick-or-treating isn't a problem for members of the Daryl
Warner family. The Warners, who live on a 60-acre farm, don't
observe Halloween in the traditional manner. Their children,
Lindsay, 10, Landon, 8, and Derek, 6, don't mind a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of taking the kids trick-or-treating, we go to a
harvest festival party that's held at the home of one of the
members (of a local church),'' Kim Warner said. ``It includes a
hayride, games and a cookout. I took Lindsay trick-or-treating a
couple of times, but she didn't care for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Warner, who grew up just down the road from where she now
lives, remembers going trick-or-treating when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole bunch of us kids would pile in the car and our parents
would take us into Brookville to get candy,'' she recalled, adding:
``We always made it a point to go to the houses that gave out the
best stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Randy and Ieshsa Engle are looking forward to another
fun Beggar's Night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dress up in costumes when we take the kids
trick-or-treating,'' he said. ``Last year I was Uncle Fester from
The Addams Family TV show, and she was a witch. We're still trying
to figure out what we're going to be this year.''
</P>
<P>
   _Batz writes for the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
