<SLUG> BC-TV-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV GUIDE JOINS EFFORTS TO LURE HISPANIC MARKET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent marks are needed over o in Univision, o in Galavision
and second i in Utilisima; a tilde is needed over n in Espanol.) 
 
By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Latino influence on U.S. business and culture gets
a significant boost this week with the introduction of a
Spanish-language insert in TV Guide. It follows by one week the
launch of a satellite TV system designed specifically for Spanish
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The insert, which began appearing Monday on newsstands in
specially marked TV Guides, includes Spanish-language interviews
and feature stories.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite system, DirecTV Para Todos, provides Hispanic
viewers access to more than 20 Spanish-language channels ranging
from the familiar (Univision, Telemundo, GEMS, Galavision) to the
exotic (TV Chile, Cine Latino, Canal Sur, Utilisima).
</P>
<P>
   That both developments deal with television should come as no
surprise, since the whiff of ``dinero'' follows large audiences,
and when it comes to television, Latinos love to watch.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Hispanics see an average of 15.3 hours of Spanish
programming and 10 hours of English programming a week, according
to a 1998 study by Market Segment Research and Consulting in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research says there are 8.67 million Hispanic TV
households in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Combine those statistics with a national Hispanic purchasing
power estimated at $375 billion annually, and it becomes clear why
there are campaigns for Latino eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos watch more television on average than the American
viewer, and they're brand-loyal,'' said Chiqui Cartagena, executive
editor of TV Guide en Espanol. ``These things factored in to the
executives of TV Guide saying, `Hey, this seems like a logical
thing to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Top 10 Hispanic TV markets in the United States are Los
Angeles, New York City, Miami, San Francisco-San Jose, Chicago,
Houston, San Antonio, Dallas-Fort Worth, Harlingen-McAllen area in
South Texas, and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide en Espanol is launching in 15 markets. DirecTV Para
Todos is available only in Miami, San Jose/San Francisco and
Houston. (DISH Network, a competing satellite service provider,
offers a less extensive Spanish-language lineup.)
</P>
<P>
   It is significant that both new services are bilingual, said
Cartagena, since three-quarters of the Spanish-speaking population
is bilingual.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between Spanish-dominant and
Spanish-preferred,'' said Cartagena, who was founding editor of
People en Espanol. ``My parents, who have been here 20 years, still
watch Spanish-language television because they feel more
comfortable. They're perfectly fluent in English. It's as if (an
English speaker) would move to Paris. (He'd) probably watch CNN in
English and not the local news.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who subscribe to DirecTV Para Todos get ``some of the
best'' Spanish-language networks from the United States, Latin
America and Spain, said Yolanda Macias, senior director of
programming for the service. Customers can choose between two
packages: a 38-channel lineup (14 in Spanish) for $19.99 a month,
and a 98-channel lineup (21 in Spanish) for $31.99. Both lineups
include seven Spanish music channels.
</P>
<P>
   The dish for the service is more oblong than the standard
18-inch-round dish used by DirecTV's 7.7 million customers. Its
shape enables it to pick up channels off more satellites than the
standard dish. Existing customers who want the Spanish service will
be able to upgrade their equipment, Macias said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, which initially will be available through rack
sales only, may have a tougher go of it than the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Nestor Rodriguez, an associate professor of sociology at the
University of Houston, believes TV Guide en Espanol ``is going to
have to cultivate a market, because those who read English and
Spanish probably read English mainly. Those who read Spanish may be
hard to persuade to read something written primarily in English.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis O'Neill, vice president and publisher of Editor and
Publisher magazine, believes the magazine will be a regional trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pockets, the audience is great,'' said O'Neill, who
previously was president of TV Update, a service that provided TV
listings to newspapers. ``I don't see magazines or TV or major
communication outlets going automatically Hispanic in a major way.
TV Guide is just trying to be aggressive with their product.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's circulation has dropped dramatically during the
past decade. One source said subscriptions have dropped from a high
of about 20 million to 13 million now.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do a Spanish insert for a Spanish market is quite an
operational commitment on their part,'' O'Neill said, ``but the
returns are potentially enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   One early return: Cartagena said ad sales for the insert are
sold out for the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
