<HEADLINE>
ORCHID VARIETIES VARY IN THEIR NEEDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I have two orchids on my covered patio that were in
full bloom when I received them 18 months ago. I did all the things
the directions said to do but have had no blooms since.
</P>
<P>
   The two Norfolk pines at my front steps are growing beautifully
and are 4 feet tall. How can I keep them from freezing? Can they be
cut back?
</P>
<P>
   A: Orchids belong to a highly diverse family, and while they are
not difficult to grow, they do vary somewhat in their cultural
needs. Try to determine which genus and species yours are and you
can be more specific in giving them their requirements. You want to
try to give them an environment as similar to their native habitat
as possible. Perhaps yours do not receive quite enough light.
</P>
<P>
   Most orchids live in the tropics, where many are epiphytes that
use roots to hold onto trees and get nourishment from organic
matter collected along the branches. Each orchid lives at the
height where it gets the light it prefers. All orchids enjoy the
air circulation found in such lofty dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   Terrestrial orchids, on the other hand, find nutrients in
organic matter on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   We can grow epiphytic orchids outdoors (except in cold weather),
on windowsills and in greenhouses. Orchids have fewer roots than
other plants, yet these are highly sensitive and do not like to be
restricted. Therefore, rather than than use soil, growers choose
porous mediums such as bark chips, tree fern fiber and stones.
</P>
<P>
   Watering, of course, is also important. Orchids like wet-dry
cycles _ going from being wet to almost dry. A waterlogged medium
will suffocate the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Watering is determined by the pot type, the medium and the
number of sunny days. Orchid type also is a factor. Orchids with
velamen, a layer of cells covering the roots that helps prevent
moisture loss, require a long, heavy drink.
</P>
<P>
   Cattleyas, the popular ``corsage'' orchids, do not need as much
water as phalaenopsis, the popular moth orchids, because they store
water in thick stems, or pseudobulbs. Therefore, a clay pot would
be more suitable for a cattleya, while a moisture-retentive plastic
container might work for a phalaenopsis. Vandas like their
velamen-coated roots to hang freely and are often grown in charcoal
_ or even in empty wooden baskets, therefore requiring watering
almost every day the sun shines.
</P>
<P>
   There is some variation in light needs among the genera, but too
much light will sunburn any plant. Too little light results in dark
green but weak foliage and no flowers. Orchids can tolerate sun
before 10 a.m. and after 4 p.m., but between those hours the plants
should be in filtered light.
</P>
<P>
   Vandas are at the high end of the light scale and, except during
winter, like to be outside, where they receive good light.
Cattleyas and dendrobriums should also be grown in good light. They
like more light than phalaenopsis, loved for their long-lasting,
mothlike blooms, and paphiopedilums, the lady's slippers, which are
suitable for windowsills since these are on the low end of the
light-requirement scale.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a temperature-bloom relationship among some,
orchids basically are comfortable when we are. Try to avoid
temperatures much below 60 or higher than 90 degrees. Heat
tolerance rises with air circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners apply diluted amounts of fertilizer with almost
every watering. A weak application weekly is an easy schedule to
follow. Dilute a 20-20-20 fertilizer by one-half or one-third of
the manufacturer's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming your Norfolks are in containers, the best thing to
ensure winter survival is to move them to a protected area during a
hard freeze. If you can't do this, generously wrap the pots and
plants and hope for the best. Water the plants well before the
temperatures drop.
</P>
<P>
   You could prune your trees back, but you would ruin the natural
shape. When Norfolks become too tall for their locations, some
gardeners opt to take a foot or 1 1/2 feet off the top and root
this cutting to produce a new plant. While this still results in a
rather misshapen plant, it may not look quite as bad as removing
more than the top. The top cutting should include two tiers of
lateral branches. Remove the bottom branches before planting the
cutting.2\A)4}x &Cx1f;  |
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
