<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FOOD-TROTTER-2NDTAKE-     10-27 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TROTTER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL CHICAGO CHEF JAMS AT THE AMERICAN RESTAURANT'S 25TH
ANNIVERSARY DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   .MDNM/(something, but chefs do it and it's so fleeting and it's
gone.'')
</P>
<P>
   The next quick fix
</P>
<P>
   As Americans learn more about food but cook less, Trotter
predicts chefs will become the next quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February Trotter will open Trotter to Go, a mile from his
restaurant. The take-out concept will feature spit-roasted organic
birds, loins of meat, 35 types of grain, noodle and marinated
vegetable salads, a 100-bottle esoteric wine section, breads and
pastries plus a ``juice bar element.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have time to cook and maybe you've never really
learned to cook and here's a Wolfgang Puck frozen pizza, I've heard
of this guy and I've read a few articles about him in Bon Appetit,
this is probably going to be pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy prepared foods a la Emeril Lagasse and you can expect
southern New Orleans flare. A la Alice Waters and it's going to be
organic and Provencal, clean and vegetable driven.
</P>
<P>
   ``These chefs have kind of carved out these niches, and their
reputation immediately signifies something. If you're not going to
have time to cook at home, wouldn't it be great to have these
products?''
</P>
<P>
   Trotter's first foray into the home kitchen was successful. His
Gourmet Cooking for Dummies (1997, IDG Books Worldwide) sold more
than 100,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``I'm not necessarily interested in the home cook,'' he
says. ``My job is to put together the most flavorful food I can.
I'm not trying to appeal to elite diners either. I'm just trying to
stay true to a point of view and produce food that I personally
would like to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if doing a certain dish at the restaurant involves rare,
esoteric ingredients that would preclude the home cook from doing
that dish, then I'm interested in taking that idea _ that
combination of flavors _ and doing it in a greatly simplified way.
But I'm not out there trying to rope in the mainstream. I can't
think in those terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Books by Trotter
</P>
<P>
   - Charlie Trotter's (Ten Speed Press, 1994) _ A
behind-the-scenes look at the award-winning restaurant, with 72
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   - Charlie Trotter's Vegetables (Ten Speed Press, 1996) _
Passionate about vegetables, Trotter focuses on the shapes and
textures of vegetable artistry. Chapters are divided into the 12
months of the year, and specific vegetables are featured at the
peak of ripeness.
</P>
<P>
   - Charlie Trotter's Seafood (Ten Speed Press, 1997) _ Fish and
seafood are showcased in 75 recipes using more than 80 different
fish and shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   - Charlie Trotter's Desserts (Ten Speed Press, 1998) _ Trotter's
modern dessert presentations are primarily fruit driven.
</P>
<P>
   - Gourmet Cooking for Dummies (IDG Books Worldwide, 1997) _
Trotter goes mainstream with a guidebook to kitchen savvy, complete
with Charlie cartoon faces.
</P>
<P>
   - The Kitchen Sessions With Charlie Trotter (Ten Speed Press,
1999) _ A companion to Trotter's PBS Television series of the same
name, this book is written for the home cook and encourages using
the recipes as a ``framework'' for more spontaneous cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   - Lessons in Excellence From Charlie Trotter (Ten Speed Press,
1999) _ Written by Paul Clarke, this business school-style text
uses Charlie Trotter's as a case study on how to run a successful
company.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-roasted salmon with red miso-lemongrass broth Makes 4
servings
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 large turnip, peeled and cut into batons
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   1 cup 1-inch-thick leek slices (white part only)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tamari soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red miso
</P>
<P>
   4 (4-ounce) pieces salmon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups watercress, thick stems removed
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the broth: Place the chicken stock, 2 tablespoons of
butter and turnip in a medium saucepan and bring to a simmer. Cook
3 to 4 minutes or until the turnip is about half cooked. Remove the
turnips from the liquid and season to taste with salt and pepper.
Add the lemongrass to the liquid, simmer 7 minutes, strain and
discard the lemongrass. Add the leek to the liquid and cook 7
minutes or until the leeks are soft. Add the rice wine vinegar,
tamari and red miso and cook 2 minutes. Season to taste with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the salmon: Season the salmon with salt and pepper
and rub with the olive oil. Place the turnip batons on a sheet pan
and place the salmon on top. Roast in the oven at 250 degrees 15 to
20 minutes or until the salmon is cooked medium.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the watercress: Wilt the watercress in a hot saute
pan with 2 tablespoons butter 2 minutes and season to taste with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Reheat the broth, if necessary. Place some of the wilted
watercress and turnip batons in the center of each shallow bowl and
top with a piece of the salmon. Ladle some of the warm broth in the
bowls and over the salmon. Top with freshly ground pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Wine note: An Austrian Riesling is a great match for the red
miso-lemongrass broth. The full-bodied, dry and intensely aromatic
style by producers like Prager and Knoll is a wonderful complement
to the haunting flavors in this dish. For the perfect pairing, try
a Prager ``Steinriegl'' Federspiel Riesling.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 331 calories (62 percent from fat), 23 grams total
fat (9 grams saturated), 90 milligrams cholesterol, 6 grams
carbohydrates, 25 grams protein, 1,703 milligrams sodium, 1 gram
dietary fiber.  &LR; hd32:Turn gourmet into OK
</P>
<P>
   - Use the supermarket as your prep kitchen. Buy a roast chicken
or marinated vegetable salald from the deli but ``tweak them up.''
Add some sauteed chopped garlic, a fresh herb or baby greens.
</P>
<P>
   - Plate foods in attractive ways _ stack a couple of
ingredients, for example, or garnish with a contrasting-colored
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   - Create textural contrasts with crispy and soft foods.
</P>
<P>
   - Take time to cut vegetables into even, precise cuts.
</P>
<P>
   - Cook foods separately before tossing them together.
</P>
<P>
   - Shock blanched vegetables in ice water to stop the cooking
process.
</P>
<P>
   - Take risks with your recipes!
</P>
<P>
   _ Excerpted from Gourmet Cooking for Dummies (IDG Books, 1997)
by Charlie Trotter
</P>
<P>
   The American Name Game.
</P>
<P>
   Big names. Big food. Big wine.
</P>
<P>
   For the recent 25th anniversary gala dinner at the American
Restaurant, co-executive chefs Debbie Gold and Michael Smith
invited two chefs: one to represent the American ingenuity of
American chefs, the other to pay homage to European culinary
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The food of Charlie Trotter of Chicago's world-renowned Charlie
Trotter's and Guenter Seeger of Seeger's in Atlanta was paired with
wines from Cakebread Cellars, a family-owned winery in Napa Valley.
The gala benefit raised money to benefit the Children's Center
Campus.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time big names had a hand in shaping
cuisine at the American Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   - James Beard, the late-great culinarian and proponent of
American cuisine, was an early consultant to the restaurant, as was
New York restaurateur Joe Baum whose restaurant concepts included
the fabled Rainbow Room and Windows on the World.
</P>
<P>
   - Architect and interior designer Warren Platner designed the
space that offers breathtaking views of the Kansas City skyline.
Platner also designed Windows on the World in New York's World
Trade Center and Water Tower Place in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The American's first chef was Bradley Ogden, now at the Lark
Creek Inn in Larkspur, Calif. Ogden has been recognized as the chef
who first made the idea of American cuisine respectable.
</P>
<P>
   And what goes around comes around.
</P>
<P>
   - Current co-executive chefs Michael Smith and Debbie Gold met
while working at Charlie Trotter's. Earlier this year the chef duo
was named Best Chefs of the Midwest by the James Beard Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
