<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HORROR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BREED OF HORROR THRILLERS CARVING OUT BETTER STORYLINES,
GRAPHICS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A new breed of vampires, assorted demons and even a
few zombie cows are carving a new image for the horror genre in
computer games.
</P>
<P>
   No longer a nightmarish afterthought in the multibillion-dollar
computer gaming industry, horror-themed games are capable of
creating the terrifying scenes once only found on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   A few highly anticipated titles this year include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nocturne ($49.99, Gathering of Developers and Terminal
Reality), which will hit stores by Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gabriel Knight III: Blood of the Sacred, Blood of the Damned
($49.95, Sierra Studios), arrives this fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vampire: The Masquerade _ Redemption (price not available,
Activision and Nihilistic Software) is expected this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Recent releases, such as System Shock 2 by Looking Glass
Studios, Legacy of Kain: Soul Reaver by Eidos Interactive, or the
darkly humored role-playing game Dungeon Keeper 2 by Bullfrog
Productions Ltd. also have pumped up the genre.
</P>
<P>
   The stale storylines, sluggish technology and lame characters
that held back horror games in the '80s and early '90s are gone. In
the best of these games, players can expect original characters,
breathtaking settings, and the advanced software that allows
boogeymen to jump out of your monitor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHADOWS AND GHOULS
</P>
<P>
   This year, the game that shows how far technology and visuals
have come is Terminal Reality's Nocturne.
</P>
<P>
   The storyline isn't complicated. Players are thrown into a world
where things that go bump in the night are horrifyingly real.
Werewolves, vampires, gargoyles and zombies threaten mankind. It's
up to the ``Stranger'' to keep chaos from reigning.
</P>
<P>
   But what has made Nocturne one of this year's most talked about
computer games is the technology that makes it seem like a horror
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Nocturne's lights, shadows, and fog come close to mimicing real
life. The locations are lush, and nearly photo realistic. The
animation is fluid and natural. Characters, cloth and objects all
behave based on real physical rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these elements hasten the player's willing suspension of
disbelief,'' said Drew Haworth, an artist on the Nocturne
development team. ``So, when you introduce unnatural monsters into
such a realistic environment, you can't help but consider them
real, and therefore very frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   All those effects were possible because of the game engine,
which took Terminal Reality President Mark Randel three years to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nocturne is made up of many different smaller engines, each
with a specific function,'' said Randel, who is lead programmer on
Nocturne.
</P>
<P>
   Players are sent out by a government agency called the
Spookhouse to explore one of four global missions: cemeteries in
France; a ruined castle in Germany; the sinister evil of a small,
Texas town; or the creepy back alleys of Chicago. Each mission is
presented as a self-contained cinematic episode with its own story.
</P>
<P>
   Though the full version of the game is just now making its way
to retailers, two demo versions of the game were available through
magazines or from a free download online.
</P>
<P>
   Nocturne is a scary game, no bones about it. This is the one
game where you'll run from zombie cows in Redeye, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The second demo, set in Al Capone's Chicago, pushes fear to a
higher level. The game's engine makes you hear footsteps before you
see anything. You jump at shadows. And all around you are
Frankenmobsters _ Capone's goons brought back to life a la
Frankenstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroic pulp is a curiously unexplored genre that Terminal
Reality recognized as perfect for gaming,'' Randel said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dark set designs that make Nocturne a future genre
classic came from films such as ``Batman'' and ``The Crow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually got the Crescent Theater design (in the Chicago
act) from an actual movie theater I used to work at during high
school. It had been around since the 1920s and had tons of hiding
places,'' said Den Johnson, senior digital artist at Terminal
Reality. ``It's a very scary place in real life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   While most games out there will run on low-end machines, this
game demands screamingly powerful hardware.
</P>
<P>
   For example, to fully enjoy the game, a powerful graphics card
such as ATI Technologies' Rage Fury (at $299) is required. The
32-megabyte graphics card can handle the power and detail of games
like Nocturne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BLOOD IS THE LIFE
</P>
<P>
   The creators of Gabriel Knight III used a different approach to
grab players by the throat.Writer Jane Jensen relied on a
heart-pounding storyline here.
</P>
<P>
   This third episode, ``Blood of the Sacred, Blood of the
Damned,'' takes place in a small village and valley in rural
Europe. A child is kidnapped and it's up to the hero, Gabriel, to
solve the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``GK is a series that takes story very seriously,'' Jensen said.
``It is closer to (the television series) `X-Files' than to (id
Software's) Doom. And like `X-Files,' the players got very attached
to the main characters, Gabriel and Grace. There's a lot of
bantering and smart aleck dialogue in GK that tempers the scary
storylines. It's a combination that people seem to like.''
</P>
<P>
   The series has undergone drastic changes, from its early
beginnings as a straightforward computer adventure to a confused
period when most games turned to full-motion video for a while. Its
current incarnation uses highly rendered 3-D art.
</P>
<P>
   ``When given a chance to do my own series, I wanted to use a
mystery format because in mystery the detective interrogates
people, examines evidence, visits crime scenes, does many things
that translate very well into interactive puzzles,'' Jensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Sins of the Father'' or ``The Beast Within,'' this
Gabriel Knight adventure lets the player control the view _ you
move it around to check out things _ as in LucasArts' Grim
Fandango. Just click on an object to have your character respond to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, a lot is lost in this departure from the popular series.
The hunt for clues gets caught up in the camera angles the player
has to make.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the animation used here doesn't seem to match Jensen's
dark storyline. It's too easy to be reminded you're playing a game
when you look at the hero's cartoon-like features.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the tension of uncovering the game's scheme will keep you
hunting for clues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DUNGEON MASTERS
</P>
<P>
   If all this strikes you as just too dark, there are games that
have taken a lighter approach.
</P>
<P>
   In Dungeon Keeper 2, humor plays a key role _ the darkest
element here is that the player gets to be the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are loads of games where players get to play the
goody-two-shoes heroes out to slay the bad, old monsters,'' said
Nick Goldsworthy, a producer at United Kingdom-based Bullfrog.
</P>
<P>
   But in Dungeon Keeper 2, you're in control of those monsters.
``In fact you control their entire realm _ a nasty, dark dungeon,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics, sound and music really bring this to life. Your
evil minions grumble aloud or cackle aloud, sounding suspiciously
like they're up to no good. You'll need to keep your eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   The original Dungeon Keeper looked more like cartoon animation.
But the 3-D used in its sequel puts it on par with today's games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visually the games are stunningly different,'' Goldsworthy
said. ``DK2 is a fully 3-D game, though you don't need a 3-D
(graphics) card to play. The original DK looked much more cartoony.
DK2 is as real as a virtual-dungeon can get.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-22-99 1602EDT &QL;
</P>
