<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TROTTER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL CHICAGO CHEF JAMS AT THE AMERICAN RESTAURANT'S 25TH
ANNIVERSARY DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   .MDNM/KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It's after 3 p.m. and the fleshy,
orange-pink sides of salmon are filleted and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Word is Charlie Trotter has landed in Kansas City, but instead
of making a beeline from the airport to the American Restaurant to
prep for dinner, he stops _ with his chef-entourage in tow _ to
linger over a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   An intensely focused personality who demands perfection on the
plate, Trotter likes to put pressure on himself and his kitchen
staff. When jetting into a city for a gala appearance, he'll often
make reservations for a leisurely, 31/2-hour lunch, then watch his
cooks break out in a cold sweat, furtively glancing at their
watches.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, the vaunted Chicago chef has either the confidence
_ or the audacity _ to arrive at 3:30 p.m. The seven-course,
$250-a-plate benefit dinner to celebrate the 25th anniversary of
the American Restaurant is scheduled to start at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Trotter and company immediately head for the kitchen, where he
ties on a crisp, starched white apron bearing his restaurant's
signature turquoise ``T'' monogram and launches into a
Trotter-style jam session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way we approach food is a lot the way Miles Davis
approached music, as epitomized by the comment `I'll play it first
and tell you what it is later.' We're still figuring out the
presentation on our dishes right now,'' Trotter says during an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, sideman//sous chef David LeFevre appears carrying
a plate of salmon. Trotter eyes the size of the filet and checks
the overall presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Bright orange and so succulent it melts in the mouth, the fish
has been slow-roasted over a mirepoix of finely diced aromatic
vegetables in a 250-degree oven for 20 minutes. It is riffed by a
ginger-soy sauce with fresh water chestnuts, bits of preserved
pineapple, earthly elegant chantarelle mushrooms and grace notes of
hajiki seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   Like saxophonist Charlie Parker, for whom the chef is named,
Trotter improvises. Working with only the most pristine raw
ingredients, he creates daring flavor combinations and presents
them in bold, almost minimalist designs. Those in the culinary-know
rave that he is creating nothing less than an original American art
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have a repertoire where we'll say, `OK, let's
do this signature dish.' It's very much in-the-moment food. It's a
little bit like working without a net,'' Trotter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to get out there and sort of say, `Well, let's
try this or let's try that.' Here we're going to do this for 160
people tonight and they have no idea that we've never really done
anything quite like this before. There's a margin for error which
can be exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   On becoming a chef
</P>
<P>
   At 40, Trotter is widely considered one of the, if not the most
influential American chef in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Wine Spectator named his restaurant ``the best in the
world'' for both food and wine. The Mobil Travel Guide gave the
restaurant its highest rating of five-star. The James Beard
Foundation named Trotter Outstanding Chef of the Year for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a month to get a weekday reservation at Charlie
Trotter's and 10 to 12 weeks to get one on the weekend. The
restaurant offers three degustation or tasting menus for $100 per
person. A $90 vegetable is also available.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the accolades, ``we still get people in who open their
menu and then tell their waiter, `We're from New York,' '' says
Trotter, a native Chicagoan. ``Nothing gives me more satisfaction
than bringing these pathetically jaded New Yorkers to their knees
and proving to them it doesn't matter where you are from.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, food was ``never an issue'' in his home
while growing up, although his mother may have been ahead of her
time by serving fish two or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Trotter worked as a busboy at a steak and burger
restaurant. ``I just liked the energy of here comes the guests and
here's all these things you had to do to make it happen,'' he
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Trotter discovered his love of food almost by accident during
college, when he and a roommate found themselves in a friendly
competition to see who could make the more extravagant four-course
meal.
</P>
<P>
   A political science major, Trotter took a year off between his
junior and senior year to work as a waiter and bartender, but
still, ``there was no grand scheme. I thought I'd do it for five
years, and if nothing else, I'd learn enough about cooking to feed
my family and friends for the rest of my life. I figured because
food is such an important part of life, it behooved me to learn all
I can about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotter graduated from college with a political science degree.
At 23, he took a job working under his mentor and longtime friend,
chef Norman Van Aken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a stereotypic idea of what a chef was,'' Trotter says.
``I thought a chef was some 55-year-old French guy. You know,
heavyset, ruddy cheeks with a mustache. Bellowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman was young. I think he was 30 at the time. I thought,
`Wow! This guy's a chef?' This was the first time I'd ever seen
anything opposite of what I thought. It was very interesting that
this American guy was carving out a place.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen art
</P>
<P>
   In the white-coated bustle of the kitchen, Ouida and Robert
Merrifield look out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing street clothes, Robert bends his head in concentration.
His hands, though not unskilled, are a bit slower and clumsier than
the line cooks. He slices black olives for a red wine//black olive
sauce. Ouida stands next to him, intently stripping thyme leaves
from their stalks.
</P>
<P>
   The Merrifields own the Polo Grill, a fine dining restaurant in
Tulsa, Okla. Although they have never met Charlie Trotter or eaten
in his restaurant, they eagerly volunteered for kitchen duty in
hopes of rubbing elbows with the celebrity chef.
</P>
<P>
   As Trotter's assistant Sari Zernich supervises their efforts,
Robert confides, ``We're just trying to do what Sari tells us and
try not to get yelled at!''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want me to yell at you?'' Trotter asks.
</P>
<P>
   Startled, Robert breaks into a smile as he discovers Trotter has
sneaked up on Robert's left side and is looking over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now why would I yell at you? My evil twin is the one who
yells. He stays back at the restaurant,'' Trotter says
mischievously. ``Sari, these people want you to yell at them so
they feel useful.''
</P>
<P>
   A pop celebrity with a devoted following, Trotter also has been
accused of creating food that is suitable for framing. His artistic
eye is most evident in his series of opulent Charlie Trotter
cookbooks, which are strewn with esoteric ingredients and plate
presentations that are sculptural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'm a little envious of creative folks _ artists and
craftsfolks who work in mediums that are more permanent,'' Trotter
admits. ``For example, musicians can put it down on a disc or a
tape. Other people can do it with woodwork or on a canvas or with a
piece of rock they can sculpt something, but chefs do it and it's
so fleeting and it's gone.'' MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
