<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITABLE CD-ROM DRIVES PUT TO TEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most fascinating aspects of the computer revolution
is how individual devices once considered overpriced and esoteric
become mainstream, gotta-have-it features. We've seen this with
modems, scanners, color printers and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the latest hot peripheral is the writable and rewritable
CD-ROM drive. Besides the fact that prices have dropped through the
floor, several trends are driving this demand.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that once people purchase a scanner or a digital
camera, they want some kind of removable storage on which to place
these images. CD-ROM disks are nearly permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Another is music _ people have long wanted a way to make copies
of music CDs just as they can with cassette tapes, and writable
drives now make that affordable. Add to that the MP3 craze: Folks
want to transfer tunes downloaded from the Net onto CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the good, old-fashioned need for a decent
backup system. CD-ROM disks can hold up to 650 megabytes, and while
a single one won't hold all of what's on today's multi-gigabyte
hard drives, they still have greater capacity than many other types
of removable drives.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these drives can work with disks that let you write to
them once as well as disks that allow rewriting and erasing. They
can also read standard CD-ROM disks.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at three writable CD-ROM drives you can add to
your system. All use the Enhanced IDE interface and are designed to
be installed internally.
</P>
<P>
   All the drives reviewed here include Adaptec's DirectCD
software, which lets you use the drive just as you would any other
drive on your system. You can drag and drop files onto its icon in
My Computer, create folders, even install software onto it.
</P>
<P>
   The drives also come with a ``light'' version of Adaptec's Easy
CD Creator, which lets you make audio disks and better manage the
process of storing files on a data disk. (While this software is
nice, if you get serious about using a writable/rewritable drive,
I'd strongly recommend getting the latest version, Easy CD Creator
Deluxe 4. It has a friendlier design and nifty new features,
including the ability to get song information off an Internet
database.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ZipCD, $210, Iomega Corp.: The maker of the popular 100- and
250-megabyte Zip disk drives has duly noted the writable CD-ROM
revolution. While Zip drives remain more popular than writable
CD-ROM drives, Iomega is covering its bases with this model.
</P>
<P>
   The ZipCD can record on a write-once CD at four times the speed
of the original CD-ROM drive. It also can rewrite and erase on
rewritable disks at that speed. And it can read standard CDs at 24
times the speed of the first CD-ROM drive. You'll see these
specifications usually expressed in this type of notation: 4x4x24.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Adaptec software, it includes a copy of Adobe's
Photoshop LE, Avery Media's label-making software and Iomega's
QuikSync backup software.
</P>
<P>
   The ZipCD comes with a minimum amount of printed documentation.
Most of the information is in the form of a multimedia presentation
on how the drive works and how to install it. The information is
very basic, though more details are available as Web page files
saved to your hard drive. I thought some of the information was
over the heads of most novices, particularly a crucial page that
tells you how to configure your new drive as either a master or
slave so it co-exists peacefully with other drives in your system.
</P>
<P>
   The drive performed well, though it significantly extended the
boot time on my PC. The BIOS seemed to be trying to figure out what
the drive was. Once the system was running, though, the drive
worked flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   _ CD-Writer Plus 8210i, $249, Hewlett-Packard: Of the three I
tried, this one was my favorite. It was very easy to install, ran
flawlessly and was very friendly to my system.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ZipCD, this also has a multimedia presentation on CD
that shows you how to install the drive. However, rather than have
you figure out on your own whether to set the drive up as a slave
or master, it examines your PC's configuration and makes
recommendations as to how best to install it. You can then print
this out as a kind of customized instruction sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The 8210i also is a 4x4x24 drive, and its performance was almost
identical to that of the ZipCD. However, it didn't slow down my
PC's bootup routine.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with both the Adaptec programs, as well as CD
label-making software from Neat-O; Broderbund's Multimedia
Organizer; HP Simple Trax, a backup program; and HP Disaster
Recovery, which lets you create a CD to be used in case of a system
failure.
</P>
<P>
   _ CD-ReWriter CRW4432A, $215, Acer Peripherals: This drive is a
great buy. Not only is it faster in reading traditional CD-ROMs
than the other two drives, but it also has more internal memory
that can keep recording glitch-free.
</P>
<P>
   Acer's drive is a 4x4x32 drive, with a maximum read speed of
32X. That's as fast as a lot of standard CD-ROM drives sold in PCs
today.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with eight megabytes of internal buffer, which can
help prevent what are known as buffer overruns. This is when the
data being written to the disk fills up the buffer, usually
resulting in corrupted files. Although having more memory won't
guarantee this won't happen _ particularly on older, slower
computers _ it can help.
</P>
<P>
   However, this drive comes with terrible documentation in a
poorly written manual that is a bad translation from an Asian
language into English. I'd only recommend this drive for more
experienced users who don't need much handholding.
</P>
<P>
   The drive also comes with a minimal amount of software _ it's
got the Adaptec titles, and that's it. However, it was the only
drive of the three to come with Windows 3.1 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-22-99 1556EDT &QL;
</P>
