<SLUG> BC-CPT-AIR-FORCE-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE TURNS TO CYBERSPACE TO BOOST RECRUITING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SIG CHRISTENSON   
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Struggling to recover from a record-setting
recruiting tailspin, the Air Force has launched a retooled Internet
site that sports a 3-D view of jets and an arcade of video games.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned site (www.airforce.com) was activated this week
and uses high-tech advances to showcase Air Force offerings as the
service tries to strengthen its recruiting effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The innovative artistic design and increased functionality of
the Web site allows users the choice to link to `microsites'
focusing on career and educational opportunities provided by the
Air Force,'' said Tech. Sgt. Charles T. Marshall, one of the
designers of the site. ``The level of sophistication involved in
this site is more of what one would expect from a CD-ROM rather
than the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a series of new, fast-paced television spots that recently
aired in major television markets, the Web site comes with bells
and whistles the Air Force hopes will spark the interest of
computer-literate young people, said Master Sgt. Tom Clements, a
spokesman with the Air Force Recruiting Service in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what we're trying to do,'' he said Wednesday. ``We are
looking for the young people who are technically savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   A disappointing recruiting year is behind the marketing efforts,
Clements conceded, and ``greatly increased and enhanced'' the
service's turn to the Internet, which is seen as a key area for
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   The service fell 1,734 enlistees short of its goal in the fiscal
year ending Sept. 30, making it the Air Force's worst recruiting
year since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   As the Army pondered changing its time-honored slogan, ``Be all
that you can be,'' and last month lured new soldiers with a $6,000
bonus in hopes of trimming a shortfall of its own, the Air Force
spent millions to air several slick Hollywood-produced television
spots as part of its first paid advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The same Dallas company that handled the advertising campaign,
BJK&AMP;E, also designed www.airforce.com, Clements said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site includes links to the three television spots, and
tries to draw the attention of Web surfers by displaying old
fighters, bombers and experimental planes, as well as the latest in
high-tech hardware.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Web site sections include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Boneyard,'' featuring older aircraft and a fact sheet with
information about the size, speed and armament of now-discarded
aircraft, as well as how they were used in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hangar,'' a section on the present-day Air Force, offering
what the service called ``vivid displays'' of today's jet aircraft.
Each month a plane will be featured with a 3-D view, a video, photo
gallery and an analysis, plus facts and figures on the aircraft's
size, speed and weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Flight Plan,'' which introduces visitors to the careers of
current Air Force members and invites them to complete a
questionnaire on their hobbies, achievements, educational plans and
goals. Users also are encouraged to take the completed
questionnaire to recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   Other sections of the site are devoted to life in the Air Force,
technology now in use, screensavers and three video games, one in
which the player ``flies'' an F-15 combat mission against a
fictitious enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to see something this high-tech representing the
Air Force,'' Clements said. ``We've always been known as the
high-tech branch of the military.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-21-99 1437EDT &QL;
</P>
