<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9883 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FOOD-APPLES-KANSAS-KA     10-27 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-APPLES-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CARAMEL APPLE A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a good idea that led to a not-so-great caramel apple.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pillow wanted to create a gourmet caramel apple with a
Halloween twist so he stuck a stick in a tart Granny apple, dipped
it in caramel, rolled it in roasted pumpkin seeds and drizzled it
with chocolate tinted orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible!'' Pillow says in a recent telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Pillow and his partners at Candy's Apples in Phoenix have
been right on with many of their other flavor combinations.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Kum-Ba-Yah, a tasty combination of caramel,
marshmallows and graham cracker bits drizzled with milk chocolate.
Or the Englishman, a blend of caramel and crushed Heath Bar. Or the
decadent Big Kahunana with caramel and macadamia nuts drizzled with
a choice of milk chocolate or white chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for these premium caramel apples are not cheap. A popular
corporate gift-giving item, they range from $6.95 to $14.95 per
apple, although most go for $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a dozen standard flavors, the company offers an
apple-of-the-month club to its best customers, so they dream up new
flavors on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it really doesn't matter if Pillow couldn't come up
with a Halloween-themed coating. When you're in the caramel apple
biz, it seems December is the month.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Pillow and company work 18- to 20-hour days. To
churn out 1,000 apples a day, they swirl through 300 to 400 cases
of caramel, each case weighing about 70 pounds. Conservatively
that's 2,100 pounds, a virtual river of caramel. The handcrafted
apples are dipped in caramel that was formulated to Pillow's
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Pillow shared the following tips for making gourmet caramel
apples at home:
</P>
<P>
   - Choose a tart apple. Pillow uses gigantic Granny Smith apples.
Not only does the green of the Granny make an appealing color
contrast, ``if you have a sweet apple and you put all those sweets
on top, it overpowers the apple and you don't get a good contrast
in flavors,'' Pillow says. If you really want a red apple, try a
McIntosh variety.
</P>
<P>
   - Proper caramel viscosity. ``The key is the caramel,''
according to Pillow. As one of the largest buyers of caramel in the
country, he was able to get a product that was customized to his
personal specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The home cook should use a sticky caramel that will help the
goodies you apply adhere like glue. (In a side-by-side comparison,
I found the homemade caramel recipe included here, while not as
thick as store-bought caramel, was definitely stickier and seemed
to coat the apple better.)
</P>
<P>
   - To roll or not to roll? For maximum coverage, Pillow advises
to roll instead of sprinkle the goodies. Use food-grade plastic
gloves to ``pack on the nuts'' and shape the apple. (Always be very
careful when working with hot caramel; it can leave nasty burns.
Parents should always supervise kids.)
</P>
<P>
   - Use a heat-proof spatula. To get a flat top on your apple, use
a heatproof spatula to swipe the top while spinning off any excess.
</P>
<P>
   - Give one to your doctor. By his calculations, Pillow figures
just about every doctor in Phoenix will receive one of his caramel
apples this year. Nurses and pharmaceutical reps are among his best
customers. They, of course, order caramel apples for their docs.
</P>
<P>
   Instant apples
</P>
<P>
   Zapple _ For a no-fuss way to make caramel apples, zap those
individually wrapped caramels (sans wrappers!) in the microwave. At
least one brand includes five sticks inside the bag and directions
on how to ``zap an apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrapple _ Don't trust yourself with a candy thermometer? Concord
Foods supplies a flat sheet of caramel. You wrap it around an
apple, then warm it in the oven or microwave until gooey.
</P>
<P>
   Dapple _ T. Marzetti's, the folks who positioned salad dressings
next to the lettuce, offer several tasty flavors of apple dip, near
the apple display in the produce section, of course. Flavors
include plain caramel and caramel-peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   Surf apple _ Gourmet candy apples can be pricey. Try up to $15 a
pop! But then again, it's hard to resist the Big Kahunana, a tart
Granny apple swathed in caramel, macadamia nuts, milk chocolate or
white chocolate. Look for 13 luscious-sounding varieties at Candy's
Apples at candyapples.com. Or call, 1-888-5-APPLE-1.
</P>
<P>
   Skewer perspectives
</P>
<P>
   Sure the standard Popsicle stick will work. But if you want to
get Martha Stewarty, try these ideas:
</P>
<P>
   - Cinnamon sticks _ To avoid breaking the stick, insert one
cinnamon stick just slightly offset from the core. Use the same
cinnamon stick over and over to bore a hole, then insert a new
stick.
</P>
<P>
   - Licorice sticks _ These natural twig-looking branches are not
to be confused with licorice candy sticks. Look for them in natural
foods stores.
</P>
<P>
   - Chopsticks.
</P>
<P>
   - Bamboo skewers.
</P>
<P>
   The tart factor
</P>
<P>
   Macoun _ A smaller, crisper, spicier McIntosh, Macouns from
upstate New York make lovely caramel apples.
</P>
<P>
   Jonagold _ You can't miss with this cross between a Jonathan and
a Golden Delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Empire _ A McIntosh cross, the Empire holds its shape well and
has a mild, sweet-tart taste that marries well with caramel.
</P>
<P>
   Granny Smith _ When it's caramel apples, we tend to think red,
but Granny Smith's hard, crisp and tart flavor does a bang-up job.
</P>
<P>
   Lady and Cortland _ Your kids don't always eat the apple part?
Try these petite, kid-sized varieties.
</P>
<P>
   On a roll
</P>
<P>
   Roll your caramel apple in ...
</P>
<P>
   - Coconut and drizzles of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   - Chopped pecans and drizzles of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   - Toffee bits.
</P>
<P>
   - Roasted almonds and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   - Chocolate sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   - Crushed candy bars.
</P>
<P>
   - Granola and coconut.
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter and chocolate.
Caramel apples Makes 14 to 16 small apples
</P>
<P>
   14 to 16 small tart apples
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) package (2 and one-fourth cups) packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Line an 8- by 8- by 2-inch or 9- by 9- by 2-inch baking pan with
foil, extending foil over edges of pan. Butter the foil.
</P>
<P>
   Wash and dry apples; remove stems. Insert a skewer into the stem
end of each apple. Place apples on baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy 3-quart saucepan melt butter over low heat. Add brown
sugar, condensed milk and corn syrup; mix well. Cook and stir over
medium-high heat until mixture boils. Clip a candy thermometer to
the side of the pan. Reduce heat to medium; continue boiling at a
moderate, steady rate, stirring frequently, until the thermometer
registers 248 degrees (about 15 to 20 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Remove the saucepan from heat; remove thermometer. Stir in
vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Working quickly, dip each apple into hot caramel mixture; turn
to coat. Roll or drizzle with your choice of toppings. Chill for up
to two days.
</P>
<P>
   Per apple, based on 14: 457 calories (30 percent from fat), 16
grams total fat (10 grams saturated), 45 milligrams cholesterol, 81
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 200 milligrams sodium, 3
grams dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better Homes and Gardens New Cook Book (Meredith)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
