<SLUG> BC-CPT-WINE-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINTNERS MAKE LAST STAND IN FIGHT FOR NET SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD   
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of the Napa Valley Vintners Association
issued a ``declaration of war'' Wednesday against the alcohol
distribution system, escalating the already pitched battle between
liquor wholesalers and California wineries seeking to ship wine
directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Shelton, the chief executive officer of Joseph Phelps
Vineyards and president of the winemakers group, warned wine
wholesalers at a Washington press conference that direct sales over
the Internet are ``a fact of life ... because consumers demand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton's comments underscored the winemakers' furious uphill
lobbying campaign against pending legislation that would
significantly strengthen the Prohibition-era system requiring wine,
beer and spirits to be sold through state-licensed wholesalers and
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Wine wholesalers were quick to lash back, accusing Napa wineries
of fattening their own profits at the expense of wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've hidden behind the guise of small winery access (to
consumers) for years, and at this press conference they made it
clear that this is not about small winery access,'' said David
Dickerson, spokesman for Wine and Spirits Wholesalers of America.
``It's about protecting the profits they make on direct
shipments.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for both sides are enormous, as the Internet
threatens to breach traditional commercial barriers between
producers and consumers. Nowhere is that more visible than in the
wine industry, where the barriers are buttressed by state laws.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers contend that the legislation, called the ``21st
Amendment Protection Act,'' is needed to prevent teenagers from
buying alcohol over the Internet and to allow states to enforce
their liquor regulations. Five states have made it a felony to ship
wine directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers charge that the bill, which has passed both the House
and Senate but must be consolidated in its final form, is nothing
but an effort to shield state-protected wholesaler monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton railed against the system Wednesday, likening it to
something ``out of a banana republic.'' He said small wineries
often cannot get their boutique labels on store shelves, and even
when they find a willing wholesaler, some state laws require that
the winery enter a contract to continue doing business with that
wholesaler indefinitely, regardless of performance or even whether
the wholesaler pays its bills.
</P>
<P>
   States that by law ``shackle you to a distributor for life,''
Shelton declared, ``must disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the system archaic and said it ``should not survive
the evolution of e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson retorted, ``We believe that following the law will
never be outmoded, and the law says there are specific ways to sell
and distribute alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet still accounts for only a tiny fraction of wine
sales _ under 2 percent at Joseph Phelps, Shelton said. (Limited
direct sales are permitted to some states that have entered into a
mutual pact with California.)
</P>
<P>
   But Shelton said non-Internet direct sales _ from winery tasting
rooms, wine clubs and direct mail, all of which are also sharply
limited by state liquor regulations _ represent a significant
percentage of winery sales, as much as 12 percent at Joseph Phelps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very profitable percentage, I might add,'' Shelton
said, ``and one that's very important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wineries that sell directly can capture the entire markup on a
bottle of wine rather than sharing it with wholesalers and
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   John De Luca, president of the San Francisco-based Wine
Institute, which represents all California vintners, said the
entire industry agrees that the more stringent felony laws and
state-enforced wholesale monopolies need to be combatted.
</P>
<P>
   But in toned-down criticism of the existing distribution system,
he said it needs reform, ``but we're not out to eliminate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Any threat to tear down _ as opposed to reform _ the liquor
distribution system is sure to meet with powerful resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Liquor wholesalers are a potent lobbying force, much more widely
represented than wineries on Capitol Hill and in state
legislatures. They also enjoy a close relationship with the House
GOP leadership through David Rehr, the top lobbyist for the
National Beer Wholesalers Association, and a member of the
exclusive ``kitchen cabinet'' that meets regularly with GOP Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Napa Valley vintners also are seeking to protect their
geographic ``brand'' from large wineries that label their wines
Napa when in fact they come from places such as Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   A 1986 federal regulation prohibited the practice but
grandfathered in an exception for wineries that were using the Napa
label at the time. Shelton said mass-production wineries can buy a
small label that owns the exemption and then slap the Napa Valley
name on wines that come from more pedestrian regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer finds a $5 bottle of Chardonnay and thinks it's
got to be good because it's from Napa,'' Shelton said. ``We believe
it's consumer fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that the chances of getting federal regulators to
lift the exemption are ``a long shot,'' but said vintners are
working on a voluntary ``seal of authenticity'' that vintners could
use to assure consumers that their wines really come from Napa.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``geographic brand'' issue can work both ways. For
years, California vintners have borrowed place names such as
Champagne, Burgundy, Port and even Johannisberg Riesling from
Europe, much to the consternation of vintners in France, Portugal
and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Treaties governing the issue will be revisited in the upcoming
World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle. The Wine Institute, a
larger trade group that represents all California vintners, is
about to release a white paper exploring the trademark issues to
help determine what position the group will adopt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-21-99 0228EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
