<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICAN-RESORTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESORTS OFFER AN INSULAR RETREAT FROM JAMAICA AND THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCHO RIOS, Jamaica _ Jamaica is old pirate movies with Errol
Flynn, James Bond's Dr. No and romance novels with steamy cover
illustrations of brawny captains and luscious maidens.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a nation of 2.6 million people, a third of whom live
in absolute poverty, according to the United Nations. The island is
ringed with hotels, golf courses and resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica, a member of the British Commonwealth, is the queen of
all-inclusive resorts, some 31 in all. But is that the be-all,
end-all in island vacationing?
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone finds Jamaica a vacation paradise. Gang wars in
Kingston hit the news in July and riots erupted in the spring when
the government announced a 30 percent hike in gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaican officials called out the armed forces to help patrol
the country's beaches. Periodically, warnings spring up on the U.S.
State Department's Web page (http://travel.state.gov/).
</P>
<P>
   Warnings aside, I wanted _ no, I needed _ a Jamaica vacation.
</P>
<P>
   From Montego Bay to Negril, Ocho Rios to Kingston, resorts such
as Sandals, Hedonism, SuperClubs, Grand Lido and Franklyn D attract
singles, families and groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica Tourism's Charles Handal, regional manager in the
southern United States, says the all-inclusive concept goes back to
the late 1950s. The first location was Frenchman's Cove in Port
Antonio and they certainly catered to guests. ``If they didn't have
it, they would fly it in.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1970s, Negril Beach Village (now Hedonism II) had
guests buying beads to exchange for drinks. Today, some 60 percent
of Jamaica's visitors stay at an all-inclusive resort, according to
Handal.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is this: You pay one price for accommodations, all
meals, all alcoholic drinks, gratuities and water sports equipment
(Sunfish, snorkeling, paddle boats, etc). It is much like a cruise,
except you don't get a big bar tab at the end and there is no
slipping the room steward an envelope. Or do you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tipping is accepted,'' said Patroy Stewart, guest services
manager at the Jamaica Grande. Sandals and SuperClubs have a
no-tipping policy.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Knatt and her extended family from Baton Rouge, La., can't
stop raving about how good the service was on their second visit to
the Jamaica Grande. ``We just loved it so much,'' she said a month
after the family get-together. And perhaps one of the reasons is
that Knatt estimates that her husband, Theodore, an orthopedic
surgeon, shelled out $250 in tips for the week. Wait staff
practically ran to help the family at every opportunity, Knatt
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Knatts and their four children shared our van on a 2
1/2-hour ride from Montego Bay to Ocho Rios. Avery and Mary Knatt
and Lionel Vitale (Doris Knatt's brother) and his wife, Detra, were
on their first visit to Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Vitale, a scout with the New York Jets, had difficulty getting
beyond Jamaica's obvious poverty, the narrow winding highway and
the roadside fruit stands. ``When I get home, I'm going kiss my
house,'' he said standing at the roadside rest stop, 30 minutes
from the resort. Minutes later, our speeding van hit a goat.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Jamaica, mon.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamaica Grande was once two hotels. In 1993 the properties
became one under the Renaissance umbrella and a central open-air
lobby was built linking the east and west towers. With 720 rooms,
it is the island's largest single property. There are five
restaurants, the Jamaic'n Me Crazy disco, casino and children's
Club Mongoose. The Fantasy Pool is a replica of the nearby Dunn's
River Falls, with caves, bridges, Jacuzzis and swim-up bar. The
white sandy beach fronts the azure-blue Mallard's Bay, where
patrons get free use of Sunfish sailboats, kayaks and snorkel
equipment. Despite moderate tipping on our part, food and service
were not great at the Grande. The mediocre food came as a surprise
after reading a Jamaica bulletin Web site where past visitors raved
about the ``excellent'' cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   While the bars are plentiful, finding a bartender was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Table waiters were less than friendly and service was spotty
during our mid-July stay.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Knatt conceded the food was better on a previous visit.
</P>
<P>
   We fared better at the smaller 420-room Sunset Beach Resort and
Spa (the former Seawind Hotel) at Montego Bay. It didn't have the
fabulous beach of the Grande _ Sunset's was more rocks than sand
and the view wasn't striking _ but the service was warmer, food far
superior and entertainment more intimate. A duo played during the
Jamaica night dinner and the full-service spa was a nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   The big minus here was the reggae band playing loudly under our
fourth-floor balcony until 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   With multiple restaurants, water sports and entertainment, you
may ask: Why leave the grounds? Many people don't and that's where
Jamaicans lose. For some tourists, it is fear that keeps them
inside the resort's walls. Uniformed hotel guards do make an
intimidating presence on the beach. But island crime has dropped 30
percent since 1996 and visitor arrivals have increased steadily
over a 10-year period. Handal said that August visits were up 9.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   We ventured a few feet past a fence that marked the end of the
resort's private beach on the first night on the island. Stepping
out of the shadows a young entrepreneur quickly approached and
offered to sell marijuana. No surprise; a recent Jamaica Tourist
Board survey reveals that 60 percent of visitors are approached to
buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In the outdoor crafts market at Ocho Rios, a few blocks from the
resort's main gate, we were the only shoppers on a sunny Wednesday
morning. Merchants, mostly women, use intense flattery to get you
to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, pretty lady, over here. Let me show you what I have. Step
inside, there is no charge to look,'' they chant in singsong
voices. We found tourists aplenty at the duty-free shopping center,
about three blocks from the crafts market. Vans of shore excursion
cruisers disgorged at shops selling Swiss watches, Lalique and
gemstones.
</P>
<P>
   Early each morning there was a different cruise ship, such as
Carnival's Imagination and Royal Caribbean's Majesty of the Seas,
calling at Ocho Rios. By 4:30 p.m. the ships sailed away from
Jamaica. About 800,000 people have arrived in Jamaica by cruise
ship since Jan. 1, mostly to spend a day.
</P>
<P>
   All-inclusive resort stays, which were first geared toward
couples, now appeal to families. Children under 12 eat and stay
free at many, including the Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Smith, a native Jamaican and resident of San Antonio,
took her family of five to the all-inclusive Franklyn D Resort at
Runaway Bay in 1998. ``It was very nice, the people were very
friendly,'' Smith said, adding that management mingled with the
guests.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths, with two children under 10, enjoyed the experience,
especially the Franklyn D nanny assigned each family at check-in.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says she felt especially ``shielded from everything
outside. I'd go back to the resort, but I'd get out (via taxi) a
lot more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The resort gives its patrons escorted field trips to tourist
sites or shopping. Getting out and away from the insular resort is
the only way to see Jamaica and its people.
</P>
<P>
   On a boat trip to Dunn's River Falls, our guide, Dudley, was
informed and lectured. He pointed out the sites, including Mick
Jagger's and Barbra Streisand's homes perched high on the hills
above, before launching into a history/economics lecture. A former
British colony, the island won independence in 1962, although Queen
Elizabeth II remains head of state. By the 1970s, it lost U.S.
support because of commerce with Cuba. The once-strong Jamaican
dollar has fallen in value in the last 35 years and is now worth
about 38 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley pleaded with the boat passengers to see the real Jamaica,
the small boutique hotels and mom-and-pop owned restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come back, but don't stay at an all-inclusive,'' he urged. And
when you do return, ``Tip the people!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
