<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV ON THE INTERNET: A FUZZY PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So there's Sam Donaldson on your computer screen, all smiley
with a head shrunk to the size of a postage stamp. He's trying to
drum up enthusiasm for his recently launched news show, which airs
three times a week on the World Wide Web. ``Television on the
Internet,'' he says, ``is a two-way, not a one-way, street.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Television on the Internet, at least for now, is a
frustrating dead end.
</P>
<P>
   What were the folks at ABC News thinking, anyway? You can't just
put an old-fashioned news talk show on the Internet, add a few
creaky ``interactive'' features, and expect to keep viewers. Bad TV
is still bad TV, even if it's on line.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about this concept was wrongheaded from the start.
Donaldson is best known for his acerbic, confrontational style, but
on SamDonaldson(at)ABCNews.com, he's trying to be Mr. Congeniality.
Since the show debuted three weeks ago, he has chatted up former
presidents George Bush and Jimmy Carter and talked amiably with the
always controversial Governor Jesse Ventura. His questions are
softballs, and the witty banter is anything but. This isn't hard
news; it's soft corn. And when you can find breaking news and the
latest jokes all over the Internet, why would anyone put up with
the limitations of the technology to watch a ``news'' show in which
the host makes quips about Dan Quayle?
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, the former White House correspondent seems to
know he's out of place in this medium. ``I'm quite aware that
you're seeing me in a little box, 2 inches by 2 inches,'' he says.
``But we save on makeup. There is no expensive set back there, and
the technology will get better,'' he promises.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it can't get any worse. When I tried to watch the show
live on Wednesday (it airs Monday, Wednesday, and Friday at 12:30
p.m. at www.abcnews.go.com), it crashed my browser three times. It
wasn't any easier watching the archives, either. An interview with
former Treasury secretary Robert Rubin looked like two little Pez
heads suspended in a split screen. Sometimes the screen froze, and
at other times, the video lost pace with the audio, making the
Rubin Pez head deliver Donaldson candy.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem here isn't just the technology or the insipid
content. The real potential of Web television is the option of
interactivity. But like most Web TV, this show doesn't tap that
potential. So far, Donaldson has taken a few ``unscientific''
polls. In one, viewers were asked to evaluate their boss
(``excellent'' or ``jerk''); in another, they were quizzed on the
spelling of, you guessed it, potato. Stal(e)?
</P>
<P>
   Viewers are also invited to e-mail questions to Donaldson, but
so far, the format is less spontaneous than that of a typical
call-in talk show. The questions from the viewers have actually
been quite intelligent, but communication on line, whether it be in
a chat room or on a news show, is stilted by its very nature. It's
impossible to get a real dialogue going by typing missives to a
talking head on a tiny screen.
</P>
<P>
   True interactivity may be impossible, but the Donaldson show
doesn't even come close to breaking new ground. The reporter is a
suit-and-tie kind of guy trying to fit into a jeans-and-T-shirt
world. ``Hit me again,'' he says, looking a bit worried that
someone might take him literally. No need to fret. Repeat hits
aren't a danger when it's so easy to just go click.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  The Reform Party's list of presidential candidates keeps
growing _ Warren Beatty! Donald Trump! Cybill Shepherd! Oprah
Winfrey! _ and the cyber squatters are already one step ahead of
the candidates. Kiley Pryor, a 22-year-old college student in
Amarillo, Texas, bought the domain name www.Oprah2000.com back in
March. ``We would like to make a great deal of money on it,'' says
the entrepreneur, who paid $100 for the Web address and hopes to
sell it to the talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   And there are already several Beatty sites. Beatty2000.com is a
site ``created to gauge interest'' for the actor's candidacy; its
Webmaster, Dave Perry of New Phase Media Design in Nashville,
refuses to say whether the site is paid for by the Bulworth, we
mean Beatty, machine. The actor already has an unofficial tribute
at www.beatty4president.org; it was started by Adrian Wild, a
University of Florida student. ``He's a charismatic outsider,''
says Wild.
</P>
<P>
   So far The Donald, the Talk Show Host, and the Model haven't put
up political sites. But Shepherd has a vanity site
(www.cybill.com), and Trump has a site for his hotel and casino
operations (www.trump.com). One has a platform for Revlon; the
other takes a stand on the Taj Mahal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Dubious Internet firsts. Amazon.com has announced, quite
breathlessly, that Moby's performance on  &UR; tonight &LR; 's ``Late Night
With David Letterman'' show will be available for free download at
Amazon immediately after the show. ``This is an exclusive
opportunity, and it's the first time a song played during the show
will be available for download,'' says Amazon spokeswoman Jenny
Cherrytree. Well, we can't wait for the next one.
</P>
<P>
   We're told that a new site, www.beer.com, embraces ``a total
beer lifestyle and entertainment concept.'' Now, that's a scary
concept. The site has a feature called a bar finder, which helps
you locate a place where everybody knows your name. When we
searched for a watering hole in Boston, we got the response ``Zero
bars found.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-21-99 1458EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
