<HEADLINE>
BOB MACKIE DOESN'T MIND THE TITLE `PRINCE OF GLITZ' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a charming Bob Mackie moment. He grins his
boyish grin and looks around at the assemblage of his designs of
the last 35 years. ``It feels good now to see them out,'' he says,
``... having a good time again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stripped down to his shirtsleeves, he is overseeing completion
of a retrospective, ``Unmistakably Mackie,'' at New York's Fashion
Institute of Technology, now through Dec. 31. It coincides with the
publication of a book of the same name by fashion writer Frank
DeCaro (Universe, $45) and a limited-edition fragrance in the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Mackie, 59, is, of course, the quintessential celebrity
designer, having fashioned starmaking, hey-look-at-me clothes for
such entertainers as Cher, Carol Burnett, Diana Ross, Ann-Margret,
Mitzi Gaynor, Elton John and RuPaul since 1965. Let people snicker
at Cher's tacky Oscar costume, gasp at the exotic Las Vegas
dancers' beads or pay five-figure prices for a sequin-drenched
Barbie doll. Mackie gets the credit.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years he worked on the Carol Burnett show, churning out
as many as 50 costumes a week, including glamorous evening gowns,
for her openings and dozens of comic clothes for her caricature
skits. Mackie's own humor instinct came into play to help the
actress push the edge. One of the most famous sartorial jokes: the
Southern belle drapery knock-off from the segment ``Went With the
Wind,'' where Burnett appeared in a gown with the drapery rod still
attached.
</P>
<P>
   When the bumbling Mrs. Wiggins was first discussed, Mackie
suggested she do the role ``as one of the bumbling CBS secretaries
we all knew at the time,'' he says. He created a dress so
tight-fitting, she could barely walk. But he knew how to go for the
laugh; he advised her to stick out her rear end to exaggerate the
silhouette. For the ill-starred Eunice, he found a flowered
thrift-shop frock.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, he says, when she took questions from the audience at
the start of the show, someone inevitably asked who created her
costumes. Each time she gave Mackie credit. ``I kept thinking
they'd know by now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Fashion Institute show also includes the gown Madonna wore
to the Oscars when she sang ``Sooner or Later,'' from ``Dick
Tracy,'' and Sharon Stone's sequin gown from the film ``Casino.''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John's luminous silver coat is a reminder of his moment
singing ``Lucy in the Sky With Diamonds.'' After Mackie did Cher's
first television special, John came to him and said, ``I want some
things like Cher has. ... I drew him up about 50 sketches thinking
he would pick some. He picked them all.''
</P>
<P>
   An entire section of the retrospective is devoted to Cher, whom
early on he found to be a remarkable muse, someone to dress as one
would a Barbie. He started working with her on ``The Sonny and Cher
Comedy Hour,'' beginning in 1971, and he took her from character to
character _ an exotic dancer to gypsy to Olive Oyl to an Indian
princess in a beaded loincloth. Sometimes he would design her
costume for one song, he says, and then the song would be changed
at the last minute when it was too late to make her something else.
</P>
<P>
   Mackie made the skintight, pearl-strand dress she wore on the
cover of Time in 1975 and all her all-too-revealing Oscar gowns and
hats. One of the most notorious is the bare, beaded gown and
feathered headdress she wore when presenting Don Ameche with an
Oscar in 1986. She was annoyed, Mackie says, at the academy because
she was not nominated for ``Mask.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think this is a bit much?'' Mackie asked her,
according to the book.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, ``she was just so thrilled ... this is so
fun,'' Mackie says. She was like a chameleon enjoying the fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years she came into her own. ``She has become Miss
Expert,'' Mackie says like a loving parent discussing an errant
child. ``... She has been watching MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly for Bob Mackie, his destiny was set from early
childhood. At 5, he cut his chin when he fell down the stairs while
dressed as Carmen Miranda. When he was 10, he put together a
Halloween costume meant to look like a French lady of the evening.
He grew up going to movies where he found the spark of glamour and
fantasy he craved.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is involved with several projects: He designs for the
wealthy and glamorous on a custom-order basis; he provides his
talent to a less expensive ready-to-wear house and successfully
sells an affordable line on QVC. His signature fragrance is still
selling in department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Each year he also makes a new dazzling over-the-top Barbie Doll
costume, and the dolls ultimately become fine prizes for Barbie
collectors who pay thousands for them.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a negative being typecast as the ``Prince of Glitz''?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than being typecast for overalls,'' he says
cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   As for any regrets, there is one: He had to turn down the job of
designing costumes for the 1970s film ``The Great Gatsby.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
