<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUIET, PLEASE: TEST IN PROGRESS
</P>
<P>
   It has been three months since IBM and major record labels began
the experiment: selling albums over high-speed Internet cable
modems in 1,000 households in metropolitan San Diego. But efforts
to assess the music test's progress, have met the sound of silence.
The companies have effectively imposed a publicity blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Max Martens, a spokesman for the project, which is called Album
Direct, said the participating companies did not want the news
media to influence the buying patterns of the San Diego consumers _
or to even know who the consumers were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like sequestering a jury,'' Martens said. ``We don't want
to taint the very perceptions we're trying to evaluate.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts and competitors posit a different courtroom
analogy: mistrial. There are rumblings in the industry that the
project simply is not living up to the organizers' vision of a
21st-century music delivery method that protects copyrights. And
since the effort began in June, the participating record companies,
including the industry giants Universal and BMG, have begun
pursuing technologies other than the IBM system.
</P>
<P>
   What IBM has said is that the trial lets record companies sell
albums directly to consumer's homes over high-speed Internet lines.
After paying for and downloading music, the consumers can transfer
the songs from their computer to compact disks using so-called CD
burner technology, effectively creating their own home-grown CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, IBM and Album Direct officials are not saying much.
It will be at least the end of the year before they share
information about the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a tight-lipped, shifty-eyed type of thing,'' Martens
said. ``It's just not time to share yet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Matt Richtel
</P>
<P>
   THE PC INDUSTRY SHOWS STRONG GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   The personal computer industry is continuing to show significant
global growth, with third-quarter shipments of machines increasing
by 23.2 percent over the comparable quarter last year, according to
a Dataquest report to be issued on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest, a market research company based in San Jose, Calif.,
cited strong growth in all regions of the world and lower prices as
the foundation of the continued surge in computer shipments, which
totaled 28.5 million in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer remained the world's largest PC maker with a
12.8 percent market share, although that figure was down from 13.4
percent last year. Compaq shipped 3.65 million computers during the
quarter, according to Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast Dell Computer, the No. 2 PC company, whose sales
have grown along with the rise of Internet commerce, expanded its
market share from 8.2 percent to 10.8 percent, shipping 3.07
million computers during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the two leaders were three other computer makers based in
the United States: IBM., Hewlett-Packard and Gateway. Dataquest
analysts said that companies like Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and IBM,
which have typically sold to customers indirectly, had experienced
slower growth than those like Dell specializing in direct sales
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Compaq's global leadership position, it dropped behind
Dell in sales of machines within the United States. That was a
milestone for Dell, according to Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, Dell's domestic market share rose to 17.1
percent, up from 13.4 percent a year earlier _ a growth rate of
56.5 percent. Compaq's domestic shipments, meanwhile, rose only
24.9 percent, as its United States market share edged up to 15.3
percent, from 15 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, IBM's overall market share sank to 7.6 percent, from
8.4 percent in last year's third quarter. Last week, the company
announced that it was exiting the retail market and in the future
would sell its personal computers via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest said that the quarter was unusual because of the rise
of computer memory prices, a trend whose impact had been felt most
directly by Dell, but also by many of the other computer makers, in
terms of lower profits margins.
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest said that Gateway's new partnership with America
Online, announced last week, was an example of a shift to a
``next-generation PC economic model,'' which would shift the
emphasis in competition beyond high inventory turnover.
</P>
<P>
   _ By John Markoff
</P>
<P>
   AN E-COMMERCE SITE FOR E-COMMERCE VENDORS
</P>
<P>
   Electronic commerce is made possible by advanced communications
services and equipment. So it is noteworthy that many of the
companies that sell those services and equipment don't rely more
heavily on e-commerce themselves. But Telezoo.com, a Web site that
began operating earlier this year, is meant to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Telezoo's main asset is a data base of nearly 20,000
communications products and services from about 300 vendors and
communications carriers. At least as important as the data base's
breadth is its format.
</P>
<P>
   Telezoo's users _ generally information technology professionals
_ are able to submit their technical requirements for a given
product and then see a list of items that might meet their needs.
Or, a potential customer can submit a request for proposals from
carriers or equipment makers. Users have been logging into Telezoo
from various countries, including Egypt, Malaysia, Germany and
Singapore _ although the biggest contract handled on the site so
far has been a $55 million deal to supply communications equipment
to a Florida company. Elias Shams, the site's co-founder, who calls
himself ``chief zookeeper,'' said the site intended to charge
vendors fixed fees for listing their products and also a percentage
of the value of deals consummated through the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to find a product when it comes to telecom, which is such
a complex industry, is a three to five months average trying to
find a switch, a router or a service,'' Shams said. ``Even after
you spend that time, 30 to 40 percent of the time you might make
the wrong decisions because you're under a lot of stress, you have
to meet deadlines. At Telezoo, as a network engineer, you say,
`Give me a router, these are my requirements' and then _ zoom,
voila, you're shown an apples-to-apples comparison and put in touch
with someone at the vendor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Schiesel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-24-99 1923EDT &QL;
</P>
