r l BC-FASHION-HISTORY-KANSA     10-27 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HISTORY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR EXPLAINS HOW COUTURE GAVE WAY TO CLOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It began in the early 1990s when companies as vast as
Pittsburgh-based aluminum company Alcoa began to allow casual
office attire. The rest is history. Dress from airplanes to good
restaurants to some workplaces degenerated to such extremes that by
February 1995, Newsweek magazine asked in a cover headline, ``Have
We Become a Nation of Slobs?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after an excessive fashion-feeding frenzy of the
1980s, the clothing consumers became enamored with the charms of
bargain shopping, boasting of finding the $20 Gap T-shirt or the $9
Target polo shirt. The trend was fueled by a wave of simple styles
that made differences between high and low couture remarkably
subtle.
</P>
<P>
   And so, writer Teri Agins declares, fashion as we knew it began
a downhill slide to its demise.
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street Journal reporter who grew up Kansas City, Kan.,
Agins argues the point in a new book, The End of Fashion: The Mass
Marketing of the Clothing Business (William Morrow &AMP; Co., $25).
</P>
<P>
   Women long ago stopped heeding the dictates of designers to
select clothes for their own needs and tastes. So in the 1999 age
of Gap, Ralph Lauren and Tommy Hilfiger, Agins notes, the fashion
field is driven more by marketing than designer whims. The power is
in a logo (Hilfiger), a lifestyle image (Lauren) or a campaign that
positions a label as so cool (Old Navy and Banana Republic).
</P>
<P>
   Agins tracks some of the influential movements that have helped
to shift the industry since the time when the elite French
designers set the styles that were copied by everyone else to
today's democratized society when many designers mine ideas from
people in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what everybody's wearing,'' she says during an
interview, pulling on the sleeve of her black shell designer top
and patting her trousers. ``These happen to be Zoran but you can
get the look anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Agins, who has been covering fashion retailing for The Wall
Street Journal for more than a decade, is the daughter of Phyllis
and William Agins of Kansas City, Kan. Her mother was a reading
consultant in public high schools and her father was deputy
regional director with Consumer Products Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   As she recalls, in about the ninth grade at Northwest Junior
High _ about the same time she started spelling her name with
little letters _ she began to consider journalism. She briefly
wrote a column call for the school paper called ``teri's tips for
fashion flair.'' ``The journalism teacher knew I liked clothes,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   She went to Wyandotte High School, Wellesley College in
Massachusetts and returned to the University of Missouri to study
journalism. In the summer of 1973 she had an internship at The
Kansas City Star where she wrote obituaries. ``It was a good
learning experience. You had to check every detail,'' she says. The
next year she was an intern at the Boston Globe. While at Missouri,
she also wrote her master's thesis on ``How the government controls
the press in Lima, Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her early jobs was with the menswear trade journal Daily
News Record in the Chicago office. She married and for about five
years she lived in Brazil, where she taught English and wrote
free-lance articles for American newspapers. She later divorced and
in the summer of 1984 settled into her job with the Journal in New
York, covering small business. She ultimately helped develop the
fashion business beat.
</P>
<P>
   While she researched the book, her 14-month leave from the
Journal stretched into 20 months. Interviewing about 140 people,
she chose to use case studies to reflect some of the recent
struggles and evolution of the apparel industry. Asked about
surprises she encountered, she says it was mostly how people had no
qualms about canceling or postponing interviews when she was short
on time and budget.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes a chapter on Emanuel Ungaro, one of the most
successful European designers in the United States, who sold his
business to Italy's Ferragamo House in 1996. It was not a perfect
marriage, and the well-known Emanuel sportswear label ultimately
suffered losses in sales and status.
</P>
<P>
   She writes about Chicago's Marshall Field, the once preeminent
department store acquired by Dayton Hudson and thrown up against
Bloomingdale's when the trendy New York retailer entered the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the genius in marketing a fantasy lifestyle has been
Ralph Lauren, whose images of the uppercrust good life helped to
put his clothing and home products on the front burner of the
American psyche. Lauren also appropriated the American flag as a
motif and, in 1998, as a cause by donating $13 million for the
restoration of the original star-spangled banner.
</P>
<P>
   His charity only intensified the hostile competition between
Lauren and Hilfiger, who has found inspiration not only in the flag
but also apparently in several other marketing ploys identified
with Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Agins writes about how Giorgio Armani introduced the first
unstructured jacket for men and women and decidedly influenced the
shape of menswear in the 1980s. But equally noteworthy, Armani was
well ahead of the curve when he first used celebrities to showcase
his clothes, starting with Richard Gere in the 1980 film ``The
American Gigolo.'' (An excerpt of the Armani chapter was rewritten
for the Journal in mid-September.)
</P>
<P>
   Armani was the first to hire a West Coast public relations
representative _ Wanda McDaniel, a close friend of Maria Shriver's
who was recommended to Armani by Shriver's aunt's sister, Lee
Radziwill.
</P>
<P>
   One of McDaniel's accomplishments was bringing Lakers coach and
Armani customer Pat Riley into the fold as a highly visible Armani
billboard. He and his wife were given an Armani wardrobe each year
and, pacing at courtside, he set a stylish pace for sports
commentators, coaches and basketball fans who wanted to dress like
him.
</P>
<P>
   The book is not necessarily an insider's story. Agins'
background information is well-developed. And the account may
actually be most interesting to readers outside the industry's
inner circles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
