<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-TELECOM-COLUMN-NY     10-27 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TELECOM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE REPORT: SOME PRODUCT REVIEWS ON WEB BRING ADVICE FROM 
ANYONE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditionally, advice on consumer purchasing decisions has been
the province of print publications like Consumer Reports, PC
Magazine or Car and Driver. While many of these publications have
moved their content online, the growth of the Web has empowered
another source of buying advice: the neighbor, cousin or uncle who
just bought a particular item and is more than willing to share an
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Internet retailers and some publishers have already capitalized
on this instinct by allowing users to post opinions about products
the companies sell or review. But a handful of companies are hoping
to take the age-old effectiveness of word-of-mouth recommendations
one step further, by creating independent Web sites that give
common folks and bona fide experts a forum for their opinions and
users a way to rate the pundits. While some of these sites are
charging users for qualified help, most are looking for more
creative ways to balance their books and keep users coming to the
site.
</P>
<P>
   The company that has generated the most recent buzz around this
idea is Epinions, which was started in the summer by several
well-known Silicon Valley venture capitalists. It is not the first
company to provide users with opinions on what to buy, but it has
been a force behind some changes in how these sites approach their
business.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the Epinions service, for instance, is that
it both rewards and rates product reviewers, in hopes of giving
them enough incentive to provide useful opinions. Anyone can sign
up to give advice on products that fit into the site's 12
categories, and prospective shoppers can browse through the reviews
and rate them on a scale from ``not useful'' to ``very useful.'' To
build credibility _ and eliminate suspicions that they are merely
company shills in disguise _ advisers can build a page on the site
with photos and personal information.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff is aimed at both the reviewer's wallet and ego.
Reviewers earn royalties of from one to three dollars for every 10
times their review is read by an Epinions member, and their picture
might be featured on the front page of the site if their reviews
are widely read.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nirav Tolia, a company co-founder, the site relies
on a so-called ``web of trust'' in which users, reviewers and
advisers tend over time to be matched up with people whose opinions
they have come to trust. ``It mimics the way word-of-mouth works in
the real world,'' Tolia said.
</P>
<P>
   When word-of-mouth recommendations result in a sale, Epinions
earns an undisclosed referral fee from merchants who pay to have
links displayed in areas where their product categories are
discussed. Epinions also earns money by displaying banner
advertisements on its pages, and can charge higher advertising
rates than general information sites _ between $30 and $70 for
every thousand banner ads displayed _ since advertisers know they
are reaching buyers more qualified than the general surfing public.
</P>
<P>
   Tolia said the company also earned money by licensing its
service to other e-commerce sites like Lycos, which included the
Epinions service in the new Lycoshop. ``It's hard to find people
who've actually walked the same path you're walking when you're
looking for a product,'' said Jeff Bennett, vice president for
e-commerce at Lycos. ``Epinions is very good when it comes to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, like Productopia.com and Deja.com, have offered
recommendations from users for months, building expansive archives
of reviews across hundreds of categories of goods. But those sites
do not compensate contributors for their opinions _ at least not
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Phillips, Deja.com's chief executive, said the company
planned to use both a rating and a reward system for reviewers in
the near future. The reward system ``could involve ego
gratification,'' he said, rather than financial incentives.
``There's a way to do both successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Neal, Productopia's chief executive, said his company had
no plans to compensate consumers who post reviews, since it already
pays professional product reviewers to post recommendations on its
site. ``We'd rather have people doing it for the normal reasons
they post on message boards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One question about the business model of these sites is whether
the quality of the user reviews is enough to attract a lot of
visitors on an ongoing basis. Phillips, of Deja.com, acknowledged
that the responses can be mixed, but said the current quality of
reviews on his site ``is pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly get some three-word reviews that are insipid,''
he said, ``but anyone who's put any effort into it usually has
something worthwhile to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is objectivity. These sites purport to be more
objective than retailers that offer user opinions. But some
question whether sites that accept commissions, referral fees or
advertising can deliver worthwhile information, even if it is
provided by individuals with no vested interest in the products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since these sites derive revenue from transactions that result
from people responding to an opinion, it ultimately raises a
question of bias,'' said Andrew Bartels, an e-commerce analyst with
Giga Information Group, a consulting firm. Unscrupulous sites could
prominently display reviews that favor certain products, for
instance, and gain higher transaction fees for those products. ``It
could be that the only way to get true, unbiased opinions is for
users to pay for it,'' Bartels said.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips, of Deja.com, disagrees. ``I don't buy that
argument,'' he said. ``We have no incentive to do anything except
try to make this valuable for consumers. The primary relationships
we have are with marketers who sell all of the products across a
category, so we don't do any better on one product versus
another.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one company is betting that consumers are willing to
pay for advice, although the services offered generally do not
focus on purchase decisions. Exp.com, introduced last month,
enables consumers to buy advice and services on topics ranging from
career planning and tax shelters to what type of roses to plant.
According to Mark Benning, the company's president, the site allows
users to rate the performance of its advisers, and takes a 20
percent cut of whatever the advisers charge.
</P>
<P>
   The service is unusual in that users contact the expert with a
specific question or request, and negotiate a fee before the advice
is given. ``So they get a much more personalized response,''
Benning said.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, however, whether the arrangement will pay
off for those who offer their services for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Walworth, for instance, is a horticulture consultant and
columnist in Idaho who joined Exp.com in the late summer. She said
demand has been light, even though she often charges as little as
$5 for a short consultation _ and sometimes gives flower-buying
advice for free. ``Let's be real here: At that rate, I'm not going
to Europe any time soon,'' she said. ``But I got into this business
to help people.''
</P>
<P>
   Exp.com's motives, on the other hand, are decidedly more
profit-minded. Benning said he was optimistic that the company
could operate in the black, given what he has seen so far. ``We've
done thousands of transactions in just a month,'' he said. ``We're
pretty pleased with that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-24-99 1738EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
