<HEADLINE>
DREAMWORKS AND IMAGINE JOIN TO CREATE A WEB SITE OF DIGITAL 
ENTERTAINMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In what its principals say is a first glimmer of the
rapidly approaching digital entertainment world, executives at
Dreamworks SKG and Imagine Entertainment said Monday they would
join to create a new Internet entertainment company and Web site
offering short films, streaming video, live events, games,
performance art, continuing series, ``nonlinear interactive
features'' and whatever else they can think of.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks, a ministudio formed by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey
Katzenberg and David Geffen, announced the partnership with
Imagine, a film and television production company headed by Ron
Howard and Brian Grazer, and vowed that the new company, to be
called POP.com, would be operating by early spring. The company is
to have offices in New York and Los Angeles, and the announcement
of its first chief executive will be made shortly, Spielberg said.
</P>
<P>
   POP.com is being financed by Vulcan Ventures, the investment
vehicle of Paul G. Allen, the Microsoft co-founder who is already a
major Dreamworks investor. Vulcan has committed $50 million for the
initial phase of the project, Katzenberg said. For that, Vulcan
will get 50 percent of the company; Dreamworks and Imagine will
split the other half.
</P>
<P>
   When it goes online, POP.com is to offer a daily menu of
interactive shorts it calls ``pops,'' most running between 30
seconds and six minutes. The emphasis will be on comedy, but no
genres will be ignored, Spielberg said, and each ``pop'' will come
with its own chat room and instant messaging capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be so seductive and ultimately addictive that
people don't click out after one click,'' Grazer said.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg and Howard, both film directors, said they intended to
contribute their own ``pops'' to the site, though they added that
initially much of their work would be to encourage others to get
involved and to nurture the work of fledgling digital artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emerging and evolving new format,'' Katzenberg
said. ``The analogy I keep coming back to is 25 years ago when you
had this wonderful style called music and someone said, let's turn
it into an audio and video experience, and out of that was born
MTV. We believe we are at that time and moment now for the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement is indicative of the scurrying in
Hollywood in recent months to find ways to understand and
capitalize on the sweeping technological advancements in online and
digital filmmaking and utilize it to shape the entertainment world
of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Howard said, they want to have some fun. ``This is kind of
free-wheeling, less about narrative drive and all the discipline we
have to live with when we make a movie and more about the
exploration of interesting new ideas,'' he said. ``I think we're
going to able to entice a lot of really talented people to do some
work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``pops'' presented on the site might also be the seeds of
other, larger projects, from video games to television series to
feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly see this as like a large, fertile field,''
Spielberg said. ``You can harvest all sorts of spin-offs, just from
whatever germinates. It could be a book, a piece of music, a movie,
who can say?''
</P>
<P>
   As word of the venture began to make the rounds in Hollywood and
in the investment community, most executives and analysts said they
wanted to reserve judgment until they could see exactly what was
planned, and how it might differ from other, perhaps smaller
Internet sites offering digital films.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they promote it?'' asked one entertainment analyst.
``It's very nice to digitize films and put them on the Internet,
but where is the value in it for investors? I guess my initial
reaction is, `yeah, so?'''
</P>
<P>
   Digital moviemaking _ sometimes called microcinema _ is a
relatively small but growing movement of small-scale filmmakers
utilizing the cheaper and rapidly evolving digital technology to
make short films and exhibit them on the Internet. The October
issue of Wired magazine listed more than a dozen Internet sites
offering short digital films, among them Atomfilms _ which exhibits
shorts that are festival favorites or Academy Awards nominees and
counts as its partners the HBO and Warner Bros. Online units of
Time Warner _ and the Bit Screen, which offers short first-run
films and episodic series of 10 minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   POP.com will be different, its founders say, in the scope of its
ambitions, the people associated with it and the strategies it will
use to turn a profit. They intend it as a money-making enterprise.
``We definitely see this as an advertiser and sponsor-supported
business,'' Katzenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, POP.com plans to talk with Madison Avenue
executives about ideas for advertising on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same way that we have to really discover these new
forms, Madison Avenue is going to have to reinvent the way it
advertises to this kind of viewer,'' Katzenberg said. ``Each step
that is being taken in this world today is a first step. All of us,
individually and collectively, are on as big a learning curve as
you can be on. There are no rules, and there is no proven formula
for success in this as yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg said they did not intend to corner the market in
digital filmmaking or to muscle out weaker competitors. ``I think
there will be many stimulating sites in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will still be movies, and there will still be TV,''
Grazer added. ``We're not thinking we're changing the world. We're
just trying to be a part of the sensibility of this new medium.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-25-99 2040EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
