<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DEATH-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN DEATH VALLEY: CALIFORNIA PARK OVERWHELMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN HOLDER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOVEPIPE WELLS, Calif. _ The story should have seemed
suspicious from the beginning. In the canyons of Death Valley
National Park an explorer had come across treasure _ a chest of
gold and some other artifacts thought to be nearly 150 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But that was all I needed to start dreaming. Hey, I was on my
way to Death Valley in just a few weeks, and if a semiretired
substitute teacher could find $500,000 in treasure, well, who
knows?
</P>
<P>
   My fantasy didn't last long. Almost as soon I paid my $10 entry
fee into the park, I learned the find had been discredited. The
coins were authentic, all right, but the chest wasn't, and neither
were some of the other contents.
</P>
<P>
   There was no treasure for me to find in Death Valley. Or was
there?
</P>
<P>
   Boom and bust
</P>
<P>
   The search for treasure in Death Valley has been going on for
150 years or longer. Pioneers in the 1849 California gold rush
stumbled across the area looking for a shortcut. When they found
their way out a month later, the legend goes, one member of the
party turned back and cried, ``Goodbye, Death Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold and other minerals were discovered and boom towns sprang up
all over. But the gold made only a few people rich and the boom
towns quickly became ghost towns. The area became much more well
known for its borax deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Death Valley became a national monument in 1933 and a national
park in 1994. At 3.3 million acres, it's bigger than any national
park except Denali in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Its enormity is one of the first things you learn about Death
Valley. It's one of the first challenges as well. There's no
practical way to see a national park nearly the size of Connecticut
in just a few days. But choose a path that runs roughly from
Stovepipe Wells on the north to Badwater on the south (about 50
miles away), and you'll have all the canyons, mountain peaks and
geographical oddities you can handle.
</P>
<P>
   How low can you go?
</P>
<P>
   If Death Valley is famous for anything, it's as one of the
hottest and lowest places on earth. The average high temperature in
July is 115 degrees. Winter is much more survivable, if not
enjoyable. In January, when I visited, the average high reaches
only 65 or so, and it's the elevation that's much more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   As you wind your way into the park along California 190, the
signs won't let you forget that you're dropping: 3,000 feet, 2,000
feet, sea level. By the time you hit Badwater, about 17 miles south
of the visitor center at Furnace Creek, you're 282 feet below sea
level.
</P>
<P>
   A sign at Badwater announces that you're at the lowest point in
the Western Hemisphere. But you can appreciate that more by craning
your neck and looking up at the brown mountain east of the highway.
Way up on the mountainside, a white square stands out. So high up:
It's sea level. And in the other direction Telescope Peak soars to
11,049 feet _ from where you stand, even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Badwater got its name when a pioneer's mule refused to drink
from a permanent spring there. Even on the hottest days the water
remains, but it's unpotable, thanks to a combination of sulfur and
salt. ``And it is nasty,'' said one park ranger.
</P>
<P>
   The real treat at Badwater, however, is the salt flats that
stretch out for 5 miles beyond the highway. It's so easy to imagine
the pioneers coming around a bend and seeing this great white
expanse of what, at first, sure looks like thirst-quenching water,
or maybe ice. What a disappointment this hard, crusty sea of salt
must have been. The surface patterns created by the wind and rain
are fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the middle it's bright _ grab those sunglasses. And you
almost have a feeling that you're on a lake covered with ice that
could give way at any time. Reality check: Pinch off a piece of the
surface and take a nibble. The briny taste will stay with you.
</P>
<P>
   Fore?
</P>
<P>
   The geography gets even more bizarre just to the north, at the
Devil's Golf Course, which got its name from a 1934 Park Service
guidebook that said ``only the devil could play golf on such a
surface.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance it looks like nothing more than a huge field of
dirt knobs, but on closer inspection you have to marvel at the
thousands and thousands of tightly spaced rock formations, created
when salt crystals exerted enormous pressure, forcing columns
upward.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the things you grow to quickly appreciate about
Death Valley. It's up to you to find the ... well, treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death Valley is certainly a place that takes people by
surprise,'' said Charlie Callagan, a park ranger. ``We encourage
you to walk and explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Look closer ... closer
</P>
<P>
   Life is all around, even though it's not readily apparent in the
hot, arid conditions of this place. Consider the sand dunes near
Stovepipe Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning, Callagan said, is the best time for
finding wildlife tracks. Overnight the wind will have blown away
all signs of people. ``It's a real treat to be out there early in
the morning and look for the tracks of the creatures who have been
there during the night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here I was just before sunrise and the only tracks I could
find were tennis shoes _ mine. But there's no way this place could
be a disappointment. And there's no better time to see these
magnificent dunes, one of five sets spread throughout Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A few cars were parked along the highway, and one photographer
had set up a tripod waiting for dawn. But out in the middle of
hundreds of dunes, I was alone and it was magnificent. As the
evidence of a new day grew, the tan colors of these hills, as well
as the pinks and purples of the distant mountains, changed minute
by minute. And just when I thought I had noticed everything, the
sun leaped into the sky, creating a new world of light and shadows.
</P>
<P>
   And the wildlife? It was there, too. Tiny tracks offered plenty
of evidence that birds, beetles and kangaroo rats had been here.
All I had to do was look.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky roads
</P>
<P>
   If you pick sunrise to visit the dunes, you might save a canyon
for sundown. Death Valley has hundreds to explore.
</P>
<P>
   Mosaic Canyon, just past Stovepipe Wells, is notable because of
the artful patterns you'll find embedded in the rock walls. You may
have to scramble up and over the rocks here as you walk the narrow
trail, but you'll be rewarded again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Near Badwater, Natural Bridge Canyon is easily worth the
0.3-mile hike up a pebbly path, to see _ what else? _ a rock bridge
high overhead. Keep walking and you'll end up at a dry waterfall, a
stopping place for many of the canyon trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always amazed by people who come here looking for a loop
hike,'' Callagan said. ``I say, `Well, you can go so far, but
you're going to have to come back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the geography stops you, it's not so easy to turn back.
``It's almost like it lures you around the next corner,'' Callagan
said. ``You say, `I wonder what's going to be around there?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Also check out the Golden Canyon Interpretive Trail and Gower
Gulch Loop, both through badlands near Furnace Creek. Titus Canyon,
about 35 miles north of Furnace Creek, boasts Native American
petroglyphs. MORE
</P>
<P>
   (of Furnace Creek, boasts Native American petroglyphs.)
</P>
<P>
   Now you see it ...
</P>
<P>
   You may well come away from Death Valley more impressed by what
you never saw than by what you did. That's the power of the tiny
Salt Creek pupfish.
</P>
<P>
   These 2-inch or smaller creatures once lived in what was Lake
Marley, a 90-mile-long freshwater lake. But the lake dried up
10,000 years ago and the creatures became trapped in all that was
left _ an underground river. The thing is, much of the year you
can't see any water at all.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the cold of winter and the unbearable heat of summer,
these fish bury themselves under the ground, where they thrive and
even reproduce. At certain times of spring and fall, when Salt
Creek makes its presence known, you can actually see the fish _ the
rangers promise. The rest of the time you'll just have to take
their word for it.
</P>
<P>
   Walk along the half-mile boardwalk and you'll learn how
difficult it is for anything to survive here. The salty soil allows
only a few plants, notably salt grass and pickleweed, to flourish.
So if you hear the sound of trickling water below, be sure to look.
You won't find Salt Creek pupfish anywhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Not just a slogan
</P>
<P>
   You know the reputation of mules. Try getting 20 of them to
cooperate at once.
</P>
<P>
   At the ruins of Harmony Borax Works, just north of Furnace
Creek, the term ``20 mule team'' becomes much more than an
advertising slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Harmony Borax Works, just north of Furnace Creek, was
established in 1883 to process ulexite cottonball borax, used to
make soap, fiberglass insulation and cosmetics, among other things.
Harmony closed in 1888, but the borax is still evident on the white
flats west of the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   You also can see the adobe remains where the mineral was
processed and hauled away in rugged wagons, which when full weighed
36.5 tons. Between 1883 and 1888, the 20-mule teams carried more
than 15 million pounds of borax out of Death Valley on 20-day round
trips.
</P>
<P>
   Those mule teams, by the way, often consisted of 18 mules and
two horses. The driver sat 120 feet away from the lead mule, with
whom he had to communicate. Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Harmony was just one of many borax works throughout Death
Valley. In fact, the crystals are still mined in some places here.
The Furnace Creek borax museum has plenty of artifacts and borax
examples on hand to help complete the story.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, borax is kind of a symbol for Death Valley. It was a
unexpected boon, much more so than the lure of gold. Even if it's
gold that brings you here now, it's the unexpected treasures you'll
remember.
</P>
<P>
   GOING TO DEATH VALLEY NATIONAL PARK
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Death Valley National Park is about 120 miles west of Las Vegas,
Nev. Recent airfares between Kansas City and Las Vegas ran from
about $200, with restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the park
</P>
<P>
   Entrance to the park costs $10 per vehicle; the fee is good for
seven days. You can pay at ranger stations at Furnace Creek,
Grapevine, Stovepipe Wells or Beatty. Be sure to pick up a park map
and visitor's guide.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   - The Furnace Creek Inn was opened by the Pacific Borax Co. in
1927 and is undoubtedly Death Valley's most plush place to stay.
The 66-room resort boasts a spring-fed pool, tennis, massage,
horseback riding and carriage rides. Room rates run $230 to $345
through May. Call (760) 786-2345.MDSD/.MDNM/ or visit
www.furnacecreekresort.com or www.amfac.com
</P>
<P>
   - Furnace Creek Ranch, adjacent to the park headquarters, has
the feel of a Western town. Rates for the 224 motel rooms and
cabins range from $94 to $134 through December. A gas station and
general store are nearby. Call (760) 786-2345 or visit
www.furnacecreekresort.com or www.amfac.com
</P>
<P>
   - Stovepipe Wells Village, about 30 minutes north of the Furnace
Creek park headquarters, offers 83 motel rooms, which it describes
as ``modern to rustic.'' Prices range from $63 to $84. Near ranger
station, gas station and general store. Call (760) 786-2387 or
visit www.furnacecreekresort.com or amfac.com
</P>
<P>
   - Panamint Springs Resort has 14 motel rooms and one two-bedroom
cottage on the park's western edge. Rates range from $57 to $90 for
motel rooms to $130 for the cottage. Campsites and RV hookups are
available. Call (775) 482-7680 or visit www.deathvalley.com
</P>
<P>
   - Camping opportunities are available throughout the park. For
reservations and information call (800) 365-2267 or visit the Web
site at
</P>
</TEXT>
