<SLUG> BC-THAI-CHEF-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVELY CHEF KNOWS NO BOUNDS IN CREATING THAI DISHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRIS WORRELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROTTERDAM, N.Y. _ Tommy Tang is throwing a pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides all the tropical fruit in Thailand, pineapple,
especially in the south, pineapple over there is so sweet, whenever
you go there, you must try them. You will love it! What we gonna do
with fruit, like this? We can play football with it!''
</P>
<P>
   He whips it to an assistant, who lobs it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaahh, touchdown!'' shouts Tang as he catches the pineapple,
then sets it on a counter. ``OK, now we're gonna go cooking now.
Enough of football.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Tommy's world, a place where rapid-fire, elliptical
English, Hawaiian shirts, goofy antics, and hot Thai spices mix
together like a big pot of Bangkok Jambalaya. Tang, the 50-year-old
celebrity chef who introduced Thai food to America two decades ago,
is the king of fusion, both in life and in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to California from his native Thailand in 1972,
Tang has been a self-appointed ambassador for Thai cuisine, first
as a chef in Los Angeles, then as owner of Tommy Tang's
restaurants, two in California and one, now closed, in New York. He
has his own line of spices and sauces. In 1991 he wrote a
best-selling cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   He even makes a cameo in the new Bruce Willis movie ``The Story
of Us,'' in which he tells Michelle Pfeiffer's character, in a Thai
cooking class: ``Spicy food makes better lovers. The hotter the
food, the hotter you get!''
</P>
<P>
   But Tang's version of Thai food is, like everything else about
him, his own. While he uses plenty of traditional Thai ingredients
such as fish sauce, lemon grass and bamboo shoots, he also uses
everything from pine nuts to black olives. Some purists have
criticized his modern twist on Thai, but Tang dismisses them with a
wave of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to create new things. All the traditional stuff, I've
done that before. Can you ask Picasso to paint the same picture
over and over? Same thing with cooking. You need to create new
things. That's why I create this Thai fusion,'' says Tang, who has
two young daughters with his wife, Sandi, a Jewish
Italian-American. ``I just mingle the whole world, to do it my
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Tang was in the studios of WMHT-TV in Rotterdam,
taping the third season of ``Tommy Tang's Modern Thai Cuisine,'' a
cooking show that airs on 75 to 100 public television stations
nationwide. Tang and a crew from WMHT first travel to Thailand for
several weeks to tape segments on location, then finish filming the
26 episodes in the studio over a three-week period.
</P>
<P>
   Today's recipe is Macaroni with Shrimp, made with (among other
things) elbow pasta, shrimp, diced tomatoes, eggs _ and ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why ketchup?'' says Tang, as he scoots back and forth in the
studio kitchen, wearing one of his customary colorful Hawaiian
shirts and a bright blue bandana. ``In Thailand when I was young,
when we go to the restaurant, they call (it) macaroni with shrimp.
I didn't know it was supposed to be called tomato paste! All we
know is ketchup, so I use ketchup to make this dish. And now I
could use tomato paste, but why? My childhood memories, I'm very
fond about this dish.''
</P>
<P>
   Tang has his own unique style. He chatters nonstop, expertly
tossing shrimp into a frying pan, adding more olive oil until the
whole thing goes up in a quick flame. At that, Tang lets out one of
his gleeful giggles. ``Whoa, what we got, a shrimp flambe?''
</P>
<P>
   Tang's first meal in the United States was significantly less
flashy. He says he landed in Los Angeles on Christmas Eve in 1972.
Hungry, he went to a movie theater to get something to eat because
no restaurants were open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course a movie theater in Thailand has every kind of food
imaginable that you can go and eat,'' he says. Tang ordered a hot
dog and large Coke, which he says he didn't realize would be quite
so large.
</P>
<P>
   But things, in general, got bigger for Tang once he was in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Bangkok, the oldest boy of 10 children, Tang and his
family became homeless after a fire destroyed their house. He
dropped out of school after finishing the fourth grade, and began
working a series of jobs, first in a factory, then in a coffee shop
with a restaurant, where each night he emptied the buckets that
served as both ashtray and spittoon, and eventually began assisting
the cook. Next he worked as a bellboy in a top hotel in Bangkok
that catered to international tourists and American servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   Tang taught himself English by reading a dictionary and seeing
movies. If he came across words he didn't know, he wrote them on
his arm during the film to look up later. ``So by the time I come
out, it looks like I have tattoos on my whole arms,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Although he made good money at the hotel, the lure of education
called, and when Tang was accepted to a community college in
Blythe, Calif., he went. While in school, Tang boarded with an
elderly woman, who volunteered him to cook for her ladies group.
``I said, `Are you out of your mind? I never cooked in front of
people!''' Tang's cooking became so popular that he began a
catering business on the weekends while finishing school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when he graduated from college with a degree in
automotive mechanics and business, he did not think of himself as a
chef. He moved to Los Angeles and began managing a friend's rock
band. He was tempted back into the kitchen when the girlfriend of
one of his guitar players asked him to help out in the Thai
restaurant where she worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little did I know, I would just enjoy it more and more,'' he
says, adding that it didn't take long for him to quit the music
business. ``There was a whole kitchen for me to create in!''
</P>
<P>
   Tang worked his way up to executive chef at Chan Dara, the tiny
restaurant in Hollywood that some say was the first Thai restaurant
in the country. He developed a devoted following there, which he
took with him when he left in 1982 to open his own restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
