A9944 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-27 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN AND REFORM: A BAD MARRIAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So it's official. Pat Buchanan is no longer a member of the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for the Republican Party, which has significantly
upgraded the quality of its membership.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan stood before the TV cameras Monday and tried to palm
off his switch to the Reform Party as an act of principle. What it
was, of course, was an act of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan wants to run for president. The Republican Party has no
interest in his candidacy. He went shopping for a party that needs
a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is out on the question of Buchanan's appeal as a
potential standard-bearer for the Reform Party, but let's be
realistic: A political party that was founded by Ross Perot and
claims Jesse Ventura as its highest-ranking officeholder definitely
figures to be goofy enough to nominate Buchanan for president.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan is desperate for a political party to prop up his
candidacy, how desperate is the party that agrees to prop him up?
Pretty desperate, I'd say, especially when you consider that
Buchanan's only opposition at the moment is Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Trump has already set the tone for the campaign, by the way,
attacking Buchanan as a ``Hitler lover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he's an anti-Semite,'' Trump said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan replied, more or less, that sticks and stones may break
his bones but words will never hurt him. Trump and others have
resorted to name-calling, Buchanan said, because people are afraid
of the ideas he represents.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan does have at least one legitimate idea: his pledge to
keep the United States out of foreign wars that are none of our
business.
</P>
<P>
   But there is good reason for people to be afraid of other
Buchanan ideas, especially his would-be policies on trade, race
relations, immigration, education and the relationship between
government and religion. Buchanan was going nowhere in the GOP
because he is too far out of the mainstream for even the most
conservative of Republican conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the issue of Buchanan's compatibility
with the Reform Party. Except for similar views on some economic
and trade issues, what does Buchanan have in common with the
Reformers? He seems to believe that the government should have
morality cops going door-to-door to enforce his version of
Christian culture, whereas the Reform Party is basically
libertarian on issues of personal morality _ not to mention
pro-choice on the issue of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan bolted the Republican Party because the party
leadership has de-emphasized the moral and social issues he holds
so dear, how in the world can he hook up with an outfit that never
had any interest in those issues in the first place? He calls that
an act of principle?
</P>
<P>
   It was a blatant act of political expediency.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Buchanan doesn't really represent ideas or a cause
or even a constituency. He represents his own ego _ a beast so huge
and insatiable that he had to sever his lifelong affiliation with
the Republican Party in order to keep feeding it.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggesting that Buchanan might have a significant
impact on the general election if he turns out to be the Reform
Party's nominee are ludicrous because they presume that people who
care enough about their country to vote in a presidential election
would be willing to waste their votes on a man who is so obviously
unsuited for the job he seeks.
</P>
<P>
   The electorate makes mistakes from time to time. But the voters
_ not even 5 percent of the voters, as one poll suggests _ would
never so much as flirt with the notion of handing over the keys to
the White House to the likes of Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   All these nervous-Nellie Republicans who are shaking in their
boots over Buchanan's potential to hijack votes from the Republican
presidential nominee need to stop worrying and get on with the
business of choosing a candidate and winning the election.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's presidential candidacy is a joke _ a bad joke, but a
joke nonetheless. If the Reform Party chooses him as its nominee,
it will be a joke as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
