<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TIMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UN'S JOB IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has never been anything quite like the reconstruction task
the United Nations has accepted in the liberated but devastated
territory of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the Security Council authorized a UN administration
for East Timor until the Timorese can exercise the independence
they have long desired. Because Indonesian forces and their proxies
deliberately destroyed nearly everything that could be destroyed in
East Timor after the population voted overwhelmingly on Aug. 30 for
independence, the UN mission will have to create not only the
material infrastructure for a sustainable economy but also the
institutional foundations for durable self-government.
</P>
<P>
   Daunting as the task of nation-building will be, it is fitting
that the responsibility falls on the UN. Since Indonesia invaded
East Timor in 1975 and annexed it the following year, the UN has
properly refused to recognize Indonesian claims to sovereignty over
the Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   This year the UN took on the job of supervising preparations for
a referendum on independence for the territory. However, UN
officials failed to heed warnings from the Timorese about the
possibility of violence organized by the Indonesian military.
Because the UN left security in the hands of the Indonesian Army
and did not insist on international protection for the Timorese
people, it has an added obligation to shepherd East Timor toward a
viable independent existence.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there is no other candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Money and skilled workers will be needed to rebuild burned
houses and public edifices, to install water and sewer systems and
a communications network. Timorese coffee growers will need
assistance to revive cultivation of their most important cash crop.
The UN's interim administration will have to foster an indigenous
civil service, a police force, a judiciary, and the groundwork for
a constitutional government.
</P>
<P>
   The UN's rebuilding of East Timor is a mission that deserves
financial and political support from Washington and the rest of the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
