A9968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-FAIRNESS-BO     10-27 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FAIRNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORK OF FAIRNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a social minefield to discuss why white students, on
average, get higher grades and test scores than black and Hispanic
students. The issue is fraught with aspects of history, fairness,
politics, money, and assumptions about innate talent. But this
turmoil can be avoided by sticking to facts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the debate over affirmative action, a new College Board
report says: ``Our public institutions have pursued relatively few
education policies specifically targeted to minorities.'' Most of
the work has been done in programs like Head Start that focus on
the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   From pre-kindergarten through college, opportunities exist to
address minority underachievement using thoughtful, often proven
methods.
</P>
<P>
   One classic program was a calculus workshop at the University of
California at Berkeley in the 1970s. Taken at the same time as an
introductory calculus class, the workshop let students study in
depth, fill holes in their education, and use the strategy of
studying in groups.
</P>
<P>
   Workshop students learned to do hard work well. Most got an A or
B in the calculus class. This undermined stereotypes among other
students and faculty. And the program showed the need to strengthen
both students and schools.
</P>
<P>
   This takes many ingredients. One is money for innovations at all
school levels and across class lines. Growth, says the report,
should occur in the ``parallel education system'' _ the many
out-of-school programs that parents of all races use to supplement
their children's education.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes are tougher. Black students who get good grades
have to shake off the slur that they are ``acting white.'' Colleges
have to root out what has been called a ``lack of hospitality''
toward minority students that many experience as hostility. Changes
on this level could lead to insights on better teaching for boys,
who tend to underperform academically in comparison with girls.
</P>
<P>
   Missing is the public courage to insist that closing achievement
gaps need not be racist or discriminate against white students. It
simply responds to a problem with powerful solutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
