<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9973 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-HALLOWEEN-RECIPE     10-27 2970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HALLOWEEN-RECIPES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No tricks to making these treats
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goblins and ghosts, mummies and monsters are all around you.
Just look in the grocery aisles. Licorice and candy corn make great
eyes and lips. Crooked nuts are noses. Corn chips are ears. Whipped
cream piped just so looks like ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   There are also great cupcake papers, sugar decorations, gel
icings and even canned frosting with orange and black confetti. So
pulling together something scary for a weekend fright fest should
be a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Ghoul-Aid Punch
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If you are in a pinch and don't have time to make an elaborate
punch, try this one. Kids are sure to love it. For an extra touch,
try floating ghoulish ``hands'' in the punch. The idea came from a
book chock-full of fun ideas _ ``Kraft Halloween: Let's Make
Something Good'' (Meredith Books, $12.95). This punch bowl will
have the goblins circling.
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope cherry flavor unsweetened soft drink mix
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope grape flavor unsweetened soft drink mix
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope tropical punch flavor unsweetened soft drink mix
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   18 cups cold water (4 1/2 quarts)
</P>
<P>
   Ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   Place soft drink mixes and sugar in large punch bowl. Add water;
stir to dissolve. Serve over ice cubes._ From: ``Kraft Halloween:
Let's Make Something Good'' (Meredith Books, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 136 calories, no protein, no fat, 35 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 6 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   To make floating hands
</P>
<P>
   Wash and dry plastic or latex gloves. If the gloves have a
powdery residue inside, turn them inside out and soak in warm water
or wipe with soapy water and rinse. Allow to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare one envelope of an unsweetened soft drink mix according
to package directions; or fill a large bowl with water and drop in
food coloring until the water is very dark (the color may lighten
when frozen).
</P>
<P>
   Put a few gummy worms in gloves, if desired. Add enough soft
drink to fill gloves, but not so full that the fingers will not
move. Fasten gloves tightly with twist-ties. Place paper towels on
a cookie sheet and lay ``hands'' on paper towels. Freeze. When
frozen solid, carefully use scissors to cut gloves off frozen
``hands.'' Float ``hands'' in bowl of punch.
</P>
<P>
   The Purr-fect Treat
</P>
<P>
   Makes 36 cookies Preparation time: 20 minutes Chilling time: 1-2
hours Cooking time: 7-9 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We found this recipe for a firm chocolate cookie along with
other spooktacular ideas for Halloween on the Better Homes &AMP;
Gardens Web site (www.bhg.com/halloween). The cookie is not very
sweet, so it benefits from decoration. The number of cookies will
vary depending on the size of the cutter. I used a variety of 2-
and 4-inch cutters in the shapes of pumpkins, ghosts, cats and
bats.
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon finely shredded orange peel
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Orange Icing:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 drops orange food
</P>
<P>
   coloring
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, beat shortening and margarine or butter
with an electric mixer on medium to high speed for 30 seconds or
until softened.
</P>
<P>
   Add 3/4 cup flour, sugar, cocoa powder, egg, 2 tablespoons milk,
orange peel and juice, baking powder and vanilla. Beat till
combined, scraping bowl occasionally. Beat or stir in remaining
flour. Dough may be rather dry. Feel free to add 1 or 2 more
tablespoons milk if needed. Divide in half. Cover; chill for 1 to 2
hours or until easy to handle. On a lightly floured surface, roll
each dough portion to 1/8-inch thickness. With cookie cutter, cut
in shapes. Place shapes 1 inch apart on an ungreased cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 375-degree oven for 7 to 9 minutes or until edges are
firm and bottoms are light brown. Remove cookies; cool thoroughly
on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   In a small mixing bowl, stir together confectioners' sugar, 1/4
teaspoon vanilla and enough orange juice (2 to 3 teaspoons) to make
of piping consistency. Stir in enough orange food coloring (or a
combination of red and yellow) to color the icing orange. Place
icing in a small, sealed plastic bag with a small hole snipped out
of one corner, or in a pastry bag fitted with a small round tip.
Decorate cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 86 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 41), 13 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 42 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Buttermilk Cupcakes Makes 24 cupcakes Preparation
time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, along with the one for the Traditional Vanilla
Buttercream, comes from a charming little corner bakery in New York
City that specializes in old-fashioned layer cakes and cupcakes _
the Magnolia Bakery, which has a just-released cookbook, ``The
Magnolia Bakery Cookbook'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   We think it's worth the effort, which is only a few minutes more
than a mix. It's my new favorite chocolate cake recipe (this recipe
can also make two 9-inch layers, cooking 25 to 30 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces unsweetened chocolate, melted and cooled 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Put cupcake papers in a muffin pan
and set aside. In a medium-size bowl, sift together flour and
baking soda. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, cream butter, sugar and brown sugar with an
electric mixer until smooth, about 3 minutes. Add the eggs one at a
time, beating well after each addition. Add the chocolate, mixing
until well-incorporated. Add the flour mixture in thirds,
alternating with the buttermilk and the vanilla extract, beating
after each addition until smooth. Spoon batter into the cupcake
papers about 3/4 full. Bake for about 20 minutes or until tops
spring back lightly when touched. Remove cupcakes from pans and
cool on rack. When cooled, frost and decorate.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without buttercream): 228 calories, 4 grams
protein, 13 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 50), 27 grams
carbohydrates, 74 milligrams cholesterol, 65 milligrams sodium,
less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Vanilla Buttercream
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for a 9-inch layer cake or 24 cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, very soft
</P>
<P>
   4 cups confectioners' sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Place butter in a large mixing bowl. Add 2 cups sugar, then the
milk and vanilla. Beat until smooth and creamy. Gradually add
remaining sugar, 1 cup at a time, until icing is thick enough to be
of good spreading consistency (you may not need all the sugar). If
desired, add a few drops food coloring and mix thoroughly. Use and
store icing at room temperature, as icing will set if chilled. Can
store in airtight container up to three days. _ From: Magnolia
Bakery
</P>
<P>
   Per cupcake serving: 114 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 4
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 32), 20 grams carbohydrates,
11 milligrams cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Snake Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 48 cookies
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 4-5 minutes per batch
</P>
<P>
   You don't need cookie cutters to have fun. Just grab a roll of
sugar cookie dough from the refrigerated case in the grocery (or
make your favorite) and roll instead of cut to make these scary and
scrumptious snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerated sugar cookie dough
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Black food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Orange food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Freeze sugar cookie dough for 45 minutes or until thoroughly
chilled. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cut a 1/8-inch slice of dough and roll into a very thin pencil
shape on a floured surface. Each ``snake'' should be 1/4 inch in
diameter and 4 to 5 inches long. Carefully place the shapes on
ungreased cookie sheets, giving them a slight curve in the middle
to resemble crawling snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 4 to 5 minutes, until the edges are golden brown. Allow to
cool on cookie sheets before removing and transferring to racks.
(The cookies will break if you try to move them while they're
warm.)
</P>
<P>
   For the icing: Mix confectioners' sugar with 2 to 3 tablespoons
water until the consistency of a thick glaze. Transfer a few
tablespoons of the icing to a separate bowl and tint with black
food coloring. Add orange food coloring to the big bowl of icing.
</P>
<P>
   Place cooled cookies on wire racks set on top of newspaper to
protect the countertop. Use a thin paintbrush to completely coat
each snake with a liberal amount of orange icing. Put black icing
into a zippered plastic snack bag. Seal, and cut a tiny hole in one
corner.
</P>
<P>
   When orange icing has dried on snakes, pipe black stripes
horizontally on each cookie. Alternatively, you may decorate the
cookies while orange icing is still wet with sprinkles, sugar
crystals or other cookie decorations. _ From: Dallas Morning News
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 69 calories, 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 34), 11 grams carbohydrates, 4 milligrams
cholesterol, 52 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosts in the Graveyard
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: at least 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Using all convenience items, you can make this centerpiece for a
Halloween party in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   1 package (20 ounces) chocolate sandwich cookies
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups cold milk
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (4-serving size each) chocolate flavor instant
pudding and pie filling
</P>
<P>
   1 tub (11-12 ounces) frozen whipped topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   Set aside 6 cookies for decorations. Crush remaining cookies in
zipper-style plastic bag with rolling pin or in food processor.
</P>
<P>
   Pour cold milk into large bowl. Add pudding mix. Beat with wire
whisk 2 minutes. Gently stir in 3 cups of the whipped topping and
half the crushed cookies. Spoon into 13-by-9-inch dish. Sprinkle
with remaining crushed cookies (to look like dirt in the
graveyard). Refrigerate 1 hour or until ready to decorate and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   To decorate graveyard: Use assorted cookies and decorator icings
or gels to create ``tombstones'' with the cookies. Write R.I.P. on
vanilla wafers or Milano cookies or others of your choice. Then
stand ``tombstones'' on top of dessert with candy corn, candy
pumpkins and tiny jelly beans. Drop remaining whipped topping by
spoonfuls onto dessert to create ghosts. Decorate with candies to
create ``eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Store leftover dessert, covered, in refrigerator. _ From:
``Kraft Halloween: Let's Make Something Good'' (Meredith Books,
$12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 305 calories, 4 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 42 grams carbohydrates, 7
milligrams cholesterol, 203 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Jack-O'-Lantern Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 12 minutes Refrigeration
time: 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   Another fun idea frKraft folks, this time from their Web
site, www.kraftfoods.com. Have fun with the face. We made licorice
and candy corn eyes, a chocolate triangle (cut from a chocolate
bar) for a nose and candy corn for teeth.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 package (4-serving size) orange
</P>
<P>
   flavor gelatin dessert
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   1 small tub (8 ounces) frozen whipped topping, thawed, about 3
cups, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 ready-to-use chocolate flavor crumb crust (6 ounces or 9-inch)
</P>
<P>
   (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Candy corn
</P>
<P>
   Black licorice, cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Pour boiling water over gelatin in large bowl and stir 2 minutes
or until completely dissolved. Stir in cold water. Refrigerate 1
hour or until slightly thickened (consistency of unbeaten egg
whites).
</P>
<P>
   Stir in 2 cups of the whipped topping with wire whisk until
smooth. Spread in crust.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate 2 hours or until firm. Just before serving, decorate
pie to make jack-o'-lantern face with remaining whipped topping,
candy corn and licorice.
</P>
<P>
   Store leftover pie in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For a darker, richer crust, place 8 to 10 ounces of
chocolate sandwich cookies in a plastic bag and crush with a
rolling pin. Place crumbs in a bowl and add 1/4 cup melted butter.
Press into pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 326 calories, 3 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 45 grams carbohydrates, 1
milligram cholesterol, 242 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Dracula's Eyes (shown above)Makes 20 eyeballs
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These are certain to be the special of the haunted house, spooky
and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces vanilla-flavored candy coating
</P>
<P>
   20 candy-coated milk chocolate pieces
</P>
<P>
   Red and black decorator gel icing
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, stir together peanut butter and butter.
Gradually add confectioners' sugar, stirring until combined. Shape
in 1-inch balls; place on waxed paper. Let stand about 20 minutes
or until dry.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, melt candy coating pieces over low heat.
Dip balls, one at a time, into coating. Let excess coating drip
back into pan. Place coated balls on waxed paper.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately press a candy-coated chocolate piece into the center
of each peanut butter ball. Let stand until coating is firm. Add a
dot of black gel to the center of candy pieces for pupils. Drizzle
red gel onto balls for bloodshot eyes. _ From:
www.bhg.com/halloween
</P>
<P>
   Per piece: 141 calories, 2 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 50), 17 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 68 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Spooky
</P>
<P>
   Ghost CupsMakes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: at least 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Fluffy and funny, these easy ghosts can be made in a flash,
leaving plenty of time for making any last-minute costumes.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cold milk
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (4-serving size each) vanilla flavor instant pudding
and pie filling
</P>
<P>
   2 cups frozen whipped topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   8 (7-ounce) clear plastic cups or glasses
</P>
<P>
   Pour cold milk into large bowl. Add pudding mix. Beat with wire
whisk 2 minutes. Gently stir in whipped topping.
</P>
<P>
   Pipe or spoon mixture into cups to resemble ghosts. To pipe:
Spoon mixture into large zipper-style plastic bag. Close bag
tightly. Snip 1/2-inch piece off one corner of bag. Holding top of
bag tightly, squeeze mixture into small plastic cups. Create a
``face'' with decorating icing and candies.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate until ready to serve. _ From: ``Kraft Halloween:
Let's Make Something Good'' (Meredith Books, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 177 calories, 2 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 35), 27 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 195 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Two Step
</P>
<P>
   Taco DipMakes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The tricks for making a cat face could be used on many dips.
Black bean dip might be fun to dress up as a black cat.
</P>
<P>
   1 container (16 ounces) sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 1/4 ounces) Taco Bell Home Originals Taco Seasoning
Mix
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped tomato
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Mexican style shredded cheese
</P>
<P>
   Garnishes: Green bell pepper, sliced crosswise; pitted and
sliced black olives; tomato slices and fresh chives.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine sour cream and seasoning mix until
well-blended. Spread on bottom of 9-inch pie plate or quiche dish.
Layer lettuce, tomato and cheese over sour cream. Top with
garnishes to create a cat's face. Serve with tortilla chips. _
From: ``Kraft Halloween: Let's Make Something Good'' (Meredith
Books, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without chips): 200 calories, 6 grams protein, 17
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 77), 6 grams carbohydrates,
41 milligrams cholesterol, 568 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Honeyed Popcorn and PeanutsMakes 6 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Caramel popcorn, popcorn balls and other popcorn mixes are often
a part of Halloween celebrations. Here's an easy, microwave
technique for creating a homemade version of Cracker Jack. You can
even find prizes at party or toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   1 package (3 1/2 ounces) salt-free microwave popcorn
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups roasted salted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   6 small paper bags (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Prepare popcorn according to package instructions. Place in
bowl. Add peanuts and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1-cup microwavable measuring cup, combine butter, honey and
cinnamon. Microwave on high (100 percent) until butter is melted
(30 to 60 seconds). Stir to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle butter mixture over popcorn mixture. Toss to coat, pour
into bowl and serve warm. Or divide popcorn among 6 small paper
bags; set filled bags in microwavable dish and reheat in the
microwave on high until warm. Just before serving, add
plastic-wrapped party favor to each bag, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-cup serving: 318 calories, 11 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 65), 23 grams carbohydrates, 10
milligrams cholesterol, 215 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
