<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HALLOWEEN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Halloween treats so easy it's scary
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wicked weekend is upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly ghosts and frightening ones will be roaming our
neighborhoods. Cackling witches and kind ones will be ringing our
doorbells. Ghastly monsters and goofy ones will be circling our
punch bowls.
</P>
<P>
   And they all have the same demand: treats.
</P>
<P>
   As times have changed, more and more folks are choosing to
celebrate Halloween in their homes, schools and community centers
rather than focusing on door-to-door visits. That means we need
more party fare.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who like the traditional trick or treating may want
more since Halloween falls on a Sunday. The whole weekend is set up
for freaky fun.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't given the first thought to how you'll satisfy the
little goblins, hold back that blood-curdling scream. We've got a
bag of speedy and spooky tricks _ 13 of them in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Like ghoulish punch with floating hands, Dracula's Eyes and a
Jack-O'-Lantern pie.
</P>
<P>
   So now's a good time to hop on the old broomstick and get to the
grocery, where you'll find everything you'll need for these creepy
13.
</P>
<P>
   1. Float some fun
</P>
<P>
   Give the goblins a scare when they dip into the punch bowl. The
day before the party, freeze colorful punch in plastic or latex
gloves. Just before serving, cut the gloves off and then float the
dismembered hands in the punch bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Spooky cookie
</P>
<P>
   Ghosts, bats, pumpkins and cats. We found cookie cutters for all
those shapes and more in local grocery and craft stores. So pick up
a roll of sugar cookie dough or try our recipe for
orange-and-chocolate cookies inside. Cut, cook, frost or sprinkle,
and you'll have spooky cookies in no time.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cute cutouts
</P>
<P>
   Those cookie cutters can cut more than dough. Stack thick-cut
slices of bologna and cheese and then cut into shapes. Or put the
stacks between two slices of white bread and cut _ for that ghostly
look. Use cheese, mustard and ketchup to add faces.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bewitched
</P>
<P>
   Whether you do this one in advance or make it a party activity,
it's sure to bewitch your pint-size guests. Freeze full, round
scoops of sherbet (lime is creepy, orange is Halloweeny) on small
paper plates. Set up a decorating station, with sugar cones for
hats, licorice for hair, nuts for noses and candies for eyes and
lips. Let guests create their own witches and then dig in. (If you
have some slowpokes, refreeze before eating.)
</P>
<P>
   5. Funny faces
</P>
<P>
   Halloween cupcakes are so easy to dress up. Candy corn and round
candy-coated chocolate make the eyes, noses and mouths. Thin
licorice or icing pens can also make the mouth. Or simply frost and
plop a spider ring on top. Use your favorite cake mix or try our
luscious buttermilk chocolate cake recipe inside.
</P>
<P>
   6. Sssscary snakes
</P>
<P>
   make snakes. Then ``paint'' them with orange and black frosting
to give them spots and stripes.
</P>
<P>
   7. Toothsome tombstones
</P>
<P>
   Create a ``graveyard'' in a baking pan by layering pudding,
whipped cream and crumbled cookies. Then stand assorted cookies in
the top for tombstones and use whipped cream to create ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   8. Jack-O'-Lantern Pie
</P>
<P>
   The face of a pie is a perfect palette for trickery. Licorice
eyebrows and candy corn teeth add a little fright and a lot of fun
to an easy orange cream pie.
</P>
<P>
   9. Popcorn party favors
</P>
<P>
   Stuff small paper bags with honey-coated popcorn and peanuts for
an old-fashioned caramel corn effect. And just for fun, throw in a
plastic-wrapped surprise, like a spider ring or a Halloween
noisemaker.
</P>
<P>
   10. I spy Dracula's Eyes
</P>
<P>
   For a really haunting treat, disguise peanut butter and
chocolate candy in a vanilla coating, then press in candy pieces in
the center for irises. A dot of black gel will make the pupil, and
squiggles of red gel will give the eyeballs that bloodshot look.
</P>
<P>
   11. Goody goblins
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of a tempest in a teapot. How about a ghost in a
cup? Spoon fluffy mounds of pudding and whipped cream into clear
plastic cups, then decorate with small candies and icing for
goblins sure to be gobbled up.
</P>
<P>
   12. Purr-fect dip
</P>
<P>
   Just a few quick tricks, like green pepper triangles for ears
and nose, black olives for eyes and chives for whiskers, and you
turn a basic dip into perfect party fun.
</P>
<P>
   13. Seedy sensation
</P>
<P>
   After you've carved the pumpkin, rescue the seeds. Wash and then
toss in a bowl with 2 tablespoons soy sauce, 1 tablespoon vegetable
oil,
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar and a pinch of cayenne pepper. Preheat
the oven to 350 degrees. Spread the seeds out on a nonstick baking
sheet and bake for about 12 minutes, checking once or twice and
stirring them around on the pan when they get bubbly. Let cool
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
