<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP28-COX     10-27 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Raisin bread good choice for gift-giving
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Helen O. White of Winston (Ga.) came through with a
great recipe for quick Applesauce Raisin Bread, as requested by
Frances Fowler of Cumming (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   If you use regular raisins in this bread, soak in 1/4 cup of any
fruit juice _ we tested it with orange juice and liked the
additional flavor. If you use the newer moist baking raisins
available in many supermarkets, just reduce the amount of fruit
juice to 2 tablespoons.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said that before she lost her recipe, she liked to bake
several loaves of this fragrant bread for gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Applesauce
</P>
<P>
   Raisin Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 loaf, about 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fruit juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground
</P>
<P>
   cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup quick-cooking or
</P>
<P>
   old-fashioned oats
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups applesauce
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour an 8 1/2-by-4 1/2-inch loaf pan (or 1-quart
casserole dish).
</P>
<P>
   In a small, shallow bowl, combine raisins and fruit juice and
let soak while mixing the batter.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium mixing bowl, whisk together the flour, baking
powder, baking soda, cinnamon, oats and brown sugar. Add
applesauce, oil, beaten eggs and milk; stir just until all dry
ingredients are moistened. Mix in raisins and their fruit juice.
Pour batter into prepared pan. Bake until golden brown and
toothpick inserted in center of loaf holds moist, but not sticky,
crumbs; about 50 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from pan immediately and cool on wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 236 calories, 4 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 27), 40 grams carbohydrates, 36 milligrams
cholesterol, 137 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   ``The recipe I'm looking for is a sweet-and-sour rice salad ...
(with) long grain white rice and chopped green onions and perhaps
raisins and a dash of cinnamon,'' says Susan Terry of Roswell
(Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lived near San Francisco, I used to eat this dish all
the time. But in Atlanta, I cannot find it on any menu, nor have I
found any Chinese chef that knows the recipe,'' says Sandi Boneta
(e-mail). ``It consists of chopped chicken and vegetables in a
tasty sauce _ it kind of reminds me of Mu Shu Pork. The best part
is the lettuce leaves. Using the largest leaves, put them in
boiling water for just a minute, then dip them in cold water. Put a
heaping amount of chicken and vegetables on a leaf and roll it up
like a burrito. It's wonderful!''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Whaley of Rome (Ga.) is wishing someone has the recipe for
Butter Fruit Cake like that one sold in the Sears catalog many
years ago. ``It had lots and lots of pecans, pineapple, raisins. It
was real good and moist,'' she remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
