 Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Undated) _ In the first square-off of their bid
for the Democratic presidential nomination, Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley are expected to labor assiduously
tonight to display dramatic differences between themselves. That
may be difficult to do. A news analysis. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TERRORIST-ASSETS (Washington) _ Sens. Frank R. Lautenberg of New
Jersey and Connie Mack of Florida introduce a bill that would allow
victims of terrorism to sue the foreign governments responsible for
it and to use that country's financial assests in the United States
to pay any monetary awards. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ Senate and House Democratic leaders
urge Congress to pass legislation that would strengthen the federal
government's ability to prosecute hate crimes and would add new
protections for those victimized because of their sexual
orientation, disability or gender. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Ironically, Rhode Island Sen.
John Chafee died just hours before Patrick Buchanan bade farewell
to the GOP with a verbal blast at the enlightened mainstream
Republicans that Chafee personified. No two Republicans could have
been further apart. Chafee understood that the world is round
rather than flat. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
