<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ The new government says it will
reopen the corruption investigation of Suharto, the former leader,
which was ended by the succeeding Habibe government with no charges
being brought. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ Falun Gong developments: Reuters quotes
members as saying 100,000 other members have slipped into Beijing
area from around the country and will stage protests.
</P>
<P>
   YEMEN-KIDNAP (Dateline to kum) _ Three Americans _ head of the
American Institute for Yemeni Studies and her parents _ are
kidnapped in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE (Hanover, N.H.) _ Al Gore and Bill Bradley share a
stage at their first forum together in New Hampshire. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-SOCSEC (Washington) _ Earl Pomeroy, an earnest North
Dakota Democrat, has been one of the party's strongest voices for
protecting Social Security. So he finds it particularly galling
that he is one of seven Democrats under attack in a Republican ad
campaign that accuses the Democrats in the House of raiding Social
Security. He complains that a year before the election, things are
already on a campaign footing. And that is just the point. After
years of being clobbered by Democrats in the annual budget fight,
Republicans are aggressively aiming at the next election, and seem
to battling the Democrats to a draw. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on appropriates
bills; the president speaks, etc. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Alarmed by an Oregon law that
allows doctors to help terminally ill patients end their lives, the
House is expected to pass legislation on Wednesday that will outlaw
the practice. There is Senate support for a similar measure, and
the White House has signaled it may support such a step as well. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-LABOR-RIGHTS (Undated) _ In a decision that expands the
rights of illegal immigrants, the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission has ruled that these immigrants have the right to be
reinstated to their jobs and collect back pay if their employers
fired them for discriminatory reasons of race, sex or age. The EEOC
said employers that knowingly hire illegal immigrants should not
then be free to discriminate against them or otherwise exploit
them. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-BAN (Urbana, Ill.) _ Folo on the federal appeals court
decision upholding Illinois and Wisconsin laws that criminalize a
late-term abortion procedure its opponents call ``partial birth.''
By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-MURDER (Denver) _ The governor of Colorado is expected to
announce that he will not appoint a special prosecutor in JonBenet
Ramsey murder case. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   MARILYN-AUCTION (New York) _ Marilyn Monroe's famous birthday
song dress, among other goodies, are to be auctioned. By James
Barron.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOOD-INSPECT (New York) _ Eight USDA inspectors are among 21
people arrested on charges of rigging the food inspection system at
the city's biggest wholesale food market, Hunt's Point. By Benjamin
Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
