A0007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-HOME-AUCTION-HNS &LR;      10-27 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-AUCTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLUENT FIND HOME AUCTIONS BEAT OPEN HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATTHEW YI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANTON, Calif. _ This might just be the cure for those who
want to sell their multimillion-dollar property without the
headache of waiting months or even years for the right buyer to
come along: auction it.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the heir to a dried-fruit packing house did Tuesday.
Mark Mariani, the chairman and chief executive officer of Mariani
Fruit Inc., auctioned his five-bedroom ranch home and the 252-acre
lot surrounding it for $3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The property, which sits just over the hills from the tony
Contra Costa County community of Blackhawk, also includes a guest
home, swimming pool and a private chapel with stain-glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   Each prospective bidder was required to bring a $100,000
cashier's check to the auction and agree in writing to close the
deal within 30 days of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this would be a unique way of merchandising
property,'' Mariani said. ``It's hassle free, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   The auction, held among 10 bidders and 40 observers sipping wine
on the west-side veranda of the main house, began with the
auctioneer rattling off dollar figures in the millions.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 30 minutes later, the property went to the highest
bidder, Julie Wallunas of Diablo. Including the fees to the auction
company, Wallunas' total bid was $3.44 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad I got it at the price that we got it for,''
Wallunas said as she was whisked away to a small bedroom to make
the initial $344,000 payment.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, she will have to pay the remainder of
the purchase price within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Mariani said he also was satisfied with the price and was happy
that the property had been sold promptly.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of property at an auction is nothing new to Mariani.
</P>
<P>
   He recently bought a ranch home on a 600-acre lot in Shasta
County at an auction organized by the same company that
orchestrated Tuesday's auction, National Auction Group Inc. from
Gadsden, Ala. Mariani paid $1.9 million for that property.
</P>
<P>
   While some may feel uneasy about putting their high-priced
property up for auction, some real estate agents say the practice
is a growing trend among large estate owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a novel idea,'' said Vicky Campbell, of Alain
Pinel Realtors in Danville, who also attended the auction. ``It's
not easy selling properties like this. ... It's expensive, and it's
a long process.''
</P>
<P>
   Foremost, it's difficult finding buyers who can afford such
high-priced properties, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she has a 122-acre ranch home east of Fremont that
has been on the market for more than four years.
</P>
<P>
   And when the property doesn't sell right away, the owner's costs
can mount, mostly from advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, National Auction spent about two months advertising
through mailers and newspapers. The last two to three weeks were
spent showing the property to prospective bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The auction itself took less than 30 minutes, and that included
a five-minute break after three of the bidders asked for some time
to consult with their family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum started really quickly,'' said auction group
President William Bone, referring to the higher-than-expected first
bid of $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding rose to the $3 million mark in just a few minutes.
When the auction resumed after the brief break, about half of the
bidders didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   Bone said his decade-old business had been picking up in recent
years. Last year, his company held 50 real estate auctions and this
year, the number jumped to 75. Next year, 100 are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bone's clients include celebrities such as Kenny Rogers,
who is planning to sell his 360-acre property in Athens, Ga., on
Nov. 4. Two years ago, Bone auctioned off a 10,000-acre ranch owned
by former U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen for $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years, we've had to turn people back,'' Bone
said. ``Even today, I had some people ask me to come and see their
property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
