r e BC-FILM-CENTURY-REVIEW-L     10-27 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CENTURY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
'20s MEET '90s IN `MAN OF THE CENTURY'  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:   2 stars  
(Eds: for use Friday, Oct. 29 and thereafter. Fact box at bottom.) By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Man of the Century'' is one of those movies that just makes
you go, ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished enough feature directing debut from Adam
Abraham, this low-budget, black-and-white whatsit has such an
arcane premise, it definitely puts the conceit back into the
concept of conceit.
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick? The film's protagonist, a Runyon-esque 1920s
newspaper reporter (named, appropriately, Johnny Twennies), is
actually operating in '90s Manhattan. He says stuff like, ``Let's
fidget with the digit,'' writes on a manual typewriter and
chain-smokes like there's, well, no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny's girlfriend Samantha (Susan Egan, of Broadway's ``Beauty
and the Beast'') is an art gallery worker who wonders why, after a
month of dating, she hasn't gotten any action. It's those
old-fashioned values of his, of course, although a gay couple finds
him more than a little intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the non-story involves Johnny trying to crack a big
corruption story before he loses his job. In pursuit of this
objective, he inexplicably winds up in a fantasy sequence wearing a
sailor suit at some Chinatown nightclub. That's one of the film's
more egregious Why moments.
</P>
<P>
   Lesser Whys keep popping up as Johnny runs into people who seem
to be in the same time warp that he is. This plays havoc with the
movie's internal logic: If there is indeed a parallel world from 75
years ago existing side-by-side with the contemporary one, how come
everybody from our time who encounters Johnny acts like they've
never seen anyone like him before?
</P>
<P>
   Gibson Frazier does a nice job as the fast-talking newshound,
but that ``Oh you kid'' jive gets mighty irritating after five
minutes. At feature length, it evokes the same, unhappy feeling you
got listening to ``Whiteboys' '' pale rappers.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham fools around with images and icons from (mostly bad)
silent and early sound films, but he amuses himself much more than
he does us. Extra arcana is supplied by the appearance of Frank
Gorshin in bondage leather and Bobby Short as a washroom attendant.
</P>
<P>
   A formal experiment that might have worked better with a more
consistently applied rigor, ``Man of the Century'' should have been
given, somewhere along the production line, the old '23 skidoo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
___ &QL; 
The film: ``Man of the Century'' (R; language, mild violence). &QL; 
The stars: Gibson Frazier, Susan Egan, Anthony Rapp, Cara Buono. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Adam Abraham. Written and produced
by Gibson Frazier and Abraham. Released by Fine Line Features. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 18 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
