<SLUG> BC-MARC-ANDREESSEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN BEHIND NETSCAPE STARTS INTERNET SERVICE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENLO PARK, Calif. _ Netscape Communications co-founder Marc
Andreessen has launched a new company that is more mystery ship
than coming Internet juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone news conference Tuesday, Andreessen, who in 1993
helped germinate the seeds of the first commercial Web browsing
software, said LoudCloud Inc. would provide an array of Internet
services to electronic commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what those services will be, Andreessen said, will be
announced in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Andreessen, who recently left his post as chief technology
officer at America Online to become an AOL consultant, did say the
company will help both new and existing e-commerce companies avoid
creating technological infrastructures from scratch. America Online
acquired Netscape in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce companies ``are forced to reinvent the wheel over and
over again,'' the 28-year-old Internet executive said, forcing the
companies to invest in ``huge technical teams, hire lots of
people.'' The result, Andreessen said, is a ``huge distraction to
the management team.''
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to define exactly what LoudCloud would do to
help companies avoid these pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   LoudCloud press releases have heralded the Internet ``all star''
team that Andreessen has recruited. This crew includes chief
executive Ben Horowitz, veteran leader of several divisions at
Netscape and AOL, and Tim Howes, a co-inventor of an array of
Internet directory technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Andreessen insists LoudCloud will be a ``relatively
unique'' creature, it does seem to have come from the same phylum
as many other Internet companies, ranging from startups like
BigStep, which allows small businesses to create e-commerce Web
sites, to giants like Microsoft and IBM, which have been
aggressively pitching Internet companies to contract out their
technological needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
