<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0027 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-MUSIC-REVIEW-LAD     10-27 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUSIC-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREEP DESERVES STANDING OVATION FOR `MUSIC OF THE HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: For use Friday, Oct. 29 and thereafter. Fact box at bottom)  
Our rating:   3 stars  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An inspiring crowd-pleaser, ``Music of the Heart'' is based on
such a remarkable true story that it would take a complete hack to
mess it up. Fortunately, director Wes Craven makes good on his leap
from horror to the heartwarming, delivering a solid, if predictable
movie that will likely have audiences on their feet, a la ``Mr.
Holland's Opus.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's subject, violin teacher Roberta Guaspari, was
featured in the 1996 Oscar-nominated documentary, ``Small
Wonders.'' This time she is played by the formidable Meryl Streep,
which translates into a performance that's as close to real life as
any actor will come. Streep practiced violin four to six hours a
day and wound up playing the demanding instrument quite
convincingly throughout the movie. Forget all her film accents _
this is Streep's most impressive technical accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Guaspari was a military man's wife, moving with her Navy husband
from base to base. The film opens with the news that her husband is
leaving her and a grief-stricken Guaspari asking, ``What am I going
to do?'' Answers her practical mother (Cloris Leachman): ``Get a
job, any job.''
</P>
<P>
   The job Guaspari winds up taking is in East Harlem, where she
moves with her two young boys. She will be a (temporary) violin
teacher at an elementary school. She has little teaching experience
aside from schooling her own children, but she does possess one
important asset _ violins, 50 of them, in fact. Out of such small
origins, a thriving institution is built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music of the Heart'' shows the genius behind Guaspari's
method. Doubters scoff that inner-city kids don't have the
discipline to learn the violin, but Guaspari believes that kids
want to succeed and will respond if challenged. She demands
attention, requiring her students to do things her way. She's
tough, too _ a class blackboard reads ``Do you LIKE the sound
you're making?'' _ but the kids listen and learn, delighted that
someone believes in their capacity to master a new talent.
</P>
<P>
   The film also delves into Guaspari's home life with her children
and love life with various suitors, including a wandering
journalist played by Aidan Quinn. Angela Bassett is persuasive as
the school's beleaguered principal, and singer Gloria Estefan has a
small role as a teacher sympathetic to Guaspari's cause.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand in a climactic scene at Carnegie Hall: famed
violinists Itzhak Perlman and Isaac Stern, as well as some of
Guaspari's actual students, being led in Bach's Concerto in D Minor
for Two Violins by, yes, Streep herself.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has enough melodrama for three films, but Craven keeps
the manipulation to a minimum, aside from a couple of shots of a
cute puppy dog. His greatest resource is Streep, who invests a
believable humanity into a character that, in lesser hands, would
have been rendered some sort of saint. It's hard to believe Madonna
was slated to play Guaspari. That, indeed, would have been a
scream, and not the kind that Craven appreciates. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
___ &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``Music of the Heart'' (PG; brief mild language and
sensuality). &QL; 
The stars: Meryl Streep, Aidan Quinn, Gloria Estefan, Angela
Bassett, Cloris Leachman. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Wes Craven. Screenplay by Pamela
Gray. Released by Miramax Films. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, three minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-WILLS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     10-27 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-WILLS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 EVANSTON, Ill: ...William F. Buckley Jr.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wills spent six years as a Jesuit seminarian in the '50s and
remains an observant Catholic. The best way to understand his
politics, perhaps, is through his religion. ``It's important to
everything,'' he says of the church's influence on him. Figures
like Chesterton, St. Augustine, and Dorothy Day (the socially
radical and doctrinally conservative founder of the Catholic Worker
movement) have done more to shape Wills's politics than any elected
official or political theorist has.
</P>
<P>
   If Wills belongs to any school of thought, it's communitarianism
(he emphasizes the lower-case c, to distinguish his views from
those propounded by such upper-case Communitarians as the
contemporary liberal thinkers Amitai Etzioni and William Galston).
For Wills, an emphasis on the individual rather than on the
community endangers the spirit of both that individual and the
society she or he belongs to.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my papal sin book,'' Wills says, ``I've read several works
by Edith Stein (the Jewish-born Catholic nun who died at Auschwitz
and was canonized by John Paul II in 1998). Reading her, I
realized, yeah, this is what I've thought for a long time. She says
that our own self is born out of empathy with other selves. If it
weren't for that, we wouldn't have a self. That's a very strong and
important idea. It's in Augustine also. For me, I think the self's
interplay with other selves is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Wills was born in Atlanta. His father was a salesman, and the
family soon moved to the Midwest. Wills grew up in several towns in
Wisconsin and Michigan. Initially, he attended parochial schools.
``When my father went in the Army,'' he recalls, ``we moved to
Albion, Mich., where there was no Catholic school. I was way ahead
in the school there because the nuns had been so good. I had a very
good teacher there, Miss Beifuss _ she died about 10 years ago _
and she said, `Well, you're ahead, so don't waste your time here,
go to the school library and read.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was a lesson that has stood Wills in good stead. As he showed
during his Esquire days, he's no slouch at on-the-scene reporting.
What's most characteristic of his work, however, is Wills's
scrupulous attention to texts and thoroughness of research. ``I
spend a lot of time in libraries,'' Wills concedes. A book like
``Lincoln at Gettysburg'' or ``Inventing America'' (1978) is, in
effect, an extended exercise in close reading (of the Gettysburg
Address and the Declaration of Independence, respectively).
Conversely, Wills recalls his surprise at discovering that no one
before him had troubled to look up Newt Gingrich's doctoral
dissertation or Hillary Rodham Clinton's law review articles when
each came to national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Wills attended a Jesuit high school and, impressed by his
teachers, decided to enter the seminary. ``For five years I was
completely cut off, no radio, TV, or newspapers,'' he recalls. ``It
seemed natural for a while, but I guess I missed (the outside
world) toward the end.''
</P>
<P>
   That cloistering helped make him a journalist. Sent for the
summer to a facility that did allow students access to secular
writing, Wills came across a stack of old Time magazines and went
through them in two days. The ``sleazy righteousness'' of Time
style so offended him he eventually wrote a critique that he sent
to National Review (one of the few magazines he was familiar with,
thanks to its staunch anticommunism).
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Buckley himself telephoned Wills to accept
the piece and urge him to come to New York. Wills, who had recently
left the seminary (``It was eros specifically and generally,'' he
once told an interviewer), immediately agreed. Thus was a career
born. ``I didn't plan it this way,'' Wills says with a smile.
``It's largely (been) accident, but I'm happy with the accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what the former seminarian who spent the summer of
1957 serving as culture editor at America's foremost conservative
publication would make of ``A Necessary Evil,'' a stoutly liberal
defense of the value of government. Wills began the book in 1994 at
the height of the term-limits movement. Those days now seem as
distant as Gingrich's speakership, but Wills isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superficially things have changed, but I don't think they have
deeply. The antigovernmental feeling runs through so much of our
lives. . . . That's why America is the only major industrialized
nation without any health care. All that people have to say is
`Socialized medicine: The government's coming, the government's
coming!' Or campaign finance reform . . . as if it would be
depotism for the government to say you can't give more than x
amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what will follow the papal sin book. ``There are
things I would have liked to write long ago,'' Wills says, ``but
there hasn't been an editor interested enough so that he or she
would give me a good enough advance!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ideas to last two lifetimes
</P>
<P>
   Prospective book topics include James Wilson, the unsung hero of
the Constitutional Convention; the Supreme Court; the historian
Henry Adams; Verdi's Shakespeare operas; the fusing of religion and
violence in the films of Oliver Stone, Martin Scorsese, and Paul
Schrader; and a mystery novel (it would be Wills's second _ his
first, ``At Button's,'' appeared in 1979). ``I'll never write half
the books I've thought about doing,'' he laments.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than mourning volumes unwritten, the rest of us are
likelier to marvel that someone so myriad-minded has managed to
write as many books as Wills has.
</P>
<P>
   Writing once about Dorothy Day, Wills posed this question:
``What would a job applicant trying to fill her shoes choose as his
or her title?'' His answer, when asked that question, comes softly
but with hardly any hesitation: ``student.'' And that student's
curriculum would consist of? ``Oh, all kinds of things,'' Wills
says. ``That's why I insist on `student.' I can't imagine limiting
myself to one thing. Everything leads to everything else. Their
interaction is what's so fascinating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0040 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS28-TAKE     10-27 2042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS28-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that the battleship New Jersey is being towed
from Washington state, where it has been in mothballs for years, to
the Philadelphia Navy Yard. Do you have any information about this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The towing of the New Jersey from Puget Sound Naval Inactive
Ships Facility at Bremerton, Wash., began Sept. 12. ``Big J,''
pulled by the tug Sea Victory, entered the Panama Canal's western
end Oct. 16, and exited four days later on the eastern end. Arrival
at the Naval Inactive Ships Facility in Philadelphia is expected on
or about Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The battleship, the most-decorated in U.S. Navy history, is
destined to become a floating museum and memorial in the state for
which it is named, assuming the Navy releases the ship to the
Battleship New Jersey Commission. The most likely site is the
soon-to-be-former Military Ocean Terminal in Bayonne. Jersey City
and Camden also were contenders for the permanent site.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the battleship's official status is ``category
X'' on the Naval Vessels Register, meaning ``Stricken, on donation
hold as a museum or memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about the New Jersey can be found online at the
Battleship New Jersey Historical Museum Society's Web site:
www.quuxuum.org/bnj/
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Jim Gray interview with Pete Rose after the All-Century
Team festivities prior to Game 2 of the World Series was a low
blow. Many of us are outraged. How can we contact Gray and NBC to
let them know how inappropriate we think it was?
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Gray and/or NBC Sports at this address: NBC, 30
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10112. Or call 212-664-4444 (main
switchboard) or 212-664-2333 (audience line).
</P>
<P>
   Q: It has been reported several times lately that the South Pole
is the coldest place on Earth. In World War II, when I was
preparing for the North African desert, I was stationed at Camp
Young, in California's Mojave Desert. We were told that it was the
hottest place in North America. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: It does get hot in the Mojave, but Greenland Ranch, in
California, holds the record for the highest temperature ever
officially recorded in the United States: 134 degrees F. It
occurred on July 10, 1913. This station is in the below-sea-level
Death Valley, to the north of the Mojave.
</P>
<P>
   As steamy as it was at Greenland Ranch back in 1913, it wasn't
quite as hot as the high temperature of 136 degrees F reached on
Sept. 13, 1922, at Azizia, Tripolitania, in Libya. According to The
Weather Almanac, that temperature is generally accepted as the
world's highest recorded under standard conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a boy, I remember my father telling me what an injustice
was done to those of Japanese heritage living in the United States
or serving with U.S. forces during World War II. Now I see that
ground has been broken for a Japanese American Memorial in
Washington. How can I make a donation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Donations are welcomed for the memorial, to be built on
government-donated land in the shadow of the Capitol. Send your
check to: National Japanese American Memorial Foundation, 1920 N
St. NW, Washington, DC 20036. Make your check out to the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My question concerns the F-117 Stealth shot down over Serbia
earlier this year. Conspicuously absent from the news reports was
any mention of what became of the wreckage. Was it recovered or
destroyed by U.S. forces, or did it fall into the hands of the
Serbs?
</P>
<P>
   A: The latter. Articles at the time did report it, and TV
footage and still photos showed Serbs examining large pieces of the
wreckage after the F-117 Nighthawk fighter-bomber was downed March
27.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon briefing April 20, U.S. military authorities were
asked if there was any concern about Yugoslavia sending parts of
the aircraft to Russia for analysis of America's ``low observable''
(commonly termed ``stealth'') technology. Air Force Maj. Gen. Bruce
Carlson responded that this particular aircraft employed
long-outmoded technologies, and what little could be discerned from
the pieces wouldn't be significant.
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically why U.S. pilots didn't bomb the Nighthawk's
wreckage to prevent its study by enemies, Carlson explained that
the plane crashed in a remote location, and he wasn't sure that the
commander in the field felt it was worth the risk ``to try and go
in there and bomb it.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that Social Security pays $250 in death benefits?
How does one apply?
</P>
<P>
   A: The amount actually is $255. It's a one-time payment made
when a person dies if that person has enough work credits, said
Patti Patterson of the Social Security Administration. The payment
can be made only to that person's spouse or minor children if they
meet certain requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Information on the requirements, and about procedures for
applying for the benefit, can be obtained from any local Social
Security office or by calling 1-800-772-1213.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article indicated that the Oct. 19 telecast of the
11-inning Braves-Mets baseball game had a national Nielsen rating
of 15.4, highest for a League Championship Series since the
Braves-Phillies drew a 17.4 rating in 1993. Can you list the 10
programs with the highest Nielsen ratings ever, whether they were
sports or not?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nielsen Media Research lists these: ``MASH Special,'' CBS,
Feb. 28, 1983, 60.2; ``Dallas,'' CBS, Nov. 21, 1980, 53.3;
``Roots,'' part VIII, ABC, Jan. 30, 1977, 51.1; Super Bowl XVI,
CBS, Jan. 24, 1982, 49.1; Super Bowl XVII, NBC, Jan. 30, 1983,
48.6; XVII Winter Olympics, CBS, Feb. 23, 1994, 48.5; Super Bowl
XX, NBC, Jan. 26, 1986, 48.3; ``Gone With the Wind,'' Part 1, NBC,
Nov. 7, 1976, 47.7; ``Gone With the Wind,'' Part 2, NBC, Nov. 8,
1976, 47.4; and Super Bowl XII, CBS, Jan. 15, 1978, 47.2.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently heard about a recall of Hotpoint dishwashers. Do
you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: GE Appliances is recalling about 3.1 million GE and Hotpoint
brand dishwashers of certain models manufactured between April 1983
and January 1989. They have a slide switch that allows consumers to
choose between heat drying and energy saver functions. Over time,
the slide switch can melt and ignite, posing a fire hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The recalled machines are model GSD500D, GSD500G, GSD540,
HDA467, HDA477 or HDA487 with a serial number that has a second
letter of A, M, R, S, T, V or Z (for example, BM12345). The model
and serial numbers are on a rectangular label on either the right
or left front edge of the inner tub.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are advised to stop using the recalled dishwashers
immediately, and to keep the dishwasher door unlatched to prevent
the flow of electric current from the latch to the slide switch.
</P>
<P>
   GE is offering consumers a rebate toward the purchase of a new
dishwasher. Call 1-800-599-2929 or check online at
www.geappliancerecall.com for information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I obtain an Atlanta Braves-New York Yankees World
Series program? I don't live anywhere near either city and can't
attend the games.
</P>
<P>
   A: World Series programs and other official merchandise can be
obtained from the Atlanta Braves Clubhouse Catalog (1-800-433-2728)
and from Major League Baseball (1-800-694-9444). Programs cost $10
from either source, plus fees for tax, postage and handling. Orders
for programs and other playoff and World Series merchandise also
can be placed online with Major League Baseball's store,
shopmlb.sportsline.com/sportsstore/
</P>
<P>
   Another officially licensed source is OfficialStuff.com, which
also sells programs for such events as the Super Bowl, Stanley Cup
finals, NBA finals and Olympics. Information: 1-888-677-8833 or
online at www.OfficialStuff.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the widows of Gen. Douglas MacArthur and Chiang Kai-shek
still living? Where? Ages?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both are still living, but neither one makes public
appearances. Madame Chaing Kai-shek, who observed her 101st
birthday earlier this year, is said to be in a wheelchair most of
her waking hours at her duplex apartment near New York's Gracie
Square. On the occasion of her birthday in May, the New York Post
reported that she's attended to around the clock by three nurses,
along with several personal attaches and plainclothes guards. The
Post quoted a recent visitor as saying Chiang was less talkative
than she had been the year before, when she questioned him about
Taiwanese politics and joked about tea and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Jean MacArthur, meanwhile, observed her 100th birthday last Dec.
28. She also lives quietly in New York, in the Waldorf-Astoria
Hotel. As Q&AMP;A reported earlier this year, she has shunned the
limelight for years, never appearing on talk shows and rarely
turning up in celebrity columns. Col. Bill Davis of the MacArthur
Library Archives and Memorial in Norfolk, Va., described her as
being in good health. But other than that, he chose not to describe
her activities, saying only that she is ``very much a private
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I grew up in the Midwest, where hockey was common. I always
thought the ice had to be 3 or 4 inches thick, but I heard on the
radio that it's only a half-inch thick at the new Philips Arena in
Atlanta. Can you check on this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Philips ice is one inch thick. It's built up in three
steps, and is kept at 14 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper article described an exhibit in Charlotte,
N.C., of art glass created by Dale Chihuly of Seattle. If this is a
traveling exhibit?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is a traveling exhibit. A number of exhibitions of the
glass artisan's works are planned in various locations for the
remainder of this year, and next year, however. So if you're in
Tacoma, Wash., between now and Jan. 9, for example, you can view
some at the Washington State Historical Society. Now through Nov.
7, a group exhibition including Chihuly works will be shown at the
Oklahoma City Art Museum. Another group show is at Gibbes Museum of
Art in Charleston, S.C., until Dec. 19. The Indianapolis Museum of
Art's Columbus Gallery in Columbus, Ind., is showing works until
Jan. 2. And the Habatat Gallery in Boca Raton, Fla., has a Chihuly
exhibition going on into the year 2000 (end date not yet known).
</P>
<P>
   Next year's schedule includes a group show at the Mobile (Ala.)
Museum of Art, Jan. 14-March 15; and installations at the Knoxville
(Tenn.) Museum of Art, July 1-Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Chihuly Studio in Seattle is closed to the public, but you
can get information by calling 206-781-8707 or online at
www.chihuly.com/ Q: In all the news reports about the physician who
was airlifted from the South Pole, I haven't seen any mention of
the nature of the research being done there. What are the
scientists up to?
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. Antarctic Program is undertaking nearly 150 research
projects at the three U.S. stations (McMurdo, Amundsen-Scott South
Pole, and Palmer), aboard its two research ships (Laurance M. Gould
and Nathaniel B. Palmer) in the Ross Sea, at remote field camps,
and in cooperation with the national Antarctic programs of other
Antarctic Treaty nations. General research subjects include
astronomy and astrophysics, biology and medicine, geology and
geophysics, glaciology, ocean and climate studies, and
environmental research. Human research focuses on the effect of
isolated and confined environments on human physiology and social
interactions.
</P>
<P>
   NASA also conducts missions in Antarctica, including
microbiology in the Dry Valleys, diving in McMurdo Sound and the
Dry Valley lakes, weather and ozone studies, and
communications/satellite projects aimed at improving telephone, TV
and other data services.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the research is available online at the
National Science Foundation's Web site, www.nsf.gov (click on Polar
Research), or call 703-306-1070. Issues of the Antarctic Journal of
the United States with reports by investigators about recent
research projects can be viewed online at
www.nsf.gov/od/opp/antarct/journal
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
