<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS28-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Like most Braves fans, I thought I hated Mets manager Bobby
Valentine and all the players. But they truly gained my respect and
admiration for the outstanding series they played. How can we write
to say we appreciate their worthy efforts, and we feel for the way
they lost?
</P>
<P>
   A: What a gracious gesture. The address: New York Mets, Shea
Stadium, Flushing, NY 11368.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best advice about giving out one's Social Security
number?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Social Security Administration spells out its
recommendations in Publication No. 05-10002 (viewable online at
www.ssa.gov/pubs/10002.html). It says the agency can't prevent
others from asking for your number, but notes that having the
number doesn't give anyone access to your Social Security records
(they're private unless disclosure to another government agency is
required by law).
</P>
<P>
   The publication adds the obvious, that if a business requests
your number and you refuse to provide it, you may have to do
without the purchase or service for which your number was
requested.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion: ``Our primary message is this: Be careful with
your Social Security number and your card, and protect their
privacy whenever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read an article several months ago about the health
benefits derived from eating blueberries. What is in blueberries
that gets the credit? Is this ingredient available in pill form?
</P>
<P>
   A: Blueberries contain phenolic acids, compounds that help
suppress lung, skin and liver cancer cells in laboratory animals,
said Chris Rosenbloom, a professor at Georgia State University's
department of nutrition and a spokesperson for the American
Dietetic Association. They also contain plant chemicals, fiber and
vitamins considered valuable in fighting disease.
</P>
<P>
   While the helpful compounds can't be distilled out and made into
pill form, Rosenbloom said you'd be doing yourself a favor by
eating a variety of fruits and vegetables _ blueberries included _
for their health-giving properties. ``Don't think about finding
something in pill form,'' she advised. ``Instead, increase your
consumption of fruits and vegetables for the biggest health
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell us Joe Torre's complete managerial history?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's the scoop: 1977-81, New York Mets (player-manager May
31-June 17, 1977); 1982-84, Atlanta Braves; Aug. 1, 1990-June 16,
1995, St. Louis Cardinals; 1996-present, New York Yankees. From
1985 through July 31, 1990, Torre was a TV broadcaster for the
California Angels. He also managed the 1997 American League
All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting: Torre is the fourth manager to wear both Yankees
and Mets uniforms, joining Yogi Berra, Dallas Green and Casey
Stengel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that Andrew Young had been diagnosed
with prostate cancer, and would undergo surgery in December. Why
wait?
</P>
<P>
   A: The main reason the 67-year-old former ambassador and his
physicians agreed on the delay is because the problem was detected
early, said Lee Echols, Young's spokesman. That detection gave him
more options than if it had been detected later. The mid-December
date also enables Young to complete some obligations, such as
scheduled appearances, and it gives him the holiday season to begin
his recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   Echols reiterated Young's previous statement that he had gone
public with the news about his prostate cancer in part to encourage
middle-age and older men to get checks for prostate problems. ``So
he is quickly becoming another kind of ambassador,'' Echols said,
``this time an ambassador for prostate screening.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How and when can fans get tickets to the baseball All-Star
Game in Atlanta next year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Be patient. The only way you can be assured of a ticket is by
purchasing season tickets to next season's Braves games. And
information about season tickets for 2000 won't be available before
December. The number to call in December: 404-577-9100. At this
point, all the Braves are saying about individual tickets to the
All-Star Game is that information will be released ``at a later
date.'' The game will be played July 11 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about the recent earthquake in Southern California
said it registered magnitude 7.0 and was ``three times stronger
than the 6.7 Northridge quake,'' referring to a 1994 earthquake
also in California. How could magnitude 7.0 be three times 6.7?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Richter scale uses a logarithmic basis. In the scale,
magnitude is expressed in whole numbers and decimal fractions. As
the U.S. Geological Survey explains, because of the logarithmic
basis, each whole number increase in magnitude represents a tenfold
increase in measured amplitude (ground motion 10 times greater than
that represented by the next lower number). As an estimate of
energy, each whole number in the magnitude scale corresponds to the
release of about 30-31 times more energy than the amount associated
with the preceding whole number value.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, in an earthquake of magnitude 7, the ground moves
10 times as much as it moves in a quake of magnitude 6. And an
earthquake of magnitude 7 releases about 30-31 times the energy
released by a quake of magnitude 6.
</P>
<P>
   For more information online, visit the Geological Survey site: 
http://gldss7.cr.usgs.gov/neis/general/handouts/magnitudeintensity.h
tml
</P>
<P>
   Q: When Dr. Jerri Nielsen was airlifted from the South Pole, she
was replaced by another physician. I haven't seen that doctor's
name in the media. Is his or her identity being kept secret?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dr. Robert Thompson of Harrisburg, Pa., took Nielsen's place.
His identity wasn't intended to be a secret, and in fact he has
been granting interviews to the media, said Mary Hanson of the
National Science Foundation, which operates the U.S. research
stations in Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Articles about Dr. Jerri Nielsen, who was rescued from the
South Pole recently so she could be treated for breast cancer,
called it the coldest place on Earth. I'm confused about this.
Isn't the North Pole just as cold?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The reason, as explained by Von Woods of the National
Weather Service, is elevation. The South Pole research station is
on a hard, rocky plateau, at an elevation of 9,000-plus feet, while
the North Pole is just above sea level. Just like anywhere else,
the recorded temperatures are lower at the higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
   Several stations at Antarctica have been recording temperatures
since 1957. A world record low, 128.6 degrees below zero
Fahrenheit, was recorded at Vostok (Russian station) on July 21,
1983. At America's Amundsen-Scott station, on a snow plain within a
few hundred yards of the geographical south pole, the average
annual temperature from 1957 through 1964 was 59 degrees below zero
F.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, that makes the coldest temperature ever recorded
in the United States _ 79.8 degrees below zero F, on Jan. 23, 1971,
at Prospect Creek Camp in Alaska's Endicott Mountains _ seem almost
mild.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've followed Tom Brokaw's career with interest over the
years, and have just finished reading his book, ``The Greatest
Generation.'' How can I write to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: The address: Tom Brokaw, c/o NBC News, 30 Rockefeller Plaza,
New York, NY 10112-0002.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ABC's ``World News Tonight'' recently did a segment about
baseball and mentioned that the first baseball commissioner was
Kennesaw Mountain Landis. Can you give me any information about
him? There must be some connection to Kennesaw Mountain in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   A: There is indeed a connection, but the commissioner's name was
spelled Kenesaw, not Kennesaw. There's an explanation for this;
read on. But first, some general information about the man.
</P>
<P>
   Landis became baseball's first commissioner _ and absolute ruler
of the sport _ when he took office in January 1921, after the
Chicago White Sox scandal in which members of the team threw the
1919 World Series to the Cincinnati Reds. His mandate was to deal
as he saw fit with anything deemed detrimental to baseball. His
decisions, and penalties, were to be binding, with no recourse to
the courts. The eight ``Black Sox,'' as they soon were dubbed, were
the first to feel Landis' wrath when they were expelled from
baseball for life.
</P>
<P>
   And about the spelling of the name: Previously a U.S. district
judge, Landis was given his unusual moniker by his father, Abraham
Landis, a Union soldier in the Civil War who was wounded at the
Battle of Kennesaw Mountain in Georgia. Apparently his father's
recollection of the spelling of Kennesaw was faulty, hence the
single ``n.''
</P>
<P>
   Landis was born on Nov. 20, 1866, in Millville, Ohio. He died on
Nov. 25, 1944, in Chicago. He was elected in 1944 to baseball's
Hall of Fame by the Committee on Baseball Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The PBS television program ``The NewsHour'' has two new
reporters, Gwen Ifill and Ray Suarez. Did they replace anyone, or
are they just new members of the show's staff?
</P>
<P>
   A: There have been several changes in the recent past, said Sara
Hope Franks, spokeswoman for ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer,''
which is entering its 25th year on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Ifill (formerly of NBC) and Suarez (formerly of National Public
Radio's ``Talk of the Nation'') joined veteran journalists
Elizabeth Farnsworth and Margaret Warner as the program's senior
correspondents on Oct. 4. Phil Ponce left ``The NewsHour'' in July
to become anchor of WTTG's ``Chicago Tonight,'' where he had served
as correspondent and subanchor prior to ``The NewsHour,'' Franks
added.
</P>
<P>
   The senior correspondents share the same duties: conducting
newsmaker interviews and studio discussions, reporting from the
field, and serving as backup anchor to Lehrer, the award-winning
program's executive editor and anchor.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
