<HEADLINE>
WILLS CONTINUES TO FASHION REMARKABLE LIBRARY OF THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ ``I'm interested in a lot of things,'' Garry
Wills says, demonstrating that not the least of his many talents is
a keen grasp of the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, few authors, living or dead, have tackled such a
variety of subjects or so excelled at cross-fertilization on the
page.
</P>
<P>
   Wills is best known for his writing on politics and history.
``Lincoln at Gettysburg'' (1992) won both a Pulitzer Prize and a
National Book Critics Circle Award. ``Nixon Agonistes'' (1970)
earned him a place on the White House enemies list. ``Reagan's
America'' (1987) is ``still, by far, the best thing that anyone has
written about Reagan,'' says Columbia University historian Alan
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   Wills's latest book, ``A Necessary Evil,'' examines Americans'
distrust of government. Yet Wills's reach extends far beyond
presidents and policies. Earlier this year, he published a
biography of St. Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he came out with ``John Wayne's America,'' and
three years before that books on Shakespeare's ``Macbeth''
(``Witches and Jesuits'') and the nature of leadership (``Certain
Trumpets''). He's published 22 books in all and is working on one
about papal sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dante said the papal sin was greed and money,'' Wills notes.
``(Lord) Acton said it was power. I don't think there's much of
that around anymore (in the Vatican), but deception, dishonesty,
structures of deceit are pervasive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wise, and youthful
</P>
<P>
   Wills has been writing professionally since 1957. Even so, it's
startling to realize he's 65. From the outset, he seemed wise
beyond his years. In author photos, he had the slightly wide-eyed,
slightly pugnacious look of the smartest kid in class. Now, though
there's a little gray evident in his reddish-brown hair, he seems
youthful beyond his wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1959, Wills has been married to the former Natalie
Cavallo, a photographer. They have three children: John, a computer
programmer; Garry Jr., a film technician; and Lydia, a literary
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Wills has a blocky build and squarish face and wears boxy
spectacles. They combine to give a sense of bulk in abstraction.
Briskly low key, he speaks formally, in a mellifluous voice. The
precisely enunciated legato of his speech suggests there is an
answer to any question Wills might be asked _ and that he is in
possession of it. Chances are, he is. If there's any one problem
with Wills's work, it's his faintly know-it-all tone. Perhaps,
though, that can be excused as truth in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an intellectual of a type that there really aren't very
many anymore,'' says Brinkley. ``I'm not sure there ever were very
many _ a person who's able to think intelligently and synthetically
about a huge range of subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore Vidal would say, `He's comparable to me,' '' suggests
Richard Brookhiser, a senior editor at National Review, where Wills
got his journalistic start, and the author of books on George
Washington and Alexander Hamilton, ``but it would be insulting to
Garry to make that comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all,'' adds Robert Silvers, editor of The New York
Review of Books, ``he's a man of such exceptionally wide and also
deeply thought-through interests that I think there's no one like
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Wills's uniqueness lies in his ability to straddle
scholarship and journalism. He has a PhD in classics from Yale and
taught the subject for several years at Johns Hopkins. Since 1980,
he has taught American history at Northwestern University here in
Evanston. He is a member of the American Academy of Arts and
Letters and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even before he got to Yale, Wills was a regular contributor
to National Review (so regular that he had to publish some reviews
under a pseudonym, ``William Roman,'' to keep his byline from
dominating the book pages). While at Hopkins, he was an integral
part of the New Journalism high-wire act that was Esquire under
Harold Hayes. Wills has long been a frequent contributor to such
publications as The New York Times Magazine and The New York Review
of Books, and since 1970, he's written a twice-weekly syndicated
column on politics. ``If you write for four hours every morning, it
just piles up,'' he says with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   As much as versatility and vocational ambidexterity, ideological
volatility has distinguished Wills's career. In his first book, on
the English Catholic man of letters G. K. Chesterton, he wrote that
``conservative'' and ``liberal'' are ``the most misleading terms in
the modern world.'' Wills has spent much of the past three decades
proving that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Though he started out at National Review, a publication
considered even more conservative then than now, he was later
arrested twice for demonstrating against the Vietnam War. Asked to
discuss Wills's political views, NR's Brookhiser demurs,
diplomatically noting that to do so would simply be to list ``a
catalog of disagreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Though others would place him firmly in the liberal camp, Wills
hesitates to do so. Indeed, he kept calling himself a conservative
well into the '80s. And a book like ``The Kennedy Imprisonment''
(1982), with its scathing indictment of the mythology of Camelot,
demonstrates a freedom from liberal cant worthy of someone whose
first editor was William F. Buckley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; BC-AUTHOR-WILLS-2ND &LR;   &UR; TAKE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EVANSTON, Ill: ...William F. Buckley Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
