<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0046 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV3     10-27 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV31-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAFEE AND BUCHANAN: A STRIKING CONTRAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 31)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) ,
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ironically, Rhode Island Sen. John Chafee died just
hours before conservative commentator Patrick Buchanan bade
farewell to the Republican Party with a verbal blast at the
enlightened mainstream Republicans that Chafee personified.
</P>
<P>
   No two Republicans could have been further apart in philosophy
and approach to government than Chafee, who was ending his fifth
term in the Senate, and Buchanan, who ended his fourth unsuccessful
bid for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee understood that the world is round rather than flat and
that humanity's future depends on the ability of nations to work
together for the greater good. Buchanan is basically a throwback to
19th century nationalism in which protectionism and isolationism
were the policies that guided an America separated from the
travails of Europe and Asia by two mighty oceans.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the revolutionary changes of the 20th century, Buchanan
continues to believe that the most powerful country on earth can,
in the age of mass communications, convert itself into a Fortress
America and abandon its neighbors on this ever-shrinking planet.
</P>
<P>
   His White House aspirations having been rejected by Republicans
in the 1988, 1992 and 1996 primaries and the preliminaries this
year. Buchanan now wants Reform Party stalwarts to give him the
prize that the GOP denied him.
</P>
<P>
   If he succeeds, he will have a campaign fund of $12.6 million,
provided by the federal government, and a probable seat at the
televised debate table with the Democratic and Republican nominees.
</P>
<P>
   When Buchanan claims that he severed ties with the GOP over
matters of principle and because party loyalty ``asks too much of
us,'' voters should note that he made his move when it became clear
that he could not raise the funds or get the votes to win the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Had he fared better against George W. Bush, John McCain and the
other presidential contenders in the early ratings, he undoubtedly
would have been content to remain loyal to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   So, it should be understood that his move toward the Reform
Party is not selfless. It is his one chance to join the
presidential race next year.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not assured the Reform Party nomination. Several
hurdles could separate him from that goal. Their names are Donald
Trump, Jesse Ventura and Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   John Chafee, a former Marine who fought at Guadalcanal and
Okinawa in World War II and later was recalled to duty in Korea,
was the antithesis of the explosive Buchanan. A three-term governor
of Rhode Island before he was elected to the Senate in 1976, he
worked quietly with his political opponents to achieve a compromise
on such issues as environmental protection and health care than
indulge in an explosion of political bombast.
</P>
<P>
   Where Buchanan cultivates the blue-collar vote by promising to
turn the clock back to the policies of the past that helped produce
the Great Depression and World War II, Chafee won the support of
labor by working diligently to win passage of Medicaid expansion
and clean air and water legislation that improved the lives of
working people and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of Chafee's death, his friend, Vermont Sen. James
Jeffords, another Republican moderate, explained why Chafee, from
the mid-'70s to the late '90s, was a respected and luminous
presence in the Senate. ``In a city that is known for its partisan
rancor, John was a champion of consensus and bipartisanship. I
don't know anyone that didn't respect John Chafee.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee served as governor of Rhode Island in the 1960s _ a time
that might be described as the ``golden age'' of moderate
Republican chief executives. Among the others were New York's
Nelson Rockefeller, Washington's Dan Evans, Oregon's Mark Hatfield
and Tom McCall, Pennsylvania's William Scranton, Michigan's George
Romney and Massachusetts' John Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   They were achievers who shunned the kind of wild rhetoric that
flows from Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, candor compels us to admit that our vaunted two-party
system is a snare and a delusion, a fraud upon the nation,''
Buchanan said in announcing his bolt to the Reform Party. ``Our two
parties have become nothing but two wings on the same bird of
prey.''
</P>
<P>
   After years in television, Buchanan is a master of mouthing
attention-getting sound bites. The two parties do on occasion
achieve bipartisanship, but more often they are at each other's
throats.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's diatribe, ignored the sharp differences between them
on abortion, gun control, campaign finance reform, tax cuts,
education, nuclear testing and allocation of the first federal
surplus in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   One has to wonder whether the supporters who cheered, applauded
and shouted, ``Go, Pat, go'' when Buchanan announced his party
switch agree with his outrageous contention that America's
participation in World War II was unnecessary because the brutal
aggressor Adolf Hitler posed no threat to us. It would be sad if
they agree with his anti-Jewish, anti-immigrant, anti-black,
anti-free trade philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   It is fascinating to find the news spotlight shining brightly
and simultaneously on two public figures, such as Chafee and
Buchanan, who differed so drastically in ideology and professional
conduct but who, for a time, claimed membership in the same
political party. That is a manifestation of democracy in action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
