<HEADER>
A0056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SEA-CUCUMBERS-BOS &LR;      10-27 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-CUCUMBERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAR EAST DELICACY CREATES A QUANDARY IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILBRIDGE, Maine _ Sea cucumbers are not easy to love. Bringing
the bulbous creatures up in their nets, generations of Down East
fishermen stomped on them and dumped them back into the sea. One
Maine man described their interior as resembling ``red vomit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Chinese, the largest population that dines on sea
cucumbers, deemed the New England variety strange and inferior.
Unmolested for millennia, Cucumaria frondosa colonized the bottom
of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last five years, as preferred varieties in the
Pacific became scarce, Mainers persuaded Far Eastern buyers to take
another look, and for struggling New England fishermen, a new
market appeared out of thin air. Now, in the villages of coastal
Maine, the saga of the sea cucumber is a familiar tale. Regulators
are seeing sea cucumbers take on the pattern of several ``trash
fish'' species that became sudden hits in Asia: a dizzying
opportunity followed closely by a precipitous depletion from
overfishing.
</P>
<P>
   The number of boats dragging for sea cucumbers has tripled in
the last year alone, harvesting as much as a million pounds a week,
officials said. The much-maligned relative of the starfish is now
the focus of such intense attention that the Department of Marine
Resources this week moved to cap the number of people who can enter
the fishery, preventing a bust, basically, by preventing a boom.
</P>
<P>
   The sea cucumber's Cinderella story reminds fishermen and
regulators alike of another story, one that ended badly. Around
1985, Japanese buyers found that Maine's sea urchins resembled
their own scarce species. Fishermen had been bringing in annual
catches of about 70,000 pounds from 1947 to 1987, according to the
Department of Marine Resources. Then, sped along by the advent of
the fax machine and overnight flights to the Far East, during an
eight-year gold rush, the catch increased to a 1993 rate of 42
million pounds. This stretch of coastline had entered a complex
global market; when the Asian markets faltered, such as when the
Japanese emperor died in 1989, prompting Japanese businessmen to
put aside favorite foods in mourning, Winter Harbor felt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have these urchin divers saying, `The emperor died, so
we're not going fishing,' '' said Pete Collin, a Sunset
entrepreneur who helped open markets for the sea urchin and the sea
cucumber. ``We realized if you put a pebble in the water, the
ripples extend.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials first imposed restrictions in 1992, but it was too
late, both for the sea urchin and for the communities of fishermen
who had come to count on the market. Even with the restrictions,
commercial samplings from the sea floor dropped every year from
1993 until 1998, according to Ted Creaser, a marine resource
scientist at the Department of Marine Resources. The catch dropped
to 38 million pounds in 1994 and 32 million pounds in 1995. Last
year's catch was 16 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to break that boom-and-bust cycle, Maine's Legislature
passed the Emerging Fisheries Act, which can severely limit access
to a new fishery, so that the next trash-fish-turned-delicacy,
whether it is periwinkles or starfish or seaweed, will never reach
those giddy heights or that sudden collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They catch us completely off guard,'' Creaser said of the
Asian markets. He added that the sea cucumber will not be the last
species to find its first market halfway across the world. ``I
don't think we can even project at this point what those markets
might be,'' he said. ``They might be these dog whelks we see along
the shore, for all I know. It's only a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to look hard to see the Asian connection in Milbridge,
a town with one movie theater that shows one movie once per night.
Stray tourists might enjoy the grand, turreted, white Victorian
houses overlooking stretches of silver water, but the picturesque
tableau ends abruptly inside Lawrence Ray's sea cucumber processing
plant, where two lines of 30 workers are scraping sea cucumber
innards. To the rushing of 60 hoses, crates full of glistening gray
sea cucumbers are reduced to their usable parts: a small ring of
pink muscle and a patch of dark skin.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the creature slops into huge vats of stinking waste;
150 pounds of raw material yield just 7 pounds of meat, according
to Ray's wife, Drusilla.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, a former scalloper, had been dragging up sea cucumbers by
accident for years, but it took years of lobbying by Collin to
convince him that Cucumaria frondosa could be regarded as food.
Collin recalls sending out 20 or 30 samples of sea cucumber meat to
dealers in the early 1990s and receiving one response.
</P>
<P>
   Until five years ago, he figured, he was the sea cucumber's only
predator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been my obsession for 10 or 12 years,'' said Collin,
whose company, Coastside Bio Research, markets nutritional
supplements made from sea cucumbers. ``I consider this my baby.''
</P>
<P>
   As Maine scrambles to control the Asian demand for sea
cucumbers, it is worth noting that the state helped create that
demand. Working with $3,500 in federal grant money, Collin said, he
and a few others ``singlehandedly introduced this species into the
Asian cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chamberlain, who was working in the research wing of
Maine's Fisheries Extension Program at the time, recalls Collin's
dogged efforts. ``Pete went through a lot of trials and
tribulations,'' he said. ``Nobody wanted to deal with anything that
ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Collin needed any proof of his success, he got it last
Wednesday when Commissioner George Lapointe moved to use the
Emerging Fisheries Act for the first time to curtail the growth of
the sea cucumber industry. Within three weeks, he will announce
temporary emergency regulations, Lapointe said, declining to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Creaser said he would recommend that no more than 10 boats be
allowed in the market. A slow-growing species, sea cucumbers are
not ready to harvest for at least five years, he said. ``Even (10
boats) might be too high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Poised to challenge those limits, with a lawsuit if necessary,
are fishermen and processers who planned to increase their trade in
sea cucumbers. Roger Kratz, a vice president at East Ocean Seafood
Co. in Los Angeles, which buys sea cucumbers, has proposed a fleet
of 50 boats. He argues that by imposing strict limits, the
Department of Marine Resources risks stifling healthy competition
in an industry's infancy. His Maine Sea Cucumber Processors'
Association protests that until the state has some data on the sea
cucumber population, its regulations are bound to be arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   What the department has not acknowledged is that the sea
cucumber population is truly vast, extending north to the Arctic,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible to make the last Cucumaria frondosa
disappear. If we sent attack subs down there to kill every sea
cucumber, they would fail in their mission,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, by limiting the business to fishermen who are
in it already, authorities will give an unfair advantage to the man
who has been in the business longest _ Lawrence Ray, who owns four
of the 12 boats dragging for sea cucumbers and one of the two East
Coast plants processing them. Already, one Portland, Maine,
entrepreneur has scrapped his plans to build a processing plant
because of anxiety over the new regulations and the threat of
monopoly, Kratz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is against restricting access per se,'' he said. ``It's
just that the group of fishermen shouldn't be so small that it can
be manipulated.''
</P>
<P>
   But regulators said they have seen too many fisheries fall flat
to stand by and watch it happen again.
</P>
<P>
   In Milbridge, many of the fishermen who cashed in on the urchin
boom are stuck with payments on the houses and vehicles they bought
during the glory days, said Christy Kennedy, 35, who works in The
Cinnamon Stick, a Milbridge gift shop. ``They really blew it. They
were making good money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Ray, whose father and grandfather fished for herring, and
who saw herring run out in his lifetime, stands at one end of a
line of workers, surrounded by crates and crates of sea cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead, leave it the way it is,'' he said. ``I would say in
three years, the industry will be over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
