<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-27 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAFEE'S DEATH LEAVES SENATE A LESS HONORABLE PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Senate, his Republican Party, and the political life that
John Chafee left behind upon his death Sunday at 77 were far
different from the Senate and party and politics he embraced in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   There is one fewer stand-up senator on the shrinking Washington
ice floe of civil and civic-minded politicians. In a season when
serious discussion of potential presidents mentions the likes of
Pat Buchanan, Donald Trump, Jesse Ventura, Ross Perot, and Warren
Beatty, the passing from the scene of an honorable gentleman of
probity and restraint is all the more keenly felt.
</P>
<P>
   John Chafee left Yale in 1942 for the Marine Corps and the
terrifying and perilous work of invading Guadalcanal and Okinawa.
In 1951 he left Harvard Law School for the risky task of leading
Marine riflemen in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   This week the class examines the likes of Bad-knee Pat Buchanan,
a Nixon speechwriter who begged off Vietnam but led the
grenade-tossing from the White House; a developer and casino
operator who flaunts his womanizing; a voluble governor who says
pro wrestling is on the level but politics isn't; a squirrelly
industrialist; and a Hollywood character of whom it might be said
that ``I'm-not-a-politician-but-I-play-one-in-the-movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does a John Chafee fit in that mix? Answer? He doesn't.
The times and the trade of politicking have passed him by,
mercifully. ``He was in government to do good,'' murmured his
sorrowful Republican colleague, former senator John Danforth of
Missouri. Chafee could claim paternity over the Clean Air Act and
other environmental protections. A champion of Medicaid and
Medicare, he sought to create middle ground in a Senate where the
center does not hold, where partisan rip tides kept eroding the
foundations Chafee and his ever-shrinking band of moderates tried
vainly to erect.
</P>
<P>
   There were heartfelt tributes from Narragansett Bay to the
Senate floor and the White House Tuesday. Some of the same
Republicans who voted to dump Chafee from the one leadership post
he held waxed eloquent at his sudden loss. For six years till 1990,
Chafee was number three in the Senate GOP leadership, but he was
too moderate for the party that was being yanked rightward by Sun
Belt right-wingers in an intramural putsch.
</P>
<P>
   Former senator Alan Simpson of Wyoming listed the number of GOP
moderates whose departure had shrunk Chafee's centrist coalition in
an interview with CNBC's Chris Mathews: Maine's Bill Cohen,
Missouri's John Danforth, New Hampshire's Warren Rudman, Kansas's
Nancy Kassebaum _ those were the moderates whose help Chafee
enlisted to ameliorate some of the harsher Republican efforts. He
might have added Oregon's Mark Hatfield and Colorado's Hank Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The old Rockefeller wing of the GOP has atrophied steadily,
displaced by Republicans who relish pushing issues like banning
late-stage abortions. In a measure of how this Senate, hobbled as
it is by partisanship, stumbles from the sublime to the ridiculous,
Simpson pointed to last week's vote on abortion as one of the kind
that causes good men and women to weep at the inanity and futility
of much of the Senate's work.
</P>
<P>
   If Chafee was such a legend in his own time to his own kind, how
come we didn't hear more of him? Two reasons. The first is
personal, the second systemic. As a rectitudinous Yankee of
aristocratic stripe, tooting his own horn made him sick. The real
aristocrats, including many of the old Protestant families whose
ancestors led the carving of America out of the wilderness
hereabouts, were not plaster saints, but neither were they crass
self-promoters. Like Claiborne Pell, his seatmate for decades,
Chafee was a classy guy in a business that has lost a lot of its
class.
</P>
<P>
   The systemic reason why Chafee was an MIA in the media melange
that passes today for political journalism? The bad news about
doing good works is that routinely doing the right thing tends to
be, well, boring.
</P>
<P>
   Crafting legislation requires minute staff work, lengthy
hearings, interminable wrangles with lobbyists and interested
parties, extended colloquy in public but also in private with your
colleagues, and the inevitable deal-cutting, ticket-balancing,
log-rolling, and vote-brokering it takes to yield a finished
legislative product. Done right, it's tedious; done boldly, it
requires tradeoffs that might make a nun blush; done for a living,
it requires great stamina; done honestly, it requires saying no to
temptation a dozen times a week.
</P>
<P>
   The inherent friction and conflict of the legislative life are
not just the fault of willful politicians. Ask yourself: What would
you be more likely to follow? The exhaustive explication of how a
senator from Rhode Island worried about striped bass or the details
of a prominent politician's sex life, money problems, domestic
difficulties, or past indiscretions?
</P>
<P>
   Standing squarely on the principles he adhered to over four
generations in politics, Chafee presented a stoic rebuke to the Sun
Belt commandos who have captured the Senate. He voted consistently
for choice, gun control, patients' rights and the nuclear test ban
treaty. The old Marine captain memorialized in Jim Brady's book
about Korea, ``The Coldest War,'' was a magnificent soldier whose
lot in life was to wage a rugged rear-guard action his last decade
in Washington. The Senate was a better place for his presence and
is the worse for his leaving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
