<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS A CIVICS LESSON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a specter hanging over American politics. The specter
of civic journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Civic journalism, or public journalism as it is sometimes
called, is a voguish new addition to the campaign scene.
</P>
<P>
   Cooked up by an unholy alliance of charitable foundations so
rich they have no idea how to spend their money, pseudo-academics,
public broadcasting crackpots, and some sackcloth-and-ashes former
journalist types, civic journalism purports to reform the way the
media cover candidates for electoral office.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the foundations bankroll vast swaths of
coverage of issues they think voters should care about, and wag a
scolding finger at old-fashioned election coverage, which focuses
on such ``horse-race'' issues as polls, or fund-raising success. In
this looking-glass world of perfect democracy, informed voters are
dying to attend lengthy debates on the future of Social Security,
and are indifferent to ``gotcha'' coverage of politicians'
character flaws. The ur-civic journalism creature, of course, is
Bill Clinton: articulate, perfectly briefed on all policy issues,
and a complete louse. Getting to the bottom of the Lewinsky scandal
is not the Pew Charitable Trusts' idea of a worthwhile news story.
</P>
<P>
   The brief history of civic journalism would be funny, if it
weren't so pathetic. A dozen years ago, Marvin Kalb was pushing a
scheme called ``Nine Sundays,'' which wanted to fob nine
presidential debates on the American people at a time when they
would much rather be watching ``60 Minutes.'' That idea went
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, civic journalism, which is driven by the liberal
ideology of the big East Coast foundations, intervened in the North
Carolina senatorial race with disastrous results. The Jesse
Helms-Harvey Gantt rematch was a morality play that bedeviled
liberals, who just couldn't figure out how come a racist cracker
like Helms kept beating a nice black pol like Gantt. (Hint: It's
not just Duke University professors voting down there.) So the
North Carolina media dreamed up a civic journalism project called
Your Voice, Your Vote, which promised to focus voters' attention on
issues like affordable health care and education, instead of such
distracting ``hot button'' subjects as race, or family values.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what happened? Helms refused to participate, so the effort
went for naught. Caught up in the miasma of focus-grouped ``issue
forums'' and similar rubbish, the press ignored much of the
campaign. ``At the core of the idea, there was always a fraud,''
according to Michael Kelly, who wrote about North Carolina's civic
journalism experiment for the New Yorker. ``The fraud was the
notion that a self-selected group of reporters and editors somehow
could or should determine the fit subjects for debate in an
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess who's the civic journalism poster boy these days? Jesse
Ventura. That's right, the Pew-financed Campaign Quality Project is
very proud of having included Ventura in a series of debates that
provided ``a commanding alternative to the political ads and sound
bites that have so impoverished campaign discourse in recent
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Project director Paul Taylor _ this is the former Washington
Post reporter who has issued many a public mea culpa for asking
Gary Hart during the 1988 campaign if he was an adulterer _ noted
that the debates prompted an unusually large voter turnout, which
helped Ventura. ``I can't pass judgment one way or the other on
whether he'll be a good governor,'' Taylor said after the election.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem with civic journalism is that it is a cure for
a disease that doesn't exist. High voter turnout doesn't
necessarily produce better politicians. If memory serves, Leonid
Brezhnev won many an election with 99 percent of the vote. Debates
often obfuscate rather than elucidate. And voters know what issues
are important to them; they don't need a small army of
grant-grubbing double-domes to tell them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Globe columnist Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
