<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-FASHION-TIES-BOS &LR;      10-27 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-TIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYING DRESS-UP WITH COMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The casualization of America has been bad news for necktie
makers. Industrywide, tie sales have flattened as more men
gravitate toward business-casual clothing. What's a fashion
designer to do? Create casual neckwear.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. There is now a push to sell ``khakis-friendly''
ties, or neckwear that coordinates with chinos. Typically, they are
earth-toned; made of fabrics like knit, cashmere, silk, or flannel;
and constructed with either no lining or a very thin one, so
they're lighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an evolution of the tie,'' pronounces Jarlath Mellett,
design director at Brooks Brothers, which touts casual with, for
example, an indigo- and khakis-striped cotton twill version. ``In
the past, ties were geared toward shirts and suits, and there was
no other way to wear a tie.'' Now, with the advent of casual
workplaces, Mellett reasons, the casual tie is a means to stand out
as authoritative, without wearing a jacket. ``The whole idea of
getting dressed up again is coming back but in a new way: you're
comfortable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a sham if you want. But the fashion industry does make
one good point _ many American men have gotten sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very short list of people I would consider
stylish,'' says Alan Flusser, author of ``Style and the Man'' and a
New York menswear designer whose clothes are sold in Saks Fifth
Avenue. ``If (the industry) could somehow teach men how to dress .
. . how to wear a dark suit, white shirt, dark tie, dark socks, and
shoes perfectly . . . which kind of tie to buy for your complexion,
how to put the tie in the collar properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know how to do that, no amount of fashion, money,
or high-quality will enable you to dress well.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, say style professionals, there is a whole generation of
young men under 30 who have never even worn a tie. ``Kids really
don't know how to put an outfit together,'' says Bill D'Arienzo, a
New Jersey marketing consultant to the apparel industry. ``They
were raised in jeans and sneakers. They were raised in an era of
confusion when there were major (sartorial) transitions going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outer dressing is really a reflection of your inner self,'' he
adds. ``People have lost sight of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tailored Apparel, Jewelry and Accessories Council _ an
alliance of 12 trade associations _ is determined to change all
that. This spring, it's launching a three-year $30 million national
ad campaign designed specifically to encourage men and women to
dress up. Ads will appear in magazines like GQ, as well as on
billboards, at bus stops, and on TV, says D'Arienzo, who is founder
and executive director of the group. ``The key is to create images
and messages which make dressing up fun again. It ought to be a
lifestyle choice. Just as you wear jeans, you wear a tie and
gown,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, plenty of casually dressed men think the whole
dress-up idea is bogus. ``A casual tie is an oxymoron,'' says
Stephen Burgay, vice president of corporate communications at John
Hancock Financial Services in Boston, who typically wears khakis or
jeans, button-down shirts and sweaters on casual Fridays. ``I think
people made casual day, not fashion designers. It has become as
popular as it is because people genuinely like it, not because it's
a fad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are concerned about comfortable clothes and
(the fashion industry) is concerned about making more money. . . .
My closet will be a casual-tie-free zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Cortez, a human resources professional at Cahners Business
Information in Newton, owns five ties and eight pairs of khakis and
he intends to maintain that ratio. ``Ties just aren't comfortable
garments,'' says Cortez, whose company allows him to dress casually
five days a week. ``You have to button your shirt at the top and
that's just not comfortable. Making a tie casual won't make a
difference. The only occasions I'll wear a tie are a funeral,
wedding, or job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers concede the concept is a tough sell. ``You can't push
men too far,'' says New York designer Joseph Abboud, who is
introducing casual ties in his fall 2000 line. ``Men love
stability. They don't want to ever appear foolish or frivolous.
Most of the guys I know will say `I'm not wearing that.' It will
take two or three seasons and then they'll get it. . . . We have to
walk gently with this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Abboud is convinced the concept is a winner. ``There is a
way to bring ties into sportswear,'' he says. ``A sportshirt,
cardigan, or unconstructed jacket with a tie is a nice accessory
for men.'' Unlike in the past, when knit ties were so thick that
they couldn't be knotted neatly, Abboud's new product is more like
a scarf-tie, he says. ``I'm using a lot less lining. It falls
differently. It's not so firmly attached to your chest. It's not
perfectly aligned. It has the effects of a scarf but it still ties
beautifully and it moves with your body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of the either-or syndrome. . . . Men don't have
options. Women can wear short skirts, long skirts, pants. If we
take away options for men, we're going to be a little boring.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the necktie hasn't outlived its usefulness. Bankers,
lawyers, and other corporate types wear ties everyday. In 1998, 105
million ties were sold nationwide and retail tie sales were $1.6
billion, according to the Neckwear Association of America. In 1997,
105 million ties were also sold. ``Reports of our death are greatly
exaggerated,'' says NAA executive director Gerald Andersen. ``A tie
is still the only accessory item men have in their wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   The necktie _ or its precursor _ has been around for centuries.
It originated in Europe in the 1600s, when, it is generally
believed, Croatian soldiers wore neckerchiefs (or scarves) with
tassles that draped on their chests, says Valerie Steele, chief
curator of the museum at the Fashion Institute of Technology in New
York. ``Originally, the soldiers could use it to wipe sweat or
blood off their faces,'' she says. In the late 1600s to 1700s,
France's King Louis XIV made cravats (in linen or muslin with lace
edges) a popular fashion statement in western Europe. By the late
1700s to 1800s, ``there were so many different ways of tying the
cravat that there were even books on it. . . . It definitely was a
major status symbol,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The long tie with fold-over collar was born in the late 1800s in
England, she says. It has prevailed ever since _ until casual day
changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think American men have never looked worse,'' says Andersen.
``The knit shirt and stomach hanging over the belt and wrinkled
pants is just not the answer.'' But he is optimistic. ``I think
young people will start to dress up again because they won't want
to look like their parents. When they see mom and dad traipsing off
everywhere in jeans, they will dress nicer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
