<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-POWELL-BOS &LR;      10-27 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-POWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS FROM THE HEROIC, RICHLY HUMAN DAWN POWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SELECTED LETTERS OF DAWN POWELL &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Edited by Tim Page &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holt, 373 pp. $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweights like her friends Edmund Wilson and Gore Vidal tried
to establish Dawn Powell's position in American literature, but
their efforts were unavailing. Powell's books swiftly went out of
print and stayed there; they became difficult to find. After her
death, her literary rights were caught in the logjam of her estate.
But finally, through the efforts of music critic Tim Page _ not an
academic, but a ``general reader,'' the kind Powell would have
appreciated the most _ nearly all of Powell's books have been
restored to print by the Steerforth Press. They have delighted and
touched a whole new generation of general readers, and one feels
certain that Dawn Powell and her books _ she wrote 15 novels, 10
plays, and more than 100 stories _ are now here to stay. We need
them. We need her exact depictions of a vanished Ohio and a
vanished New York City, and still more, we need her timeless wit,
sensitivity, and fortitude, her ability to make us laugh out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Page also edited Powell's diaries and produced a splendid and
moving biography. Now, he has completed his labor of love and
delight by editing a selection of Powell's letters, from 1913 to
her death in 1965. The letters, in conjunction with Page's helpful
seven-page ``time line,'' present an alternative autobiography, and
add different perspectives to her life. We see her again as wife;
mother of a beloved child injured during birth; devoted (but not
unquestioningly) family member; struggling Hollywood screenwriter;
peerless friend; deadly enemy; astute commentator on New York's
artistic scene, providing unusual glimpses of famous people we
thought we knew from other contexts; an unflinching observer of her
own behavior and, needless to say, that of others. Page's editorial
contributions provide a helpful guide to Powell's many worlds, and
this reader caught him out only once. (It is probably necessary to
provide a footnote elucidating the old advertising campaign ``Which
twin has a Toni?'' Page seems to think a Toni was a dye job, but
all readers of a certain age will remember that it was a home
permanent. Sic transit gloria mundi.)
</P>
<P>
   After judging a writing contest, Powell comments on the literary
college students of the time: ``The influence of Freud and
psychoANALYSIS is clear _ they write in the first person a lot and
remember sexy moments from their childhood and faraway first lays
when they were a rather bored ten or eleven. In fact, they seem
self-absorbed, sex-obsessed, oblivious to all surroundings and
people _ curious.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell herself boasted an indefatigable curiosity, and it is
instructive to watch her construct entertaining little dramas, or
short stories, for her correspondents out of the real dilemmas of
her life, to watch her wit rescue her from self-pity. ``How
frighteningly dependent we are on things beyond our control,'' she
writes to Edmund Wilson. ``Do I sound like Lin Yutang?'' She can
even make writer's block sound like fun. ``I think I will write a
short story,'' writes Powell to novelist Malcolm Lowry. ``I think I
will take a dexedrine pill and go out and have my hair dyed yellow
with matching accessories. I think I should take care of my
health'' _ and this is only one stanza out of a delirious and
disturbing aria.
</P>
<P>
   When lyricist John Latouche was searched at US customs after a
trip to Africa, the inspector sat down for a thoughtful study of
Powell's letters, ``tittering appreciatively from time to time,'' a
response that readers will still summon.
</P>
<P>
   One therefore hates to think of Powell's falling into the hands
of the universities and the lit-crit business, though this iron
butterfly is unlikely to be broken on any wheel of their devising.
Teachers and scholars will want to consult the entire known body of
Powell's letters _ more than a thousand of them are known to
survive, Page states, and he is certain that still more will turn
up. His own personal and engaging selection is not intended to
throw strong illumination onto Powell's novels: She doesn't seem to
have been given to discussing the aims of her own work very much,
except when she had to. Instead, the book aims to provide a
representative collection that documents Powell's life, interests,
and the various personae she constructed for her different
correspondents _ all facets of the same memorable, heroic, and
richly human character. The book's value is that it gives Powell's
captivated readers a few more hours in her delightful and
sympathetic company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
