<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-27 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LIBRARIES WITH ONE THING IN COMMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Nine subway stops and acres of attitude
away from Harvard Yard, the first sits beside the Atlantic on
Boston Harbor. The second occupies a hillside above the Pacific,
375 miles south of Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the John F. Kennedy Library nor the Ronald Reagan
Library resides where originally intended. Despite rejection
letters from Harvard and Stanford, both are prospering in handsome
locations. Decades of bitter debate have ended happily.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Presidential Places,'' author Gary Ferris catalogues
birthplaces and tombs, also listing the Web sites of 10
presidential libraries. Under ``programs'' of speeches and
conferences, a pattern is clear: Libraries not affiliated with
universities are livelier, with a strong sense of identity with
their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Dorchester is now a destination and Simi Valley is a new
intellectual hub for Ventura County. Each library is an ``agora,''
the ancient Greek concept for a marketplace of ideas, flourishing
while liberated from the passions of academe.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents are people, too, awed by academe. But ivy can
suffocate originality. In the past two years, the JFK Library
sponsored conferences re-examining the presidencies of Calvin
Coolidge and Herbert Hoover to the delight of C-Span fans. This
transideological innovation might have offended student groups
eager to demonstrate or disrupt. (Harvard students have treated
politicians rudely since Federalist thugs hooted at Andrew Jackson
during Old Hickory's visit to Cambridge in 1833.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Oct. 14 Dorchester Reporter, Bill Forry documents the
odyssey of the JFK Library, celebrating its 20th anniversary, from
the Charles River to Columbia Point. UMass-Boston was nearby but
not dominant. The clincher was that the president's mother, Rose
Fitzgerald Kennedy, was born in Dorchester and graduated from
Dorchester High.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's legacy is breathing independent air, as is Reagan's.
The Gipper's demonstrated popularity in America would meet its
match in Stanford's notorious zeal to enforce political conformity.
Had Edmund Morris, author of ``Dutch,'' done his research on
campus, he might have been lionized instead of laughed at. The
deconstructist and Dadaist caucuses in the English department would
have saluted his data-don't-matta biography. Morris might have won
tenure as a professor of literature, history, or physics.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s in Massachusetts and the 1980s in California,
aesthetics rather than politics ruled antilibrary emotions. Citing
the moat-and-drawbridge icons of ``traffic and parking,''
Cantabrigians and Palo Altans objected less to the archives than to
the visitors, all those Americans invading their high-rent
hangouts.
</P>
<P>
   During both disputes a compromise was floated: OK for the
archives on campus, but send the tourists elsewhere. But the
democratic instinct is often sounder than dusty archives. Hearing
Reagan's voice muse on his career as an actor, how can any
biographer think him ``unknowable''? While some politicians
reinvent themselves, this politician, willing to screen his own
Warner Brothers clips, must be the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The gift shop is often where it's at. In Independence, Mo., a
popular item is a reproduction of Harry Truman's desktop reminder,
``The Buck Stops Here.'' At the Reagan Library gift shop, visitors
can buy a $25 copy of Reagan's favorite artifact, a paperweight
saying, ``There's no limit to what a man can do or where he can go
if he doesn't mind who gets the credit.'' One need not agree with
his legacy of lowering taxes and filling the skies with missiles
and bombers to appreciate the ultimate political guile of
guilenessness.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy scouted library real estate near Harvard in April 1963.
Reagan and Stanford agreed in 1983 that his papers would go to
Stanford. Neither plan worked out, but two presidential libraries
prove that intellectual life can thrive off campus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-27 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING UP TOO LATE IN STUART CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether his musings were that of a chastened or conniving mind,
Mickey Roache has brought a final clarity to the Stuart case. We
now know exactly how expendable black people were.
</P>
<P>
   Roache, today a Boston city councilor, but 10 years ago the
police commissioner, last week made the out-of-nowhere claim that
his cops never considered William Bennett a suspect in the murder
of Carol DiMaiti Stuart. Roache now blames then-District Attorney
Newman Flanagan for making Bennett the prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Roache said his office begged Flanagan not to arrest Bennett.
Bennett was arrested. Roache said he held his breath as the arrest
``brought the city to the brink of serious disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Roache said, ``The one thing that has really bothered me'' over
these last 10 years ``is Willie Bennett was not in jeopardy of
being indicted . . . I was overruled.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this recounting is true, it did not bother Roache enough
10 years ago to break the code of silence among cops. It was a
silence that, however candid Roache thinks he is being today, makes
yesterday even worse than before.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Oct. 23, 1989, police were called to shooting
in the Mission Hill area. Inside a car were Charles Stuart and his
pregnant wife Carol DiMaiti Stuart. Carol was dying. Charles was
bleeding with severe wounds to the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The two had just left birthing classes at Brigham and Women's
Hospital. Charles claimed a black man shot them. Charles's wounds
convinced police to go searching for a black man.
</P>
<P>
   It was far more than a ``search.'' Mayor Ray Flynn called for
``every available detective.'' Flynn fueled racial tensions by
saying the city _ despite the many murders of African-American
women and children _ particularly empathized with the Stuarts
because they had a ``bright, hopeful future.''
</P>
<P>
   It was understandable how Charles could fool the cops for a few
days. But instead of asking new questions as the chase led to dead
ends, the police vented their frustration on black men.
</P>
<P>
   The original description of the ``assailant'' was a black man in
a sweatsuit. Stuart could have substituted tuxedo for sweatsuit and
it would not have mattered, given how scores of black men,
including college students and those coming home from work in
suits, ties, and dress shoes were stopped and frisked. Back then,
Maria Sanchez of the Puerto Rican Tenants of Mission Hill in Action
said, ``The invasion of Panama was nothing compared to the invasion
of Mission Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   As we know, white communities, no matter the crime, are not
invaded like this. One black man, Alan Dawson, was jailed on Oct.
29 for 23 days, merely because a sweatsuit was found in his
apartment. Then, Bennett, a man with a criminal record who happened
to live near the crime scene was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   According to an investigation by US Attorney Wayne Budd,
Roache's cops berated and threatened to beat and imprison Bennett's
friends and relatives if they did not make false statements to
incriminate Bennett. Budd decided not to seek criminal charges, but
criticized the police over ``the fact that a community of color was
falsely targeted for this crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Roache's own policies led to the false, easy, and lazy targeting
of an entire community of color. It was Roache who enthusiastically
endorsed a decade ago a policy of ``stop and frisk,'' which police
justified because of the high murder rates and crack hysteria of
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the policy was often abused to harass law-abiding
African-American men, sending the message far and wide that all
black men are suspects. Such policies came back to haunt Boston in
1994 when cops stormed an apartment in a botched drug raid and
literally scared a black minister to death. Such policies live on
today in Driving While Black, in which African-American and Latino
motorists are stopped for no cause by police.
</P>
<P>
   One well-mannered high school student told me in 1990, ``Here, I
go to school, I go to work, and I have to feel every day that I
could go to jail.'' A 45-year-old African-American businessman told
me how he and his 47-year-old and 43-year-old professional friends
have been stopped more than once at gunpoint. ``No matter how old
we are, it's as if people are trying to say we're members of some
black gang,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Roache let this go on, with a gut feeling that Bennett was
not the suspect, then it betrays the gutlessness of his leadership.
If he is telling the truth, it means he placed the code of silence
over civil rights. It means he sacrificed the dignity and psyche of
untold black men to keep Flanagan happy.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years removed, Roache says he is ``amazed to this day that
we didn't have a riot.'' If he is telling the truth, he cannot be
amazed, since he could have blown the whistle to stop the invasion
of Mission Hill, but refused to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Today Roache says he was ``overruled.'' He cannot escape the
truth that he inflicted grievous wounds in the Stuart case. No
matter how much he changes the story, Roache inflamed the city by
playing too much by the wrong rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
