<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      10-27 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSTOCK REVISITED; CAGE'S RETURN TO ACTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been months since the anarchic mess known as Woodstock
99, but Harper's Magazine for November comes up with one of its
best chronicles. By David Samuels, the you-are-there piece moves
from the behind-the-scenes obliviousness of people like Michael
Lang and John Scher to the concert-and-camping chaos where at least
four women were raped, two people died, and riots erupted after
three days of stepping through sewage. Samuels is unforgiving in
his portrayal of the dated ``hippie'' philosophies spouted by
people like Lang and Wavy Gravy, and he conveys a profound sense of
the disconnect between the show's organizers and its massive
audience. He's also got plenty of shade left to throw on his fellow
reporters, as they swarm around the highly promoted event. ``They
bustle around the walkie-talkie-wielding flacks . . . tossing out
hard questions about a reported drug overdose in the campgrounds
last night and the fact that the band Sugar Ray has backed out of
their slot on this afternoon's bill. Then they lower their voices,
shift from foot to foot, smile, and ask for interview time with
Alanis Morissette.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuels stumbles upon a wealth of telling images during his
weekend wanderings. Amid a carnival of topless women and leering,
yelling men, the writer's eye turns upward: ``Looking up at the
bright orange blimp hovering over my head, I wonder whether its
message _ FRIED DOUGH _ might be some kind of key to the deeper
meaning of this event. If the original Woodstock was about peace,
love, music and making a good movie instead of a bad one, Woodstock
99 is about feeling the grease soak through the paper and onto your
fingers.'' Watching the arriving knapsacked concertgoers kick up
dust, he thinks of ``a herd of dispossessed extras in a
made-for-MTV version of `The Grapes of Wrath.' '' He never manages
to define the malaise of the Woodstock 99 generation as well as he
nails their elders, but Samuels powerfully conveys the event itself
in all its aimlessness, sloppiness, and lack of unity.
</P>
<P>
   His is a far more visceral piece than William H. Gass's argument
in favor of paper and ink, ``In Defense of the Book.'' The essay,
brainy and sometimes beautiful, is filled with Proustian notions
about the life of a book and the memories it holds, from food
stains to handwritten marginalia. Gass also has plenty to say about
the profound importance of browsing and the inner life of
libraries, where epiphanies, ``enrichments of mind, and changes of
heart, are the stuff of everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director David Lynch once called Nicolas Cage ``the jazz
musician of actors.'' But since 1995, after riding ``Leaving Las
Vegas'' to international fame, Cage has pretty much turned away
from the art of jazz and taken up advertising jingles. For paydays
that are often more than four times the budget of ``Leaving Las
Vegas,'' Cage has devoted most of his post-Oscar energy to
big-budget actioners like ``The Rock,'' ``Con Air,'' and ``8mm,''
steroid puffery that requires little more than a firm physique, an
ironic smirk, and the tart delivery of trailer-ready lines like
``Put the bunny back in the box.'' He has become bent on replacing
over-50 action heroes like Sylvester Stallone and Arnold
Schwarzenegger.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 11 Rolling Stone profiles Cage on the occasion of his
first ``actorly'' role in years, in Martin Scorsese's ``Bringing
Out the Dead.'' How does the 35-year-old actor take all the
criticism about his post-Oscar career, such as when former friend
Sean Penn told The New York Times Magazine, ``Nic Cage is no longer
an actor. He could be again, but now he's more like a . . .
performer''? Cage: ``A sellout _ I've heard that word _ is only a
sellout if you're being paid to do something you don't want to do.
I want to make these movies. I like working with (Jerry)
Bruckheimer. I like the work we've done together.'' Indeed, Cage's
next project is ``Gone in Sixty Seconds,'' a Jerry Bruckheimer
production about car theft that promises no shortage of burning
rubber.
</P>
<P>
   The November issue of Vanity Fair profiles an actor moving in
the opposite direction. As Cage loses his attraction to the art
house and eccentric characterizations, Jim Carrey is cultivating
the artiste approach to acting and working against his multiplex
reputation. Cage got his acting props and now seeks box office
clout; Carrey started off with top-grossing hits and is now looking
for some credibility. For his turn as comic Andy Kaufman in the
forthcoming ``Man on the Moon,'' Carrey stayed in character on the
set and pulled some Method stunts, including berating Elton John in
the guise of Kaufman's lounge-act character, Tony Clifton. ``It's a
wonderful thing to get an Oscar,'' says Carrey. ``But I really
don't like the idea of kissing people and changing myself to get
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
