<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START-UP CRASHED, STAFF BURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one can accuse Charlie Guyer of being afraid of risks.
</P>
<P>
   In July, he left a secure marketing position at Nortel Networks
to work for a one-year-old North Andover, Mass., firm that develops
software and hardware for telecommunications companies. That
start-up, Quantum Bridge Communications, has received $22 million
in venture capital so far and has a 45-member staff that, like the
company's founders, is banking on the firm's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The further you go in your career, the bigger the risks,''
said Guyer, 30. ``But there is also an opportunity for greater
rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are replete with stories about tiny Internet
start-ups and high-tech firms that have helped turn company
founders and core employees into millionaires. ETrade Group Inc.,
Microsoft, Dell Computer, and Compaq are all part of the lore.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Cambridge-based Allaire Corp. has had a meteoric
rise. Known for its application server Cold Fusion, it traded its
stock for the first time nine months ago at $20 per share. That
stock is now valued at $70 per share. In a second IPO last month,
another one million shares were sold at $62 each. ``It's been quite
a ride,'' said David Orfao, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the successful start-ups, there are numerous
failures, according to the Small Business Administration. It
reports that for every 100 established firms, 16 start-ups are
created annually and a dozen or more fail.
</P>
<P>
   Most high-tech professionals thrive on risk, but a shutdown can
be stressful, especially when workers don't know it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Phil DiBello of Billerica. In the 18 years since he
became a software engineer, the 39-year-old manager and father of
four has worked for five start-ups and numerous other firms, each
time lured by the promise of success and the thrill of launching a
new product.
</P>
<P>
   But DiBello is still reeling from the treatment he says he
received when a former employer shut down without warning last
year. ``I'm not that concerned about a company failing,'' he said.
``Companies go out of business all the time. What concerns me is
how they treat their people.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBello found work in just three weeks, but his anger lingers.
This spring, he and 16 others filed a lawsuit in Middlesex Superior
Court charging the defunct firm, UniPrise Inc. of Chelmsford, with
breach of contract. The suit alleges that the software firm closed
in 1998 without paying 16 workers and a consultant more than
$250,000 in wages, benefits, and business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   DiBello, who says he is owed $25,000 in wages and business
expenses, said he financed a business trip to San Jose and agreed
to work without pay for seven weeks after company officials
convinced him their financial problems would end as soon as a
sought-after contract was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the lawsuit alleges that William J. Zures,
former UniPrise chairman, transferred software and assets from
UniPrise to a new company called Acrylis Inc., which later opened
in UniPrise office space.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs contend Zures was appointed chairman of the
UniPrise board the same day defendants Joseph Z. Perry, company
president, and chief executive Robert Z. Mowry resigned, giving
Zures total control of the financially ailing firm. By transferring
software to Acrylis, they say, Zures generated a stream of income
for the new start-up.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview last week, Boston lawyer James Coyne
King, who represents Zures, UniPrise, Acrylis, and Mowry, declined
to comment in detail, saying, ``There was no fraud or
misrepresentation.'' Both sides are scheduled to appear in court
Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service representative Karen Buretta had been with
Digital Equipment Corp. for 12 years when she heard about UniPrise
at a trade show. ``I was hired in 1997, and I really liked the idea
of going to a small company where people could work hard and grow
with the firm,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Buretta, 38, of Brookline, N.H., said she had no inkling that
there were financial problems until the company stopped paying
employees about 18 months after she joined the firm. ``I lost seven
paychecks in all,'' said Buretta. ``We were constantly told to sit
back, not to panic. We were told there was a deal going and as soon
as it went through, we would get paid . . . . People thought we
were nuts to stay, but we believed in the company and the
product.'' She says the defendants owe her more than $7,000 in
wages.
</P>
<P>
   For DiBello, whose children range in age from 6 to 12, the
shutdown and the loss of seven weeks' wages led to financial
strain. DiBello landed a job at American Internet Corp. in Bedford
shortly after he lost his job. That company was purchased by Cisco
Systems last month.
</P>
<P>
   As for his last employer, DiBello said, ``I was stung, but I did
not die . . . . The issue here is one of justice. The issue isn't
going out of business. That happens. For us, the question here is
why lead us on?''
</P>
<P>
   Attracted to UniPrise by a unique software product the firm had
purchased from a Helsinki firm, consultant Steve Orr says he
eagerly accepted a job assembling a team of skilled engineers. Orr
was laid off three months before the company shut down. A plaintiff
in the suit, Orr is seeking $8,000 in unpaid vacation time, 40,000
shares of stock, and damages. He and others claim company officials
used money targeted for employees' 401(k) accounts to run the firm
during its final days.
</P>
<P>
   Orr, who had options on 75,000 shares, was hoping for an IPO
with an initial sales price of $15 per share. As it turned out, the
company never went public.
</P>
<P>
   Would Orr take a chance on another start-up? ``When you are a
software engineer with talent, you can make money three ways: be an
employee, consult and triple your money, or join a start-up in the
early phase for equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work, the most you can make is a function of the number
of hours you put in during the year,'' said Orr. ``But if you join
a start-up and the company takes off, the sky is the limit . . . A
big company may be guaranteed to grow 10, even 15 percent, but that
is child's play compared to what these young firms can do. They
have serious, serious potential.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contact Diane Lewis at work(at)globe.com or 617-929-2069.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
