<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-27 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS COULD BE SITTING PRETTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On paper, the next two weeks can't be any better for the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-2, the Patriots are doing better than expected. Sunday's
opponents, the Arizona Cardinals, are 2-4, and hurting. If the
Patriots win, they will head into their bye week at 6-2, in great
shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, after winning their first playoff game in nearly
50 years last January, and being regarded as a Super Bowl contender
this year, have fallen upon hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has gone right for coach Vince Tobin. Several key
players left in free agency. A car wreck and injuries have combined
to ruin his offensive line. And worst of all, his talented young
quarterback, Jake Plummer, has suffered a series of injuries since
preseason and will not be available this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some might call this a ``trap game'' for the Patriots, who are
coming off an exciting, and very important, win against the Denver
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   There is always danger lurking in the NFL when things look this
good.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin would like nothing better than to restart his season with
a win over New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched most of the Patriots game on television,'' said
Tobin, echoing the words of every coach that has played against New
England this year. ``They are very talented. (Drew) Bledsoe is
playing at a high level. They have a great bunch of receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the turning point of the year for us. A win in this
game could go a long way. I told our team this week, we need
another start. Just one win. And then think about winning the next
one. And if we get it, I think good things will start happening for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal offense, playing with a wounded Plummer, has been
pathetic. They are ranked 29th in the league, better than only
Philadelphia and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five games, the Cardinals have scored 16, 10, 7, 14,
and 10 points, for a total of 57, an average of 11 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer fractured the ring finger on his right (throwing) hand
in Arizona's last game, Oct. 17 vs. Washington (a 24-10 loss).
Former Giants starter Dave Brown will take over against New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our team we are lucky to have Dave,'' said Tobin.
``He's a guy who has started a lot of games, and won a lot of games
in this league, and you are fortunate when you have a backup with
that kind of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent the last week changing around our offensive line.
The break came for us at the right time to give us a chance to do
it. Circumstances have dictated a lot things with our offensive
line, so we are going to put one of our draft choices, L.J.
Shelton, at left tackle. He was a holdout in training camp, so he's
been behind. And we are going to put Anthony Clement at the other
tackle. Clement has been injured but is close to being all the way
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Those moves would give the Cardinals the youngest pair of
starting tackles in the league. Only one lineman, center Aaron
Graham, will remain from the formation that lined up against
Washington two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell how bad the offensive line has been. The
quarterbacks have been sacked 15 times. Plummer, under a lot of
pressure, has thrown a league-high 14 interceptions. The Cardinals
are the worst in the league at giving away the ball _ 20 times
between interceptions and fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't continue to make mistakes on offense like that
and hope to win,'' said Tobin. ``Our defense hasn't been that bad.
But it's hard when you try to overcome so many turnovers by your
own offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also has been weak against the run _ 29th in the league,
surrendering 136 yards per game. This will give the Patriots an
opportunity to see whether their 133 yards rushing vs. Denver were
an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   The tough matchup for Bledsoe &AMP; Co. could come in the passing
game. The Cardinals are fourth in the league in pass defense. The
Patriots have been living on the pass all year. Arizona has a solid
group of defensive backs, headed by Pro Bowler Aeneas Williams, who
almost certainly will be assigned to Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   However, two of the best Arizona defenders may not be factors.
Mark Smith, considered by some the Cardinals' best defensive
lineman, had knee surgery in the past 48 hours and will not play
Sunday. Eric Swann, also dogged by injury, will play only on
third-down pass-rush situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the things that have happened to us,'' said Tobin,
``the attitude of the team is still good. We know we can win. We
know we have to be more consistent and do a better job of
protecting the ball. If we do that, I'm sure we will start winning
again. I told them this thing isn't over yet. We can get it
together and still get back into the playoff picture.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
