<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET'S GOLD-RUSH MENTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We live in an e-world. There is e-commerce, e-brokerage, and
e-banking.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, what follows are some e-bservations on some of
the latest developments in the Internet business, not all of which
make sense to those of us who are not as caught up in the
e-xcitement as others.
</P>
<P>
   --If you came from another planet and watched the first game of
this year's World Series, you would assume that the most popular
activity on earth was on-line investing. During the first eight
innings of the game _ we went to sleep after that _ there were
advertisements for six different on-line brokerage services:
ETrade, Ameritrade, Fidelity, Waterhouse, Merrill Lynch, and Datek.
Doesn't anyone drink beer or drive cars anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Don't get us wrong. We love the ads, especially the Ameritrade
ads where Stuart, the redheaded rebel, teaches his stodgy old boss
how to trade on line. But from an investment perspective, there is
definitely something wrong with this picture.
</P>
<P>
   After an explosive start, electronic trading has lost momentum.
The up-and-down stock market hasn't helped. It could also be true
that many of the people who are active stock traders have already
made the leap to cyberspace. Ameritrade, which will report its
earnings this week, is expected to say that average daily customer
trades fell 10 percent during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the electronic brokerages are spending money as if this
market had unlimited potential. According to press accounts, the
on-line companies are spending up to $500 to snag each new
customer.
</P>
<P>
   As Mr. Rogers might put it: ``Can you spell shakeout, boys and
girls?'' Savvy investors apparently are catching on to the
underlying lunacy here. ETrade's stock is at 22, down from 60 in
May; Ameritrade's stock has dropped from 45 in April to 17. Rock
on, Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   --Speaking of competition, stock prices, and the Internet, what
are we to make of the incredible valuation the market has placed on
Sycamore Networks?
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, Sycamore, a start-up based in Chelmsford,
Mass., did an initial public offering last Friday. At the end of
the day, it had a market value of $14 billion. The company has sold
$11 million worth of equipment since May. Naturally, it has not yet
turned a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are not quite as ridiculous as they seem. Sycamore
is in a hot field. It is building the next generation of
telecommunications gear. All the world's biggest telephone carriers
will need such equipment to cope with the growing data traffic
generated by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore also has good credentials. Its founding executives, Dan
Smith and Desh Deshpande, sold their last company, Cascade
Communications, for $3.7 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bet on Dan and Desh,'' says Todd Dagres, a partner
with Battery Ventures, a Wellesley venture capital firm.
``Investors have faith they will figure out what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But the dynamic duo will have plenty of competition.
All of the world's big makers of telecommunications gear _ Lucent
Technologies, Cisco Systems, Nortel Networks, Alcatel _ are in a
race to supply this same equipment. The giants may be big and slow,
but they are not stupid. And it is unlikely they will let upstarts
like Sycamore take away their business without a serious fight.
</P>
<P>
   So far investors seem to be ignoring the competitive aspect of
the business. They are caught up in the story of the Internet as
Gold Rush and they have convinced themselves that the companies
that supply the ``picks and shovels'' to the gold miners will
strike it rich. Maybe. But what happens if lots of companies make
``picks and shovels,'' and it is hard to tell their products apart?
Can they all strike it rich?
</P>
<P>
   --Speaking of striking it rich, the people involved in the
Sycamore deal have done that and then some. As of Friday, Dan and
Desh were each worth more than $2 billion. The stake owned by the
venture capital firm, Matrix Partners, was also worth more than $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Matrix's money will be divided up among its partners;
the rest will go to its investors, who typically include some of
the nation's biggest college endowments, foundations, and pension
funds.
</P>
<P>
   What do all those winners have in common? They are all already
very rich. Dan and Desh split $150 million when they sold Cascade.
The investors in Matrix have enjoyed a fantastic decade of venture
deals.
</P>
<P>
   In a column called Boston Capital, you are not going to hear
anyone criticized for making money. Creating wealth is a good
thing, and the folks involved in Sycamore did it by being smart and
fast. Good for them.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to wonder if there is not a way, short of Marxism,
that would spread the wealth around a little more. Is there a price
to pay for living in a world where a handful of people win
megabucks while everyone else just watches from the sidelines? We
don't know the answer. It's just an e-bservation.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
