<HEADLINE>
HAPPY FOR A SECOND-PLACE FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, Karen Smyers won the Hawaii Ironman Triathlon
World Championships. Last weekend, she was happy to finish second
in a performance that sealed a remarkable comeback from injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``After having won it once, I'll never be totally satisfied not
winning it again,'' a tired Smyers said Tuesday afternoon, straight
off the red-eye and back home in Lincoln, Mass. ``But all things
considered, I really did have a pretty good day, and that's all I
can ask of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ``things'' include slashing a hamstring in a household
accident in 1997, giving birth to daughter Jenna on May 1, 1998,
and getting sideswiped by an 18-wheel truck while on a bike ride 3
1/2 months later. Smyers finally came back this spring and has been
competing well on the shorter, Olympic-distance circuit (0.93-mile
swim, 24.8-mile bike, 6.2-mile run), but Saturday was her first
Ironman since she finished third in Hawaii three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in with a different perspective this year,'' the
38-year-old Smyers said. ``I really appreciated getting to the
starting line healthy. I don't take that for granted anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Smyers's swim was the fastest she's ever had at the Ironman, and
she came out of the water well enough to take the lead about 35
miles into the bike portion. Going into the run, she was still in
front and feeling optimistic. Calculating her pace as she covered
the early miles, she figured her seven-minute miles would be good
enough for a 3:02 marathon, which would be her fastest ever, and if
anyone could catch her, more power to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big thrill to lead the race for so long,'' said
Smyers, who in her 1995 victory passed a depleted Paula
Newby-Fraser just before the finish line. Another high point came
early in the run, when she got the chance to high-five a very
special spectator: her 17-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The euphoria was short-lived. About 10 miles into the run,
eventual winner Lori Bowden of Canada blew by her, opening up a gap
so quickly that Smyers's spirits sagged until she realized there
was still a race going on (``I hoped maybe she went too early and
was going to pay the price later'') and that if she wanted to hang
on to second place in front of Fernanda Keller of Brazil, a
notoriously fast finisher, she had better buckle down. She did,
finishing in 9 hours 20 minutes 40 seconds, about four minutes
ahead of Keller. The 32-year-old Bowden, meanwhile, ran the fastest
marathon in Ironman history (2:59:16) to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, Lori Bowden was just totally inspiring,'' said Smyers.
``Lori earned that victory big-time. I don't feel it was anything I
did wrong. She was just better.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was a decent day for the Smyers clan; 42-year-old
sister Donna, of Montpelier, Vt., finished second in the master's
division in 10:31:31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fence of gold
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Purcell, a sophomore at MIT, won a gold medal earlier
this month in the sabre competition at the Junior/Cadet Pan
American Fencing Championships in Porto Alegre, Brazil. The
19-year-old from New York City, who is studying civil and
environmental engineering, also helped the US win the team relay.
This is the first year that sabre has been an NCAA sport, and in
November the first women's world championships will be held in
Seoul, Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
