<SLUG> BC-FILMFESTIVAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM FEST HAS A SMARTER SOPHOMORE YEAR _ BUT WITH GROWING PAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The second annual Fort Worth Film Festival
had an educational bent this year. ``This has been a very special
experience,'' actor Brock Peters said in his mellow baritone while
helping to introduce ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' to an almost full
house Saturday night. ``I will no longer,'' he continued, ``confuse
Fort Worth with Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival learned a lesson from last year. Things were more
concentrated, and as a result less hectic than during its inaugural
year. The first year had a biting-off-more-than-it-could-chew
quality, which made sense: Ambition is an American, and a Texan,
trait. Because things were less spread out, attendance looked to be
consistently higher, especially for the big events. Although last
year there was nothing quite on the scale of this year's keynote
event, film icon Gregory Peck discussing his career in a
Saturday-afternoon Bass Performance Hall show titled ``A
Conversation With Gregory Peck.'' After a well-chosen spattering of
clips, Peck employed his husky-voiced calm to discuss his life in
film and the reunion of the cast of ``Mockingbird;'' this was the
first time that Peters (Tom Robinson), Mary Badham and Phillip
Alford (who played his young children, Scout and Jem) had all been
in attendance for one of his shows.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most moving responses in the Conversation came
during the audience Q&AMP;A. When Peters was asked how he found his way
through the role of the black man accused of rape in
``Mockingbird'' (the film is an attack on racism, set during the
Depression, based on Harper Lee's novel), he talked about drawing
on the racism he had suffered. (Later, Badham said that Peters was
so powerful during a courtroom-scene rehearsal that ``... people
cried and (director Robert) Mulligan was motioning to get the
camera going. I think that was the take they used.'')
</P>
<P>
   This year's big-winner film was ``New Clear Farm,'' Danny
DeLoach's amusing short about a pair of yokels with an awesome
responsibility, the nuclear bomb they discover. There were other
shorts with fun elements, such as director Julienne Greer's ``Hand
of a Lifetime,'' a spotty film about a husband's anxiety over the
birth of his child. The film has one great scene: Just as he's
about to be beaten by a pack of thugs, the husband stammers that
he's about to be a daddy, and the thugs suddenly start whipping out
pictures of their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most charming aspect of the festival was hearing the
filmmakers stand and speak before the shorts ran. Generally,
introductions happen only during feature films at festivals, and
this touch is specific to Fort Worth. Unfortunately, these intros
make things a little more heartbreaking when the walkouts begin
during some of the less endurable films. This year at the Caravan
of Dreams, the lights illuminating the steps were kept on _ most of
the time _ which made that walkout much safer.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Anne Francis was also on hand to introduce a showing of
``Forbidden Planet,'' the 1956 sci-fi take on Shakespeare's ``The
Tempest.'' She looked spectacular and made a good impression; she
joked about the groundbreaking social-conscience melodrama
``Blackboard Jungle,'' in which she appeared, saying the gang boys
in that film ``are like pixies compared to today.'' (The guys in
the gang included Sidney Poitier and Jamie Farr _ Klinger from TV's
``MASH.)''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbidden Planet'' ``doesn't show you everything,'' Francis
said, ``you have to feel it.'' It barely showed much of anything,
given that it suffered most from the print and projection problems
that are the inevitable plague of film festivals. The print had
faded _ it was as pink as Bugs Bunny's gums _ and, at the AMC
Sundance, seemed to be projected through a Cuisinart. (There's talk
that next year, extra projectionists will be brought in to
alleviate the projection snafus.) Although a beautiful Technicolor
print did show up for the festival's surprise screening, a showing
of the heretofore unavailable ``Fort Worth,'' which festival
artistic director Dwight Greene browbeat Warner Bros. into
locating. ``Fort Worth'' stars the heroic, though inexplicably
prissy, western mainstay Randolph Scott.
</P>
<P>
   While introducing the film, actor Barry Corbin reiterated the
hilarious wisdom that ``if you close your eyes, Scott sounds just
like Oliver Hardy'' of the screen comedy team Laurel and Hardy.
``Fort Worth,'' in which Scott plays a gunslinger-turned-crusading
newsman who has to pick up his guns again _ and no, this is not the
story of any current Star-Telegram employee _ features dialogue
such as, ``His only friend was a gun'' and the audience favorite:
``News comes in pieces, like suits of clothes. Don't ever sport the
jacket unless you got the pants.'' While this lacks the simplicity
of the Star-Telegram's slogan _ ``What do you want to know?'' _ it
has an unforgettable poetry.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
