<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-WOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON FACES TALL ORDER TO REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. looked as if it might soar a year ago. Boasting
several recent acquisitions and a hotshot new chief executive, the
defense contractor seemed ready to transform itself into an
industry star.
</P>
<P>
   But this month Raytheon, Massachusetts' third-largest private
employer, suffered a hard landing instead. Orders for its Patriot
ground-to-air missile are off. An investment in a huge satellite
phone system flopped. Its construction unit continues to miss
schedules on power plant projects, keeping them off line as the
peak winter heating season approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The string of bad news culminated with the company's warning
Oct. 12 that its profits would be far below expectations this year
and next. The report eroded its credibility on Wall Street and
pushed its stock to around $30 a share for the first time since the
early 1990s, when Raytheon was a $10 billion company _ half its
current size.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, the company now admits, its purchases of other
missile and defense electronics facilities created a distraction
that left it vulnerable to increased competition. As a result, to
the intense displeasure of investors, Raytheon has taken charges
against earnings of $638 million this year. The company also will
cut 2,380 positions from its worldwide work force of 106,000,
including about 340 jobs in New England.
</P>
<P>
   These troubles have obscured some notable successes. One came
this month when a Raytheon antimissile rocket, known as an
``exoatmospheric kill vehicle,'' demolished a target during a trial
over the Pacific Ocean, a big step forward in the development of a
land-based Star Wars defense system. In June, a Raytheon-led team
won a $1.3 billion bid to build a radar system for the British
government. That month, Raytheon also won a major contract to
produce a prototype shipboard radar system for the US Navy,
positioning the company to win contracts that could eventually be
worth billions.
</P>
<P>
   Now chief executive Daniel Burnham must prove he can continue to
deliver such results while molding Raytheon into a high-profit
whole. He is relying on new quality-control programs and a massive
restructuring begun last year that has installed new executives in
half the company's top 175 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect a rough ride ahead for Burnham, who
replaced Raytheon's longtime chief executive Dennis Picard last
December. Even Burnham's hobbies have proved punishing: Riding with
other aerospace executives at a conference in Wyoming in September,
Burnham was thrown from a horse and knocked unconscious, and
suffered two broken ribs and a scar above his left eye that ``gives
him that Humphrey Bogart look,'' according to John R. Galvin, a
member of Raytheon's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham and other top executives say they now have a better
handle on operations and pledge to raise profit margins to the 6
percent level they once forecast. They also promise better
oversight of Raytheon's financial records, which are tracked by 50
different computer systems, many of them seriously dated.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at the company's pace of restructuring, ``In
retrospect, we tried to do too much too fast,'' Burnham told
analysts on a long conference call announcing the charges this
month. While the company's underlying operations are sound, he
said, the focus on acquisitions caused the company to lose track of
changes in the market.
</P>
<P>
   That message, however, may be difficult to sell to investors,
few of whom expect the company's earnings to recover soon. One
problem is that Raytheon's largest customer is the Department of
Defense, which prevents the company from disclosing much data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to see precisely what's going on internally'' at
Raytheon, said Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette analyst Joe Nadol.
``They give a lot of details but not the kind that offer a lot of
insight.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Burnham's ascendency was supposed to mark a
new era of openness at Raytheon. Hired from AlliedSignal Inc.,
Burnham was given a mandate to integrate major acquisitions of
missile and defense electronics makers Raytheon undertook in 1997,
including the operations of Texas Instruments Inc. and Hughes
Electronics Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham has taken some steps to make the Lexington, Mass.,
company more transparent, meeting with investors, visiting more
plants, and responding to personal e-mails from employees. Burnham
also declared his ``embarrassment and guilt'' over the recent
performance, unusual confessions in the defense industry. Lehman
Brothers analyst Joseph Campbell calls those statements ``more
convincing than the damage control efforts'' by other defense
contractors that have had problems, such as Lockheed Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But vestiges of Raytheon's old, closed culture are still
evident. In February, Raytheon brought a lawsuit against 21 people
who allegedly disclosed company secrets on an Internet chat board.
The suit drew criticism that Raytheon was trying to stifle debate
on line. Raytheon dismissed four employees after discovering their
names through subpoenas, but dropped the suit in May before
recovering any damages.
</P>
<P>
   Observers and some former company employees also say Raytheon's
ongoing layoffs contributed to its financial surprises, by making
managers reluctant to share bad news with their superiors in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stretches the imagination to think that anybody is going to
criticize the regime or (Burnham) personally when that person's
name could be considered one of those to go,'' said fund manager
Lee Forker Jr., president of New England Research Management.
Forker says he sold shares in the firm in September.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs have brought criticism on Beacon Hill from
legislators. They say the reductions violate the spirit of a 1995
tax-cut agreement designed to protect state jobs by committing
Raytheon to maintain certain payroll levels. The deal once was
estimated to be worth up to $20 million a year for the company,
though a report issued Oct. 14 by the state's Department of Revenue
shows that Raytheon and two other defense contractors claimed
benefits of only about $9.4 million in 1996 and about $3 million in
1997, the last year for which figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon says it has met the terms of its agreements. But the
company makes it clear that it plans to reduce its blue-collar
employment base and hire more software engineers and other
professionals whose work commands higher profit margins. Those
hires will keep the company's total employment in Massachusetts
around 13,700 this year, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The company's main concern is keeping its projects on track.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 6,000 different projects in all, Raytheon has lagged
in some areas. The Army, for instance, has delayed a $100 million
payment to Raytheon and a partner for the shoulder-fired Javelin
antitank missile, because of problems with a fuse supplied by a
subcontractor. But military spokesmen say Raytheon has met its cost
and work schedules on other high-profile contracts such as the
Tomahawk cruise missile and on an extremely high-frequency
satellite communications program for the Navy. ``They're doing
fine,'' said Navy Lieutenant Meghan Mariman, spokeswoman for the
Navy's Tomahawk program.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's work on individual jobs isn't as important to
investors as is its ability to track its overall finances and
provide a clearer outlook on earnings, said Lehman analyst
Campbell. He estimates Raytheon's 25 largest projects account for
only about 10 percent of its revenue, compared to about 60 percent
for Lockheed Martin. Raytheon's ``program mix has a lot of programs
you've never heard of, which is probably an advantage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Burnham says he will continue shifting executives
until the company improves its performance. His own job is secure,
says Raytheon director Galvin. Burnham also has support from more
unlikely quarters, including one of the employees who was dismissed
as a result of the company's investigation into on-line messages.
</P>
<P>
   The former employee, who posts under the moniker ``Winstoncar,''
wrote on the board last week that because of the company's recent
disappointments, ``I should feel vindicated but I feel sorry for
Burnham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is doing the best he can under the current
circumstances,'' the former employee wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
