<SLUG> BC-WOM-RUNNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVEN ANOTHER YEAR, SHE'S ON THE RUN AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Lehane, Boston University's cross-country coach, knows
that one runner does not make a team. Still, he can't help but brag
when it comes to talking about Ann Kovalsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is critical,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Critical in that she's helped vault the Terriers to their
first-ever national ranking. And critical in that she's even on the
team at all.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky, a fifth-year senior who graduated with a bachelor's
degree in exercise physiology last spring, should be in her first
year of graduate school at Sacred Heart University in Fairfield,
Conn. But after running in three meets last year, then being
hospitalized with blood clots in her lungs, Kovalsky spent the
winter recuperating and petitioned the NCAA to grant her a medical
exemption, which would allow her to continue running for one more
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of startling to see the turn of events, because
there was a time when we didn't even know if she could run again,''
Lehane said. ``Having her back is fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky is thrilled, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting a lot of attention and energy into this year
because I know that this is my last opportunity to do it, and I
really feel like this year was a gift,'' she said. ``From whom, I
don't know. But I really feel like this is a gift to be able to
come back here and do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky, 22, grew up in Ridgefield, Conn., where she was an
accomplished soccer player _ her team won county titles several
times and won the state championship one year.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in shape for soccer, she decided to run track in the
winter and spring. Soon she realized that she had promise there,
too, when she ran a 5:09 mile during her freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I sort of figured out that I guess by playing soccer all
those years I had a natural tendency to run,'' said Kovalsky, who
started playing soccer when she was nine. She kept running, set
four high school records, and by the time she was ready for
college, was ready to abandon soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really had enough of it,'' she said. ``Running was new and
exciting for me, and I believed I could improve a lot, so I wanted
to go that route.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky was named MVP of the cross-country team in 1996 after
helping BU break through the NCAA rankings, something it had never
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's a team sport, you have to have someone go to
the front,'' Lehane said of the sport where the team's total point
score is derived from how each runner places. ``Last year we would
have gone to nationals if we'd had her.''
</P>
<P>
   But those aspirations came crashing down after the team's third
meet in October. Kovalsky had experienced some trouble breathing
since August, but by mid-fall she developed chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we went through it, it was quite confusing, and we thought
it might be exercise-induced asthma, were thinking of going with
that, then she deteriorated,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky said she remembers well the team's PreNational meet in
Kansas last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it was a mediocre day, and I personally had a really
horrible race,'' she said. ``We got back Sunday night, and by
Tuesday I was in a lot of pain and feeling really sick. I had pain,
basically anywhere your ribs are.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Kovalsky was told that what was initially diagnosed as
asthma was bilateral pulmonary emboli, or blood clots in her lungs.
Dr. Jack Ansell, a hematologist at BU Medical Center, had Kovalsky
hospitalized for a week and put her on blood thinners to dissolve
the clots.
</P>
<P>
   Ansell said the clotting disorder is a genetic one that was
probably exacerbated on the plane ride back from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running is not an issue, but sitting for long periods of time
can be bad,'' he said, adding that he didn't fault other doctors
for their earlier diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think her initial treatment and evaluation was just right; I
would have done nothing different,'' Ansell said. ``She probably
does have a touch of asthma.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky spent the next two months thinking about the pain in
her chest, thinking about not being able to run, and thinking about
how her collegiate cross-country career had apparently come to an
abrupt conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really difficult time, because my supposed last
cross-country season had ended, and I wasn't going to run indoor
track because I wouldn't be fit,'' she said. ``It was sort of
depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   But her depression turned to determination, as Kovalsky vowed to
regain her collegiate eligibility. The NCAA rule book states that
you cannot run in more than two meets and then be redshirted. She
was one over the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she said, but she ran those meets when she shouldn't have,
when she was suffering from blood clots and didn't realize it. She
wrote to the NCAA, her doctors wrote, BU admistrators wrote, all
saying that if Kovalsky had been diagnosed in September, this never
would have happened.
</P>
<P>
   The months went by, and instead of concentrating on her final
exams and graduate school applications, Kovalsky was biding time.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, six months after her last meet and three months away
from graduation, Kovalsky got her wish. The NCAA told BU that she
could run another year.
</P>
<P>
   That spring, Kovalsky ran track for BU and placed fifth in the
ECAC meet in the 5,000 meters. She graduated in May, asked to defer
her graduate school admission for a year, went home to Connecticut
for the summer, e back to BU this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the PreNational meet this October, both the team and Kovalsky
shined. She placed 22d, with a time of 17:51, over the 3.1-mile
course in Bloomington, Ind. Teammates Lauren Matthews and Kathryn
Ireland finished 71st and 76th, respectively, and the team was
ranked 13th nationally. It was the first national ranking ever in
the program's 22-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The team will compete in the America East championships this
Sunday, then the NCAA Regionals on Nov. 13, where the first two
finishers, along with an at-large selection, will be invited to the
NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're in good shape even if we finish third,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   lsky said the meet in Indiana ``was the most positive
experience that I've had my entire college career. As a team we
went in there as unknowns, and we came out as 13th ranked in the
country. People were not aware of our depth, of our strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to say it, but it was one of those things
when you go, `finally, all of this work has paid off,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention all the waiting and wondering she went through
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalsky said even though others might not understand it, she
knew there was no question that she'd fight to run another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like I'd been cheated out of what I love to do the
most,'' she said. ``You know, you can only compete four years, and
you can never go back. So I felt like it would always be unfinished
business, and I really didn't want to walk away from it at that
point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
