<SLUG> BC-FRITOPIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO, SANTA FE IN FRITO PIE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A real Frito pie feud is brewing between San Antonio and Santa
Fe.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico legend has it that Woolworth's employee Teresa
Hernandez concocted the first Frito pies in 1960, when business was
lagging at the new store in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   It was right after Christmas, and the normal lull in sales had
the store manager worried, Hernandez explained, so he challenged
his workers to come up with something special to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   After trying several versions, one of which included refried
beans, Hernandez sliced open a bag of Fritos and poured hot chili
on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked it,'' she said Tuesday in a telephone interview from
Five and Dime, the successor to Woolworth's, where she is part
owner. ``It became very popular.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is all well and good for Santa Fe, but 1960 was
nearly 30 years after Daisy Dean Doolin created the cold-weather,
Friday-night-football staple in her San Antonio kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Monday's Wall Street Journal recalled the incident.
The Journal explained that Doolin, mother of Frito company founder
Elmer Doolin, invented Frito pie in 1932 in her San Antonio home.
She poured leftover chili _ Texas chili _ over Fritos.
</P>
<P>
   John McCarty, a longtime Santa Fe resident who was a Frito-Lay
executive for years, backed up the Journal account. McCarty,
recruited by Doolin in 1952, hired Frito's first home economist,
Nell Morris, who put together a cookbook of recipes using company
products, including Frito pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably published the first official version of it, as far
as I know,'' McCarty said. ``That was in the 1950s.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe ``New Mexican,'' in an obvious attempt to defuse
the controversy, reported Tuesday that although San Antonio might
indeed be the birthplace of the dish, ``Frito pies apparently
aren't well-known in San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   A receptionist at the San Antonio Convention and Visitors Bureau
told the paper that ice cream trucks were the only places she knew
that sold them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, no, no,'' Martha Quan of the bureau said Tuesday. ``I
don't know who they talked with, but I'm just appalled by this. I
can't believe this. Everyone in San Antonio knows about the story.
They are very popular.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe paper said San Antonio food writer Ron Bechtol
hadn't heard that Frito pies were invented in his city, and he
added, ``The only place they're served is in funky places in the
Hill Country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that,'' Quan said. ``He's our food critic, and
he's been around for a long time. I'm sure he knows about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bechtol could not be reached to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Taylor, a district manager for Sonic Drive-Ins, said
``chili pie'' is a standard item on Sonic menus throughout Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a mean chili pie, and we sell a lot of them,'' he
said. ``I mean a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also dispelled the idea that the dish is scarce in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they have them down there because it's a standard item
on our menus and we have 42 Sonics in San Antonio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Santa Fe had to settle for claiming the best Frito
pie, if not the first.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Mackenzie, spokesman for Plano, Texas-based Frito-Lay,
agreed with Santa Fe's claim to the ultimate pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had Frito pies at the Texas State Fair and at Woolworth's
in Santa Fe,'' he said. ``I think Santa Fe can lay claim to being
better than anybody else. If who invented it first is disputed,
then the best is undisputed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' said Dee Dee Poteet, also with the
San Antonio Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``We don't recommend
specific restaurants, but I can tell you that Fritos were invented
here and so was chili con carne. It would make sense that we know
how to do the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   (This report includes material from The Associated Press. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
