<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GAY-MINISTER-HNS &LR;      10-27 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY MINISTER USED HIS FRIENDSHIP WITH FALWELL TO ARRANGE MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mel White, the Southern California minister who
got Jerry Falwell and 200 of his conservative faithful to meet with
him and 200 gay faithful last weekend, tried not to be gay.
</P>
<P>
   Raised by fundamentalists to believe God hates homosexuality,
White spent half a lifetime trying exorcisms, faith healings,
psychotherapy and electroshock aversion treatments and, finally,
slicing both his wrists _ before realizing the problem was not
within but without.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Southern California minister and one-time
ghostwriter for Falwell and Pat Robertson is on a quest to end the
``spiritual violence'' against gays waged by fundamentalist
Christians and by most mainstream religious denominations in some
form.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Falwell and his faithful to meet was White's most
visible effort so far to stop the rhetoric of hate.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: White will lead a contingent to Grand Island, Neb.,
next month as the United Methodist Church puts the Rev. Jimmy
Creech on trial again for blessing the union of a homosexual
couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to try to stop that trial,'' a tired but excited
White said Tuesday by telephone from Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Disrupting the trial, White explained, is ``not for Jimmy
Creech's sake, but because the trial will be another opportunity
for the nation to hear all this spiritual violence against gay
people _ that their relationships aren't worthy of being blessed,
that they are not good enough to be full-fledged members of the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   White, 59, has been on his quest since the early 1990s, but only
now has the conflict between religious proscriptions against
homosexuality and the gay rights movement taken center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Casting the struggle in high relief have been highly publicized
crimes against gays, such as the Matthew Shepard killing in
Wyoming, which White blamed in part on the anti-gay fervor of the
religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   His family's conservative religious roots run deep. His
grandmother led tent revivals. Carl and Faythe White raised their
sons in the Santa Cruz area, in the Church of God, and later served
as missionaries in Soweto, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   White, in his 1994 autobiography ``Stranger at the Gate,'' wrote
about the depths of his struggle to overcome his attraction to
other boys.
</P>
<P>
   He married his high school sweetheart, Lyla, after they both
graduated from a small Christian-oriented college in Oregon, and
they moved to Pasadena to raise their daughter and son.
</P>
<P>
   White earned a divinity degree at the evangelical Fuller
Theological Seminary in Pasadena, taught there and pastored a small
Swedish Covenant Church _ all the while grappling with his demon.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote books, and his speed and style caught the attention of
Richard Baltzell, who then worked for the Revell religious
publishing company in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   It was Baltzell who put White in touch with two conservative
ministers, Falwell and Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   White thrived through the 1980s as a ghostwriter for them and
another giant of the Christian right, D. James Kennedy, plus
evangelist Billy Graham and Oliver North. At the same time he
produced 53 movie and television documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   White has always said that he had never written anti-gay
rhetoric for any of them. He also refused to allow his name to
appear anywhere in their books, knowing his gayness might one day
tarnish them.
</P>
<P>
   He told Lyla of his struggle early on; she loved him, and they
vowed to cure him together. But none of his desperate measures
worked. Finally, he ripped his wrists with a bent coat hanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got out of intensive care, Lyla turned to me and said,
`Mel, you're gay. I like gay people, I just didn't want you to be
one,''' White recounted. ``She gave me the gift of life.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the early 1980s. Soon, White met Gary Nixon at All
Saints Episcopal Church in Pasadena. They have been partners for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   He has stayed close to Lyla and their children. Daughter Erin,
30, teaches fifth grade and raises her 7-year-old daughter; son
Michael, 29, is co-producer of TV's ``Dawson's Creek'' and a writer
on NBC's new series ``Freaks and Geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents, now of Scotts Valley, took the news hard. Their
move toward acceptance mirrors the one he's challenging Falwell and
the Methodists to make.
</P>
<P>
   Faythe White now feels, though her church doesn't, that
homosexuality isn't a choice. Carl White says he is more in
Falwell's camp _ recent Falwell, that is _ loving the sinner, but
not the sin.
</P>
<P>
   He's quick to say, ``Rest assured, we love Mel. And Gary, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White's public coming out took longer. He has been criticized
for continuing to write for Falwell and Robertson through the
1980s. He has said he did it to pay the rent and send his children
to college.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the strain of his double life crashed in on him. He
told Falwell and Robertson that he was gay, and sought to talk with
them about their anti-gay fund-raising letters. They refused.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, White has served as dean of the Cathedral of Hope
Metropolitan Community Church in Dallas, the largest congregation
of homosexuals and lesbian in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now back in Laguna Beach, he and Nixon have founded Soulforce, a
nonprofit organization based on the teachings of Mahatma Gandhi and
Martin Luther King, to use nonviolent means to end ``spiritual
violence against gays and lesbians.''
</P>
<P>
   White has persisted in his efforts to talk to his old employers.
He fasted three weeks in jail after being arrested for refusing to
leave Robertson's headquarters in Virginia, when the televangelist
would not see him.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, his efforts yielded the meeting with his old
friend Falwell _ and a softening of the Christian Coalition
founder's anti-gay message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
