<HEADER>
A0135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS28-COX     10-27 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS PLANS HUGE AD CAMPAIGN TO URGE PARTICIPATION
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau unveiled its first-ever paid
advertising campaign Wednesday as part of a $167 million effort to
reach minority groups that have been missed by past national head
counts.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is aimed at reversing a 30-year trend toward fewer
Americans completing and returning the census forms that are mailed
out once a decade. The ads will target groups that have
historically been undercounted: African Americans, Latinos, native
Americans and new immigrants from all countries.
</P>
<P>
   From January through April, the peak season for pushing the
forms, the Census Bureau will rank behind only McDonald's and
Burger King as a national advertiser, said Rep. Carolyn Maloney,
D-N.Y., the ranking minority member on the House subcommittee that
oversees the census.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will feature more than 250 different spots in 17
languages on 3,000 media outlets _ TV, radio, newspaper and
magazine advertisements and billboards. All revolve around a
central theme: ``This is your future. Don't leave it blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Required by the Constitution, the census is used to apportion
each state's membership in the House of Representatives and to
distribute billion of dollars of federal funds. Conducting the
census ``will be the most important job our government will do over
the next year,'' said Commerce Secretary William Daley at
Wednesday's ``Census 2000 Campaign Launch.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its importance, census participation has fallen in
recent decades. In 1990, the return rate was only 65 percent for
the forms mailed to the nation's 120 million households. That rate
compared to 75 percent who mailed back the forms in 1980 and nearly
80 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Without the new advertising campaign, a 61 percent return rate
had been projected for the 2000 census, said Kenneth Prewitt, the
bureau director.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the falling response rates are related to changes
in attitudes and demographics. Distrust and indifference toward
government has grown, he said. A growing proportion of the populace
is also made up of immigrants or their offspring, he said, and
these newcomers often don't understand the census forms or their
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   An advertising campaign aimed at some Hispanic groups will
stress the confidentiality of the forms, said Prewitt. The census
counts resident aliens as well as citizens, and some communities
fear the forms will be used by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service to deport those who are here illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge fire wall between the Census Bureau and the
INS,'' said Prewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the census ads are the opposite of most
advertising, which is aimed at the most likely customers for a
product. The Census Bureau wants to reach the audience that is
least likely to fill out its forms.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some census commercials will be in Spanish and air
on networks such as Univision. Others will feature African American
actors and be seen on Black Entertainment Television.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the spots stress that filling out the forms serves the
interests of the community. One shows an overcrowded school.
Another depicts a fireman with a defective hose. Yet another shows
a woman seeking day care for a child. ``Will you get your fair
share?'' they ask, in an reference to the public funds distributed
according to census findings.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising campaign was designed by Young &AMP; Rubicam, with
input from several other agencies. Before it is over, the Census
Bureau estimated, 99 percent of all Americans will have seen or
heard 50 of the spots on the air or in print. People in the
targeted groups will have seen 100 or more. The campaign will use
more than 3,000 media outlets and carry more than 130,000
announcements during a six-month period.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Census Bureau has relied upon donated time for
public service announcements, which mostly aired late at night or
at other periods of slack audiences, said Prewitt. This year, the
spots will run in prime time or other periods of high viewership by
the targeted audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Daley predicted the campaign will be ``the largest civics lesson
that the country has ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
