<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-GOODIES-2500(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER YOUR AGE, DON'T BE AFRAID TO CELEBRATE HALLOWEEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adults are discovering what they once knew and then forgot.
Halloween is fun.
</P>
<P>
   Now the second-largest American holiday (in dollar terms, and
what is more important in America?) Halloween has transcended
urchins with bags begging throughout the neighborhood. It's now a
holiday of light displays, extravagant and sometimes off-color
parades, specially brewed beers, and Elvira marathons. Adults just
want to have fun. After all, it was their holiday first.
</P>
<P>
   GROWN-UP TREATS
</P>
<P>
   BABY PUMPKINS FILLED WITH WORMS AND MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   _ 12 baby pumpkins (about 10 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   _ 12 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 pound dried mushroom linguine or dried black squid-ink
spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 pounds beef or pork, or combination, made into 24 meatballs
and cooked
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cups spaghetti sauce, purchased or homemade
</P>
<P>
   _ Freshly grated good-quality Parmesan cheese, to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Using a large, firm-bladed serrated
knife, carefully cut off the top section of each pumpkin to a depth
of about 1/4 inch using a sawing motion. Reserve tops, then scoop
out the seeds and membrane of each pumpkin and discard.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 sprig of thyme plus a little salt and pepper inside each
pumpkin and replace the tops. Transfer pumpkins to a baking sheet
and cover with aluminum foil. Bake for 30 to 35 minutes or until
pumpkins are just soft inside, being sure not to let them lose
their shape.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of salted water to boil. Add linguine or black
spaghetti and cook until al dente, stirring occasionally. Drain,
toss with butter and season to taste with salt. Meanwhile, warm
meatballs in spaghetti sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pumpkins from oven, discard thyme and fill each one with
the hot black spaghetti. Top each pumpkin with some of the sauce
and 2 meatballs, then garnish with the grated cheese. Place pumpkin
tops alongside pumpkins and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 429 calories, 16 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 23 grams protein, 62 milligrams cholesterol,
418 milligrams sodium, 33 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``The Lake House Cookbook'' by Trudie Styler and
Joseph Sponzo (Clarkson Potter, $35)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY STICKS WITH ORANGE CHEESE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 18
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 pound boneless, skinless turkey breast
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 1/4 cups fresh bread crumbs, toasted
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons turmeric
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 large eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 cups mild orange Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   _ 3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons prepared English mustard
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: You can make the cheese sauce in advance if necessary.
Don't worry if it firms up. Rewarm it in a double boiler over
simmering water, stirring until smooth. Serve the sauce in
hollowed-out squash for a decorative touch.
</P>
<P>
   To make cheese sauce, combine cheese, cream and mustard in
double boiler over barely simmering water. Cook for 15-20 minutes,
stirring occasionally, until melted and well-combined.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, preheat oven to 350 degrees. Cut turkey into 18
pieces measuring about 1 1/2 by 2 inches. Using a mallet or bottom
of a heavy skillet, flatten turkey pieces until they're about 1/2
inch thick. Season on both sides with salt and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine bread crumbs, turmeric, paprika and nutmeg in small
bowl. Place flour and eggs in 2 bowls. Dip turkey in flour, shaking
off any excess, then dip it in egg and let any excess drip off,
then press it in the crumb mixture on both sides to coat pieces
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   In large nonstick skillet, heat 1 tablespoon oil and 1
tablespoon butter over medium heat. When hot, add 1/3 of the
breaded turkey and cook for 2 minutes on each side. Transfer cooked
turkey to parchment-lined baking sheet and wipe out pan with paper
towels. Repeat with remaining turkey, adding more oil and butter
and wiping out pan between batches. Transfer baking sheet to oven
and bake turkey for 4-5 minutes. Serve with cheese sauce.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 171 calories, 12 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 12 grams protein, 66 milligrams cholesterol,
190 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``The Lake House Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MULLED CIDER
</P>
<P>
   Yields 16 cups
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 gallon fresh cider
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/8 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/8 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   Combine cider, cinnamon, cloves and allspice in large pot and
bring almost to a boil over low heat. Strain and store in
refrigerator until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 117 calories, 0 fat, 29 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 8 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``The Lake House Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ICY HANDS
</P>
<P>
   _ Latex gloves
</P>
<P>
   _ Black food coloring, see Note
</P>
<P>
   _ Water
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: As the hands melt, they will turn the punch black. If you
don't want that effect, fill the hands with uncolored water.)
</P>
<P>
   Fill gloves with water colored black with food coloring or with
clear water. Securely close the wrists with rubber bands or tie
them in a knot. Place them in the freezer on a flat surface until
solid.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the ice hands from freezer, peel off the latex and float
the hands on top of the mulled cider.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``The Lake House Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN PATCH CHEESE BALLS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 36
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 drops yellow food coloring
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 drops red liquid food coloring
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 teaspoon ground red pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ 6-ounce plastic roll of garlic cheese
</P>
<P>
   _ 7-ounce jar pimento-stuffed olives, drained
</P>
<P>
   Bake pine nuts in shallow pan at 350 degrees, stirring
occasionally, 5 minutes or until toasted; cool.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together butter and food colorings in large bowl. Add flour
and red pepper; cut in cheese with pastry blender until mixture is
blended. Shape into a large ball using hands.
</P>
<P>
   Press 1 tablespoon mixture around each olive. Using dull side of
a paring knife, score cheese balls with vertical lines to resemble
pumpkins. Chill 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bake on parchment paper-lined baking sheet at 400 degrees for
10-12 minutes or until golden. Place 1 pine nut into each cheese
ball to resemble stem. Serve immediately or at room temperature or
freeze up to 1 month.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER PUMPKIN: 67 calories, 5 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 4 milligrams cholesterol, 144
milligrams sodium, 65 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Southern Living'' magazine
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SPOOKY CUPCAKES
</P>
<P>
   SPIDER: Tint white icing with violet and frost cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   Tint more white frosting with black food coloring and fill a
decorating bag fitted with a No. 2A tip. Make the top and bottom
portion of spider body with the pastry bag.
</P>
<P>
   Using thin black licorice, place 3 arms and legs on each side of
the body. Use mini white jawbreakers for eyes. Pipe 2 dots on eyes
with a No. 2 tip. Place orange jawbreaker at bottom of both eyes
for the nose.
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN: Tint white icing orange and frost cupcakes.
</P>
<P>
   Fill decorating bag with more orange icing. From top to bottom
of cupcake, pipe 1 line down each end. On side of the line, pipe 1
more line on a slight diagonal to form the pumpkin rind, then pipe
middle line. You will have 5 lines on the cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   Using brown M&AMP;Ms, place eyes, nose and mouth in appropriate
places on the cupcake. Place a green gumdrop at the top of the
cupcake for the pumpkin stem.
</P>
<P>
   MONSTER: Tint white frosting with green food coloring and ice
cupcakes.
</P>
<P>
   Fit a No. 6 tip on a decorating bag and fill with green
frosting. On either side of cupcake, about 3/4 of the way to the
top, pipe the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Use black icing to form mouth, smoothing with a spatula. Using
the green frosting, and the No. 6 tip, pipe a circle that forms an
open mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Place white Tic-Tacs all around the open mouth to form teeth.
Place a green M&AMP;M above mouth for nose. Use two white gum balls for
eyes. Attach a No. 2 tip to a decorating bag with black-tinted
icing. Pipe black dots in middle of gum balls and pipe eyebrows
using the same tip.
</P>
<P>
   Tint icing orange and using a No. 16 tip, pipe hair on top of
cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   WOLFMAN: Ice cupcakes using chocolate frosting. Fit a decorating
bag with a No. 17 tip and fill with more chocolate frosting. Pipe
fur on top of cupcake in pullout star motion. Use 2 yellow gum
balls for eyes. Using a No. 2 tip and black frosting, pipe dots on
middle of gum balls and for eyebrows. Use a brown M&AMP;M for nose and
candy corn for teeth.
</P>
<P>
   WITCH: Ice cupcakes with green frosting.
</P>
<P>
   Using a No. 12 tip and more green frosting, pipe a nose in
center of cupcake. Use white gum balls for eyeballs. Using a No. 2
tip and black frosting, pipe black dot in middle of eyes. Pipe
mouth. Use a Tic-Tac for tooth.
</P>
<P>
   Using orange frosting and a No. 16 tip, pipe hair on top of
cupcake. Put black gumdrop that has been molded to a point on hair
as a hat.
</P>
<P>
   MUMMY: Using white frosting, fit a pastry bag with a No. 47 tip.
Pipe bandages on cupcake. Use green M&AMP;Ms for eyes. Using a No. 2
tip and black frosting, pipe black dots in middle of M&AMP;Ms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wilton Enterprises nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN BRULEE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 vanilla beans
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   _ 5 ounces sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 ounces maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup canned pumpkin puree
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 whole egg
</P>
<P>
   Split vanilla beans and scoop out inside. In saucepan, combine
vanilla with heavy cream, sugar and maple syrup. Heat until sugar
is dissolved. Remove from stove and mix in pumpkin puree, egg yolk
and egg. Combine well with a large whisk. Pour mixture into ceramic
molds and bake in water bath at 300 degrees for 15-20 minutes. When
cooled, sprinkle additional sugar on top and flambe with a torch,
if desired.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 259 calories, 18 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 241 milligrams cholesterol,
28 milligrams sodium, 63 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boca Raton Resort &AMP; Club, Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S TREAT
</P>
<P>
   SCAREDY CAT
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 frozen unbaked rolls (either 1.3 ounces each or 2 ounces
each), thawed
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 currant
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   Press 2 rolls together and form a 12-inch rope. Bend rope into a
horseshoe shape. This will be the body and legs of the cat. Place
on baking sheet sprayed with nonstick spray. On an angle and with
scissors, cut up the inside of the legs about 4 inches. Separate
each leg, turning the cut side down on baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   For tail, shape another roll into a 6-inch rope, making one end
pointed. Tuck pointed end behind sides of horseshoe.
</P>
<P>
   Flatten last roll and cut out a piece at the top to form the
cat's head and ears. With some of the cut-out piece, form 1 very
tiny ball and flatten it for the lower mouth. Form 2 other small
balls for the top of the mouth. Place them on the face. There will
be leftover dough. Place head on opposite side from the tail,
slightly overlapping body. Cut 2 slits for eyes and press a currant
above the mouth for the nose.
</P>
<P>
   With scissors, clip deep cuts on the cat's body and tail. Brush
with egg and let rise for 30 minutes. Bake at 350 degrees for 20-25
minutes or until golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER TREAT: 496 calories, 12 grams fat, 79
grams carbohydrates, 17 grams protein, 168 milligrams cholesterol,
793 milligrams sodium, 22 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BARN BAT
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 frozen, unbaked rolls (either 1.3 ounces each or 2 ounces
each), thawed
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 currants
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   For body of bat, press one roll into teardrop shape. Cut a small
triangle out of the rounded bottom for legs. Press 2 rolls into 2
triangles for the wings. Scallop the bottom of each wing with a
knife or scissors. Place wings and body on baking sheet sprayed
with nonstick spray. Make 3 deep slashes in each wing. Pinch top
point on each wing together.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 scallop pieces, form 2 feet by slashing deeply into each
piece twice. Place under body of bat. Using about 2/3 of another
roll, form a smaller teardrop shape for the head. Slash this
teardrop from the point to the middle of the roll. Pull the 2 sides
apart to form ears. Place above body. Press finger firmly into each
ear.
</P>
<P>
   Using some leftover dough, shape 2 small balls and 1 tiny ball.
Place them on bat's face to form the mouth. Press 2 currants on
face for the eyes. Place 1 currant above mouth pieces for a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Brush bat with egg and let rise for about 30 minutes. Bake at
350 degrees for about 20 minutes or until golden brown. Redefine
ear indentations before and during baking.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER TREAT: 497 calories, 12 grams fat, 79
grams carbohydrates, 17 grams protein, 168 milligrams cholesterol,
793 milligrams sodium, 22 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OOGLIE EYEBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 16
</P>
<P>
   _ 10.25-ounce pouch fudge brownie mix
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup sweetened dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 cups white chocolate chips or morsels, melted
</P>
<P>
   _ Tubes of decorative writing gel: green, red, black
</P>
<P>
   Prepare brownies according to package directions. Bake for 24 to
28 minutes in 8-inch pan or 18 to 22 minutes in a 9-inch pan or
until toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. Don't overbake.
Trim crisp edges from the brownie while warm; eat or discard.
Crumble remaining warm brownie into medium mixing bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Combine sweetened dried cranberries and warm crumbled brownie
until a thick doughlike mixture forms. Shape dough into 1-inch
balls, pressing firmly. Dip balls in melted white chocolate,
letting excess drip off. Place on wax paper-lined baking sheets.
Refrigerate 1 hour or until chocolate is firm.
</P>
<P>
   To create eyeball decoration, use red gel to make veins, green
gel for center of eye and black for the pupil.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER EYEBALL: 207 calories, 10 grams fat, 32
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 16 milligrams cholesterol, 55
milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ocean Spray
</P>
