<P>
   DUTCH-ARCHITECTS (Amsterdam) _ Architecture is a fractured
field. There are some who build but seldom break new ground, and
the experimenters whose idiosyncratic designs and arcane language
can scare off clients with the power to promote them. And then
there are a few, like Ben van Berkel and Caroline Bos, succeeding a
different way. By Philip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPERFECT-DESIGN () Were it not largely obscured by a privet
hedge, Gary Guerrette's three-bedroom bungalow might cause a
neighborhood revolt. But in low-key Water Mill, N.Y. _ where
picturesque dilapidation can be a badge of honor _ the rippling
asphalt-shingle roof, buckling wood steps and architectural malaise
pass without remark. ``It needs a little work,'' said a
brightly-smiling Mr. Guerrette, 40, of the house he shares with his
partner, Tom Lawson, 42, a massage therapist. Informally formal,
rough yet elegant, it is a semaphore for design on the century's
cusp _ a lively mosaic of pleasures and passions rather than a
catalogue of aspirational perfections. ``I don't think we own
anything that isn't chipped, rotten, broken or falling apart,''
Lawson said. By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND-RETREAT (Delaware, N.J.) _ When Hal Bromm, a TriBeCa
gallery owner, and Doneley Meris, a bereavement therapist, bought
the old yellow clapboard Delawanna Hotel here as a weekend retreat
for themselves and their friends, there were 23 bedrooms. And lest
any of those friends felt left out, there was a stone guest house
on the hill. ``People keep stopping in to ask if this is a bed and
breakfast, and how much does it cost a night,'' said Bromm, a tall
man with dark curly hair, managing to sound both bemused and ever
so slightly annoyed. ``We tell them it's just for us.'' By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2, 3.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   BARRIER-FREE-DESIGN (Undated) _ I never thought, somehow, that
the Rolling Stones would be the ones to sum up our experience of
installing a new bathroom for our mother on the farm in Maryland.
But they must have known something when they said, ``You can't
always get what you wah-ahnt.'' But after two months of trying, we
got what we needed. What we needed, in the material sense, was a
downstairs bathroom, with a shower. But what we also needed, big
time, was a new attitude. Nobody wah-ahnts to get old, for
instance. My 86-year-old mother certainly doesn't like it _ hates
it, in fact, when it means she can't run up and down the cellar
stairs with 30-pound turkeys, or see Africa again. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-AWARDS (New York) _ Six futuristic innovators will be
lugging weighty chunks of the here-and-now home as the latest
winners of the Daimler Chrysler Design Award. The awards,
menu-shaped slabs of cast tombasile, or white bronze, weighing in
at more than 15 pounds, are to be presented in a ceremony tonight
at the Four Seasons restaurant in Manhattan. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   SALTO-POTTERY (Undated) _ It's rare that pottery can give you a
good scare, or that decorative art disturbs, but Axel Salto's does.
You think twice about touching it. It gives you goosebumps; it
looks like goosebumps. By William L. Hamilton.
