<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     10-27 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOME OFFICE: DECISIONS, DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first steps to creating a home office are evaluating your
space needs and then finding a suitable place in your home. Next,
estimate the amount of electrical power you need for equipment;
after that you can determine if the existing household circuits can
deliver the power without overloading.
</P>
<P>
   To estimate your power requirements, make a list of your office
machines. The list may include a computer, monitor, printer, fax,
answering machine and copier. It should be as complete as possible,
including even lights and appliances for comfort like a coffee
maker or microwave. Make a separate list for the climate-control
machines like the air-conditioner and heater; these should be on
individual circuits because they create power surges that can
affect the other office machines.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a complete list, calculate the amount of current
(this is measured in amperes) that each machine draws. Amperage
ratings are indicated in the owner's manuals and on labels at the
back of the machine. Typical current draws for office machines are
3 amps for a computer, 1.9 amps for a 17-inch monitor, 0.1 amps for
a telephone answering machine. Total the numbers. This is the total
current draw, or load, for all your machines.
</P>
<P>
   Most house circuits are designed to carry a load of 15 amps, but
it is recommended that you draw no more than 12 amps on these
circuits. Similarly, a 20-amp circuit should not have more than 16
amps. If your total exceeds these numbers, you can plug some of the
machines into another circuit. But remember that even if the load
falls within the specified circuit limit, you may still cause an
overload if other household appliances are on that circuit. In the
long run, it may be better to run a new line from the service panel
exclusively for your office machines.
</P>
<P>
   All of the circuits in your office should be properly grounded.
Don't assume that an outlet with three holes is properly grounded.
Use a circuit analyzer, a small hand-held device available in
electrical supply stores for less than $5, to check the ground
connection at each outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Office machines, particularly computers and printers, have
sensitive circuitry that can be damaged by power fluctuations.
Install surge protectors to safeguard your machines from voltage
spikes. Also consider installing an uninterrupted power supply unit
for your computer. This device has a battery that provides a
continuous flow of electricity in case of a power failure. The
continuous power will give you enough time to save current files
and shut down the computer properly. The unit also has a filter
that evens out electrical fluctuations to provide clean power. This
will result in better performance, reduce repair costs and increase
the longevity of your office machines.
</P>
<P>
   After evaluating the electrical circuits, concentrate on the
office plan. Start by designing a layout for the computer,
administrative and production areas. These are the areas where you
will spend most of your working time, and they also have more
elements _ furniture, shelves and machines _ to position. The
meeting and storage areas need little planning because they have
fewer elements.
</P>
<P>
   Workstation layouts will vary according to your needs, but the
most practical arrangements are the straight, galley, corner,
alcove and U-shaped arrangements. The straight arrangement,
sometimes called the railroad layout, is the simplest. The
worktables are arranged in a line along one wall, with necessary
shelves and cabinets mounted above. This arrangement works well in
a long narrow room that has at least one wall without a window. If
the room is wider, you can go to a galley arrangement. Here two
lines of worktables are installed in straight lines directly across
from each other on opposite walls. This is a good arrangement if
there are two people working in the office.
</P>
<P>
   In the corner arrangement the worktables, shelves and cabinets
wrap around a corner into an L-shaped arrangement. This layout
provides more legroom than either the straight or galley layout and
is a good choice if you have a room with two adjacent windowless
walls. In the alcove arrangement the worktables, shelves and
cabinets wrap around three walls of a room. This arrangement uses
the most wall space, but it can create a claustrophobic or cramped
feeling in a narrow room.
</P>
<P>
   The U-shaped arrangement is similar to the alcove layout except
that one stretch of worktables projects into the center of the
room, not along a wall. This is a versatile layout because it makes
the office into a meeting room as well as a work area. However, it
can only be installed in a wide room.
</P>
<P>
   Work out your office plan carefully on graph paper to see which
arrangement will fit into the space you've chosen for your office. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
