<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-49ERS-YOUNG-HNS &LR;      10-27 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS QB STILL SEES HOPE OF PLAYING THIS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER and LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ San Francisco 49ers quarterback Steve
Young said Wednesday he would neither retire nor go on a
season-ending injured reserve status because of his fourth
concussion in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 38, said he was still suffering complications from his
latest concussion in a game with the Arizona Cardinals on Sept. 27,
but he also maintained that did not preclude him from returning to
the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good now,'' Young told a news conference. ``It's really
a function of time. We have some time. We'll take some time. ...
It's something you can't rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a series of discouraging reports in the wake of his
most recent concussion, the 49ers had been expected to place Young
on the injured reserve list.
</P>
<P>
   After an examination by his primary neurologist, Gary Steinberg,
at Stanford Medical School two weeks ago, Young was encouraged by
the 49ers to seek other opinions on the risks inherent in
continuing to play football with a history of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Young's agent, Leigh Steinberg, who is no relation to Gary
Steinberg, said independent medical evaluations were not
encouraging for someone looking to play football again. Leigh
Steinberg said Tuesday there would be no decision on the
possibility of Young's retirement until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   If he never plays again, Young will leave the National Football
League with 33,124 yards passing and 232 touchdowns to go with
4,239 yards rushing. The rushing total is second in NFL history for
a quarterback, behind Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Young's problems with concussions began on Oct. 27, 1996, in a
game against the Houston Oilers. While scrambling, he was hit hard
by linebacker Michael Barrow and left the game. He was taken to a
local hospital for evaluation and treatment. He sat out the next
game against New Orleans and returned Nov. 10 for a game against
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Cowboys, Young again got hit hard while running with
the ball. This time, the knee of linebacker Jim Schwantz caught
Young in the forehead, resulting in his second concussion in 15
days. Young missed the next game against Baltimore but returned the
following week and finished out the season without event until
breaking three ribs in a playoff game against Philadelphia on Dec.
29, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Young's 1997 season started painfully. On Aug. 31 at Tampa, Bucs
linebacker Hardy Nickerson came sliding in to help on a tackle of
Young and his knee inadvertently slammed into the back of the
quarterback's helmet. That was concussion No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Young did not play the next week against St. Louis, but he
returned the following game against New Orleans and played a more
cautious brand of football as the 49ers concentrated on the running
game to take the pressure off their quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Young had his finest statistical season in 1998 as he passed for
4,170 yards and 36 touchdowns, both franchise records. At one
point, he had 300 yards passing in six consecutive games to
establish an NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming San Francisco's starting quarterback in 1991,
Young has been to the Pro Bowl seven times. He was the NFL's player
of the year in 1992 and 1994. Young's career peaked in the 1994-95
season when he led the 49ers to a 49-26 victory over San Diego in
Super Bowl XXIX. He threw a Super Bowl-record six touchdown passes
against the Chargers and was named Most Valuable Player of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   In Young's absence this season, Jeff Garcia has started the last
four games for the 49ers, during which the club went from 2-1 to
3-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still growing,'' head coach Steve Mariucci said of
Garcia. ``He'll show flashes of being a darn good quarterback, and
he'll show flashes of being a new quarterback. He's only going to
get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0143 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HAM-SHORTAGE25-COX     10-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAM-SHORTAGE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ham operators dwindling
 &HT;    EDITORS: RESENDING TO EXPLAIN REFERENCE TO ``HAMILTON''
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There's a worldwide shortage of hams.
</P>
<P>
   Not those canned pork products, and not theater bugs, but rather
those amateur radio enthusiasts who, during emergencies, are often
the only links to ravaged areas.
</P>
<P>
   Augie Schwab has seen his friends, one by one, set aside their
radio equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of ham equipment sitting around not being
used,'' said the 77-year-old ham enthusiast, who lives near Boynton
Beach. He said one son dabbled in ham radio three decades ago but
none of his children or grandchildren is interested now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not replenishing'' the ranks of ham operators, Schwab
said.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely culprit: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage was brought home in September when Hurricane Floyd
threatened South Florida. A local volunteer group comprised of area
ham clubs that normally staffs storm shelters didn't have enough
operators to go around. Ham radio operators become crucial when
telephone lines go down, providing links between shelters and
administration and emergency operations centers. Radio Amateur
Civil Emergency Service, which uses the acronym RACES, coordinates
with emergency managers before hurricane season to staff shelters.
</P>
<P>
   County officials, police and paramedics rely on ham radio
operators at shelters when telephone lines are swamped or go down.
They also can become the only links to Caribbean islands hit by
storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly concerned about it,'' Palm Beach County
Emergency Manager Bill O'Brien said of the shortage. ``The hams are
basically the last-ditch communications with the shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergency operations center is offering to let RACES leaders
use Palm Beach County equipment to train ham operators so they can
qualify as volunteers, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hamilton, an electronics technician for Palm Beach County
Fire-Rescue and the county's coordinator for RACES, blames the
overall drop in the numbers of ham operators on demographics and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   First, the hobby of amateur radios dates back several decades,
and the median age of hobbyists is over 50, so many of its
enthusiasts are getting older or have died, Hamilton said. Also,
many of those retirees had lived in mobile homes, so they planned
on being the first to evacuate and were the first to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hamilton said, many have moved into retirement villages or
even nursing homes and probably would stay. Younger people joining
the hobby often must balance demands of career and family, he said.
And younger retirees _ along with the general population _ are now
moving away from ham radio, once the only way to talk to people
around the world for free, and toward its successor: the Internet,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ham radio is the original information superhighway, the
original World Wide Web,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Hagy, spokeswoman for the Amateur Radio Relay League,
isn't ready to blame it all on the Internet. But she did say that
membership in the group, which dates back to 1914, has steadily
risen each year to an all-time high of 175,000 in January 1997, but
then dropped to the 163,000 it is now. That's about the same time
when the Internet exploded into popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Hagy believes hams still love the challenge of amateur radio
that the Internet can't provide _ ``being able to throw a wire up
in your back yard and not know who you're going to reach and how
far you're going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   She believes a greater factor is that there are more hobbies and
distractions today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different things to interest people,'' Hagy
said from the organization's headquarters near Hartford, Conn.
``There's a million different groups and organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Augie Schwab is convinced the Internet is responsible. Many of
his friends ``have minimized their activity on ham radio and
maximized their activity on the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The native of New York's Long Island, who ran an import business
until he retired and moved to Florida in 1989, was a radio operator
in World War II in Africa and built his first ham radio in 1955. He
is Indian Springs' hurricane emergency coordinator and still enjoys
reaching fellow hams around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it will ever die out together,'' Schwab said.
``I just think there will be fewer hams worldwide.''-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
