<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ETHICAL-SHOPPING-     10-27 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ETHICAL-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE SOMETHING FOR YOU, AND FOR HUMANITY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Reporter's e-mail address: Slatalla(AT)nytimes.com.) 
(nk) 
 BY MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hope I am not the first person to tell you that you do not
need a hemp linen pillow stuffed with buckwheat hulls. So what if
it has a zipper for easy hull removal? Never mind that the photo on
the Ethical Shopper home page made this $24 pillow look deeply
comfortable (www.ethicalshopper.com).
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't need it and I don't need it. Nor do we need to buy
a wool passport bag from Nepal ($9), a pet collar made with natural
hemp webbing ($7.95) or an earth-tone potpourri box with a lid
handle shaped like a frog ($14).
</P>
<P>
   So why am I lingering over the product descriptions (``Liven up
your bathroom with these bright colored all-natural, herbal
soaps'') at Ethical Shopper? Perhaps because the people behind it
and other ``ethical shopping'' sites like Ecomall and Enviroshop
are no fools. They know that for many consumers, the act of
shopping isn't just about what they want to own but also about what
they want to be.
</P>
<P>
   And so if I clicked the Order button, perhaps I would become
socially and environmentally conscientious, someone who supports,
say, the earthenware-producing efforts of an Indonesian women's
cooperative. I could also buy products that show my support for
animal rights, human rights, employee rights, community rights.
Also, I try not to litter.
</P>
<P>
   As you can probably tell, I didn't arrive at Ethical Shopper
with anything but disdain for something I saw as a marketing
gimmick. Even for someone who likes to shop as much as I do, it
would seem the height of self-delusion to equate the process of
buying useless trinkets with responsible behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping, in fact, is the kind of activity I engage in to avoid
behaving in a morally responsible fashion. If I truly cared about
animals, for instance, wouldn't I stop gazing at the picture of the
hemp pet collar long enough to take my dog out into the yard for
some training to reiterate the importance of not running in front
of cars?
</P>
<P>
   Ethical shopping sites play upon that exquisitely painful
combination of lust and guilt that only shopping elicits. I was
online, happily imagining how the potpourri box would look on the
shelf in the bathroom when all of a sudden, my mind flashed on the
sad image of a chocolate Labrador retriever limping around the
neighborhood in a hip cast.
</P>
<P>
   Guilt won. And if I had been browsing among the limited wares in
a small gift shop in the real world, I would have simply walked
out. But online, where shopkeepers aren't limited by the amount of
physical space available to store inventory, the varied wares of
countless independent retailers are displayed enticingly on a
single Web site. And impulse buying is much easier when all you
have to do is click. I realized this when in my haste trying to log
off, I accidentally clicked instead on Eco-Supermarket and saw that
the Ethical Shopper was selling Annie's Homegrown Macaroni and
Cheese. I usually buy cheaper, inferior brands, the ones with
artificial colorings and artificial flavorings and actual
preservatives, because Annie's costs $1.49 a box at my local
supermarket. But here was an opportunity to get a case of 24 boxes
of the comparatively delicious Annie's brand at nearly $1.35 per
box ($27, plus $5.30 for shipping) and yes, the bunny pasta shape
was available.
</P>
<P>
   To reassure myself that 14 cents per box was a significant
saving, I applied my Starbuck's standard: let's see, 14 cents times
24 boxes equals slightly more than two cups at Starbuck's. Just
think of all that free coffee I would be drinking next week.
</P>
<P>
   Did I need 24 boxes of macaroni and cheese? Of course not. But I
did need to believe, temporarily, that I could be the sort of
mother whose children could finish dinner without having the
telltale evidence of orange chemical residue on their lips.
</P>
<P>
   I made a quick side trip to compare prices at the Annie's
Homegrown Web page (www.annies.com). I could order the identical
item for $30 including shipping _ $2.30 less than the Ethical
Shopper price. Then it hit me: Since the Ethical Shopper charges a
flat-rate shipping fee, the answer was to purchase more things,
spreading out the shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   Did I forget to mention that I had been eyeing a bamboo-strip
book journal ($12), with paper made from Himalayan bark? With two
daughters who are diary-keeping fiends, I was bound to purchase
some journals somewhere out there in the world of shopping. Why not
buy socially responsible ones?
</P>
<P>
   Comparison shopping. Flat-rate shipping. Coveting Himalayan
bark-paper diaries. Somehow I didn't feel I was really in the
spirit of ethical shopping. But as I found out later, talking to
one of the Ethical Shopper's co-founders, Rachel Prishkolnick, on
the phone, that is exactly the reason shoppers end up buying
environmentally friendly products.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to buy a certain item anyway,'' she said,
``and you're given the choice of buying a product that's socially
conscious over something that's not, where's the dilemma? There
also is an increasing knowledge of our environment and the damage
we've done and how that affects us.''
</P>
<P>
   So buying from one of the growing number of online purveyors of
socially conscious products fills a great shopping need: the
ability for me to believe simultaneously in behaving selflessly
(supporting socially conscientious companies) even while I
selfishly get what I want. In other words, I could buy what I
wanted and, in some small way, what I wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the experience cost me $56.30, and we will be eating
macaroni until it makes us cry. But at least I didn't get hulls all
over the bedroom floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
