A0149 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BUNDY-RECIPES-TEX     10-27 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUNDY-RECIPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKLED GREEN TOMATOES ARE QUITE A CATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara McAlister has a bumper crop of green tomatoes and would
like to duplicate the pickled green tomatoes served at McGehee's
Catfish Restaurant in Marietta, Okla. We happened to have that
recipe in our files.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CADDO LAKE TOMATO PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 7 pints
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup pickling salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 quart white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 gallon green tomatoes, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 quart onions, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 quart green hot peppers, chopped (jalapenos or a mix of
jalapenos and sweet bell peppers)
</P>
<P>
   Bring sugar, salt and vinegar to a boil. Add vegetables. Bring
contents of pot to a boil and boil for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pack into hot, sterilized canning jars. Seal and process in
hot-water bath for 10 minutes. Serve either chilled or at room
temperature, with fried fish or any other plain meat.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER 1/4 CUP: 24 calories, 0 fat, 6 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 359 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT FOR THE HOLIDAYS: Mary Andrews of Azle in North Texas
would like a recipe for cheese puffs. This is a classic recipe,
using French pate a choux. Don't let that scare you; the dough is
rather fun to make, and you'll feel so accomplished afterward. This
version is from ``The Joy of Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE PUFFS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 48
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 tablespoons (1 stick) unsalted butter, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 1/2 cups Gruyere cheese
</P>
<P>
   Position rack in lower third of oven. Preheat oven to 400
degrees. Line cookie sheets with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Bring first 4 ingredients to full boil over medium heat. Add
flour all at once and stir vigorously with wooden spoon until
mixture pulls away from sides of pan. Continue to cook and stir
mixture for about 1 minute, to eliminate excess moisture. The
butter may ooze out, which is fine; it simply means the moisture is
evaporating. Transfer to a bowl and let cool for 5 minutes.
stirring occasionally. Beat in eggs one at a time with a wooden
spoon, or on low speed with a mixer. Make sure the paste is smooth
before adding the next egg. Beat dough until smooth and shiny. Stir
in 1 cup cheese. Choux paste can be covered and refrigerated for up
to 4 hours. When it is cold, you don't need to bring the paste to
room temperature before shaping.
</P>
<P>
   To shape, spoon dough into a pastry bag fitted with 1/2-inch
plain tip. Pipe puffs 1 inch wide and 1 inch high. If you're
frightened of pastry bags, a common affliction, spoon dough onto
parchment paper with a tablespoon.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth any tails or curls on the puffs with a finger dipped in
cold water. Dust tops of puffs with some of the remaining grated
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 400 degrees for 15 minutes. Lower heat to 350 degrees
and continue to bake until golden brown and very firm to the touch,
up to 15 minutes more. Turn off oven, turn puffs upside down and
let sit in oven for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER PUFF: 51 calories, 2 grams fat, 2 grams
carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 36 milligrams cholesterol, 46
milligrams sodium, 67 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REQUESTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ An Internet request came for Lady Bird Johnson's lemon cake
recipe. Does anyone have that recipe?
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Long's husband's grandmother (following all of that?)
used to make a banana pie that was like a fruit pie _ not a cream
pie. Does anyone have such a recipe?
</P>
<P>
   _ Flo Clark would like to duplicate Walnetto candy at home. Can
anyone help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Sheila Childress would like to make a cappuccino mix similar
to the one sold at Wal-Mart under the Superior Coffee brand. The
flavor is French vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the ``Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.'' Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy,
``Star-Telegram,'' Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
