<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Hanover, N.Y.) _ Vice President Al Gore and former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, meeting in their first debate, a
CNN-televised town hall meeting at Dartmouth College. By CRAGG
HINES and BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY-ANALYSIS (Undated) _ In the first square-off of
their bid for the Democratic presidential nomination, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley are expected to
labor assiduously tonight to display dramatic differences between
themselves. That may be difficult to do. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Dubuque, Iowa) _ Republican presidential hopeful
George W. Bush visits a pregnancy crisis center in Iowa, a state
where the Texas governor has launched a series of radio and
television advertisements to shore up his bid for the party's
nomination. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SPENDING (Washington) _ Republican leaders in Congress
work to polish their plan for an across-the-board budget cut to
make it acceptable with the party's own members. Meanwhile, the
Republicans take credit for the $123 billion budget surplus from
last year. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   TERRORIST-ASSETS (Washington) _ Sens. Frank R. Lautenberg of New
Jersey and Connie Mack of Florida introduce a bill that would allow
victims of terrorism to sue the foreign governments responsible for
it and to use that country's financial assets in the United States
to pay any monetary awards. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ Senate and House Democratic leaders
urge Congress to pass legislation that would strengthen the federal
government's ability to prosecute hate crimes and would add new
protections for those victimized because of their sexual
orientation, disability or gender. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-RATHER (Jasper, Texas) _ CBS newsman Dan Rather has been
subpoenaed to testify in the trial of Shawn Berry, the third
defendant in the gruesome slaying of James Byrd Jr., a black man
who was dragged to death behind a pickup. Prosecutors want to know
what was edited out of Berry's only interview, which was televised
a few weeks ago on CBS. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   AMENDMENTS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Common Cause and senior
lawmakers bemoan the abundance of constitutional amendments on the
statewide ballot in Texas and urge a complete rewrite of the
document in 2001. Meanwhile, a lively debate is under way over
judicial pay and other thorny propositions among the 17 amendments
on next Tuesday's ballot. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A new state Senate committee
begins looking at projections for enrollment in Texas universities
and community colleges in the new century and talks about ways to
boost minority enrollment. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-YOUNG (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ San Francisco 49ers
quarterback Steve Young says he will not retire or go on a
season-ending injured reserve list because of his fourth concussion
in three seasons. He also maintained that the injury did not
preclude him from returning to the playing field later this season.
By JOHN CRUMPACKER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEQUILA-IMAGE (Amatitan, Mexico) _ Tequila is in the midst of a
radical image makeover. A growing fascination with Mexican food and
Latin culture, along with some crafty marketing by tequila makers,
is helping make it the fastest growing type of alcoholic spirit in
the United States. Tequila sales have increased 112 percent since
1985, according to the Distilled Spirits Council of the United
States. By GREG HASSELL. (Photo available on the NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   With: TEQUILA-TYPES
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Ironically, Rhode Island Sen.
John Chafee died just hours before Patrick Buchanan bade farewell
to the GOP with a verbal blast at the enlightened mainstream
Republicans that Chafee personified. No two Republicans could have
been further apart. Chafee understood that the world is round
rather than flat. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
