<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICS-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH TURNS DOWN MONEY TO HELP PAY FOR ANTI-GAY INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON and LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Catholic archdiocese of San Francisco has
turned down an offer from a private donor to cover the church's
contribution to support the statewide voter initiative that would
reinforce California's ban on gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   California's 12 Catholic dioceses have contributed more than
$310,000 to support the initiative, formally known as the
Protection of Marriage Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   After the San Francisco Archdiocese announced its $31,724
contribution to the campaign, a donor came forward offering an
anonymous contribution to cover that expense, archdiocesan
spokesman Maurice Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the archdiocese and the California Catholic
Conference, the public policy arm of the state's 28 Roman Catholic
bishops, found that state law would not allow the donor to remain
nameless, Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   Healy declined to identify the potential donor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a San Francisco priest has written Archbishop William
J. Levada objecting to the Roman Catholic hierarchy's financial and
political support of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rev. Zachary Shore of Most Holy Redeemer Catholic
Church read his letter to Levada at Sunday's 10 a.m. Mass,
parishioners gave him a thunderous standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Gay parishioners ``are hurt, they're frustrated, they're
angry,'' he said, describing his congregation's reaction to church
support of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, which will be on the ballot in March 2000, is
sponsored by state Sen. William J. ``Pete'' Knight, R-Palmdale,
whose gay son has publicly opposed the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Shore assured his gay parishioners that their offerings to
Sunday collections would stay in the parish and would not go to
support the initiative. He said his parish's only contribution to
the archdiocese comes through a special annual collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0179 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k BC-IRAN-$ADV31-COX     10-27 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBASSY ECHOES: IRAN SPLIT OVER AMERICAN RELATIONS
 &HT;    (EDs: Contains optional trim.)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With IRAN-REFORMER-$ADV31.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 31 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ When student revolutionaries stormed the U.S.
Embassy here 20 years ago this week, Hossein Sarbazi was only 1
year old.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is a product of their revolution _ with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   He serves in the Revolutionary Guard forces established by the
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. He won a national championship in
wrestling _ Iran's number one sport.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for a bus last week in front of the old embassy, now
housing a military school and the wrestling club, he discussed his
dream: To attend Georgetown University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that better relations between Iran and the United
States will someday allow his dream to come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they put an embassy here again,'' he said, showing a smile
beneath his Georgetown Hoyas ball cap, ``I assure you many young
people will come apply for visas.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the wooded embassy compound is still an emblem of two
countries that have not found common ground.
</P>
<P>
   The echoes of the embassy takeover, which turned into 14-month
hostage crisis, carry emotions and misconceptions that still
reverberate between the two nations. These days, as Iranians openly
and sometimes heatedly reassess the revolution, relations with the
United States are front-page news on an almost daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   The stubbornness of the impasse can be put in perspective this
way: During the last 20 years, the United States has opened an
embassy in Vietnam and Iran has traded official visits with its
former enemy in war, Iraq. But, Iran and the United States still
treat each other as foes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite U.S. oil companies' desire to start pumping in Iran
again, America maintains economic sanctions against Iran. And while
Iranians yearn for business with the world's biggest economy, Iran
continues to stoke anti-American sentiments in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy takeover shocked America. It became a deciding
factor in an election _ Ronald Reagan's defeat of then-President
Jimmy Carter. It showed that fundamentalist religion, Islam, had
re-emerged in world politics. Americans also realized that their
Cold War support of dictators carried a high price.
</P>
<P>
   But for Iranians, it was so much more.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Islamic revolution's Boston Tea Party and Battle of
Bunker Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Ayatollah Khomeini called it ``the Second Revolution.'' The
hostage takers became heroes. Their actions the text of college
curricula.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 years ago. These days, Iran is brimming with debate
about its future. Iranians seek to fit into the world community
without sacrificing its revolutionary identity.
</P>
<P>
   The debate pits the young, like Sarbazi, against the old, like
Mehdi Naeini, a 48-year-old owner of a crafts store across the
street from the old embassy. And America is at the heart of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the Americans who are making things tense,'' Naeini
said, ticking off a list offenses, most recently comments by U.S.
officials accusing Iran of supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Iranians, he blames the United States for the Iraqi
attack that lead to an eight-year war in the 1980s, killing
hundreds of thousands of Iranians. Murals of the martyrs are on
buildings throughout the country. In fact, the United States did
provide intelligence to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Naeini points to the embassy compound wall and notes that the
anti-American murals there were recently repainted.
</P>
<P>
   One reads, ``On that day (sic) U.S. would praise us we will
mourn.'' Another states, ``We will make America face a severe
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, between the hope of youth and the defiance of the
old guard, are many of the former hostage takers. Many are student
extremists-turned-moderates, who say relations with the United
States are desirable, as long as America treats Iran as an equal.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Ebrahim Asgharzadeh, was a leader of the students who
stormed the embassy and is now a 44-year-old Tehran city council
member who has been physically attacked for his moderate views.
</P>
<P>
   He does not regret the embassy takeover, but has invited former
hostages to return as guests to his country. America and Iran, he
said, do not have to sacrifice their identities to renew relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not necessary to forget the past to build a future,'' he
said. ``We have to accept realities and the future should be built
on facts.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   To him, there was no alternative to the events of Nov. 4, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years before, Carter visited Mohammad Reza Pahlavi _
the detested but U.S.-backed Shah of Iran _ and declared Iran ``an
island of stability.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later there was an upsurge of riots against the Shah.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations, street-fighting and murderous reprisals from the
Shah's troops resulted in the return from exile of respected cleric
Khomeini. The Shah fled in February. When Carter allowed him into
the United States for medical treatment, students took to the
streets again.
</P>
<P>
   They marched to the embassy, cut through the gate and
overwhelmed the small security contingent. They expected a siege of
just a few days. Surely, they mistakenly thought, the U.S. would
relinquish the Shah.
</P>
<P>
   But, U.S. officials reacted instead with economic sanctions and
the takeover turned into a stand-off that captured the Iranian
imagination. It provided an opportunity for Khomeini's
fundamentalists _ overshadowing revolutionaries seeking a secular
government _ to energize and unify their supporters around
opposition to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 52 American hostages were held for 444 days and
released the day Reagan took office. By then, it was branded into
the identity of the new Islamic Republic of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is part of the sacred tenets of the revolution,'' said
Iranian political scientist Hadi Semati. ``It is still seen as
current and is very hard to analyze objectively.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Iranians are doing a lot of analyzing these days.
</P>
<P>
   They have gone through the war with Iraq, experienced 20 years
of sacrifice and strict Islamic government.
</P>
<P>
   Though still widely revered, the charismatic Khomeini has been
dead for 10 years. More than half the country's 63 million people
were born after the revolution. They never knew the Shah or his
American patrons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Iranians shocked the world again. They voted 70 percent
to 30 percent to make underdog Ayatollah Mohammad Khatami
president. He promised economic progress and more democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But, the country's most powerful person remains Supreme Leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamani. He controls the army and courts.
</P>
<P>
   A sometimes-violent tug-of-war is underway and at times it seems
Iran has two governments. Reformers have opened hundreds of
newspapers and slightly loosened strict Muslim codes. Conservatives
have closed papers and even killed a few critics of religious rule.
</P>
<P>
   Amid it all, Iranians live firmly in the modern age. Many have
Internet access. They watch satellite dish broadcasts, though
dishes are technically illegal. The oil-driven economy has been
growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
   But, the population and unemployment are growing faster still
and people yearn for a prosperity many believe can only come with
the end of the U.S. trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   There have been tentative steps by both sides. Last year,
Khatami called for more cultural exchange and a ``dialogue of
civilizations.'' That was probably as far as he could go without
inflaming the powerful clerics.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton has praised Khatami and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright has acknowledged that Iran has
``grievances'' against the U.S. support of the Shah.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have long lists of demands. American officials call
on Iran to end its support of terrorist groups, drop its opposition
to the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, stop developing weapons
of mass destruction and improve its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, Iranians say that the U.S. Congress has sent
money to the Iranian opposition, a group responsible for
assassinations of Iranian officials. They argue that they are not
developing weapons of mass destruction and that U.S. officials do
not object to Israel's nuclear arsenal or Egypt's chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Iranians call for the United States to drop economic sanctions
and stop trying to discourage other countries from dealing with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   They also call on the United States to release billions of
dollars in Iranian assets and drop opposition to a proposed oil
pipeline through Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But, relations are still marked by missed or poorly sent
signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental problem in American policy is the fact that
they don't realize how their policies are perceived here,''
political scientist Semati said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, analysts expect progress to be slow. Iran has
parliamentary elections in February and the U.S. elections follow
in November. Candidates in neither country want to be seen as soft
on their nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also note, however, that America could use a friend
next to troubled Pakistan, anarchic Afghanistan and rebellious
former Soviet satellites. By comparison, Iran is peaceful and
appears to be moving toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Revolutionary Guard Sarbazi said he got hooked on the
Georgetown Hoyas while watching the school's basketball team on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 60 to 70 percent of Iranians want to have relations
with America,'' he said. ``I am for relations of all kinds _
political, economic.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he fears his position could get him in trouble, he
gives an answer that bodes well for democracy as well as relations
with America: ``I don't care. I believe what I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
