<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTER AND FASTER, BUT WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another generation of faster microprocessors is about to arrive
in the stores, just in time to spark a new wave of holiday
technology lust among the pocket-protector crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Faster chips are introduced every few months. We all know that
the hot new PC chip that is the champion of the silicon drag strip
today will in just a couple of years become the desktop equivalent
of the embarrassing old clunker that leaves oil stains in the
driveway. But as always, the most significant result of the
introduction of new chips is that they inevitably trigger a price
war, and that typically translates to cheaper yet better computers
for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though costs are rising for memory chips and other PC
components, this week's processor price wars between the Intel
Corporation and its main rival, Advanced Micro Devices, are
expected to offset most of those increases and keep PC prices
steady before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any PC sold today, even those costing less than $500,
have enough processing power to perform the basic computing tasks
that consumers ask them to do, like connecting to the Internet for
electronic mail and online shopping, playing simple games and
writing business plans for new Internet start-ups. Getting more
processing power for the same money is a welcome bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few more advanced applications, like 3-D graphics,
high-end computer games, professional graphics, rocket science,
software development, digital video editing, speech recognition and
downloading streams of bootlegged music files from the Internet
while doing the computer equivalent of standing on one foot and
balancing spinning plates on a stick, the faster the microprocessor
the better.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal to that audience, the Intel Corp. this week introduced
15 new and enhanced Pentium III microprocessors based on an
advanced production technology called Coppermine. Nine of the new
Coppermine Pentium III chips will be used in desktop computers,
with speeds ranging from 500 megahertz to 733 megahertz, or
millions of cycle per second. Computers built around these chips
are expected to cost from $1,200 to $2,500. Three chips will be
used in notebook computers, with speeds of 400, 450 and 500 MHz.
Three more, at speeds of 600, 667 and 700 MHz, are to be used in
powerful workstations and servers that consumers rarely see.
</P>
<P>
   Coppermine has nothing to do with the copper manufacturing
process developed by IBM as a superior replacement for aluminum in
microprocessors. Rather, it is Intel's code word for a new
.18-micron manufacturing process. A micron is a millionth of meter,
so .18 microns is exceptionally small. Earlier Pentium III and
Pentium II chips were made using a .25-micron process.
</P>
<P>
   By squeezing the Pentium III's 28 million transistors into less
space, the new Coppermine Pentium III chips are smaller, faster and
cooler. Faster is better for obvious reasons, and smaller chips not
only allow smaller and more stylish devices, but they also consume
less power, which means they do not get as hot. Smaller, cooler
chips that use less power are ideally suited for portable PC's.
</P>
<P>
   The new manufacturing process allows Intel to integrate the main
processing unit with a high-speed memory subsystem called a Level 2
cache, all on the same die. Until now, the L2 cache was on a
separate chip. The 256 kilobytes of full-speed, integrated cache on
the Coppermine chips improves their performance significantly,
Intel says, outperforming twice as much cache memory on a separate
chip.
</P>
<P>
   That's the easy part. Unfortunately, Intel made this a very
confusing introduction.
</P>
<P>
   After months of hype, Intel failed to deliver a new supporting
chip set, called the i820, that the company said was to have been
the underlying platform for getting the highest performance from
the new Coppermine processors. The i820 chip set is needed to allow
the new Pentium III to take advantage of a high-speed memory
subsystem called Rambus. The jury is still out on the value of the
Rambus technology for consumers. Rambus memory modules are much
faster, but also much more expensive, than current memory
technologies. Intel now says the i820 chip set will be sent to PC
makers before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the confusion, some of the new chips work only with a
slower, 100-MHz system bus _ the data path between the processor,
the memory and other system components _ while others work only
with a faster, 133-MHz bus. Some work with either.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some of the new chips appear to compete with earlier
Pentium III chips at the same clock speed. Some consumers will need
help telling them apart without opening the computer case.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect is that there is a lot of confusion about the new
chips, even among industry analysts with advanced engineering
degrees. Consumers who do not need to buy a new PC right away may
want to wait until the smoke clears. High-end-PC users, including
game fanatics, may want to wait until computers arrive with the
i820 chip set, which also includes support for a new graphics
standard called AGP 4X.
</P>
<P>
   Technological esoterica aside, the Coppermine chips will allow
Intel-based machines to keep up with computers based on the
exceptionally fast Athlon processor from Advanced Micro Devices, at
700-MHz the current speed champ and darling of the 3-D game
community.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered the Salieri to Intel's Mozart, AMD makes
microprocessors that run Windows software just as well as Intel's
chips do, but at lower cost. AMD has vowed to keep prices 25
percent below Intel's for comparable chips.
</P>
<P>
   AMD plans to move to the .18-micron process next year. Both
Intel and AMD have publically demonstrated 800-MHz chips, and both
have said they will push speeds beyond 1 gigahertz by the end of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Why does this matter?
</P>
<P>
   Faster chips must be evaluated in three distinct ways. One, do
they allow me to do interesting new things that I could not do
before? In some cases, yes, but remember that it takes time for
software developers to take advantage of the faster chips, and by
the time they do, prices typically are lower.
</P>
<P>
   Two, is it worth spending more now for the fastest PC chip?
Buying the fastest processor available may prolong the useful life
of the computer, but not by that much. Other important PC
components evolve as well. In terms of value, it often makes more
sense to buy a lesser computer and to plan to replace it sooner.
</P>
<P>
   And three, will a faster chip save me at least four minutes a
day? There are 1,440 minutes in a day, but there is something
magical about 4-minute chunks of time. According to ``Faster,'' a
new book by James Gleick, Americans spend an average of four
minutes every day just booting up and shutting down a Microsoft
Windows-based personal computer. Americans spend an average of four
minutes a day filling out government paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans yearn for more time to fill out government forms
or to watch Windows booting. But I would be willing to spend the
money on a new computer if it allowed me to devote more time to
more interesting pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet users spend much more than four minutes a day
waiting for their computers to retrieve electronic mail, download
graphics and audio files, and display Web pages. Investing in a
cable or DSL connection would in theory have a more profound impact
on their romantic lives than getting a faster processor.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the Internet was faster and less
frustrating to use, people might spend more time in front of the
computer screen than they probably should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
