<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0182 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-KIDS-CREATE-NYT &LR;      10-27 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-CREATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHETTING A CHILD'S IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Product notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagynasium's opening montage of fish, chairs, kitchen
appliances and other mundane objects floating through space gives
the impression that this isn't just another drawing program for
bored children. The program, developed with Robert Redford's
Sundance Institute, has a much higher sense of purpose _ it wants
to provide an expansive workout area for creative young minds to
refine their storytelling, music and art skills.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for children 7 to 12, Imagynasium is an engaging
program than pushes them to think in both linear and nonlinear ways
by creating projects on screen and off.
</P>
<P>
   After starting the program, the player is whisked to the
Skyscape screen, a futuristic, rainbow-hued urban sprawl. The names
of the various Imagynasium areas pop up as the cursor moves around
the city, and a quick click takes the user right to the desired
place.
</P>
<P>
   The program has three main sections: Downtown, the Jingle Jungle
and the Curio Shop. Little candy-colored space aliens named Mondo,
Frida, Roxie, Riff and Spike guide the child through the program,
serving as hosts in the different areas and providing instructions.
The child is also given an on-screen box called a collector to use
during the session. Objects found throughout the program, like
pictures of telephones or bison, can be dragged into the collector
for use in the creative areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Downtown, children can make festive collages by combining
objects, text and backgrounds onto a canvas. Separate items in the
collage can also be given motions and sounds through the program's
controls, and the work can be viewed full size on the computer
screen with one click. The art can also be saved and printed out
for framing or prominent placement on the family's refrigerator.
(This section of the program was particularly exciting for someone
who had to make collages in the early 1970s with nothing but safety
scissors, paste and old copies of Newsweek _ thus producing far too
many sticky masterpieces starring Henry Kissinger, Olga Korbut and
the bird from the Old Crow whisky ads.)
</P>
<P>
   The Jingle Jungle is the music area of Imagynasium. A blue
soundboard sits in the middle of the screen, surrounded by dozens
of icons like bugs and flowers that represent different sounds. The
child can listen to the sounds, everything from harmonica wails to
soprano vocal flourishes, by clicking on them. The sounds can be
arranged to make a soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The soundboard itself is divided by a grid, allowing four
different sounds to play simultaneously. Background rhythm tracks
are represented by creatures called ``backbeat worms'' (a great
name for a rock band, by the way) and play along with the other
sounds the child has selected.
</P>
<P>
   The story-creation place in the program is the Curio Shop. Using
a circular, multipage canvas, children can create their own visual
narratives by dragging and dropping stock characters, backgrounds,
sound effects and music onto a palette. The user can write text to
go with the picture and add it to a page. The resulting opus can be
read like a storybook or viewed like a movie.
</P>
<P>
   For children who need help deciding what to do next, each
section of Imagynasium comes with its own Brain Booster area that
provides suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Imagynasium has a distinctive look _ sort of Salvador Dali
crossed with Monty Python _ that engages the child's visual
faculties right off the bat. The program's instructions, easily
found by pressing the F1 key, are not always obvious on screen.
That encourages the user to wander freely, pointing and clicking on
things to see what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the thought and effort that has been put into
Imagynasium, it is still not a substitute for spending time with
paint and crayons. A character in the program offers perhaps the
best advice of all: ``This is a great place to come and be
creative. But you don't have to stop when you go back to the real
world.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   IMAGYNASIUM
</P>
<P>
   (South Peak Interactive; $19.95; Windows 95 and 98.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
