u a BC-CIR-HALLOWEEN-NYT &LR;      10-27 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HALLOWEEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE DARK CORNERS OF THE WEB: SITES FOR HORROR AND THE OCCULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Halloween is a holiday with ancient roots that span many
cultures. The modern observance is thought to be a mixture of
influences from the Celtic festival of Samhain, Pomona Day in
ancient Rome and the Christian holidays of All Saints and All Souls
Days. In tune with its varied ancestry, Halloween sites on the Web
range from serious to silly.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a quick supply of Halloween information,
go to the obvious address, www.halloween.com. A hefty collection of
links resides there, and you can find everything virtual from
haunted houses to ghost stories and Halloween jokes. Information
about witches, both fictional and modern Wiccan, abounds. A link to
an electronic tour of Arlington National Cemetery in Virginia is
there as well, for those who want a historical digression.
</P>
<P>
   Another plentiful source of spooky lore is the Halloween on the
Net page (www.holidays.net/halloween). In addition to a virtual
pumpkin patch to tromp through, the site has a section devoted to
Los Dias de los Muertos _ the Day of the Dead, a traditional
Mexican holiday. It is celebrated Oct. 31 through Nov. 2 to honor
one's ancestors. Although a holiday with the name Day of the Dead
may sound a bit morbid, it is actually a rather joyful time of
remembrance in Mexico, with parades and family gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween seems to be a natural time to look up the writer J.K.
Rowlings' ubiquitous Harry Potter, with his adventures and tales of
adolescent witches and wizards. In addition to starring in three
best-sellers, the young wizard-in-training has his own official
home on the Internet www.scholastic.com/harrypotter, and the site
has a few features that do more than sell the books. Children can
play trivia games and download a Harry Potter screen saver (
available for both Windows and Macintosh). The site also contains
discussion guides and a reading circle where readers can post
comments and share their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Scary.com (www.scary.com) is a horror-themed Web site that
offers plenty of G-rated thrills and chills. A character named
Shriek the Bat (who even has his own playable theme song) leads
children through the fully interactive site, which includes a jam
session by a mummy band and a point-and-click haunted house. The
site features original Web cartoons _ one of which is ``Dead Run,''
the tale of a boy who really, really wants to be a vampire. The
cartoons are created by Spunky Productions, which also has
non-Halloween-themed shows at its main site, www.spunkytown.com.
The cartoons are created in Macromedia's Flash program and new
episodes appear regularly. Children can click on a character in
midshow to get more information and can e-mail jokes from the
program to friends. And there is a bonus for parents: the Web
cartoons can be watched at any time of year.
</P>
<P>
   And for those of you too shy _ or too cool _ to scream on the
big night, www.americangreetings.com is offering free electronic
Halloween greetings that will send the screams of seven
celebrities, including Gillian Anderson from The X-Files, _ to the
e-mail boxes of your friends and family. For every scream sent,
American Greetings says it will send make a 10-cent donation to the
Starlight Children's Foundation, a non-profit group dedicated to
helping children with serious illnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
