<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOMAIN OF ONE'S OWN 
</HEADLINE>
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently purchased a domain name from Network Solutions and
was under the impression that it cost only $29. A month later, I
got a bill for $70 for a registration fee. Is this a legitimate
charge, or am I being fleeced?
</P>
<P>
   A. The fee on your bill is the price that Network Solutions
charges for the initial registration of a domain name. The standard
price is $70 for the first two years, then $35 a year after that.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions is a private company designated by the United
States government to handle domain-name registrations; it also
administers the master database for domains.
</P>
<P>
   The government has recently approved a few other companies, like
Register.com (www.register.com), to begin selling domain names as
well. There are some companies that offer to register a domain name
with Network Solutions for a small fee, but that often does not
include the actual Network Solutions fee.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing a domain name _ the unique part of a Web address,
like ``banjo.com'' _ is a fairly simple procedure that you can do
yourself on Network Solution's home page
(www.networksolutions.com). The site will let you check for
existing versions of the name you want, and if your choice is not
already taken, you can sign up for it right there.
</P>
<P>
   The name can have a maximum of 26 characters, including the
three-letter suffix. In addition to the .com address, there is an
option to acquire the .net and .org suffixes for your desired
domain name if they are available.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
