<HEADLINE>
TYPES OF TEQUILA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Anejo) 
(For release Sunday, Oct. 31) 
 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Blanco or silver: Clear, unaged tequila that comes fresh from
the still. It has a straightforward agave flavor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gold: often flavored with caramel, and therefore not 100
percent agave, gold tequilas are popular for shooters and
margaritas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reposado (rested): Oak aging for less than a year mellows the
flavor. Excellent for sipping or mixed drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anejo (aged): aged at least a year in oak barrels, fine anejos
are sipped like premium cognacs. Some aficionados consider it a sin
to use this in any kind of mixed drink.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
