<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UP-CLOSE, PERSONAL LOOK AT AIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It begins, appropriately, with a gray shot of a graveyard. Then
the camera pans to a little girl twirling in the wind, and you're
left with a sick feeling in the pit of your stomach.
</P>
<P>
   This is where mothers and fathers with AIDS end up. They die.
Sometimes their children die, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it has the potential to look like is decimated
communities, decimated economies, decimated work forces, decimated
families,'' a woman with flowing dreadlocks is saying now about the
devastating effect of AIDS in the African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   This is the result. This is why we shouldn't let our guard down,
and why we should pay attention to AIDS. It's why it's important to
be our sister's keeper. Our brother's, too.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a national awareness and outreach campaign announced
last week by the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, or NAACP, the film suggests as much.
</P>
<P>
   And then you're eye to eye with a sweet-faced little girl, and
she's telling you what you already knew, but what she just learned
about the deadly virus: ``I knew you could catch it, but I just
thought it would never come this close to home.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how AIDS is. It's personal. And still very deadly.
</P>
<P>
   To date, an estimated 6 million women worldwide have died from
AIDS. And although treatment has progressed, there is no cure.
There are measures women can take, however, to prevent being
infected. This is the other message the NAACP wants to convey.
</P>
<P>
   The civil-rights organization, along with DuPont Pharmaceuticals
and AT&AMP;T Broadband &AMP; Internet Services, began distributing
education films last week focusing on HIV prevention, detection,
treatment and access to care.
</P>
<P>
   The three films will be showcased over AT&AMP;T and other cable
television systems, including Cablevision, Cox and Time Warner.
They will also be made available at AIDS service organizations and
the NAACP's 2,200 branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film project is an important step for the NAACP and our
continued commitment to fighting this health epidemic,'' Kweisi
Mfume, president and chief executive officer of the NAACP, said in
a news release. ``With the escalation of HIV/AIDS in the
African-American community, we are taking the initiative to deal
with what has become a national health crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the film, poet Maya Angelou put it this way:
``It really is a war against not just the virus, but it is a war
against ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   This brings to mind one of the film's Deborah Fountaine moments.
Fountaine is an AIDS outreach coordinator in Atlanta. Women tell
her all the time, she said, that the epidemic ``doesn't affect me;
I don't have to worry about that, I have been with my man for five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   What she tells them is that they have no idea who else he has
been with during those five years.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, we don't hear the men's stories. Not in this
film. But you know this is their story, too. According to the
national Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta,
AIDS is the leading cause of death among African-Americans ages
25-44. That's men and women. In addition, blacks account for 45
percent of new reported AIDS cases, although we make up only 13
percent of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Mika Washington, Arlene Clark, Evelyne Zachary and Michele Lopez
were monogamous. Their men weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you are among those who say that those stories have
nothing to do with you. That's what these women believed, too. They
found out they were wrong, and the loss and mourning began long
before they were infected.
</P>
<P>
   This is what AIDS is like. It's personal, and we had better
start treating it that way.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Send E-mail to gbs(at)startext.net. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
