<SLUG> BC-WEEKEND-RETREAT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOTEL OF ONE'S OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2-4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELAWARE, N.J. _ The little notice, thumbtacked to the peeling
wallpaper, is easy to miss. In spindly script, oxidized by time, it
reads: ``Please don't throw hair, papers or anything else in the
slopbucket.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the charms of a country hotel, circa 1900.
</P>
<P>
   When Hal Bromm, a TriBeCa gallery owner, and Doneley Meris, a
bereavement therapist, bought the old yellow clapboard Delawanna
Hotel here as a weekend retreat for themselves and their friends,
there were 23 bedrooms. And lest any of those friends felt left
out, there was a stone guest house on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep stopping in to ask if this is a bed and breakfast,
and how much does it cost a night,'' said Bromm, a tall man with
dark curly hair, managing to sound both bemused and ever so
slightly annoyed. ``We tell them it's just for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, they've ripped out walls, stripped woodwork and painted,
painted, painted: unusual colors, like a spice-laden pumpkin-pie
yellow, a frosty turquoise and the deep, deep green of ivy on a
shady wall. They've transformed the downstairs into elegant salons
and have combined some second-floor chambers into big bedrooms
ready for their 15 pages of design-magazine fame. They just
finished turning a separate two-bedroom apartment into a home
office, as Bromm spends less and less time in TriBeCa. Along the
way, they created collections: globes, stuffed birds and antique
vacuum cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   They started with 23 bedrooms. Now they're down to just 20.
</P>
<P>
   But the third floor is still untamed. It's reminiscent of ``The
Shining'': all the doors leading off a skinny, dark hotel corridor.
And those bedrooms _ rooming-house size, 8 by 13 feet, each with a
tall four-paned window, each with its original Easter-egg-colored
paint, which, appropriately, has cracks running from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bromm owns an art gallery the house is stuffed with
canvases hung on all the walls (even in the unused and unheated
third-floor bedrooms). Others fill a couple of unused rooms like
bubble-wrapped mummies.
</P>
<P>
   On the third floor, there's a room furnished with the work of
Russell Sharon, an artist represented by Bromm: wavy pieces of red,
yellow, green and blue wood create a headboard. Another assemblage
turns out to be a table and chairs. The room won't be used in
winter: a collection of air-conditioners (nonvintage) are arrayed
on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Bromm and Meris were reluctantly surrendering to
the autumn winds. The 120-foot-long wooden porch, which for half
the year is bedecked with vintage flags, was going into
hibernation. The 1920s ice cream parlor chairs were being stacked
and taken up to a bedroom. The white wicker planters followed. The
McCoy pottery planters in asparagus green and maize yellow were
emptied and arrayed on a wooden side table with turned legs, its
white paint just beginning to flake off. The plank floor, painted
the black-green of your mother's best Windsor chair, was swept and
will be repainted in the spring, whether it needs it or not.
</P>
<P>
   As they carried furniture, the screech of a power tool ripped
the air. A carpenter was taking off siding before blowing cellulose
insulation into the walls of one wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the endless list of invisible work that people
seldom appreciate,'' Bromm said. ``Traditionally, people think of
paper, floor finishing and colors. But a lot of very serious and
important work needs to happen first. The stuff that when people
come over for a drink on your porch, they don't say, `Ooh, look at
that great electrical outlet under the plant stand.'''
</P>
<P>
   Meris turned up the Brazilian music on the stereo. ``We look at
it as a 20-year project,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the two men were scouring Connecticut,
upstate New York and all of New Jersey for a weekend house that
needed work. One Sunday, they saw an advertisement for an old barn
in the village of Delaware, in the mountains a few miles from the
Delaware Water Gap, an hour and a half drive from TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   They fell in love with the barn but just missed it. It had been
sold to an artist, who has since become a friend. Months later,
they heard about the hotel, built as a two-story private house in
the Civil War era and enlarged to become a hotel at the turn of the
century, when the railroad was extended to this village and summer
visitors started arriving.
</P>
<P>
   When they first saw the hotel, the porch was caving in. A leak
poured into the entrance foyer. The real estate agent told them on
the telephone that they'd love the guest cottage but that they'd
probably have to tear down the old hotel. But there were six and a
half acres on the house side of the road, three and a half (and a
stream) on the other side. They ended up paying less than $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   That was nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, they have done a lot of the work themselves, guided
by a philosophy of choosing their battles, or knowing when to let
things alone.
</P>
<P>
   They have fixed up the house in dribs and drabs. For instance,
they bought a wonderful wood-grain pantry cupboard at a house
auction in Hope, N.J., about five miles away, for $150. But they
say they have no idea how much they've spent all together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've restored one or two rooms a year, on average,'' said
Meris, a full-time bereavement counselor at the Lesbian and Gay
Community Services Center in Greenwich Village. ``But it took four
years to do the dining room.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years into the process, they still want to put two
bathrooms on the third floor (where there are now none). They also
think it would be fun to use the old sepia photographs the past
owners gave them to restore all the small bedrooms to their
turn-of-the-century charm, when the Delawanna was a summer hotel.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate they're going, they figure it will take 11 years
more.
</P>
<P>
   And then it will be time to start renovating again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
