<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-TEQUILA-IMAGE-ART-2TA     10-27 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEQUILA-IMAGE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV31-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEQUILA GETS ITS SHOT: NEW DRIVE TO PROMOTE QUALITY LIQUOR SEEMS TO
BE WORKING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 31) 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent marks needed over third a in Amatitan, over i in
Martinez, o in Limon and e in Jose; tilde needed over n in pina.) 
 
By GREG HASSELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMATITAN, Mexico _ When Lucinda Hutson started work on a book
celebrating fine tequila, many of her friends were astonished that
she would devote herself to something they considered to be little
more than Mexican moonshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, tequila was not regarded as a good thing.
People called it To-Kill-Ya,'' recalled Hutson, an Austin, Texas,
author whose book ``Tequila! Cooking with the Spirit of Mexico''
was published in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas and throughout much of the United States, tequila was
seen as little more than a raw and powerful libation. The brave
souls who licked salt, slammed back a shot and bit through a lime
wedge expected to get drunk that night _ and be hung over the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that tequila is too strong and harmful, and
that it makes you falling-down drunk. They say it was invented for
thieves and murderers,'' Enrique Martinez Limon facetiously wrote
in his book, ``Tequila.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, tequila is in the midst of a radical image makeover.
Aficionados are sipping it from snifters, slowly savoring its
essence as if it were a cognac or brandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started carrying Herradura Suprema at Taco Milagro. It
costs $200 a bottle, and we are selling it for $35 per shot,'' said
Susan Bennett, director of restaurant development at Augusta Foods,
the group that includes Houston eateries Cafe Annie, Cafe Express
and Taco Milagro. ``And it's selling. It's amazing. People don't
even flinch.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing fascination with Mexican food and Latin culture, along
with some crafty marketing by tequila makers, is helping make it
the fastest growing type of alcoholic spirit in the United States.
Tequila is cashing in on the same, sudden elevation in status that
sent nouveau connoisseurs flocking to single-malt scotches and
Cuban cigars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRADITIONAL DRINK &QL; 
FROM HEART OF JALISCO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tequila is rather long in the tooth to suddenly find itself at
the center of a fashionable trend.
</P>
<P>
   People in Mexico have been producing it for at least 380 years,
and the recipe for making tequila is as simple as it is ancient. In
its purest and best form, it is nothing more or less than the
distilled essence of the blue agave plant, which grows abundantly
in the highlands of Jalisco, a state on the Pacific side of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   By Mexican law and international agreement, all tequila comes
from Mexico. About 98 percent of it is made in Jalisco, especially
in the little villages of Tequila, Amatitan and Arandas. On the
winding roads that connect these villages, field after field is
bristling with rows of agave that shimmer with a blue-green light.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this part of the world, tequila is a drink. It also is a
town, and it is a mountain,'' said Juan Pablo Castro, the Tequila
Herradura representative responsible for U.S. exports. ``Tequila is
an attitude. It is a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the Tequilan volcano, workers known as
``jimadores'' harvest agaves by hand, using a razor-sharp tool
called a ``coa.'' In less than two minutes, a skilled ``jimador''
can dig the agave out of the ground and shave off the spiky leaves
until nothing is left but the pineapple-shaped heart, called the
``pina.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``pina'' is cooked _ right out of the oven, it tastes like a
sweet potato spiked with a mild tequila _ and shredded so the juice
can be extracted. Each ``pina'' yields about three liters of raw
juice, which is fermented and then distilled. About 70 percent of
the fermented liquid is lost in the distillation process.
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive tequilas are aged in oak barrels, a process
that gives it a golden color that gradually deepens with time. The
aging process means another 12 percent to 15 percent of the liquid
is lost to evaporation, a sacrifice that is poetically known among
producers as the ``angel's share.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why there are so many problems in the world _
tequila-drunk angels,'' Houston chef Robert Del Grande quipped
while on a tour of the Tequila Herradura distillery in the heart of
Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
   The angels certainly have had a rapidly increasing supply of
vapor to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. tequila sales have increased 112 percent since 1985,
according to the Distilled Spirits Council of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   To judge just how fashionable tequila has become, consider that
rocker Sammy Hagar has come up with his own brand, called Cabo
Wabo. He and his band, the Waboritas, flog the drink by making
promotional appearances and singing songs such as ``Mas Tequila.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of tequila has not been lost on the giant
brewing company Anheuser-Busch, which is churning out a new beer
called Tequiza. Made with tequila and lime flavoring, Tequiza is
trying to squeeze a little of tequila's good fortune out for
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The most dynamic growth in the tequila category is in the high
end of the market, where the price per bottle hovers in the $30-$50
range. Sales of El Tesoro and Chinaco brands _ two highly regarded
brands generally placed among the first rank of tequilas _ have
increased 50 percent a year for the past three years. Sales of
Tequila Herradura's brands have grown 40 percent to 60 percent
during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 50 percent growth of not much is still not much,''
cautioned Robert Denton, the American importer for the El Tesoro
and Chinaco brands and one of the pioneers in promoting top-shelf
tequila in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Denton figures the entire category of super-premium tequilas _
those made of 100 percent agave _ sell about 100,000 cases a year
in the United States. That works out to be about 1.2 million
bottles, or less than 300,000 gallons. By contrast, total tequila
sales in the United States hit 15.7 million gallons last year.
</P>
<P>
   The big train pulling the bulk of tequila sales is still the
margarita, named by the readers of Gourmet magazine as the most
popular cocktail in the United States. A great deal of the tequila
going into margaritas is far from the best stuff and is rarely made
with 100 percent agave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MAKING PRODUCT WITH CARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexican law requires tequila be at least 51 percent blue agave,
but the rest can be lesser ingredients such as cane sugar. Cuervo
Gold, the best-selling tequila in the United States, is not 100
percent agave. The golden color is the result of caramel coloring.
</P>
<P>
   One of the brands that never strayed from making tequila out of
100 percent agave is Tequila Herradura, which has been in
continuous production since 1870. Its owners, the Romo family, have
been in the vanguard of those promoting tequila as being on par
with the best spirits made anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to get away from the idea of licking salt,
throwing back a shot of tequila, biting the lime and then throwing
up later,'' said Mitch Murray, the regional representative for
Sazerac Co., which imports Herradura into the United States. ``We
are trying to uplift the image of tequila. It is something to
savor.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Herradura's methods is its ``Embassy Program.'' The
distiller is selecting 250 restaurants nationwide with which to
form long-term marketing relationships. As part of that
relationship, Herradura takes the restaurateurs on an extensive
tour of the company's operations in Amatitan. They go to great
pains to show details, such as how all of the agaves used by
Herradura are grown on the family's 10,000-acre estate and are
harvested only after they reach full maturity of eight to 10 years.
It shows how the ``pina's'' are slow-cooked in big clay ovens for
24 hours and cooled for 24 more, not zapped in industrial
pressure-cookers that are the distiller's equivalent of a
microwave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to move forward the education process, and we want to
do it on a one-on-one basis,'' Murray said, while standing in a
courtyard of the Romo family hacienda that is adjacent to the
company distillery. ``We couldn't convey with billboards what this
family believes.''
</P>
<P>
   The distillery believes restaurant owners are the ones who help
define the culinary standards for a city. It hopes the ``embassy''
restaurant will extol the virtues of fine tequila, especially
Herradura.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word-of-mouth recommendations from the right people will do
more for us than all the billboards in the world,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the distillery tours in Mexico, after all of the
participants were well-stoked on tequila and rich Mexican food,
Murray raised a glass and jokingly announced the terms of their
marketing partnership: ``We are married now. There is no divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRINGING IT ACROSS THE BORDER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herradura has been available in the United States since the
1960s, when Hollywood stars Bing Crosby and Phil Harris secured the
rights to import it to America. However, until recently, it was
only marginally successful here. Some observers say the first real
shots in the ``revolution'' of promoting pure tequila were fired in
1983, when U.S. businessman Robert Denton started importing
Chinaco, a gourmet brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first to battle for the truth about tequila,''
Denton said from his office in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Denton would pour the tequila for bar owners, trying to convince
them it was the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They liked it, but they said it wouldn't sell because it was
way too smooth,'' he said. ``We heard a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Denton persisted with Chinaco and El Tesoro, tequilas
that are made by distilleries adhering to the old methods and old
standards. Denton gradually was able to build a core following,
especially among those in the film and music industries on the West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Denton introduced these renegade tequilas made of 100
percent agave, and that's what started this whole trend,'' Hutson
said. ``El Tesoro is an exquisite example of the lost art of
tequila tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutson believes key factors in the growing taste for tequila
include the ``incredible popularity'' of Mexican and Southwestern
food, increased tourism to Mexico, and the distinctiveness of
``tequila's bright and lively flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rydman, president of Spec's Liquor Warehouse in Houston,
sees the trend as the logical extension of current drinking habits.
By and large, people are drinking less, but they are drinking
better. They have explored the rarefied realms of single-malt
scotches and boutique bourbons and are now moving on to tequila as
a new frontier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FINER BRANDS STANDING OUT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the increased recognition and affection surrounding it,
this would seem to be a golden age for tequila producers. However,
the runaway popularity of tequila is threatening some producers
with a day of reckoning. Because it takes eight to 10 years for an
agave to fully mature, production cannot be easily or rapidly
altered to match changing demand. As a result, there is an agave
shortage brewing in Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I sold my agaves for 70 centavos per kilo,'' said
Jose Camarena, who owns four farms near the town of Arandas. ``This
year, I will sell my agave for 5 pesos per kilo.''
</P>
<P>
   With the current exchange rate, last year's price works out to
be about 7 cents per kilo, while this year's price is around 50
cents per kilo.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the wild run-up in prices, Camarena is not sure he
wants to plant more agave. Prices could slump before they reach
maturity sometime in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 70 centavos, we weren't making any money. We barely broke
even,'' said Camarena, who also owns the Arandas chain of taquerias
in Houston. ``The ones who have been making all the money have been
the distilleries.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to the agave shortage, some distilleries are pulling their
cheapest stuff out of the marketplace, conserving their agaves to
make tequila with better profit margins. Prices for most tequila
brands haven't jumped at the U.S. retail level, but they might,
especially for tequilas made by businesses that buy bulk agave on
the open market. Those that grow their own agave supplies will feel
less pressure to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, even raising prices won't be enough to save some
operators. Several distilleries in Mexico have closed in recent
months because of the agave shortage, and it seems likely more will
be forced to shut their doors in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are only about 50 tequila distilleries in all of
Mexico, some makers are hired to churn out a variety of different
brands. As a result, there are several hundred brands of tequila on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these brands are going to disappear. They have to,''
Denton said. ``What will be left will be the established
distilleries and the established brands.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be just fine with Denton and some others, who aren't
entirely comfortable with some of the faddish aspects of the
tequila revolution. They wouldn't miss some of the goofy bottles,
such as the one shaped like a worm, which is ironic since a worm is
sometimes placed in a bottle of mescal, not tequila. And they
wouldn't miss some of the marketing hype, such as the newcomer
Porfidio brand that has concocted a fictional history tracing its
heritage back to Don Ponciano Porfidio, a man who never existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we'll go back to the basic, traditional core,''
Houston chef Del Grande said. ``There will be a falling out, but I
think there has been an irreversible change of people appreciating
fine tequila. That will not go away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
