u a BC-CRASH-CONTRACTORS28-S     10-27 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-CONTRACTORS28-SHORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FALLING FROM THE SKY: Liability protections shield the military
and contractors in crashes
 &HT;    
 &HT;    This is part of a six-day series from the Dayton Daily News on
the safety of military aircraft, the result of an 18-month
investigation and study of databases of incidents from the
military's safety centers. The series is available for use starting
Sunday, Oct. 24, through Friday, Oct. 29.
 &HT;    Photos and graphics are moving from the New York Times News
Service.
 &HT;    Stories are moving on this schedule:
 &HT;    Moved Friday for Sunday, Oct. 24: CRASH-MAIN, CRASH-SC,
CRASH-HOW.
 &HT;    Moved Friday for Monday, Oct. 25: CRASH-METAL.
 &HT;    Moving Monday for Tuesday, Oct. 26: CRASH-MAINTENANCE,
CRASH-TIMMER.
 &HT;    Moving Tuesday for Wednesday, Oct. 27: CRASH-COUNT,
CRASH-BUTTON.
 &HT;    Moving Wednesday for Thursday, Oct. 28: CRASH-CONTRACTORS.
 &HT;    Moving Thursday for Friday, Oct. 29: CRASH-KNIGHTS,
CRASH-MCNALLY.
 &HT;    Starred files will move in long and short versions.
 &HT;    The first day's installment is also available as a CoxNet Focus
page at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    If you have questions, please contact CoxNet at 404-526-5456.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Russell Carollo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When Navy Capt. Henry M. Kleeman shot down a
Libyan fighter during a dispute over international waters between
the United States and Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi in 1981, he
became a military superstar.
</P>
<P>
   His death four years later made him a different kind of
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Kleeman died Dec. 3, 1985, in an F-18 crash at Miramar Naval Air
Station, Calif. The plane crashed after the right main landing gear
failed, causing the tip of the right wing to hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy had known about problems with landing gear in the F-18
for at least three years. Kleeman's widow, Carol, left with four
children to raise on her own, sued the company that made the plane,
McDonnell Douglas Corp. Though she lost the case, her legal battle
is required reading for legal scholars and a small, specialized
group of plaintiffs' attorneys because her case helped expand a
legal doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   That doctrine, called the government-contractor defense, created
an exception to one of the most important tenets of American law:
the right to hold someone accountable in a civil court for
negligence causing injury or death. The defense, created in the
1980s, protects private companies _ including large aircraft
manufacturers _ from lawsuits for deaths and injuries caused by
their products.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known how much the threat of lawsuit promotes safety in
civilian aviation, but experts say it plays some role.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have plaintiffs' lawyers running all over the country:
self-appointed safety officers saying this product is designed
badly or that product is designed badly,'' said San Antonio
attorney Ron Sprague, who defends major airlines and aircraft
manufacturers in lawsuits over aviation accidents. ``For better or
for worse, their input gets heard by the manufacturer. If they're
right, quite often a product is changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The government contractor defense closed a giant window of
liability for the aerospace companies that manufacture military
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies began facing more lawsuits after a U.S.
Supreme Court doctrine in 1950 barred lawsuits against the
government for harm caused to active-duty military personnel.
Unable to sue the services, victims of military aviation accidents
and their families instead sued civilian companies that made the
aircraft, serviced them or had other related contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The companies began seeking protection, arguing that they
shouldn't be held responsible for products built to government
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kleeman case, Navy records show the service partially
blamed Kleeman for the crash but acknowledged that the primary
cause was the right main landing gear. ``Similar failures have
occurred in this type aircraft over the past several years,'' the
records say.
</P>
<P>
   Those words could have convinced a jury to award millions to a
plaintiff in a civilian aviation case, but Kleeman's case was
dismissed before trial. Years later, attorneys representing
aircraft companies still cite the decision when trying to have
lawsuits thrown out of court.
</P>
<P>
   The case that ultimately established the defense came in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Corps Lt. David A. Boyle died April 27, 1983, after he
drowned when his CH-53 helicopter crashed and sank into the ocean
off the coast of Virginia. His father sued the Sikorsky Division of
United Technologies Corp., which built the helicopter, alleging the
company improperly repaired a part that caused the crash. The
lawsuit also blamed the helicopter's design because the co-pilot
emergency escape hatch opened out instead of in, making it
difficult to open under water.
</P>
<P>
   A jury awarded Boyle's father $725,000. An appeals court
reversed that ruling, and on April 27, 1988, the U.S. Supreme Court
ruled 5-4 in favor of Sikorsky.
</P>
<P>
   The decision in the Boyle case did something nearly unheard of
in the American legal system: It prevented private citizens from
suing private companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contractor may invoke the defense in suits brought not
only by military personnel like Lt. Boyle, or government employees,
but by anyone ... including, for example, the children who might
have died had respondent's helicopter crashed on the beach,''
Justice William J. Brennan Jr. wrote in a dissenting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had respondent designed such a death trap for a commercial
firm, Lt. Boyle's family could sue under Virginia tort law and be
compensated for his tragic and unnecessary death.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan also argued that many government contracts are no more
than rubber stamps because the manufacturer has a heavy hand in
writing the specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The government contractor defense created another irony: When
civilians are killed and injured, the federal government can be
forced to pay while private companies can be protected by the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Emory's wife, Rose, a civilian, was killed in 1992 when
an F-18 Hornet crashed into her pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Emory collected $800,000 from the federal government, but his
lawsuit against McDonnell Douglas was thrown out of court before
trial because of the contractor defense.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, 1992, three days before Rose Emory's 28th birthday,
she was driving a pickup truck at the Patuxent River Naval Air
Station, Md., where she worked for a civilian company testing the
water quality on the base. She had just tested water near an
ammunition dump when the jet, weighing nearly as much as five
African elephants, fell directly on the cab of the pickup she was
driving, turning the truck and the plane into burned rubble. The
pilot and co-pilot ejected and survived.
</P>
<P>
   The F-18 had arrived at Patuxent River only two months earlier.
Before that, it was at Cecil Field, Fla., where it sat for nearly a
year without being flown and was known as a ``hangar queen,'' a
term the military gives to a plane used only as a source of spare
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Emory collected damages from the government because his wife was
a civilian. Had she been in the military, he likely would have
received no compensation for his loss. But he was unable to collect
damages from McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got away with murder,'' he said from his home in
Maryland. ``They should be liable for what they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carollo writes for the Dayton Daily News in Dayton,
Ohio. The complete text of this series is available at
www.daytondailynews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
