<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0216 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS28-COX     10-27 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini audio reviews
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino, Sonia Murray and Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``LeAnn Rimes''
</P>
<P>
   LeAnn Rimes. Curb. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Since breaking through with the throwback yodel hit ``Blue,''
teen queen Rimes has become one of the hottest properties in
country music, an All-American hitmaker who has achieved
international status. So, why can't she seem to realize she's not
on the set of ``Star Search'' anymore? Her new CD is an uninspired
collection of cover tunes that sounds as plodding as the talent
portion of a beauty pageant. Rimes deserves credit for mining
classic country rather than turning to pop, but the tunes she has
chosen sound as predictable as Chrismas carols _ ``Your Cheatin'
Heart,'' ``Faded Love,'' ``Me and Bobby McGee,'' ``Cryin' Time''
and two Patsy Cline classics, ``Crazy'' and ``I Fall to Pieces.''
The arrangements are bland, and Rimes takes no risks. It's a shame,
because the Texas singer has a voice that could knock over bowling
pins. Perhaps the problem is that she is so used to being a
one-trick pony _ ``tiny girl with big big voice'' _ that she is
failing to mature her style beyond a belt-out-the-national-anthem
approach. One exception is the sassy single, ``Big Deal,'' the only
new tune on the album and the only track that lets her pump
attitude and tease into the notes. One just wishes that her
producer/father, Wilbur Rimes, would have let some of that passion
spill over into more new material. One clue that Rimes has it in
her: On the album artwork, she's sporting an ankle tattoo.
Unfortunately, this CD makes her sound like she should be wearing a
recital dress.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Only God Can Judge Me''
</P>
<P>
   Master P. No Limit Records. 23 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly retired rapper Master P returns to the ring with an
album that swings wildly from the inspirational to the silly,
stumbles a lot, but never falls flat. His team-up with rapper Nas
on the admirable ``Where Do We Go From Here'' and the hook-driven
``Step to Dis'' and ``Say Brah'' throw strong rights. What's left
are his usual grunted proclamations of how much money the Forbes
cover subject has made (``Ice on My Wrist''), followed by reminders
that even with the New Orleans entrepreneur's mainstream success,
``Ain't Nothing Changed'' _ he's still streetwise. And like many a
punch-drunk boxer, P clearly didn't know when to stop this 23-track
album, offering too many forgettable two-minute songs.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Luxury of Time''
</P>
<P>
   David Mead. RCA .13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   While Capitol works up a sweat trumpeting boy band escapee
Robbie Williams as the savior of old-school pop, along comes this
out-of-nowhere New York artist to make a run for the title.
Brimming with smart arrangements, sophisticated singing and
well-crafted melodies, Mead's debut album makes ``The Ego Has
Landed,'' Williams' synthetically anthemic first effort, sound
positively amateurish. Imagine a summit meeting between Hall &AMP;
Oates and Oasis, arbitrated by Semisonic, and you begin to get a
picture of ``Luxury's'' hooky appeal. ``Robert Bradley's Postcard''
kicks off the disc with a grand flourish _ a pop chamber orchestra
of piano, organ and acoustic and electric guitars builds to a sweet
crescendo as Mead references Allen Ginsberg, Marlon Brando and Joni
Mitchell with blithe elan. The album wanders a bit in the middle,
but comes soaring back with the lovely ``Everybody Knows It But
You,'' which has all the makings of a slow-dance classic.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino, Sonia Murray and Doug Hamilton write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
