r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS28-COX     10-27 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Blair Witch Project'' (R) _ It's a first-person journey
into the kind of terror that comes from trying to glimpse something
moving in the shadows just beyond the campfire. Three students head
into the woods to document an 18th-century witch tale, then
disappear. The movie wrings chills out of the slightest effects:
odd twiglike contraptions hanging from trees, or an unexpected pile
of stones, or strange noises in the night. Like the 1963 version of
``The Haunting,'' its power comes from psychological intensity.
Priced to buy: DVD $29.98, VHS $22.98, including footage not
included in the theatrical release. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Never Been Kissed'' (PG-13) _ Drew Barrymore is Josie
Geller, a mid-20s newspaper copy editor and former high school
dweeb (``Josie Grossie,'' they called her) who goes back to
teenville as an undercover reporter, promptly relives high school
hell and pretty much bumbles her way to popularity. Everything
about her career is implausible. The movie's jokes are lame, its
situations loopy. But Barrymore does make a go of it. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hideous Kinky'' (R) _ Kate Winslet follows up her
``Titanic'' splash with this small-scaled independent film about a
single mother who takes her two young daughters to Morocco in 1972
in search of spiritual enlightenment. Set in the waning days of
flower power, the movie is a portrait of a generation whose
idealism had its poisonous side. Winslet gives a wondrously brave
performance as a loving but blinkered mommie-weirdest whose
feckless romantiscm makes her a benign menace to her children.
Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Twice Upon a Yesterday'' (R) _ This romantic fantasy starts
out with flat-footed awkwardness but gradually grows deeper,
nimbler. Its ideas about love and destiny gleam with promise, even
if the movie never quite finds the structure to show them off
properly. It's a near-miss. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stop Making Sense'' (unrated) _ This ain't no party, this
ain't no disco, it's just a milestone concert film. Fifteen years
after it first appeared, director Jonathan Demme's wonderful ``Stop
Making Sense'' hasn't lost a bit of its energy and elegance. Though
the Talking Heads have acrimoniously parted ways, the movie
preserves the band members in their prime, young and percolating
with cross-cultural rhythms and their early-1980s blend of joy and
alienation. Priced to buy: VHS, $19.95, DVD $29.95. The DVD has
bonus tracks, audio commentary from all four band members and
Demme, and storyboard-to-film comparisons. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Bob Longino write for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
