<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-ROAD28-COX     10-27 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ROAD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspense resides on `Arlington Road'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Arlington Road'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   The squeaky-clean suburbs of Washington darken into something
strange in this paranoia thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bridges plays a professor of domestic terrorism who starts
to suspect things about his new neighbors, the Langs (Tim Robbins
and Joan Cusack). They seem like an impossibly wholesome bunch,
almost a throwback to the '50s ideal of lemonade stands and tag
football in the back yard. They're so perfect there's something off
about them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bridges becomes convinced that the Langs are up to some
deadly secret business. Is he onto something? Or is he having a
meltdown, letting his personal and professional lives intertwine?
The movie keeps us guessing, though it can't totally sustain its
suspense. In its second half, it becomes too moody and baroque for
its own good, relying on monster-movie shots of Robbins and Cusack
to reflect Bridges' anxiety. But the script manages to stay a few
steps ahead of us, luring us toward a slam-bang, unexpected climax.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's marred by patches of obviousness, ``Arlington Road''
possesses a sharp sense of timing. It's a variation of Alfred
Hitchcock's chilling 1943 film ``Shadow of a Doubt,'' hot-wired to
a national nervous system that's already jolted by heavily armed
teenage commandos and high school spree shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
