<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-IRAN-US-$ADV31-COX     10-27 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-US-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE CRISIS THAT HELD AMERICA HOSTAGE 20 YEARS AGO
 &HT;    With IRAN-$ADV31.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 31 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For two weeks, U.S. diplomats watched from their
office windows at the American Embassy in Tehran as hundreds of
militant Iranian college students gathered each day on
Takht-e-Jamshid Avenue to chant ``Margh Bar Amerika'' _''Death to
America.'' But on that drizzly Sunday morning, the crowd seemed to
be in a particularly ugly mood.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 10:30 on Nov. 4, 1979, their worst fears were realized:
With bolt-cutting shears, a vanguard snipped the chains that
clasped the iron gates while others stormed over the 10-foot
concrete wall. Soon, students were swarming through the 27-acre
manicured grounds. Flak-jacketed Marines sought to hold back the
rampaging mob with tear gas grenades, but they were soon routed.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, the diplomats and their security detail were bound
with tape and blindfolded. As TV images of the takeover circled the
globe, the United States began a prolonged ordeal, whose impact is
still being felt today.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, those events permanently eroded the presumed
sanctity of diplomatic immunity. But, more broadly, during the 444
days that the hostages were held captive, America's self-image, as
well as the nation's prestige abroad, plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the public, Iran became a metaphor for everything,'' said
Gerald Rafshoon, then-President Jimmy Carter's media adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Ignorance changed to obsession, as Americans found themselves
checking their atlases and tracking the story so closely that the
names and views of the most obscure Iranian mullahs became
household names.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his poll numbers initially surged, Carter made what
turned out to be a fatal error: stating at the outset that his
primary concern was bringing the hostages home alive. By placing
the value of the hostages' lives above all else, Carter himself
became a kind of hostage to an angry public, a setting that would
haunt him throughout his re-election bid and eventually drive him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Fed by a ravenous press corps, the hostage mania proved in time
to be more harmful to long-term U.S. interests than shocking events
in far-off Iran.
</P>
<P>
   For a subsequent generation of Americans, the collapse of the
Soviet Union and the emergence of the United States as the world's
unchallenged pre-eminent power has removed much, if not all, of the
lingering sting. But in many European and Asian capitals, it is
still widely believed that U.S. foreign policy remains crippled,
especially in the Middle East, by the hostage trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Concluded political analyst Daniel Pipes: ``The United States
paid in many ways for the emotionalism of its leaders. Officials
devoted so much time to this issue that their attention to matters
of greater significance was much reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Soviet troops occupied neighboring
Afghanistan, the president remained so consumed by the hostage
crisis that he was unable to act decisively.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Carter resisted pressure to bomb Tehran, unlike
President Clinton who earlier this year approved the American-led
bombardment of Belgrade. One major difference: Carter lacked the
``smart bombs'' that NATO allies could deploy to cherry-pick
targets in the Serbian capital.
</P>
<P>
   When the crisis over Kosovo erupted, former presidential adviser
David Gergen noted: ``The temptation again is to make it an
obsession. And you can't allow that to happen, because it will
suddenly begin to drive your policy in ways that are very
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 4:30 in the morning in Washington when word of the
hostage taking first reached Hamilton Jordan, the president's chief
of staff. Jordan's immediate fear was that it would trigger a war
with revolutionary Iran, incensed because Carter had granted
sanctuary in New York to the ailing deposed Shah.
</P>
<P>
   War didn't come. But neither did a settlement _ at least not
until Jan. 20, 1981, the day Carter left Washington. Ronald Reagan
had been president for 20 minutes when the remaining 52 hostages
flew off to a U.S. military hospital in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the hostage crisis of 1979 gave rise to that
peculiar agony, increasingly familiar to Americans in subsequent
decades, which arises after a major terrorist strike. It is an
agony born of great power, coupled with the knowledge of how little
at times it can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials empathized with the victims, heightening the sense
of crisis. Passengers of a downed Korean 747 receive more attention
than tens of thousands of Afghan peasants because Americans can
picture themselves sitting in a Boeing jet; similarly, fellow
bureaucrats can see themselves in an embassy surrounded by an
agitated mob.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were matters helped by a fierce policy dispute between
Zbigniew Brzezinski, Carter's activist national security adviser,
and the late Cyrus Vance, who as secretary of state, argued that
diplomacy could resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As historian Douglas Brinkley has written: ``For nearly a year
the crisis handcuffed the administration, which tried everything it
could think of to end the standoff: suspending oil imports,
freezing Iranian assets, expelling Iranian diplomats, imposing
economic sanctions, even conducting clandestine negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, a former naval officer, hoped to repeat the
success of an Israeli commando raid that had freed 103 airline
passengers at Entebbe, Uganda, in 1976. But the U.S. operation
proved a humiliating failure.
</P>
<P>
   As Brinkley noted: ``After the aborted rescue attempt, many
believed that Carter had not only tarnished the nation's honor but
lost control of his own administration in the process. Critics
condemned him for failing to mount a rescue operation sooner, for
not putting enough military hardware into it once he did act, and
then for retreating at the first sign of hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Brzezinski had counseled Carter to bomb Tehran if the rescue
mission caused the deaths of would-be rescuers, hostages and
captors. Although no such attack took place, Vance quit in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Many years after the fact, Carter told reporters that he still
believed he could have been re-elected if he had bombed Tehran
until the hostages were released or incinerated along with the
entire Iranian government. But that kind of ground-zero solution
was morally repugnant to Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of grumbles about my handling of the hostage
crisis,'' he said in looking back, ``but not a single responsible
politician offered a more realistic alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   An echo of such internal quarrels could be heard in Clinton's
1998 decision to launch a cruise missile attack against a
pharmaceutical plant in Sudan in a bid to punish Osama bin Laden,
the Islamic militant blamed for blowing up two American embassies
in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Brzezinski is hardly alone in believing that the Iran
hostage crisis crushed Carter's prestige. ``I think it was
devastating,'' he said. ``The Iran hostage crisis was one of the
two central reasons for Carter's defeat in 1980, the other reason
being domestic inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Brzezinski contends that the events in Iran heightened
the nation's sense of vulnerability, particularly in the Middle
East. ``Once the Iranian pillar had collapsed, we were faced with
the possibility that one way or another, before too long, we may
have either a hostile Iran on the northern shore of the Persian
Gulf facing us, or we might even have the Soviets there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another lasting legacy of the crisis is ABC's ``Nightline,'' the
media grand-daddy of today's saturation coverage, on cable networks
and the Internet, that arises whenever news blow-outs occur.
</P>
<P>
   Neither medium existed when Roone Arledge, the innovator of ABC
News, created ``America Held Hostage'' to track the crisis in
depth.
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Reynolds left in December to cover the presidential
campaign, his role was taken up by Ted Koppel, the network's
diplomatic correspondent. In time, Koppel began anchoring
permanently, with the renamed ``Nightline'' premiering on March 24,
1980. It remains a stable of light-night TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some grudges that Americans seem to nurse longer
than others,'' Koppel said. ``Lord knows this program no doubt
contributed to that mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the days before it was known as 'Nightline,' when it
was still called 'America Held Hostage,' we tagged a number on the
back, indicating just how many days it had been since the Ayatollah
Khomeini's followers first seized the embassy in Tehran . . . Many
people probably still remember it as the program that highlighted
the indignity and humanized a situation far removed from most of
our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In looking back on the program's first decade, Koppel once
reflected: ``What will never change is that hostages are by
definition a tremendous emotional and explosive domestic issue.
Ideally _ and this sounds very callous _ a president ought to be
able to say, 'We aren't going to deal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter did not.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass, senior correspondent in the Cox Newspapers
Washington Bureau, covered the Carter White House and Iranian
hostage crisis.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
