<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BARRIER-FREE-DESIGN-2     10-27 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRIER-FREE-DESIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING THE BARRIERS TO BARRIER-FREE LIVING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never thought, somehow, that the Rolling Stones would be the
ones to sum up the experience of installing a new bathroom for our
mother on the farm in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   But they must have known something when they said, ``You can't
always get what you wah-ahnt.'' Because after two months of trying,
we got what we needed.
</P>
<P>
   What we needed, in the material sense, was a downstairs
bathroom, with a shower. But what we also needed, big time, was a
new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wah-ahnts to get old, for instance. My 86-year-old mother
certainly doesn't like it _ hates it, in fact, when it means she
can't run up and down the cellar stairs with 30-pound turkeys, or
see Africa again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too old,'' she'll say simply. She can't stand euphemisms
like ``senior citizen'' and ``elderly.'' Still, she isn't the type
to hop into a wheelchair. My brother Jim did talk her into one of
those electric chairs that attaches to a staircase.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was a shock to see her get into the blue upholstered chair
and ride the steel track that now runs up the old polished
living-room staircase. (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But it was a pending hip replacement operation last June and her
10 days in a rehab unit (which we all called ``Mother's boot
camp'') that got us, finally, to stop pussyfooting around: a new
era had dawned, and it was time for the 200-year-old farmhouse to
get with the program.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with a downstairs bathroom built along the principles
of barrier-free universal design.
</P>
<P>
   We'd often talked about installing a shower in the old pantry
off the kitchen, where more than 50 years ago my parents had taken
down the shelves and cookie tins and put in a toilet and sink. But
it's a small space _ about five and a half feet square _ with a big
window on one side. So, putting in anything more than a narrow
shower stall meant taking down a wall and extending into Mother's
beloved flower porch, a sunny, glassed-in space where her potted
plants thrive in winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we just order a shower stall from Gary Watts and be
done with it?'' she had said, months before. Gary is our plumber;
his father had put in a shower stall on the third floor, when part
of the attic was converted into a bedroom. It works just fine. But
it has a four-inch-lip at the entrance, which anyone with a stiff
knee or hip could trip over.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been to the universal design show last fall at the
Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum, where I was entranced by
Gianfranco Zaccai's prototype shower, with attractive grab bars, a
hand-held shower head and a comfortable bench. I could see,
suddenly, what universal design meant: everyone would enjoy a
well-designed space _ and it would remove the stigma of
``handicaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The design has not yet hit the production line, but I had seen
less elegant versions at the Rusk Institute of Rehabilitation
Medicine in Manhattan, so I made an appointment with Lucy Beck, the
designer there who helps patients redo their homes for independent
living. I took a rough sketch of the little downstairs room with
me.
</P>
<P>
   There were two basic options, she said, if we didn't want to
tear down any walls. We could buy the base of a prefabricated
shower unit, without the walls, and hang a curtain from a rod
attached to the walls and ceiling. That would leave the tiny room
more of a sense of space, though the base of the stall would make
maneuvering _ from toilet to sink to shower _ difficult for anyone
in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mother had insisted that she would not be using a
wheelchair, but what about other people? Why not design a bathroom
convenient to all?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beck's design for our little room created a no-barrier
shower without walls. A floor that sloped a quarter inch a foot
toward a drain in the corner of the shower space would keep water
from flooding out toward the sink and toilet. We would have to
install a lead pan or waterproof membrane beneath the tile floor
and a waterproof board behind the wall tiles in the shower area.
</P>
<P>
   We would have room for only a small, hanging corner sink by the
window, which would be accessible to anyone in a wheelchair. Ms.
Beck recommended a 19-inch-high toilet, which is five inches more
than the standard design, and grab bars at strategic points around
the room.
</P>
<P>
   The prefab unit might cost $2,000, without the labor, she said;
the no-barrier design, $8,000 to $12,000, depending on materials
and labor and unforeseen structural snafus.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began my first construction project. To my surprise, mother
voted for the no-barrier design, and went off to the hospital
saying: ``I'll leave all that to you. I'm sure you'll do a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   I think it was the pain that inspired such confidence in her
neophyte contractor, which was not shared by the plumber, Gary
Watts; the carpenter, Randy Winecke, and Bernie Eckenrode, the
caretaker who can fix just about anything in this place. They had
been all set to install one of Gary's shower stalls, with the least
time and disruption to the house, and they looked at me with wary
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want us to rip up this linoleum, and put in a
subfloor,'' Randy said, mentally juggling his other jobs all over
the county. ``We'll have to see how the joists are running under
the house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to move the pipes,'' Gary muttered, as the two men
descended the cellar steps and started banging around downstairs.
Bernie turned to me and said, ``We'll have to take out that
radiator and put in some kind of overhead heater fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Joists? Heater fan? At age 50, I had successfully avoided doing
anything more than calling my landlord when the faucet started
leaking. Here I was trying to persuade these veterans of exploded
pipes and collapsed ceilings to tear up the floor and knock out the
old plaster, to move pipes and radiators _ not to mention tiling
the entire room _ just so Mrs. Raver wouldn't have to lift her foot
a few inches off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Then came my education at a family-owned tile company in
Westminster. I could have saved money shopping for tiles at the
Home Depot, but Gary, Randy and Bernie ``don't do tiles.'' I needed
someone who knew how to slope and line a floor properly.
</P>
<P>
   Then I had to choose colors. Look at your shelter magazines, the
tile man advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there's no insulation behind this wall,'` Randy
said, as he knocked plaster off ancient wooden lathing. So, we had
to insulate, which would take a few days. Meanwhile, the house was
letting loose in other ways, like the kitchen drain that crumbled
when my brother Jim poked a coat hanger down the clogged line,
sending water all over the floor. Mother would just laugh, gaily,
from her cell in boot camp. We were seeing what it took to keep
This Old House from falling down.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   All this was being negotiated in between trips to the hospital
and shopping for heater fans (I got the wrong one), and faucets
with levers, and grab bars, and toilet seats (oval or rounder?).
Days were turning into weeks, as our design kept bumping up against
reality, like the fact that the floor could not be lowered, because
of the joists supporting the house _ so this impermeable floor
would have to be built on top of the old one.
</P>
<P>
   After I decided on the color scheme (creamy white, with dark red
tiles in a simple alternating pattern), it turned out that the tile
store's best man would not be available for the installation.
</P>
<P>
   I suddenly understood the hysteria I've disdained in my
homeowner friends. But another man was sent in his place to lay the
floor. When my sister, Martha, and I returned from Home Depot, the
tile man had left for the day, and the tiles were laid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't the slope look like it's going the wrong way?'' Martha
asked. We weren't supposed to walk on the tiles, so we leaned
through the window. It was.
</P>
<P>
   In the week it took for someone else to come and do the job
right, Mother returned home, to a hospital bed in the living room
and plaster dust, and the high whine of a tile saw. The
bathroom-in-progress was missing even its original toilet and sink.
So, we got the ancestral potty chair down from the attic, and she
took sponge baths _ for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But finally, it all did take shape. The red tiles looked
beautiful. ``Like a New York diner,'' the tile man said, which was
a compliment, I think.
</P>
<P>
   It drains beautifully. The whole bathroom came in very close to
$8,000, which is a bargain when it means living where you want to,
safely and comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
