<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-Y2K-HOME-2TAKES-N     10-27 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Y2K-HOME-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, THE YEAR 2000 THREAT IS AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: 2 optional sidebars at end of article; in the second
sidebar, titled `Y2K Information Sources', change (POUNDSIGN) in
the Web site address to the typographical symbol, with no
parentheses)  
 (bl)  
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Bennett doubted that his home computer had Year 2000
problems, so when a visitor to his New York apartment raised the
subject 16 months ago, Bennett decided to prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   He set the date on its Windows 95 operating system ahead to the
last minute of 1999. Voila! The clock rolled smoothly into Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett then demonstrated that he could enter Year 2000 dates in
his Excel data program and his Lotus Organizer before calling it a
night. It was not until he reset Lotus to the current date the next
day that he learned to his horror that the test had wiped out his
Lotus data files, including freelance-writing records he needed for
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus offered to send a free updated version of the program, but
told him it knew of no way to recover the purged files.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a painful experience,'' said Bennett, who is an editor
at The American Banker, the financial services newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett undoubtedly has company. Computer experts say home
computer users may encounter a variety of Year 2000 flaws, some of
them potentially disastrous for people who operate businesses out
of their homes. But the biggest hazards for most people are most
likely to be misguided tests and mistakes in applying Year 2000
fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Home computer problems fall into three major areas: hardware,
the operating system (usually a form of Microsoft Windows) and
software applications. Some owners with extensive databases,
including those who use older versions of Excel, may also have
problems with the dates stored in them.
</P>
<P>
   In all three areas, the first step toward Year 2000 peace of
mind is to check with the companies that made your equipment and
programs. Fortunately that is a lot easier to do than in mid-1998,
when Bennett was first considering the problem. At that time,
Microsoft chairman and chief executive Bill Gates and much of the
personal computer world was dismissing Year 2000 as mainly a
problem for mainframe users.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all the major vendors have learned that PCs are also
prone to enough date bugs to be worrisome. As a result, their Y2K
Internet sites are finally relatively helpful. They may not explain
what will go wrong all that clearly, but at least they tell you
which products are flawed and offer advice on ways to cope with the
flaws. Telephone advice is also available for those without Web
access.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware defects are especially common in computers made before
1998. They stem from the way a chip known as the basic input-output
system, or BIOS, retrieves the date and time from another chip
called the real-time clock, or RTC, each time a computer is turned
on.
</P>
<P>
   RTC's keep time with batteries, and most track the ``year'' and
the ``century'' in separate two-digit registers. The ``year''
register, which now reads 99, will automatically move to 00 on Jan.
1, but the ``century'' register, which has read 19 ever since the
RTC was manufactured, is not likely to shift automatically to 20.
</P>
<P>
   What happens on Jan. 1 depends on how new and smart your BIOS
chip and operating system are. Some will update the clock when the
computer is rebooted or, at the very least, realize that a year
beginning with 19 is old and substitute 20. But if the BIOS does
not correct the clock when the computer is rebooted next year, an
older operating system like Windows 95 will conclude that the date
is Jan. 4, 1980, the earliest 20th-century date that it recognizes.
</P>
<P>
   None of that would prevent anyone from using a computer for word
processing or playing games, any more than a clock blinking 12:00
on a microwave oven interferes with cooking. But many applications,
from occasional tasks like sorting e-mail to ongoing activities
like banking online, look to the operating-system clock and require
accurate dates as well as times.
</P>
<P>
   A number of free tests are available online or on disks you can
get from vendors to probe the Year 2000 readiness of a PC's
hardware (all Apple computers are Y2K-ready, even though some
software for Apple machines may not be). And many free BIOS
upgrades are available if the tests turn up a problem. To find out
what BIOS your computer has, hit the Pause button as it is booting
or call the computer vendor with the model and serial number of
your computer.
</P>
<P>
   As nice as they sound, however, free tests and BIOS upgrades may
cause serious heartburn for users who become nervous at the thought
of doing anything more complicated than surfing the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BIOS upgrade is usually over most folks' heads, and it can
virtually ruin the machine if the procedure fails,'' said Thomas
Becker, president of Rightime Co., a Miami-based vendor of computer
timing products for corporate desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Becker said that anyone with a computer old enough to have date
problems should probably be thinking about buying a new computer.
Another strategy is to turn to a number of companies, including
his, that sell products to automate the process of finding and
repairing home-computer flaws.
</P>
<P>
   But that may not be necessary in many cases, Becker added. Many
home users who have the Windows operating system can simply go to
the Control Panel and open the Date/Time folder to reset the
computer's clock the first time it is booted next year. Often, that
will change the century register in the RTC to 20 for good.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the programs that find and fix glitches look at software
as well as hardware and operating systems. But many are loaded with
features that the average home user does not really need because
they were designed to help corporate computer managers overseeing
the Y2K readiness of hundreds or even thousands of desktop devices.
</P>
<P>
   There are a wide variety of operating-system problems that could
surprise home computer users, although most are so obscure that
many users might never encounter them. Microsoft lists 13 known
problems for Windows 95 on its Web site, including mysterious dates
in the file manager program after Jan. 1, 2000 (which appears as
1/1/:1).
</P>
<P>
   The list includes faulty date interactions between the operating
system and bundled applications, like the credit card tracking
function in MS Wallet (in early versions, an expiration date of
5/01 will be read as May 1 of the current year instead of May
2001).
</P>
<P>
   Home computer users may be surprised to learn that their systems
_ including those from Apple _ can hit Year 2000 snags in faulty
software even if the hardware and operating systems are ready for
2000 dates. For instance, the online banking applications of
Versions 5 and 6 of Quicken for Windows and Versions 6 and 7 of
Quicken for Macintosh will not recognize dates later than Dec. 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Intuit, the manufacturer of Quicken, a popular personal-finance
program, is offering customers with the flawed programs (or earlier
Quicken releases that Intuit has not tested for Year 2000
compliance) a choice of free upgrades to Quicken 98 or reduced
prices for its latest product, Quicken 2000.
</P>
<P>
   PC users with extensive databases and spreadsheets can run into
a separate set of date problems. Programs that handle the rollover
to 2000 smoothly can still flub the handoff of other dates from one
to the other: for example, one may interpret 1/1/15 in a
spreadsheet as Jan. 1, 1915, and the other as Jan. 1, 2015, even
though they agree that 1/1/00 is Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users may need to install special interface software to
prevent such database confusion. Others may want to move all their
data to newer database programs that are ready for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As Bennett's experience points out, however, crucial data should
be backed up before any effort is made to test or upgrade your
system.
</P>
<P>
   NO NEED TO WORRY: MR. COFFEE WON'T GET THE Y2K JITTERS
</P>
<P>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Are you looking for your own niche as a technology collector, a
chance to specialize in something so rare and offbeat that a stash
of, say, early portable computers would look as commonplace as
Beanie Babies by comparison? Try rounding up consumer products
other than computers with Year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 fears have always focused primarily on the giant,
intertwined systems that provide society with basic services like
power, phones, banking and water. And, of course, personal
computers at home could have some problems if they are old or have
old software. But Year 2000 alarmists and even some of the more
moderate Y2K worriers also originally suspected that many popular
consumer entertainment and appliance products could stumble as New
Year's Eve turned into New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern was that hundreds of millions of such devices
contained microchips incapable of handling Year 2000 dates and
capable of malfunctioning if badly programmed, resulting in
unpopped popcorn, melted ice cream and VCRs incapable of recording
``Beverly Hills 90210.'' There were even fears that thermostats
would fail or that the family car would sputter to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew what the situation was, and we couldn't get any
answers from the vendors,'' said Ann Coffou, a leading Year 2000
analyst at Giga Information Group in Cambridge, Mass., recalling
the warnings she issued about consumer products at Congressional
hearings in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Now the answers are there, and they are almost uniformly
reassuring. Microwave ovens, coffee makers and other appliances
were among the first home products to disappear from the Y2K
nightmare scenarios. The Consumer Products Safety Commission, trade
groups and major manufacturers all say they have yet to encounter
appliances with Year 2000 problems. The microchip clocks in
appliances track time and occasionally the day of the week, they
say, but have not been programmed to bother about the date.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar in cars. General Motors, Ford and the
other manufacturers say cars will have no date problems, despite
the swarms of microchips embedded in them. The chips' timekeeping
capabilities are used for things like controlling the deployment of
airbags fractions of a second after a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Auto experts say that an expert with sophisticated equipment
could conceivably program the chips in a way that could shut down a
vehicle as the ball fell in Times Square. But no one has suggested
that anyone is trying to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average mechanic certainly isn't going to be up to such a
thing,'' said David Cole, an associate professor at the University
of Michigan's Transport Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   There is at least a possibility of failure for some consumer
electronics devices, but the glitches are still rare and, in some
cases, downright odd. Having checked their product lines,
manufacturers have come up with a handful of very old camcorders
that will continue working but will not print dates on film or, in
other cases, will display incorrect dates starting next year.
Despite speculation that some cameras may have a similar flaw, none
are listed on the company Web sites of the leading camera makers.
</P>
<P>
   One Philips pager (model PRG 2220) cannot be programmed to
delete messages automatically when the year reads ``00'' in the
date. But Philips says that problem will end when the date reads
01, in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Old VCRs may also have Y2K quirks. Some 1991 and 1992 models
made under the RCA name by Thomson Consumer Electronics cannot
easily be programmed at the end of this year to record programs
early next year using the VCR Plus feature, but users can still
tape by entering the time, date and channel information manually.
</P>
<P>
   Customized products _ some home security systems installed by
small, local operators for example _ may have unpredictable date
routines. But assuming that the power is on come Jan. 3, the clock
radio, the garage door opener and any other device you count on to
get you to work on a typical Monday will not miss a beat. You will
need something other than Y2K as an excuse for being late to the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K INFORMATION SOURCES
</P>
<P>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER
</P>
<P>
   Home computer users can get information on Y2K readiness
directly from manufacturers and convenient links to free tests. A
good entry point for research is www.pcy2000.org, a clearinghouse
created by major manufacturers. Several trade magazines also
provide useful if somewhat overwhelming portals, including PC World
(www.pcworld.com/onlinefeature/1707/countdown2000) and PC Week
(www.zdnet.com/pcweek/filters/zdy2k/resources).
</P>
<P>
   Users of Microsoft products may want to go directly to
www.microsoft.com/y2k and click on the Home and Small Business
site. Before heading there, though, stop to check Microsoft's
warnings about the latest Y2K hoaxes _ hackers have been sending
e-mail messages that purport to offer a Year 2000 countdown program
but can plant a virus in home computers.
</P>
<P>
   For an overview of consumer products, consult the Federal
Consumer Products Safety Commission at www.cpsc.gov/about/y2k.html.
The Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association at
www.cemacity.org/govt/cema2000.htm(POUNDSIGN)(NU)4 has links to
major manufacturers of consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have access to the Internet, the information
clearinghouse run by President Clinton's Council on Year 2000
Conversion can provide written materials. Phone (888) USA-4Y2K
between 9 a.m. and 8 p.m. to reach an operator.
</P>
</TEXT>
