<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Oct. 28, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much of the nation will be dry and rather mild as expansive high
pressure over the East and South continues to block the return of
moist air from the Atlantic Ocean and the Gulf of Mexico. A large
potent storm centered near Vancouver Island will result in strong
winds as well as widespread rain and mountain snow in the
Northwestern States.
</P>
<P>
   Windswept rain will dampen the Northwest Coast Thursday morning
as onshore winds gust frequently over 40 mph in exposed coastal
areas. Periods of snow will accumulate in the Cascades, especially
at elevations above 6,000 feet. Snow levels will fall during the
day as a pool of high-level chill passes overhead. Rain and wind
will diminish gradually during the afternoon and evening. Showery
valley rain and mountain snow will be common near the leading edge
of the cooler air as it spreads into the interior Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Ample sunshine will bathe a large area from the Southwestern
States to the east slopes of the Rockies and northern Plains.
Clouds will increase in northern sections later in the day as
moisture from the Pacific storm spreads east.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, a strong warming trend will develop from the lower
Mississippi Valley to the west slopes of the Appalachians as
breezes from the southwest increase. After a chilly dawn in the
East Coast states, plentiful sunshine will boost temperatures near
or above seasonal values in most locations. Onshore breezes will
cause patchy clouds to gather near the Southeast Coast later
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sympathetic Storms
</P>
<P>
   Like the explosions from a set a fireworks, major storms have
been developing around the northern hemisphere. On Tuesday, a storm
rapidly strengthened in the North Atlantic near Iceland. Its
central pressure fell below 28 inches of mercury. Thursday, the
Pacific Northwest Coast will be lashed by rain and strong winds
from a potent Pacific storm. Major storms often form around the
same time at disparate locations. When a big storm develops the jet
stream pattern around the hemisphere becomes contorted providing
added energy for storms at several spots many thousands of miles
apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
