<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DVD-RENTAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDE-RANGING MOVIE SITES OFFER THE RARE AND OFFBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blockbuster last week announced that it would offer movie
rentals over the Internet by the middle of next year and said it
was evaluating ways to transmit movies into people's homes on
demand. But you don't have to wait until then to order movies over
the Internet and have them delivered to your door.
</P>
<P>
   There are already a number of videotape and DVD movie rental
sites on the Web, many offering the kinds of films you would never
see at a chain video store. The selections include high art and
film rarities.
</P>
<P>
   A quick search of the Internet turned up six online video rental
stores and nine DVD rental sites. Some are simply extensions of
brick-and-mortar video stores; others are Internet-only businesses.
Some, like Net Flix, are well financed and slick; others appear to
be shoestring, amateurish operations. All function in a similar
way, allowing some kind of search through a trove of films that can
be ordered on the site for delivery by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 15 sites, most people could eliminate DVD Rent right off
the bat _ it offers film and music rentals and sales throughout
Australia. And DVD Wave and Video Ltd. no longer rent movies, even
though their Yahoo listings say they do. Laser Discovery required a
security deposit of $500, which seemed excessive _ wasn't that the
total shooting budget for ``The Blair Witch Project''?
</P>
<P>
   The video sites offered more eclectic film collections than
those that handle DVD's, in part because some of the more offbeat
movie titles are not yet available in the DVD format. But as a
group, the video sites had the least consumer-friendly policies.
</P>
<P>
   Best Video (www.bestvideo.com) promises a broad selection, but
charges $16.99 per rental _ pretty steep, considering that a video
at the local Blockbuster is less than $4.
</P>
<P>
   Several video rental stores did not include a return mailer or
return postage in the cost of the rental. In the time it takes to
wrap up a video and wait in line at the post office, a movie lover
could watch an entire film festival. Both Facets Video
(www.facets.org), which also required a $35 membership, and Rick's
Video, (www.ricksvideo.com), which charges $19.95 for up to three
tapes or DVD's, do not offer the convenience of a return mailer.
</P>
<P>
   Two other video sites do not offer return postage, although they
do have intriguing film collections. One is Video Vault
(www.videovault.com), which has a delightfully tacky Web site. It
lives up to the slogan ``Guaranteed Worst Movies in Town'' with
rentals like Ed Wood Jr.'s ``Glen or Glenda,'' as well as the film
Siskel and Ebert used to cite as the worst ever made, ``I Spit on
Your Grave.''
</P>
<P>
   The second, www.videowasteland.com, specializes in horror,
exploitation and B movies. One of them is ``Skeeter,'' which
features giant mutant killer mosquitoes _ a movie certain to be in
demand in New York after the events of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth videotape site, Home Film Festival
(www.homefilmfestival.com), charges a $6 rental fee and a minimum
shipping fee of $4.30. There is also a $9.95 membership fee,
bringing the total to $20.25 for the first video. That's a lot of
money, but Home Film Festival could come up with a hard-to-find
cult classic like, for example, ``The Harder They Come,'' starring
the reggae singer Jimmy Cliff, so it might be worth it to a real
film buff.
</P>
<P>
   An order for membership and the movie was placed about 6 p.m. on
a Friday. On Monday, an e-mail message confirmed that the
membership had been processed but said ``The Harder They Come'' was
not available. It was an expensive movie not to see. But later, a
215-page catalog showed up with finds for cinemaphiles like
``Absolute Beginners,'' starring David Bowie, and ``Zou-Zou,''
starring Josephine Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Things went better with the DVD providers. The King Kong of DVD
sites is Net Flix (www.netflix.com). It has a wide selection _ it
was the only DVD site of those surveyed to have the hard-to-find
1970s Richard Lester costume romp called ``The Three Musketeers''
and the even-harder-to-find sequel, ``The Four Musketeers.'' The
site is also loaded with viewing suggestions. Leonard Maltin, the
reviewer, has a page where he recommends five films each month.
</P>
<P>
   Net Flix also packages films into fairly random collections of
five or so movies. The cover of ``Midnight in the Garden of Good
and Evil'' on the main page, is linked to the Southern Charm
collection, which includes ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof,'' ``Sling
Blade'' and ``Eve's Bayou,'' but not ``In the Heat of the Night.''
</P>
<P>
   The main page is so jammed with films that it's a little busy,
and the box cover shots are postage-stamp size on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   No membership is required at Net Flix, but the site offers
packages. The Marquee service, for a monthly fee of $15.95, gives
viewers four films a month with no due date, late fee or shipping
charges. There are also package deals of 10, 25 and 40 disks that
offer discounts of about 50 cents on each rental, once shipping is
figured in. Single rentals are $3.49 per disk plus a shipping fee
of 95 cents and a flat fee of 99 cents per order, for a total of
$5.43.
</P>
<P>
   An order is quickly followed by an e-mail confirmation, another
to say the DVD's have been shipped and a third when it's time to
send them back. Disks ordered about 6 p.m. on a Friday arrived on
Tuesday. A stamped return mailer was included. The major downside
to Net Flix is the marketing blitz an order sets off, including
automatic subscriptions to electronic newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   DVD Overnight (www.dvdovernight.com) has a streamlined opening
page, with video box pictures that are a little larger than most.
And the rentals are a reasonable $3 per disk with a flat shipping
fee of $3, return included, whether you rent one disk or six, the
maximum. The site carries mostly new releases, which means that you
would need to search for all but the most common classic films
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But DVD Overnight has one thing that neither Blockbuster nor Net
Flix has: pornographic movies. And that means you should be careful
surfing the site with children. The company said it would always
make sure that the DVD box art that appears on the main page for
such movies was not particularly revealing. However, if you click
on DVDO Top Rentals, the page of most popular films, the box art
for pornographic films can be sexually explicit.
</P>
<P>
   The site suffers the occasional technical glitch. Clicking on
``Toxic Avenger 2,'' for example, sent the surfer to ``Magical
Mystery Tour.'' But DVD's ordered on a Friday appeared by Wednesday
in good shape, with a return mailer that was easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   The Digibuster home page (www.digibuster.com) has the look of a
homemade Web page, with a champagne glass background and a very
prominent link to a different Reuters entertainment news article
each day. There is also a link to India Weekly, with which it must
be allied, because India Weekly appears on the credit card receipt
for rental DVD's. In fact, there is a special link to movies from
India.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a small selection, about 150 DVD's, and most are
the sort of movies that would have been featured on the wall at a
Blockbuster months ago. But it is among the least expensive: disks
are $1.99 plus $1.49 handling and shipping for each one, for a
minimum of two disks. An order was followed by an e-mail
confirmation, and the movies showed up in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   DVD Cache (www.dvdcache.com) has a Web page that proved a little
cranky, at least on a Netscape browser _ it loaded slowly, and
sometimes without a scroll bar. But the site was fairly easy to
shop, partly because it offers only about 350 titles, including a
total of six Westerns and five classics.
</P>
<P>
   The scroll bar was not the only technological problem. Using the
search engine to look up ``Costner'' turned up several films, but
not ``Silverado,'' with Kevin Costner, even though it was in stock.
Rentals are $2.99 each, with a flat $4 shipping fee for up to six
DVD's. If you order six, the shipping is free. But the return
mailer must be postmarked seven days after the shipping date _ most
other sites allow a lenient seven days from the time the movies
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   If you are willing to put up with the occasional technical
glitch and wade through some hard-to-browse pages, these sites
offer a broader array of films than you are likely to find in a
single store. All you need for your own film festival is the
popcorn _ also available for delivery on line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
