<HEADER>
A0262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-IMPERFECT-DESIGN-2TAK     10-27 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPERFECT-DESIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF MAKING A HOME PERFECTLY IMPERFECT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)   By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Were it not largely obscured by a privet hedge, Gary Guerrette's
three-bedroom bungalow might cause a neighborhood revolt. But in
low-key Water Mill, N.Y. _ where picturesque dilapidation can be a
badge of honor _ the rippling asphalt-shingle roof, buckling wood
steps and architectural malaise pass without remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs a little work,'' said a brightly smiling Guerrette,
40, of the house he shares with his partner, Tom Lawson, 42, a
massage therapist. Informally formal, rough yet elegant, it is a
semaphore for design on the century's cusp _ a lively mosaic of
pleasures and passions rather than a catalog of perfections. ``I
don't think we own anything that isn't chipped, rotten, broken or
falling apart,'' Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of precious,'' chimed in Guerrette, a floral
designer who has segued into creating gardens and interiors for
clients in Manhattan and near his Water Mill home on Long Island.
(His company is called the Mad Gardener.) ``When everything's
perfect,'' he added, ``a room loses its spontaneity.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing a visitor sees upon opening the front door is a
German Expressionist-style portrait of a young flapper, surrounded
by an 18th-century English gilt frame. The pairing is a potent
symbol of Guerrette's all-forgiving, all-inspiring vision; the
battered canvas is too small for the frame by at least two inches.
It is a flaw that offers a startling side effect: a glimpse of blue
wall that surrounds the canvas like a mat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more interesting to look at that way,'' said Guerrette,
who found the discarded painting on a street in Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Independent, clashing and, above all, loads of fun, the
Guerrette-Lawson bungalow is the kind of home that mainstream
shelter magazines avoid like the plague. Though positioned to teach
as well as tout, editors too often shy away from challenging the
status quo, claiming that their public would not understand.
(Translation: Readers lack imagination, are conventional and have
no sense of humor.)
</P>
<P>
   But who could fail to be inspired by cozily stylish rooms that
look like they took about a weekend to pull together _ and probably
did?
</P>
<P>
   For now, rows of staples brazenly hold yards of checked cotton
to the walls of a spare room, though Guerrette swears that ``one
day soon'' he will get around to concealing the evidence under
decorative braid.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the staples, skirting the margins of the room like
a sort of quicksilver Morse code, is momentarily odd but, in an age
when the cult of perfection can paralyze even the most confident,
it is strangely comforting at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In the living area, a gingham-check slipcover is seamed with
dozens of straight pins, its lumpy silhouette camouflaged by a
fluffy white sheepskin. Underneath the whole thing is a battered
rattan footstool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is properly sewn,'' Guerrette said. Few things are
properly hung either. The impromptu tapestry in the dining area, an
eight-foot length of a Manuel Canovas pineapple-print cotton, is
held aloft by transparent plastic pushpins. (So are the curtains
that frame the dining area like a theatrical tableau.)
</P>
<P>
   No, the decorator did not bother to conceal the manufacturer's
name emblazoned along the cotton's selvage. ``Anything done
correctly here would look out of place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He says even his mother has begged him, without success, to hem
the canvas curtains under the china cabinet that holds a cache of
English creamware, French faience, American ironstone and
miscellaneous lusterware. The china cabinet is homemade, too, made
by fitting an existing alcove with shelves and window frames backed
by chicken wire.
</P>
<P>
   Though Guerrette views pushpins and thumbtacks as viable
decorating tools for himself, clients typically prefer their rooms
more finished. For them, the designer's work is strictly couture.
</P>
<P>
   At a still-under-development apartment in a prewar building on
West End Avenue, for instance, the living room walls are shiny
aubergine, which Guerrette _ armed with a plastic graining tool
from a paint-supply store _ gave a subtle random pattern recalling
silk moire.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Louis XVI-style chairs are upholstered in silk striped
in two shades of blue, and lettuce-green taffeta curtains hang at
the windows. Of course, there is a flea-market touch, albeit a
swank one, amid the Dior-deluxe trappings: gold-tone spun-aluminum
table lamps, each topped with an exaggerated stovepipe shade.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrette and Lawson bought the Water Mill property for less
than $400,000 a year and a half ago, seduced by its physical
charms: towering trees, privacy, the sense of otherworldliness.
(There was income potential, too, thanks to a small cottage at the
back of the lot, which the men briefly lived in, smartly renovated
and now rent out.)
</P>
<P>
   Visitors walking to the end of the gravel drive take in a view
that is pure Millet, a bucolic scene stretching from a farmer's
field of organically grown vegetables out to the sparkling waters
of Mecox Bay on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, because the trees are changing, you feel like
you're in Burgundy,'' said Guerrette, who comes by his Francophilia
naturally (he had a French grandfather) as well as commercially (he
briefly sold 19th-century French antiques at a shop he opened near
the 26th Street flea market). ``It's all silver, gray and blue,
with touches of orange and yellow.''
</P>
<P>
   At the bungalow, where the couple live year-round, Guerrette has
settled on French color and English comfort. Cultural
cross-pollination, not purity, was the goal. ``I like when the
French do an English look, or vice versa, because they knock each
other down a bit,'' he said. ``It's not right, but it's better.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the bungalow's woebegone state, Guerrette and Lawson do
have a long-range plan of improvements in mind, among them siding
the house in natural shingles, adding another bedroom upstairs,
removing the linoleum that paves the entire first floor and
replacing the ``awful'' 1970's picture windows with multipaned
charmers.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, Guerrette will be painting the interior trim
driftwood gray, inspired by a French manor featured in a
12-year-old issue of Vogue Decoration, now defunct. The floors will
be painted the same weathered blue that a French artist used for
the interior doors of his country house.
</P>
<P>
   Although on a recent afternoon the latter plan came as somewhat
of a surprise to Lawson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember, Tom, I showed you the article,'' Guerrette said,
puzzled that such a perfect idea could have slipped his partner's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   An awkward pause followed. ``Oh, OK,'' Lawson said slowly,
eyebrows raised, face bemused.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Turning to a visitor, he said: ``I'm not the decorator, and I
accept that. There's something to be said for knowing what you can
and cannot do.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   It was Guerrette, Lawson pointed out, who solved the spatial
problem of a long but narrow spare bedroom. First, he divided it
horizontally with secondhand cotton curtains that he upgraded with
chartreuse-and-black grosgrain ribbon. Then, he outfitted the far
side of the room as an alcove bed, installing a mattress and a box
spring and piling on cushions of blue damask and flowered chintz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only way to make a full-size bed fit and make
something out of the room,'' said Guerrette. He also stapled up a
couple of bolts of grape-and-white checked cotton, bought for $1.50
a yard at Paterson Silks, and for good measure, dragged into the
scheme an extravagant console table with a marble top. Once
grandly, garishly gold _ call it Sunset Boulevard Baroque _ the
base of table has been painted soothing delphinium blue.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see things the way Gary does,'' Lawson said. ``He has
the vision; I'm the practical one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawson acknowledges that Guerrette has a transformative way with
unexceptional flotsam. A rococo-style chest of drawers, sludge
green picked out with gold, was given an instant facelift with an
allover coat of slick azalea-pink paint. Guerrette next painted a
wood console from Ikea to match, and placed the blushing pieces on
either side of the front door, to balance a wall in the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to leave everything as I found it,'' said Guerrette.
``This is the first time I've consciously tried to coordinate
colors for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He is presently under the spell of gesso, the chalky white
undercoat that lurks under the gilt surface of frames. ``It gives
things a more sculptural look than glossy white paint,'' Guerrette
said. ``The texture is like plaster.''
</P>
<P>
   He gets it at Andy's Art Supplies on West 23d Street and relies
on it as a sort of esthetic Wite-Out, taming questionable
flea-market finds _ like garish metal sconces, or a fussy mirror
frame _ into submission. (Manufactured by Golden or Prima, the
gesso costs $21 to $35 a gallon, and is available in black or
white.)
</P>
<P>
   Guerrette is a paint manufacturer's dream consumer. To distract
attention from a previous owner's shoddy Sheetrock _ it was applied
directly over the existing walls, so every light switch and
electrical outlet in the house is buried an inch deeper than normal
_ he ennobled the living room with do-it-himself boiseries. Some
are sand-colored, some cobalt blue.
</P>
<P>
   The neoclassical panels were painted freehand, without benefit
of any measuring, and roughly, which gives the room a stage-set
artifice and, better yet, an architectural oomph that it never had.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th century was the most prosperous era in France, which
explains why you see so much furniture from that time in the flea
markets there, especially Charles X and Louis-Philippe,'' said Gary
Guerrette, a decorator and seasoned scavenger who lives in Water
Mill, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Once the co-owner of a Manhattan shop of mid-19th-century French
antiques, Guerrette advises bargain hunters in France to go south.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are massive flea markets in Beziers, Montpellier and
Avignon, and the stuff is really cheap,'' he said. ``Dealers from
the Paris flea market go there, stock up and sell everything for 10
times as much.'' Guerrette said he bought two blue velvet Victorian
slipper chairs in one of those markets for his living room for
$200.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, finding the perfect chair and shipping it home are
two different things. Guerrette _ who also haunts Ruby Beets, a
shop in Southampton, and the Calvary St. George's vintage furniture
shop on Park Avenue _ suggests contacting a specialist in the
packing and shipping of antiques. He relies on Edet, a Paris
company owned by Sandy Simpson and staffed with English-speaking
associates (011-33-1-48-59-11-73).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
