<HEADLINE>
PILOT'S FRIENDS STUNNED BY CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Md., Ohio) (nk) 
 By JOY MURPHY   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER HAVEN, Fla. _ Stephanie Bellegarrigue's friends didn't
know she was interested in flying planes until after she graduated
from Winter Haven High School in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those friends are stunned that the 27-year-old pilot died
in the plane crash Monday that killed golfer Payne Stewart and four
others in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard Stephanie was going to be a pilot, we were
shocked,'' Sherry Anastasio, her former coach in synchronized
swimming. ``We called her spacey, but if she put her head to
anything, she could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was the oldest of Dr. Roberto and Irma Bellegarrigue's three
children. Reached in El Salvador were they now live, the
Bellagarrigues were distraught and could not talk about their
daughter's death.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bellegarrigue, who returned to his native country when he
retired last year, said the family will travel to Orlando, where
his daughter lived.
</P>
<P>
   The family, described by friends as close knit, moved to Winter
Haven from Maryland in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be real devastating,'' said Debbie Banniza,
office administrator at Neurology and Neurosurgery Associates,
where Bellegarrigue practiced for 14 years. ``She grew up with us.
She even worked here one summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Brackett, who retired from the same medical practice,
heard about the accident in France, where he now lives. ``It's
almost like losing one of my own family,'' he said. ``She was much
beloved by her family, a very close family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bellegarrigue, who had logged more than 1,700 hours in
flight time, was one of two pilots who died in the crash. The
captain of the plane was Michael Kling, 43, a former Air Force
fighter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Ms. Bellegarrigue attended Ohio State
University for about a year. Then she transferred to Embry-Riddle
Aeronautical University in Daytona Beach, graduating in 1993 with a
degree in aeronautical science.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school swimmer, Ms. Bellegarrigue traveled the state
and country performing. She also represented her native El Salvador
in international competition, her father said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a good synchronized swimmer,'' said Anastasio, her
former coach. ``She gave it everything she had and then some.''
</P>
<P>
   Anastasio last saw Bellegarrigue in June, when she attended the
wedding of Anastasio's daughter, Dawn.
</P>
<P>
   After college, Bellegarrigue moved to Orlando and worked as an
on-call pilot for various companies until landing a job with Sunjet
Aviation Inc. about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still not sinking in,'' said Carol Greene, who said she'd
known Bellegarrigue for about five years. ``You just keep expecting
her to walk back in the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an awesome pilot,'' Greene said. ``I trusted her. She
didn't scare me.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides flying, Bellegarrigue enjoyed gardening. ``She'd just
gotten the front yard like she wanted it,'' Greene said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
