<SLUG> BC-SF-PROSECUTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SAN FRANCISCO RACE, SUPPORTING DEATH PENALTY IS A LIABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the ``Only in San Francisco Department,'' the
four candidates for district attorney are sniping at each other
over who would send fewer murderers to their death.
</P>
<P>
   Californians have twice voted overwhelmingly to allow juries to
impose capital punishment in certain murders with ``special
circumstances.'' But San Francisco's electorate marches to a
different drummer.
</P>
<P>
   Here, even tentative support for the death penalty among
prospective prosecutors could be a liability among largely liberal
voters. San Francisco is the only county to reject both pro-capital
punishment ballot initiatives in the 1970s. Juries in the city have
imposed the death sentence four times in the past 20 years, and not
at all since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The four major candidates for district attorney, including
incumbent Terence Hallinan, are either opposed to the death penalty
or express extreme reluctance in seeking capital punishment for
killers.
</P>
<P>
   Two challengers _ Matt Gonzalez and Bill Fazio _ have repeatedly
accused Hallinan of waffling on the issue. Both call Hallinan a
hypocrite because the incumbent has made conflicting statements
about his stand on the death penalty since taking office in January
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terence Hallinan has made so many conflicting statements that
I don't know if anyone knows what he really thinks,'' said
Gonzalez, a deputy public defender and opponent of the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can respect a moral difference on this issue, but he seems
to change his mind depending on the audience,'' said Fazio, a
former homicide prosecutor and a ``very cautious'' death penalty
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career as a defense attorney and member of the
Board of Supervisors, Hallinan has been against capital punishment.
Then, when he ran for district attorney in 1995, Hallinan said he
would support the death penalty in very limited circumstances _
``only in the clearest kind of case'' _ including crimes in which
women or children were tortured to death.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hallinan says he is absolutely opposed to seeking capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not asked for the death penalty in the past four years,
and I will not ask for it in the next four years,'' Hallinan said
at a recent candidate forum.
</P>
<P>
   But his office unsuccessfully sought the capital punishment once
_ seven months after Hallinan took over as top prosecutor _ during
the murder trial of Victor Diep and Than Wu in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Hallinan clarified his position,
saying that he had not ``initiated'' any new death penalty cases
since taking office. He inherited the 1992 Diep-Wu case from
predecessor Arlo Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply followed through with the plan to seek the death
penalty,'' Hallinan said. ``It was a heinous, brutal killing of a
9-year-old boy who was murdered for insurance money. ... I said
that I would let the jury decide, and they did. They went for life
without parole instead of death. I'm absolutely satisfied with that
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan said he had had a change of heart after spending four
years in a job that allowed him ``the sobering power'' to make life
or death decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, I promised to look at every single case that
might merit the death penalty,'' Hallinan said. ``I promised to
carefully evaluate these cases and only seek the death penalty in
the most heinous, clear-cut cases. Now, after four years in this
job, I see that there are no clear-cut cases. There are always some
complicating factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in murder cases with special circumstances, he will
seek life a sentence of life in prison without the possibility of
parole.
</P>
<P>
   In two other special circumstances cases Hallinan inherited, he
allowed the defendants to plead guilty to murder with life
sentences without parole, in return for avoiding a possible death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the district attorney candidates, only Fazio has sent a man
to death row.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Fazio's first murder cases, Russell Coleman was
convicted in 1981 of raping and sodomizing a woman, and then
strangling her with her own pants. Coleman, 48, is still on death
row after his capital sentence was set aside but then re-affirmed
on appeal last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that in four years in office I would never seek
the death penalty,'' Fazio said. ``But I wouldn't rule it out. It's
a tool that is available to prosecutors in the state of California.
It should only be used very rarely, in those most terrible cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who criticizes Hallinan and Fazio on the issue, called
on all candidates to support a ``death penalty moratorium,'' saying
that ``moral leadership on this issue should start in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Castleman, also a candidate for district attorney, said
that all this focus on the death penalty was misguided because
``juries here don't like it, and it has no deterrent value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not object to it so much on moral grounds as I do believe
that it does not work,'' said Castleman, a former prosecutor who
specialized in white-collar crimes. ``There are no studies to
indicate that the death penalty in any way serves as a deterrent to
murderers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
