<SLUG> BC-BUYER'S-EDGE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technology is raising the bar with state-of-the-art kitchen
fixtures that make food storage, meal preparation and cleanup a
snap
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Take a look at what manufacturers have rigged up for
the kitchens of the new millennium, and you'll be dazzled by
gleaming stainless steel, brushed chrome and control panels that
glow like the inside of a Boeing cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The latest dishwashers will come with pullout drawers rather
than pull-down doors, and one company even has a prototype of a
refrigerator that includes a built-in computer screen on the door.
With Electrolux's Screenfridge you can send e-mails and check out a
built-in library of recipes. And Sharp Electronics has its own
prototype: a microwave that pulls out like a drawer. But that's
still a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are the Jetsons would blink in disbelief at these
ingenious kitchen devices.
</P>
<P>
   But looks and slick tricks aren't everything in the new century.
Apparently speed cooking is.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers are falling all over themselves to offer customers
fast cooking with excellent results, says Bob Wells, associate
merchant for appliances at Expo Design Center at Perimeter Mall in
Atlanta. ``These companies are looking at the consumer's lifestyle
and realizing that people are too busy to stay home and spend a lot
of time cooking,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   However, that doesn't mean we want to swap flavor for speed.
After all, a microwave will cook a steak in a few minutes, but who
would want it?
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest items is Advantium by General Electric. It's
not a conventional oven, but through the use of light, it cooks
oven-quality meals in a fraction of the time it takes in a regular
oven. It requires no preheating and uses 25 percent less energy
than a conventional range.
</P>
<P>
   GE claims Advantium browns, crisps and even bakes. And with the
push of a button it converts into a fully functional microwave.
Expect to pay $1,200-$1,399 for the oven, which is on the market
now.
</P>
<P>
   While consumers might be cooking with the speed of light, they
could have a hard time finding their refrigerators, which will
blend into the woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   Sub-Zero's latest refrigerators and freezers meld seamlessly
into kitchen cabinetry. And forget the rule that says the freezer
belongs with the fridge. The company offers mix-and-match
components for infinite flexibility and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you can design your unit to look exactly like a
bookcase complete with drawers. Each drawer can be either a
refrigerator or freezer compartment.
</P>
<P>
   While rich woods are hot, they're also pricey. Today's consumers
are still opting for kitchen appliances in more traditional
finishes. Wells says stainless finishes are top sellers, with black
coming in second and white third.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are introducing a darker version of off white
such as biscuit and bisque, which is quickly gaining popularity.
Avocado, coppertone and harvest gold have had their day for now.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing never seems to change: As the 21st century
approaches, it's a sure bet that the kitchen _ even with its sleek,
high-tech look _ will remain the heart of the home.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rosie, the Jetsons' robotic maid, would have to agree.
</P>
<P>
   A HIGH-TECH KITCHEN
</P>
<P>
   Hadco, a Suwanee appliance distributor, has several fully
operational kitchens so you can see the appliances
</P>
<P>
   in action through demonstrations that include the making
</P>
<P>
   of a four-course meal.
</P>
<P>
   This kitchen grouping features a stainless steel 600 Series
Sub-Zero refrigerator and freezer ($2,999 and $3,199); Thermador
Dual Fuel cooktop with four gas burners and two electric ($1,849);
Thermador self-cleaning oven ($3,599); and a Bosch Millennium
Series dishwasher ($999).
</P>
<P>
   DISHWASHING DYNAMICS
</P>
<P>
   Fisher &AMP; Paykel DishDrawer ($1,500) consists of two independent
wash drawers to give you a variety of washing options. You can put
delicate crystal in one half and more heavily soiled pots and pans
in the other. This innovative dishwasher is perfect as a second
dishwasher in a butler's pantry. At Expo Design Center.
</P>
<P>
   TWIN BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Gemini range ($1,399-$1,499) by Maytag provides two separate
ovens
</P>
<P>
   in the space of one. The range's dual ovens are designed to
prepare several dishes simultaneously at different temperatures.
The self-cleaning upper oven features 1.2 cubic feet and has a
``keep warm'' and a toasting feature. The full-size lower oven at
4.0 cubic feet is also self-cleaning. Both have broiling
capability. At Best Buy.
</P>
<P>
   WASH AWAY
</P>
<P>
   Those with laundry rooms on a second
</P>
<P>
   story might consider a second washing
</P>
<P>
   machine and dryer for the kitchen. Bosch
</P>
<P>
   offers convenient under-counter washers
</P>
<P>
   and dryers ($1,699/set) that take up little
</P>
<P>
   space. Note that front-loading washers don't use an agitator _
allowing more space for laundry. Also, front-loaders tumble
clothes,
</P>
<P>
   for less wear and tear. At Hadco.
</P>
<P>
   WINE TIME
</P>
<P>
   The Sub-Zero 400 Series wine storage ($3,949) maintains a
constant temperature and a nearly ideal humidity of 60 percent to
prevent corks from drying out. The high-tech units come with an
optional lock and also tie in to your home security system. And you
can customize them with wood panels to match your decor. They come
in four sizes, holding from 46 to 147 bottles. All have the ability
to store half-bottles as well as magnums. At Hadco.
</P>
<P>
   WARMING TREND
</P>
<P>
   Commercial looks in the home kitchen are gaining in popularity.
This handsome warming drawer by Viking ($987-$1,431) lets you keep
food warm like the pros. The electric warming drawer comes in 27-,
30- and 36-inch
</P>
<P>
   widths and features moisture control and temperature settings
from 90 to 250 degrees. You can warm plates, proof bread or serve
steaming soup. At Expo Design Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
