<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-AWARDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVY WEIGHT DESIGN AWARDS HONOR SIX 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six innovators will be lugging weighty chunks of the
here-and-now home as the latest winners of the Daimler Chrysler
Design Awards. The awards, menu-shaped slabs of cast tombasil, an
alloy similar to white bronze, weighing in at more than 15 pounds,
will be presented in a ceremony Thursday night at the Four Seasons
restaurant in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   This years winners are John Maeda, a digital artist at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Media Laboratory; Karim
Rashid, an industrial designer who gave trash receptacles unsought
sex appeal with his plastic Garbo wastepaper basket; Peter Girardi,
founder of Funny Garbage, a digital design production company;
Pablo Ferro, a film maker of title sequences, among them the
fractured face of Steve McQueen in the original ``Thomas Crown
Affair'' and the credits in the more recent ``L.A. Confidential;''
Gael Towey, creator of the Martha Stewart look in all its guises,
and the architectural team of Jesse Reiser and Nanako Umemoto,
recent finalists in the competition to redesign the Penn Station
rail yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Daimler Chrysler Design Awards, presided over by Chee
Pearlman, editor in chief of I.D. Magazine, and Leslie Gill, an
architect, was created six years ago to recognize what Ms. Pearlman
described as ``problem-solvers on a higher plane.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize, which comes with $10,000, is both prestigious and
idiosyncratic, honoring a melange of the well-known and the obscure
and unsung. Frank Gehry and the designers of the popular iMac
computer have been recipients, as have Philip Zimmermann, a master
cryptographer and creator of a popular standard for encoding
e-mail, and the engineering team for the Mars Pathfinder, which
invented the air bags that broke the fall of the Mars probe as it
rammed the red planet.
</P>
<P>
   The weighty new trophy was designed by Todd Williams and Bille
Tsien, Manhattan architects and honorees in 1998. They chose
tombasil, which is used in the fabrication of fire hose nozzles,
ship propellers and inlaid tomb inscriptions (thus the name),
because, Williams said, it's ``strong and malleable, cool and
modern, but also warm and traditional.'' Tombasil also happens to
be the material the architects selected as cladding for the new
Museum of American Folk Art in Manhattan, for which ground was
broken just last month. Williams said, ``We designed the award so
that people could use it as a trophy, a bookend or an ingot of
metal to be melted down.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they manage to muscle it home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
