 &HT;    Where to get hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to
help you locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track
down every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the
column will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag.
Write us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at
buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please include your name, the city you live
in and daytime phone number)
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was a store manager for A&AMP;P, and although I do not eat it,
I know a lot of people will be looking for the Jane Parker
fruitcake this holiday season. Have any other chains made
arrangements to carry them? We had customers who came from out of
state to buy these popular fruitcakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Doyal, Forest Park(Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: For you folks who go nutty over fruitcakes, the corporate arm
of A&AMP;P has come to your rescue. You can order these traditional
cakes at 1-888-451-4444. A 3-pound cake is $14.75 plus shipping; a
4 1/2-pound cake is $17.50 plus shipping. Pay by Visa, money order
or certified check. Each light fruitcake comes in an airtight
holiday tin that keeps it fresh for weeks (maybe years, some might
even joke). Jane Parker fruitcakes are filled with glazed
pineapple, whole and broken cherries, golden raisins and citron
peel and topped with pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Guiltless Gourmet Spicy Bean Dip in the
glass jar. I know Harry's Farmers Market carries their chips but
not the dip. If you could help, I won't have to stock up when I
visit Chicago next month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laura Hassett, Alpharetta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: You can finally get that spice back into your life. We found
your Spicy Black Bean Dip (16-ounce jar, $2.79) at Kroger, 3979
LaVista Road, Tucker (770-939-6304). This dip, a blend of black
beans, bell peppers, jalapeno peppers and spices, contains no fat
or cholesterol. Two teaspoons contain 30 calories, so go ahead and
dip in.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Most grocers carry the Guiltless Gourmet items in the
natural/health/nutritional food sections of their stores.
</P>
<P>
   You can also order all the Guiltless Gourmet items through
Atlantic Fitness &AMP; Nutrition, at 1-800-929-2543. To read more about
the company, and find recipes, visit online at
www.guiltlessgourmet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find the book ``Get a Good Life'' by Emily
Wilson and Dudley Shearburn. For the life of me, I can't find it.
Please help.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carolyn James,
</P>
<P>
   Charleston , S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Now that you will be reading ``Get a Good Life'' by Dudley
Shearburn and Emily Wilson, you can get on with your life. Order
the book directly from the publisher, Wildwood Press, at
336-922-5254 for $9.99 plus shipping. The Web site Amazon.com sells
the book for $10.99 and Barnes &AMP; Noble stores can order it for
$12.99. The book, by Shearburn as told to Wilson, is a collection
of amusing stories about Shearburn's life raising seven children,
on her own, while getting her Ph.D. Both writers are from the South
_ Shearburn from Birmingham, Wilson from Columbus _ and now reside
in Winston-Salem, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter complains about feeling the ``crack'' in the
middle of two single beds she's put together as a king. Do you know
where I can purchase the foam insert to smooth out this problem?
</P>
<P>
   _ Marsha Tunick, Marietta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: Your daughter will soon sleep like a queen. This gizmo is
called a twin-to-king converter. Simply push two twin beds together
and lay the 8-inch-wide cushioned polyester/acrylic pad on top and
along the center gap between them. A belt attached to the washable
pad wraps around both and secures them together. It takes just
minutes to convert twins to a king. The Hammacher Schlemmer catalog
has the converter for $42.99, item No. 73804G. To order:
1-800-543-3366.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Three years ago, I visited a relative in Ketchum, Idaho, and
enjoyed Cock 'n Bull ginger beer. When I returned to Atlanta, I
tried to locate it. No luck. Help! This is the best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anthony C. Murphy, Alpharetta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: This is not a cock-and-bull story. The aforementioned,
non-alcoholic ginger beer contains triple the amount of ginger than
that of ginger ale, according to Daniel J. Meyers, majority owner
of C-B Beverage Corp. in Minnesota. ``That's what gives it the
extra zing,'' says Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   While once available nationally, the product is now only on the
West Coast. However, Meyers plans to once again roll out the beer
to other parts of the country, when he can find distributors. Until
then, you must rely on Western friends to mail you a four-pack of
12-ounce bottles, which ranges from $2.99 to $3.99. If you're
interested in this ginger beer, write to: C-B Beverage Corp., P.O.
Box 49, Hopkins, MN 55343. The company will keep your name on file
and contact you when it becomes available in your area.
</P>
<P>
   Originally this ginger beer was served at the now closed Cock 'n
Bull Pub in Hollywood, Calif. It was, and still is, used as a mixer
for making a Moscow Mule _ a jigger of vodka, juice of half a lime,
ice cubes and ginger beer _ and giving the drinker quite a kick.
Today, Meyers says sales are primarily to those who enjoy a soft
drink with extra ginger.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
