<HEADLINE>
DEAL REACHED ON DISMANTLING NATION'S FIRST COMMERCIAL NUCLEAR POWER
PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE GENIELLA   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ After 20 years of regulatory wrangling,
California's Public Utilities Commission has set the stage for
early dismantling of the nation's first commercial nuclear power
plant.
</P>
<P>
   In what is seen as a precedent-setting agreement for the
nation's nuclear power industry, the commission next month is
expected to formally authorize Pacific Gas and Electric Co. to
spend $7 million of ratepayers' money in return for the utility's
commitment to begin decommissioning the Humboldt Bay plant,
possibly as early as 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1963, the Humboldt plant was shut down 23 years ago,
after an earthquake fault was discovered running beneath it. The
region surrounding Humboldt Bay is considered to be among the
nation's most quake-prone.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, state and federal regulators, PG&AMP;E representatives
and spokesmen for a Humboldt citizens group that waged a two-decade
battle to get the plant shut down and removed agreed that the
utility commission's deal paves the way for early decommissioning
of all aging commercial nuclear power plants across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humboldt Bay will be the first nuclear power plant to be fully
dismantled in the United States,'' said Scott Fielder, an attorney
for the Redwood Alliance, the Humboldt citizens' group. Fielder
said the temporary storage technology PG&AMP;E plans to use at Humboldt
Bay will serve as a model for other power plant operators facing
similar dismantlings.
</P>
<P>
   Alec Arago, a PG&AMP;E spokesman, said the company can now move
ahead to secure a federal license to temporarily store spent
nuclear fuel at the Humboldt Bay plant site in concrete ``dry
casks'' until the federal government constructs a long-sought
national repository for all nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   Redwood Alliance was credited by an administrative law judge for
the PUC with breaking a stalemate between PG&AMP;E and state
authorities who had held up the company's plans. The state refused
to agree to spend ratepayers' money unless PG&AMP;E committed to early
dismantling.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E agreed to the state demand, after Redwood Alliance showed
how the utility could save at least $47 million in annual
inspection costs if it dismantled the Humboldt Bay plant 10 years
earlier than originally planned, according to the PUC decision
released Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
