A0278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2K-SCHOOLS28-COX     10-27 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SCHOOLS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TWO-THIRDS OF SCHOOLS, COLLEGES NOW Y2K COMPLIANT
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of the nation's school districts and
colleges said their key computer systems are Y2K compliant in a
study conducted this month, the Department of Education reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The department called the figures ``significant progress'' from
the summer, when only 28 percent of school districts and 30 percent
of postsecondary institutions said all their mission critical
systems were fully compliant.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is troubling that more than one-third of school
districts and colleges are not yet compliant, said John Koskinen,
chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion.
</P>
<P>
   The main concern at this point for schools without Y2K-compliant
systems is that their margin of error is extremely slim at this
point, Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the delays vary, said Marshall Smith, deputy
secretary of education, at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Many communities focused first on health and safety issues,
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``School districts may have been on the second tier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the delays might be attributed to the
tendency of school districts and college administrators to view Y2K
compliance as an information technology issue, not something
requiring their immediate attention, Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken them a long time to understand how much they rely
on information technology,'' Koskinen said, adding that school bus
pick-ups are often controlled by computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Education has encouraged schools to
incorporate Y2K readiness into classwork with an activity that
allows students to pinpoint areas in their schools that might
require updating, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately it's a local issue,'' Smith said. ``We're prepared
to support that effort as we roll 65 days into the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men emphasized that since Jan. 1 falls on a Saturday,
schools have three days to make sure their systems, particularly
the ones controlling heat, fire alarms and security, are
functioning properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three days, if well spent, can save us and parents a lot
of grief. Schools need to keep working up through the first because
it's the first, second and third of January,'' Smith said. ``Those
will be the most critical days.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late to start, said Dave Alston, a spokesman for
the General Accounting Office, which commissioned a survey for the
Senate Committee of the Year 2000 Technology Problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually you have to get these systems in order,'' Alston
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
