<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL-LIFE DRAMAS OF SINGLE MOTHERHOOD
</HEADLINE>
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do Hollywood producers know about single motherhood?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, if you've been watching ``Once and Again'' on
Tuesday nights is, apparently, very little. In case you've missed
the show, the ABC drama stars the extremely sexy and well-eyebrowed
Sela Ward, whose character is newly separated and has two lovely
children. In the car-pool line at school one day, she sees an
incredibly dishy man dropping off his progeny. What fortune! He's
divorced! The two happy Beautiful People _ free from any personal
issues or anxieties _ begin the coupling process with a series of
nail-biter situations that dare to ask such deep questions as,
``Should I call him back if he calls me?'' and ``Will he notice my
cellulite when we're nuzzled in my fresh, white 350-count cotton
percales?''
</P>
<P>
   The big drama moments come when Sela's ex-husband stops by to
kiss her on the forehead and tell her he ``just wants her to be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, pleeeeease.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the show's co-producer, Marshall Herskovitz, is divorced
himself (says my reliable-source sister, who lived down the road
from his ex-wife in Santa Monica), but perhaps life in LaLa Land
has made him immune to real-world problems that obviously lie
outside the province of the Beautiful People.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of a) helping the lovely Sela keep her day job
and b) retaining my personal commitment to Tuesday-night
television, I hereby humbly offer Herskovitz a sampling of
situations from this past week in my own life as a real single
mother. Note that it's a hybrid lifestyle that involves Issues of
the Married (even though, technically, I no longer am), the Rampant
Anxieties of the Single Female and a whole host of new experiences
peculiar to the Single, with Children.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Herskovitz, feel free to pluck any or all of these poignant
snapshots for your show.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese restaurant on a Thursday night: Nice white tablecloths.
Kids are on best behavior. Feel good about life. Tell kids that
their dad has decided to go to Scotland for a Halloween party so
they'll spend that whole weekend with me _ won't that be fun? Kids
seem unaffected. Kindergarten daughter puts egg roll down. ``Any
other news from `Dad'? '' she asks, forming her fingers into
sarcastic little quote marks as she says the word Dad. Wonder for
the 35th time why ``Dad'' took a then-5-year-old to see ``Austin
Powers,'' where she learned this Dr. Evil mannerism. Wonder if
daughter has deeper issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pediatrician's office on a Friday night: Here for my daughter's
6-year-old checkup. Nine-year-old son, in full football pads having
just come from practice, smells like a goat. He's jumping up and
down behind the doctor's back and glaring at me. Doctor leaves the
room for moment and son rushes over. ``Mom, I can't believe you.
Fix your shirt. The doctor can see your bra.'' Classic example of
being Single, with Overprotective Children.
</P>
<P>
   Son's Saturday morning football game: Ex-brother- and
sister-in-law (does this make them ``outlaws?'') arrive. Haven't
talked to them since separation, 2 1/2 years ago. Ignore their
attempts to ignore me and bridge the 3 yards between us. Try to
keep forced smile despite their far-right, self-righteous comments.
Must maintain harmony. Might as well be Married.
</P>
<P>
   Single anxiety on Saturday night: Reading ``Bridget Jones'
Diary,'' the hilarious novel about neurotic 30-ish London woman who
is single. I'm at home. Alone. Have fever of 100.5. Think Bridget
is lucky: At least she's exchanging lively, flirtatious e-mails
with her boss. Envy her full life.
</P>
<P>
   Single anxiety on Sunday afternoon: Boyfriend from 1998 leaves
message while I'm at Garden Ridge, buying 100 tea candles. He's
returning my call, returning his call. Yes, he's had a great
birthday weekend. It's super to be 27. He's on his way to his
mother's, but I sounded sick on my message. Can he bring me some
soup? Decide to pretend I didn't get message. Wonder what I was
thinking in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Might as well be married on a Sunday night: Ex-husband calls to
say he has to go out of town for business tomorrow. He'll be gone
for a couple of days. Was supposed to have kids until Wednesday.
Can I take them? (Do I have choice?) Have no one to pick up kids
from after-school program for these days, so I'll have to leave
work early. It's the week before my yearly evaluation, but surely,
this will all be OK, right? Have flashback to pre-divorce days when
ex actually said his job was more important than mine. Wonder how
things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Might as well be married again on Monday: Get mysterious letter
from IRS in mail. Says back taxes are due, from when married,
filing separately. Call ex on cell phone. He says, ``Don't worry,
it's all taken care of.'' Feel dependent. Feel helpless. Feel
married.
</P>
<P>
   Sickly single on a Wednesday: Drink too much with girlfriend
after work. Try calling most recent ex-boyfriend on cell phone. No
answer. Realize he's probably out with new girlfriend, getting on
with life, being happy. Feel sad. Console self that this is for the
best because tomorrow night is Taste of the World PTA meeting at
the elementary school and need to bring apple pie. It's 11:30.
Drive to Tom Thumb and buy $3.99 pie, along with two six-packs of
Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Single parent pressures in the a.m.: Wake up early Thursday.
Feel great! On highway to work by 8:11. Going to be early! Will
make fabulous impression for week of annual evaluation! Cell phone
rings. Ex-husband says he forgot to tell me that last night in
daughter's take-home folder there was a note saying to bring pies
to school in the morning, rather than the evening. Turn around. Go
home. Get pie. Drive to school. Go to daughter's classroom. Get
caught in the Pledge of Allegiance part of the proceedings. Feel
embarrassed that I don't know the Texas pledge and have to fake it.
Daughter gives me a big hug. Feel great again. On highway by 8:30.
Late for work. .MDRV/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
