A0282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-ASSASSINS-TEX     10-27 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ASSASSINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ASSASSINS' SHOOTS ITSELF IN THE FOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
SARAH LUNDAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Assassins''
</P>
<P>
   by Jerry Jenkins and Tim LaHaye
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Tyndale Press, $22.99
</P>
<P>
   You know that trite saying about books, ``It was so good I
couldn't put it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Think the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assassins,'' by Jerry Jenkins and Tim LaHaye, was so bad I
couldn't keep picking it back up. It literally sat on my coffee
table half-read while I thumbed through cheesy magazines and
flipped on the television.
</P>
<P>
   This book caused a rabid reader to avoid her favorite pastime.
</P>
<P>
   When I first began to read ``Assassins'' I realized that,
although its Christian message is sincere, its style is stale. It
seems as if Jenkins and LaHaye were fearful that writing with
pizazz might upset God.
</P>
<P>
   The book's eschatological plot centers on Revelation and a group
of newly converted Christians who are struggling to live under New
Babylon, a regime that wants to kill all Christians. If you've read
Revelation, you pretty much know what to expect. The authors' only
challenge was creating characters to carry the plot.
</P>
<P>
   After the 100-page mark, I began to like the characters and the
style used to describe the last days of the world before Jesus
Christ comes again. But my feeling of warmth for the book was
similar to the feeling I get watching a soap opera: I had invested
myself in getting to know the characters, so I wanted to know what
would happen to them in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assassins'' is the sixth installment of 12 books in the Left
Behind series planned by Jenkins and LaHaye. It ranked No. 3 on the
hardcover Christian bestseller list last month, and it also ranked
No. 4 among fiction bestsellers on the Amazon.com list.
</P>
<P>
   For the life of me, I cannot figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   The book is entertaining, but not well-written. The dialogue can
be confusing. At times, I didn't even know who said what.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the poor transitions in dialogue, a 12-year-old could
read this series. Oh, but that would override the need for the
publishers to print a ``Left Behind: The Kids'' series for children
10 to 14, which they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the previous installments in the series _ which also hit
the bestseller lists _ are carrying this one by reputation. I
haven't read the previous books. Evidently, those books introduce
the Antichrist and describe the chaos that occurs when Christians
begin disappearing, as Revelation says they will when the end is
near.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I did respect about ``Assassins'' is that it didn't
assume I had read the previous books. At the beginning, there is an
easy guide to the characters, listing their names and backgrounds.
My favorite characters are Tsion Ben-Judah, a Christian convert in
his late 40s who works as the prophet to thousands of underground
Christians. He posts daily messages about the events of the future
on the Internet. I also found myself liking one of the ``enemies,''
as Jenkins and LaHaye call them. Leon Fortunato was a more
believable character than some of the other polished Christians. He
made mistakes, as real people do. And his facial expressions were
often described in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins and LaHaye seem to hold the other characters back by
making them two-dimensional, black and white. The Christians are
flawless believers and the enemies are flawlessly evil, according
to the authors.
</P>
<P>
   But I can't forget to mention Rayford Steele, the former 747
captain for PanContinental who is the focus of this installment. I
didn't like him, and maybe that's why I didn't like the book. After
about 150 pages, I tired of Steele's all-too-predictable thoughts
and mood swings. He was a Christian who doubted his role as the
head of a safe house concealing other Christians. He obsessed about
killing Nicolae Carpathia, the ruler of New Babylon, the man
Christians believe to be the Antichrist. The reader knows this much
about Steele in the first 50 pages. But the book keeps returning to
it for the full 413 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this book drags because of the publisher's decision to
extend the series. Tyndale, a Christian publishing company, had
originally slated ``Left Behind'' as a six-book series. As the
first titles began to fly off the racks, Tyndale obviously saw the
advantages of adding more books.
</P>
<P>
   I believed I would like this book. I wanted to like this book. I
wanted Jenkins and LaHaye to be the next Frank Peritti, who is one
of few other authors who have crossed over from Christian to
secular bestseller lists. Peritti's ``This Present Darkness'' made
me think that Satan had spirits roaming the Earth influencing
people. Peritti's writing was fast and exciting. He made me believe
that Satan was imperfect and God would win the world.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins and LaHaye fail in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
