<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-RED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR RED
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-28REDNYT (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the year of the scarlet woman.
</P>
<P>
   Once scorned, she's now leading the fashion parade into the next
millennium. But we're talking clothes, not professions, and whether
it's rose, ruby or rouge, tomato or vermillion, red is red-hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout history, red has signaled excitement, dynamism,
danger and sex. Red is intense, passionate, dramatic, energetic,
aggressive and daring. It is the second most powerful color,
following black,'' says Leatrice Eiseman, executive director of the
Pantone Color Institute and author of ``Colors for Your Every
Mood'' (Capitol Books; $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   Eiseman, a former San Fernando Valley resident who now works for
the New Jersey-based Pantone company, studies the psychological and
physiological aspects of color and predicts color trends for 100
countries around the world. She says she knows why we're seeing red
this fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last holiday season of the century and there's a
spirit of excitement. And red says it better than any other
color,'' Eiseman said. ``It's energetic, but also smacks of
nostalgia, taking us back to a time when we always wore red for the
winter holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the historical significance of red. In ancient
times, red dye came from the Far East and was therefore expensive.
It was the color of kings and religious royalty and thought to be
the color of life and energy in the Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have even shown, says Eiseman, that brain function, as
measured by electrical responses, is more affected by red than any
other color of equal intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Justina Vail, star of TV sci-fi adventure ``Seven Days,'' (8
p.m. Wednesdays on UPN), hasn't done any scientific studies on the
color, but she knows red turns heads.
</P>
<P>
   The auburn-haired actress who lives in Los Angeles and
Vancouver, says her favorite color used to be olive green until she
wore a red gown to an awards show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. I got so much attention,'' she said
with a sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   But she says it took a lot of nerve to wear it. ``It's very
sexy, and you have to have confidence to wear it ... even to wear
red lipstick,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   East Coast designer Calvin Klein says fire red is his signature
color this year, worn layered over other brights or played against
neutrals; while Bill Blass claims women want colors such as
bittersweet orange to spike up their colorless wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, West Coast designers such as Max Azria for BCBG have
cooled down their reds with a blue base and described sweaters,
skirts, shoes and coats as ruby, garnet and vermillion. And it's
the same color story at other local design houses, including ABS,
Laundry, Guess? and XOXO.
</P>
<P>
   According to Eiseman, blue-toned reds are more sophisticated and
elegant, while yellow-based reds are considered more immature,
energetic and sexy, which is why they go so well with animal print
fabric (a favorite combo of locals Eduardo Lucero and William B.).
</P>
<P>
   It also explains why career consultants advise against wearing
red to job interviews. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SCOLIOSIS-SURGERY-TEX     10-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOLIOSIS-SURGERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PROCEDURE STRAIGHTENS SPINE WITH LESS TRAUMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long gone are the days when patients spent a year lying flat on
their backs in full-body casts to correct severe spinal curvature.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, too, are the casts and braces of 20 years ago that
immobilized patients for up to four months after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a few cases, gone are the long surgical incisions that
have been necessary to insert rods and hooks and screws to
straighten the spine without a cast since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Cox, 11, has four tiny scars that mark where surgeons
at Texas Scottish Rite Hospital for Children implanted a 6-inch
titanium rod and seven screws to straighten her nearly 50-degree
spinal curve in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has four little nicks, basically _ and a much straighter
spine,'' says Steve Richards, orthopedic surgeon and assistant
chief of staff at Scottish Rite, in Dallas. Richards led the
orthopedic surgeons who made four smaller-than-1-inch incisions to
insert the tiny camera and all the tools necessary to fuse the
spine and properly place and tighten the rod.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional surgery involves attaching two metal rods and
multiple hooks to the spine through a 12- to 14-inch incision down
the middle of the back.
</P>
<P>
   For younger children with a lot of growth ahead, such as
Jennifer, it is also necessary to fuse the front part of the spine
to prevent twisting and deformity. That requires an additional 4-
to 5-inch incision in the chest and the removal of several spinal
discs and a rib.
</P>
<P>
   Thoracoscopic anterior spinal instrumentation and fusion, as the
new procedure is known, requires one rod installed through four
keyhole incisions.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure was developed in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just ecstatic that Jenny's surgery could be done this
way, without a major incision,'' says Bethany Cox, Jennifer's
mother. ``She was up walking around in two days, and is back in
school full time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny, who lives in Wichita Falls, says it was ``a little
scary'' being the first to have the new procedure in the Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   She tires easily and can't take phys ed yet, and she is wearing
a protective plastic jacket for the first few months, except when
she showers or goes to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Because she is not supposed to lift more than 5 pounds for a few
months, her sixth-grade teachers have provided an extra set of
books so she can keep one at home and carry only notebooks back and
forth to school. She is more concerned that she can't pick up her
cat for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   After six months, she will be free to do anything she wants _
except play on a trampoline, her mother says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once her spine has healed, she will have no restrictions, no
limitations,'' Richards says. ``If she wished to participate in
gymnastics, she could give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer's mother first noticed the crook in her daughter's
spine seven years ago, when the child was 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see a curve already then, and her right shoulder was
higher than her left,'' recalls Bethany Cox. ``Her right scapula
(shoulder blade) winged out in back, and when she was sitting she
had a pronounced rib hump. She started curving so young, I knew
something was terribly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors began talking about the need for surgery when Jennifer
was 6, but the family was hoping to put it off until she was 13 or
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put her in a brace 2 1/2 years ago, but then last year,
it started getting worse real fast. In five months, her curvature
went from 40 to almost 50 degrees, and we knew it was going to get
worse, so we opted to do surgery now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer has idiopathic scoliosis, meaning the cause is unknown.
But orthopedic surgeons at Scottish Rite also treat children who
have scoliosis caused by birth defects, spina bifida, cerebral
palsy and muscular dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   About four of every 1,000 children develop scoliosis that is
severe enough to require treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are numerous reasons for it. I estimate we do 250 to 300
spine surgeries to correct scoliosis each year,'' Richards says.
``Scoliosis treatment is our most visible specialty to the
community. We have seven orthopedic surgeons on staff, working for
the hospital. Patients come from all over Texas. There is no
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards went to California to learn more about the new spinal
surgery after Jennifer's mom found some information about it on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea he was going to do that. I was amazed. He was
curious, but it was new, and he had to be convinced it would
work,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Laparoscopes are not new to orthopedic surgery, but spinal
surgery is a new application, Richards says. One of the first
procedures to be done routinely through a scope was knee surgery,
to trim bulging and torn cartilage from damaged knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very uncommon now to open a knee,'' the doctor says.
</P>
<P>
   However, the traditional surgery for scoliosis works so well, he
says, he was hesitant about switching.
</P>
<P>
   After trying thoracoscopic anterior spinal instrumentation and
fusion on Jenny, he says: ``I would use it again. I sure would.
Recovery is quicker because the incisions are so much less
invasive... and from a cosmetic viewpoint, there is no contest.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
