<HEADLINE>
THESE SLATES WOULD SNAZZ UP THE OVAL OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Elizabeth Dole quit the presidential race last week, our
response was, ``Oh, yeah; she was in the presidential race, wasn't
she?'' That's how dull this campaign is shaping up to be. Sometimes
we even have to remind ourselves that Gov. George W. Bush, Vice
President Al Gore and Bill Bradley are in the race _ or at least
that they're not the same person.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are some interesting teases, famous folks who've been
coy about whether they intend to run as independents. Pundits are
busy questioning what business celebs like Warren Beatty, Cybill
Shepherd, Donald Trump and Jesse Ventura have running for the
presidency. We say they have plenty, because at least they'll be
entertaining. Here's our view of what might happen if any of them
won the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty
</P>
<P>
   Vice president: Dustin Hoffman, Beatty's sidekick in ``Ishtar.''
Proved in ``Wag the Dog'' that he knows something about media
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   First lady: Annette Bening. Keeps Beatty from dangerous
fraternizing with vice president and Cabinet members. Plus, has
experience from starring in ``The American President.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of state: Jack Nicholson, whose impish smile and macho
charm appeal to foreign leaders of both sexes. Causes trouble when
he refuses to date women his own age. President never takes him
golfing.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of defense: Sylvester Stallone, after Beatty's
persuasiveness causes Stallone to change party affiliations. Wants
to win this time.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign theme song: Carly Simon's ``You're So Vain,''
supposedly written about Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   Inauguration band: Politically motivated rappers Public Enemy,
inspired by Beatty's film ``Bulworth.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeleton in closet: Appearance in Madonna's ``Truth or Dare''
documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Davidlike retreat: The original Planet Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   White House renovations: All walls replaced with mirrors. His
staff objects, contending that no work will get done.
</P>
<P>
   Possible scandal: Discovery that his sister, Shirley MacLaine,
had a fling with an intern in a previous life.
</P>
<P>
   Cybill Shepherd
</P>
<P>
   Vice president: Christine Baranski, her sidekick on ``Cybill.''
Makes martini-swilling politicians fashionable with her pithy
comments.
</P>
<P>
   First man: Kevin ``(Hercules)'' Sorbo, who once played
Shepherd's love interest on ``Cybill.'' Best-looking first man
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of state: Ron Silver, whose brusque demeanor belies _
or perhaps indicates _ a sharp political mind.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of defense: Bruce Willis. Feuds from ``Moonlighting''
days convince Shepherd that Willis can stand down the nastiest
warmongering despot.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign theme song: ``Nice Work If You Can Get It.''
</P>
<P>
   Inauguration band: Cybill and her bands, despite rumors that her
singing will lead to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Skeleton in closet: Starred in the musical bomb ``At Long Last
Love,'' featuring Burt Reynolds and other nonsingers doing Cole
Porter songs.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Davidlike retreat: L'Oreal headquarters. She's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   White House renovations: All female staffers required to wear
Keds with skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Possible scandal: Elvis, whom she once dated, discovered to be
alive and working undercover as her chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump
</P>
<P>
   Vice president: Bill Gates. The Donald will lay the groundwork
and then sit back as his successor takes over the world.
</P>
<P>
   First lady: Whatever the forgettable name of his newest, much
younger love interest is, she said that she'd marry him within 24
hours if he proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of state: Warren Buffett. Popular with foreign
diplomats until they find out that he's not the guy who sang
``Margaritaville.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of defense: Ted Turner. Ownership of sports teams
helps in strategy and negotiation skills.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign theme song: ``It's All About the Benjamins.''
</P>
<P>
   Inauguration band: Puff Daddy, part of a mutual-admiration
society with Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Skeleton in closet: Marla Maples, who now demands half of White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Davidlike retreat: Trump Tower.
</P>
<P>
   White House renovations: Refurbishes outside to build a facade
of the Taj Mahal.
</P>
<P>
   Possible scandal: Develops addiction to eBay bidding that leads
to bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura
</P>
<P>
   Vice president: ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin. We dare ya to make
fun of him.
</P>
<P>
   First lady: Sable _ the only first lady to have posed for
Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of state: Hugh Hefner, who shares Ventura's sense of
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of defense: None _ instead, challenges intransigent
dictators to steel-cage death match.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign theme song: ``Welcome to the Jungle'' by Guns N' Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Inauguration band: A reunited Steppenwolf.
</P>
<P>
   Skeleton in closet: Like he needs one.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Davidlike retreat: Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   White House renovations: Replaces majority of Cabinet with
scantily clad women who parade through rooms during breaks at
summit meetings. Builds wrestling ring in Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Possible scandal: Whenever he opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
