<HEADER>
A0287 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FARMWORKERS28-COX     10-27 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMWORKERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROPOSAL WOULD GIVE LEGAL STATUS TO SOME ILLEGAL FARMWORKERS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With growers nationwide facing a shortage of legal
farmworkers, a group of bipartisan lawmakers unveiled a plan
Wednesday to change the foreign guest farmworker program.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the current system _ commonly known as the H2A
program for its provision in the law _ claim that it is too
cumbersome and takes too long for growers to be able to hire
foreign workers. The result, they say, is a flood of illegal
workers who often are taken advantage of and who live in constant
fear of being deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulation-ridden H2A program is an example of government
bureaucracy at its worst,'' said Rep. Sanford D. Bishop Jr., D-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Saxby Chambliss, R-Ga., said the bill would give local
farmers the assurance of having legal workers so they ``don't have
to look over their shoulders to see if the INS'' (Immigration and
Naturalization Service) is coming into their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Farm worker advocates opposed similar efforts last year to
change the H2A program, arguing that the bill did not do enough to
protect workers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan _ which is expected to be introduced soon in both
houses of Congress _ would immediately grant temporary legal status
to an estimated 600,000 illegal farmworkers. Those workers could
gain permanent residency status if they continued to work in
agriculture for at least 150 days during the next five out of seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require growers to offer available jobs to
domestic farmworkers enrolled on a computerized database to be
maintained by the U.S. Department of Labor, which already has such
a system for non-farm employment.
</P>
<P>
   If no domestic workers were available, growers would then be
allowed to bring in foreign workers on a temporary basis under a
streamlined H2A guest worker program.
</P>
<P>
   Workers would receive at least the federal minimum wage,
employer-provided housing or a housing allotment, and
transportation if they are required to relocate more than 100
miles. Growers would be responsible for paying all these costs.
</P>
<P>
   Although a similar bill passed the Senate 68-31 last year, it
ran into strong opposition in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Wash., said the bill faces ``an uphill
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
