<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-FASHION-RED-LADN &LR;      10-27 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-RED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR RED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the year of the scarlet woman.
</P>
<P>
   Once scorned, she's now leading the fashion parade into the next
millennium. But we're talking clothes, not professions, and whether
it's rose, ruby or rouge, tomato or vermillion, red is red-hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout history, red has signaled excitement, dynamism,
danger and sex. Red is intense, passionate, dramatic, energetic,
aggressive and daring. It is the second most powerful color,
following black,'' says Leatrice Eiseman, executive director of the
Pantone Color Institute and author of ``Colors for Your Every
Mood'' (Capitol Books; $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   Eiseman, a former San Fernando Valley resident who now works for
the New Jersey-based Pantone company, studies the psychological and
physiological aspects of color and predicts color trends for 100
countries around the world. She says she knows why we're seeing red
this fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last holiday season of the century and there's a
spirit of excitement. And red says it better than any other
color,'' Eiseman said. ``It's energetic, but also smacks of
nostalgia, taking us back to a time when we always wore red for the
winter holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the historical significance of red. In ancient
times, red dye came from the Far East and was therefore expensive.
It was the color of kings and religious royalty and thought to be
the color of life and energy in the Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have even shown, says Eiseman, that brain function, as
measured by electrical responses, is more affected by red than any
other color of equal intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Justina Vail, star of TV sci-fi adventure ``Seven Days,'' (8
p.m. Wednesdays on UPN), hasn't done any scientific studies on the
color, but she knows red turns heads.
</P>
<P>
   The auburn-haired actress who lives in Los Angeles and
Vancouver, says her favorite color used to be olive green until she
wore a red gown to an awards show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. I got so much attention,'' she said
with a sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   But she says it took a lot of nerve to wear it. ``It's very
sexy, and you have to have confidence to wear it ... even to wear
red lipstick,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   East Coast designer Calvin Klein says fire red is his signature
color this year, worn layered over other brights or played against
neutrals; while Bill Blass claims women want colors such as
bittersweet orange to spike up their colorless wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, West Coast designers such as Max Azria for BCBG have
cooled down their reds with a blue base and described sweaters,
skirts, shoes and coats as ruby, garnet and vermillion. And it's
the same color story at other local design houses, including ABS,
Laundry, Guess? and XOXO.
</P>
<P>
   According to Eiseman, blue-toned reds are more sophisticated and
elegant, while yellow-based reds are considered more immature,
energetic and sexy, which is why they go so well with animal print
fabric (a favorite combo of locals Eduardo Lucero and William B.).
</P>
<P>
   It also explains why career consultants advise against wearing
red to job interviews. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MILITARYWASTE28-COX     10-27 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARYWASTE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    6.700 ARMY TRAILERS USELESS BECAUSE THEY'RE UNSAFE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army spent $57 million for ``high mobility''
trailers that were supposed to be towed up to 20 miles per hour
cross-country or 55 miles per hour on highways.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 6,700 trailers are sitting in storage because the
Army has determined they are unsafe at any speed.
</P>
<P>
   And the Pentagon has not figured out how to fix the problem. One
necessary repair will cost taxpayers $4.2 million, but mechanical
experts are still stumped on other modifications that are needed,
said the U.S. General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, in a report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are simple trailers,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who
had requested the study. ``If the Army couldn't properly manage
this contract, how can we expect them to handle high-tech missiles
and other weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The trailers were built to be towed by trucks known as High
Mobility Multipurpose Wheeled Vehicles, the 1990 version of the
Army jeep.
</P>
<P>
   Electrospace Systems Inc., of Richardson, Texas, now part of
Raytheon E-Systems, Inc., won the contract for the trucks but
subcontracted the manufacture to Silver Eagle Manufacturing Co., of
Portland, Ore. A spokeswoman for Raytheon Wednesday had no
immediate comment on the GAO findings.
</P>
<P>
   According to the GAO report, the contractor was not held
responsible for repairing the trailers because the Army accepted
the design in 1996, despite the fact that the trailers damaged the
trucks towing them during testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program office did not believe the truck damage was a
major problem because only three of the trucks were damaged during
testing,'' the GAO said. Later, the Army found that the trailers
were not usable because the trailer drawbar could break,
disconnecting it from the truck and sometimes causing the trailer
to overturn.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, which plans to buy 18,000 additional trailers, is
considering starting from scratch on the design. However, the GAO
concluded that ``it is not clear yet if the Army plans to
demonstrate, prior to production, that the new design will meet its
requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department, in its response, concurred with the GAO
findings and said that, in the future, it would perform tests to
demonstrate that new trailers meet its standards without damaging
the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COWGIRL-HALLOFFAME-TE     10-27 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWGIRL-HALLOFFAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATS OFF TO COWGIRL HALL OF FAMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Western movies were dominated by cowboys,
shaping the image of the Old West held by much of the world. But in
real life, cowgirls filled a big place in the western landscape.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, check the list of those in Fort Worth's National
Cowgirl Museum and Hall of Fame: Pioneering women from writer Laura
Ingalls Wilder to markswoman Phoebe Ann Moses Butler _ better known
as Annie Oakley _ have been inducted, as have an assortment of
artists, entertainers, tribal leaders, businesswomen and educators.
In honor of today's inductees, here are quick snapshots of their
claims to western fame.
</P>
<P>
   Bertha Kaepernik Blancett
</P>
<P>
   She has gone down in history as a champion bronc rider and trick
roper from back in the days when the West was still young.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``Champion Lady Buckaroo,'' Bertha Kaepernik
Blancett rode her way through a 40-year career in rodeos, Wild West
shows and western films with Tom Mix and Hoot Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who broke horses on her family's Colorado homestead,
began riding competitively at the 1904 Frontier Days Celebration in
Cheyenne, Wyo. She continued, evolving from bronc rider to the
``pickup'' who rescues fallen bronc riders, until she was nearly 60
years old.
</P>
<P>
   She was inducted into the National Cowboy Hall of Fame in 1975,
four years before her death.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Norton Jones
</P>
<P>
   This living legend breeds, trains and races quarter horses and
thoroughbreds from the ranch she owns with her husband, Ralls C.
``Punch'' Jones, in southeastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As a young woman she rode western and English styles, and she
rode in the international show circuit and in college rodeo. She
went on to win every major horse show in North America, from
Madison Square Garden to the Concurso Militar in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-H horse-handling school in Albuquerque is named in her
honor, a tribute to her decades of training young people in
handling horses. Several of her students and horses have appeared
on the U.S. Olympics equestrian team.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after seven decades as a horsewoman, she was inducted
into the American Quarterhorse Association Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen her interviewed on Leno or Letterman a few
years back. Julie Krone retired this year as one of America's
leading jockeys, with more than 2,800 races under her saddle, and
$50 million in career purse earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Krone was the first female jockey to ride in the
Belmont Stakes and, in 1993, she became the first to win that leg
of the Triple Crown. She also was the first woman to compete in a
Breeders' Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   Always popular with the news media, she has been on the cover of
``Sports Illustrated,'' and when ABC named her a news person of the
week, CBS News turned around and named her one of five Women of the
Year in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Serpa
</P>
<P>
   This Manhattan native and Vassar College graduate is said to
have brought more positive exposure to the sport of rodeo than
anyone. She does it with a camera.
</P>
<P>
   Serpa left behind her East Coast upbringing and became the first
woman sanctioned by the Rodeo Cowboys Association to shoot inside
the rodeo arena, where the flying hooves and spurs can be dangerous
to anyone not savvy to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Serpa started shooting junior rodeo as a way to pay bills in
Tucson, Ariz., in 1961. She parlayed that endeavor into a
photography career that has gained her entry into the Grand
National Steeplechase in England, the Dublin Horse Show in Ireland
and the Royal Easter Show in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A documentary on her life, ``When the Dust Settles,'' was shown
nationally on PBS in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
