<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, October 28, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ Delta holds its annual meeting Thursday in Boston. Leo
Mullin is expected to be named chairman and shareholders will vote
on several proposals submitted by the pilots' union. (Thurston,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-PRIVACY _ BellSouth is offering a new privacy service,
claiming that it's the final weapon in the arms race between
consumers and callers. ''Privacy Director'' is a service for people
who have caller ID. It makes callers with private or unlisted
numbers identify themselves (or unblock their number) before it
even rings your phone. Then, you either see the number on your
caller ID or you hear them say who is calling. And then you have
the choice of taking the call or not. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-GUATEMALA _ BellSouth has continued its march through
Latin America, purchasing a license for Guatemala. This is their
third country in Central America, tenth country in Latin America
and 14th worldwide. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-WEBSITE _ ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau plans to increase its web presence with a revamped
interactive web site that will allow visitors to make hotel
reservations, buy tickets to different events, plan trips and buy
Ga merchandise. If this goes as planned, the ACVB will be the most
connected convention and visitors bureau in the nation. Officials
expect it to be a revenue generator and plans are to tailor a
separate site specifically for conventions. A conventioneer can go
online and get the day's schedule. etc. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PATENT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Trilogy Software Inc. has filed suit
against Michael Dell-backed CarsDirect.com, alleging that the
company is infringing on one of its patents. The patent, which
covers a broad method for selling cars on the Web, was issued to
Trilogy last year as the company was ramping up its CarOrder.com
site. (Park, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
