<P>
   FBC-INTERNET _ The internet has become part of the pre-game
planning for major college coaches, including Florida's Steve
Spurrier and Georgia's Jim Donnan, whose teams face each other this
weekend in Jacksonville. Both schools have employees who read fans
sites that sometimes offer information about opponents that used to
be impossible to find. Of course, figuring out what's true and
isn't true comes with the deal. (Dolch, Palm Beach Post). 28.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BARNHART _ Tony Barnhart's inside college football weekly
feature, with lead on Florida-Georgia. (Barnhart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UGA-GRANT _ Georgia freshman Charles Grant, highly touted
before the season by coach Jim Donnan as the greatest thing since
sliced bread, showed why Saturday against Kentucky. He scored two
touchdowns on offense and played a solid game on defense. (Towers,
Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   BORLAND _ A profile of Bruce Borland, one of the top golf course
designers in the country, who was one of five people killed Monday
when a Learjet leased by Payne Stewart crashed in South Dakota
after an eerie pilot-less flight over America's heartland. (Tays,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   HORSE RACING
</P>
<P>
   RAC-HORSE-NOSESTRIPS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A winner by a
nose. That long-used racing term has taken on a new meaning, just
in time for the Nov. 6 Breeders' Cup at Gulfstream Park. The
company that developed Breathe Right nasal strips for humans has
introduced similar strips to be worn by thoroughbred horses when
they train or race. (Crittenden, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
