<HEADER>
A0309 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TERRORIST-ASSETS-HNS &LR;      10-27 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-ASSETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BILL WOULD HELP VICTIMS COLLECT CASH FROM TERRORIST STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two senators introduced legislation Wednesday that
would reverse Clinton administration policy and allow victims of
foreign-sponsored terrorism to collect money from the country
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time we make these country pay in some way for pain and
suffering that they have caused,'' Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
told the Senate Judiciary Committee, which held a hearing on the
legislation. The other sponsor was Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 federal law empowers American victims of foreign
terrorist attacks and their families to sue the country responsible
in U.S. courts. Since then, U.S. courts have awarded damage
judgments in a number of cases against terrorist countries,
including Iran and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But the victims have been able to collect their judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Payment of the court judgments has been blocked by the Clinton
administration on the basis that such awards might provoke other
nations to retaliate against the United States and further
complicate relations with hostile governments.
</P>
<P>
   The legal ability of the administration to block collection
stems from a provision in the same law that allows the president to
stop payment of judgments against foreign countries if it is in the
U.S. national interest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed legislation, known as the ``Justice for
Victims of Terrorism Act,'' the frozen assets of any country could
be freed to satisfy U.S. court judgments in terrorism cases and the
president would not be able to block a successful plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``American citizens deserve the right to know that their
government stands with them when acts of terrorism are committed
against their families,'' Mack told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Clinton administration supported the idea that
U.S. families could sue terrorist nations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, after a 1996 incident in which Cuban air force jets
shot down an airplane flown by unarmed members of a Cuban exile
group _ Brothers to the Rescue, the White House issued a statement
saying the president would ``request the Congress to pass
legislation authorizing payment of compensation to the families of
victims out of Cuba's blocked accounts in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Congress passed the Anti-Terrorism Act of
1996, which allowed victims to sue Cuba and other foreign nations
that supported acts of terrorism. Within a year, U.S. federal
courts had awarded $187.5 million to Brothers to the Rescue
families and $247.5 million to the family of Alisa Flatow, a
20-year-old American college student killed in a 1995
Iranian-backed bombing in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said the administration knew of the possible diplomatic and
financial complications when it supported the law in 1996.
President Clinton's later decision to block the award payments
amounts to an ``abandonment of his word and his support for the
families of victims,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Flatow, father of the slain college student, told the
committee that Clinton personally encouraged him to sue Iran after
his daughter was killed. ``I don't think I would have done it had
the president not called me and told me it could be done and that
it was the right thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past two years, Flatow said, the Clinton
administration has ``done everything possible to stonewall my
family's case'' after the family won a judgment against Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat defended the
administration's policy, arguing that the frozen assets of a
terrorist country can be a significant bargaining chip in
international relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, the only leverage we have with a rogue country is (its)
money in the United States,'' Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that in some cases, such as Cuba and Iran, the
large number of potential lawsuits against the country would likely
result in damage awards far in excess of the amount of money that
the foreign nation has in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are literally thousands of Cubans who could win tens of
millions of dollars each,'' Eizenstat said. ``Cuba's frozen assets
in the United States aren't even close enough to the size needed to
pay those people off.''
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members, however, appeared skeptical that U.S.
national security would be harmed by unfreezing the assets of
terrorist countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, the United States doesn't have any
leverage with terrorist countries anyway, so why not hit them where
it hurts for once?'' Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said to
Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz., said the president was ``putting the
interests of foreign countries over his own citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
