<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NEED MORE MINORITY COLLEGE GRADUATES, PERRY SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Annual public college enrollment by Hispanics
must quadruple and for blacks it must grow at an even greater rate
by 2015 if Texas hopes to close the gap between minorities and
Anglos who get four-year degrees, a top education official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate of enrollment, it would take 100 years to
close the gap, Higher Education Commissioner Don Brown told a new
statewide special Commission on 21st Century Colleges and
Universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a longer period of time than we ought to wait,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry appointed the commission of state senators
and education and business leaders to look at how Texas can meet
future training and employment needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an increasingly global economy, advances in
telecommunications and the incredible progress in high technology,
more and more jobs will require a college education,'' Perry told
the 16-member group at its maiden meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today in Texas only about 20 percent _ or 1 in 5 _ of our
citizens will earn undergraduate or graduate degrees. Unless we
encourage more of our citizens to pursue a college education,
whether it's at a four-year institution or at a community or
technical college, Texas will suffer from a growing education
gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic enrollment in Texas public colleges and universities
has increased, on average, by 2,100 per year, Brown said. To keep
pace with projected population growth and to close the gap with
Anglos, Texas must enroll 8,300 more Hispanics per year, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   For blacks, keeping pace with population trends will mean hiking
enrollment by 3,200 each year, compared to the current average
annual increase of only 400.
</P>
<P>
   The gap is particularly significant, several commission members
noted, given that population projections show ethnic minorities
will soon outnumber white residents in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will study population, enrollment and graduation
trends as well as other higher education issues as it develops
recommendations for the Legislature when it reconvenes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas merely maintains the current trends and does not
increase the numbers of Texans with college degrees, Brown said,
the state will face increased spending on prisons, welfare and
Medicaid because of a growing unskilled and undereducated
population unsuited for a technology-based workplace.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, encouraged the group
to look at where major universities are located, noting that there
are no professional programs _ such as medical, engineering and law
schools _ in heavily Hispanic South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Although the percentage of minorities attending college is
increasing, Brown added, minority enrollment is still far below
enrollment of white students, especially when it comes to getting
bachelor's degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, according to Brown's figures, almost 8 percent of
Anglos ages 15 to 34 were enrolled in a Texas public university,
compared to fewer than 4 percent of Hispanics and 4.5 percent of
blacks in the same age group.
</P>
<P>
   And while 57 percent of Anglos enrolled in public universities
eventually got undergraduate degrees, only 27 percent of blacks and
34 percent of Hispanics did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
