<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     10-27 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., NOV. 14, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: About two years ago we had a fold-down stairway installed in
our hall ceiling so that we could get up into our unfinished attic
more easily for storing luggage and similar items.
</P>
<P>
   Now we notice that on cold, windy days we can feel a chilly
draft coming down from around the ceiling door or panel that covers
this ladder opening.
</P>
<P>
   We believe this is wasting fuel and would like to insulate the
opening. What do you think is the best way to do this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The best way to insulate such an attic opening is to build an
insulated plywood box that fits over the opening as shown here. The
box should be easily removable (it can be hinged or simply lifted
off when necessary).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to lining the inside with rigid, foil-faced
insulation, the box should have weather-stripping installed around
the rim on all four edges so that it will form a reasonably air
tight seal when in place over the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I live in a rented house that is not air conditioned, so I
cannot install a regular whole-house attic fan to help cool it.
</P>
<P>
   I do not like (and cannot afford) a room air conditioner for
each of our bedrooms, but have been told that installing a large
window exhaust fan will work almost as well. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   A: A large window exhaust fan can serve to bring cool air into
one or two bedrooms, although it will not be as effective as a
whole house attic fan.
</P>
<P>
   However, such a fan will only help if turned on after the sun
goes down and outside temperatures drop lower than the indoor
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The fan will be most effective if installed in the window of a
room other than the one you are actually trying to cool.
</P>
<P>
   The fan draws hot air out from inside the house while
simultaneously pulling in cool air through one or two open windows
in the adjoining rooms _ or even in rooms on a different floor.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure that except for opening the windows in the bedroom you
are trying to cool, all other windows in the house are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our bathroom has plastic tile on the wall that was put up
years ago with some type of mastic adhesive. What can I do to
remove this tile so that I can paint or paper the walls?
</P>
<P>
   A: Use a wide flat scraper or chisel to pry off the tiles, then
use a scraper to remove as much of the mastic as possible.
</P>
<P>
   If the walls are plaster you should be able to get most of the
mastic off by scraping and sanding, even if you have to use an
electric sander to get it all off.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the walls are gypsum board (drywall) then scraping
may be impossible without damaging the surface. In that case you
may have to replace the drywall _ or install another layer of
drywall on top of the existing layer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a water stain on the top of my beautiful wood desk.
What can I do to remove this stain and repair the original finish?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most water stains on varnish, lacquer or similar finishes
show up as a white mark or ring. This usually means that the stain
is in the finish only and has not penetrated deep enough to
actually be in the pores of the wood, so refinishing is not often
required.
</P>
<P>
   This type of stain can usually be removed by rubbing with a rag
that has been moistened with alcohol. If this doesn't work, try
using camphorated oil instead.
</P>
<P>
   If this still doesn't do the trick, try rubbing with a rag
dipped into toothpaste _ preferably one of the brands that
advertises it has extra ``whiteners'' in it (these actually contain
a very mild abrasive).
</P>
<P>
   Spread a little paste over the stain, then rub vigorously with a
piece of cloth wrapped around one finger. If this dulls the finish
you should be able to restore the luster by waxing or polishing.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
