<HEADLINE>
A POLITICAL SLAP IN ANY LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone knowing the modest size of  &UR; Dianne Feinstein &LR; 's war
chest, Rep.  &UR; Chris Cox &LR; , R-Newport Beach, said on Tuesday, would
surmise that South Bay Republican  &UR; Tom Campbell &LR;  has a good chance
of beating her for the Senate. ``I am surprised,'' he said, ``she
only has a million dollars and some in the bank after six years,
and that suggests her heart's not in it.'' Cox said he had called
Feinstein personally to discuss this point of view, a frankness
that might seem surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, though, when it's viewed as another way of saying what
Capital Style alleges Cox said about Feinstein at the recent
California Republican Convention in Orange County: ``She's old, fat
and lazy, and her husband doesn't want her in politics anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox says he never said that. ``That's not the way I'd express
myself. I called Sen. Feinstein and told her so. I'm going to write
a letter to the editor, which they told me they would print. ...
It's an opportunity fiction piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital Style stands by its story, insisting that two of its
reporters heard the quote. ``We're owned by the Economist,'' said
editor  &UR; Bill Thomas &LR; , ``and we make very few mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox referred to Roll Call, the Washington newspaper from which
Capital Style spun off. ``It's just not journalism,'' he said.
``...It's a high school newspaper we have on our campus here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIBRARY OF CONGRESS WANTS KING PAPERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Members of the House of Representatives are negotiating with the
 &UR; Martin Luther King Jr. &LR;  Center for Nonviolent Social Change to
make the most expensive Library of Congress purchase ever: a
collection of King's papers.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has appraised the 80,000 or so documents and valued
them at $30 million. Rep.  &UR; Jim Clyburn &LR; , D-S.C., sponsor of a bill
authorizing the purchase, told Roll Call he's hoping that the King
family will lower the price ``as a gift to the nation. ... I do
believe, that if approached directly and by the right people, that
they would be benevolent with this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The library's most expensive past purchase was a Gutenberg
Bible, bought in 1930 for $1.5 million. The 1815 purchase price of
 &UR; Thomas Jefferson &LR; 's library was $23,950.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLEARING AN ART BUY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A recent purchase of an 8th century Mayan stone carving by the
de Young Museum in San Francisco was approved by the governments of
Mexico and Guatemala because neither country thought it could claim
origin.
</P>
<P>
   The stela, which was bought from a private collection, was
attributed to a civilization that straddled both countries.
Concerned about looting ancient cultures, Fine Arts Museums
director  &UR; Harry Parker &LR;  and curator  &UR; Kathleen Berrin &LR;  consulted
officials in both: The Guatemalans said it probably was a Mexican
work; the Mexicans said it was probably Guatemalan. Both OK'd the
buy. And the Guatemalans said the San Franciscans were the first
Americans to have consulted them before making a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Bill Clinton &LR;  fell asleep during a White House screening of
``Music of the Heart'' last weekend, but his guests weren't miffed,
says MSNBC. ``We were in the president's private screening room,''
said  &UR; Gloria Estefan &LR; , who's in the movie, ``and at one point he
had to get up to go to the bathroom, &LR;  and brought back popcorn for
people. Do you know how awesome that is?''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Chris Morano  &LR; says the owner of a BMW Z3 that bears a ``B
HUMBLE'' license plate is a much nicer guy than the juxtaposition
of plate and car would indicate. And on Townsend Street,  &UR; Andy &LR; 
 &UR; Orrock &LR;  overheard a guy telling some pals, ``Oh yeah, if I were a
girl, I'd definitely be bisexual.'' And cartoonist  &UR; William &LR; 
 &UR; Hamilton &LR; , where are you?  &UR; Dan Henry &LR;  said that all conversation
``ground to a stony silence'' at one of those trendy inner
Mission/east of Potrero cafes when a woman exclaimed loudly to her
companion, ``Donald, this isn't about the cocaine!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Upon leaving Costco,  &UR; Daryl Glen  &LR; accepted a dozen and a half
eggs in exchange for his e-mail address, a trade he realized was
eggs for spam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: How do you feel about your boobs? A: I'm really attached to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Courtney Weaver interviews Patricia Arquette in Allure
magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
