<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheaper Digital Camera Connects Directly to PC
</P>
<P>
   UMAX, a company known for its scanners, is introducing a
low-cost digital camera on Monday that borrows a feature from
palm-size devices: linking to a PC with a single touch of a button.
</P>
<P>
   The camera, called Astracam, connects to a Windows-based
computer through a cradle that is plugged into a USB port. Press a
button on the cradle and images from Astracam's memory load onto
the computer. The cradle also recharges the camera's two AAA
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Astracam has a list price of $199 but will sell for considerably
less at some discount outlets, making it one of the least expensive
digital cameras on the market. The tradeoff is that it offers only
medium resolution and few features. There is no flash, and no
preview screen, and there is also a lag between the time the
shutter button is pressed and the photograph is taken; slow shutter
speed means any movement results in a blurry image.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the camera, which can store up to 46 images
and can make voice recordings through a built-in microphone, comes
with software that makes it easy to e-mail images, create greeting
cards or make screen savers from photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Images can be modified for brightness or contrast, and the
inclusion of Adobe Photo Deluxe Home Edition allows advanced
special effects like making a picture look like a charcoal
drawing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Roy Furchgott
</P>
<P>
   Digital Video Camera Is Freed of Its Tether to the PC
</P>
<P>
   Cams _ tech slang for tiny video cameras for personal computers
_ have been popping up in all sorts of shapes and styles. The
latest, Video Blaster Webcam Go, is the first to free itself from
its wired connection to the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Creative Labs, this $150 digital-camera-to-go can
snap individual pictures and snippets of motion pictures, all of
which are easily uploaded to the Internet or attached to e-mail.
The camera can also be used to set up video conferences, and,
detached from its wired base, it can be used like a point-and-shoot
digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   With four megabytes of on-board memory, the camera delivers 90
good-quality 640 x 480 images (or you can get more than 200 images
at a much lower resolution) in Internet-ready JPEG format.
</P>
<P>
   _Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Making It Easy to Put TV Signals on Your Computer
</P>
<P>
   TV cards, which let you watch television on your computer
monitor, have been slow to gain popularity. Cable hook-ups and
antennas are often not conveniently located near computers, and
some people don't like the distraction of a television running in a
window on their monitor while they're trying to work.
</P>
<P>
   But another big reason for the slow adoption of TV cards is that
selecting and installing the right one can be complicated. They
come as stand-alone cards or, in the case of the the market leader,
the ATI All-In-Wonder 128, as part of a state-of-the-art graphics
card.
</P>
<P>
   So before you buy one, you have to know which of an alphabet
soup of slots your computer has _ older ISA, newer PCI or a special
slot for graphics cards, the AGP. Then you have to open your
computer to install it, which strikes fear in many a consumer's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   A new product from the consumer division of Pinnacle Systems, a
leader in professional video editing equipment, promises to solve
the complications of installation. Its Studio PCTV is an external
device that plugs into any computer equipped with a USB, or
universal serial bus, port.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to accepting up to 128 channels, the $99.95 device
can record screen snapshots, full TV programs or home videos on a
hard drive, recordable CD or Zip disk. It also comes with an FM
tuner.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ATI card, it includes software for video editing, video
conferencing and producing streaming video for the Web, offering
yet another way to amaze family, friends and unsuspecting party
guests with those videotapes you shot 11 years ago at Sea World.
</P>
<P>
   _Rob Fixmer
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MP3 Goes on the Road: A Digital Player for the Car
</P>
<P>
   Portable digital audio devices, commonly known as MP3 players,
continue to evolve faster than the music they play. A new
Atlanta-based company recently introduced a twist on an old idea:
an MP3 player for the car.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a bloated pager, the Ego is designed to tap into
the car's stereo system through the cassette-tape player with an
adapter similar to ones used by portable CD players. It also
features a built-in port that permits a more direct connection to a
car's stereo system.
</P>
<P>
   Like all MP3 players, the Ego, made by I2go, has no moving
parts. It stores and plays its music, also like all MP3 players, by
way of computer chip and electronic storage technology.
</P>
<P>
   For the Ego, the storage is managed by Compact Flash II memory
cards; the same slots can accommodate IBM's new micro drives for
removable storage. The player has no on-board memory for audio
storage, but it does have two card slots, giving it the capacity to
store up to 680 megabytes of near CD-quality music and much more
for voice recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The player, which comes in three shells _ black, clear and
translucent blue _sells without memory for $189. A player that
includes a 96-megabyte memory card sells for $329.
</P>
<P>
   The Ego also includes software to help users download and
organize MP3 files when the player is connected to an
Internet-connected computer. The software can also convert e-mail
text into voice files, storing them in the player in the MP3 format
so they may be played back when the player is attached to the car's
stereo system.
</P>
<P>
   The Ego will be sold on Web sites, including www.I2go.com,
beginning Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   _Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Live From Las Vegas, a Concert on the Internet
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet grows, bigger stunts are needed to attract
attention. It's hard to imagine what will top the online iBash that
the new streaming video company, Pixelon, will stage this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to call attention to its new ability to send
full-screen, live pictures over the Internet by giving a party in
Las Vegas, hiring acts like the Who, the Dixie Chicks and Faith
Hill and broadcasting their performances live. The show begins at
2:30 p.m. on Friday, Pacific standard time, and ends at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Pixelon is a small, tightly held start-up company that is
reaching out to the public with a big gesture to demonstrate how
its Web-based solution could replace old-fashioned television.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fenne, Pixelon's founder, said that the company was able
to shrink the size of the data stream to about 100,000 bits per
second, about a third of what the standard, MPEG, would use to
represent the moving pictures. The solution represents several
years of serious mathematical research into how to represent images
on the screen with the least amount of data.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also investing heavily in placing proprietary
technology at the local substations to which home computers would
connect. These points of presence, or POPs, are getting a huge bank
of disk drives to hold video for delivery on demand as well as a
satellite link for picking up live events like the Las Vegas
concert.
</P>
<P>
   The new system also includes a technology that will tailor the
advertisements shown to the demographic information about a viewer.
If the scheme works as planned, a 23-year old man who used the
Pixelon network to tune into a talk show like ``Oprah'' would still
see advertisements for a forthcoming monster truck rally and
wrestling festival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Peter Wayner
</P>
<P>
   A New Web Site for Armchair Marathoners
</P>
<P>
   As race time approaches for the 30th New York City marathon on
Nov. 7, runners, spectators and enthusiasts can get a preview of
the 26.2-mile pageant of sweat, muscle and determination by way of
a new Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, an official Internet sponsor of the race, has joined
the New York Road Runners Club, which puts on the race, in
developing a site that offers training tips, weather reports,
suggestions of the best locations to see the race, marathon trivia
and screen savers.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site www.nycmarathon.msn.com is set up to track each of
the 30,000 registered runners, via sensors on their sneakers.
Statistics will go on line as soon as they become available, and
the information will be searchable by runner number, age group,
country, city or state.
</P>
<P>
   _Michel Marriott
</P>
</TEXT>
