<SLUG> BC-CAPUTO-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE VOYAGE': SENDING THE BOYS OFF TO MEET THEIR FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, the title of Philip Caputo's tumultuous new novel,
``The Voyage,'' appears to refer to a strange seafaring journey
undertaken by four young men.
</P>
<P>
   On a June morning in 1901, Cyrus Braithwaite, a craggy Boston
millionaire, rows a dory with his three sons, Nathaniel, 16, Eliot,
15, and Andrew, 13, out to his two-masted schooner, Double Eagle,
moored off the shore of the family's summer estate in Maine.
Presumably they're embarking on their annual weeklong summer
cruise.
</P>
<P>
   But Cyrus has commanded the boys to do an unusually vigorous
overhauling of Double Eagle this year. He seems in a darkish,
autumnal mood as he accompanies his sons to the yacht. He has
brought no personal gear with him. Once aboard, he inspects the
boat, hands each of the boys $10 and announces: ``You boys are to
leave as soon as I'm off this boat. You are not to show your faces
until September. That money should last. If it doesn't, don't ask
for more, because you won't get it. Understood?''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he climbs back into the dory and takes his leave.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Cyrus do such a mystifying thing? Sybil Braithwaite,
his great-granddaughter, wonders too, there having been no record
of the trip that she is at first aware of, or any family talk of
it, in the succeeding 100 years. So she sets about to write an
account of the voyage, using the ship's log, which turns up, along
with her unusual ability to imagine the past. She will try to clear
up other mysteries as well: why the boys' mother was in a Boston
hospital and the puzzling behavior of their half-brother, Lockwood,
who has somehow displeased Cyrus.
</P>
<P>
   The oceangoing part of ``The Voyage'' is a reckless adventure. A
former reporter who has written eight other books, among them ``A
Rumor of War,'' a memoir of Vietnam, and five works of fiction,
Caputo has mastered nautical terminology and the language of
seascape. The trip starts off slowly, with the boys paying social
calls and picking up a Yale friend, Will Terhune, as their
navigator. But as Cyrus probably anticipated, the boys' restless
spirits get the better of them and they decide to head south to
visit the Florida Keys, where Cyrus once worked in the wrecking
business. They get caught in various storms, visit one of Cyrus'
wrecks with disastrous results and end up shipwrecked off the
northern coast of Cuba, where they undergo their ultimate loss of
youthful illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the deeper you get into Caputo's adventure, the more you
become aware of a second voyage the title refers to: the passage to
understanding why Cyrus acted as he did. This trip is not nearly as
satisfying as the first.
</P>
<P>
   During the sea journey, little light is shed on the mystery.
True, the boys pay a visit to an aunt in Beaufort, S.C., who hints
at something they don't know about their mother. In retrospect you
realize that some of their experiences reflect the family's dark
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   What they go through on their trek could conceivably be what
their father had in mind by sending them into exile, particularly
during one storm when they hear ``a prolonged bass groan, deafening
and demented, as if a lunatic were pounding on the keys of a
cathedral organ.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage continues: ``It was, each of them thought in his own
words, the cry of that power in the universe which hated integrity
and sought disintegration, which despised order, peace and
contentment and sought their opposites. It was the voice of
chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of their adventure, however, when they finally arrive
in Havana physically injured, out of money and emotionally
traumatized, and they arrange for the American legation to cable
their father for help, all they receive in return is a telegram
that reads: ``Look not to Isaiah but to Corinthians for passage
home. Stop. C.R.B.'' The mystery is only compounded.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the final 35 pages of ``The Voyage,'' heavy curtains
are torn away, sudden light is allowed to penetrate the darkness,
chambers within chambers are opened. Consistent with what turns out
to be the theme of the novel, skeletons turn up in the closet of a
family ``whose ways and opinions had once been templates for the
nation, whose sovereignty was once unquestioned.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's all a bit too much, absurd in its compression, gothic
in its extremeness and insufficiently connected to the sea journey
that precedes it. It's a little like the moray eel in the Straits
of Florida that lunges out of a little cave in a coral wall _ ``a
hideous, green, eel-like thing as thick as a man's arm and twice as
long'' _ and sucks a chub into its maw and shoots back into its
lair, shocking Eliot Brathwaite over the bestiality of aquatic
life.
</P>
<P>
   Or like one image of a sunrise at sea: ``A golden shimmer
appeared where the horizon was supposed to be, then a red sun
pushed up, like the head of some fiery infant bulging out of the
gray sea's womb _ water giving birth to its opposite element.''
</P>
<P>
   Too sudden, too obvious, too brutal and finally, a cartoon
treatment of a subject deserving of both grander and subtler
handling.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE VOYAGE'
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Caputo
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 416 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
