<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS CALL FOR HATE CRIMES LAW TO PROTECT HOMOSEXUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats on Wednesday urged Congress to approve
new protections for gays and lesbians by expanding federal laws
that already provide harsher penalties for crimes motivated by
race, religion or national origin.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of gay rights and other supporters of expanding the
hate crimes legislation to cover sexual orientation, disability or
gender were outraged to discover last week that Republicans had
deleted the provision from a spending bill funding the Commerce,
Justice and State departments.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., a lead sponsor of the hate
crimes proposal, told a news conference that crime triggered by
prejudice ``attack the human spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They send a poisonous message that the majority in society can
assault the minority,'' Kennedy said. ``We must act now to give
federal law enforcement the tools it needs to combat these
senseless and violent acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., also speaking at the news
conference, said violent crimes of prejudice are growing at a time
when crime rates in general are falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigotry and hatred are corrosive elements of any society,''
Leahy said. ``We need to make clear that a bigoted attack on any
member of society diminishes all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The hate crimes legislation gained traction earlier this year,
in the aftermath of the beating death in October 1998 of a gay
student in Wyoming and the June 1998 case of a black man who was
dragged to his death in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who oppose expanding the definition of hate crimes
say it would create separate classes of victims. ``A crime is a
crime,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Republicans oppose the move to broaden the law. In the
Senate, Arlen Specter, R-Pa., is a co-sponsor of the hate crimes
bill.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., said he was
outraged that the Republican leaders dropped the hate crimes
provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice has been delayed and denied for too long,'' Gephardt
said. ``This is a matter of simple decency and what's right and it
should transcend partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Correia, the White House special counsel for civil rights,
said the provision is ``a high priority and the president urges
Congress to enact it as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a gay rights bill,'' Correia said, ``it's a
human rights bill.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest advocacy group for gays and
lesbians, urged the Clinton administration to fight for the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is near death in a partisan ditch,'' Birch
said. ``The issue is whether the Republican leadership is going to
call an ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, the spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi, said it was doubtful the hate crimes
legislation would be included in any spending legislation this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that happening,'' Czwartacki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
