<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ARE ON THE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday has the makings of another white-knuckle day for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Two economic reports will be out in the morning, both of which
will provide new information about the market's greatest fear:
inflation. If the numbers are god, which is to say, price
pressures are modest, the market may breathe a sigh of relief and
rally. If the inflation news is bad, hang on to your hat.
</P>
<P>
   The employment cost index probably has the greatest potential to
spook the market. The index tracks how swiftly wages and benefits
are rising. Since labor costs are a huge piece of any business'
costs, it stands to reason that if pay is on the rise, prices could
be, too.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, despite a booming economy and very tight labor
markets, wages have been climbing an unthreatening 3.5 percent per
year. ``Companies are under competitive pressure to hold down
costs,'' says David Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poors DRI
in Lexington. ``In that kind of environment you cannot afford to
give big pay increases.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few hints that wages are rising more steeply.
Last week McDonald's said its expenses rose because it had to pay
more to attract workers. In general, though, analysts are not
terribly concerned about the wage side of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said for benefits. ``That is the piece we are
worried about,'' says Wyss. Health costs are the biggest
contributor to benefit costs. Thanks to some good luck and the
impact of managed care, medical costs have barely budged over the
past three years. By all indications, that hiatus from medical
inflation is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going back to the bad old days, but the latest news
is not good,'' says Frederick Breimyer, chief economist at State
Street Corp., referring to the sharp increases in health insurance
premiums that have been announced recently.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street expects the employment cost index to rise 0.9
percent Thursday. A gain of over 1 percent will not be looked upon
kindly.
</P>
<P>
   The other key report will be the first release of third-quarter
gross domestic product. Everyone agrees the summer quarter was a
humdinger. The pessimists think the economy expanded at a 4 percent
rate; the optimists predict the number could top 5 percent. The
bigger the number, the more anxious investors will be.
</P>
<P>
   All the gears were clicking in the third quarter. Consumers were
spending, businesses were investing, exports were expanding, and
retailers were restocking depleted inventories. Put it all together
and you get an economy that continues to grow well above the 3
percent pace the Federal Reserve would like to see. ``This is not
where the Fed intended to be,'' says Breimyer.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank did not raise interest rates at its last
meeting, but said it was leaning towards a rate hike. No matter how
the numbers come out Thursday, the Fed is likely to hike rates in
mid-November, say analysts. ``Given their druthers, the Fed would
like to take out a little insurance against future inflation,''
says Wayne Ayers, chief economist at Fleet Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is: What happens after mid-November? Or to put
it another way: Will one more rate hike be enough to satisfy the
Fed that inflation is under control?
</P>
<P>
   Ayers points out that inflation, in fact, is under control. The
rise in prices so far this year has been quite modest. ``It has
been the same story throughout this whole cycle,'' says Ayers.
``The economy goes at full tilt, the labor market is tight, and we
have not seen the wage and price pressures we would expect to see.
It leaves the Fed and everyone else in a quandary.''
</P>
<P>
   Some reassuring numbers Thursday _ modest wake hikes and a good
but not great economy _ might help ease the nervousness a bit. Keep
your fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
