<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-DUTCH-ARCHITECTS-1200     10-27 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTCH-ARCHITECTS-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIC AND GRITTY: A DUTCH TEAM WANTS IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP NOBEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ Architecture is a fractured field.
There are some architects who build but seldom break new ground,
and then there are the experimenters whose idiosyncratic designs
and arcane language can scare off clients with the power to promote
them.
</P>
<P>
   Ben van Berkel and Caroline Bos are succeeding in a different
way.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance van Berkel, 42, and Ms. Bos, 40, behave just
like other experimental architects: their graphic style, leaning
heavily on computer models, can be slick; their language can veer
close to inscrutable ``archispeak,'' and their designs, many
showcasing novel and fluid forms, can be perplexing even to the
initiated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet earlier this year, following a competition to rethink the
Penn Station rail yards in Manhattan, the chairman of the New York
City Planning Commission, Joseph B. Rose, found himself so drawn to
their entry that he invited the Amsterdam-based husband-and-wife
team to his office to inspire his staff.
</P>
<P>
   In singling them out from three other finalists _ and from the
competition winner, Peter Eisenman _ Rose pointed out that,
surfaces aside, ``they did intelligent, insightful and creative
analysis that was also artistic.'' It was an analysis, he added,
``by people who don't have their heads in the clouds.''
</P>
<P>
   In their proposal, a bubbling cluster of work and residential
spaces hovers over a generous park envisioned as a ``lobby'' for
Manhattan. It resulted from a year's study of New Yorkers _ their
cravings for waterfront access, the pressure on waves of commuters
coursing through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gehry, a competition juror, picked up on the rigor in the
architects' work. ``Some of these young people think that they can
do a souffle, and it'll go to the moon, and they're going to be
stars,'' he said. ``For foreign architects to come in and
understand the city like that was very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Berkel and Ms. Bos are building a full-service practice that
they hope can be trusted to tackle everything from boutique private
houses and museums to thornier problems like bridges and train
stations. With a staff of 50, they are trying to project the
competence of a U.S. corporate firm while retaining the star-system
chic that clings to many independent European architects.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of collaboration and seven of marriage, the pair
took their names off the door to form the U.N. (for United Net)
Studio, a network with contractors, engineers and designers, whose
work they say they will synthesize but not dictate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like mixing music,'' van Berkel said, smiling and sliding
the controls of an imaginary recording console. Ms. Bos, the more
grounded of the two, countered: ``It's against the old idea of the
master builder scribbling away on his drawings. If you've built one
building, you know you are only a bit player in the whole
process.''
</P>
<P>
   In their large new office in an old school building just beyond
Amsterdam's outermost ring of canals, the network idea is taking
form: a hotline connects to the offices of consulting engineers
across town; an in-house graphic designer works on architectural
projects as well as the firm's promotional publications.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through their studios last week with a visitor, the
scope of the work was in evidence: A wood and steel bridgelike
table they designed for an office building; a model of a giant
transportation hub under construction in Arnhem, and a
one-of-a-kind ceramic platter. The platter exhibited the spare
folded geometry found in their best-known project, the Moebius
House, completed last year in an Utrecht suburb for a reclusive
family that Ms. Bos called ``the Greta Garbos of architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   As the firm's submission to the rail-yards competition was
turning heads in New York, U.N. Studio was proving itself in a more
rarefied context: the Museum of Modern Art. The Moebius House was
one of 26 projects in the museum's recent ``Un-Private House''
exhibition. Pointing out that the Netherlands has been ``a
peculiarly intense incubator for architectural talent,'' Terence
Riley, the chief curator of the museum's department of architecture
and design, praised van Berkel last week for his handling of the
house's complexity. ``They told Ben, `Don't make it too simple.'''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. The Moebius House is a gorgeous train wreck of
concrete and green-tinted glass that might be easily mistaken for a
study in fragmentation. But as with so much U.N. Studio work,
surfaces are deceiving. The volumes of the house have been set in a
purposeful collision that creates intermingling zones to suit two
work-at-home parents and their two teen-age children. Its amorphous
halls form fluid webs of space that give the house its name.
</P>
<P>
   While it is hard to believe at first that it was not created for
the eye, the seductive masses do seem to be in the service of a
deeper idea: the pursuit of unity through flow.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to achieve an architecture where space and structure
unite to erase all seams, U.N. Studio is heir to a great tradition
of Dutch modernism. In the first decades of the century, the Dutch
were early adapters to the ideas of Frank Lloyd Wright, whose
organic architecture prescribed just this kind of unity, what
Wright saw as aspiring to the principles of nature, not just its
forms. Though the pair bridle politely at this suggestion, their
designs and their new, inclusive practice point at this kind of
organic urge. (When van Berkel is explaining an idea, he invariably
draws figure-eights.)
</P>
<P>
   Add to this inclination a contemporary love of asymmetry and
movement _ they even drive a car with five cylinders _ and you get
U.N. Studio's sweeping design for the central train station in
Arnhem, near the German border. There, working for a constellation
of clients that includes government agencies and the national rail
system, the firm is trying to fashion a transportation complex that
will handle buses, trams, trains, 5,000 bicycles, and 65,000 people
a day. The structure is based on walls that deflect into drooping
ramps and roofs to provide for circulation and shelter within a
unified system.
</P>
<P>
   The urge to express movement seamlessly is also apparent in
their signature public project, the 460-foot tall baby-blue Erasmus
Bridge, spanning the Maas River in Rotterdam. The $342 million
bridge, completed in 1996, synthesizes an amazing amount of
structure and function _ including a section that is the largest
bascule, or counterweighted, drawbridge in the world _ into a
graceful whole that has been nicknamed ``the swan.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sweeping form of the Erasmus Bridge there is evidence of
the influence of Santiago Calatrava, the Spanish architect who
reintroduced lyricism to engineering in the late 1980s. Van Berkel
worked on Calatrava's trend-setting Stadelhofen light rail station
in Zurich in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned everything on that project,'' van Berkel said,
though he did not pick up the decorative tendency in his mentor's
work.
</P>
<P>
   A subtle influence are the interpenetrating forms of Zaha Hadid,
who taught van Berkel at the Architectural Association in London in
the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if U.N. Studio can transplant its broad
practice from the architectural hothouse of today's affluent and
accepting Netherlands. Rick van der Ploeg, the Dutch secretary of
state for culture and media, thinks that a favorable native climate
is underpinning the success of U.N. Studio and the other firms,
like MVRDV, that make up the current Dutch invasion. ``We haven't
got much land in Holland, so we want to invest more in our
surroundings,'' he said. ``In a way architects and designers are
the heroes of a new age.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Studio's latest building, the Museum Het Valkhof, a
regional museum in Nijmegen, opened its doors in late September to
crowds that dwarfed all estimates. Using very large, very simple
elements that the architects call ``big details'' _ an inexpensive
undulating aluminum-stave ceiling, a raw and beautiful system of
solid wood stair rails _ U.N. Studio devised a strategy to make an
uncompromised building on a very tight budget. On a visit last
week, however, van Berkel found a glaring problem: a giant black
sign that the museum had clamped on to a neat concrete retaining
wall. ``Should we just take it off right now?'' he asked, patting
his pockets as if looking for the right tool.
</P>
<P>
   Van Berkel may be a sort of architect's architect, but Ms. Bos
is the firm's secret weapon. She is thoughtful and serious and,
most important, not trained as a designer. She first studied law
and then turned to architectural history and theory. Her outsider's
course has given her a jaundiced view of the profession; she seems
to have a well-developed sense, visible in a glance, of when her
husband is testing the limits of architectural credulity.
``Sometimes when we're talking about spatial effects and flow
diagrams, she just says, `Who cares?''' van Berkel said.
</P>
<P>
   While at the Villa Wilbrink recently, a modest 1994 residence in
Amersfoort that is a meditation on solidity, built in the form of a
bunker for a privacy-loving client, van Berkel remembered an
epigram he admires: ``Architecture is the mother of every ruin.''
Then he explained its birth: ``I said, `All architecture ends as a
ruin,' but Caroline was reading a lot of Freud at the time, and she
fixed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Berkel and Ms. Bos have a daughter, Emily, 7, whom they
raise while working 14-hour days. They typically have dinner at
their home nearby, on the Amstel River, then they retire to a
basement studio to write, draw and play computer games. Their
favorite is Riven, the sequel to the popular game Myst.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of a taste for the fantastic _ and an expression of the
couple's overlapping relationships _ can also be found on the cover
of their latest book, ``Move,'' a boxed collection of their work.
The jarring cover image, a creature they call ``Manimal,'' merges
head shots of the couple with photographs of a lion and a snake. It
is a suitably fierce mascot for an architectural team trying to be
everything at once.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
