u a BC-AMENDMENTS-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      10-27 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMENDMENTS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER SAYS NUMBER OF AMENDMENTS SHOWS NEED FOR NEW CONSTITUTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A key lawmaker Wednesday bemoaned the long list
of proposed amendments to the Texas Constitution on next week's
ballot, but said he doesn't believe there is adequate support to
redraft the entire document.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen amendments, none very controversial, are on Tuesday's
statewide ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that every other year Texans have to go to the polls
and vote on 15-20 amendments to the Texas Constitution is a prima
facie case for the need for a new Constitution,'' said Senate
Finance Committee Chairman Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff joined the consumer watchdog group Common Cause in
lamenting both the length of the ballot and the low projected voter
turnout. But he said his attempt to redraft the 80,000-word
Constitution in the legislative session earlier this year ``didn't
get very far,'' and ``I frankly don't know whether we will try
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically ``tough'' votes on issues such as school finance
make the task unpalatable to lawmakers ``in the absence of
crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since its adoption in 1876, the blueprint for state government
has been amended by voters 377 times. This year's propositions
include policy questions, a bond issue and one amendment aimed at
removing useless constitutional provisions. Also included are
proposals impacting gubernatorial powers, judicial pay and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause Chairman Bill Stouffer said ballots too often
include special interest amendment proposals that ``set up special
funds, tax exemptions or other benefits that are not necessarily in
the public interest.'' He said that less than 10 percent of the
registered voters are expected to cast ballots, and some
propositions in 1997 were decided by as few as 4 percent of those
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly not what we usually think when we discuss
majority rule as one of our dearest American and Texas values,''
Stouffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said Texans may be signaling their concern by avoiding
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that one day the people of Texas will simply stop
going to the polls to vote on constitutional amendments until we
fix it. Maybe that's what they've already done,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Local issues in Houston and San Antonio inadvertently could make
voters there overwhelmingly responsible for the outcome Tuesday,
Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told that in this particular election it's the people in
Houston and San Antonio that are going to decide the constitutional
amendments because they're the only ones that are going to go to
the polls. And the reason is not the constitutional amendments _
it's for arena proposals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a Texas tragedy that we can't seem to come to
grips with the fact that we need a new basic document going into
the next century for Texas government,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Secretary of State Elton Bomer said he, too,
is concerned about a low turnout to address anachronisms in the
``sacred document'' of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing it has been amended many times,'' Bomer
said. ``If it had not been, ministers of the gospel would not be
able to be legislators. If you had ever participated in a duel, you
would not be allowed to hold public office. And indeed, if you had
ever received any kind of public financial assistance, you wouldn't
even be allowed to vote,'' Bomer said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the ballot issues has been the subject of widespread
advertising, either pro or con. But lawmakers who sponsored the
amendments _ and groups that might benefit from them _ have gone on
the offensive in recent weeks to promote expansion of urban
homestead sizes, two mortgage proposals and college student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Few amendments have drawn loud opposition, but Rep. John
Shields, R-San Antonio, has called Prop. 9 a ``Trojan Horse'' and
``smoke screen'' _ a charge its author denied. The proposition,
which would create a commission to recommend judicial salaries,
duplicates the Legislature's functions, Shields said. Voters
probably aren't aware that lawmakers' pensions are pegged by
formula to judge's salaries, he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
