<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COWBOY-ARTIFACTS-TEX     10-27 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-ARTIFACTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOY COLLECTOR HEARS THE CALL OF THE WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Doug Harman has a collection of cowboy
memorabilia that could knock yer boots off. But the president of
Fort Worth's Convention and Visitors Bureau also has a knowledge of
history and art that would impress the most distinguished
collector-connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   Harman can't pass up a good pair of chaps, but he's also the
picture of urban refinement, from his perfectly knotted tie to his
well-shined dress shoes. He is part Wild West, part modern
businessman _ and thoroughly entertaining. Which makes him, in a
sense, the ideal representative of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Harman's collection can be found all over town. Pieces
are on display at the Convention and Visitors Bureau's downtown and
satellite offices, and some of his artifacts were used in an
exhibit about West Texas ranches at the Amon Carter Museum. The
museum also has a large collection of photographs by Erwin E.
Smith, who photographed ranches in Texas and the Southwest during
the early 1900s _ exactly the type of ``everyday life'' details
that Harman studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be a good idea to have some objects on
display that were similar to what you could see in the
photographs,'' said Carter director Rick Stewart. ``We had saddles,
and we had cowboy paraphernalia on display in cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug loaned from his collection and talked to people about
it,'' Stewart said. ``If he had the time, it would have been great
to have installed him as a living exhibition in the show.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Harman's collection so valuable is his encyclopedic
knowledge of the items: when they were used, where they could be
found, how they changed through the years. He will share some of
that knowledge this week when he speaks at the recently opened
Carter Downtown museum. As part of the museum's Fall Fridays series
of lunch-hour speakers, Harman will discuss the work of
19th-century American West illustrator Frederic Remington, using
examples of western artifacts from his collection.
</P>
<P>
   In his downtown office, Harman points to the stirrups, hats and
boots in a print of Remington's 1895 painting ``The Fall of the
Cowboy.'' He explains why the items pictured reflect the era the
painting depicts. The style of boot (very plain, like most
turn-of-the-century boots), the type of spurs worn (he has some
that are similar) tell Harman a lot about the cowboys pictured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remington was quite a collector,'' Harman says. ``He often
used the actual artifacts (he collected) in his paintings _ it was
a way for him to make his paintings authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Harman's office looks a little like a western-wear store. The
walls are covered with chaps and spurs, hats and ropes, and
original paintings and postcards. A bookcase holds cascading piles
of postcards and artifacts of cowboy life.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy paraphernalia overpowers the building's interior. A
closet holds a jumble of boots and old stock-show trophies; a back
room downstairs contains more framed newspapers and pictures. Much
of it is from Harman's personal collection.
</P>
<P>
   He gives a brief tour: Here's a rare stirrup marked ``Fort
Worth, Texas,'' made by a local company for Texas Rangers based in
the city. And over here, a pair of chaps with gold studs that spell
out ``Texas'' _ ``The cowboys were real proud of being from
Texas,'' Harman says, ``so Texas things like that got into the
decoration pretty often.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes photographs by Erwin Smith, and loads of
old Texas maps. Harman points to one: ``You've got Marshall,
Athens, Hillsboro, Phantom Hill _ no Dallas, no Fort Worth.''
Hanging on a wall in the visitor's center is another one, dating
from about 1845. State population: 213,000.
</P>
<P>
   And here's something to study: A turn-of-the-century brand
inspector's book that shows the brands of cattle owners across the
state, providing key information about Texas history. ``It's
exciting ... to touch something with that much history,'' Harman
says, knowing how many miles its owner must have carried it on
horseback around Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Harman says he feels fortunate that his interests and hobbies
contribute to his work. Visitors want to know about the city's
western heritage _ and Harman has ``a certain level of knowledge so
I can talk about western lore and the hats and the boots and the
history and things like that in a reasonable way,'' he says. ``I
think the job and the personal interest have really come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
