<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HALLOWEEN-MOVIES-ART-     10-27 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-MOVIES-ART-2TAKES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDRY AND SCARY: MOVIES FOR HALLOWEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MIRIAM SILVER   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ A lot of heavy philosophizing goes on about
why people want to see scary movies. Real life is just too
frightening, too unknown, too daunting to deal with, so we run to
the movies to see something far worse. We go for the improbable but
eerily possible set-up and then the tidy close that the world can't
ever seem to get in real time.
</P>
<P>
   Horror films _ whether their leading villain is a sci-fi alien,
supernatural creature, homicidal demon or satanic warlord _ bore
into that primal ooze inside us, reaching into our nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Some academics say horror films rise in popularity at the same
rate of extreme social and cultural stress. They provide a
drug-free adrenaline rush _ violence at a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project,'' the indie standout just released on
video, had extraordinary success this year but it is only one of
many terrifying films that can help you mark Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Forthwith, here is a list of the must-see classics, with baby
boomer biases, teen-slasher prototypes, quality British and good
ol' flicks in any genre, conducted from an unscientific poll of
friends, colleagues and those strange slasher-and-horror movie
buffs who tend to glow in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one trend among them, most were unable to come up
with just one great scary film. They couldn't do it, which goes to
show that our list is for suggestions only, not intended as the
last word.
</P>
<P>
   We left out a lot of the contemporary B, teen-slasher flicks
because frankly they are just not good and seem to go mostly for
the a knee-jerk gore shock value.
</P>
<P>
   If you are Internet friendly, check the www.esplatter.com Web
site for comprehensive lists and reviews of horror and slasher
movies. While you are there, don't miss ``Lucius Gore's'' top six
most disgusting movies ever. (They are not on our list.) Another
great place to explore the Halloween genre can be found at
www.filmsite.org/horrorfilms.html.
</P>
<P>
   Still Scary After All These Years
</P>
<P>
   ``PSYCHO,'' 1960. The Alfred Hitchcock thriller with
secretary/embezzler Janet Leigh meeting ultimate psycho and weird
son Norman Bates, played by Anthony Perkins, in the role that
marked his character until his death more than three decades later.
The infamous stabbing in the shower is so terrifying that Leigh was
rumored to avoid showers for years. No blood ever, but everything
seethes. Incredibly charged sex scenes with John Gavin at the
beginning, and not a naked torso in sight. (The Hitchcock runner-up
is ``The Birds,'' 1963, with leading actress Tippi Hedren suffering
nightmares for years after filming.)
</P>
<P>
   ``NIGHT OF THE LIVING DEAD,'' 1968. Director George Romero's
shaky camera, ``Blair Witch''-style, pseudo-style horror flick
about strange atmospheric changes that cause the dead to rise from
their graves and go on a flesh-eating, murderous rampage across the
Pennsylvania countryside. Within the first 10 minutes, the horror
begins, and there is little let up. Especially disturbing: zombies
tearing apart one victim, piece by piece, organ by organ.
</P>
<P>
   They Couldn't Make It Today
</P>
<P>
   ``FREAKS,'' 1932. The macabre movie using real circus ``freaks''
like Siamese twins, dwarfs, armless and legless men and women that
was one of the last made by director Tod Browning. It was Browning
who nurtured Lon Chaney Sr. and the silent horror film, as well as
launched stage actor Bela Lugosi in the classic ``Dracula'' the
year before. While ``Freaks'' is a compassionate take on the lives
circus people, Browning was accused of exploitation, and the film
went into near-obscurity for decades. Still, stunning and
thought-provoking.
</P>
<P>
   Truly Disturbing
</P>
<P>
   ``ROSEMARY'S BABY,'' 1968. Director Roman Polanski's take on the
unholy conception and birth of the devil, with Mia Farrow as the
unwilling mother married to John Cassavetes, a beguiling and
handsome husband who sells his soul to further his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE EXORCIST,'' 1973. More devil stuff. This time,
Oscar-winning ``French Connection'' director William Friedkin's
shocking, truly thoughtful (if you pay attention to the story and
not just the antics of a spinning neck) film of William Peter
Blatty's story of the devil vs. religion in the body of possessed
13-year-old Linda Blair. Mom Ellen Burstyn brings in a priest,
Jason Miller, and the king of exorcists, Max Von Sydow.
</P>
<P>
   ``HENRY: PORTRAIT OF A SERIAL KILLER,'' 1989. Tough to take,
based on a real-life Texas serial killer. It is scary and can make
you feel you are watching a snuff film. Seering psychological
drama; no kid stuff here.
</P>
<P>
   The Classics _ See Them in Their Pure State
</P>
<P>
   ``FRANKENSTEIN,'' 1931. Director James Whale's adaptation of
Mary Shelley's Dr. Frankenstein and the monster he created made
Boris Karloff a deserved star. This is a treat. (Also delightful,
the 1935 ``Bride of Frankenstein'' with Elsa Lancaster.)
</P>
<P>
   ``DRACULA,'' 1931. Bela Lugosi's breakthrough screen role, as
the Transylvanian vampire who needs to suck the blood of others for
his own eternity. Lugosi, unable to ever really shake off the role,
parodied himself in later years and was buried in 1956 with his
vampire cape.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MUMMY,'' 1932. Boris Karloff again in the title role of
Im-ho-tep, a lost ancient Egyptian magician.
</P>
<P>
   ``KING KONG,'' 1933. Still-terrifying special effects now taken
for granted puts the gorilla monster with Fay Wray in his arms atop
the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``CAT PEOPLE,'' 1942. Subtle, the first of horror producer Val
Lewton's films. Sexual horror with new bride Simone Simon cursed
with an ancient panther inside her who arises when she is aroused.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE BODY SNATCHER,'' 1945. A must for today's genetic
engineers, Boris Karloff and Bela Lugosi together in a Robert Wise
film, an adaptation of the Robert Louis Stevenson story on
unethical doctor who doesn't care how he gets the research bodies.
``You can't build life the way you put blocks together,'' says
Karloff.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the Top
</P>
<P>
   ``BLACK CHRISTMAS,'' 1974. Presages the ``chick/slasher'' films
of later years, with sorority sis Olivia Hussey, doomed friend
Margot Kidder, weirdo boyfriend Keir Dullea in a Canadian thriller
about a killer hiding in a sorority house attic, making obscene
phone calls and knocking off a few residents at Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   ``HALLOWEEN,'' 1978. John Carpenter's widely imitated genre
teen-slasher film, with psycho killer escaping from mental ward and
returning to the neighborhood where he killed on Halloween 15 years
earlier. Bad girl gets it, leading to a heroic struggle by innocent
baby sitter Jamie Lee Curtis (daughter of ``Psycho'' star Janet
Leigh), completely clothed, in her first movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SHINING,'' 1980. It's a Jack Nicholson kind of thing; you
gotta love him to go for this screen adaptation of the edgy Stephen
King novel with all of director Stanley Kubrick's excesses intact.
Shelley Duvall is a kick as his naive wife. Nicholson hits all his
notes, long before the notorious ``Here's Johnny'' ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``SCREAM,'' 1996. ``Nightmare on Elem Street'' director Wes
Craven scored a hit with the high school and 20-something crowd
with this teen-slasher flick about worried good girl Neve Campbell,
daughter of mother killed by a serial killer. Lots of gore,
in-jokes and so much hopeless teen stuff that it's instant camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``RAVENOUS,'' 1999. Cannabalism, the Civil War and Indian
folklore. Scary stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Classy British-style Suspense
</P>
<P>
   ``CURSE OF THE DEMON,'' 1958. Skeptical psychologist Dana
Andrews is invited to England to research the devil cult. The film
opens with shadowy shot of Stonehenge, and then some well-appointed
and articulate men sitting in a lovely parlor sipping brandy and
discussing murder and the occult. Very fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HAUNTING,'' 1960. Just one of the many great films by
director Robert Wise an adaptation of the Shirley Jackson story
about young s Julie Harris caught in the spell of a haunted
house. Sci-fi writer Ray Bradbury called this film one of the best,
with Claire Bloom, two classy actresses having such a good time in
the early part of their stunning careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``CHILDREN OF THE DAMNED,'' 1963. Sequel to but better than the
1960 ``Village of the Damned,'' ``Village'' is a Cold War parable
about six alien, highly intelligent children born to earth mothers
in London.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Boomer Biases
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DAY THE EARTH STOOD STILL,'' 1951. Terrific sci-fi with
articulate alien Michael Rennie touching down in Washington to
issue an anti-nuke message to the powers that be, stopping all
machinery on earth to make his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``FORBIDDEN PLANET,'' 1956. Robotic sci-fi, with space travelers
encountering Walter Pidgeon, his daughter and the exacting Robbie
the Robot on a planet he has made his own personal empire, a la
Shakespeare's ``Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``THE BAD SEED,'' 1956. Talk about challenging children. Patty
McCormack as 8-year-old girl who seems to have inherited her
grandmother's murderous tendencies. Subtle psychological terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE TINGLER,'' 1959. This is the famous William Castle flick
that got the director in trouble for rigging some movie theater
seats with electric buzzers to heighten the fear experience. I
``watched'' much of the movie with my cousin's jacket over my head
at a Saturday matinee, but have since seen it again on video, and
swear it is still scary in places and really funny in others. With
the always eloquent and inspired Vincent Price as the doctor who
discovers the source of human fear is a scorpion-like creature that
lives in our spines.
</P>
<P>
   Good Story, Fine Film in Any Genre
</P>
<P>
   ``INVASION OF THE BODY SNATCHERS,'' 1956 and the 1978 remake.
Both very fine, the earlier version with Kevin McCarthy discovering
alien, emotionless pod people, who replicate and take over the
town. Donald Sutherland, Leonard Nimoy and Jeff Goldblum show up in
the '78 version with pod people in San Francisco, sounding
strangely very Werner Erhard-like.
</P>
<P>
   ``WHATEVER HAPPENED TO BABY JANE,'' 1962. A fine second act to
their careers, Bette Davis losing her own mind as she terrorizes
her crippled sister Joan Crawford in the lonely old house they
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``HUSH, HUSH, SWEET CHARLOTTE,'' 1965. Bette Davis again, this
time as demented spinster haunted by 30-year-old murder and
terrorized by a not-as-sweet-as-she-seems Olivia de Haviland.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WICKER MAN,'' 1973. Edward Woodward as a straight-arrow,
religious British constable who travels to an island to investigate
the disappearance of a young girl and discovers pagan free love and
sacrifices. Horror star Christopher Lee as the cult leader in
sideburns, long hair and tweed jacket, swaying to ritual Celtic
songs, considered it his best role. Fans of today's ``Burning Man''
festivals will enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Just For the Fun of It
</P>
<P>
   ``TROG,'' 1970. Joan Crawford's last movie, and she tries to
play it straight, but can't help herself, thank goodness, as
accomplished anthropologist and reluctant spelunker who takes in a
prehistoric cave dweller, known as a troglodyte, tames and mothers
him and fights the evil local developer who wants Trog killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HUNGER,'' 1983. Catherine Deneuve, David Bowie and Susan
Sarandon. Kinky vampire Deneuve looking for blood to survive, with
Bowie as her companion and Sarandon the victim. Need we say more?
</P>
<P>
   ``BEETLEJUICE,'' 1988. Outrageous Tim Burton flick with a
fabulous, utterly uninhibited Michael Keaton as Betelgeuse helping
a dead couple (Alec Baldwin and Geena Davis) killed in a car
accident get the new people out of their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``ED WOOD'' 1994. One more from Tim Burton, a touching movie
with Johnny Depp as the real-life Ed Wood, who made some of the
worst sci-fi horror flicks of all time. With Martin Landau, amazing
as the aging Bela Lugosi. Fans of the old classic horror and sci-fi
films cannot miss this film.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Silver writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
