<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LITERARY-BIOGRAPHY-NY     10-27 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERARY-BIOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EFFORT OF A LIFETIME FOR BIOGRAPHER AND SUBJECT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, France)   By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norman Sherry, a deeply cultivated scholar of English
literature, has been working for more than 20 years on a
three-volume authorized biography of Graham Greene, and that
otherwise happy fact leads to a melancholy observation. Sherry's
first two volumes have been praised by critics. Yet it is close to
a certainty that a relatively small number of people, including
those who love Greene, will buy any of Sherry's eventual three
volumes, and even fewer will read them.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of massive literary biography in general:
the two volumes on Samuel Taylor Coleridge by Richard Holmes,
Benita Eisler's recent 837-page life of Lord Byron, Phyllis
Grosskurth's earlier 510-page work on the same subject, Kenneth R.
Johnston's 963 pages on ``The Hidden Wordsworth: Poet, Lover,
Rebel, Spy,'' or Richard West's recent ``Daniel Defoe,'' a fine and
relatively slender work at 427 pages with the intriguing subtitle
``The Life and Strange, Surprising Adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   In the publishing industry, literary biographies are generally
not profit-making ventures. The authors spend many years
researching and writing them, testimony to the old adage that the
most honorable work does not always bring the most cash. Yet
massive and less massive biographies of writers continue to be
produced and published. This month there is Judith Thurman's
``Secrets of the Flesh: A Life of Colette,'' nine years after Ms.
Thurman's prize-winning biography of Isak Dinesen. There is Fred
Kaplan's new 850-page biography of Gore Vidal, and recent
biographies of William Styron and T.S. Eliot. Soon to be published
are James Atlas' biography of Saul Bellow, Belinda Jack's life of
George Sand and others.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to wax sardonic about encyclopedia-length literary
biographies, to treat them as strange obsessions, eerie instances
of Freudian transference, or maybe just the underused, academized
products of a literary underworld financed by foundations.
Certainly many of them are too long, and take too long to write. I
can see being Greene, but spending two decades reconstructing his
life seems like the very definition of literary vicariousness.
</P>
<P>
   There is something strange about the genre of literary
biography, something unnerving in the degree of dedication to
another person that it requires. But there is something strange and
unnerving about literature too, and that is the point: literary
biography is an emblem of the strength of our commitment to
literature and hence to civilization. It is a mark of seriousness
at a time that, let's face it, is not very serious.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, Sherry, who previously wrote a two-volume
biography of Joseph Conrad and single volumes on Jane Austen and
the Bronte sisters, is an author to be highly regarded. What's
more, his two volumes on Greene are hard to put down.
</P>
<P>
   To put this another way: in the age of ``The X-Files'' and
``Lethal Weapon 9'' (or whatever number we're up to now), it's
reassuring that room can still be made for ancient instrument
ensembles, newly discovered cuts of ``Grand Illusion'' and
prolonged examinations of the lives and works of the writers. That
our culture still produces long literary biographies tells us that
we are not engulfed by junk after all, that the bottom line does
not determine absolutely everything.
</P>
<P>
   Gustave Flaubert once said that he wanted to lead a calm and
boring life so he could be untamed and savage in his novels. The
suggestion is that writers, unlike, say, presidents or explorers of
Antarctica, lead lives of solitude and secondhandness that make
them dull subjects.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not true. Flaubert himself had an eventful life,
which, among many other things, included contracting venereal
disease in Egypt and a tempestuous, letter-producing love affair
with Louise Colet. Greene was a spy for the British during World
War II, which is what brought him to Sierra Leone, the setting for
``The Heart of the Matter.''
</P>
<P>
   For his research, Sherry is said to have visited every place
that figured in Greene's adventuresome life, which makes writing
the biography sound like fun. (Earlier, Sherry duplicated the sea
voyages of Conrad.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, why do some writers devote years of their lives to the
lives of other writers? Why do publishers continue to publish their
sometimes oversize products?
</P>
<P>
   The second question is easier to answer than the first: some
literary biographies do actually earn money, especially in foreign
and paperback sales. Even when they don't, which is most of the
time, literary biographies add luster to a publisher's list and to
the publishing house itself. Besides, editors at publishing houses
are often serious people who wish to do serious work. It is
rewarding to publish a biography of William Blake even if you pay
the rent with vampire novels or the recipes of Oprah Winfrey's
cook.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these motivations apply to the biographers themselves,
especially the concern for literary reputation and literary
seriousness. One could uncharitably say of biographers what
Flaubert uncharitably said of critics: ``One becomes a critic when
one cannot be an artist, just as a man becomes a stool pigeon when
he cannot be a soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   That line, especially the part about the soldier and the stool
pigeon, may be one of the few stupid things Flaubert ever said. But
substitute biographer for critic and there is something to ponder
here. Literary biography is an act of love qualified by envy. It is
estranged identification, or more. Holmes, the biographer of
Coleridge, once said of Leon Edel, the author of the monumental and
magisterial five-volume work on Henry James, that he was ``a
parable of the modern literary biographer's self-immolation in his
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   If writers are the forgers of consciousness, how revealing an
endeavor it is to chronicle the forging. That consciousness is both
public and private, and that is why literary biographers spend a
good deal of time on the private, including the sexual, dimensions
of their subjects. It is interesting to know that the author of
``The End of the Affair'' was at one point juggling a wife and two
mistresses even as he was working for British intelligence. We know
that about Greene thanks to Sherry's indefatigable research.
</P>
<P>
   I myself right now am reading Ms. Thurman's biography of
Colette, a figure who stood at the very beginning of our age of
erotic self-expression and androgynous self-exploration. Ms.
Thurman, an accomplished writer, spent nine years on Colette. From
what I have read so far, it seems to have been worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
