<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0374 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CARMINA-BURAMA-MUSIC-     10-27 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMINA-BURAMA-MUSIC-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING POLISH TO A `PROFANE' MASTERPIECE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Lawrence A. Johnson writes about music for The Chicago Tribune, The
New Criterion and Opera News.  
 By LAWRENCE A. JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even amid the dizzying heterogeneity of 20th-century musical
styles, ``Carmina Burana,'' by the German composer Carl Orff,
remains one of a kind. Written in 1936, this ``profane cantata''
sets medieval Latin texts depicting the pleasures of drink,
gambling and divers country matters.
</P>
<P>
   Primitive in its harmonic cast and rhythmic vitality, the music
conveys a raw elemental quality befitting the sensuality of the
texts. If the devil gets the best tunes in opera, the sinners in
Orff's work get the best choruses.
</P>
<P>
   A less jocose factor is the scent of contemporary Nazi strains
lurking in the work, in both the elevation of the primal and the
exaltation of the Bavarian Volk ideal. Early performances were
lavishly staged in the late '30s, and photographs of those
productions bear an unsettling similarity to Leni Riefenstahl
spectacles extolling the robust physicality of National Socialism.
</P>
<P>
   That immutable taint apart, Orff's score remains a glorious
musical achievement, and ``Carmina Burana'' has enjoyed fine
advocacy on disk, with recordings by Eugene Ormandy, Andre Previn,
Herbert Blomstedt and Leonard Slatkin among the most distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Thielemann's new version with the Chorus and Orchestra
of the Deutsche Oper Berlin (Deutsche Grammophon 453 587-2; CD)
finds an admirable balance between refinement and intensity,
avoiding the standard-issue garrulity too common in performances of
this work. For all the high-gloss orchestral sheen here, Thielemann
also uncovers myriad details of scoring and expression.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any lack of drive or fervor, with the orchestral
clarity only adding to the impact of Orff's more uninhibited pages.
Indeed, Thielemann galvanizes his forces to playing and singing of
tremendous dynamism, and the joyous rhythms of ``On the Green'' and
the riotous drinking choruses have rarely registered with such
Dionysian abandon.
</P>
<P>
   There is more here, too, than a fast ride in a monastic sex
machine. The moments of introspection are just as atmospherically
presented, as in the plaintive chantlike section of ``The Merry
Face of Spring,'' where the conductor sensitively details the
sadness underlying the search for ephemeral physical pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Keenlyside, a warm-voiced baritone, contributes more
elegant singing than is usually heard in this music. Perhaps his
``Burning Inside'' lacks something in pointed bitterness, but the
bibulous Abbot's song emerges as genuinely tragic, generously
swathed in angry self-loathing. David Kuebler's rather grainy tenor
arguably fits the song of the roasted swan.
</P>
<P>
   The tender solo ``In trutina'' has become an improbable
classical hit in England, by virtue of the sweet yet
uncomprehending performance by the preadolescent, apple-cheeked
soprano Charlotte Church. Here Christiane Oelze sings more
knowingly and with great feeling of ``submitting to the yoke,'' and
her raptly beautiful reading is one of the finest on disk.
</P>
<P>
   Thielemann elicits superb singing from the Berlin chorus, firmly
pointed yet rich and vividly atmospheric. The engineering
complements Thielemann's precision with striking clarity, although
the wide dynamic range loses focus in the chorus' quieter moments.
</P>
<P>
   This is another impressive outing for Thielemann, who seems
incapable of making a dull recording.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
