<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 28 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Michael McGarr at (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-ZACARIAS (Los Angeles) -- A day after embattled Los
Angeles Unified Superintendent Ruben Zacarias offered his plan to
rebuild the district, the school board announced plans to fire him
by buying out his contract. By Greg Gittrich, David Baker and
Sherry Joe Crosby. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire,
and ``a'' national wire.)
</P>
<P>
   FLU-VACCINES (Los Angeles) -- In a harbinger of a severe flu
season, the first Los Angeles County case was reported Wednesday,
several months before the bug typically surfaces. And public health
doctors say they are working to determine if the strain found in a
40-year-old Carson woman is covered by the vaccines offered. Tests
could take a few days. By Harrison Sheppard. (Will move on the
``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   ARMENIA-SLAYING (Los Angeles) -- In the largest seat of Armenian
culture outside the homeland, area expatriots reacted with shock to
the slaying of the Armenian prime minister during a session of
parliament. Local Armenians are glued to television sets and radios
for news. They care deeply about activities in the country _ 2,500
of the 60,000 Armenians in Glendale voted in the last Armenian
election. Memorial services are planned here for those who died. By
Lee Condon. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire, and ``a''
national wire.)
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS-LOTTERY (Los Angeles) -- Despite the almost decade long
economic expansion, many Americans have underestimated their
ability to build wealth by saving their pennies, prefering instead
to take their chances with the lottery, according to a survey to be
released Thursday. By Chris Sieroty. (NOTE: This story must not be
released until 7 a.m. a.m. PST.) (Will move on ``n'' California
news wire, the ``a'' national wire and the ``f'' financial news
wire.)
</P>
<P>
   POWER-ONE (Los Angeles) _ Shares of Power-One Inc. plummetted 36
percent Wednesday after the Camarillo-based supplier of electronic
power packs reported strong quarterly earnings but warned that
future sales had slowed slightly. In yet another sign that
investors remain extremely jittery about any sign of weakness,
Power-One lost approximately $200 million in market capitalization
because it has $2 million less in future sales booked. By Jason Z.
Cohen. (Will move on ``n'' California news wire, the ``a'' national
wire and the ``f'' financial news wire.)
</P>
