<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FOCUSES ON `BEAUTY OF ADOPTION' AT IOWA PREGNANCY CENTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBUQUE, Iowa _ Feeling his way through the issues of abortion
and adoption, George W. Bush said Wednesday he would use the
presidency to help private counseling centers that urge pregnant
women to reject abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be looking for ways that I can assist and I am open to
suggestions,'' Bush said on a visit to the Tri-State Pregnancy
Center, which counsels women toward alternatives to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In a related campaign development, Republican rival John McCain,
who has been surging in polls nationally and in first-primary state
New Hampshire while Bush's lead has been shrinking, said Wednesday
he is reconsidering his decision to skip campaigning in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   As a feature of his Republican presidential campaign, Bush has
said he wants the federal government to fund some of the social
service work of private, religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, he said the Dubuque counseling center, funded by
donations from churches and individuals, might not need or want
federal involvement _ echoing an argument often made by opponents
of government funding for private agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The center's leading staffers told Bush during his visit that
the best role for the government would instead be to encourage
donors to support their cause. Directors of other faith-based
organizations where Bush has campaigned on this theme have
expressed similar reluctance to take federal money and then abide
by federal requirements such as open hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wound up the discussion by stating, ``I don't have a
specific role in mind yet'' for the centers, which he said number
3,000 across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who says abortion should be outlawed, explained that he
came to the center with reporters in tow to highlight ``the beauty
of adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's counselors often recommend adoption as an
alternative to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``These events show where my heart is,'' he told a news
conference outside the brick, storefront facility.
</P>
<P>
   Bush routinely told Iowa audiences this week that he would
follow principle rather than public opinion in the White House. But
he has also said that he wouldn't be ready to press for a
constitutional amendment against abortion because the conscience of
the nation does not favor such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he rationalizes the two statements, Bush said,
``America will be ready when we value life.``
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's presidential primary caucuses take place Jan. 24, making
it the first state to award delegates for the GOP and Democratic
presidential nominations next year.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he will participate in at least one early January
debate in Iowa but was ``still discussing'' with advisers how much
other time and effort to expend in advance of the state's Jan. 24
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of Elizabeth Dole and Lamar Alexander, two
centrist GOP figures, McCain is concerned about leaving the middle
of the field to Bush. But Iowa is essentially an organizational
test that requires advanced planning and is not given to late
jump-in candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has bypassed Iowa in part because of his opposition to a
federal subsidy for ethanol, a corn-based fuel additive. He made a
point of that opposition Wednesday at a news conference in New
Hampshire where he appeared amidst dried corn stalks and a black
oil barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator was also implicitly critical of the Iowa
caucuses in which participants go to precinct meetings and declare
their presidential preference when they sign in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be more competitive where there's a secret ballot,''
said McCain, who is hoping to jump-start his candidacy in New
Hampshire and then move on to the primaries in South Carolina and
California.
</P>
<P>
   Although the primary system has not historically been kind to
candidates who were choosy about where they competed, McCain said
he would stick with the old military view: ``You pick your best
ground to fight on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
