<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETRADE FOUNDER DONATES $25 MILLION TO BUSINESS SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The founder of the on-line brokerage ETrade, William A. Porter,
has donated $25 million to the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Sloan School of Management for a new building intended
to foster innovative use of technology in entrepreneurship at the
47-year-old business school.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is the largest the school has received since its
founding in 1952, when Alfred P. Sloan Jr., then chairman of
General Motors, gave a grant that established the MIT School of
Industrial Management, later renamed the Sloan School.
</P>
<P>
   Porter's gift will pay for nearly half of a proposed $55 million
William A. Porter Management Center, which would contain
classrooms, faculty offices and be technologically equipped to
``lead the school into the next century,'' Sloan School dean
Richard Schmalensee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do this right, it will be the first step in moving Sloan
to a higher level,'' Schmalensee said. ``People can say, `It's only
a building.' But we intend this building to shape the way we
operate and the way we function.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter, 70, an engineer who was a Sloan School fellow in 1967,
is counted as a pioneer in Internet commerce development. He began
an electronic service for stock brokers that performed the world's
first on-line trade in July 1983, and later founded ETrade
Securities Inc., the first electronically based business allowing
investors to buy and sell stock over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company, headquartered in Menlo Park, Calif., now has over 1
million active accounts and a market capitalization of $5.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made some substantial money, and I'm quite wealthy now,''
Porter said in a telephone interview. ``Naturally, we give to a lot
of charities, but in talking it over with my wife, we wanted to
make a substantial gift that would help humanity. I'm a technology
guy. I believe technology makes our lives better and better here on
Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter, who lives in Palo Alto, Calif., said he wanted the money
to ``form a stronger fusion'' between the Sloan School and MIT's
scientific and technological departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``MIT is in my opinion the best technological school in the
country, probably the world,'' he said. ``Exploiting technological
innovation requires entrepreneurship and financing and marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT officials said several committees have yet to determine who
will design the building and where it will be built, but that it is
likely to go on the east side of the Cambridge campus, near
existing economics and political science buildings.
</P>
<P>
   After its scheduled completion in 2002 or 2003, the Porter
Management Center would become a central location for faculty and
classes now spread among seven buildings, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
