A0397 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PSYCHIATRIC-HOSPITAL-     10-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHIATRIC-HOSPITAL-1600(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN TREATMENT REMOVES THE STIGMA OF MENTAL ILLNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
WICHITA FALLS, Texas:disobeyed the rules. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out on the second-story porch, a man looks at the campus below,
his hands grasping the metal lattice that obstructs his view. But
the man's stay is more of a respite than a life sentence _ these
days, more than half the patients are sent home within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment has been progressing for decades, says hospital
Superintendent Jim Smith, and it's time for people to stop thinking
of state hospitals as ``scary places right out of grade-B movies.''
</P>
<P>
   TREATMENT TAKES TIME
</P>
<P>
   It's almost 7:30 a.m., and a daily ritual begins.
</P>
<P>
   One woman wanders over to the closed and locked medication
window in the middle of the hallway, waiting patiently for her
usual dose. Several patients obediently take their place in line
behind her.
</P>
<P>
   It's the medicine, most of which began to be developed during
the late 1950s and early 1960s, that gives patients the key to
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It's the daily dose that helps 41-year-old Kathleen Nunley see
through the fog of mental illness long enough to learn how to
balance a checkbook, plant a flower or eat a nutritious meal.
</P>
<P>
   Nunley, who was found to have an illness with symptoms similar
to schizophrenia, sits quietly in the front row of a recent
living-skills class, learning how to rent an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher is trying to show the patients how to read
classified advertisements, but the discussion is quickly
sidetracked by a woman chomping furiously on a piece of gum as she
tells the class about a big fancy house where she once lived.
</P>
<P>
   Nunley watches the other patients, cowering in her chair as if
she were trying to avoid a blow. Perhaps she's hearing the voices
of the ghosts she believes raped her son.
</P>
<P>
   For Nunley, attending and participating in class is progress.
And every time she cooperates, she earns privileges. It could be a
trip to the canteen for a soda or an excursion off campus.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesdays, it means a chance to dance.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun shines through the stained-glass windows of the
campus chapel, ``We will, we will rock you,'' blares from the disc
jockey's speakers.
</P>
<P>
   A tall man with a white knit cap stomps around the dance floor,
weaving in and out of the other dancers, acting out every word of
every song.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Crow, a handsome 23-year-old, lounges on a metal folding
chair, his baseball cap pulled down, hiding most of his face.
</P>
<P>
   But when the disc jockey plays the ``The Electric Slide,'' Crow
lifts his head as if someone had just flicked his ``on'' switch,
and walks out to the dance floor. In the middle of the song, Crow
stops dancing, returns to his chair and goes back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Life changed dramatically for Crow about three years ago. It was
then, he says, that a friend who was a witch put a curse on him,
``then turned into freakin' Satan and tried to kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not believe that he has schizophrenia, rather that he
is undergoing a supernatural experience that others simply cannot
understand,'' doctors wrote in a December 1998 evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Crow's father, Denton resident Robert Crow, desperately wants
his son to heal and dutifully makes the frequent drive to Wichita
Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, his devotion turns to frustration, and he accuses his
son of not taking enough initiative to get better. But he hasn't
given up hope that his son will escape the demons that torment him.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING PROGRESS
</P>
<P>
   Joel Inman walks along the rows of the buried, stopping
occasionally to dust dirt off a marker or two, as if he were
brushing hair from a child's face.
</P>
<P>
   A third-generation hospital employee, Inman remembers hearing
about when his grandparents worked as attendants in the 1940s and
1950s. Inman began his career at the hospital as a teen-ager, when
he mowed the grass of the hospital cemetery. Now, he directs the
hospital's program for recent patient admissions. He believes that
it was ignorance, not cruelty, that left No. 965 and the others
like him alone in a world of anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Inman has attended a few funerals at the cemetery, but not so
many anymore. Now, families aren't afraid to bury their loved ones
with the rest of the relatives. They aren't afraid to say that the
mentally ill are beloved mothers, brothers and sons.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun peeks through the cedar trees, casting rays of light
here and there, Inman stops to pull a couple of weeds that have
covered one of the newer grave markers.
</P>
<P>
   Etched in stone, surrounded by the thousand or so markers
bearing nothing more than a number, is a name.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDSD/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
