<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PSYCHIATRIC-HOSPITAL-     10-27 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHIATRIC-HOSPITAL-1600(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN TREATMENT REMOVES THE STIGMA OF MENTAL ILLNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Nestled in the grass among a cedar grove,
the marker bears no name, no ``In loving memory of,'' no dates of
birth or death.
</P>
<P>
   It says ``965'' and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-year-old man buried beneath the marker, alongside more
than 1,000 others interred beneath anonymous markers, suffered from
manic depression, and his illness earned him a stay at the Wichita
Falls campus of the North Texas State Hospital. Admitted in 1931
and dead by 1957, he was buried in a coffin that other patients
built.
</P>
<P>
   He lived in the era of ``lunatic asylums,'' when mental illness
was an embarrassing family secret and most patients were admitted,
abandoned and left to die.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his days shuffling aimlessly through the halls,
watching as the men and women around him babbled incoherently,
responding to the voices no one else could hear.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was electroshock-treatment day, when patients lined up
and waited to have electrodes attached to their bodies. The
electrodes delivered the electric current that made them jerk, jolt
and _ for a little while _ forget.
</P>
<P>
   No. 965 understood the consequences of uncontrollable behavior
when fellow patients returned from a frontal lobotomy, brain
surgery performed with little more than a mini pickax and a hammer,
that left them emotionless shells.
</P>
<P>
   For 26 years, No. 965 lived in a warehouse for the demented,
amid the chaos of mental illness, which few understood and almost
everyone feared.
</P>
<P>
   When hospital staff members gathered as his body was lowered
into the ground, No. 965 was, perhaps for the first time, in a
place where he could rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   A TIME OF FEAR
</P>
<P>
   Although public opinion remains mired in the past to some
degree, the subject of mental illness has grown from a family's
whisper to Tipper Gore's recent public revelation about her battle
with depression.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1922, when the Wichita Falls institution opened, people
were openly hostile and fearful of the mentally ill. So the
hospital was built on isolated land, with a trolley as the only
connection between it and the nearby town of Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's Hollywood building, which now sits vacant in the
middle of the campus, is a harsh reminder of those times. The
exclusive Hollywood facility offered a few more luxuries to its
residents _ private rooms, a beauty parlor _ but the feeling of
hopelessness remains palpable in its deserted hallways.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the hospital's 300-acre campus is not a formidable
place. It has a cottage for the family members who constantly visit
their loved ones among the 365 patients. Some patients have checked
in at the urging of relatives; others are committed by judges
because their families can no longer care for them, or because they
committed a misdemeanor and are not competent for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is no longer a prerequisite for a stay at the state
hospital; with insurance limits on mental health care, even
patients from midincome levels wind up in Whichta Falls. With the
daily cost per patient averaging $284, and a staff of 1,000, the
hospital runs a high tab of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of electroshock therapy, patients today are given
freedoms and punished with restrictions. The list of infractions is
long: hitting another patient, sneaking a cigarette, leaving the
building without permission, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent summer day, a thirtysomething woman sits on the
floor at the end of a hallway, cross-legged, facing the window, her
purse on one side, a bottle of Gatorade in hand. She sits there for
hours conversing with the voices in her head, unable to leave the
building for a group meeting because she has disobeyed the rules.
MORE &QL; 
.MDSD/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
