<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA REVIVES INVESTIGATION INTO SUHARTO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The new Indonesian government said
Wednesday that it would reopen a corruption inquiry into former
President Suharto that was dropped as one of the final acts of the
previous government.
</P>
<P>
   But President Abdurrahman Wahid said that while he approved the
renewed investigation, he would ultimately prefer a negotiated
settlement with Suharto. ``That would be better than getting all
excited in court, while scores of years go by without the case
being settled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said the decision was in the hands of the new
attorney general, Marzuki Darusman, a former human rights
commissioner who was an opponent of Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to foreign businessmen Wednesday, Marzuki said, ``The
intention is to reopen the case and have it brought to court.'' He
said this would involve either reopening the previous investigation
or targeting different areas of Suharto's wealth.
</P>
<P>
   In another move to pursue corruption and reopen cases stalled
under former President B.J. Habibie, who was Suharto's vice
president and who succeeded him after his ouster last year, the
attorney general said he would press ahead with an investigation
into a bank scandal that had tainted Habibie and his close
associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is crucial that these two issues are resolved properly and
transparently so that the message is clear,'' Marzuki said. ``We
will not tolerate any monkey business any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki's announcement Wednesday was a first step toward
defining the new government, which has not yet won the confidence
of foreign investors. The Cabinet is too diverse and its top
officials too untried to allow firm assessments to be made about
the country's future policies and stability, investors and
political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices in Jakarta continued a four-day slide Wednesday,
falling 3 percent, and Indonesia's currency dropped against the
dollar after nine days of gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian press mixed praise for the government with words
of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are still coasting on the euphoria of the change
to a new government, the mood could easily swing to widespread
dissatisfaction if the government fails to deliver in meeting
public expectations,'' said the English-language daily The Jakarta
Post.
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki's move to investigate Suharto addresses one widespread
public demand. Wahid's attitude seemed to reflect his desire to
address difficult issues with a minimum of the confrontation that
has battered Indonesia for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, we investigate,'' he told local editors. ``From the
result of that investigation, we then decide how much has to be
returned by Mr. Suharto to go towards efforts to improve the
economy and overcome the food crisis. That is better than if we
quarrel or go to court.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of its most damaging self-inflicted wounds, Habibie's
government closed an investigation into Suharto's wealth on Oct.
11, only days before an electoral assembly in which Habibie was a
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie never overcame the stigma of his close association with
Suharto and he withdrew his candidacy on the day before the
assembly's vote on Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong investigation, which had already aroused anger
through its evident half-heartedness, had focused on a complex of
charitable foundations controlled by Suharto. Critics charged that
he had laundered huge payoffs as part of a corrupt regime that
earned him many billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto and his children have been accused of stashing billions
of dollars overseas, a charge Suharto has denied. Corruption by
Suharto, his children and his cronies during his 32 years in office
distorted the Indonesian economy and contributed to a wave of anger
that drove him from office in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the focus of a new investigation, Marzuki said, it
would remain a corruption case. He said the government was obliged
to proceed because of an overwhelming public clamor for an
accounting of the widespread corruption of the Suharto years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political will has to be there because of public
pressure,'' he said. ``Short of that, there will be great
skepticism out there and it will only lead to a secondary crisis if
the government is not seen to be serious in ending this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank scandal centers around 546 billion rupiah in government
bailout funds siphoned out of Bank Bali to a company affiliated
with associates of Habibie. Critics say the money was used in
Habibie's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, among other
international lenders, have suspended further loans to Indonesia
until an audit of the transaction is made public and anyone guilty
of wrongdoing prosecuted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
