<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-1ST-LEAD-WRITETHROUGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST WHERE DOES E-MAIL GO? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Corrects byline)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Where do e-mail messages go between the time the sender sends
them and the recipient turns on her computer and receives them?
</P>
<P>
   L.M., Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Here's how the compugeeks would describe it: ``First you use
PPP and TCP/IP to connect to your ISP. Then you send your message
packets at various BPS using SMTP and receive it using POP.''
</P>
<P>
   In real speak, it goes like this. When you send an email message
and your modem starts going ``EEEEK, HHHSSSSSHHH, BOING BOING''
you're connecting to a company that has an electronic gateway to
the internet. That's your Internet Service Provider (ISP). What
you're hearing is literally an electronic conversation between your
computer and theirs, using standardized programs called PPP (Point
to Point Protocol) and TCP/IP (Transmission Control
Protocol/Internet Protocol). The conversation between the computers
is so they can see how fast each one is, so they can set themselves
at a mutually agreeable speed of Bytes Per Second (BPS) at which
the information is to be transferred. They're also testing to see
how strong the phone line is, to guard against mistakes in the
message. And of course they're asking each other for identifying
information like passwords and user names, to make sure it's okay
to make the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Once the two systems have electronically agreed on the terms of
their ``conversation,'' your email program gets a signal to start
sending the message. But it doesn't send it all at once. Inside
your computer is a standardized transmission program, called SMTP,
for Simple Message Transfer Protocol. SMTP sends your message out
in chunks, called packets, which are anywhere from 100 to 2,000
bytes (characters) long. SMTP gives each packet a label (the
compufolks call them headers) to identify it. Headers include
information like ``This is packet number X, coming from Y, going to
Z, and has Q numbers of characters in it. Send back a confirmation
that you got it before I send you another packet.''
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't get a confirmation, it won't send the rest of the
packets. The idea of breaking the message into packets is to catch
any electronic errors that would make the message unreadable,
before the whole thing is sent.
</P>
<P>
   When the packets get to the ISP, the receiving computer
reassembles them into one whole message. A computer looks at the
information on the right hand side of the ``(at)'' symbol, the
domain name. Let's say you sent something to howwhy(at)globe.com.
The ``globe.com'' part is the domain name. It's the post office to
which to send your mail.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a small local ISP company, it may send your message
directly to the domain name computer. More likely it will send your
message to a bigger internet company, run by firms like GTE or MCI,
since they have giant lists of all domain names and know where to
send messages.
</P>
<P>
   When it finally arrives at the domain name post office, the
server (a computer dedicated to one basic use, in this case email)
looks at the address on the left of the ``(at)'' symbol, the
``howwhy'' part, and puts the message into a file with that address
name. It's like your personal post office box. And there it waits
until you turn on your computer and tell it to ``Check Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   This time the ``EEEEK,HHHSSSSSHHH, BOING BOING'' is the Post
Office Protocol (POP client) in your computer, talking to the POP
server holding your message.
</P>
<P>
   The digi-conversation goes like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any mail for L.M.?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' answers the server.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many messages?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How long is the first one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``4,300 bytes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Send it.''
</P>
<P>
   As best we can tell, computers don't say please or thank you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
