u f BC-ATLANTA-WEBSITE28-COX     10-27 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-WEBSITE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta visitors bureau maps out bigger presence on Internet
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau plans to get more cyber
active in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau plans to increase its presence on the Internet next
year. A revamped ACVB Web site will allow online visitors to book
hotel reservations, buy tickets to city events and make restaurant
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is shifting to the Web and we don't intend being
left behind,'' said Gregory Pierce, ACVB vice president of finance
and technology. The site will get help from several corporate
partners and sponsors including BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The ACVB has had a Web site since the mid-1990s. The site gets
about 4 million hits a month. Pierce said the files downloaded most
are maps of the airport, downtown and its hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The upgraded site could also include merchandise sales, though
Pierce said it may not be a huge revenue generator. ``We're not a
retailer and won't keep inventory,'' he said. ``We would look for a
partner to handle those pieces. We'll basically be an order
taker.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site could generate up to $500,000 a year in revenue, in
part through reservation booking fees or a percentage of business
generated from the site. Details are being examined.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce said the bureau is also working with BellSouth on a pilot
project to have sites geared toward specific conventions. The site
would offer a daily schedule of the convention and a calendar of
events for the city.
</P>
<P>
   The ACVB could be ahead of many bureaus across the nation in
using the Web. Most convention and visitors bureaus have Web sites,
said Michael Pina, a spokesman for the Washington, D.C.-based
Travel Industry Association of America. ``The issue is what are
they doing special with their Web sites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such sites are becoming more popular, said Pina, whose
association will soon release a report on travelers' use of the
Internet. Preliminary findings indicate that 20 percent of
travelers who use the Internet have used it to make online
reservations. That percentage has doubled in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Of frequent travelers, those who have taken five or more trips
within the last year, 22 percent say they have used the Web for
reservations. That's up from 13 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
