<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's Mullin likely to add loftier title today
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines President and Chief Executive Leo
Mullin will likely get a third title today.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's board of directors, at the annual shareholders
meeting in Boston, is expected to name Mullin chairman of the
board.
</P>
<P>
   The additional title would have little practical effect. But it
would be an affirmation by the board of Mullin's leadership after a
little more than two years at the helm of Atlanta's biggest
corporate employer.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Grinstein, a longtime director who lives in Seattle, has
been Delta's ``nonexecutive'' board chairman since Mullin was hired
in August 1997. Grinstein is expected to relinquish that role but
remain on the board as an outside director.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the meeting, shareholder votes will be tallied on two
proposals backed by Delta's pilot union. One links executive
bonuses to employee satisfaction measures, while the other calls
for shareholder approval of any executive severance packages worth
more than $2 million. The latter is in reaction to the
multimillion-dollar package given Mullin's predecessor, Ronald
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The Grinstein-Mullin title shuffle is no surprise. Grinstein
said in an interview in March that he planned to hand Mullin the
chairman post this fall.
</P>
<P>
   A more significant question is whether Mullin will pick a clear
second-in-command from his top lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Operating Officer Maurice Worth, who retired in September,
had occupied the No. 2 position on the flow chart since Mullin's
arrival. But Mullin has said he has no immediate plans to fill that
slot. The next management layer consists of five executive vice
presidents, all of whom report directly to Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   Today's shareholder meeting, at the pricey and elegant Boston
Harbor Hotel, will mark the second straight year Delta has held the
gathering in a major Northeast city rather than its corporate
birthplace, Monroe, La.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was picked because of the city's importance in Delta's
route network, airline spokesmen said. Also, Delta may use the
event to tout plans for a new terminal at Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's meeting was at the Waldorf Astoria Hotel in New
York. Previously, Delta held its meetings at a Holiday Inn in
Monroe _ an annual nod to the carrier's crop-dusting roots that was
deemed outdated by Mullin, a Massachusetts native.
</P>
<P>
   Those ties will be further thinned by today's retirement of
board member Henry Biedenharn, a Monroe businessman and the last in
a long line of family members to sit on Delta's board.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
