<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firms making room for religion at work
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a spiritual revival going on in America. The
real news is that it's taking place on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Nov. 1) takes a look at the phenomenon in its
cover story.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine offers a number of reasons why there's more
religion in the workplace. One is simply that it makes sense, given
the time people spend at their jobs. After all, work is where more
and more people eat, date, use on-site day care and in some
offices, even take naps, the magazine notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But perhaps the largest driver of this trend,'' Business Week
says, ``is the mounting evidence that spiritually minded programs
in the workplace not only soothe workers' psyches but also deliver
improved productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies made room for religion long before productivity
became part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask S. Truett Cathy of Atlanta, chief executive of
Chick-fil-A, which is closed on Sundays and offers prayer service
for employees on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Sunday school boys would think I'm a hypocrite if I'm up
there teaching while my cash register is jingling,'' he told
Business Week.
</P>
<P>
   STILL A BELIEVER
</P>
<P>
   John Neff, former manager of the Windsor Fund, offers his voice
in favor of low-P/E value investing in the November Bloomberg
Personal Finance.
</P>
<P>
   His verdict? Investing in stocks with low P/Es is not a thing of
the past. Excesses in the market ultimately ``hand low-P/E
investors the chance to capture extraordinary gains, when worthy,
out-of-favor stocks regain the market's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the magazine: a look at the possibilities that the
Internet brings to bond investing.
</P>
<P>
   ARE THE BIG STOCKS BETTER?
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (November) tries to answer that question in a report
on the 10 most valuable stocks in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   The 10, in order, as of Sept. 10: Microsoft, General Electric,
Intel, IBM, Cisco Systems, Wal-Mart Stores, Lucent Technologies,
Exxon, Merck and Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
