<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestling grapevine: Rumors, gossip from the industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the bigger rumors this week had the WWF making a move to
sign Randy ``Macho Man'' Savage and announce it in Toronto, just
days before WCW's ``Mayhem'' pay-per-view. WWF honcho Jim Ross has
already said the WWF is not interested in Savage, whose WCW
contract ends in December.
</P>
<P>
   Did Jeff Jarrett get a bonus for dropping the Intercontinental
belt to Chyna before leaving for the WCW? Some say yes, to the tune
of $100,000-plus. Others say he got the money, but it was money
owed to him. His WWF contract ran out the day before the ``No
Mercy'' PPV.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF will get back one star sooner than expected. The
Undertaker will return from a series of injuries by the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bischoff was spotted with Hulk Hogan at the Tyson fight on
Saturday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   WWF's stock has leveled off since its dramatic opening last
week. The stock, which opened at $21 per share and has jumped as
high as $34, is currently trading around $24.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the WCW wrestlers and personalities released over the
past few weeks: Johnny Attitude, Mike Enos, Arturo Flores (Eddie
Guerrero's LWO bodyguard), Bret Hamner (one of the Master Blasters
in WCW), Barry Horowitz, Hard Body Harrison, Scott Norton, Sick
Boy, Barry Darsow, Chad Fortune, Hak, Marcus Johnson (NWO referee),
Robert Smedley and Eric Watts.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Fabulous Moolah in the record books as the oldest
women's champion. Moolah, believed to be 69, has the belt back. She
first held the WWF Women's title in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Internet sources say Stone Cold Steve Austin has agreed to turn
heel in the next few months and probably feud with the Rock. Triple
H's return to the Degeneration X stable Monday night opens the door
for Austin and the Rock to be the main focus soon.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet report says the WCW has plans to bring back the
Hardcore division. Of course, it's strange that they would after
losing Hardcore stars such as Raven, Hak and Mickey Whipwreck over
the past two months. Also, former Hardcore champ Fit Finlay may
never wrestle again after a serious leg injury.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme Championship Wrestling's first pay-per-view since
joining TNN had about 85,000 subscribers _ the same as WCW's ``Fall
Brawl,'' with much less advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Reports say the WWF has asked employees to sign a contract
stating that if they were to be released from the company for any
reason, they cannot work for WCW for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF ``Raw is War'' show at the Georgia Dome in Atlanta drew
33,375 fans paying $861,441. The show ranks as one of the top 10
U.S. wrestling shows ever.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
