<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WRESTLING-HAVOC-COX     10-27 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-HAVOC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Havoc signals bloodier WCW
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   World Championship Wrestling's latest pay-per-view, ``Halloween
Havoc,'' was the beginning of a new era for the wrestling
organization in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The first pay-per-view put together by the writing duo of Vince
Russo and Ed Ferrara had more violence and muddled endings than
previous WCW shows. It also boasted a couple of unique twists.
</P>
<P>
   The show started with the Filthy Animals being stripped of the
tag team titles because one of four members was unable to wrestle.
That was done to change the basic tag-team title match into a
three-team, six-man tag that Harlem Heat won to become 10-time tag
champions.
</P>
<P>
   A crowbar then became the weapon of choice in a series of
matches _ Ric Flair beating Eddy Guerrero to end his match with
Saturn, Diamond Dallas Page returning the favor in his match with
Flair.
</P>
<P>
   There was more violence as Flair cut himself open during his
match and the Sid Vicious-Goldberg match resulted in a bloody
ending. The match was stopped when it was decided Sid had lost too
much blood.
</P>
<P>
   There were also some big gaffes in the show.
</P>
<P>
   In the Flair-DDP match the referee only counted to two but gave
DDP the win.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, titles change hands only if there has been a pinfall or
submission, but Goldberg got the U.S. title after Sid was declared
too bloody to fight. During the Sting-Goldberg match, announcers
Tony Schivone and Bobby Heenan made it clear that it was a
non-title match. Yet when Goldberg pinned Sting, he was awarded the
World Title.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest gaffe, or maybe the biggest work, was Hulk Hogan
laying down to allow Sting to pin him in what was to be the main
event. On air, Hogan has voiced his displeasure with the changes in
WCW.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest rumors circulating in wrestling circles is
that Hogan has talked with Fox officials about starting another
wrestling group. This past spring, Hogan had NBC set to buy into a
Saturday night WCW show. The deal fell apart when Bret Hart took
time off to mourn his brother and WCW's ratings continued to fall.
</P>
<P>
   A deal with Hogan and Fox makes sense because Fox head man
Rupert Murdoch would love to battle WCW's Ted Turner in another
arena (the two moguls already battle with baseball teams and media
companies). With Murdoch's money and Fox's network status, Hogan
would be able to raid the WCW and WWF, where wrestlers might sign
deals not to compete in the WCW.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
