<HEADLINE>
PHARMACEUTICAL GIANT SETS GENOMICS PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Hoechst Marion Roussel, which this month
gained control of its joint venture with Cambridge-based Ariad
Pharmaceuticals Inc., will establish a local genomics presence and
expand employment at Ariad to 100 from 65 here by late next year.
</P>
<P>
   The German pharmaceutical giant is merging with Rhone-Poulenc
SA, the large French chemical and pharmaceutical company, and next
month will change its name to Aventis Group. It will have its
largest genomics operations in Cambridge, said Dr. Harvey J.
Berger, Ariad's founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies, he said, will have smaller genomics
facilities in Vitry, France, and Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Ariad sold its 50 percent interest in the Hoechst-Ariad Genomics
Center LLC to Hoechst Marion Roussel and received $40 million in
cash along with the rights to all its drugs created during the
nearly five-year collaboration. Ariad also got back 3 million
shares of its stock, for which Hoechst Marion Roussel had paid $30
million plus $2 million in forgiven loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have cash for the next 2 1/2 years,'' Berger said,
``and will focus (at Ariad) on getting drug products into the
clinic, while (Aventis focuses) on genomics research.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, sources said Wednesday that London-based Wellcome
Trust, part of the British pharmaceutical giant Glaxo, is
considering Cambridge as a site for its genomics laboratory. The
trust is reportedly seeking a facility that could accommodate up to
1,000 people and is also looking at sites in Maryland and near
Glaxo's US headquarters in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   If Glaxo joins Hoechst in Massachusetts, it would be part of a
booming biotech research enclave. Already here are BASF, which is
conducting biopharmaceutical research in Worcester, and
Astra-Zeneca, a Swedish firm building a facility in Waltham. Bayer
has a joint research program with the German company LION at the
Whitehead Institute in Cambridge, and Worcester-based Athena
Diagnostics is owned by Elan PLC of Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Already, several US pharmaceutical companies, including Pfizer
Inc. and American Home Products, have biotech research facilities
in Cambridge, and Amgen is slated to break ground Nov. 11 for an
eight-story building in Kendall Square. Merck &AMP; Co., meanwhile, is
about to locate near Emmanuel College in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bulk of the local expansion is by US companies, ``I
am getting about four calls a month from groups representing
European pharmaceutical companies looking for space between
Cambridge and Worcester,'' said Joseph Donavan, director of
emerging technologies at the Massachusetts Department of Economic
Development.
</P>
</TEXT>
