A0444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BC-BOS &LR;      10-27 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE EXPECTS NO SYMPATHY FROM SYRACUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sure, Syracuse might have an insight into how it feels
to suffer a devastating loss after absorbing a humiliating 62-0
thrashing two weeks ago at Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston College safety Pedro Cirino does not expect the
Orangemen _ who will play host to the Eagles at noon Saturday at
the noisy Carrier Dome _ to have any sympathy for the Eagles, who
squandered a 28-0 lead in a 31-28 loss last Saturday against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would they?'' Cirino said. ``They're coming off a tough
loss against a damn good team and they've had an extra week to
prepare for us. So they have to be looking forward to this game to
make a statement and to make amends for what happened against
V-Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse coach Paul Pasqualoni said during Monday's
teleconference, ``I'd still rather be coming off BC's (loss) than
ours,'' because, ``to me, they played a heck of a game and we did
not play well.''
</P>
<P>
   The words came as no consolation to Cirino. ``I don't find
either way (to lose) to be acceptable, regardless if you go down
fighting, especially when you have a lead like we did,'' Cirino
said. ``That makes it even tougher. I know Syracuse had a tough,
tough, tough time against V-Tech, and a lot of people will. I just
watched the tapes of that game Wednesday and V-Tech looked scary on
defense. They were out there pounding on Syracuse.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was his initial reaction upon hearing Syracuse's
staggering final score from Blacksburg, Va.? ``I was like, `Damn,'
'' Cirino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syracuse just doesn't get beat like that. V-Tech made a
statement. Syracuse will bounce back, but hopefully not against
us.''
</P>
<P>
   That explained why Cirino's only concern, really, was how the
Eagles respond after their killer loss. ``I think it is a major
concern for us,'' he said. ``We have to put that game behind us,
but we let that game get away ourselves. There was nothing that
Miami did. We beat ourselves at the end when we had too many missed
assignments and too many missed tackles in the fourth quarter. They
made us pay for them, and that's something we have to work on and
continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we won't put ourselves in that situation in the
future and we won't have a letdown like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirino reiterated the vow he made to do everything in his power
as a senior defensive co-captain to prevent what transpired in the
second half Saturday _ when the Hurricanes rallied for 31
unanswered points in the final 17:11 _ from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not going to,'' Cirino said. ``If the guys can't make
the adjustments and if the coaches can't make the adjustments, then
we're not going to be in the game, period. So it's something we
have to learn from and something we have to take into account. We
have to go out there, and when the coaches draw something up on the
board, we have to know what the hell they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes for everyone, including myself. I saw things out
there that didn't seem to make sense _ and they didn't make sense _
and it caused me to make a couple of mistakes. It's a team defense
and everybody has to play their part, and that wasn't the case in
the fourth quarter against Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of three quarters, BC's defense dominated
Miami. Until, that is, the Hurricanes came roaring back and
capitalized on several miscues, including the winning 30-yard field
goal by Andy Crosland with seven seconds left. After gaining just
101 yards total offense and four first downs in the first half,
Miami finished with 396 yards and 20 first downs, gaining an
average of 7.0 yards per play in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   So how will the Eagles bounce back against Syracuse?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be another emotional game for us, really,''
Cirino said. ``It's definitely going to be a gut-check for this
team, considering what happened to us last week. It's going to be
the same for them coming off the drubbing they came off of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect them to come out fired up, because they're at home,
so I don't see why not. We just have to make sure that we match
their intensity and, hopefully, come out with the victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
