<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush has work to do in New Hampshire, poll shows
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush maintains a solid lead over
nearest rival John McCain in New Hampshire, but a new poll
indicates Bush may have some work to do there.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Herald survey released Wednesday showed Bush is backed
by 44 percent of the 362 respondents who identified themselves as
likely voters in the New Hampshire GOP primary. McCain was second
at 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted Sunday through Monday, carries a margin of
error of five percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But, in what McCain trumpeted as a seminal moment in the race,
67 percent of the respondents said they have a favorable impression
of him, while only 12 percent said they had an unfavorable
impression of him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got a favorable rating from 64 percent, down 10 points from
August. Nineteen percent said they view Bush unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Kelly Myers, who did the research for the Boston
newspaper, said Bush is finding out that New Hampshire residents
make candidates work for their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said from the beginning that George Bush is in the very
awkward position of being such a strong front-runner,'' said Myers.
``It is inconceivable that he would ride easily to victory in New
Hampshire. It rarely turns out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said Bush, who has spent nine days in the Granite State,
needs to make more trips to New Hampshire to stop the slide in his
favorable ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has gotten bashed upside down for not being here as part of
the series of debates,'' said Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, as the other major GOP contenders gather at Dartmouth
College for the second New Hampshire debate, Bush again will be
absent. After campaigning today in North Dakota, he heads to Dallas
to join his wife Laura as she is honored by Southern Methodist
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is George Bush skipping a debate for the second
consecutive time but he's thumbing his nose at the people of New
Hampshire,'' said McCain spokesman Dan Schnur.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who will participate in a Dec. 2 debate in New Hampshire,
will be interviewed live this evening on a Manchester TV station to
discuss his absence from tonight's debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to explain to the people of New Hampshire why he
isn't going to be there and to answer questions that might have
been asked at the debate,'' Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Myers noted that Bush is still well-positioned to undo
any damage he has incurred in New Hampshire. Each Bush visit is
received as a celebrity event, and he has the backing of U.S. Sen.
Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, who has the state's best political
organization. Bush, who campaigned Wednesday in Iowa, returns to
New Hampshire next week to deliver a major policy address on
education.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is now on a three-day bus tour of New Hampshire, which
holds the nation's first primary next Feb. 1. The Arizona senator
has more time to spend there because he is ignoring Iowa, where the
first major battle of the presidential season happen at Jan. 24
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
