<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S `SCIENCE' HARDLY EXPERIMENTAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every record Bush makes is a two-star record, a disc that would
be completely empty if it weren't filled with so much unoriginality
_ but they're not without scarce moments of shallow luxuries. You
cringe while hitting the track-repeat button.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes on effort No. 3 from Bush, the criminally popular
English rock band that has come to represent everything that's
wrong and wronger with modern rock. Specifically, they've sold
millions of copies of their first two CDs, ``Sixteen Stone'' and
``Razorblade Suitcase,'' if only because they came along with the
perfect sound at the perfect time: They mimicked Nirvana as Nirvana
was leaving us.
</P>
<P>
   The guitars roar like Kurt Cobain's did. Gavin Rossdale moans
and mourns like Cobain did. The group even enlisted renowned studio
whiz Steve Albini to give his Midas touch of abrasiveness to
``Razorblade.'' (Albini tweaked Nirvana's final studio disc, ``In
Utero.'') Bush has mindlessly followed in Nirvana's footsteps _ and
you've rewarded them for it.
</P>
<P>
   With Nirvana gone, Bush was on its own for this, its third
effort. But it's bad-business-as-usual here, a repeat of everything
Bush has tried to pass off as its own. Drum loops and digital
pulses turn up sporadically, perhaps trying to prove the band is
going in a new direction, which, in case you haven't noticed,
everyone else is going in, too. If the occasional flash of aptitude
weren't here, ``Science'' would be Bush's worst album yet _ and
those first two are pretty tough to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Those moments of skill: the opener ``Warm Machine'' and
``Prizefighter'' are two relatively simple songs that somehow come
off dramatic. There's nothing really special about either track,
but the band _ guitarist Nigel Pulsford, bassist Dave Parsons and
drummer Robin Goodridge _ plays so ferociously, and Rossdale sings
with such verve, that you actually obsess over them. It's as if you
hear them in your sleep, in your car; you get up to turn them down
and realize your CD player's not even on. These two songs are that
good.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad those feelings don't last. The rest of ``Science'' is as
mechanical as it is predictable _ a blatantly noisy song here
(''English Fire''), a soft one there (''40 Miles from the Sun''),
the in-between singles (''The Chemicals Between Us, Spacetravel'').
</P>
<P>
   Going through the motions, spinning their wheels, been
there/done that _ no cliche I could write is half as cliched as
this _ most of this, anyway.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
