<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0455 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-27 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STRAWMEN NEVER DIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It would be easy,'' said the president, ``easy
for a president of the United States to buy some popularity by
going along with the new isolationists. But I submit to you that it
would be disastrous for our nation and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The president was Richard Nixon in 1969, asserting his
internationalism at an Air Force Academy graduation even as he
began withdrawing troops from Vietnam. I wrote that speech, toning
down an even tougher anti-appeasement draft from Pat Buchanan. The
``new isolationist'' label infuriated protesters against the
Vietnam War, linking them with the appeasement of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   That same rhetorical device _ bunching all opposition into an
extremist straw man and then knocking it down _ is back with us
today.
</P>
<P>
   In his tele-tantrum after the Senate rejection of his test ban
treaty, President Clinton made the Nixon phrase his own, direly
warning of ``signs of a new isolationism.''
</P>
<P>
   That evocative theme and phrase was amplified last week by his
national political-security adviser, Sandy Berger. ``The
internationalist consensus that has prevailed in this country for
more than 50 years,'' he told the Council on Foreign Relations,
``increasingly is being challenged by a new isolationism. ...''
</P>
<P>
   How does the new New Isolationism differ from the old New
Isolationism? Nixon's straw man had no faith in American strength;
Clinton's straw man has no faith in treaties and multilateral
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton wanted to avoid Senate rejection of his flawed
agreement, he was offered an honorable way out: Simply agree in
writing not to bring it up next year. But he refused, demanding a
loophole enabling him to spring it at election time. Because
experience taught senators his word is not to be trusted, his
treaty was laid to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's new New Isolationism charge has a second leg: The
United States has not paid its U.N. dues. But the Helms-Biden deal
to pay those dues pegged to U.N. bureaucratic reform has long been
struck. What's holding it up is Clinton's debt to abortion
absolutists: he wants our U.N. dues to support Planned Parenthood
abroad, and a majority of Congress does not. The United States is
being made to look like a deadbeat because Clinton is in thrall to
a domestic lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third thesis of the new isolationism,'' cries Berger, is
``if it's over there, it's not our fight.'' He claims credit for
stopping the war in Bosnia and Kosovo despite sniping from the
dangerous ostrich element.
</P>
<P>
   But for years Clinton and our European allies were hand-wringing
appeasers in the face of Serbian aggression, abdicating to a
feckless United Nations. Only massacres shown on TV aroused public
opinion and shamed Western leaders into halfhearted action. The
lack of internationalist leadership invited the self-doubt and
derision that nourished isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Clinton was the most reluctant interventioneer.
Thousands of Kosovars died before counter-punishment rained down.
Even then, with tactical airstrikes needed to take out rampaging
tanks, fear of risk in Clinton's Sit-room sitzkrieg kept NATO
bombardiers three miles high _ and the ethnic cleansing was carried
out. Only when NATO became serious about massing troops near
Serbia's border to back up the air war, as Sen. John McCain had
urged, did the resolve of Slobodan Milosevic crack.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where Clinton's political hatchet man gets mean.
``Serious people actually lamented that we did not have enough
casualties in the Kosovo conflict,'' Berger told the Establishment.
Only the most partisan Clintonite would charge that critics of a
delayed operation that failed to stop the slaughter were
``lamenting'' that more Americans had not died. That's below the
Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything new to the newest New Isolationism? The
lunatic fringe of Festung Amerika will always be with us,
embarrassing more responsible skeptics of intervention. Nothing new
there, and not a growing movement; it's only a reconstituted straw
man.
</P>
<P>
   What is new is the pervasive distrust of our politicized
national security leadership. That raises suspicion of poll-driven
policy, of half-measured responses to crises and of commitments
grandly announced that may not be kept. That _ and not the latest
new isolationism _ is the danger to internationalism today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
