<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0456 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MANSFIELD-PARK-FILM-2     10-27 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANSFIELD-PARK-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING AN AUSTEN HEROINE MORE LIKE AUSTEN  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
Barbara Kantrowitz is a senior editor at Newsweek 
 By BARBARA KANTROWITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fanny Price, the heroine of ``Mansfield Park,'' should have been
one of Jane Austen's most memorable creations. Fanny is a Regency
Cinderella, a poor girl shipped off to live with ill-tempered
wealthy relatives.
</P>
<P>
   She ultimately wins her prince _ in this case, her cousin Edmund
(nobody worried too much about genetics in those days). Fanny
always takes the high road; she's the only character who sticks to
her principles and resists all temptation to change.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her considerable virtues, Fanny just can't get any
respect. Most readers find her irritatingly prissy and passive.
Even Austen's own mother pronounced Fanny ``insipid'' when
``Mansfield Park'' was first published, in 1814. More than 100
years later, the British writer Kingsley Amis called her ``a
monster of complacency and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder it's taken so long to produce a feature-film
adaptation of Austen's most complex and controversial novel.
Patricia Rozema took on the challenge two years ago, after she got
a call from Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax Films. He was
convinced that somewhere in the dense shrubbery of ``Mansfield
Park'' there was a story that could rival the success of recent
versions of ``Pride and Prejudice,'' ``Sense and Sensibility'' and
``Emma.'' Weinstein already had a screenplay of the novel under way
and wanted Ms. Rozema to take over the project.
</P>
<P>
   Although she had read Austen's novels, she was far from an
expert on period pieces; one of her most recent works was a sextet
of short films inspired by the cellist Yo-Yo Ma. She didn't claim
to be a fan of ``Mansfield Park,'' either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dare I say it? I don't think it's a perfect novel,'' she said
by telephone from Toronto, where she lives. Her first question to
Weinstein was: ``Why me?'' She says he told her he wanted ``someone
very visual'' to give the film a distinctive look. With that
mandate, Ms. Rozema proceeded to create a radically new Fanny, one
who will undoubtedly shock Austen purists when the film opens, on
Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a Jane Austen film,'' says Ms. Rozema, the writer and
director. ``It's a Patricia Rozema film. My job as an artist is to
provide a fresh view.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired of what she describes as ``polite'' Austen
interpretations, Ms. Rozema infuses the character of Fanny with the
spirit of the author herself. Using Austen's letters and other
writings as a source of dialogue, she turns the hapless young girl
into a reasonable facsimile of what Ms. Rozema imagines the young
Jane was like. Ms. Rozema's Fanny (portrayed by the Australian
actress Frances O'Connor) is a budding writer, witty, lively,
surprisingly modern and eminently likable.
</P>
<P>
   She's a decidedly feminist Cinderella. That transformation alone
would be heresy enough for the Austen purists, but Ms. Rozema has
added a few more startling revisionist touches _ like sex.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the most graphic moment in an Austen adaptation was a
relatively chaste kiss. Ms. Rozema says she set out ``to make a
movie that was emotionally charged.'' In one scene, Fanny and the
urbane Mary Crawford (Embeth Davidtz) appear to be on the verge of
a lustful lesbian embrace. At another point, two adulterous
characters romp naked in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rozema defends these scenes _ which are certainly not in the
novel _ as historically accurate. ``I don't think blood temperature
has changed, especially among the young and free,'' she says. ``I
was almost required to show them having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking liberties with an author as revered as Austen is always
risky, but Ms. Rozema says she's not afraid of the critics.
``Whenever you turn a novel into a movie, you're changing form,''
she says. ``I felt fairly free to make changes as long as I felt I
could face Austen if I met her.''
</P>
<P>
   She did extensive research, reading a number of scholarly
studies and Austen biographies, as well as just about every
surviving word the author wrote. She concluded that Austen intended
Fanny to be strong and tough, the only character in the novel
willing to stand up for her principles.
</P>
<P>
   To convey that image in a modern context, Ms. Rozema felt Fanny
had to be much more active, even bold. Fanny's interior life is
largely hidden in the novel. Ms. Rozema gives it a voice in the
film through letters Fanny sends to her sister Susan. She also has
Fanny write a farcical history of England, just as Austen did when
she was 14.
</P>
<P>
   Turning Fanny into Jane Austen is not as outrageous a leap as it
might seem. Some scholars consider ``Mansfield Park'' Austen's most
autobiographical work. It was her third published novel, written
after a difficult period in her life, and it is much darker than
the witty, lighthearted visions in ``Pride and Prejudice'' and
``Sense and Sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling of oppression, even doom, about the
characters. Fanny is a captive of forces she can't control. Her
only weapon against the tumult around her is perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Austen places her in a cold room apart from the rest of the
Mansfield Park family, a symbol of her emotional exile. She is an
observer and chronicler of human frailty. It's easy to imagine
Austen identifying with her heroine, as she struggled to stick to
her writing while her family sought a safe harbor after her
father's death.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years, Austen and her mother and sister shuttled
from home to home before finally settling at Chawton in Hampshire,
where all three would live until Austen died (probably of Addison's
disease, a failure of the adrenal glands) in 1817, at the age of
41. Neither Jane nor her sister, Cassandra, ever married, although
there is some evidence that the writer did suffer through at least
one failed love affair.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rozema believes the popular image of Austen _ a prim
spinster writing witty repartee between teas _ is a distortion.
``If you met her as a teen-ager, you would have typed her as a
revolutionary by nature,'' she says. ``She had an almost surrealist
bent at the beginning.'' But like many writers, she did what she
had to do to get published. In the novels, her nonconformist spirit
is still discernible.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rozema decided to emphasize the political overtones of
``Mansfield Park.'' The family patriarch, Sir Thomas Bertram (the
playwright Harold Pinter), is more clearly presented as a
slaveholder, a role only alluded to in the novel. In one scene,
Fanny discovers a portfolio of drawings by the dissolute oldest
son, Tom (James Purefoy), showing slaves being beaten and tortured.
The implication is that his decadence results from his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bertrams are an aristocratic family (besides Edmund
and Tom, Fanny's rich cousins include the marriageable Maria,
played by Victoria Hamilton, and Julia, portrayed by Justine
Waddell), they are far from admirable in the novel. Ms. Rozema's
screenplay ratchets up their flaws, so that only Fanny _ and, to
some degree, Edmund (Jonny Lee Miller) _ are worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rozema also decided to dramatize the class differences
between Fanny's family and the Bertrams. At one point in the story,
Fanny is sent back to Portsmouth, where her mother and father
preside over a chaotic household filled with badly behaved children
of various ages. In some other Austen adaptations, poor people _ if
they are shown at all _ are depicted as plain, honest and
good-hearted. Fanny's home is deliberately miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rozema says Austen was always worried about money, perhaps
because of her nomadic life in the years after her father's death;
she and her mother and sister were often dependent on the charity
of relatives, especially her brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to show poverty as unpleasant,'' Ms. Rozema
says. ``I think she was terrified of poverty and completely at the
mercy of the men around her. That must have made her crazy.'' Ms.
Rozema rendered Fanny's suitor, the unscrupulous Henry Crawford
(Alessandro Nivolo), more charming than he appears in the book so
that Fanny's rejection of him would appear even more dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Marrying a rich man would have provided an easy way out of
Fanny's situation, but she would have been betraying herself by
settling for someone she didn't love. The scene echoes one in
Austen's own life: when she was nearly 27, she accepted a marriage
proposal from a younger man but changed her mind a day later.
</P>
<P>
   After spending nearly two years bringing ``Mansfield Park'' to
the screen, Ms. Rozema says she has a greater insight into Austen's
genius. ``I came to admire her much more in the course of writing
it,'' she says, especially ``her ability to define character with
effortless grace. She was brilliant, just brilliant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0458 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DEVRIES-SCULPTOR-2TAK     10-27 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVRIES-SCULPTOR-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLOSER LOOK REVEALS A DUTCH MICHELANGELO  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
Theodore K. Rabb is a professor of history at Princeton University.
A new edition of his ``Renaissance Lives'' will be published next
year. 
 By THEODORE K. RABB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For Michelangelo, who was uniquely qualified to
judge, sculpture was superior to painting. And yet it is rare for a
sculptor other than Michelangelo himself, Donatello or Bernini to
be included among the many heroes of Renaissance and Baroque art.
</P>
<P>
   The dominance of painters is not, of course, just a matter of
taste. By and large, sculptors' works take longer to complete, cost
far more, are more awkward to place and are more difficult to look
at closely and grasp in totality.
</P>
<P>
   They are, as a result, fewer in number. Moreover, they often are
unnoticed because they tend to be part of the scenery. To see a
painting we have to go to a gallery, and once there we feel obliged
to concentrate. But very few of the millions who each day walk past
them give heed to the statues and fountains that adorn our cities'
streets and squares, let alone stop and view them as works of art.
</P>
<P>
   If statuary is the glory of classical Greece, this glory is the
exception that proves the rule, because a disproportionate number
of sculptures, saved by their materials, have survived from
antiquity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite these extenuating circumstances, however, it is clear
that major injustices have been done, notably to the artist who is
the focus of ``Adriaen de Vries, Imperial Sculptor,'' a show at the
J. Paul Getty Museum through Jan. 9. Although he was said to have
done for bronze what Michelangelo did for marble, de Vries was not
even mentioned by name when a traveler described one of his
masterpieces, only 60 years after his death, in terms usually
reserved for the ancient Greeks. Such cavalier treatment of
Tintoretto, Annibale Carracci or Guido Reni, his contemporaries, is
inconceivable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And yet de Vries (1556-1626) was clearly their equal as a
master, first of the twisting, straining style of the Mannerists
and then of the grandeur, the ornament and the emotional drama that
we associate with the Baroque. It is true that many of his works
are off the traditional tourist track, in Prague and Stockholm, and
thus did not receive the sustained interest that travelers
lavished, for instance, on the Berninis in Rome.
 &UR;  &LR; Nevertheless, the long neglect of this artist has been lamentable,
though redeemed somewhat by a turnaround in the last 10 years or
so, prompted by forces political and economic as well as esthetic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Vries gained new recognition, first, because two of his
bronzes, both now in the Getty, sold for huge sums in the 1980s:
``Rearing Horse'' for more than $1 million in 1984 and ``Juggling
Man'' for $10.7 million in 1989; second, because his chief patron,
the Hapsburg Emperor Rudolf II, attracted intense interest (and two
major exhibitions) after Czechoslovakia's Velvet Revolution of
1989, when admiration for the newly liberated Prague helped draw
attention to the city's golden age under Rudolf; and third, because
the Dutch, led by Frits Scholten, the curator primarily responsible
for assembling this exhibition and editing its splendid catalogue,
were delighted to add a new star to their artistic heritage.
 &UR;  &LR; Whatever the reasons, however, it is cause for rejoicing that the
Getty, collaborating with the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam and the
National museum in Stockholm, has brought to an American audience
38 bronzes and 6 drawings by de Vries along with 27 related
sculptures, engravings and paintings, all of which offer a rich
introduction to his extraordinary oeuvre. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To work in bronze is to tempt fate. It was hard enough to
uncover the form that Michelangelo described as ``hidden'' in
marble, or to transform its surfaces as he and Bernini did. But
bronze called on the metal founder's art to complement the
sculptor's; the disasters that always lurked when metal was heated,
poured, shaped and cooled could defeat even the greatest virtuosos,
as Leonardo and Cellini discovered.
</P>
<P>
   It was not much consolation for de Vries that the fault was the
founder's, not his, when the mold cracked and the molten bronze was
lost while he was casting one of two grand fountains for the city
of Augsburg, Germany, in the 1590s. The successful recasting is
stunning: a group of relaxed figures around flowing water,
surmounted by a monumental Hercules killing a fearsome Hydra _ an
ensemble that united charm and narrative force with a power never
before seen in a mere fountain.
</P>
<P>
   This colossus could not be moved, but the exhibition does have
five elements from another fountain, celebrating Neptune, displayed
as individual pieces of sculpture. One of them, a languid Triton
worthy of Bernini, embodies the movement and the surface glow that
was de Vries' hallmark. That these bronzes blend skill in
engineering with high art makes the results all the more
remarkable, and the Getty has provided, as an adjunct to the show,
a fascinating demonstration of the casting techniques that produced
the sculptures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main revelation of the exhibition, however, is the variety
of effects a great artist could summon up from this cold metal
medium. Although the statuary for the garden of one of de Vries's
most discerning patrons, the military commander Albrecht von
Wallenstein, was confiscated by a Swedish army, replicas adorn his
palace grounds in Prague to this day, and suggest the paradisiacal
setting, full of the figures of myth, that the sculptor could
create.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of these pieces is at the Getty, a tender, relaxed portrayal
of a life-size Adonis, his dog at his feet, carrying across his
shoulders a deer, the trophy of his hunt. He looks fondly down at
Venus, who opens her arms and delicately touches his side. It is a
group that evokes bucolic pleasure and young love, wonder and sheer
delight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a late work, completed two years before de Vries's death
at age 70, but his skills had been apparent long before. Born to a
prosperous family in The Hague, he went to Florence in his mid-20s
to work in the studio of a fellow northerner, Giambologna (two of
whose elegant sculptures are also on view at the Getty). By his
early 30s, after a stint in Milan, he was the court sculptor to the
Duke of Savoy in Turin, but soon he was ``borrowed'' by Rudolf II
and taken to Prague.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, where Tycho Brahe and Johannes Kepler studied the
heavens, where the fantasies of Giuseppe Arcimboldo took root,
where artists from all Europe found encouragement, that de Vries
spent most of his remaining years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His first commissions were small sculptures for Rudolf's
collection. Among the examples at the Getty are a heroic bust of
the emperor, finely detailed horses in different postures and a
dazzling group of Hercules holding up his wife Deianeira as the
dying centaur Nessus, from whom he has just saved her, lies in
agony between his legs.
</P>
<P>
   This last is an essay in movement and emotion, form and feeling,
in which de Vries captures not only the loving looks that flow
between Hercules and his wife but also the contrast between their
embrace and the torment of their foe.
</P>
<P>
   Late in life de Vries returned to the Nessus theme, on a larger
scale, at the moment when Hercules attacks the centaur and his wife
finally breaks free. Both the complexity and the intensity are
heightened: Nessus is now more monstrous, Hercules murderously
intent as he yanks back the centaur's head, and Deianeira in active
flight. Circling the sculpture, we have to work harder to decipher
the unfolding story.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bronze has an almost impressionistic surface,
with muscles and features suggested rather than elaborated. De
Vries, maybe aware of his advancing years, has abandoned the
meticulous detail of his earlier work and creates his effects with
almost nonchalant grace.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the ease and mastery he achieved as he entered his
60s, de Vries could dare to take on a classic from antiquity, the
Laocoon, which he had sketched on a visit to Rome. His version,
created for Wallenstein, is upright and columnar, unlike the
friezelike ancient monument. And his bravado in attempting one of
the icons of the sculptor's art was again matched by his style, in
which he almost sketches the subject, undistracted by ornament or
unnecessary detail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was fortunate for de Vries that, after the travels, the
shifts of patronage and the disruptions of war that were the lot of
the sculptor in his age, he was able to settle down and bring his
talents to this remarkable culmination in his last years.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch were not wrong to describe him, in the publicity for
the Amsterdam exhibition, as their Michelangelo. And perhaps our
century, when sculptors have more often matched painters as
cultural heroes, may at last give him his due.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Getty's superb natural lighting, and the close
examination its display allows, we can at last see for ourselves
why, in recent years, de Vries' rising reputation has prompted
comparisons with the leading figures of Western art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
