<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0460 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-MALKOVICH-FEATUR     10-27 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MALKOVICH-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL IN JOHN MALKOVICH'S HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: For use Friday, Oct. 29 or thereafter) 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ John Cusack calls it ``the craziest piece of
writing'' he has ever read. Cameron Diaz has never quite been able
to figure out what it's about, while Orson Bean thinks he knows the
secret but doesn't want to share for fear of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   And John Malkovich?
</P>
<P>
   Let us just borrow a quote from Cusack and call him ``sportsman
of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie producing all the head scratching is ``Being John
Malkovich,'' the strangest film to hit theaters in, well, a century
of cinema. Written five years ago by a first-time screenwriter and
directed by MTV auteur Spike Jonze, ``Malkovich'' is a
one-of-a-kind wonder that defies easy description. R.E.M.
singer/movie producer Michael Stipe, whose Single Cell Pictures
developed the film, probably comes closest to being the movie's
most coherent spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about an out-of-work puppeteer who takes a job in an
office and finds a membranous tunnel which, when you crawl through
it, emerges into the soul of John Malkovich for 15 minutes and then
spits you into a ditch by the New Jersey turnpike,'' Stipe says.
``Chaos ensues.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple, huh?
</P>
<P>
   The movie slyly spoofs our fascination with celebrities, but
underneath all the weirdness, ``Malkovich'' is really about human
needs, both desperate and despairing. Nobody here seems happy in
their own skins _ or, sometimes, in their own gender _ and the
portal into Malkovich represents a logical escape hatch,
particularly for a generation weaned on ``Entertainment Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the film's writer, Charlie Kaufman, will cop to none
of this. Heck, he won't even reveal his age, let alone whatever
peculiar place in his head that this idea came from. What Kaufman
will say: He is not interested in being a social critic. He wrote
the movie without an outline and with no sense of direction or
purpose. And he is not obsessed with, nor is he stalking, John
Malkovich.
</P>
<P>
   That latter point is rather important because when Malkovich
came across the script, shortly after Kaufman had written it, he
was more than a little curious about the individual who would dream
up such a fantastically personal scenario. Thus, he dispatched his
business partner, Russell Smith, for a meeting with Kaufman. The
following exchange ensued:
</P>
<P>
   Smith: What is your relationship with John Malkovich?
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman: Um ... I ... um ... admire him greatly as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Smith: So why did you set part of the movie on the
seventh-and-a-half floor of an office building?
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman: Um ... (Kaufman pauses frequently in conversation) I
... um ... thought it was funny visually.
</P>
<P>
   Smith: Well, did you know that John's apartment in New York is
number seven-and-a-half?!?
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman says a chill went down his spine at that moment and he
figured the jig was up. No one, particularly Malkovich, would
believe the whole thing was coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Says Smith, (somewhat) facetiously: ``I thought he was a stalker
and he thought I was there to kill him. I mean, there were just a
lot of coincidences in the script that made you a little
suspicious. I thought maybe John slept with his wife and this
screenplay was his revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kaufman didn't know anything more about Malkovich than
``your average moviegoer'' and chose the actor and his name because
``it just seemed right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my theories about why,'' Kaufman says, ``but they all
came after I chose him. This was something I just wrote for myself.
I never figured it would actually be made into a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else did, either. Kaufman's screenplay was one of the
most popular reads in Hollywood, but no one offered to produce it.
Kaufman didn't even get a meeting for it. What he did get was a lot
of work (screenplays, the television sitcom ``Get a Life''), so he
figured the script had served its purpose. Besides, Malkovich
himself _ despite the coincidences _ loved it and his praise
(received secondhand) was reward enough.
</P>
<P>
   Stipe and his producing partner, Sandy Stern, thought
``Malkovich'' was too good to sit on the shelf, however, and, two
years ago called Jonze, asking if he would consider directing it.
Jonze loved the script and found a kindred soul in Kaufman, a man
whose absurdist take on life closely matches his own. (``Neither of
them are easy reads,'' Stipe says. ``They tend to hold their cards
close to their chests.'')
</P>
<P>
   The two spent nine months revising Kaufman's original draft. All
the while, the great unanswered question hung in the air: Would
Malkovich agree to ``Being John Malkovich''? Alternate names were
proposed _ William Hurt was a front-runner _ but no one seemed as
right as Malkovich.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting with Malkovich was set, and Jonze jetted off to Paris
to pop the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some doubts,'' Malkovich admits, ``but they had nothing
to do with the material, which I thought was fantastic, and nothing
to do with making fun of me. They had to do with this: I have tried
to construct my life so whatever public notoriety I have doesn't
become invasive. And this movie crosses that line. So, I had to
decide if I wanted to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I had said no,'' Malkovich continues, ``it would have
been for all the wrong reasons, and this really original, inventive
thing wouldn't have been done. So Spike and I worked it out.
Ultimately, what I'm doing is playing the character of John
Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Cusack interjects: ``And I think he got it all wrong.
He's too close to the character to do it justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack, naturally, is kidding. He agrees with Stipe, who says it
took incredible nerve for Malkovich to portray himself in this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The persona he's presenting is clearly not himself, but the
public's idea of what it's like to be a famous movie star _
arrogant, misogynistic, ordering towels out of a catalog for your
kitchen,'' Stipe says. ``It's completely banal. And it points out
how absurd our notions of celebrity are.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Jonze: ``He was a trouper. Every day, John would come in
and laugh and say, `I thought yesterday was the most humiliating
thing I'd ever shot, and it just keeps getting more humiliating.'
But he'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which surprised some of Malkovich's fellow cast members, who,
fittingly, had their own ideas about what the actor would be like.
Catherine Keener, playing one of the characters who enters
Malkovich's head, calls it a mystique; co-star Diaz says he's
initially ``a little intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just figured he was a weird guy,'' says Orson Bean, who
plays the owner of the company that resides on the
seventh-and-a-half floor. ``You know, he plays wackos so well, he'd
be a little wacko himself. He isn't. He's a swell guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Malkovich doesn't really care how he's perceived, which is good
because otherwise he could never have done this movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much know what I am, and I pretty much always have,''
Malkovich says. ``But in Hollywood, you're a kind of product.
They'll give you so much money to play a bad guy and the other
scripts don't come in because that's your `product,' your
identification. But I know I can do other things. I've done it my
whole life. Maybe people haven't seen it, but I don't really care.
It's more a loss for others than it is for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Will people go see Malkovich in ``Malkovich''? Stipe, for one,
thinks the public is ready for such a wacky challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are sick to death of movies that are the same story
they've seen and heard for the past 40 years,'' Stipe says. ``If
Kevin Costner makes another baseball movie, I will personally
throttle the man. Maybe this film can help chink away the armor a
little bit and get people in this business (away) from thinking
about the lowest common denominator.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
