<HEADER>
A0462 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-REPUBS-SOSEC-NYT &LR;      10-27 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-SOSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CUE FROM DEMOCRATS, GOP SEEKS TO CAPITALIZE ON SOCIAL
SECURITY ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Nev., Kan., Conn.)   (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Earl Pomeroy, an earnest Democrat from North
Dakota, was able to go to college after his father died only
because of Social Security benefits for survivors. And he has
devoted his six years in Congress in large part to pension issues
and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   So he finds it particularly galling that he is one of seven or
so House Democrats from swing districts in states like North
Dakota, Nevada, Kansas and Connecticut who are being hit this month
with Republican commercials that portray Democrats as thieves or
wild revelers who want to fritter away Social Security reserves
``on big government programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington has gotten to the point where the sessions between
the elections are kind of like the setup period for the next
election,'' Pomeroy complained. ``These ads have certainly made
this October feel like an election year October, and triggered
every competitive instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Dakota Democratic Party, in fact, has fired back with
commercials of its own quoting a newspaper editorial calling the
Republican ads ``a new low in the campaign gutter.''
</P>
<P>
   The air war shows that as much as this end-of-session budget
battle is about the nitty gritty of federal programs and policy,
both parties also consider this a pivotal moment that could shape
next year's struggle for control of the House. And after years of
losing each such faceoff with President Clinton, the Republicans
are fighting this fall to define the terms of the budget debate to
their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Each day they hold news conferences to hammer home the theme on
Social Security that is amplified through their ads. And
Republicans say this concerted campaign has legislative and
political goals.
</P>
<P>
   They hope that the ads may cause some conservative or marginal
Democrats in Congress to vote with them as the budget battle goes
on. And politically, the commercials are designed to inoculate
Republicans on an issue that is traditionally a Democratic strength
by painting the GOP as the party trying to protect the popular
retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Republicans call the commercials a warning that
some Democrats will pay a price if their party prolongs the budget
fight for partisan advantage in hopes that the Republicans once
again will look as if they want a government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican leaders suggested this week that they could
expand the campaign to other districts. ``The main thing is we just
need everyone to understand _ it could be your place next,'' said
Rep. Dick Armey, the House majority leader from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats complain bitterly about the Republican ads. But
it was Clinton who pioneered the technique.
</P>
<P>
   At this very moment in his first budget struggle with the new
Republican Congress in 1995, Clinton used the Democratic National
Committee to run commercial after commercial hammering Republican
leaders for their proposal to slow the growth of Medicare by $270
billion.
</P>
<P>
   That television campaign, which cost at least $35 million , paid
huge political dividends. Clinton's aides said the commercials gave
the president the public support to stand up against the
Republicans in the budget battle that led to the government
shutdown. Some of his political strategists said those early ads so
shaped public thinking that they essentially won him the
presidential election the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican House campaign is tiny compared with Clinton's.
The Democrats, who are monitoring the ad campaign closely, say it
is now hovering around $500,000 and that few of the commercials are
running in prime time. The Republicans predict that before it is
over their campaign will cost $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties disagree strongly about whether the ad campaign
_ or the entire Republican posture on Social Security _ is having
any effect on the public. A Gallup poll of 1,005 adults conducted
in recent days for CNN and USA Today suggested it is not. Asked who
they trust more to act responsibly with the government funds set
aside for Social Security benefits, 38 percent of those polled said
the GOP in Congress while 50 percent chose Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Republicans' focus on Social Security has put the
Democrats on the defensive. Day after day, Democrats have had to
stand up and argue in their own news conferences that the
Republicans' spending bills are really using up billions of dollars
of Social Security money. Mustering evidence, they say that the GOP
is using every accounting trick and gimmick possible to be able to
make their claim that they are protecting the Social Security
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been putting out false information,'' Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader, said on Wednesday.
``They've been saying for weeks now that they're not spending
Social Security money,'' he said. ``This is the big lie. It's the
big fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   But a scuffle over which party is telling the truth over Social
Security degenerates into a confusing argument that does not draw
bright lines of distinction between the parties. And attempts to
explain budgetary gimmicks can quickly become mind-numbingly
complicated. Knowing this, Republicans are guardedly optimistic:
Given their past record, for them it is a win even to fight the
Democrats to a draw on budget matters.
</P>
<P>
   So the Democrats are looking for ways to change the dialogue.
``We are not just arguing about Social Security for this year, but
who's going to strengthen Social Security for the long term,'' said
Geoffrey Garin, who conducts polls for the Democratic congressional
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton in recent days sent lawmakers a proposal that would use
federal budget surpluses to keep the retirement system solvent
through 2050. And he proposed Medicare legislation that he said
would save money and enhance care by steering Medicare patients to
certain doctors and hospitals that offered discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said it was too late to take up the Medicare
legislation this year. And they pronounced the president's Social
Security plan dead on arrival, arguing that it does nothing to
narrow the mismatch between the program's revenues and the benefits
that will have to be paid out when baby boomers start retiring in
droves.
</P>
<P>
   For Pomeroy, meanwhile, this first session of the 106th Congress
has felt like a wasted opportunity, since the focus on whether
Social Security reserves are left untouched has little to do with
any efforts to guarantee the system's long-term health. He had
hoped that this year, before campaign 2000 went into full swing,
would provide breathing room to make progress on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office this week, he said with a sigh, ``This has
been a very dysfunctional session.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
