<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0464 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEMOCRATS-MOOD-BOS &LR;      10-27 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-MOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES HIT THE STREETS OF COLLEGE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ It was hurry up and wait Wednesday as the two
Democratic candidates killed time, browsed on Main Street, and met
the students here.
</P>
<P>
   The Dartmouth College campus swarmed Wednesday with a sea of
television trucks, reporters and volunteers waving signs and
chanting for Al Gore and Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, Bradley took a walking tour of Hanover, his
6-foot-5-inch frame bobbing above more than 60 reporters and
cameramen. Inside Lou's Restaurant, a favorite local spot for
breakfast, Bradley and his wife, Ernestine, chatted with customers.
The Bradleys seemed in a jovial mood, with the former senator
calling out for his wife, ``Where's Ernestine?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mixing,'' Mrs. Bradley responded, somewhat indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley spied an enormous apple pie on the counter, he
motioned to his wife and said, ``She could eat all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In return, when Mrs. Bradley saw her husband approach a baby,
she called out, ``Don't hurt the kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was trailed by an enthusiastic group of students, some
of whom were spreading a rumor that Bradley hadn't really wanted to
go to Princeton. ``Dartmouth was his first choice,'' one sign said.
Wednesday, at least, that was true.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began Wednesday morning in the southern town of Bedford,
where he jogged for about 45 minutes with the cross-country team
from Souhegan High School. Later in the day, he strolled down Main
Street in Hanover, dressed in a blue blazer and khakis, shaking
hands along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Dartmouth Bookstore, Gore stopped at the information
desk to ask for Jimmy Carter's new book, ``Sources of Strength.''
He wandered through the aisles, introducing himself to shoppers and
employees until he discovered a 6-year-old, Nikkita Gottling,
sitting on a captain's chair with a book in her lap.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knelt down on one knee and asked if he could read to her.
Picking up ``Tikvah Means Hope,'' by Patricia Polacco, the vice
president read in a gentle voice the story of a cat who survives a
fire. Gottling sat quietly, her hands in her lap, occasionally
glancing up quizzically at all the people snapping her photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bradley supporters began massing outside the
bookstore, waving their signs and shouting, ``Give me a B, give me
an R . . .'' Gore's student backers quickly assembled in response,
and the result was a chanting match that could be faintly heard
inside the store.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished reading the story, Gore thanked the little girl
with the navy tights and the Mary Janes for letting him read her
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I have three little girls and one little boy and a
grandson,'' he said. ``And I have to practice reading to him.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sally Gottling's request, Gore signed the book for her
daughter, Nikkita. (Gottling is a Democrat who has not decided whom
she is supporting in the primary.)
</P>
<P>
   After walking away, Gore turned back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on Nikkita, let's go buy your book,'' he said, leading
her over to the cash register where he paid for it along with the
Carter book. Before leaving, Gore gave Nikkita a hug and said
goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
