<HEADLINE>
COOL STUFF FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By NANCY HEWITT 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE SNEAKY WITCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kids love to hear scary stories. And Keith Grimwood and his
friends at Baba Yaga Records think their 19-minute recording of the
story of Baba Yaga the Witch is just perfect for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   This story of a sneaky witch who lives in a hut that turns
around on chicken legs is based on a Russian fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   A young girl sent on an errand for her stepmother is captured by
the witch, who makes her cook and clean. The girl's only salvation
is the kindness she shows to the cat, dog and a birch tree.
</P>
<P>
   The entire recording is done as a radio play complete with
bouncy songs such as ``Baba Yaga Song,'' ``What Is That Smell?''
and ``Happily Ever After.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baba Yaga the Witch'' is available on CD for $8 or cassette
for $5. To order by phone, call (877) 302-1739. On the Internet:
www.babayaga.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEST FLOAT FORWARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once again IHOP is asking children nationwide to help design a
float for the Tournament of Rose Parade in 2001 in its 11th annual
``Dream Up Our Float'' contest.
</P>
<P>
   To enter, kids ages 6 to 12 should pick up an entry at
participating IHOP restaurants. They will need to submit a drawing
and short essay based on the year's theme: What Makes Our Country
Great?
</P>
<P>
   The grand-prize winner receives a trip for four to Pasadena and
will ride on the float that his or her idea helped create in the
Tournament of Roses parade. The winner will als receive four
tickets to the Rose Bowl football game.
</P>
<P>
   One-hundred runners-up receive IHOP pancake parties for their
class and a $100 savings bond. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
