<SLUG> BC-SWISS-ELECT(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS VOTERS, TILTING RIGHT, UNSETTLE TRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Outwardly, the strong gains posted by fervent
nationalists in weekend elections were about refugees and the
country's place in Europe. But the voting was also very much about
Swiss identity, shaped by the recent furor over Switzerland's role
in World War II and its uncertainty over what path to take in the
future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After four decades of national consensus, the gains made by the
right in the parliamentary elections have upset governing
traditions and thrown the political landscape into chaos. The tilt
to the right places Switzerland firmly in the conservative camp
currently led by neighboring Austria, which recently gave its own
far-right party a resounding electoral victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amassing nearly 23 percent of the popular vote, the Swiss
People's Party greatly increased the number of its seats in
Parliament and made an open bid to strengthen its role in the
Federal Council, Switzerland's governing body. That threatens to
undo the ``magic formula'' of coalition rule among the four biggest
parties, which has existed since 1959. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This `magic formula' is as good as dead,'' the newspaper Blick
said of the current division of council seats to balance parties
and regions and its four language groups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Peoples Party, whose most visible spokesman is a millionaire
industrialist, Christoph Blocher, appealed to voters worried about
taxes, immigrants and closer ties with the rest of Europe. With its
clear answers _ which some critics call simplistic and dangerous _
the party consolidated support from smaller right-leaning parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blocher has built a bridge between the democrats and those on
the extreme right,'' said Frank Meyer, editorialist for the weekly
Sonntags Blick in Zurich, who has frequently written in opposition
to Blocher's politics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blocher appealed to ``those who have fear of too many
foreigners, fear of globalization and fear of Europe,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a simple message,'' the writer said. ``No.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The party campaigned on contentions that too many people were
abusing asylum laws by seeking refugee status. Accusations of crime
and drug dealing and fears that jobs were being lost to foreigners
were fueled by a large influx of Kosovars who fled the war in that
Yugoslav province. Many of the Kosovars had relatives who have
worked here for decades, often as laborers. But the influx of tens
of thousands more led to an anti-foreigner backlash and calls for
tighter asylum laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those fears are linked to fears of closer relations with the
European Union, where members have to allow free movement of people
across borders.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to close the borders,'' Felix Mueller, a
commentator for the daily Neue Zuercher Zeitung, said. ``There will
be some tightening. But basically this is about Swiss identity. It
boils down to sending your kids to school and finding out that 60
percent of the other children can't speak German. There's a feeling
that there are just too many to integrate.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beat Kappeler, who writes for a Zurich weekly, Weltewoche,
agreed. ``It's a problem in the schools and at work,'' Ms. Kappeler
said. ``I don't agree with all his solutions, but Blocher asked the
right questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote also reflects a continuing reaction to disclosures
about Switzerland's role as a banker for some Nazis _ and for some
Jews whose assets seemed to disappear after in World War II,
Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is greatly underestimated, especially for the elderly,''
he explained. ``There is great anger over this, and that generation
helped Blocher build a solid base.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Tuesday in the Israeli newspaper
Yediot Aharonot and quoted by Agence France-Presse, Blocher said:
``As far as Switzerland is concerned, the threat to boycott Swiss
banks in America is pure extortion. The boycott is exactly like the
boycott which the Nazis used in the past against Jews, when they
said, `Don't buy from Jews.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said his party was ``opposed to any manifestation of
anti-Semitism and racism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blocher has been outspoken against using Swiss funds to
establish a foundation for the needy, including Holocaust
survivors, Ms. Kappeler noted, ``which helped his popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Foreign Ministry announced that it planned to set
up a relief fund from selling its gold reserves. Bolcher said the
proceeds should go only to the state pension fund, not to a broad
category of needy people.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Peoples Party's strong showing will remake the 200-member
lower house of Parliament, where it will be the second largest
party, with 44 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is undoubtedly the most important shift in the vote and,
possibly in parliamentary seats, in Swiss political history since
the introduction of the proportional system 80 years ago,'' Le
Temps, a daily in Geneva, said in a front-page article alongside a
large photograph of Blocher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The future of the seven-member Federal Council is also at stake.
Blocher said Sunday that his party should receive a second position
in addition to the one it has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
