<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-BAXTER28-COX     10-27 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BAXTER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore moves closer to voters
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Retirees can be a rowdy crowd. Impatient for Vice
President Al Gore to show up last week at a forum organized by the
AARP, a room full of gray-haired voters guffawed when Ron Tornow
sprang to his feet and gave a rendition of the White Rabbit's song
from ``Alice in Wonderland'': ``I'm late! I'm late! For a very
important date!''
</P>
<P>
   Tornow, 62, a potter from Merrimack, was hardly more reverent
after the vice president had arrived and made his pitch to this
crucial audience, but he was more impressed with the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came today to see how boring you could be, and I must say
I've been thoroughly disappointed,'' he told Gore after listening
to him respond to questions about prescription drugs, Medicare and
Social Security, as well as crime and education. Afterward, Tornow
said he would even consider changing party registration to vote for
Gore in the Feb. 1 Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   In his quest for the presidency, Gore has indeed been late.
</P>
<P>
   Only this month, losing ground to Bill Bradley in this key state
and continuing to lag behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the
polls, did the vice president move his headquarters from
Washington, D.C., to Nashville, Tenn., and take sharper aim on
Bradley in an attempt to change the chemistry of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that effort has been the decision to ``roll the dice''
and put Gore closer to the voters he has to win back, said Michael
Whouley, who is directing the vice president's ground operation in
New Hampshire and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   So at the AARP meeting Friday and a gathering of about 200
mostly undecided voters last Thursday night in the gym of Dover
Middle School, the vice president stood surrounded by voters,
dressed in khakis and boots with a Palm Pilot V electronic
organizer on his belt. He answered questions on topics from Web
pornography to UFOs and stayed a long time afterward talking with
voters about whatever subjects were on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of open-ended forum Bradley and Republican John
McCain have been successful with this year, but Gore has been
understudy to a master of the town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Gore doesn't have the raw appetite for human contact and the
sense of political timing that made Bill Clinton such a hit in the
gymnasiums of New Hampshire in 1992, but like Clinton he's
conversant with an impressive array of issues. He isn't exactly a
stand-up comic, but he could mix some humor with a message, as he
did when a youngster at the Dover meeting told him about his
schoolmates printing pornography off the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the idea is not to look too much like the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there any grandparents here? Can I see a show of hands?
Anybody got 10 grandchildren?'' Gore did the same crowd-loosening
routine at four New Hampshire stops last week, to environmentalists
and veterans as well as retirees and undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, the 51-year-old vice president talked about his joy
over his first grandson, born to daughter Karenna on July 4. He
spoke of his pride in his father, the late Sen. Albert Gore of
Tennessee, and his mother, Pauline, who got through college with
her blind sister and went on to become a pioneering lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He wove in threads of his own biography _ of his disillusionment
after his tour in Vietnam and his father's defeat, and how he
learned a new admiration for public service covering local
government for the Nashville Tennessean newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The grandparent count is a device for reassuring audiences about
Gore's maturity, as compared to the president he serves. Tellingly,
he worked it into his answer when a young mother at the Dover
meeting asked him about his moral principles, which, in light of
Clinton, is a question he has become practiced at answering.
</P>
<P>
   The issues he focused on should appeal to traditionally liberal
New Hampshire Democrats. He declared in Dover that his first act as
president would be to resubmit the nuclear test ban treaty, and he
vehemently denounced the GOP senators who voted against it two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He told environmentalists he would fight new oil drilling off
Florida and California, even on existing leases, and he told a
teacher he favors tripling federal funding for special education.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire will be critical for Gore, both in terms of the
nomination and his general election prospects. Bradley is not
mounting as serious a challenge to Gore in Iowa, the other early
state. If Gore beats him here, he can turn his attention quickly to
the Republican nominee. If he stumbles in New Hampshire, he faces a
longer, more costly and distracting battle, even if he goes on to
win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore returned to New Hampshire this week to campaign before his
Wednesday night television debate with Bradley in Manchester. Over
the weekend, his wife, Tipper, led a big vote-canvassing drive in
the state. There are plans in coming weeks for several more town
meetings like the one in Dover.
</P>
<P>
   This week there was good news for the campaign in a USA
Today-CNN-Gallup Poll that shows Gore cutting substantially into
Bush's lead and maintaining a strong lead over Bradley among
Democrats nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the effort to fashion a ``new Gore'' has anything to do
with the poll numbers can't be known, but it coincides with his
campaign's shift in emphasis from contributors to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Mason, Gore's Georgia chairman and a former Clinton White
House staffer, said the move to Nashville and the other changes
have helped Gore be ``a little bit more unrestrained'' in his
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the vice president, there's a system for making
decisions and doing things that doesn't necessarily apply well to a
political campaign,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach has helped Gore act more decisively, he said,
changing his schedule and going to Rhode Island to visit a school
Bush didn't get to, and deciding to take an outspoken stand on the
nuclear test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   If it was not a ``new Gore'' who engaged in closer encounters
with the voters last week, it was a seasoned campaigner prepared to
roll up his sleeves and battle for votes in a more direct fashion
than he has been able to so far. He's late, but he has the power of
his office and a stolid determination to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
