<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES RISE SHARPLY FOLLOWING RELEASE OF A WEAK REPORT ON
DURABLE GOODS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prices of Treasury securities were up sharply for the first time
in a week Wednesday following the release of a weaker-than-expected
durable goods orders report for September.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said, however, that prices were gaining even before the
report was released. Early in the session dealers cited
short-covering and technical buying as contributing to the gains
once the December bond contract broke above the resistance level of
111 8/32. Gains in the European bond market sparked the initial
rally here on expectations that the European Central Bank will
raise interest rates to stifle inflation when it meets on Nov. 4.
The move is expected to benefit American Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day the 30-year Treasury bond had gained 22/32,
to 97 12/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
the price, fell to 6.32 percent, from 6.37 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the day's gains were limited ahead of Thursday's
third quarter GDP data coupled with the release of the September
Employment Cost index report. Many were also waiting for a speech
in the evening by Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan to the
Business Council, an organization of top corporate chief
executives, in Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Also factored into Wednesday's trading activity was the
Treasury's $15 billion auction of new two-year notes, which saw
decent investor demand and may have even helped perk up buying
interest in other maturities as well. Dealers had expected a high
yield of about 5.95 percent for the new note, which was awarded at
5.935 percent and slightly below the when-issued yield. Fear that
the note auction could fall victim to continuing bearish sentiment
over Fed policy concerns, especially with critical economic data to
be released later this week proved unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   The slightly larger-than-expected 1.3 percent decline in
September new orders for durable goods buoyed the bond market, but
since this was the first drop in five months, it was not considered
worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed,'' said Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase
Asset Management, ``durable goods orders during the third quarter
rose 8.5 percent above a year ago, which was the strongest pace
since the end of 1997 and a rather clear indication that the
current level of interest rates is not suppressing growth in a
major interest-sensitive sector of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's scheduled third quarter GDP release and its attendant
benchmark revisions, along with the release of the September
employment cost index, Fine quipped, ``inundate market participants
with a torrent of data which can only be described as a pure case
of statistical sadism.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects the GDP to demonstrate the economy's continuing
momentum, as growth over the past few years is likely to be revised
noticeably higher, while the employment numbers will be carefully
studied for signs of a pick up in labor cost pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations of a further round of Fed tightening at the
Federal Open Market Committee meeting on Nov. 16 is now fully
incorporated into bond market thinking and rate levels,'' said
Fine, ``and another quarter point must be deemed the most likely
monetary policy scenario at this point barring any evidence of a
sudden, substantial slowdown in the economy or an imminent, severe
contraction in the stock market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
