<HEADLINE>
ESCALATION BY EXTREMISTS HAS RESEARCHERS ON EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Alicia Karas, a veterinary anesthesiologist at Tufts
University, gingerly went through her mail Wednesday as she does
every morning, checking each envelope for a return address that she
recognized before opening it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Karas is not a primary researcher, she is not taking
any chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work is to improve pain relief in all animals,'' including
laboratory animals used in veterinary medical research, Karas said.
``But I worry very much when I get an unfamiliar envelope or
package. If I can't work out who it is from, I throw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from news that an extremist animal-rights group has sent
booby-trapped letters to a dozen Harvard researchers who use
primates in experiments, Karas and others are feeling the fallout
of a fight between the animal-rights movement and biomedical
research that might be getting uglier.
</P>
<P>
   The letters, which contained a razor blade taped inside the
envelope, were sent to 84 researchers nationwide. They follow a
string of raids and other efforts by animal-rights extremists to
destroy research labs, hunting clubs, and other places they say
exemplify animal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   What is beginning to frighten researchers is an escalation of
methods reminiscent of antiabortion extremists: targeting specific
physicians by sending them harassing letters, placing their names
on Web sites, and even protesting outside their homes. Widely used
by animal-rights activists in Britain and other European nations,
these tactics are relatively new to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an escalation in the past few months,'' said
Debra Higgins Cavalier, president of the Massachusetts Society for
Medical Research, which upholds the use of animals in research and
produces educational materials about it for schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most who are in the field are very much aware of the organized
opposition and take precautions,'' she said. ``But those coming
into the sciences may be more fearful and individuals starting work
with higher-learning species may question whether they have to''
use the animals for their work.
</P>
<P>
   In July and September, the Animal Liberation Front _ a radical
international group that opposes using animals for fur, food, or
research _ took credit for wrecking three hunting and fishing clubs
in Maine and has said it will carry out more raids against other
targets in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The group also took credit for firebombing four vans belonging
to a furrier in Warwick, R.I., last Friday. On Sunday, other ALF
members broke into a university laboratory in Washington state and
stole rabbits and white mice.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday, eight of the 12 targeted Harvard researchers
had received the razor-blade letters, which were sent by a small
British-based group called the ``Justice Department.'' Only one
researcher had opened the letter, and the university handed the
letters over to the FBI, said Harvard Medical School spokesman Don
Gibbons. The FBI has declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The intended targets were listed in a communique posted on an
animal-rights Web site by the ``Justice Department'' group, which
says it sent the letters to more than 80 scientists at schools
including Tulane University, and state universities in California,
Wisconsin, Minnesota, and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is impossible to count exactly how many attacks and
incidents of harassment have taken place recently in Massachusetts
or nationwide, both sides agree that such raids have been more
frequent. The reasons behind the increase are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   David Barbarash, a spokesman in Vancouver for the ALF, said the
increased activity may be due to media coverage, which influences
other advocates to act, or to the return to campuses of students,
the backbone of many such groups. He noted that the ALF's
``economic sabotage'' has so far not led to the injury of a human
or animal.
</P>
<P>
   Barbarash said he has no direct contact with ALF members, but
publicizes the group's actions after receiving mail and video
footage of raids.
</P>
<P>
   Established animal-rights groups Wednesday condemned the
harassment and terrorism. They said the animal-rights movement is
being buoyed as more researchers themselves take up the cause after
discovering other ways to test, for example, new surgical
techniques or the toxicity of new chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marginal people who may be engaging in extremist
activities are not the majority of the animal-rights movement,''
said Dr. Theo Capaldo, president of the New England
Anti-Vivisection Society. ``But they grab the attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
