A0477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NEWT-FOXTV28-COX     10-27 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWT-FOXTV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich signs deal with Fox as analyst
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How utterly right it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich, the former House Speaker who led the Republican
Revolution of 1994, signed Wednesday to be a political commentator
with Fox News Channel, the cable outlet that is trying to start a
revolution to topple cable news king CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Fox News Channel is battling CNN on every front: for ratings, in
its behind-the-scenes business plans, and, some think,
ideologically. Although executives at Fox and CNN downplay it,
there is a widespread perception among conservative viewers that
CNN has a liberal bias, and among liberal viewers that Fox has a
conservative tilt.
</P>
<P>
   Fox plays to this with its slogan ``We Report. You Decide.''
This is conservative code, as surely as ``law and order'' in the
late '60s implied ``won't go too fast on civil rights.'' Fox's
slogan is aimed at the other television networks, including CNN,
implying they're too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Into this battlefield where viewer feelings are heated _ but
hard data is virtually nonexistent _ comes Gingrich, who's
certainly been known to generate, and take, plenty of heat. But
Gingrich joining forces with Fox was not purely a political
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't looking in regard to ideology,'' Gingrich's New
York-based agent, Sandy Montag, said Wednesday. ``We talked to a
number of people, including some talks with CNN. Newt knows (CNN
NewsGroup Chairman) Tom Johnson well and he knows (Fox President)
Roger Ailes well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt just felt this was the right fit,'' Montag said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is the latest crossover between government and TV news,
joining a field that has been growing for years. The most spins in
the revolving door go to Pat Buchanan, for his forays between CNN's
``Crossfire'' and GOP presidential primaries, but Buchanan is
joined by Jesse Jackson (who has his own CNN show), George
Stephanopolous (former Clinton aide now with ABC News), former vice
presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro (hired Tuesday by Fox
News), and many others.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich is the highest profile crossover ever, and the
political perceptions give his move to Fox an extra edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Fox has people at the top who have Republican
backgrounds and CNN has people at the top with Democratic
backgrounds,'' said S. Robert Lichter, executive director of the
nonpartisan Center for Media and Public Affairs. ``But my sense is
that both Fox and CNN are mainstream news organizations, as opposed
to opinion-oriented news.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN's talks with Gingrich about possibly joining forces indicate
that the issue is more about ratings than ideology. Although CNN is
still the leader in cable news by any measure _ viewers, personnel,
prestige, international awareness _ Fox News has been gaining
ground steadily on CNN in its three years in existence.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich will not have his own show on Fox, but will be an
on-air analyst, said Chet Collier, senior vice president of Fox
News. He may be deployed similarly to CNN's Jeff Greenfield,
analyzing politics, although Collier said Gingrich may discuss
international affairs. Most of the logistics of Gingrich's air time
on Fox are still being worked out, Collier said, but he expects
Gingrich to appear ``within a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier said the linking of Gingrich's politics and Fox News'
perceived politics is ``kind of an easy thing to jump on,''
pointing out Fox's hiring of Ferraro. ``We're giving voice to
different points of view,'' said Collier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
