<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Oct. 31,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-SOPRANOS (subslug) (Undated) _ ``The Sopranos,'' shown
earlier this year as what was, in effect, a mini-series, was
produced in the hope that it would become a continuing HBO series
if successful, which it was. Thirteen new episodes have already
been filmed, to be broadcast starting in January, after a possible
rerun of the original show the last week in December. ``Berlin
Alexanderplatz,'' ``The Singing Detective'' and ``The Sopranos''
are something more than miniseries. Packed with characters and
events of Dickensian dimension and color, their time and place
observed with satiric exactitude, each has the kind of cohesive
dramatic arc that defines a work complete unto itself. No matter
what they are labeled or what they become, they are not open-ended
series, or even mini-series. They are megamovies. By Vincent Canby.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-THEATER (Undated) _ Steven Drukman, who is writing a
history of American avant-garde theater, earlier this month, asked
nine American playwrights gathered in Provincetown, Mass., to
discuss the future of American theater. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MANSFIELD-PARK-FILM (Undated) _ Fanny Price, the heroine of
``Mansfield Park,'' should have been one of Jane Austen's most
memorable creations. But despite her considerable virtues, Fanny
just can't get any respect. Most readers find her irritatingly
prissy and passive. Even Austen's own mother pronounced Fanny
``insipid'' when ``Mansfield Park'' was first published, in 1814.
More than 100 years later, the British writer Kingsley Amis called
her ``a monster of complacency and pride.'' No wonder it's taken so
long to produce a feature-film adaptation of Austen's most complex
and controversial novel. Patricia Rozema, the writer and director,
took on the challenge two years ago. Her new Fanny, will
undoubtedly shock Austen purists when the film opens, on Nov. 17.
By Barbara Kantrowitz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARRELSON-THEATER (New York) _ Woody Harrelson, 38, is in many
ways the boyish, free-wheeling bartender _ the role that made him
famous on the successful sitcom ``Cheers.'' In a recent interview
he admitted to a long-running problem with punctuality (``I was
born two months early and have never been early since'') and
clearly has a strong carpe diem streak. Even more resonant,
Starbuck, Harrelson's character in ``The Rainmaker,'' is a rootless
wanderer, a dreamer who charms people into believing he can bring
rain, then cuts out with their cash. So it is tempting to see all
sorts of links between the actor and his latest acting job. ``The
Rainmaker,'' N. Richard Nash's 1954 comic drama, will open at the
Brooks Atkinson Theater on Nov. 11. By Robin Pogrebin. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-ART-THEATER (New York) _ A look at Michael Weller's new
satirical comedy, ``The Heart of Art.'' Weller, 57, best known for
his 1970s plays ``Moonchildren'' and ``Loose Ends'' and his
screenplays for ``Hair'' and ``Ragtime,'' had three other works
produced in the 1970s and '80s by Joseph Papp, the short,
mercurial, cigar-smoking impresario of the Public Theater, a home
to challenging drama and provocative playwrights. By Mervyn
Rothstein. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PINA-BAUSCH-DANCE (New York) _ The reports from Germany confirm
it: Pina Bausch has mellowed. ``Gone are the days of the
all-too-ugly battle of the sexes,'' announced one critic. Another
wrote that the artistic director of the Pina Bausch Tanztheater
Wuppertal ``has become gentle,'' displaying a ``new and almost
old-fashioned tenderness.'' Kissing couples abound, as do scenic
projections of erotically bursting petals and shivering stamens.
The Pina Bausch Tanztheater Wuppertal returns to the Brooklyn
Academy for its seventh appearance this week (Tuesday and Thursday
through next Sunday), after a monthlong tour in California, Arizona
and Texas. This time, the company brings the 1995 production,
``Danzon,'' one of only two dances in the repertory that feature
Ms. Bausch onstage. By Ann Daly. (Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-OF-TIME-MUSIC (New York) _ The New York Philharmonic will
present Sir Michael Tippett's oratorio ``A Chld of Our Time'' on
Thursday at Avery Fisher Hall in New York City. Those performances
will be the orchestra's first of the work. But they are by no means
the first for its principal guest conductor, Sir Colin Davis, who
has been a fervent champion of Tippett's music since the 1960s, and
who conducted a performance of ``A Child of Our Time'' in London
during the summer to honor the composer, who died in January of
last year. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CARMINA-BURANA-MUSIC (Undated) _ Even amid the dizzying
heterogeneity of 20th-century musical styles, ``Carmina Burana,''
by the German composer Carl Orff, remains one of a kind. Written in
1936, this ``profane cantata'' sets medieval Latin texts depicting
the pleasures of drink, gambling and diverse country matters.
Christian Thielemann's new version with the Chorus and Orchestra of
the Deutsche Oper Berlin (Deutsche Grammophon 453 587-2; CD) finds
an admirable balance between refinement and expressive intensity,
avoiding the standard-issue garrulity too common in performances of
this work. By Lawrence A. Johnson. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GILLESPIE-ART (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Gregory Gillespie's
``Self-Portrait in a Black Shirt'' (1968-69) is one of those
remarkable paintings that, if known only in reproduction, creates a
startling effect when seen in person. For one thing it is
surprisingly small, less than one foot square. For another, even at
this scale it packs a wallop. When Gillespie made this painting,
included in his traveling retrospective of 39 works on view through
Jan. 2 at the List Visual Arts Center at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, it offered a challenge to both prevailing
abstract movements and to Pop irony. By Miles Unger. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DEVRIES-SCULPTOR (Los Angeles) _ ``Adriaen de Vries, Imperial
Sculptor,'' is now being shown at the J. Paul Getty Museum through
Jan. 9. Although he was said to have done for bronze what
Michelangelo did for marble, de Vries was not even mentioned by
name when a traveler described one of his masterpieces, only 60
years after his death, in terms usually reserved for the ancient
Greeks. Such cavalier treatment of Tintoretto, Annibale Carracci or
Guido Reni, his contemporaries, is inconceivable. And yet de Vries
(1556-1626) was clearly their equal as a master, first of the
twisting, straining style of the Mannerists and then of the
grandeur, the ornament and the emotional drama that we associate
with the Baroque. By Theodore K. Rabb. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-RADIO-SHRINKS (Undated) _ Analyze this. Radio psychologists,
who used to go couch to couch only on the AM-FM dials, are breaking
into television. Dr. Joy Browne, who is based in New York on WOR
(710-AM) and syndicated throughout the nation, began broadcasting
last month on CBS. Her biggest rival, Dr. Laura Schlessinger, who
is based in Los Angeles on KFI (640-AM) and also nationally
syndicated, has just made a deal with Paramount for her own
television show next fall. By Andrea Higbie. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WOMEN-SUFFRAGETTES (Undated) _ Ken Burns usually prides
himself on the wide scope of his historical knowledge. But it
wasn't long ago that the director of ``The Civil War'' made a
humbling discovery: He knew next to nothing about Elizabeth Cady
Stanton and only slightly more about Susan B. Anthony, the two
19th-century women who campaigned longest and hardest for a
constitutional amendment that would give women the right to vote.
He now regards them as, hands down, ``the two most important women
in American history.'' After three years of working on his new
two-part documentary, ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The Story of
Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony,'' will premiere next
Sunday and Monday nights on PBS. By Suzanne MacNeille. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Y2K (Washington) _ Y2K travel: still questions in the
air. By Matthew L. Wald. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ In Boston, radical art of pharaohs of
the sun; Click for hotel rooms in midtown Manhattan; An airport
enters the realm of museums; A new way to see Bermuda's capital;
New role for loop landmark. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Question and answers on travel. This
week: Shroud of Turin; Cottages in Scotland; Tours to Iran. By
Suzanne MacNeille. (Moved).
</P>
