<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VISIT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton to push hate crime legislation during Atlanta visit
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton will use a speech Friday in Atlanta
to advocate tougher laws against hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth visit to Atlanta this year, the president will
address the Anti-Defamation League's annual meeting. His remarks
will center on hate crimes, a central theme of the meeting, a White
House spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is one of 10 states that do not enhance penalties for
hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   American Jewish leaders are concerned about recent cases of
anti-Semitic violence, including a shooting at a Jewish community
center in Los Angeles. In addition, three California synagogues
have been attacked by two brothers linked to white supremacist
groups, and two people were killed and nine wounded in Illinois and
Indiana by a man linked to an anti-Semitic organization.
</P>
<P>
   Specifics of Clinton's remarks on the subject were not available
Wednesday. The White House said the president also would address
foreign policy issues that concern the American Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   The speech will follow Clinton's appearance at a fund-raising
dinner for the Democratic National Committee at a residence in
Buckhead. Almost 100 people are expected to attend the
$5,000-a-couple event at the West Paces Ferry Road home of
Democratic donor Larry Cooper, said John Kirincich, executive
director of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner will raise about $350,000. It is part of a ``DNC
fund-raising sweep'' the president is making in several states,
Kirincich said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope to minimize the effect that Clinton's visit will
have on metro Atlanta traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One is scheduled to touch down about 3 p.m. at Dobbins
Air Reserve Base in Marietta. He will briefly greet base workers.
Then his motorcade will travel south on Interstate 75 to take the
president to the Grand Hyatt Hotel in Buckhead. The Secret Service
declined to release the motorcade's exact route. But Special Agent
Jim Cool said no other expressways would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be driven to the fund-raising dinner at 7 p.m.
About 8:40, he'll return to the Grand Hyatt for the speech to the
Anti-Defamation League. His motorcade is scheduled to depart about
10 p.m. for Dobbins, where he will board Air Force One to fly to
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Officials will try to create the ``the least congestion, the
least discomfort to the public,'' Cool said. ``Hopefully, we can do
our security thing and not inconvenience the public too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
