<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-BOMBING-BOS &LR;      10-27 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS UNLEASH DEADLY BARRAGE ON CHECHEN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With thousands of civilians trapped in Chechnya's
capital Grozny, Russian warplanes and artillery Wednesday unleashed
the heaviest bombardment on the city since federal troops entered
the separatist republic last month, Chechen and Russian sources
said. The toll from the barrage was put at 100 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Federal troops closed in on Grozny from three sides amid heavy
fighting, and President Boris N. Yeltsin vowed to rid Chechnya of
``terrorism'' and ``return peace and calm'' to the rebellious
Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   There was little of either in Grozny on Wednesday. Officials of
Chechnya's separatist government said 100 civilians were killed and
more than 200 were wounded in Wednesday's attacks. It was
impossible to confirm the totals. Russian commanders said 100 rebel
fighters were killed in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces bombarded the capital three days after Russian
paramilitary police blocked traffic on the main routes out of
Chechnya, halting a flow of refugees that had reached 190,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off from escape, panicked Grozny residents hid from the
bombs in cellars, according to news-agency reports from Chechnya.
Western leaders and international aid agencies expressed alarm at
the escalation of Moscow's offensive, but Russian leaders firmly
fended off criticism of what they called an internal affair.
</P>
<P>
   Russia says it is fighting Islamic militants who invaded a
neighboring region last summer and whom Moscow blames for a series
of deadly bombing attacks in September. The Chechens deny
involvement in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do away with terrorism, to get rid once and for all
of the center of terrorism, international terrorism in Chechnya,''
Yeltsin told an award ceremony in Moscow before departing for a
vacation in the Black Sea resort of Sochi.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 68 and ailing, has stayed out of public view since the
fighting began, leaving the job of leading the Chechen conflict to
his prime minister, Vladimir Putin. Putin has repeatedly said that
Russia would avoid a full-scale military assault on Grozny, where
hundreds of Russian troops and thousands of civilians died in
Moscow's disastrous 1994-1996 war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But as Russian troops pressed Wednesday toward the capital from
the north, east and west, a new assault on the war-devastated
capital appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Arkady Baskayev, commander of the Moscow district of Russian
forces, said troops should move in and take the capital despite
fears of repeating the mistakes of the earlier Chechen campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary to take Grozny, and not just Grozny,''
Baskayev was quoted as saying by the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Wednesday's strikes appeared to be aimed at the homes of
rebel leaders in Grozny. Russian rockets hit what military
officials described as the headquarters of Shamil Basayev, whose
forces have twice invaded neighboring Dagestan. They also hit the
homes of the Arab-born commander who goes by the name Khattab, and
Chechnya's informal spokesman, Movladi Udugov.
</P>
<P>
   As Grozny shook under the air assault, Chechnya's separatist
president, Aslan Maskhadov, said the death toll from a rocket
attack on a crowded outdoor market in the city last week had risen
to 282, twice that of earlier reports. Russian leaders have denied
firing rockets at the market and have blamed the deaths on a
shootout among rival Chechen factions.
</P>
<P>
   Ilyas Akhmadov, foreign minister in the government of the
self-proclaimed independent region, called on the West to halt aid
payments and loans to Russia, saying the money was being used to
help finance its military offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bullet and every shell being used by the Russians is
being backed up by money from the West,'' Reuters quoted Akhmadov
as telling a news conference in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations refugee agency called on Russia to reopen
Chechnya's border with the Russian republic of Ingushetia to
Chechens fleeing the fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
