<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CARE28-COX     10-27 1800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE readies workers with mock disasters
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At 8:20 a.m., heavy gunfire and explosives erupted at
the National Assembly. Jet fighters were flying overhead. Then came
loud explosions near the president's residence.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. embassy warned us: The situation was extremely
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   And that _ as about 50 relief workers and I were soon to
discover _ was an extreme understatement.
</P>
<P>
   We did not know yet. But before this day would end, we would
have to cope with a coup and counter-coup; ethnic strife; refugee
crises in our own country and a neighboring one; a flood caused by
a dam break; the threat of cholera; abductions, rapes and other
human rights abuses; and _ when it seemed nothing else could go
wrong _ an outbreak of a rare disease attacking small sausagelike
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   For most anyone, this could go down as the ultimate day in hell.
</P>
<P>
   For the staff of CARE USA, the Atlanta-based relief and
development agency, it was all in a day's work _ a day of training
to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   CARE is pioneering this kind of education for its staff,
according to Paul Giannone, deputy director of the CARE USA
Emergency Group. The aim, he explained, is to ensure that a core
group of employees has basic knowledge of how to cope with the
complex issues that aid workers in the field face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is CARE saying we're really serious about this
business,'' said Giannone, who has been involved in relief work
since he began helping refugees during the Vietnam war. ``We're
trying to make sure our employees are as top notch as they can be.
We put a lot of time into it.''
</P>
<P>
   CARE has run similar disaster-training sessions in England,
Cambodia and Kenya. The current session began a week ago and ends
today at Callaway Gardens, southwest of Atlanta. Similar training
is already scheduled in South Africa next year.
</P>
<P>
   For the Callaway Gardens workshops, 19 of the 53 participants
came from CARE offices in Central and South America. Others, such
as Sherine Jayawickrama and Megan Meyer, came from Atlanta
headquarters. Karen Moore and Gaelle Nizery represented
Brussels-based CARE International. And still other trainees such as
Howard Standen of Britain and Eirik-Jarl Trondsen of Norway work
for other major CARE country offices.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the training focuses on specific aspects of emergency
work: how to assess damages and needs or what to do about health
care or water and sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   But the mock emergency experience is central to the training.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency scenarios are developed by Rob Stephenson, who has
a doctorate in emergency management from Kings College of London
University. An Englishman with a devilish sense of humor,
Stephenson confided that he sometimes wishes he could write a
science-fiction novel.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has wide experience in relief work in such far-flung
locales as Somalia, Ethiopia, Uganda and Thailand. Now 49, he is
also working with CARE on an analysis of its flood control projects
in India and will head to Nepal for a meeting on those projects
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson was ``brought up in a world where people were nice''
to relief workers. But he said conditions have changed dramatically
in his two decades-plus in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on the altered landscape, he said, ``The thing that
still stands out to me is the sheer expectation of violence _ what
will happen to you. ... Some of the people we are dealing with are
some of the most unpleasant people on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   In structuring the training, Stephenson said he wants the
sessions to be realistic enough to create stress even for
experienced staff. In the evaluations that have followed every mock
training so far, including the one at Callaway, the staff members
agree that he has succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario for last weekend's drill was set in Nigeria and
neighboring Benin, not because CARE expects such tragedies to
unfold there, but because the participants had little experience in
the area and were expected to have fewer preconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew a disaster of some unspecified kind would occur
Sunday. But on Saturday the participants, meeting in a Callaway
Gardens conference center, were divided into four groups and told
to organize themselves to carry out typical CARE development
programs in nonemergency situations.
</P>
<P>
   One group set up a Benin office in what was normally a pizza and
sub shop. I joined a group establishing a country headquarters in
Abuja, Nigeria's capital. Two other groups set up satellite offices
elsewhere in ``Nigeria.''
</P>
<P>
   Real-life Nigeria is twice the size of California. These
satellite offices were just down the hall. But we still had to
figure out how to communicate with the other offices and coordinate
activities, while learning everything we could about the country _
from its culture to its transportation systems. That took a while.
But after a relatively intense 12 hours, everyone had assigned
roles from budgeting to logistics and finding donors to finance
projects. Detailed maps were on the walls. Stock rooms held office
supplies. And a filing system was in place.
</P>
<P>
   Mock programs in forestry, water quality and health care were
also set up, and we were even considering a pest management program
near Kano in northern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Martinez, who normally works for CARE in Guatemala, had
been named country director for Nigeria, and Mike Godfrey, just
back at the Atlanta headquarters after a stint in Kosovo, headed
the Benin operation.
</P>
<P>
   CARE staffers also had been assigned to represent the Atlanta
headquarters, the Brussels offices of CARE International and home
offices of other CARE countries. Still others represented other
humanitarian agencies, the United Nations and its food-aid branch,
the World Food Program. Two CARE public information officers were
designated to represent the media. And Bob MacPherson, the former
Marine colonel who is CARE's top security analyst, would play dual
roles _ as U.S. Army Col. Hamilton and Nigerian Gen. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set.
</P>
<P>
   After winding up its work around 8:30 p.m. Saturday, the Abuja
group agreed to meet again at 7 a.m. Sunday to go over the maps
again and make sure all systems were ready.
</P>
<P>
   Once the simulated sounds of firing started, however, there
seemed no way to have prepared fully.
</P>
<P>
   There was certainly little time to ponder decisions. For
purposes of the training, Sunday was not a mere day. It was 21 days
of varying lengths _ each lasting from 10 to 45 minutes and
covering a span from Sept. 5, 2000, to Sept. 25. Sandwiches were to
be brought in, but there would be no break for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Each office received a scenario at the start of each day
describing conditions in that area _ conditions all of us hoped
could not grow worse but that constantly did.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the airport in Abuja and other cities closed. The
trains stopped running. And the roads that weren't clogged with
refugees _ whose pictures we saw _ were blocked by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   By 11:30 a.m., Sept. 11, 2000, was turning into Sept. 12. The
United Nations was warning us about ``an increasingly desperate
situation.'' The authorities would allow us to travel only after
obtaining security clearances from the military faction in control
of Abuja. Ethnic conflict was increasing _ 950 people had already
been killed in a single incident. Our Lagos office had been
evacuated. And CARE headquarters in Atlanta wanted us to make one
of our senior staff available for an extensive interview with a BBC
World Service reporter on how humanitarian agencies coordinate
their services.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at a surprisingly still-cheerful Cynthia Ford, from
CARE's human relations staff in Atlanta, and said we would never
make it through this day.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterwards, our Abuja team survived a scare: Our office
was surrounded by Nigerian soldiers, offended by our
``inflammatory'' questions about the burning of a refugee
encampment, and our programs were temporarily halted by the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon, Marc de Lamotte, a Frenchman who ordinarily
serves as CARE's Honduras country director, was taken hostage and
gagged. De Lamotte and some of the other CARE staffers in the
exercise had experienced real-life difficulties almost as severe.
But, in this case at least, I was envious of the hostage: He got a
break from hard decisions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jaime Stewart, a reproductive health specialist at
Atlanta headquarters, told me we had only two hours to go, I wasn't
the only one beginning to feel a little giddy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the day's tension, however, the drill's participants
still found time to laugh. I was delighted to discover, for
instance, that I did not absolutely have to have a visa to enter
``Benin.'' My Visa card proved perfectly acceptable. And how can
you not laugh when donors are offering water beds and Slinky toys
for desperate refugees?
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson later said he liked the laughter and had injected
some of the humor deliberately. Even though their work is
critically serious, relief workers often laugh to reduce the
stress, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson took a little ribbing himself when the trainees met
Tuesday for what turned into intense self-evaluations of the
experience. ``I told you you were going to be really impressed with
the kind of mind that put this together,'' said Frank Powell, a
Nairobi-based, Emory trained consultant who led the debriefings.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one was totally satisfied with his or her performance
during the drill.
</P>
<P>
   By its end, CARE and all other humanitarian agencies were forced
to leave ``Nigeria.'' And as Jan Schollaert _ the CARE country
director in Bolivia and a veteran of truly disastrous situations
from Somalia to Bangladesh _ explained sincerely to the mock BBC:
``CARE always hates to leave people in need.''
</P>
<P>
   But Powell told the group at Tuesday's debriefing that
perfection was not the point of the exercise: ``If you make a
mistake and you learn something from it, it's not a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in truth, the CARE staffers had reasons to be proud of
their performance. They had managed to work miracles amid the
chaotic circumstances _ not only finding donors for fictional
millions of dollars but developing and supplying four huge refugee
camps in Nigeria and another in Benin.
</P>
<P>
   Carsten Voelz, a German who set up real-life CARE refugee camps
in Albania and who now works in Kosovo, put the day into
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he said, ``we got some programs started, and we
helped hundreds of thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the people and the circumstance were fictional. But
tomorrow, for these staff members of CARE, they may be all too
real.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
