<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0490 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-FORBES-MONEY-ART-3TAK     10-27 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-MONEY-ART-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES IS SELLING SHARES IN FAMILY'S EMPIRE TO FINANCE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, as Iowa voters were preparing to elect a U.S. senator
and an assortment of state and local officials, the Steve Forbes
organization flooded the state with money for a lucky bunch of
Republican statehouse candidates in order to gain their support.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sexton of Rockwell City, who heads ``Farmers for Bush,''
received $1,000. In Cedar Rapids, Ron Corbett got $5,000 from
Forbes, even though he was a Lamar Alexander supporter. David
Miller of Libertyville got a $1,000 check _ ``with no questions, no
strings attached,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the Midas touch of Forbes, a publishing executive whose
net worth of $440 million puts him in the top ranks of wealth in
this nation. And he is not shy about sharing that wealth in pursuit
of his long-shot bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his business savvy and a seemingly bottomless pool of
assets, Forbes is engaging in politics in ways that are influencing
the Republican field far beyond his standing in the polls. His
spending is running neck-and-neck with that of the front-runner,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who is bracing for the possibility
that Forbes might unleash a television campaign against him, much
like he did against Bob Dole four years ago. Already, Forbes has
hurt one Republican candidate, Elizabeth Dole, who cited Forbes'
``unlimited resources'' when she abandoned her presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Including his 1996 campaign, Forbes has spent $53,745,000 of his
own money in his quest for the White House, and he is expected to
spend another $20 million to $30 million in the months head. This
means that by the time this presidential race is over, Forbes could
well have spent $80 million or more from his own pocket on his
political dream. Ross Perot spent $63.5 million in his two
presidential bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am prepared to spend what it takes to go the distance,''
said Forbes in an interview while campaigning in Iowa last August.
``But I'm not going to put out a figure. I want to keep other
candidates scratching their heads. But be assured, I will be very
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   To be so, Forbes is quietly selling off shares in his family's
privately held publishing empire, so much so that he is no longer
its majority shareholder _ a position he inherited as the eldest
son of the late Malcolm Forbes. And in March, he relinquished his
position as editor in chief of Forbes magazine, a business
publication run by his brother, although he still writes a column
twice monthly that reads like one of his conservative stump
speeches of less government and a flat 17 percent income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes left the magazine, he said, in the belief that ``I can
get my issues across,'' even if he does not win his party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The size of Forbes' financial holdings _ and the private way he
turns them into campaign cash _ makes them difficult to scrutinize
and turns the traditional way of looking at campaign finance on its
head.
</P>
<P>
   How, for instance, can the government measure his wealth when
the most it asks of candidates on federal disclosure statements is
whether their assets are ``over $1 million?'' How can voters ask
questions about financial interests that Forbes might be beholden
to when Forbes, mainly, is picking up nearly all of his campaign
expenses? And how can voters take a financial measure of Forbes
when the bulk of his net worth is in a private business, with few
details made available on how money moves from his business to his
campaign?
</P>
<P>
   ``The troubling aspect has to do with the fact that Steve Forbes
is extraordinarily wealthy,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of
Democracy 21, a nonprofit group advocating campaign finance reform,
``and extraordinarily wealthy people should not have an
extraordinary advantage in seeking the presidency. I don't know why
Mr. Forbes would not be willing to make clear to the public what
the basis is for obtaining the resources he is using to run for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing that Forbes does in his campaign that can be
described as less than first class.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign bus, for instance, is an electronic marvel capable
of beaming campaign photos and sound bites to his Web site for the
press and supporters to download. Digital photos taken of Forbes
and his supporters at campaign stops are processed in the bus and
available instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Iowans still remember the colossal air-conditioned tent with
French doors he provided to cool voters at the straw poll in Ames _
in contrast to other candidates whose campaign tents, without air
conditioning, baked in the August heat. And, he arranged for former
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain to visit Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Even his staff is color coordinated: Woman in matching white
polo shirts, blue for the men of his national staff, grey for the
local workers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All this has money gushing from Forbes' pocket to his campaign.
On Sept. 15, for instance, he gave his campaign $300,000, another
$500,000 on Sept. 20, another $300,000 three days later, $1.5
million on Sept. 27 and $700,000 on Sept. 28. Since January, he has
spent $16.3 million of his money.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of Forbes' free-spending ways, it is difficult to
determine exactly how all that cash gets into his pockets. Even
though the Forbes publishing empire's annual revenues exceed $1
billion and even though his family's homes spread from London to
Tangier to the French countryside, Forbes is asset rich, but cash
poor.
</P>
<P>
   With an annual income of about $3 million and potentially $80
million in campaign costs, Forbes does not have enough cash on hand
to foot his enormous bills. Even the sale last year of five
publicly traded stocks of other companies from his investment
portfolio was hardly enough, bringing in $680,000 to $5.6 million,
according to his campaign disclosure forms, which permits a wide
range in values.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes magazine shares, valued in the hundreds of millions,
are where Forbes' big money is. Yet these sales are taking place
with such secrecy that it is impossible to determine if they are in
line with campaign finance laws or could be illegal campaign
contributions from the buyers of Forbes shares to him. Citing his
family's privacy, Forbes has refused to disclose information about
these sales.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance law requires that such sales be at fair market
value. But there is no obligation for Forbes, or any candidate, to
provide the financial information to determine if that is the case.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Forbes has proved to be adept at mixing his business
and public lives to his advantage. Using $14 million in donations _
along with $100,000 of his own money _ Forbes founded a nonprofit
corporation, Americans for Hope Growth and Opportunity, to promote
himself and his agenda in nonelection years. The corporate
structure he chose for this advocacy group allowed him to legally
skirt individual contribution limits and accept large undisclosed
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Until he announced his candidacy, he also maintained an active
speaking business, charging $20,000 to $32,000 to deliver what, say
those who heard him, was a variation of his stump speech now heard
for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say Steve Forbes spends $50 million or $100 million in
running for president,'' said Stephen Moore, a director at the Cato
Institute, a Washington research group. ``That will not break him.
Lots of people will give that money to philanthropy. But the truth
is that if you wanted to force America to focus on your ideas, the
single best way to spread them is to run for president. It's money
well spent, even if he loses.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the language of accounting, Forbes' federal disclosure
statement lays out his cash squeeze. His main asset is his large
stake in the Forbes global publishing empire that accounts for the
bulk of his net worth, valued at $440 million by Fortune magazine
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this stake in the family business throws off little actual
cash. This is because most of Forbes Inc.'s annual profits, by
corporate policy, are reinvested into the business rather than paid
out as dividends.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Forbes' reported income last year was around $3.3
million _ $2.3 million from Forbes Family Holdings Inc., and the
rest from his speaking tour and investment dividends and interest.
He also had the one-time capital gains from public stock sales.
</P>
<P>
   And, for a man with such a high net worth and who is spending
with such abandon, he owns a relatively modest personal investment
portfolio: He valued his stocks and bonds at $5 million to $13
million on his disclosure forms. The New Jersey farm where he lives
and nearby investment properties are valued at $11 million and $55
million. As for Forbes' share of the family business, all he would
tell the government is it has a ``value over $50,000,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to some $4 million in donations, there are three
ways Forbes can raise campaign money: He can take it from current
income, he can take out commercial bank loans or he can sell
assets.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes has not reported any banks loans, and he is required
to do so by federal campaign law. His $3.3 million annual income
and his one-time investment gains fall far short of the $54 million
he spent already and the millions ahead. And, as of last March, he
has taken an unpaid leave from Forbes Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can he call on his four siblings or his wife, Sabina, for
help. Federal election law prohibits anyone from giving a candidate
more than $1,000. And the law prohibits loans from the Forbes
family or from Forbes Inc. to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   So, Forbes is following the third option _ selling his shares.
In doing so, he has quietly slipped from being Forbes Inc.'s
majority shareholder _ he had held 51 percent of the voting shares
and 35 percent of the capital stock _ to a major shareholder. He
said the buyers are Forbes' existing shareholders who, by all
accounts, are Forbes' four siblings.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The main question, from a campaign law perspective, is whether
the shares in Forbes Inc. were sold at fair market value. If not,
any amounts above the market price would be an illegal campaign
contribution. Nor can buyers of Forbes' shares agree to sell them
back to him when the campaign is over _ that would constitute an
illegal loan.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Forbes declined to say how much of Forbes Inc.
he has sold, what price was paid, what process was used to value
the Forbes shares, what percentage he currently owns or who
specifically purchased the shares. But he said he abided by all
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a privately held company,'' Forbes said. ``I've
said I've sold personal resources and that we followed tried and
true methods that will withstand scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no agreements to repurchase his shares at a later
date.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said that all his sales had been to existing shareholders
and hinted that there might be shareholders other than his three
brothers and one sister, by saying that his father might not have
owned all of Forbes Inc.'s shares at his 1990 death. But Leonard H.
Yablon, the company's executive vice president, says that only
Forbes and his siblings are shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' explanations, say campaign finance experts, fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't say that this is a private company and,
therefore, there need not be any other eyes looking at this,'' said
Larry Makinson, who heads the Center for Responsive Politics, a
research group. ``You are looking at transactions worth tens of
millions of dollars and you need something other than the word of
the candidate. You have to have extremely sharp antennae to make
sure someone is not making a back-door contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry J. Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, said: ``This is unprecedented. I can't recall of a
similar financing scheme. Forbes is nothing if not unconventional.
His supporters would call it creative, his opponents would call it
a violation of the spirit of campaign finance laws. But the
important point Forbes hasn't seemed to grasp yet is that the
president of the United States is public property. If his campaign
goes anywhere, he will be forced to tell some of this information
whether he likes it or not.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The magazine that put Forbes on the map _ financially and
politically _ caters to a business elite of 785,000 readers and has
corporate advertisers who flock to its pages. This, along with
Forbes' lavish parties for readers and advertisers, gives Forbes
stature in business, a chance to rub elbows with world leaders and
the column to spread his political and social views.
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis for The New York Times, James Kobak, a magazine
consultant, estimated that Forbes Magazine, which is debt-free, has
gross annual revenues of around $260 million and pretax profits of
around $70 million. He estimated the magazine's market value at
about $1 billion _ up from Fortune's $750 million estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This magazine is very profitable,'' Kobak said. ``It's a
special e. It's the kind of magazine that if you own it and
call the president, the president would answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other candidates who try dearly to get positive press
coverage, Forbes has made the magazine part of a never-ending
political campaign. His column, ``Fact and Comment'' is a
compendium of key campaign themes _ so much so that the Federal
Election Commission filed a 1996 complaint against it, which
Forbes' campaign manager William DalCol said had been successfully
fought ``tooth and nail'' on First Amendment grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Steve Forbes ever stopped running for
president,'' said Lawrence Kudlow, a Wall Street banker and a
Forbes adviser.
</P>
<P>
   To keep his candidacy alive after the 1996 election, Forbes set
up the nonprofit corporation, Americans for Hope Growth and
Opportunity, financing it with $100,000 of his own money and the
$14 million from 150,000 others. The group spent all the money and
ceased operations last year; its officers now work for Forbes'
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, the group ran 72 radio campaigns and five
television campaigns in 27 states, featuring Forbes and his prime
political issues. In addition, the group set up a leadership
political action commmittee, which raised $100,464 for donations to
candidates in key primary states, including Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike a partisan political committee that must identify
donors and limit contributions to $1,000, this group was set up as
a nonprofit corporation, allowing it accept unrestricted and
anonymous donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was always a questionable operation to promote Forbes in
key presidential primary states,'' said Wertheimer of Democracy 21.
``While technically it may not have come under the coverage of the
campaign finance laws, it certainly appeared to evade the spirit of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, this group allowed Forbes to amass a core of
supporters for his 2000 campaign _ even sending them his columns
from Forbes Magazine. Alpha E. Knapp, a retiree in Chandler, Ariz.,
said his involvement in the nonprofit group started with a donation
to Forbes' 1996 campaign. ``My name got picked and I started
getting more mailings,' Knapp said. ``I take Forbes Magazine, so
what he says shows up in editorials there, too. I got a lot of
mailings _ his speeches, his Forbes editorials.''
</P>
<P>
   In Grantham, N.H., William R. Putnam, another retiree, made
donations to Forbes' campaign and the group. Asked why, Putnam
said, ``I don't want him to have to spend himself to welfare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
