<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiorentina edges Arsenal
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Giovanni Trappatoni's resignation could have been
sincere or a clever ploy to get struggling Fiorentina off the mat.
Either way, after the Italian club's clutch 1-0 win at Arsenal on
Wednesday, the second-year coach will be sticking around for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Fiorentina clinched a spot in the next round,
thanks to a dazzling 75th-minute goal by Gabriel Batistuta, giving
a badly needed lift to a club in 11th place in Serie A.
</P>
<P>
   After a dismal loss over the weekend to lowly Piacenza,
Trappatoni said he was quitting. The club rejected the resignation
and asked him to make the trip to London.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenal, which has won only three of 13 Champions League matches
at Wembley Stadium the past two years, outplayed Fiorentina much of
the game. But it could not stop Batistuta when the Argentine
streaked down the right side of the box and hammered an 8-foot shot
from a sharp angle into the far side of the net. The Gunners'
consolation is a spot in the next round of the UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other clubs advanced this week, but six spots are still up
for grabs going into next week's first-round group finales.
Defending champion Manchester United moves on after earning a 2-1
victory at Croatia Zagreb Wednesday in Group D on goals by David
Beckham and Roy Keane. Marseille lost a chance to clinch by losing
3-2 to Sturm Graz.
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up Bayern Munich and three other German clubs could be
eliminated if they don't finish well. Bayern lost 2-1 to PSV
Eindhoven, setting up a must-win situation against equally
desperate Rangers in Group F (2:30 p.m. Wednesday, ESPN2).
</P>
<P>
   Valencia, near the bottom of Spain's Primera Division, took away
an impressive 2-1 win Tuesday in Glasgow on goals by Gaizca
Mendieta and Claudio Lopez to dash Scottish hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Porto and Real Madrid won easily on Tuesday to qualify out of
Group E, and Group G favorites Bordeaux and Sparta Prague also have
advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has earned the top spot in Group A after drawing 1-1 with
Bayer Leverkusen, which will battle Dynamo Kyiv for the other
place. Norwegian side Rosenborg moves out of Group C after beating
Boavista 2-0, leaving Borussia Dortmund and Feyenoord in limbo
after they drew 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mess is in Group H, which Hertha Berlin failed to
sew up after dropping a stunning 4-1 decision at home to previously
winless Galatasaray. Hakan Sukur had two goals for the Turkish club
in a four-goal outburst in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea is tied at the top with Hertha after earning an
impressive 1-1 draw at AC Milan. Oliver Bierhoff struck in the 74th
minute for the Italian side, but Dennis Wise equalized three
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona, which won Group B last week, whipped AIK of Stockholm
5-0 on Wednesday, getting two goals from striker Patrick Kluivert,
whose league play has been less than impressive.
</P>
<P>
   EVERTON DRAWS LEEDS
</P>
<P>
   A goal by David Weir in injury time gave surging Everton a 4-4
draw with Leeds, which still leads the Premier League by a point
over Arsenal. Everton led 3-2 before Jonathan Woodgate got the
equalizer for Leeds with 18 minutes left. Weir's goal left Everton,
which has finished in the upper half of the table only once since
1992, in eighth place.... Nwankwo Kanu scored a hat trick in the
last 15 minutes as Arsenal rallied to top Chelsea 3-2. The Nigerian
striker banged in the winner from a sharp angle on the touchline
from 16 yards out after pulling out Chelsea keeper Ed de Goey....
Manchester United's Premier League free fall continues, as the Red
Devils dropped a 3-1 decision to Tottenham, their fourth winless
contest in their last five outings. The injury news got worse at
Old Trafford, with the loss of midfielder Nicky Butt for six weeks
after he underwent a hernia operation.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: AMERICA CANS KIESE
</P>
<P>
   Last week's humiliating 3-1 loss to Cruz Azul did not put a
critical dagger into Club America's playoff aspirations, but it was
enough for club officials to lose their patience with coach Carlos
Kiese. The club is the richest in Mexico, and a first-place Group 3
tie with Atlas isn't good enough. The Paraguayan was the seventh
coach to lose his job during the Torneo Invierno. On Sunday, with
new man Roberto Alderete in charge, America needed an 87th-minute
goal from Joel Sanchez to beat lowly Santos 1-0.... Jose Cardozo
scored his ninth goal in Toluca's 1-0 victory over Guadalajara.
While Toluca is well in command of Group 1, Chivas are tied for the
lead of Group 4 with Necaxa, which defeated Atlante 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   FIRECRACKER HURTS PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   A vital game in the Peruvian Clausura championship was postponed
Sunday when a firecracker thrown from the stands exploded on the
field. German Pinillos, a defender for the Sport Boys club, was
said not to be injured seriously after the object detonated near
his legs. The incident occurred in the contest between Sport Boys
and Alianza Lima, which are separated by a point at the top of the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
