<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHART28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AP voters needn't rubber-stamp No. 1
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ According to the rules of the Bowl Championship
Series, the teams that finish 1-2 in the final rankings, issued
Dec. 5, will play in the Sugar Bowl for the national championship.
It is assumed the winner will be declared the national champion.
</P>
<P>
   But as ESPN's Lee Corso would say: ``Not so fast, my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Sugar Bowl will be declared the national
champion in the USA Today/ESPN coaches poll. The National Football
Coaches Association made that decision last year when the BCS was
established.
</P>
<P>
   But the voters in The Associated Press media poll are not
obligated to vote for the Sugar Bowl winner. Thus, a team such as
Virginia Tech has hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies (6-0) are third in the BCS standings, behind Florida
State (8-0) and Penn State (8-0), because their strength of
schedule is rated 42nd in Division I-A. (Florida State's is 21st,
Penn State's eighth.) Everyone who has crunched the numbers agrees
that Florida State and Penn State will meet in the Sugar Bowl if
both teams win the rest of their games. That could leave an 11-0
Virginia Tech team on the outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this: Suppose Florida State and Penn State play an
unspectacular Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4? Suppose that a couple of days
earlier, Virginia Tech dominated somebody in the Orange Bowl to
finish 12-0? The writers would be free to vote for the Hokies, and
there would be split national champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have this thing worked out well enough where the
two best teams will play for the national championship,'' Virginia
Tech coach Frank Beamer said. ``We don't talk about it. What
concerns us right now is Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   JUST THINKING
</P>
<P>
   _ Folks in Tallahassee say that Peter Warrick's return to
Florida State hurts quarterback Chris Weinke. Why? Weinke tends to
focus on No. 9 when the receiver is on the field, and that makes
the passing game easier to defend. Against Miami _ one of the two
games in which Warrick did not play because of his suspension for
his theft arrest _ Weinke completed passes to 11 receivers. Against
Clemson, 18 of Weinke's 24 completions were to two receivers,
Warrick and Ron Dugans.
</P>
<P>
   _ After tough games against Ohio State and Purdue, Penn State
had better be ready to play Illinois, which stunned Michigan 35-29
last week. Both of Joe Paterno's quarterbacks, Kevin Thompson
(shoulder) and Rashard Casey (chest), are sore.
</P>
<P>
   _ After beating Alabama for the fifth consecutive year,
Tennessee broke out its rendition of the Lynyrd Skynyrd tune
``Sweet Home Alabama.'' The Volunteers' version? ``We Own
Alabama.'' I imagine that one will get put on the Crimson Tide's
bulletin board next year.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Georgia assistant Mickey Matthews will be the Atlantic
10 Conference Coach of the Year. His first James Madison team is
6-1, with the only loss coming to No. 3 Virginia Tech in the
opener. A year ago, the Dukes were 3-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stanford and Washington, picked to finish sixth and eighth,
respectively, in the Pac-10 during the preseason, play Saturday in
a game that could be for the conference championship and a spot in
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston College had a problem with geese landing and living on
Alumni Field. So the school bought an English bird dog named
``Blaze'' to police the field and keep the geese away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nebraska coach Frank Solich has backed off after ripping the
officials who worked the Cornhuskers' 24-20 loss to Texas last
week. During his Sunday television show, Solich used words such as
``horrendous'' and ``ridiculous'' to describe some calls. By
Tuesday he had calmed down. Still, he sent a videotape of some
calls to the Big 12 office.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH QUOTING
</P>
<P>
   ``When he had me down, he twisted my ankle. If I was him, I
probably would have done the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   KENNY KELLY, Miami quarterback, who said Boston College tackle
Chris Hovan intentionally tried to hurt him last week.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   1967: The last time Michigan lost three consecutive
regular-season games. The Wolverines have lost two in a row, to
Michigan State and Illinois. They face Indiana on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   483: Yards needed by Wisconsin's Ron Dayne to break the NCAA
career rushing record of Texas' Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   21: The lead Southern California had in its games against Notre
Dame and Stanford, only to lose both.
</P>
<P>
   5: Consecutive games in which Texas A&AMP;M has had a kick blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
