<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITISH-BANKS-MARKETP     10-27 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-BANKS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NATWEST BID FOR BANK OF SCOTLAND TURNS INTO A LONG
SOAP OPERA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The hostile bidding war for National Westminster Bank
that the Bank of Scotland started last month is turning out to be
not much of a war at all.
</P>
<P>
   No other suitors have emerged to help heighten the drama of what
now seems to be an overly long soap opera with hardly any of the
plot twists that had been foreseen.
</P>
<P>
   The story line, however, shifted ever so slightly Wednesday as
Natwest announced its defense strategy, hoping to thwart the Bank
of Scotland's $34 billion hostile bid and any other bid from
friendlier suitors that have been taking a wait-and-see approach.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy, which the British bank had publicly hinted at in
fits and starts, includes a plan to sell assets that analysts
estimate could raise the equivalent of $6.6 billion as it
desperately tries to remain independent. Natwest said it would sell
its fund management unit, Gartmore Investment Management; its
investment banking unit, Greenwich Natwest, and its venture capital
unit, Natwest Equity Partners, as well as Ulster Bank.
</P>
<P>
   If shareholders squashed the Bank of Scotland's bid, Natwest
would return the proceeds from the sales to its shareholders. As
part of its defense, Natwest also said it would cut 1,650 jobs,
beyond the 10,000 job cuts already announced.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting its defense plan, David Rowland, chief executive of
Natwest said: ``Bank of Scotland is attempting to hijack cost
savings that belong to Natwest shareholders and is claiming
unrealistic merger benefits. I urge Natwest shareholders to reject
the offer which is ill-conceived and significantly undervalues
Natwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland was appointed chief executive two weeks ago to succeed
Derek Wanless as part of an interim defense strategy. Ron Sandler,
the former chief executive of Lloyds of London, also joined the
company then as chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Natwest's plan was a bit contradictory, because in
many ways it mirrors the Bank of Scotland's plan to squeeze $1.7
billion in savings and value out of the bank, Britain's third
largest, by selling off assets and laying off employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt overall that there are still a lot of question marks,''
said Tom Rayner, an analyst at SG Securities in London. ``The
strategy looks like a lot of backtracking. There's a lot more
convincing needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Natwest's defense strategy, the Bank of Scotland
seized on the concept that the strategy is a copycat plan, that
Natwest's latest ideas concede the merits of key elements of the
Bank of Scotland's proposed strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burt, chief executive of the Bank of Scotland, continued
the verbal sparring. ``Natwest's corporate memory is either very
short or highly selective,'' he said. ``The facts are simple:
Natwest's track record is one of change, failure and
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt's assertions aside, Natwest shares remain higher than the
Bank of Scotland's original bid. Shares of Natwest closed Wednesday
at an 8.3 percent premium over the Bank of Scotland's offer price,
dropping 2.6 percent, to 1,374 pence, or $22.67.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said shares of Natwest were trading at a premium
because investors were still hoping for another suitor to emerge.
The Royal Bank of Scotland has been watching and may soon pounce,
executives close to the company said, though the company has not
made its intentions clear. Abbey National is also said to have an
eye on Natwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has decided the Bank of Scotland's bid is not
enough,'' Rayner said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that both of the companies have publicly issued their plans,
analysts expect another player could join the bidding because it
now has the advantage of knowing what it is playing against.
Investors, however, remain a bit skeptical that anyone else will
emerge with a higher bid for Natwest, as reflected by the 14
percent drop in shares of Natwest since the Bank of Scotland
formally announced its bid on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   A number of analysts privately questioned whether the Royal Bank
of Scotland would be making a bid, considering the amount of time
it has already had to do so and the way that the shares of Natwest
have performed. One analyst said that newspaper reports that Royal
Bank was planning a bid several weeks ago were simply a way for the
bank to dip its toe into the market to test interest.
</P>
<P>
   Rayner said the Royal Bank of Scotland might just be waiting for
Natwest shares to drop a little further. ``I don't think they can
afford to do nothing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
