<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-DRUG-RESISTANT-TB-ART     10-27 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-RESISTANT-TB-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS PLAN NEW STRATEGY AGAINST DRUG-RESISTANT TB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Colo., N.J.)  (Exclusive) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   International health officials and scientific experts say that
strains of tuberculosis resistant to various drugs are spreading
faster than anticipated overseas and that a new treatment strategy
is needed to prevent what has already become an epidemic from
spinning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the World Health Organization has recommended
that patients with ordinary tuberculosis take up to four drugs,
every day, for six to eight months, and that doctors and health
workers watch them take their medicine and monitor them to ensure
that they are cured. The strategy has become widely known as DOTS,
or Directly Observed Therapy Short-Course.
</P>
<P>
   But in a new report, doctors from the Harvard Medical School and
the Open Society Institute, a foundation financed by George Soros,
say more intensive treatment is needed in the former Soviet Union
and other areas where rates of TB are relatively high.
</P>
<P>
   In the intensive regimen, patients are required to take many
more expensive drugs, over a longer period of time.
Multidrug-resistant TB strains afflict on average 2 percent of
victims, and nowhere more than 30 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation has been endorsed by the World Health
Organization, whose director general, Gro Harlem Bruntland, is
scheduled to be present Thursday when the 408-page report is made
public in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But some health experts fear that new approach could make the
situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the new treatment strategy, called DOTS-Plus, doctors watch
patients take up to seven drugs daily, for 18 to 24 months, at far
greater cost per cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a landmark shift by the WHO, the most exciting step
forward in the global effort to control TB in 25 years,'' said
Michael D. Iseman, director of TB services at the National Jewish
Medical and Research Center in Denver, a leading expert in TB
treatment and research and a member of the advisory board of the
Harvard group which wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``The Global Impact of Drug-Resistant
Tuberculosis,'' contains a foreward offering an unusual endorsement
from the WHO's leading specialists of the new treatment strategy.
``In our zeal to implement DOTS everywhere,'' said Mario C.
Raviglione, the WHO's coordinator for bacterial and viral diseases,
who signed the preface, ``there was no clear policy in the program
to take care of multidrug-resistant TB. Now we realize that
something more must be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Raviglione said he does not know how much more the new treatment
strategy would cost since his world health group is only starting
to study the issue. But he conceded that the expanded strategy will
almost certainly cost hundreds of millions of dollars, ``perhaps a
billion dollars more'' than the currently recommended treatment,
which is already underfunded, many doctors complain.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, several experts said that the WHO's
recommendations were likely to intensify an already emotional
public health debate about the wisdom of expanding recommended
treatment for some TB patients at a time when two million people
throughout the world die each year for lack of adequate care.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting September in Madrid, Spain, opponents of the
expanded strategy argued that emphasizing the treatment, would
shift desperately needed public health resources away from curing
patients with nondrug-resistant tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WHO declared TB a global emergency in 1993,'' said Thomas
R. Frieden, the WHO medical officer for TB for Southeast Asia, in a
telephone interview in New Delhi. ``But six years later fewer than
20 percent of patients get even basic treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Frieden said efforts to combat multidrug-resistant TB should
focus on its cause, inadequate treatment of ordinary TB.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis is known to acquire resistance to drugs that are
being given patients inefficiently. If the wrong drugs or doses are
given for too short a time, or if the patients stop taking them,
the TB bacteria that survive may become resistant to the drugs.
Frieden and other experts fear that if new, more highly effective
drugs are also given inappropriately, the multidrug-resistant TB
strains will eventually become unresponsive to these drugs too,
making an already bad situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   Paul E. Farmer, director of the Program in Infectious Disease
and Social Change at Harvard Medical School, the report's primary
author agreed that poor treatment has led to many cases of
multidrug-resistant TB. But he said inadequate treatment was no
longer the only cause of such strains. He said new data suggest
that in some areas drug-resistant strains are now spreading on
their own, person-to-person, even in countries with good TB control
programs.
</P>
<P>
   He said multidrug-resistant tuberculosis now threatens not just
poorer countries, but Europe and, eventually, the United States as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The study concludes that multidrug-resistant TB has now been
reported in 100 countries and that its rates are rising faster in
some countries than public health officials anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in Russia's Ivanovo region, a poor province with a
vast prison population and shoddy public health, the WHO reported
in 1997 that 4 percent of TB patients had multidrug-resistant
strains. According to the new report, such cases now total 8.9
percent of people with TB.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figures like these show that multidrug-resistant TB in some
places is now out of control, and it shows we were doing something
wrong, that more than DOTS is needed in such areas,'' said
Raviglione.
</P>
<P>
   But Frieden, who was New York's TB control director between 1992
and 1996, points out that two-thirds of people with
multidrug-resistant TB developed it because the Ivanovo province
program did not ensure that patients' took their medication. ``If
medicines aren't being taken, it doesn't matter if you're being
given two or four or seven drugs,'' he warned. ``And if resistance
to reserve drugs emerges, our last line of defense against TB will
be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer agreed that failure to take drugs was still a major
problem in Russia and elsewhere. But, he added, the Ivanovo study
had also shown that ``the drugs patients received were
inadequate,'' which is primarily why only 5 percent of
multidrug-resistant cases were cured.
</P>
<P>
   Raviglione said adoption of a DOTS-plus strategy would not mean
the WHO would abandon its current DOTS strategy. In fact, both
stressed the need to ensure that doctors everywhere make sure
patients take their drugs. Rather, they said, the report stresses
the need for supplemental drugs and therapy where
multidrug-resistant strains already exist.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said that his medical team began to question the
currently recommended therapy about five years ago after a relief
worker colleague died in a Massachusetts hospital after contracting
drug resistant TB in Peru, which has an excellent DOTS treatment
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made us think that the one-size fits all treatment
approach was not universally effective,'' Farmer explained.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the scientists agreed, there would be no competition
between resources for treating nondrug-resistant and drug-resistant
TB. But given world's indifferent response to the threat, said Lee
B. Reichman, executive director of the National Tuberculosis Center
in Newark, N.J., some doctors feared there would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dots-Plus is a sexy new strategy with Harvard behind it, and
like any sexy new strategy, there is some fear of it,'' said
Reichman, who contributed to the report. ``But I'm on the WHO's TB
working group, and we've made it clear that won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard study shows that multidrug-resistant TB emerged in
Peru, despite the fact that it had an excellent control program. In
Peru, Farmer and his colleagues were able to cure 85 percent of
supposedly incurable multidrug-resistant patients by giving them up
to seven drugs over 24 months. The treatment cost between $280 to
$4,900, higher than the cost of the currently recommended therapy,
but far less than what such treatment would cost in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Reichman estimates that it costs his center in Newark, N.J., an
average of $4,800 per patient and six months to cure normal TB
without hospitalization, as opposed to $200,000 and up to two years
of treatment, including lengthy hospitalization, to cure patients
with multidrug-resistant strains. In New York City in the early
1990s, an outbreak of multidrug-resistant TB cost up to $1 billion
in extra health care costs, said Reichman.
</P>
<P>
   Because New York and other major cities have bolstered TB
surveillance, treatment and control, rates of multidrug-resistant
TB cases have recently been declining in the United States. In
1998, according to the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, only 1.1 percent of American TB cases were
multidrug-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation overseas has grown far more dangerous,'' said
Alex Goldfarb, a microbiologist at the Public Health Research
Institute, a private health group in New York and a co-author of
the report. ``Because there are ever more drug-resistant TB cases
in hot zones, ``each case is a walking time bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   In one of its many ominous predictions, the study warns that
even if the recommended DOTS treatment strategy is implemented, 171
million new cases and 60 million deaths can be expected between
1998 and 2030. The worst case scenario predicts 249 million new
cases and 90 million deaths, even with the currently recommended
treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
