<HEADLINE>
CLEAN AIR PLAN MAY HELP HOUSTON CUT SMOG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas' environmental commissioners Wednesday
approved an outline for a sweeping new effort to slash air
pollution so Houston can comply with a federal cleanup deadline in
2007.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which Gov. George W. Bush will submit for federal
approval next month, defers key decisions and rule adoptions for
several more months. A final version is not due until December
2000.
</P>
<P>
   But with Bush the Republican presidential front-runner,
Houston's chronic smog violations and the state's efforts to stop
them have drawn national attention and critical comment in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bristling at what he called unfair and incorrect charges, the
environmental commission's top staff official said the nation's
most stringent controls for one key group of smog-forming
pollutants will be imposed on Houston-area industries.
</P>
<P>
   This 90 percent cut in all industrial emissions of nitrogen
oxides _ the new smog plan's primary target _ is ``unprecedented,''
said Jeff Saitas, executive director of the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Los Angeles area, long noted for having the most
aggressive air-quality program, industries don't have such a strict
mandate, Saitas said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan approved by the three TNRCC commissioners, all Bush
appointees, indicates new pollution cuts are also in store for
private vehicles, construction equipment, marine vessels and
others.
</P>
<P>
   They would add up to major reductions from all those sources,
though not nearly as large as industries' 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State calculations indicate the Houston area must erase up to 85
percent of its combined nitrogen oxide emissions to bring levels of
ground-level ozone, a respiratory irritant and smog's chief
ingredient, below the Clean Air Act's national health standard.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC commissioners will not formally select and propose the
measures to achieve those reductions until next spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the document approved Wednesday indicates a strong
likelihood they will include a stricter tailpipe-testing program
for cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Such a program was included in the collection of potential
measures that computer modeling showed would reduce ozone levels
the most, though still not below the health standard.
</P>
<P>
   State law prohibits the TNRCC from restoring the stricter
tailpipe test that legislators junked four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But TNRCC and local air-quality planners are studying the
possible introduction of a cheaper, though similar, test that could
achieve comparable pollution reductions.
</P>
<P>
   This new test, like the one that lawmakers abandoned and banned,
would measure vehicle emissions of nitrogen oxides. The current
test in Houston's Harris County does not do so, measuring only
other smog-forming pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Because even the framework plan's most stringent set of possible
measures appears to fall short of the health standard, the TNRCC is
committed to bridging that gap by choosing additional actions,
TNRCC Chairman Robert Huston said .
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials say more measures must be identified to achieve
reductions from vehicles and from so-called ``off-road sources,''
principally construction equipment and marine vessels.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility for additional cuts in vehicle pollution,
mentioned in the plan, is a program of voluntary measures such as
new carpooling and vanpooling programs.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC has asked local officials to specify which measures
they should adopt to reduce vehicle use, and therefore vehicle
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   To lower emissions from construction equipment, the TNRCC staff
has been studying a required shift in construction activity to
nighttime hours, because ozone forms when various pollutants react
in sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Business officials have already criticized that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials could activate a ``sanctions clock'' leading
to economic penalties for Houston if they reject the plan approved
Wednesday because it did not actually choose enough measures to
meet the ozone standard.
</P>
<P>
   But Commissioner Ralph Marquez said he believes that is not a
``fatal flaw,'' because the TNRCC is promising to complete that job
next year.
</P>
<P>
   A former chemical industry official, Marquez said he now sees
greater cooperation to improve Houston's air quality than ever
before, involving federal, state and local government officials
along with business leaders and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Although the framework plan's strictest scenario doesn't yet
meet the standard, computer studies found it would shrink the
geographic area affected by ozone violations and the length of time
when readings that high occur, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
