u s BC-FBC-INTERNET28-COX     10-27 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-INTERNET28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web wars: Scouting made easy
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Florida Gators didn't have to wait
for Georgia defensive stars Marcus Stroud and Will Witherspoon to
return to the practice field to know they would be playing in
Saturday's crucial game in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   All the Gators had to do was point a mouse and click.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find out just about anything you want about a team on
the Internet,'' said Jamie Speronis, UF's director of football
administration who surfs the Net for such information. ``Things
that used to take us several days to find out through newspapers
that were mailed to us, we can now learn almost instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't think the Bulldogs haven't also added cyberspace to their
scouting report. They, too, know Florida offensive stars Travis
Taylor and Earnest Graham are expected to return for the game that
should decide which school will be playing in the SEC Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a guy who's responsible for scouting the other team
through the Internet,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``He uses it
to read newspapers and check out Web sites for things like
injuries. There's a lot of information out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But is there too much information out there in dot-com land?
Some college coaches think so. Just ask LSU coach Gerry DiNardo.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, DiNardo closed his team's practices after
Georgia team video personnel told their LSU colleagues the Bulldogs
were able to access information about the Tigers' practices on
unofficial Internet sites. DiNardo said this information included
practice video and lineup changes as well as a tip that LSU was
working on a fake on-side kick. This disclosure, of course, came
after Georgia beat LSU 23-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were getting a lot of things. It's more serious than
depth chart movements,'' said DiNardo, who admitted he's looked at
opposing team Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   While some dismiss DiNardo's actions as a desperate move by a
coach trying to save his job (LSU has lost five in a row), he
insists the Internet has become as big a problem in college
football as bad officiating and four-hour games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is not just the info that gets out there,
it's also the speed with which it gets out,'' DiNardo said.
</P>
<P>
   DiNardo isn't the first SEC coach to complain about the
Internet. Two years ago, then-Auburn coach Terry Bowden asked one
of his school's unofficial Web sites to limit some of the
information they were putting on there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those Web sites are a great service for the fans,''
Bowden said. ``But they were putting up the kind of information
that our opponents wanted to know, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's especially critical when some Web sites willingly post
inaccurate information. For example, two weeks ago, a Web site out
of Tallahassee posted a story that said Florida coach Steve
Spurrier was considering taking the Notre Dame job.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous? ``Not when we got a call from the South Bend (Ind.)
paper wanting to know if there was any truth to it,'' said Norm
Carlson, a UF football publicist since 1963. ``That's the problem
with the Internet. You don't know if it's factual.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet seems to be a bigger issue at programs with large,
loyal and passionate followings, such as Florida and Georgia. While
each school has its own official Web site _ Gatorzone.com and
Georgiadogs.com _ there also are several unofficial sites that are
more popular with fans because they provide chat rooms and they'll
post information such as rumors and recruiting updates.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most successful Web sites in the nation is
GatorCountry.com, which gives Florida fans stories from every major
newspaper in the state, as well as a chat room and the popular
Swampie's Rumor Mill. Raymond Hines, who co-owns the site with Gus
Garcia, said Gator Country receives up to 300,000 hits a day during
the season and more than 1 million hits a day during recruiting
season.
</P>
<P>
   While Hines says he and Garcia make a profit off the site,
they're not getting rich from it. Moreover, almost all of the
writers who contribute do so for free or a nominal fee. They add to
the site out of their loyalty to the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Says Hines, ``Call us a virtual tailgating party where we all
chip in on the grill.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines said neither Florida officials nor Spurrier has asked
Gator Country not to put anything on the site. Hines disagrees with
the theory that sites like his hurt the Gators because it provides
too much, or inaccurate, information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all reported one way or another; we just beat most to the
punch because of the nature of our medium,'' Hines said. Most
coaches have adopted Lou Holtz's philosophy about the Internet:
``Love it or hate it, but get used to it,'' he said. ``Because it's
here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
