<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father of kidnapped kids takes crusade to Congress
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A kidnapper hid John LeBeau's infant
twins somewhere in Europe three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To get them back, the Palm Beach Gardens businessman traveled
30,000 miles on six trips overseas, hired lawyers and investigators
in three countries, learned international law himself, incessantly
badgered the U.S. government for help, spent at least $150,000, and
ultimately, with no small amount of luck, found the children living
in Britain with their abductor.
</P>
<P>
   She was also their mother and his estranged wife, Mette LeBeau.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon John LeBeau made another trip _ this time to
Washington _ where he described his ordeal to a U.S. Senate
judicial subcommittee that is studying international parental
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thought to be 10,000 of these cases now, but mine is
the only known one in which an arrest and extradition has been
upheld,'' LeBeau said. ``What I'm trying to accomplish is to show
the Congress someone who this problem has actually affected _ show
them a real parent who lost his kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee, chaired by Sen. Strom Thurmond (R-S.C.), is
considering whether foreign governments should be pressured to
return children abducted by parents. A spokesman for Thurmond said
the United States returns 90 percent of kidnapped children to other
nations but only 30 percent are returned here.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators have threatened to block foreign nations'
extradition requests unless they honor U.S. requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now, the issue hasn't gotten much more than the old
Washington two-step,'' LeBeau said. ``We've had enough studies and
reports. What we need now is action and results.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, LeBeau's children, Luke and Ruthie, were
discovered with their mother in Portsmouth, England. A Danish
citizen, she had first taken them to Denmark. The three were
returned to Florida in December by British authorities after LeBeau
agreed to seek dismissal of the federal criminal kidnapping charges
against his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Mette LeBeau gave up her fight for custody of the children in
Palm Beach County last spring and returned to Denmark, leaving them
with their father.
</P>
<P>
   John LeBeau, 40, an insurance agent and owner of a small medical
supplies company, has criticized federal officials for their
reluctance to treat parents who kidnap as criminals and pursue
their prosecution aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never did I encounter more hostility, ignorance, incompetence,
deceit and blatant unwillingness to protect our youngest American
citizens as I did with our own Department of Justice,'' LeBeau
said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has told the Senate Judicial
Committee her office often is hamstrung by the sovereignty of
foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the international arena, custody orders entered by state
courts in the United States are not enforceable outside of the
United States,'' Reno said. ``Furthermore, state or federal
criminal warrants reach only as far as our extradition treaties
take us and as far as the domestic law of our extradition treaty
partner permits.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 5, the twins turned 4 years old and LeBeau marked the
day by founding a nonprofit corporation that bears their name.
Working with the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children, the Ruth and Luke LeBeau International Child Rights
League will attempt to assist other left-behind parents through the
political and legal morass that LeBeau conquered with
two-and-a-half years of dogged persistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome I had is virtually unheard of,'' he said. ``I want
to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
