<SLUG> BC-STEWART-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 LEARJET CRASHES EXAMINED AFTER GOLFER, 5 OTHERS, ARE KILLED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.D., Ohio, Mich., Ky., Fla., Kan., Texas)   (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal officials investigating the mysterious
crash of a Learjet in South Dakota said they were scrutinizing
three other Learjet crashes in which the passengers and pilots may
have been incapacitated by a loss of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   No cause has been determined in Monday's crash, which killed the
golfer Payne Stewart and five other people, but investigators are
speculating that all on board were rendered unconscious, or even
killed, by a lack of oxygen. The plane, a Lear 35, flew 1,400 miles
on autopilot before nose-diving into a South Dakota hay field.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators gingerly removed debris Wednesday, the National
Transportation Safety Board's investigator in charge, Bob Benzon,
said in a telephone interview from Aberdeen, S.D., that his agency
was looking into the 1983 crash of a German-owned Learjet that flew
1,600 miles from Vienna, Austria, before crashing into the Atlantic
about 200 miles off Iceland, and into a crash in Mexico that
appeared to have been similar.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said its records showed that
a Learjet crashed on Jan. 18, 1980, in Ohio, on a flight from
Ypsilanti, Mich., to Louisville, Ky. Controllers reported that the
crew's speech had been slurred, a sign of oxygen deprivation.
Everyone on board was killed in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Though he acknowledged these similarities, Benzon cautioned that
``it might behoove us to note that oxygen deprivation isn't the
only thing that could have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Robert T. Francis, vice chairman of the safety
board, had said no one could recall a similar crash. But Wednesday,
Benzon said, ``It is interesting that in current memory, at least
for folks here, we couldn't think of any, and now a couple have
popped up.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash of the German plane seemed eerily similar. The Lear
25B belonging to a West German charter company, Air Traffic, took
off on a flight to Hamburg, but kept going. As the plane flew over
northern Europe, air traffic controllers were unable to make
contact with the pilots, and British, Dutch and U.S. military
planes were sent up to intercept the plane. Two Royal Air Force
jets caught up with the plane over Scotland, according to an
Associated Press report at the time, which quoted one pilot, Lt.
John Marr, as saying ``there was certainly no one in the cockpit.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Stewart's Lear 35, which left Orlando, Fla., on a flight to
Dallas, the German plane had enough fuel for four hours of flight
and crashed when that was gone.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said at the time that they believed that the crew
had probably been rendered unconscious or had died from oxygen
deprivation. U.S. officials said Wednesday that they had no
jurisdiction in the European case and that the plane had probably
not been recovered. A spokesman at the German embassy in Washington
said he could not determine Wednesday whether an investigation had
reached any conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Benzon said that aviation experts were ``vaguely aware'' of a
similar case, in Mexico, involving a Learjet, but that he did not
know the date or other circumstances. A Learjet hit a mountain near
Hermosillo in January 1993, killing all seven people on board. But
an FAA spokesman, Eliot Brenner, said that that crash might have
been due to a loss of control unrelated to cabin atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner added that agency records showed that a Lear 23 had
crashed in Ohio on Jan. 18, 1980, and that the cause was probably
loss of air pressure in the cabin. The accident is too old to be
online at the safety board. The board keeps paper records on those
crashes but was unable to provide details late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Benzon said the German and Mexican accidents would be ``well
worth looking at,'' although he said that the crashes, especially
the German one, might not have been investigated thoroughly enough
to be of much help. He said that he had asked Learjet, one of
companies assisting in the investigation, to provide details on the
earlier crashes. A spokesman at Learjet's headquarters in Wichita,
Kan., David Franson, said that the only person in the company who
could answer the question was already at the crash site in South
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Benzon said a valve that was part of the cabin
air supply system for the plane that crashed on Monday had been
replaced on Saturday. Investigators did not know whether Monday's
flight had been the first since the replacement, or whether the
maintenance had anything to do with the crash. ``It's a routine
maintenance type thing,'' Benzon said. ``We cannot make anything of
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have recovered about 25 percent of the wreckage,
Benzon said. They have not found the cockpit voice recorder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
