<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTUGAL-SPAIN-WAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTUGUESE RECALL AID TO SPANISH REFUGEES DURING CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMPO MAIOR, Portugal _ The long line of people, film extras
portraying refugees from the Spanish Civil War, filed into the
17th-century square of this Portuguese village of whitewashed
houses and secrets kept for six decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, after so many years, we are trying to deal with our
ghosts,'' said Francisco Moita Flores, the scriptwriter for a
13-part Portuguese television series that deals with a little known
chapter of Portugal's role in the Spanish Civil War of 1936-39.
</P>
<P>
   In the scene being filmed, the refugees are being gathered for
deportation to Spain and certain death. During the war, Portuguese
dictator Antonio Salazar supported the fascists led by Gen.
Francisco Franco.
</P>
<P>
   But despite great risks, many Portuguese in villages along the
750-mile border with Spain helped the refugees who fled the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Now the stories of these events, whispered for decades in the
villages where they happened but little known in large cities like
Lisbon and Oporto, are being re-enacted for Portugal's state
television. The series, ``The Border of Fear,'' is scheduled to be
broadcast early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Moita Flores, who is also a sociology professor at the
University of Lisbon, grew up in the border town of Barrancos
hearing tales of Portuguese valor and deceit during the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six years he has interviewed 200 people for the
series, which portrays as heroes those who helped some of the
estimated 30,000 Spaniards who fled to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   In Campo Maior, six miles from the border, Spanish refugees
arrived in August 1936, shortly after Franco's troops captured the
nearby city of Badajoz and executed many people who had fought for
Spain's elected republican government.
</P>
<P>
   Manuela Silveira, 36, a co-owner of the Central Pharmacy in
Campo Maior, said her family furtively gave food and clothing to
the refugees, who sometimes hid in large ceramic tanks used to hold
wine or olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   A great-uncle, the late Joaquim Nabeiro, who Ms. Silveira said
made a living smuggling coffee into Spain, was the inspiration for
the main Portuguese hero in the series, although she said he never
used his talents to help Spaniards reach Portugal, as the
television hero does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here many people helped, although there was also a lot of
fear,'' Ms. Silveira said. ``But the human instinct to help was
what prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   The aid was perhaps all the more surprising because of the long
history of rivalry and bloodshed between Portugal and Spain. But
the border areas had long been linked by family ties and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese who took risks to provide assistance did not
worry about the political affiliations of the refugees, said Ana
Nascimento, 66, a municipal employee. ``Everyone was helped,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred local people have worked as paid extras for the
crowd scenes, including a few who actually aided the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But Filomena Goncalves, an actress who stars in the series and
who is married to Moita Flores, said not all local residents were
enthusiastic. ``Some didn't want to work as extras because they
refuse to relive those things that hurt them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moita Flores hopes that the series will help young people in
Portugal learn a part of their history neglected even after the
military rebellion that overthrew Marcello Caetano, the successor
to Salazar's dictatorship, in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But Jorge Paixao da Costa, the director of the independent
production, said it would not necessarily make a huge impression on
the national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viewers are going to get some more information,'' he said,
``but I don't know if they will be touched. Nowadays people are
into the Internet. If the series is interesting and entertaining,
they will think about it a little.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
