<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0521 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-LEGEND-REVIEW-LA     10-27 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LEGEND-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: for use Friday, Oct. 29 and thereafter. Fact box at bottom.
Note italics below.)  
Our rating:   3 1/2 stars  
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Legend of 1900' sails along &QL; 
with intriguing shipboard tale &QL; 
By Valerie Kuklenski, Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain probably would have liked ``The Legend of 1900.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest from Giuseppe Tornatore (writer-director of the
Oscar-winning ``Cinema Paradiso''), ``The Legend of 1900'' is a
mostly upbeat story with the kind of tall-tale embellishments and
maritime setting Twain would spin.
</P>
<P>
   The numerical title is not only the year the film's story begins
but also the name of the main character.
</P>
<P>
   An infant boy born aboard a trans-Atlantic ocean liner in
January 1900 is abandoned in a lemon crate in the ship's ballroom.
He's discovered by a stoker, Danny Boodman (Bill Nunn), who
informally adopts the baby, gives him the cumbersome name Danny
Boodman T.D. Lemon 1900, and raises him in the sweltering, sooty,
noisy belly of the Virginian.
</P>
<P>
   After Danny dies in an accident, the captain learns about 1900
and considers turning him over to the authorities. But one night,
the 8-year-old boy wanders up to first class and reveals himself to
be a piano prodigy. Instead of being kicked off the liner, he's put
to work playing in the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, an American trumpeter named Max (Pruitt Taylor Vince),
who has been narrating the story, joins the band. His first few
nights on board are turbulent ones, but 1900 (by now played by Tim
Roth) relieves Max's misery with what may best be described as a
(BEGIN ITAL)pas de piano(END ITAL). It's a whimsical scene aided by
Tornatore's creative camera angles and Ennio Morricone's wonderful
music.
</P>
<P>
   Max and 1900 become best friends, with an awestruck Max watching
as 1900 improvises everything from rags for the first-class
passengers and tarantellas for steerage to a haunting melody
inspired by 1900's first glimpse of a captivating young immigrant
woman (the very appealing Melanie Thierry).
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Ragtime''-style twist, Tornatore has added a historic
figure for extra spice. Jelly Roll Morton, the self-proclaimed
inventor of jazz, has heard the Virginian's pianist described as
the world's greatest, so he books passage and smugly challenges
1900 to a piano duel. That scene is a real show-stopper, and
Clarence Williams III is great as the fuming, egomaniacal Morton.
</P>
<P>
   All this time, 1900 never has left the ship. Contrary to the
common view, he feels continents are infinite (``Did you see the
streets? There were hundreds of them. How do you choose just
one?''), while the open sea represents security, even familiarity.
The faces of the passengers and crew change, but at least there are
only 2,000 of them at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Max is destitute in London, reluctantly selling his
beloved trumpet. In the music shop, he comes across 1900's only
recording, a now-cracked platter of his haunting love song. Max
starts to tell the shopkeeper about 1900, and in the process learns
that the Virginian, used as a hospital ship during World War II, is
now a rusted-out hull slated for imminent demolition.
</P>
<P>
   Max tries to halt the blasting of the ship, certain that his old
friend is hiding on board.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Legend of 1900,'' Tornatore has risen to the challenge
of his first English production, masterfully handling a script
peppered with Jazz Age vernacular and the witty profundities that
translate into any language.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, best known for playing heavies in ``Reservoir Dogs'' and
``Pulp Fiction,'' does fine work in this understated role. Vince, a
familiar face from ``Heavy'' and ``Nobody's Fool,'' plays Max with
the right mix of vulnerability and courage. While he cuts an Oliver
Hardy-type figure, there's no buffoonery about him.
</P>
<P>
   The only major shortcoming in the performances by Roth, Vince
and Williams is that they might have worked harder to fake playing
their instruments, or Tornatore and his editor might have given
them a break with fewer shots of their hands.
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued that the real star of the film is the music,
most of it composed by Morricone. He previously collaborated with
Tornatore on ``Cinema Paradiso,'' but his work has been familiar to
American audiences since Sergio Leone's 1960s spaghetti westerns
such as ``A Fistful of Dollars'' and ``The Good, the Bad and the
Ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   The music of ``The Legend of 1900'' is so rich with rag tunes,
lively early jazz and mood-setting ballads that the film truly can
be enjoyed with eyes closed. But keep them open the first couple of
times. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film:!off! ``The Legend of 1900'' (R, language). &QL; 
The stars:!off! Tim Roth, Pruitt Taylor Vince, Clarence Williams
III, Bill Nunn, Melanie Thierry. &QL; 
Behind the scenes:!off! Directed and written by Giuseppe Tornatore.
Score by Ennio Morricone. Released by Fine Line Features. &QL; 
Running time:!off! One hour, 59 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating:!off! 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BORLAND28-COX     10-27 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORLAND28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Borland's integrity stood out in personal life, courses
 &HT;    By Alan Tays
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the fairways, pro shops and 19th
holes of South Florida's golf courses, Bruce Borland's name didn't
often come up in conversation. But in the offices of the area's
many golf course designers, he was well-known and well-respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the top professionals in our industry,'' said
Gene Bates, a Palm Beach Gardens-based course designer.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County is home to some of the most famous names in
golf course architecture, including Tom and Jim Fazio, Pete Dye and
Joe Lee. Then there are the player/designers: Jack Nicklaus, Greg
Norman, Gary Player _ all have offices here.
</P>
<P>
   But golf course design isn't a one-man business. Behind the
famous names are dozens of others who do the same work but don't
shine in the spotlight. They're called design associates. Within
the business they get plenty of respect. Bruce Borland of Jupiter,
one of six people killed in a plane crash Monday that also took the
life of PGA Tour player Payne Stewart, was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the Fazios and you have Greg Norman and you have
Nicklaus,'' said Bates, who works with Johnny Miller and Fred
Couples, ``but there are a lot of other guys who are not that well
known, but they do just as good work and do work in as broad a base
as the big guys do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the Tom Fazios that haven't been recognized yet. They
probably fit in the same profile as what Tom Fazio did 15 years
ago. When Tom Fazio worked for George Fazio (Tom's uncle), nobody
knew who Tom was, although he was kind of the guy behind the scenes
doing all the leg work, all the detail work and putting together
plans and specifications. He's really the technician. He's the guy
who makes the boat float.''
</P>
<P>
   Borland, 40, was a senior design associate at Nicklaus Design in
North Palm Beach, where he had worked since 1990. Chris Cochran,
another Nicklaus senior design associate, knew him all that time,
``and I shared an office with Bruce or sat next to Bruce for the
last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took no shortcuts,'' Cochran said. ``He was very, very
thorough, excellent with the client. Everybody he worked with knew
they were dealing with someone with a lot of integrity, and you've
got to have that. You've got to win people's trust out there.
They've got to believe in you. They've got to believe in your
motives. He was a very good architect, really good with people. He
loved the game and he understood shot values and strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said he and Borland used to travel to Asia quite a bit
for the company. ``I had the work in Thailand and China and Bruce
did a lot of the Indonesian work,'' he said. ``And he did some
excellent work there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran cited two of Borland's projects, new courses in Orlando
and Missouri, as evidence of his expertise. The Missouri course, he
said, ``is going to win a lot of kudos. Bruce's work, although it
was always very good, was getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Whitten, golf course architecture editor for Golf Digest and
Golf World magazines, said he was impressed by a course Borland did
at Hilton Head, S.C., called the Golden Bear Golf Club at Indigo
Run. ``The one that impressed me the most,'' Whitten said, ``is the
one that he did with (PGA Tour player) Glen Day a couple of years
ago called Salem Glen. ``It was really, really well done and it
showed a lot of talent for fitting something into a tough site.''
</P>
<P>
   Borland was known in the business for having been one of the
first to utilize computers in golf course design.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in getting into CAD _ computer-aided design _ was
just starting to surface when I left Nicklaus Design in 1988,''
Bates said. ``And they really needed somebody who could grab hold
and implement it, somebody who had the knowledge and the patience.
That's where I think Bruce really stood out, because he was a very
patient person.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates left Nicklaus two years before Borland was hired, but the
two ran into each other often. ``We've traveled on the same
airplanes several times,'' Bates said. ``We had a lot of
opportunity to share time on the airplane and talk about our
projects. We talked about how good a man Nicklaus is and how good
he was to me, and Bruce was really excited about how he was treated
in the Nicklaus organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel is the common denominator for course designers, no matter
which company they work for. Jason McCoy, president of Greg Norman
Golf Course Design, ran into Borland recently while having lunch
near his office in Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just talking about the amount of travel that we have
to do in our business,'' McCoy said, ``and how that was the only
drawback to it. Pretty ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   Borland learned to play golf as a boy, practicing his swing in
the backyard of his Peoria, Ill., home, said Lee Antonio of
Chicago, sister of Borland's wife, Kate. Cochran said he and
Borland used to play together at the Golden Bear Golf Club at
Hammock Creek in Palm City and Bear Lakes Country Club in West Palm
Beach. ``Bruce was anywhere between an 8 and an 11 handicap,''
Cochran said. ``He was a lot of fun to play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio recalled meeting Borland while at the University of
Illinois. He was a waiter for Alpha Phi, the sorority house to
which Lee and Kate belonged in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Waiters were chosen by the sisters of Alpha Phi, and candidates
had to go through rigorous interviews to get the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was charming, driven and confident,'' Antonio said.
``That's why we chose him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Kate met him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a terrific love affair,'' Antonio said. ``And I never
had a brother, so he was the brother that I never had.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his busy work schedule, Antonio said Borland still found
time to be a wonderful father to sons Daniel, 13, Thomas, 12, and
Benjamin, 10, and daughter Elizabeth, 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He embraced his family,'' Antonio said. ``He would go to all
of his children's after-school activities, like their diving meets.
And he's taken them golfing since they could hold a stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Borland had planned to fly commercial as late as Sunday night,
Antonio said, but switched plans to fly with Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial services will be held at 4 p.m. Thursday at the First
United Methodist Church, 815 E. Indiantown Rd., Jupiter. Gifts in
lieu of flowers may be sent to one of three funds: Palm Beach
Community Church, Bruce E. Borland Building for Life Fund, 3970 RCA
Blvd., Suite 7009, Palm Beach Gardens, FL 33410; First Union
National Bank, Memorial Fund for the Benefit of the Bruce E.
Borland Children, 2000 PGA Blvd., Suite 2200, Palm Beach Gardens,
FL 33408; or Wycliffe Bible Translators, c/o Mark/Deb Borland and
Linda/David Captain, P.O. Box 628200, Orlando, FL 32862-8200.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Mike Van Sickler contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
