<SLUG> BC-BETHLEHEM-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAR GAS AND A SHOOTING IN BETHLEHEM CAST A SHADOW ON MILLENNIUM
PLANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ Street battles engulfed the entrance to
Bethlehem Wednesday for the third day in a row, casting a shadow
over preparations for millennium celebrations in the town revered
as the birthplace of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   From morning until dusk, Palestinian youths enraged by the
killing of a local man by an Israeli soldier on Monday hurled
stones at helmeted troops guarding Rachel's Tomb, a holy site on
the outskirts of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Tour buses carrying Christian pilgrims were turned back and
forced to take circuitous routes into the Palestinian-ruled city as
the main road into town became a rubble-strewn battleground
shrouded with clouds of tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen Palestinians were reportedly injured by the gas and by
rubber-coated bullets fired by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have been rising in Bethlehem in the past week, fueled
by concerns that Israel is trying to spoil Palestinian plans to
make the city a showcase for the millennium celebrations _ a claim
strongly denied by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli plans to build a new checkpoint at the entrance to town
with a separate entrance for Palestinians set off a student protest
last week that turned violent when it was repelled by Israeli
soldiers who fired tear-gas to disperse the march.
</P>
<P>
   The students complained that the beefed-up checkpoint would cut
off Bethlehem from the rest of the West Bank while segregating
Palestinians from Israelis and foreign tourists. Israeli officials
said that the new arrangements were merely intended to ease tourist
traffic into the city and the passage of Palestinian laborers
through the checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal shooting on Monday of a local souvenir vendor by a
soldier at Rachel's Tomb set off the latest unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army said the man had tried to stab the soldier, but
Palestinians who said they had witnessed the shooting asserted that
it was unprovoked and that the soldier was visibly distraught after
firing the fatal shot, apparently in panic.
</P>
<P>
   Nabeel Kassis, the coordinator of the Palestinian Authority's
Bethlehem 2000 Project, accused the Israelis of setting off the
unrest at a time when they should be trying to lower tensions,
weeks before the start of the millennium celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel should have considered measures to eliminate sources of
friction,'' he said. ``If Israel keeps reacting in that fashion,
this can be interpreted as an attempt by the Israeli side to spoil
the Bethlehem 2000 celebrations for us. How else can we see it? The
millennium celebrations are not only for us. Israel also stands to
gain from the influx of tourists to the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Ephraim Sneh, the Israeli deputy defense minister, accused the
Palestinian Authority of failing to curb the street riots, which
have gone unchecked by the Palestinian police. The televised scenes
of unrest will only drive away potential pilgrims, hurting the
Palestinians most, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they cancel their trip, tell me who will lose more?'' Sneh
said. ``If there was a strong will on the part of the Palestinian
Authority, they would stop it. Believe me, they know how to do it
better than we do. They have to explain to their people that they
are shooting themselves in the leg. This is a test of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The clashes Wednesday began after a crowd returning from the
funeral of the man killed, Musa Abu Hilayel, 29, pelted soldiers
with stones. Hundreds of chanting mourners had marched behind the
flag-draped body of Abu Hilayel, who was buried as a martyr while
Palestinian officers fired a salute.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of his death remained in bitter dispute. The
commander of Israeli forces in Bethlehem, Col. Marcel Aviv,
asserted that Abu Hilayel was shot after he lunged at a soldier
with a knife that was later found at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But Imad Madbuh, who owns a garage across the street, said that
the soldier had called over Abu Hilal and asked for his
identification card, and as the Palestinian reached for his back
pocket he was shot. The soldier looked stunned, Madbuh said, and
shouted ``What have I done!'' as he was led away by his comrades.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence Wednesday at the entrance to Bethlehem, it
was business as usual downtown. Groups of pilgrims walked through
Manger Square as work continued apace on new road-building and
construction projects for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Workmen swept freshly-laid flagstones on Milk Grotto Road, which
has been transformed into a picturesque lane lined with quaint
street-lamps and turquoise shop shutters and doors. Cranes towered
over building sites, including a new multi-tiered parking lot and a
central bus station.
</P>
<P>
   Walking with her husband in a group of American pilgrims, a
visitor seemed unfazed by the trouble at the entrance to town. ``We
just trust Him to take care of us,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
