<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSISTED-SUICIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OK'S BAN ON DOCTORS PRESCRIBING DRUGS FOR SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Doctors would be banned from prescribing narcotics
to help patients commit suicide, even if their state laws permit
it, under a bill approved by the House on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed 271-156, effectively would overturn an
Oregon law allowing doctor-assisted suicide, and would supersede
similar provisions being considered in other states. Its passage
irked officials in Oregon and was fought by several medical
associations, which oppose federal involvement in defining medical
care.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters in Congress hailed the bill as a victory in the
battle to guarantee respect for human life. The House Judiciary
Committee chairman, Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, said the bill
``emphasizes the alleviation and management of pain, not reversing
the role of doctor from healer to hangman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to add executions to the list of healing services
they provide?'' said Hyde, who sponsored the bill. ``Should Oregon
law trump federal law?''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will take up a similar measure in coming weeks if its
schedule permits, and several key Republican senators have given it
their support. Supporters of the measure, including the American
Medical Association, favor provisions that would encourage doctors
to use narcotics to ease the pain of dying patients, including a $5
million grant to medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill would encourage pain management, even if the use''
of narcotics ``to do so unintentionally hastened death,'' said
Representative Tom Coburn, an Oklahoma Republican who is a
physician.
</P>
<P>
   That provision is a variation from a bill introduced last year,
which some opponents said would make doctors afraid to prescribe
any narcotics to ease pain. To allay those fears, the House bill
explicitly states that doctors would not be punished for treating a
patient with controlled drugs, even if the patient died.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Justice Department have also endorsed the
bill's efforts to promote better patient care. But the department,
which officially opposes doctor-assisted suicide, denounced a
portion of the legislation that would criminalize the practice. In
an Oct. 19 letter, an assistant attorney general, Robert Raben,
said the bill ``would unquestionably make physician-assisted
suicide a federal crime with harsh mandatory penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, Raben said in the letter, ``would affirmatively
interfere with state policy-making in a particularly heavy-handed
way, using 20-year mandatory prison sentences (as well as civil and
administrative sanctions) to effectively preclude states from
adopting any policy that would authorize physician-assisted
suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon became the first state to permit doctor-assisted suicide,
but only after a lengthy court battle, two public referendums and a
1998 decision by Attorney General Janet Reno to allow the use of
certain controlled drugs for euthanasia. Oregon's law went into
effect almost two years ago, and 15 people used the provision to
commit suicide within the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, several other states, including California, have
debated similar legislation. But the Hyde bill would make such
state laws irrelevant, because it would forbid doctors from
prescribing lethal doses of federally controlled substances, which
are the most common drugs patients use to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors found guilty of prescribing such doses, if the bill
becomes law, could face criminal sanctions, including long-term
prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law already forbids the use of federal funds to pay for
doctor-assisted suicides, and most doctors and medical associations
say they are opposed to the practice.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of organizations object to what they said was an
unnecessary intrusion of the federal government in medical
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael D. Cantor, the chairman of the compassionate care
committee of the Massachusetts Medical Society, said the
organization opposes the bill because it would have a ``chilling
effect on prescribing adequate medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We object to the federal DEA intruding into the practice of
medicine and defining what is good medical care,'' Cantor said of
the Drug Enforcement Agency. ``The DEA should not be regulating
medical practices in Massachusetts, and I think other states agree
with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
