<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trilogy sues online car-sales rival
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Competition for online car sales has been fierce
so far. It could get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's Trilogy Software Inc. is suing a rival of its
CarOrder.com subsidiary, accusing the company of using a method of
doing business it invented three years ago and patented last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a suit filed in federal court in Austin, Trilogy claims
patent infringement and asks for a permanent injunction and damages
from CarsDirect.com Inc. of Sherman Oaks, Calif., and one of its
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is the latest in a string of business method patent
disputes between big-name companies with competing e-commerce
sites, but this one has a distinctly Austin flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Trilogy launched CarOrder.com in January and is investing $100
million in the company. CarsDirect.com is backed by several big
names _ including Michael Dell, who invested $10 million in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   CarOrder.com plans to buy up failing auto dealerships and turn
them into distribution centers. CarsDirect.com works with existing
dealerships to fill online orders for new cars.
</P>
<P>
   Trilogy's patent covers a method by which online shoppers choose
the features and options they want when ordering a car from
CarOrder.com. The system, the patent states, functions as an online
auto salesperson, helping buyers choose the configuration of their
next car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is technology that Fortune 500 companies pay $50 or $100
million for,'' said Brian Stafford, CarOrder.com's president. ``We
want to make sure that we're doing whatever we can to protect and
enforce that.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for CarsDirect.com was not available for comment
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, Trilogy claims CarsDirect.com improperly used
methods covered by its patent. Trilogy claims it warned the company
that it was infringing on its patent, but CarsDirect.com did not
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford would not discuss the details of the lawsuit other than
to say that the patent ``is in regards to the way a vehicle is
configured.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to gain an edge on their competitors, Internet companies
have overwhelmed the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office with patent
applications in the past two years, causing the agency to hire
hundreds of new patent examiners. The earliest of the patents that
were granted are now being asserted and in some cases litigated.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, e-tailing giant Amazon.com filed a suit alleging that
rival bookseller barnesandnoble.com had copied a feature on its
site that saves shoppers' billing and shipping information so they
don't have to re-input it on return visits. Earlier in the month,
airline-ticket auction site Priceline.com sued Microsoft Corp. on a
similar patent infringement claim.
</P>
<P>
   While patents for Internet business methods are fairly new, one
Austin attorney who isn't connected to the suit said Trilogy's case
could be a strong one. Not only does its patent include 85 specific
claims on its patent, it appears to cover more than just methods
for selling cars on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of leverage put on the defendant to settle the
matter by ... taking a license on the patent and paying a royalty
to the patent holder,'' said Kelly Kordzik, a patent attorney at
Winstead, Sechrest &AMP; Minick in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
