<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0530 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-CRENSHAW-HNS &LR;      10-27 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CRENSHAW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Ben Crenshaw arrived at Champions Golf Club on Wednesday morning,
as planned.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But what he hadn't planned on were the circumstances under which
he would arrive. This was intended to be a grand visit, the
triumphant Ryder Cup captain getting together with a majority of
his team to rehash and relive the greatest Ryder Cup comeback in
the history of golf.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a chance for Crenshaw to mingle with the
masses who weren't fortunate enough to be at The Country Club last
month, and soak up the glory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Crenshaw spent his morning standing on the Champions
driving range, talking quietly with his fellow PGA Tour players,
exchanging hugs and handshakes, and trying to cope with the
stunning news one of his boys was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be with these guys,'' Crenshaw said. ``I wanted to
talk to them. The best we can do is talk and be with one another.
We need to talk about it. I know I think about it every minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw was in his car in Austin on Monday when his cell phone
rang. It was Crenshaw's wife, Julie, who told Ben he needed to come
home. The news, she said, was not good. Someone in a private plane
was in trouble, and she believed it was somebody they might know.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Crenshaw returned home, he had learned Julie was
right. Payne Stewart, a member of Crenshaw's 1999 Ryder Cup team,
was on the plane that eventually would crash into a field in South
Dakota. All six people on board were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Crenshaw has been in a daze, not sure what to do or
how to cope. Except he instinctively knew he needed to be with his
other family, the golfers on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like this happens this close, we don't know
what to do,'' Crenshaw said. ``It was so sudden. This guy was a big
part of our lives. I can't believe we're not going to see him
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So Crenshaw headed to Champions to see those who would
understand his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all a family,'' he said. ``We play an individual game,
but we're with each other all the time. And when something like
this comes around, we support each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw said he was having trouble believing he wasn't going to
turn around somewhere and see Stewart, decked out in his knickers,
grinning at him. And yet the reminders that he was gone were
everywhere, from the black ribbons on the caps of the players to
the piles of flowers at Stewart's parking spot in the Champions
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, for one, couldn't imagine having to play a golf
tournament this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be so rough, from focus to concentration to
everything,'' he said. ``It's bewildering. You have a tournament of
this importance, and yet you are fighting such a lot of things.
It's going to be a search out there for these guys. I know every
one of these guys is thinking about Payne every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw said two incidents always will stand out in his mind as
examples of the kind of golfer, and kind of man, Stewart was, and
both came from last month's Ryder Cup. One was when Stewart
conceded the final hole to Colin Montgomerie after the United
States already had won the Ryder Cup. And the other came before the
Sunday round started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the match even began, Payne told Colin that if he could
help him out in any way with the fans, he wanted to,'' Crenshaw
said. ``That shows how considerate he was.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, Crenshaw said, is what he will remember most when
thinks of Stewart.
</P>
</TEXT>
