<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL WANTS MCI TO PAY $550 MILLION IN BACKTAXES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ In a clash that is heightening concern over
Brazil's treatment of foreign investors, the government is seeking
to levy hundreds of millions of dollars of back taxes and fines on
the Brazilian unit of MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's tax agency told MCI that Embratel, a long-distance
company it acquired last year for $2.3 billion when Brazil
privatized its telecommunications monopoly, was responsible for 1.1
billion reais, or about $550 million, in back taxes. The liability,
it said, came from tax money due on international calls made when
the company was still controlled by the government.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom replies that it received assurances from
authorities before it purchased Embratel that it would not be
responsible for its tax liabilities as a state company. Brazilian
officials acknowledge this was how they advised the company at the
time, but they say tax authorities have since interpreted the
matter differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were specifically told in writing that the taxes would not
be an issue,'' said Daniel Crawford, MCI Worldcom's vice president
for ventures and chairman of Embratel. ``So sure, we are
disappointed. We're taking the issue to the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the tax bill, following a recent move by a
Brazilian state government to reverse the $1 billion privatization
of its electric utility in a dispute with two U.S. utilities,
Southern Co. and AES Corp., has generated anxiety over Brazil's
privatization program.
</P>
<P>
   Itamar Franco, an outspoken former president of Brazil and these
days governor of Minas Gerais, Brazil's second-largest state, won a
legal victory on Tuesday after a state appeals court upheld an
earlier ruling stripping AES and Southern of their ability to veto
some decisions by the management of Companhia Energetica de Minas
Gerais, the utility in which they are minority partners. The case
is expected to reach the highest appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   After the events in Minas Gerais, the U.S. Embassy in Brasilia
issued a statement saying that investor confidence in Brazil could
be shaken. Although the incidents there seem somewhat isolated, and
related to the political style of Franco, who shook the markets at
the beginning of the year when he declared a debt moratorium, the
American government has intervened to try to solve the problem of
MCI Worldcom's tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil's communications minister, Joao Pimenta da Veiga,
questioned recently by Commerce Secretary William Daley, said the
government's hands were largely tied. ``I told him, like I'm
telling you, that there can be no doubt we acted in good faith in
the entire process of selling Embratel,'' Pimenta da Veiga said in
a telephone interview. ``We are so convinced of this that if MCI
doesn't want Embratel anymore, we'll buy it back from them.''
</P>
<P>
   But selling Embratel back to Brazil could be more costly than
paying taxes because the currency in which MCI paid for Embratel,
the Brazilian real, has since weakened significantly against the
dollar. ``This isn't a serious option,'' Crawford, the MCI vice
president, said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the conflict between MCI Worldcom and Brazil is a
government hungry for tax revenue as it grapples with a estimated
budget deficit of 100 billion reais, or $50 billion. Tax
authorities, led by Everardo Maciel, the head of the revenue
service, have even fined large state-controlled financial
institutions to show that they mean business.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tax and political concerns, the appetite for
Brazilian state assets still appears healthy, judging from the
results of a privatization auction conducted here today.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly undaunted by its problems in Minas Gerais, AES Corp.
agreed to pay about $470 million for a controlling stake in
Companhia Geracao de Energia Eletrica Tiete, an electricity
generator sold by the state of Sao Paulo. AES exceeded a bid of
$381 million by the Belgian utility Tractebel.
</P>
</TEXT>
