<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW AND S&AMP;P BOTH RALLY BUT NASDAQ FALLS SLIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After slumbering through much of the session, stocks
sprang to life in the final hour Wednesday to carry two of the
major averages to solid gains.
</P>
<P>
   There was no particular development to touch off the rally,
which left the Dow Jones industrials with a 92.76-point gain, to
10,394.89, but analysts said strength in the bond market seemed to
suddenly stimulate bargain hunters as the market awaited two
crucial economic reports on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling around that the bad news on the bond market
may be over, with the yield on the long bond contained under 6.5
percent,'' said Charles J. Pradilla, chief investment strategist at
S.G. Cowen Securities. The rate on that benchmark eased to 6.32
percent from 6.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 did even better than the Dow, climbing
14.80, or 1.15 percent, to 1,296.71. The Nasdaq market, however,
slumped on weakness in Internet and other computer-related shares.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay, the biggest Internet auctioneer, dropped 13 5/16 to 138
11/16 following its profit report late Tuesday that some found
disappointing. Amazon.com, which reported after Wednesday's close,
lost 5 5/16 to 75 15/16 during normal trading hours.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks led the rally in blue chips, with J.P. Morgan
up 7[ to 128{, American Express up 5~ to 150| and Citigroup up 2
13/16 to 51 5/16, accounting for the bulk of the 0.9 percent
advance in the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   But investors also found value in some heavy-industry stocks
that offset a 9|-point plunge, to 67, for Hewlett-Packard on
analysts' concern that the computer maker's sales and profits will
be shy of forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these groups have been beaten up pretty badly,'' said
Timothy M. Stevenson, a portfolio manager at Meridian Investment in
Malvern, Pa. He said bargain-seekers were prominent in betting on
financial stocks in advance of the government's reports Thursday on
third-quarter employment costs and gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas M. Galvin, chief strategist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said the markets are braced for another hefty rise in the
Employment Cost Index and contended that, if it proved benign for
inflation, stocks could rally further.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy soon shows further signs of slowing from the
unsustainably rapid third-quarter growth rate of about 4{ percent
expected to be reported Thursday, the Federal Reserve might even be
dissuaded at its Nov. 16 policy meeting from raising short-term
interest rates for a third time since midyear.
</P>
<P>
   Home sales have already softened, consumer confidence has
slipped and Wednesday the government reported the first decline in
orders for long-lived factory goods in five months.
</P>
<P>
   Another stock group that bargain-hunters fastened on was the
airlines, which also benefited from a Wall Street prediction that
Continental Airlines will curb its growth next year, reducing an
oversupply of seats. UAL jumped 3{ to 65\, AMR 3] to 59 11/16 and
Continental 1} to 38 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Of the stocks to be removed from the Dow industrials on Monday,
Sears, Roebuck and Union Carbide rose by fractions, Goodyear Tire
and Rubber lost another 15/16 to 40 5/16 and Chevron surged 1~ to
89~ after raising its dividend.
</P>
<P>
   CVS, the drug chain, slumped 4{ to 39 after disclosing lower
profit margins while the JNI Corp., which makes computer equipment,
soared to 42 from 19 in its initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange swelled to 950.1 million
from 878.4 million as advancing issues led declines by 1,739 to
1,311. New 52-week lows, however, swamped new highs by 248 to 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
