<HEADER>
A0536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PHONE-PRIVACY28-COX     10-27 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-PRIVACY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New BellSouth service keeps unwanted callers at bay
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth today will start offering Atlanta-area
customers what the company says is the ultimate weapon in the arms
race between consumers and unwanted callers.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Privacy Director,'' telemarketers phoning at dinner,
unwanted relatives and office calls to vacationers may no longer
get through _ in fact, they won't even ring the consumer's phone _
unless callers either identify themselves or their number.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of new technologies for phones in the past few years
has spurred a competition between consumers wanting to know who's
calling and callers trying to slip in under the radar.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the phone companies are arming to collect from both
sides, but Privacy Director could provide the impenetrable defense,
said Terry L. Yarbrough, BellSouth assistant vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' he said. ``This product finally puts the
customer totally in control of incoming calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is intended for people to use with caller ID, which
identifies the number of most callers _ but not all. Many consumers
rely on caller ID to screen calls or at least to prepare them for
whoever is on the other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me, I always answer a call, but I want to
know who is calling,'' Yarbrough said.
</P>
<P>
   But callers using phones in large companies, callers who have
blocked the ``delivery'' of their phone numbers and some others _
especially those on wireless phones _ will often be listed by a
caller ID device as ``unknown'' or ``private number.'' About 9
percent of residents have their numbers blocked _ which can be done
for free _ often because they do not want their number picked up
when they call a business.
</P>
<P>
   But a resident who picks up the phone is deprived of the
knowledge that caller ID is meant to provide.
</P>
<P>
   So Privacy Director is engineered to stop callers with private
or unlisted numbers. Because the call is stopped at BellSouth
central offices, the consumer's phone hasn't even rung as the
electronic sentry asks the caller to stand and identify himself. If
the caller has a number that has been blocked, he or she is offered
the option of unblocking it.
</P>
<P>
   Then the phone rings and the consumer hears the caller's
recorded identification. If it is an unwanted telemarketer, the
consumer can press a button sending a recorded message that asks to
be added to the telemarketer's ``no call'' list. Or the consumer
can convey a recorded announcement that says, in effect, not now,
call later.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the consumer can also accept the call and only then
is the caller connected.
</P>
<P>
   Other regional phone companies, including Ameritech and US West,
have versions of the service. BellSouth, which now offers it in
South Florida, plans to extend Privacy Director to the rest of its
nine-state region next year.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that offer competitive local service, like MGC
Communications in metro Atlanta, already match most features
offered by BellSouth. They are likely to add this one, too, either
by building their own systems or, more likely, reselling the
BellSouth version.
</P>
<P>
   The features themselves account for an increasing portion of
phone company revenues. Customer demand is clearly strong. Nearly
30 percent of Georgians have the $34-a-month Complete Choice
package, which includes 22 services, Yarbrough said.
</P>
<P>
   Installation of Privacy Director costs $20. After that, it is
$5.95 a month _ but with Complete Choice, it is only a penny per
month. BellSouth prices services to make the package more
attractive. By itself, Caller ID costs $7.50 per month, and call
waiting is $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Most people still answer their phones the old-fashioned way _
without knowing who is calling. But the trend is swinging toward
knowledge. About 1.1 million lines _ 40 percent of BellSouth's
residential customers _ now have caller ID in Georgia, Yarbrough
said. ``This underscores how important privacy is to customers and
that is what this is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
