<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special probe in Ramsey case turned down
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Colorado Gov. Bill Owens announced Wednesday he will
not appoint a special prosecutor in the JonBenet Ramsey case, but
he had harsh words for the girl's parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could speak to John and Patsy Ramsey,'' Owens said at a
news conference, ``I'd tell them to quit hiding behind their
attorneys, quit hiding behind their PR firm, come back to Colorado,
(and) work with us to find the killers, no matter where that may
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter whether he believes the Ramseys are
responsible for the death of their daughter, the governor
responded, ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some remarks left the Ramseys shocked and disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just in shock. I can't even think,'' Patsy Ramsey said,
according to her friend Linda McLean. ``Now who's going to catch
the killer of my daughter?''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after a Colorado grand jury completed its probe
without issuing indictments, Owens said the case remains in the
right hands. So it will remain the responsibility of the police
chief and district attorney in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Owens added, ``There is reasonable belief that more than one
person was involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments by the governor infuriated people close to the Ramseys,
who saw the remarks as veiled indications that the state's chief
executive sees the Ramseys as responsible for the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   McLean, who lives in Patsy Ramsey's hometown of Parkersburg,
W.Va., took exception when Owens said: ``The killers in this case
made some serious mistakes, but they are also very smart. They have
stonewalled effectively and covered their tracks well.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean felt Owens purposefully linked his remarks on the
Ramseys' resistance to those of the killers ``stonewalling
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Branding Owens ``a slanderous jerk,'' McLean said, ``I don't
have nasty enough words in my vocabulary for him.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean said she spoke to Patsy Ramsey after the televised news
conference. ``She said she had not watched it, so I told her,'' she
said. ``I just slapped her in the face with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patsy Ramsey was speechless at first, McLean said, adding that
the Ramseys had high hopes that Owens would intervene to straighten
out the case. McLean asserted that the Ramseys have cooperated in
the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old JonBenet was found dead in her family's Boulder
home Dec. 26, 1996. Investigators identified her parents as being
under suspicion. No arrest was made.
</P>
<P>
   Owens acknowledged that early mistakes in the investigation
would make any case ``harder to prove in court.'' But he added that
``substantial new evidence'' is currently being analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   But William Pizzi, a University of Colorado law professor,
thinks the investigation has reached the end. ``I think it will
remain unsolved,'' said Pizzi, a former federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
