<HEADLINE>
SPENDING BATTLE CONTINUES AS CLINTON TAKES CREDIT FOR RECORD
SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government posted a record $123 billion
budget surplus this year as President Clinton and the Republicans
continued their battle Wednesday over Year 2000 spending
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking the upper hand in budget talks with GOP leaders, Clinton
claimed credit for the surplus _ the largest in real dollars terms
since 1951 _ in a White House announcement.
</P>
<P>
   He cited his 1993 deficit reduction program as the catalyst for
what has become the largest economic boom in U.S. history. Not a
single Republican in Congress voted for that package of tax
increases and spending cuts, which Clinton insisted was necessary
to help retire the national debt, which at that time was about $260
billion.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president's 1993 program kicked
off seven straight years of gradual deficit reduction, making it
the longest sustained economic recovery in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   But despite claiming most of the credit, Clinton also praised
Republicans for their contributions to the 1997 budget agreement,
which led last year to the nation's first balanced spending plan
since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have closed the book on deficits and opened the door on a
new era of economic opportunity,'' Clinton said, noting that U.S.
workers and businesses have benefited from lower interest rates and
a reduced national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, eager to claim their own share of credit, cited
their efforts to cut federal spending and reduce taxes as a major
contributing factor to the government's black ink this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when Republicans take care of the
government checkbook and hold the line against tax hikes and more
spending,'' said House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement marked the first time since the Eisenhower
administration that the government had posted back-to-back annual
surpluses. The last time was in 1956-57. The 1998 surplus was $69.2
billion and this year's figure of $123 billion exceeded the Office
of Management and Budget estimates by nearly $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly all the surpluses have come from Social Security
taxes paid by working Americans. Only about $1 billion in surpluses
have been generated from other sources, although $14 billion more
is expected from other revenue next year.
</P>
<P>
   The government now has more money on hand than at any time in
history, Clinton and Republicans are having a hard time spending
much of it because of their pledge not to raid the Social Security
Trust Fund. If they leave the huge pension account alone this year,
it would be the first time in decades that at least some government
programs have not been financed by Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Congress borrowed $30 billion from a
Social Security surplus of $99.2 billion. After that money was
earmarked to other government programs, the surplus entered into
the books at the end of the year was $69.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats accused the Republicans again Wednesday of
producing appropriations bills for fiscal year 2000 that will spend
about $18 billion in Social Security money, despite the fact that
they are borrowing from future budgets and using accounting
techniques to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been putting out false information about not using
Social Security money,'' House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
D-Mo., complained to reporters Wednesday. ``This is the big lie
...They are using Social Security ... and they know it.``
</P>
<P>
   To make good on their promise not to raid Social Security, House
Republicans plan to vote today on a bill to fund education, labor
and health programs that contains a one percent across-the-board
cut in spending. It also includes a one percent reduction in the
$8,000 pay hike lawmakers gave themselves earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had proposed to cut spending 1.4 percent
across-the-board without reducing their own salaries. But they
changed that idea after Clinton said he would veto it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Republicans plan to delay the release of about $7.5
billion to the National Institutes of Health until Sept. 29, the
day before the fiscal 2000 year ends.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, who serves on the Appropriations
Committee, criticized that move as ``unacceptable and unworkable''
because it would interrupt or kill the release of much-needed NIH
grant money to a number of Texas medical facilities, universities
and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, he said the delay could affect up to 40,000 NIH
grants that are normally awarded early in the year, leading to
layoffs and delays in time-sensitive research programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen called the delay ``typical of the gimmicks the
Republican majority is using to evade the 1997 spending caps and
conceal the fact that they are spending Social Security
surpluses.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican leadership aide, however, labeled the complaint
``complete hogwash'' and noted that NIH officials had ``signed off
on it.``
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically putting controls on when they can award grants
to control the rate of spending. What's wrong with that? The
money's still going to be there, it just won't be there when
they're used to having it,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
