<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR SAYS RAMSEY CASE WILL STAY IN LOCAL HANDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Colo.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ After consultation with the officials investigating the
1996 killing of JonBenet Ramsey, Gov. Bill Owens of Colorado said
Wednesday that ``substantial new evidence'' had convinced him that
there was no need to appoint a special prosecutor to take over the
case from the local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the investigators are moving closer to proving
their case,'' Owens said in explaining why he believed that a
special prosecutor would prove disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   His decision came as something of a surprise in that efforts to
solve the crime seemed to stall two weeks ago when Alexander M.
Hunter, the Boulder County district attorney, said evidence
presented to a grand jury was not strong enough to bring charges
and dismissed the grand jury after 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking at a news conference outside his office, Owens
offered new insights into the investigation, saying the new
evidence had not been presented to the grand jury and that the
authorities were ``targeting the right suspects,'' the first
official confirmation that investigators believe more than one
person might have been involved in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also became the highest-ranking public official to
criticize JonBenet's parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, for resisting
efforts seeking their cooperation in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After characterizing the killers as ``very smart'' in that they
have ``stonewalled effectively and covered their tracks well,''
Owens was asked what he would say to the Ramseys, who now live in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He replied: ``If I could speak to John and Patsy Ramsey, I'd
tell them to quit hiding behind their attorneys, quit hiding behind
their PR firm, come back to Colorado, work with us to find the
killers in this case no matter where that trail may lead.''
</P>
<P>
   After a reporter suggested that those were strong words for the
Ramseys, whom Hunter has identified as suspects, Owens said
sharply: ``While, in our system, they are innocent until proven
guilty, as a parent, as the father of a youngster who is the same
age as JonBenet, I think that they could have and should have been
more helpful than they have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor was then asked, if he was ``implicitly saying John
and Patsy Ramsey, in your view, are in all likelihood responsible''
for their daughter's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' Owens replied.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response, the Ramseys accused the governor of
grandstanding. They said: ``Owens' slanderous remarks pander to the
fringe lynch mob which long ago cast aside the time-honored
presumption of innocence. Coming from a public official elected to
the highest office of this state, his comments are
unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys asserted that they had offered to provide
information to Owens and his legal advisers but that the offer was
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet, a 6-year-old veteran of beauty pageants, was found
strangled and beaten in the basement of her home in Boulder on Dec.
26, 1996. Her death became an instant worldwide murder mystery, the
subject of several books and a television movie now in production.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have conceded that the investigation was
compromised, in large measure, by mistakes the police made in the
early hours after the girl's body was found. Hunter said as much
the day he dismissed the grand jury, and Owens repeated the point
today, saying the case would be ``harder to prove in court because
of the initial mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was chiefly for those reasons that the governor brought
together a team of seven legal experts, including the Colorado
attorney general, Ken Salazar, to consider the option of appointing
a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting that option in favor of local investigators, he
addressed the killers directly and said: ``They will keep pursuing
you. And I am confident that each day brings us closer to the day
when you will reap what you have sown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
