<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HELMS-WOMAN-NYT &LR;      10-27 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELMS-WOMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS ORDERS 10 WOMEN FROM HOUSE OUT OF A SENATE HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif.)  (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Jesse Helms, the hard-nosed chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee, ordered Capitol police officers
Wednesday to remove 10 female House members from a Senate hearing
after he said they were disrupting the meeting by trying to present
him with a letter supporting an international treaty against the
discrimination against women.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, R-N.C., has blocked a Senate vote on the 1979 U.N. accord
and declined to meet personally with treaty supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The minor uproar began when Rep. Lynn Woolsey of California led
the group of women, all House Democrats who were accompanied by
some aides, from a Capitol Hill news conference to Helms' Senate
office and then to a nearby hearing room, where he was leading a
meeting on the Clinton administration's China policy.
</P>
<P>
   The group entered quietly, seeking to give Helms a placard-size
letter signed by 100 members of Congress in support of the
Convention on the Elimination of all Forms of Discrimination
Against Women. The pact has been ratified by 165 countries, but not
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Taken aback, Helms gaveled the hearing to a halt and scolded Ms.
Woolsey _ ``Please be a lady'' _ before ordering uniformed officers
to ``Escort them out!''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the women expressed shock at the treatment from
Helms, who is notoriously tough but also assumes a courtly air with
women who appear before his panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``While he was asking us to be ladies, he could have been more
gentlemanly in treating us like colleagues in Congress,'' said Rep.
Nancy Pelosi of California.
</P>
<P>
   The tempest marked the latest episode in a rocky week for Helms.
Last week, he made clear that he opposed the nomination of Carol
Moseley-Braun to be ambassador to New Zealand. Democrats seized on
the comments about Ms. Moseley-Braun, the first black woman elected
to the Senate, to accuse Helms and others of racial insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, the House Democratic leader, decried the
chairman's actions, saying, ``If they were kicked out of a hearing
of the Congress, that's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Helms, Marc Thiessen, disagreed, saying, ``They
came into a Senate hearing and disrupted it, holding placards and
yelling across the room at the chairman, and so they were removed
like any other protester would be.''
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the hearing showed Helms halting the testimony
from Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hearing on China and we have guests who are not
interested in that,'' said Helms, who seemed unsure who the House
members were. ``They want to demonstrate on another issue. I hope
the security people will escort them out in the corridor and let
them wait there.''
</P>
<P>
   From the back of the room, Ms. Woolsey asked the chairman to
accept their letter, but he cut her off with a bang of his gavel.
</P>
<P>
   She tried again, but Helms gaveled her silence. ``I would not be
discourteous to you where you work,'' he said. ``Now you please be
a lady. Escort them out! Escort them out!''
</P>
<P>
   After the women filed out, Helms turned to Cox and chortled,
``Heh, heh, some of your colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Not missing a beat, Cox responded: ``I thank you, senator. It's
much easier to get order in this hearing than it normally is on the
floor of the House of Representatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
