A0562 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-POWER-ONE-LADN     10-27 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-ONE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER-ONE REPORTS EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; CAMARILLO _ Ever have one of those days when no matter what you
do, it just isn't enough?
</P>
<P>
   Officers of Camarillo-based Power-One Inc. had one Wednesday,
when their company reported a 165-percent jump in sales and
earnings 2 cents higher per share than analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, their company's stock took a huge hit on the
apparently favorable news, losing more than 36 percent of its value
in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst J. Keith Dunne of Robertson Stephens Securities in San
Francisco attributed the stock slide to ``a little bit of an
overreaction.''
</P>
<P>
   A little bit of an understatement, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne said the market reacted to the projection that Power-One's
scheduled sales in the fourth quarter will be $1.7 million less
than the $61.2 million the company sold in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the number of shares outstanding, the price drop
represented a $225 million reaction to a projected $1.7 million dip
in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ridiculous,'' Dunne said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you get for setting sales records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simplistically speaking, the investors apparently wanted every
quarter to be better than the previous quarter,'' Dunne said.
</P>
<P>
   The big question mark is whether Power-One's turns business _
its unscheduled sales _ will make up the difference, Dunne said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Schnopp, Power-One's chief financial officer, said the
company told analysts and investors during its earnings conference
call it expected sales in the fourth quarter to be flat or slightly
down compared with the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said that was a very conservative estimate for the fourth
quarter,'' Schnopp said. ``Maybe we were too conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company plans to give the market time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at some point in time, it will come to its senses,''
Schnopp said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
