<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- HALLOWEEN-MOVIES-NYTR, 10-27
-- A lot of heavy philosophizing goes on about why people want to
see scary movies. Real life is just too frightening, too unknown,
too daunting to deal with, so we run to the movies to see something
far worse. We go for the improbable but eerily possible set-up and
then the tidy close that the world can't ever seem to get in real
time. (/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) JERICHO, West Bank -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- JERICHO-MAYOR,
10-27 -- A Palestinian police officer guards a new construction
site earlier this week. Five years ago Jericho became the first
city on the West Bank to be governed by the Palestinian authority.
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- FOOD-HALLOWEEN-COX, 10-27 --
Decorated cup cake and cookies for Halloween. The wicked weekend is
upon us. As times have changed, more and more folks are choosing to
celebrate Halloween in their homes, schools and community centers
rather than focusing on door-to-door visits. That means we need
more party fare. (Williami Berry/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- CIR-MANNEQUIN, 10-27 --
Fareeda Cook, left, and Jenelle Massiah, respitory-therapy students
at the Borough of Manhattan Community College, practice lifesaving
techniques on a computer-controlled mannequin that simulates
respiratory distress. In the last few years computerized simulators
that react eerily like real people have become more commonplace in
the training of healthcare workers. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- CIR-HANDICAP-2, 10-27 -- As
the treadmills churn away, people workout in a Manhattan gym while
watching the impeachment proceedings of President Clinton.
Closed-captioned television, created to help the deaf, has become
ubiquitous in the nation's health clubs, allowing people to watch
soap operas or news shows while they work out. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHEELMSFORD, Mass. -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- CIR-HANDICAP-1,
10-27 -- Marti McCuller, a Web site developer who is legally blind,
at her home-office as her seeing-eye dog takes a rest. McCuller
created a search engine that facilitates usage for Internet users
who have trouble seeing. The search engine has become popular with
the sighted as well as the blind. ``Those who can see like the fact
that there are no ads getting in the way of their information,''
Ms. McCuller said. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DELAWARE, N.J. -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- WEEKEND-RETREAT-3,
10-27 -- Hal Bromm, a Tri BeCa gallery owner, right, and Doneley
Meris, a bereavement therapist, on the porch of the former
Delawanna Hotel which they coverted into a weekend home retreat.
The house has plenty of room for guests, 20 bedrooms. It that is
not enough there is a stone guest house on a nearby hill. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DELAWARE, N.J. -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- WEEKEND-RETREAT-2,
10-27 -- Formerly an open public space in the former Delawanna
Hotel, the area has been turned into a parlor in what is now a
weekend home. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DELAWARE, N.J. -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- WEEKEND-RETREAT-1,
10-27 -- One of the restored bedrooms in the former Delawanna Hotel
which is now a weekend home. The hotel had 23 bedrooms, which have
been reduced to 20 by combining some of the smaller units into
larger rooms. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ST. ANTON, Austria -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
TRAVEL-SKI-EUROPE-HNS, 10-27 -- Skiers fill a street in the
Austrian village. The village's upscale restaurants, boutiques and
lodging make a stay here quite delightful. For many U.S. skiers and
snowboarders, an Austrian adventure represents a fantasy trip.
Alpine vistas, strange tongues and foreign food, and, of course,
the great skiing. (Syd Kearney/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
