</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- MARILYN-AUCTION, 10-27 --
Employees taking telephone bids on Marilyn Monroe items at
Christie's auction house in Rockefeller Center on Wednesday.
Auctions have become a popular way to dispose of belongings that
celebrities' heirs no longer want. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- REPUBS-SOCSEC, 10-27 --
Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D., is one of seven or so House Democrats
from swing districts who are being hit this month with Republican
commercials that portray Democrats as thieves or wild revelers who
want to fritter away Social Security reserves ``on big government
programs.'' ``These ads have certainly made this October feel like
an election year October, and triggered every competitive
instinct'' says Pomeroy. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) BISHKEK, Kyrgyzstan -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
KYRGYZ-SOVIET-HISTORY, 10-27 -- A bust of Mikhail Vasilyevich
Frunze, an early hero of the Red Army, in the national museum in
Bishkek, the capital of Kyrgyzstan. ``We don't want to eliminate
the history of the Soviet period, because that's history, too,''
says the museum director, Jumaly Momunkulov, 63, who was a baby
when his father was arrested for teaching the Koran and taken to a
prison camp, from which he never returned. (Staton R. Winter/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NIZHNI NOVGOROD, Siberia -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
DRUG-RESISTANT-TB-2, 10-27 -- Graves of prisoners who have died
from tuberculosis at the Russian prison of Kaisk. International
health officials and scientific experts say that strains of
tuberculosis resistant to various drugs are spreading faster than
anticipated overseas and that a new treatment strategy is needed to
prevent what has already become an epidemic from spinning out of
control. (Sergei Gitman/Public Health Research Institute Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) TOMSK, Siberia -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- DRUG-RESISTANT-TB-1,
10-27 --A prisoner nicknamed Gypsy suffers from tuberculosis in a
Russian hospital in Tomsk. International health officials and
scientific experts say that strains of tuberculosis resistant to
various drugs are spreading faster than anticipated overseas and
that a new treatment strategy is needed to prevent what has already
become an epidemic from spinning out of control. (Sergei
Gitman/Public Health Research Institute Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- BBO-WORLDSERIES-2, 10-27 --
Yankee fans making their way to the stadium in a pin-striped Rolls
Royce before Game 4 of the World Series on Wednesday night. The
Yankees lead the best-of-seven series 3-0, and can clinch their
third title in 4 years with a victory. (G. Paul Burnett/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- BBO-WORLDSERIES-1, 10-27 --
Yankee fans let Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker know how they
feel outside the stadium before Game 4 of the World Series on
Wednesday night. The Yankees lead the best-of-seven series 3-0, and
can clinch their third title in 4 years with a victory. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CLARION, Iowa -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- ROCKREQUIEM-AZR-B&AMP;W,
10-27 -- Glen Buxton's tombstone carries the opening chords to
``School's Out' by Alice Cooper, as well as the initials of
Cooper's band members. A founding member of the Alice Cooper group,
Buxton was cursed with a double whammy: a penchant for alcohol,
cigarettes and switchblades as well as a disdain for authority
figures -- including the doctors who struggled to keep him alive.
(Paul Brenton/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BETHLEHEM -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- SUB-ISRAEL-BETHLEHEM,
10-27 -- Israeli soldiers look at Palestinians hurling stones from
atop a rooftop on Wednesday. Hundreds of Palestinians threw stones
at Israeli troops on Wednesday, in continuing unrest after an
Israeli soldier killed a Palestinian souvenir vendor outside a
Jewish shrine earlier this week. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PATUXENT RIVER NAVAL AIR STATION, Md. -- Oct. 27, 1999
-- CRASH-CONTRACTORS-5-COX, 10-27 -- What remains of Rose Emory's
pickup truck after being hit by an F-18 Hornet at the air station
in 1992. Mrs. Emory's husband collected $800,000 from the federal
government, but his lawsuit against McDonnell Douglas was thrown
out of court before trial because of the contractor defense. (Naval
Safety Center/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEAR PATUXENT, Md. -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
CRASH-CONTRACTORS-4-COX, 10-27 -- Harold Emory holds a wedding
photo during a recent interview. Emory's wife, Rose, a civilian,
was killed in 1992 when an F-18 Hornet crashed into her pickup
truck at the Patuxent River Naval Air Station, Md., while she was
working. Emory collected $800,000 from the federal government, but
his lawsuit against McDonnell Douglas was thrown out of court
before trial because of the contractor defense. (Rick McKay/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ARLINGTON, Virg. -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
CRASH-CONTRACTORS-3-COX, 10-27 -- Michael Kleemann with a coffee
table in his apartment that has on its top an imbedded copy of the
front page of the New York Times on the day that his father, Capt.
Henry M. Kleeman, shot down two Libyan jets. When Kleeman shot down
a Libyan fighter during a dispute over international waters between
the United States and Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi in 1981, he
became a military superstar. His death four years later made him a
different kind of celebrity. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MIRAMAR NAVAL AIR STATION Calif. -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
CRASH-CONTRACTORS-2-COX, 10-27 -- The F-18 fighter piloted by Capt.
Henry M. Kleeman after it crashed while landing Dec. 3, 1985,
killing Kleeman. When Kleeman shot down a Libyan fighter during a
dispute over international waters between the United States and
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi in 1981, he became a military
superstar. His death four years later made him a different kind of
celebrity. (U.S. Navy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- CRASH-CONTRACTORS-1-COX,
10-27 -- Capt. Henry M. Kleeman in his official navy portrait. When
Kleeman shot down a Libyan fighter during a dispute over
international waters between the United States and Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi in 1981, he became a military superstar. His death
four years later made him a different kind of celebrity. (U.S.
Navy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON-- Oct. 27, 1999 -- FORD-MEDAL-2, 10-27 --
Former President Gerald Ford, center, is applauded after receiving
the Congressional Gold Medal at the U.S. Capitol on Wednesday.
Applauding from left, Gov. John Engler of Michigan, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, former first lady Betty Ford, Ford, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert and President Clinton. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) DELAWARE, N.J. -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- WEEKEND-RETREAT-4,
10-27 -- Hal Bromm and Doneley Meris' former hotel, which they
coverted into a weekend home retreat. With 20 bedrooms, the house
has plenty of room for guests. And, lest anyone feels left out,
there is a stone guest house on the hill. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- FALSTAFF-OPERA-REVIEW,
10-27 -- Mark Delavan in the title role and Amy Burton as Alice in
``Falstaff.'' Directed with vitality and imagination by Leon Major
and offering a performance by the remarkable young American
baritone Mark Delavan, this marvelous production features
attractive sets by John Conklin: mostly simple, movable panels that
suggest the interiors of Tudor homes and ale houses. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- CIR-VIRTUAL-DASHBOARD, 10-27
-- A display expected for the forthcoming In-Vehicle Information
System. Right now it exists only in the form of prototypes on
desktops and in one demonstration vehicle. As early as 2001 or
2002, 20,000 to 50,000 luxury cars will be offered for sale with
the system - virtually a large-scale test run. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MILBRIDGE, Maine -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
SEA-CUCUMBERS-2-BOS, 10-27 -- Drusilla Ray displays sea cucumbers
inside husband Lawrence Ray's sea cucumber processing plant. Sea
cucumbers are not easy to love. But over the last five years, as
preferred varieties in the Pacific became scarce, a new market has
appeared out of thin air. Now, in the villages of coastal Maine,
the saga of the sea cucumber is a familiar tale. (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MILBRIDGE, Maine -- Oct. 27, 1999 --
SEA-CUCUMBERS-1-BOS, 10-27 -- Drusilla Ray holds sea cucumbers
innards scraped out by 60 workers inside husband Lawrence Ray's sea
cucumber processing plant. To the rushing of 60 hoses, crates full
of glistening gray sea cucumbers are reduced to their usable parts:
a small ring of pink muscle and a patch of dark skin. (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON-- Oct. 27, 1999 -- FORD-MEDAL, 10-27 --
Former President Gerald Ford gets a kiss from his wife Betty as
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, center, and President Clinton look on
during a ceremony honoring Ford in the U.S. Capitol on Wednesday.
Ford had received the Congressional Gold Medal from Hastert. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- CONGRESS-SPEND-CLINTON,
10-27 -- President Clinton leaves the White House en route to the
U.S. Capitol for a ceremnoy honoring former President Gerald Ford
on Wednesday. The budget battle broke into tactical skirmishes on
Wednesday, as Republicans in Congress sought to find a way to pass
spending bills financing seven federal agencies and foreign aid
without tapping Social Security funds or triggering more
presidential vetoes. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- HALLOWEEN-MOVIES-NYTR, 10-27
-- A lot of heavy philosophizing goes on about why people want to
see scary movies. Real life is just too frightening, too unknown,
too daunting to deal with, so we run to the movies to see something
far worse. We go for the improbable but eerily possible set-up and
then the tidy close that the world can't ever seem to get in real
time. (/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) JERICHO, West Bank -- Oct. 27, 1999 -- JERICHO-MAYOR,
10-27 -- A Palestinian police officer guards a new construction
site earlier this week. Five years ago Jericho became the first
city on the West Bank to be governed by the Palestinian authority.
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
