<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-NY     10-27 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANEUVERING ON BUDGET BILLS CONTINUES AS SOCIAL SECURITY SURPLUS
GROWS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The budget battle turned to tactical skirmishes
Wednesday, as Republicans struggled to write bills financing seven
federal agencies and foreign aid without tapping Social Security
funds, triggering vetoes or tearing apart their thin majority in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides ratcheted up the rhetoric as well, with Republicans
ridiculing the Democrats for fearing their proposed 1 percent
across-the-board budget cut and Democrats calling the Republicans'
accounting techniques a Stalinist ``Big Lie'' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The battleground lay in four of 13 spending bills still in play.
The Republicans need to find ways to rewrite them or to change the
rules governing spending in ways that at least appear to avoid
using billions of dollars in Social Security surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the Treasury Department released final figures
for fiscal 1999 showing that Congress used $1 billion of the Social
Security surplus in last year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that for the second year in a row, the
government ran a large surplus in Social Security revenues _ $124
billion _ that went to pay down the national debt, which is now
$3.6 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have pledged to complete all the 13 bills
financing government agencies while spending no more than $594
billion _ the limit beyond which they would begin to drain surplus
Social Security funds. But their own calculations show them
spending about $600 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Their proposed spending cut of about 1 percent would recoup
about $6 billion, bringing their budget into balance, with the help
of an unprecedented level of creative accounting in the spending
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Without that creativity, according to an estimate by the
independent Congressional Budget Office, the Republican bills spend
at least $609 billion, or $15 billion over the limit.
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said those
figures made a fiction of the Republicans' argument that their
across-the-board cut would protect Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the `Big Lie,''' Gephardt said. The 1 percent cut, he
argued, ``doesn't keep you from spending Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans are still working on their plan, which as of
Wednesday afternoon lay in draft form as a budget cut of
nine-tenths of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to try to pass that plan on Thursday by attaching it
to the last of the spending bills to reach the House floor, a
measure financing the departments of Labor, Health and Human
Services and Education. It was not certain Wednesday that 218
Republicans _ a majority vote in the House _ would support the
plan, congressional aides said. Senate Republicans, though not
wildly enthusiastic, say they will pass it nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   If President Clinton vetoes the cut, as he has vowed, the
Republicans will have to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   They must find ways to negotiate with the White House to defuse
problematic policies in the remaining bills. These include favors
for the mining and energy industries, restrictions on money for
diplomacy and roadblocks to paying the dues Washington owes the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The president says he will not sign the $85 billion labor,
health and education bill unless the Republicans include his
program to finance 100,000 new teachers in public schools. The
bill, in its final draft tonight, does not.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton vetoed the $37 billion bill financing the
Commerce, Justice and State departments because it does not include
money for 50,000 more police officers or U.N. dues.
</P>
<P>
   The $14 billion bill financing the Interior Department has been
approved by both houses of Congress and is ready to be sent to the
president. But he says he will not sign it unless the Senate
removes a series of riders attached to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton also vetoed the $12 billion foreign aid bill,
calling it a symptom of ``isolationalism'' in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will have to remain in session long past its scheduled
Oct. 29 adjournment to redraw these bills, which must become law in
some way, shape or form. The 2000 fiscal year began on Oct. 1, and
the month's second continuing resolution, keeping the government
running without a real budget, expires at midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will have to pass and Clinton will have to sign a third
one this week as the struggle continues, with no clear end in
sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
