<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-VEND28-COX     10-27 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-VEND28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke studying `two-way' vending
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wouldn't it be neat if a business could automatically
lower prices at any hour to drive more sales? Coca-Cola Co. is
pursuing ``intelligent vending technology'' that would allow
bottlers to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   For months, researchers at the Atlanta-based company have been
studying wireless technology that would allow bottlers to
``communicate'' with vending machines to lower prices during
periods of low sales and then return prices to normal levels during
high-traffic periods.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Ben Deutsch said such ``two-way'' communication would
allow the company to remotely change the electronic price display
on vending machines. The machines also would allow consumers to
``dial up'' a soft drink using cellular phone technology and charge
the cost to a bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch said the company has no immediate plans to field test
the two-way technology and added, ``We have no plans to put any
such machine into the marketplace.'' He said the research is in
``the infancy stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft drink vending machine business has become highly
competitive because it provides high margins for Coke and its main
rival, Pepsi. Pepsico spokesman Jeff Brown said his company isn't
testing similar wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all feeds into their strategy of micromarketing and
understanding the local consumer,'' said Morgan Stanley analyst
Andrew Conway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises and two other
bottlers are testing wireless technology that helps them keep track
of how quickly soft drink brands are selling in vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   If a vending machine runs low on one beverage, say Sprite, the
bottlers would know immediately and could dispatch a truck to
restock the machine, rather than wait for the machine to be
replenished during a regularly scheduled visit. Deutsch said this
``one-way'' communications technology will help a bottler determine
the right mix of products for specific locations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to CCE, Charlotte, N.C.-based Coca-Cola
Consolidated, the second-largest Coke bottler after CCE, and
Coca-Cola Amatil in Sydney, Australia, are testing the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
