u a BC-ABORTION-BAN-NYT &LR;      10-27 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DEBATE AND RULINGS SEEN FROM UPHOLDING OF BAN ON TYPE OF
ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Wis.) (sw) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   URBANA, Ill. _ Some called it ``chilling'' and
``contradictory.'' Others called it ``well-reasoned'' and
``remarkable.'' But no one affected by Tuesday's federal appeals
court decision upholding the criminalization of a rare late-term
abortion procedure that its opponents call ``partial birth'' was
predicting instant change in Wisconsin or Illinois, the states
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is continuing as always,'' said Judy Mann, head of
Planned Parenthood of Wisconsin, which shut its clinics for a week
in 1998, shortly after Wisconsin's law was passed, because of
concerns that it was ambiguous and that doctors who performed any
type of abortions could be at risk for prosecution. The penalty,
the most severe in the nation, is life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, handed down by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, contrasted sharply with a similar case in the 8th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the 8th Circuit, the court found that laws in Nebraska,
Arkansas and Iowa banning the late-term procedure were
unconstitutional because their language might be interpreted to
prohibit common and constitutionally protected methods of late-term
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The judges in the 7th Circuit did not find the Wisconsin and
Illinois laws banning one type of late-term abortion
unconstitutional. A federal judge in Illinois had ruled that
state's law was unconstitutional but a federal judge in Wisconsin
had upheld the law there after a trial. But the 7th Circuit said it
would instruct the federal district judges handling the
partial-birth abortion cases to issue ``precautionary'' injunctions
to ensure that other, constitutionally protected abortion
procedures are not banned. The 7th Circuit judges are expected to
issue their instructions to the district court judges within the
next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, said Roger Evans, director of public policy
litigation and law for the Planned Parenthood Federation of
America, ``we will take steps to preserve the status quo.'' Evans
represented Planned Parenthood of Wisconsin and four doctors in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The laws in Illinois and Wisconsin do not specify what
constitutes a ``partial-birth'' abortion. In their decision, the
7th Circuit judges said they were upholding criminalization of ``an
uncommon procedure'' in which a woman's cervix is dilated, usually
over several days; the fetus' feet are extracted, and the brain is
then partly evacuated and the fetus is delivered dead but otherwise
intact.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th Circuit said other common methods of late-term abortion
in which a fetus is dismembered inside a woman's uterus and removed
by forceps or suction, are constitutional and protected under
Supreme Court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th Circuit's reading of the law ``was what the state said
all along,'' said Susan Ullman, the assistant attorney general of
Wisconsin. ``The state wasn't trying to stop all abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Bertocchi, the solicitor general of Illinois, said he
expected that the federal court would issue an order to Illinois'
attorney general and 102 states attorneys ``to prosecute cases in
accordance with the court's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the decision noted that the 8th Circuit struck
down similar laws in Arkansas, Nebraska and Iowa because the
imprecision of their language might allow the prosecution of
doctors who performed procedures protected by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Connell, a lawyer with the American Civil Liberties
Union in Chicago, which represented plaintiffs in Illinois, called
the 7th Circuit ruling ``radical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have a federal court enjoin a statute, tell a
state it can't enforce it, the court has to find that the statute,
either on its face or as applied, violates a federal constitutional
provision or federal law,'' she said. ``It's the most basic rule of
being a judge: before you can tell a state governmental official
they can't do something, the act they want to do has to be found
violative of federal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, of Planned Parenthood, said that the decision was
``fraught with contradictions,'' and that ``the court seems to have
set up a situation that no matter how the district judge writes the
injunction, any state prosecution will be met by a request from the
doctor for the federal court to intercede. It has set up a
situation where the federal court is dragged in every time.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Scott Fitzgerald, who wrote the Wisconsin law, said:
``In my personal view, this is groundbreaking. We have now set the
stage for a discussion on what is considered an abortion and
discuss it on the basis of the procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Coleson, who represented 55 Wisconsin state legislators
and Lt. Gov. Scott McCallum in the case, called the appeals court
decision ``well-reasoned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It applies the normal rules of law to the abortion context,''
Coleson said. ``Often we have the abortion distortion complex. The
appeals court construed the topic as it was supposed to do, to save
it from constitutional attack, and gave deference to the trial
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Weiss, director of the ACLU Reproductive Freedom
Project, which has litigated abortion cases across the country,
called the court's ruling ``heartbreaking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what these bans mean for women and doctors I represent
all over the country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A national survey of abortion providers by the Alan Guttmacher
Institute in New York found that the abortion procedure banned in
Illinois and Wisconsin accounted for 0.03 to 0.05 percent of all
abortions in 1996, the latest year for which figures are available.
In all, this would amount to 650 abortions, most performed at 20 to
24 weeks of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals judges wrote that no physicians in Illinois had said
they performed this procedure and only a few had done so in
Wisconsin. Ms. Mann said that she was troubled by the judges'
conclusion that this procedure was never medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the record in the district court was a classic case that
it's essential,'' Ms. Mann said. ``A woman was carrying a fetus
that was hydrocephalic. The woman wanted to let nature take its
course, but during the gestation, the head got so large she was in
jeopardy. There was no way to remove the fetus. Now the court has
ruled that if a doctor did this, he should go to prison for life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the ruling is very narrow,'' Ms. Mann continued,
``it puts judicial interest between the physician and the patient.
The judicial and legislative systems can't understand the
complexity of this. That's what the danger is to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weiss predicted: ``This split between the 7th and 8th
Circuits is going to force this issue before the Supreme Court
very, very quickly, in the next several months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
