<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-COSELL-REVIEW31-COX     10-27 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSELL-REVIEW31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Documentary displays classic Cosell
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Oct. 31
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ He was funny-looking and gawky. A face
for radio, that's for sure. He had a million-dollar image, but wore
a dime-store toupee. He never shied away from controversy. In fact,
he welcomed it. He championed such vilified black athletes as
Jackie Robinson, Tommie Smith and Muhammad Ali when only a handful
of white reporters would. He was loud, outspoken and brutally
condescending.
</P>
<P>
   But when you think of Howard Cosell, you think one thing: the
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that voice. It was unmistakable. Droning. Commanding. Nasal.
Annoying. Yes, it was all those things. But actor Billy Crystal
sums it up best in ``Howard Cosell: Telling It Like It Is,'' HBO's
superb documentary of the legendary broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you describe Howard Cosell on the air to someone who
had never heard him before? It's like, think of a very smart man
scolding you with a bad sinus condition who had a great
vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have put it better.
</P>
<P>
   Cosell, who died in 1995 at age 77 of a heart condition, was a
fascinating case study in contrasts. In a 1978 TV Guide poll, he
was named both the most liked and the most disliked sportscaster in
America. He possessed Michael Jordan-like confidence and was never
afraid to, as he would often boast in his famous halting delivery,
``tell ... it ... like ... it ... is.'' But he was also an
extremely insecure man who read everything that was written about
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People either hated Howard Cosell or loved him,'' Baltimore
Ravens owner Art Modell says on the documentary. ``Nobody was in
the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. I loved Cosell ... most of the time. That doesn't
mean, however, I agreed with everything he said. I applauded him
because he was never afraid to take an unpopular stand. He spoke
out against such hot-button subjects as racism and the Vietnam War.
While Cosell was often a first-class jerk and an arrogant
son-of-a-you-know-what-I-mean, I remember he was the first
sportscaster ever to call Ali Muhammad Ali on the air while
everyone else insisted on calling him Cassius Clay. That counted
for a lot, as far as I was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   How many of today's cookie-cutter, bland-as-butterless toast
sportscasters are willing to go out on a limb and say something the
least bit controversial?
</P>
<P>
   The only one I can think of is Bob Costas.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's moving documentary offers a well-rounded portrait of a
man, who at the height of his fame, was one of the most famous
people in America. For instance, Cosell despised bigotry and
prejudice because as a Jewish kid growing up in a poor section of
New York's Brooklyn borough, he was discriminated against and often
found himself running away from Irish-Catholic boys who wanted to
beat him up.
</P>
<P>
   But as he got older, that man with the funny nose, cheap toupee
and distinctive voice, never ran away from anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard Cosell: Telling It Like It Is''
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m., Monday, HBO. +468820
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
