<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-BRADLEY28-COX     10-27 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE AND BRADLEY PRODUCE NO FIREWORKS IN TOWN HALL MEETING
 &HT;    Moving in Washington (w) and Politics (p) categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley shared most opinions as well as the stage at a town meeting
with New Hampshire voters Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic presidential contenders, taking turns
responding to questions from a studio audience of about 500 at
Dartmouth College, sparred a bit over the cost of a plan proposed
by Bradley to expand health care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But their first joint appearance before a New Hampshire audience
produced little in the way of fireworks as they alternately pledged
greater efforts to improve education, expand health benefits,
reform campaign finance and protect the civil rights of homosexuals
and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The town meeting format discouraged the kind of give-and-take
between candidates that are part of presidential debates. And for
the most part, both candidates followed the format: responding in
90 seconds to questions posed from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore and Bradley both took time from their answers to other
questions to conduct a mini-debate over Bradley's proposal to
expand health care benefits to all uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggested that Bradley's plan could cost as much as $1.3
trillion, an amount the vice president contended could wipe out the
federal government's budget surplus and ultimately jeopardize
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dispute the cost figure that Al has used,'' Bradley
countered before answering a question about the Senate's recent
rejection of a nuclear test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a neck-and-neck battle with Bradley in New Hampshire,
took the offensive even before the broadcast of the town meeting
began. Before CNN went on the air, Gore invited the studio audience
to start firing questions at both of them. And they did.
</P>
<P>
   As the town meeting concluded, Gore also surprised moderators
Bernard Shaw of CNN and Karen Brown of Manchester's WMUR-TV with an
offer to remain after the broadcast to answer questions ``as long
as you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate ventured into unchartered waters in response
to any of the more than two dozen questions asked by the audience.
And seldom did they disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Both were also on their best behavior, avoiding strong enough
criticism to warrant an interruption by the moderators. At one
point, in fact, Gore complimented Bradley's eloquence in advocating
rewriting civil rights laws to include sexual orientation, although
the vice president noted his own opposition to such an approach.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, often laconic and professorial, was at his eloquent
best when he spoke of why he left the Senate in 1996. He also took
a gentle jab at Gore, who has spent most of his life as a
politician.
</P>
<P>
   He said that by leaving the Senate in 1996 _ a decision Gore has
characterized as quitting in the face of the Newt-Gingrich-led
takeover of Congres _ he had been able to ``encounter people where
they live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates walked about the stage while responding to
questions. Gore, however, joked more and often responded to
questioners with jokes and with a request to tell him more about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions were issue-oriented, with health care,
education and cynicism about the current political system
dominating the concerns of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   But the town meeting had barely begun when Gore was forced to
respond to questions about the improper behavior of President
Clinton with onetime White House intern Monica Lewinsky _ a topic
the vice president has tried to avoid throughout his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he shared the public's disappointment and anger during
the Lewinsky controversy and sought to provide ``as much continuity
and civility'' as possible. But of Clinton, he said, ``He's my
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
