<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MODEL-EGGS-NYT &LR;      10-27 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEL-EGGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGG AUCTION ON INTERNET IS DRAWING CLOSE SCRUTINY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Days after a new Web site auctioning models' services
as egg donors made a wide-ranging publicity splash, some are
questioning whether the auction is for real, or just a ploy to
attract Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Shirky, a professor of new media at Hunter College, wrote
Tuesday in an online publication, The Silicon Alley Daily, that he
had paid to join the site so that he could investigate it, called
Ron's Angels, and had sent e-mail inquiries about bidding, but
received no reply.
</P>
<P>
   Shirky and others questioned whether Ron Harris, the
photographer who founded the site, actually intended to market the
site not as an egg auction but as an erotic venue much like others
he has run.
</P>
<P>
   The site charges $24.95 a month for the opportunity to bid on
donor eggs and to get more information on the models. By last night
the site also featured an advertisement for an online pharmacy
offering drugs for impotence, baldness and obesity.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman acknowledged Wednesday that Harris had run a number
of erotic sites on the Web, but said he had been closing them and
was serious about auctioning off eggs. The fledgling site's staff
has been so swamped by media interest that it has had no time to
answer inquiries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times published an article on Saturday about the
site and the reactions of infertility specialists. On Monday, an
article in USA Today included interviews with two prospective egg
donors and a woman who said she had bid $42,000 for one model's
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   This week The Washington Post, The Boston Globe and online
publications have published articles citing skepticism about the
site's authenticity and Harris' motives.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, the number of models shown as potential donors on
the Ron's Angels site had dropped to three, from eight last week.
Harris' spokesman, who spoke on the condition that he not be named,
said that in view of the publicity and debate about the site, five
models had asked to be removed, at least temporarily. But he said
the site planned to add donors within days.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said he could not immediately make the three
remaining models available for interviews, and attempts Wednesday
to reach the two models quoted in the USA Today article were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The site has drawn outraged criticism from infertility groups
and specialists, who condemned it for turning human eggs into a
commodity that would go to the highest bidder. Infertility clinics
routinely offer egg donor profiles, sometimes on line, but they
generally pay no more than $5,000 to the donors, and the money is
meant to compensate them for their discomfort and time, rather than
for the genetic material itself.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' other Web ventures have sometimes attracted scrutiny.
The Better Business Bureau in Los Angeles, where Harris is based,
said it had received two complaints from subscribers displeased
with the content and service provided by Eros Entertainment Inc.,
one of Harris' businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the local office of the Federal Trade
Commission said it was undertaking no suits against Harris or his
companies. The Internet, however, carried ample records of
complaints against Harris for ``spamming'' _ bombarding news groups
on the Internet with advertisements for his soft-porn sites. Many
of the sites attributed to him and listed as ``rogue'' sites by
spam fighters are defunct.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Internet, on a site called 4porn.net, is an
interview with Harris from 1996 that quotes him discussing his
sites, calling himself an artist rather than a pornographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get your genes into the next generation, you win,'' he
said then. ``The only reason you are here is to breed, to transmit
your DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Shirky harshly criticized reports on the site that took
it at ``face value,'' he also said he could believe that Harris was
sincere in his ideology and in the Web site's mission. ``I don't
think this is a hoax,'' he said, ``I think it's a public relations
stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris does hope that the site will generate interest in a book
he has been writing on his views about genetics for the last 20
years, his spokesman said, but ``this is not a publicity thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the spokesman said, accusations that the site is a
hoax can be disproved only if bidders agree to go public about the
deal after the current bidding period ends Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is, stay tuned,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
