u f BC-FUJI-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-27 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUJI-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ITS BIGGEST CAMPAIGN, FUJI PLAYS DOWN TECHNOLOGY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They're the photos that people really wish their
colleagues would keep to themselves. The baby sleeping. The
teen-ager on the phone. The dog's face in close-up. They document
the everyday moments of interest to no one but the closest of kin
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But to Joan Rutherford, marketing vice president for Fuji Photo
Film USA, they are the ``bookmarks of life, the everyday rituals
people are least likely to take pictures of but are most likely to
want to remember.'' And they are the backbone of a national
campaign _ Fuji's biggest ever, Ms. Rutherford said _ which began
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is not about taking the camera out of the closet
on birthdays and holidays,'' said Howard Sherman, president of
Angotti, Thomas, Hedge in New York, a unit of the Interpublic Group
of Companies, which is the Fuji agency. ``It's about capturing
sentiments.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite an exclusive idea. Since the spring, marketing
executives at the Eastman Kodak Co., Fuji's archrival, have been
talking to industry and investor groups, saying they realize they
cannot live by graduations and bar mitzvahs alone, and that their
new strategy was to stress the everyday moments, too. The company's
ads have used a photograph-your-basic-life approach far longer than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Kodak showed ``The Lobster Dinner,'' a funny spot
about photographing a child chasing an escaped lobster across the
kitchen floor. Now, it is putting on ``Take One and Pass It On,''
in which a bunch of teen-agers pass around a single-use camera to
photograph whatever strikes their fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled that Fuji is joining us in trying to build the
industry,'' said David N. Hardie, vice president for marketing in
Kodak's consumer imaging business _ who insists he speaks with not
one bit of sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fuji's campaign differs from Kodak's in many ways. For
one thing, each of the Kodak spots, which at 30 seconds are twice
the length of Fuji's, is promoting the virtues of a particular kind
of Kodak film. The scampering lobster and child needed high-speed
(translation: high priced and high margin) Max film to capture,
while the pass-it-on spot would only work with a cheap disposable
camera that would not be a catastrophe to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, Kodak advertised concepts and Fuji advertised
products, but lately, they've reversed roles,'' said Ulysses
Yannas, an analyst with Mercer, Bokert, Buckman &AMP; Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji's campaign is uncharacteristically vague about product.
Sure, it features the Fuji logo, and Fuji film. But the five
15-second spots, along with five print ads that started running in
news magazines last week, make no attempt to trade customers up or
down on product quality or price. They simply feature a photograph
with a two-sentence tag-line _ ``Angels do exist'' for the sleeping
baby, for example, followed by ``They also wake up screaming'' _
and a quick fade out to ``Get the picture with Fuji film'' as a
voice-over says, ``Capture every day.''
</P>
<P>
   For Fuji, which until now has concentrated on promoting its
products and technology, this is a turnabout that Ms. Rutherford
insists represents the culmination of years of focus groups and
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that people are interested in the relevancy
of the photograph, and that they see the product and technology as
just a silent partner in the picture-taking experience'' Ms.
Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fuji and Kodak are less interested in grabbing each other's
customers than they are in accelerating the growth of what is
already a robust market for amateur photography. The numbers are
often in dispute, but most experts concur that the United States
consumer film industry is growing at a double-digit clip. Fuji's
share of that market has been steadily rising, and through 1997
most of that growth came out of Kodak's hide.
</P>
<P>
   But photography analysts say that Fuji is now grabbing its share
away from private-label films, not from Kodak. Kodak's share of
consumer film sales has been holding steady at nearly 70 percent
for a couple of years now, and even crept up a bit in the last
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fuji's main objective were to steal share from Kodak, it
would make the image quality of its film the hallmark of its
campaign, just as Kodak has done,'' said Steve Hoffenberg, an
imaging industry analyst at Lyra Research, a market research firm
in Newton, Mass. ``But Fuji's and Kodak's products are pretty
comparable by now, so Fuji is trying to pound its brand identity
deeper into people's awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, neither company will divulge its advertising budget.
But most analysts say that for the last three years, Kodak has been
spending about $100 million annually on promotions and ads.
Analysts say that Fuji's budget is closer to $20 million, a record
for that company. By sticking to 15-second spots, Fuji could afford
to buy time on expensive shows like `` E.R.'', ``Friends'' and
``Frasier'' and to take space in news weeklies like Time and
People.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Fuji's largest branding campaign initiative ever, and
we're going to run it aggressively for the near future,'' Sherman
said. ``We're 100 percent confident it will make a difference in
the marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
