u f BC-SONY-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      10-27 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE STRONGER YEN, SONY MANAGES SLIGHTLY HIGHER PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The stronger yen delivered a punch to Sony Corp. but the
blow was less severe than it might have been, thanks to strong
sales of personal computers and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   A reduction in corporate tax rates in Japan helped Sony post a
profit of 46.5 billion yen ($445 million) in the quarter that ended
Sept. 30, up 3.1 percent from 45.1 billion yen ($432 million) in
the same period last year. But operating profits slid 37 percent to
70.2 billion yen, and sales fell 6.8 percent to 1.6 trillion yen
($15.3 billion), largely due to the yen's appreciation, the company
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very vulnerable to exchange rates,'' Masayoshi Morimoto,
corporate senior executive vice president, said in an interview.
``The only thing we can do is cut back costs, not just in the areas
of the labor and overhead of the company, but also by shifting
production.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had assumed the yen would trade at an average of 115
to the dollar in this fiscal year, but in the second quarter, the
yen averaged 112.7 to the dollar, rising 23.3 percent against the
dollar and 30.7 percent against the euro. Like most other companies
here, not to mention the government and the central bank, Sony was
caught by surprise by the yen's rapid appreciation and had not
hedged itself against such a dramatic move.
</P>
<P>
   Had the yen remained within the company's original projections,
sales in the second quarter would have increased by 9 percent and
operating income would have been up by 25 percent compared with the
period a year earlier, Sony said. The company said it had hedged to
protect itself for 90 percent of its foreign exchange requirements
in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you discount the impact of the yen, in every market _ the
U.S., Europe and Japan _ we are growing by more than double digit
increases'' on a percentage basis, Morimoto said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's sales in Japan climbed 15 percent in the second quarter,
while sales in the United States were up 10 percent, and sales in
Europe rose 13 percent. Morimoto said sales of the company's Vaio
laptops and digital cameras like the Mavica and a new video camera
that uses 8 mm film were especially good.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Play Station, the game console that has driven Sony's
earnings for the last few years, slid in the second quarter and
will probably continue to decline until the introduction next March
of Play Station 2, an entertainment center that will combine
electronic gaming with access to the Internet, DVD and a host of
other capabilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
