<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S AWFUL SEASON FOUR YEARS IN MAKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last spring, long before the handicapped-parking
scandal or the 55-7 loss to Oregon State, UCLA's athletic
department selected ``Do You Believe?'' as its marketing theme for
the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Right idea, wrong execution.
</P>
<P>
   The season has challenged belief, for sure, but not as UCLA
intended. Spring optimism became summer embarrassment and fall
frustration. From the disabled-parking suspensions to the injuries
and inexperience and poor play, it's been a disappointing season
for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as November approaches, the two-time defending Pac-10
champs are in last place, they have lost four of their last five,
and they must defeat Arizona, Washington and USC to become
bowl-eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Do you believe . . . this mess?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're a struggling football team,'' Bruins coach
Bob Toledo said. ``We have three games remaining. The important
thing is to focus on Arizona (Saturday), then we have a bye week to
regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Is one week enough time to solve problems 4{ years in the
making?
</P>
<P>
   Lonely at the top
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's greatest problems are its small senior class, lack of
leadership and reliance on underclassmen. All three can be traced
to February '95, when former coach Terry Donahue signed his final
recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   It produced talent at the top (Cade McNown, Kris Farris) but
little depth. Three players left school. Three had career-ending
injuries. Three were forced to play as freshmen and have exhausted
their eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 17 players signed _ players who should be fifth-year
seniors _ six remain.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue resigned 10 months later. By the time Toledo was hired
in January, '96, he had just three weeks to recruit. His
hastily-compiled class has produced no elite players. Of the 18
signees, only 11 remain.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins should have 20-22 seniors. Instead, because of
injuries and attrition, they have 12 _ the second-smallest senior
class in the league. Of the 12, only six start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be a leader when you're not playing,'' Toledo
said. ``And then when you play, you have to lead by example. I
think the players are really concerned about doing their own thing
right now, as opposed to leading.''
</P>
<P>
   If substandard recruiting damaged the offense, it devastated the
defense. UCLA signed 14 defensive recruits in 1995 and '96. Several
retired because of injury (Mike Wiley, Ramogi Huma, Anselmo
Zamano). Two are hurt this season (Jason Bell, Travor Turner). Two
left the team (Damian Allen, Langston Woodberry). Two switched to
offense (Micah and Josh Webb). A few play sparingly (Eric
Whitfield, Billy Pieper and Jason Zdenek).
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, only one of the 14 is a regular this season:
defensive tackle/captain Pete Holland. The recruiting years that
should have produced the bulk of a veteran defense instead produced
one starter.
</P>
<P>
   Primary Problems
</P>
<P>
   Injuries, attrition and recruiting mistakes hit the secondary
and offensive line hardest.
</P>
<P>
   There are three first-time starters on the line. One of the
veterans, left guard Oscar Cabrera, was suspended for his
involvement in the parking scandal and hasn't played as expected;
the other, right tackle Brian Polak, practices sparingly because of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins wouldn't be in this position if six players hadn't
left school, gotten hurt or changed positions in the past year.
Jeff Wright and Scott Wiegand quit; Steve Morgan moved to defense;
Dave Wilford failed out; Kris Farris turned pro last spring; and
Josh Webb is out for the year with a bad shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Had Farris returned, redshirt freshman Blake Worley would be a
reserve and true freshman Bryce Bohlander would be redshirting.
Instead, Worley's starting before he's ready, and Bohlander's
playing a year too soon.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary is equally chaotic, with four freshmen among the
top eight players. The explanation is simple: The Bruins signed
eight defensive backs from 1995-97, and (begin ital)none(end ital)
is a full-time player in the secondary. (Note: Cornerback Ryan
Roques was signed as a tailback/receiver in 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Ali Abdul Azziz and Ryan Nece moved to
linebacker; Whitfield and Zdenek play sparingly; Allen quit; Bell's
hurt; Marques Anderson's suspended and Jason Stephens was benched
early in the season for poor play.
</P>
<P>
   Not one, not two, but three lost recruiting years in the
secondary. Impossible to overcome. &QL; 
QB, or not QB
</P>
<P>
   McNown won 30 games for UCLA in four years, but he's
inadvertently lost a few for them this season. His durability (no
games missed because of injury) prevented the Bruins from
developing a successor.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the only problem. Toledo and offensive
coordinator Al Borges spent two seasons preparing Drew Bennett to
replace McNown. After two starts, Bennett lost his job to redshirt
freshman Cory Paus. Three weeks later, Bennett moved to receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Bruins misjudged the situation, Toledo said: ``I
don't think so.'' But he agreed the month-long quarterback
competition between Bennett and Paus slowed Paus' development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he would be a little bit better,'' Toledo said. ``How
much better, I really don't know. That's hard to tell.'' &QL; 
Shooting blanks
</P>
<P>
   Last year, tailback DeShaun Foster and receivers Danny Farmer
and Brian Poli-Dixon combined for 31 of UCLA's 62 touchdowns. This
year, the playmakers have scored eight.
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon's out for the season with a broken wrist. Foster has
three carries in October because of a sprained ankle. Farmer missed
two games with a sprained ankle and played sparingly at Oregon
State because of a strained groin. In addition, big-play receiver
Freddie Mitchell is a step slow because of an aching knee.
</P>
<P>
   With a young line and rookie quarterback, every possession's an
adventure. Subtract your three biggest weapons, and production
plummets: UCLA's seven points against Cal and Oregon State is its
lowest two-game total in 35 years. &QL; 
Parking problems
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the disabled-parking scandal didn't end with 10
players missing two games and an 11th, Anderson, missing the
season. Because six were seniors, the suspensions were another
strike against upperclass leadership. It's hard to demand respect
when your pleading no contest to a horrific lapse in judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, only two of the 12 seniors (Farmer and Holland)
have the moral authority to lead in the locker room and on the
field. And asking two to lead 103 is a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there's another explanation for UCLA's predicament _
more powerful than subpar recruiting, injuries, suspensions,
inexperience and poor leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmic justice.
</P>
<P>
   Exploit the disabled, after all, and bad karma is sure to
follow. Perhaps the season was doomed before it began.
</P>
<P>
   ``That idea has passed through my mind, too,'' offensive tackle
Brian Polak said. ``It's just bad luck. You can't prove it, and you
can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can definitely believe it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
