<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT PACKARD'S SHARES SLIDE AMID LOWER PROFIT FORECAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares in Hewlett-Packard Co. fell more than 12
percent Wednesday after analysts suggested an earnings short-fall
in the fourth quarter, which ends this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard warned Oct. 1 that sales growth might slow but
said it still expected to meet earnings projections. Marlene
Somsak, a company spokeswoman, said Hewlett-Packard had not issued
any formal guidance since then but had continued to express concern
to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares fell $9.625, or 12.6 percent, to close at
$67 on the New York Stock Exchange. They have fallen 41 percent
from a record $118.4375 in July, gaining just 3 percent so far in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, cut his
fourth-quarter estimate by five cents to 73 cents. He said he now
expected sales growth of 6 percent, to $10.8 billion. He had
earlier estimated 10 percent growth, to $11.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now think Unix servers, which we thought would grow
modestly, will be down,'' Milunovich said, adding that enterprise
storage products and personal computer sales may also suffer.
``Although the company didn't point to it in a big way, I think Y2K
may be having some impact, and PC sales may have slowed in
anticipation of Microsoft Windows 2000 release.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. said Tuesday that Windows 2000, the successor to
Windows NT, would be delayed until Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Mona Eriba, an analyst with Gruntal &AMP; Co., lowered her fourth
quarter estimate to 70 cents a share from 77 cents, excluding the
results of Agilent, Hewlett-Packard's test and measurement
equipment business, which is being spun off into a separate
company. Dan Niles of Robertson Stephens reduced his estimate to 73
cents from 82 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In its Oct. 1 warning, Hewlett-Packard said its fourth quarter
revenue growth would fall at the low end of estimates because of
slow sales of its Unix servers and the disruption of its parts
supply pipeline following the Taiwan earthquake. Carly Fiorina, who
joined Hewlett-Packard as president and chief executive in July,
laid much of the blame on the company's North American sales force.
She said poor performers would be dismissed and a new compensation
plan would be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Sales growth in Unix systems remains constrained but most other
parts of the business are healthy, Ms. Somsak said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard will report its fourth quarter financial results
on Nov. 17; its quiet period begins Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   One continuing issue for Hewlett-Packard has been the weakness
in sales of its Unix servers and workstations, particularly when
compared with Sun Microsystems Inc., its arch-rival, which had a
record quarter. In a conference call with securities analysts
earlier this month, Sun president Ed Zander said Ms. Fiorina should
not blame Hewlett-Packard's sales force for poor Unix sales, but
should instead blame the Sun sales force for luring away customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hewlett-Packard has been losing share in the Unix market to
Sun for some time. Although Hewlett-Packard now has a competitive
product line, analysts said the company still lacks the focus Sun
brings to the market. Sun's message is that Unix is the most robust
operating system and that its version of Unix, Solaris, is the most
advanced. Hewlett-Packard, in contrast, sells both Unix servers and
servers that run Microsoft's Windows NT, thus diluting its efforts,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard customers may also be delaying computer
purchases while they wait for the Year 2000 problem to be resolved.
The Y2K issue prompted IBM to warn last week of lower earnings in
its fourth and first quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
