<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DH duty done well by novice
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees entered the three games at Yankee Stadium
with a big advantage at designated hitter, but the Braves came
through first.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez, making the second appearance of his career as a
designated hitter Tuesday, drove in two runs with a double to left
field off Andy Pettitte to give the Braves a 4-1 lead in the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez stranded runners at second and third in the first
inning when he grounded out to Derek Jeter, but he answered in his
next at-bat, sending the first pitch from Pettitte into the
left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably going to be tough doing it for the first time,''
Hernandez said before the game. ``I know we've had trouble scoring
runs, so I'm going to try to be patient at the plate and get on
base any way I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez entered the game hitting .143 in the postseason and
was benched after Game 4 of the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a little bit more experience going tonight in
Keith Lockhart, who will face right-hander Roger Clemens. Lockhart
was the DH in four of the Braves' nine interleague games in
American League parks this season, going 6-for-17 (.353) with a
double, four RBIs and five runs scored. Coming into this season,
Lockhart had hit .255 (12-for-47) as a DH.
</P>
<P>
   NO TEAM MEETING
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox didn't feel the need to make any special
speeches to the Braves despite their 2-0 deficit entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just some pats on the back and stuff like that,'' Cox said.
``We had (a team meeting) before we started this thing. They're
professionals. Nothing we can do about the past, but we have to be
positive about each game. We can't try to win four tonight. We have
to play one at a whack.''
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Perez will have arthroscopic surgery to repair
torn cartilage in his left knee on Nov. 4. He's been playing on a
sore right knee as well, so he will have an MRI on both knees and
his sore left shoulder the day before surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Lopez said Tuesday he has completed the 2 1/2-month
physical therapy on his right knee after surgery for a torn
anterior cruciate ligament, and his range of motion is nearly the
same now as his left knee. Now it's just a matter of working out
and increasing his strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of time and letting it heal on its own,''
Lopez said. ``I've still got a long way to go before spring
training, but it's coming along real good.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez won't start swinging a bat until next month. For now he's
focused on losing weight. He's up to 230 pounds and would like to
get down to 215 for spring training, which would be lighter than
his usual playing weight because he wants to put as little pressure
on his knees as possible.
</P>
<P>
   UNAFRAID OF CLEMENS
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Don Baylor said the Braves should be thinking the
pressure is on Yankees starter Clemens tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some things to prove to the fans,'' Baylor said. ``Why
not see if we can rattle him a little bit?''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was a teammate of Clemens in Boston when he set a
major-league record with 20 strikeouts against the Mariners on
April 29, 1986. Baylor said Clemens' velocity is down from the
mid-90s to the lower 90s and his control is off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the same type of pitcher,'' Baylor said. ``His
control is all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
