u a BC-OBIT-BLUM-NYT &LR;      10-27 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT BLUM, BUSINESSMAN WHO HELPED DEVELOP LINCOLN CENTER, DIES AT
100  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Edward Blum, a retired business executive and civic
leader who was an early problem solver for Lincoln Center, died
Friday at his home in Salisbury, Conn. He was 100.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Brooklyn, Blum graduated from Yale University in
1921, and the following year joined Abraham &AMP; Straus, the Brooklyn
department store founded by his grandfather, Abraham Abraham. He
retired in 1964 as a vice president and secretary, also serving as
a director and vice president of Federated Department Stores from
1944 to 1965.
</P>
<P>
   After ending his full-time business career, he continued as a
director on several corporate boards and worked with community
agencies, especially in the environmental field. He also maintained
his interest in New York City's many cultural institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Blum had an early role in the development of Lincoln Center for
the Performing Arts, serving as treasurer from 1956 to 1963. He had
been a director emeritus since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected honorary trustee of the American Museum of
Natural History in 1970, crowning his nearly 50 years of support
for the institution. He became a trustee of the Brooklyn Museum of
Art and remained a member of its advisory board and honorary
trustee until his death.
</P>
<P>
   He also had ties for many years with the Brooklyn Botanic
Garden, Brooklyn Public Library, the Brooklyn Academy of Music, the
Brooklyn Children's Museum, the New York Zoological Society and the
College of the Atlantic in Mount Desert, Maine He was a past
president of the Art Commission of the City of New York, and a
founder of the Bahamas National Trust and the Maine Community
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He held offices at the New York Community Trust, the New York
State Board of Social Welfare and the National Institute of Social
Services.
</P>
<P>
   Blum is survived by a son, John R. H. Blum, and a daughter,
Alice E. B. Yoakum, both of Lakeville, Conn.; nine grandchildren,
and 19 great-grandchildren. His wife, Ethel Halsey Blum, died in
1991 after 63 years of marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-27 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER'S INJURY ONLY PART OF USC'S PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What do USC's always lofty goals and Carson
Palmer's collarbone have in common? They were both shattered in
Eugene, Ore., last month.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's clavicle will eventually heal, but it is too soon to
tell if the Trojans will ever recover enough to reach the nearly
impossible standards set in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   USC's players had complete confidence they could reach the Rose
Bowl heading into the third game against Oregon, but Palmer
suffered his injury at the end of the first half and the season
quickly nosedived.
</P>
<P>
   Or so goes the conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   However, USC's breakdown in 1999 is not simple enough to place
solely on the tender shoulder of Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a given that Palmer might be the best quarterback in school
history, could be a top-five NFL draft pick and the team would be
5-2 if he were healthy. But Palmer should not be an alibi for the
unseemly things that have taken place during the Trojans'
disappointing 3-4 start.
</P>
<P>
   If you listened to the hype, the Trojans had enough talent
without Palmer to overcome his absence. And how did they take
21-point leads over Notre Dame and Stanford without their
superstar?
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett is right when he says great coaches
always have great quarterbacks. Bill Walsh had Joe Montana. Chuck
Noll had Terry Bradshaw. Tom Landry had Roger Staubach.
</P>
<P>
   But we're not talking about greatness here. Just wondering how
you slip to 3-4 with a team full of speed and experience? And why
have so many people have forgotten that the Palmer-led Trojans
barely beat San Diego State 24-21?
</P>
<P>
   No, USC's problems are far more pervasive than the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   To summarize:
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line has been a disaster for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The tailbacks have been uninspiring.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams have been atrocious.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been good but not dominating.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching has not risen to a level that would lift the
Trojans out of their funk.
</P>
<P>
   That explains a sub-.500 record as much as Palmer's injury.
</P>
<P>
   Before we leave the quarterback position, though, a quick word
about starter Mike Van Raaphorst. He's a competent player. Nothing
more. Nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   As Hackett said after last weekend's loss to Stanford, Van
Raaphorst put the Trojans in a position to win. He won't lead USC
to victory. He won't be the reason the Trojans lost. He'll just be
there.
</P>
<P>
   Those who blame Van Raaphorst should ask themselves why senior
John Fox has not been given an opportunity. Well, it would take a
big man to start a guy who was basically forced to move to tight
end a year ago because he wasn't considered good enough to hang
with Van Raaphorst, Palmer or Jason Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't expect Fox to start anytime soon. &QL; 
The offensive line
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback is really not the key to winning college football,
however. Offensive lines are what win games. Remember the '70s? And
this offensive line has been a total disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   All five starters returned from last season, so there was a
reasonable expectation it would experience some form of growth.
Instead, the line completely stagnated and at times looked worse in
losses to Oregon and Arizona. The line committed nine penalties
against the Ducks and half of those were false starts.
</P>
<P>
   There have been signs the past two games that the line has
gotten over its penchant for penalties and is actually blocking
somebody, but it might be too late to make a difference this
season. &QL; 
The tailbacks
</P>
<P>
   Here's the only stat you need to know. Chad Morton's longest run
from scrimmage this season is 19 yards. His longest run last season
was 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That's not just the offensive line's fault. Whether Morton's
lost a step or not is debatable. Some have speculated he bulked up
too much in the offseason to avoid injuries. Whatever, the fact is
USC does not have a breakaway threat.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Sultan McCullough has sprinter's speed, but the coaches
appear reluctant to use him. &QL; 
Special teams
</P>
<P>
   It seems like an unrealistic assignment to have assistant coach
Shawn Slocum worry about coaching the linebackers and the special
teams simultaneously. USC's special-teams play hasn't made anyone
think it's a job that can be split with a defensive position.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum brought in kicker David Newbury from Texas and he's made
only 8 of 14 field goals, including three misses in the
triple-overtime loss to Oregon. Punter Mike MacGillivray has been
inconsistent (39.9 yards per punt), and Hackett has toyed with the
idea of using David Bell in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the Trojans have blocked just one field goal
this season. Last year, USC blocked four punts and four field goals
and two extra points.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams were the cornerstone of USC's success last season.
Today, they are far more likely to influence a game negatively. &QL; 
The defense
</P>
<P>
   If you blow a 21-point lead, someone's giving up the points. But
it might be fair to remember that before the season, Hackett said
the offense would be ahead of the defense, in a reversal of last
year's roles.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has probably been right about where it should be.
But it has once again been under intense pressure because of the
offense's repeated ineptness.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the defense gained a bloated reputation, based on
holding Hawaii to seven points. There was also way too much
giddiness over the emergence of linebacker Markus Steele. He's a
wonderful player, but people foolishly forgot that this defense
missed Chris Claiborne. It's a point that must be made over and
over again.
</P>
<P>
   As Hackett said after losing to Notre Dame, ``The defense was
good, not great.'' &QL; 
Coaching
</P>
<P>
   Hackett went a long way toward growing into his role this week
by taking responsibility for USC's woes. It's clear his plan to
challenge the seniors last week backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have,'' Steele said. ``It's not just the seniors and
upperclassmen. We have freshmen and sophomores playing, too. We
don't want to put it on the seniors. We want to put it on the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett might be better served by loosening up a little. The
players seem to roll their eyes when he gets tough or goes
negative. They respond better to positive reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett seemed to learn this lesson, too, by trying to stay
upbeat after the Stanford loss without assessing blame.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he has not spent enough time on strategy and was
caught off-guard by Arizona's defensive scheme. He vowed to work on
that in the offseason. That's a sign he is willing to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in building and developing something for the long
term,'' Hackett said. ``I relish in that part. The thing that I
have had to learn is that I had been gone from the strategy of
college football for a while. The frustration has been that I feel
like I've been a little behind in terms of the strategy in our
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   With only five games left, it's time to catch up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
