<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEWLETT-PACKARD SHARES FALL ON EARNINGS CONCERN
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares fell 12.56 percent, to $67, after an
analyst suggested the company might have an earnings shortfall in
its fourth quarter, which ends this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard warned on Oct. 1 that sales growth might slow
but said it expected to meet earnings projections. Since then, it
has expressed concerns to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   SBC EXCEEDS PROFIT FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications, the regional Bell in the Midwest and
Southwest that is to become a Dow component, said it earned a
better-than-expected $1.1 billion, or 33 cents a share, in the
third quarter. That set off a rally in its shares. Qwest
Communications and Global Crossing also exceeded or met forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   DOW RISES 92.76 IN LATE RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks sprang to life in the final hour of trading to buoy two
of the main gauges. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 92.76
points, to 10,394.89. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed
14.80, to 1,296.71, but the NASDAQ composite index fell 8.95, to
2,802.52, reflecting weakness in some technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose sharply for the first time in a week after
the release of a weaker-than-expected durable goods orders report.
The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 6.32 percent from 6.37
percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Durable goods orders fell 1.3 percent last month, the first drop
in five months.
</P>
<P>
   CVS NET RISES, BUT ITS STOCK FALLS
</P>
<P>
   CVS reported third-quarter profit rose 19 percent, meeting
analysts' forecasts, but its share price fell $4.50, to $39.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL IN ROW WITH MCI WORLDCOM
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian government is seeking to levy hundreds of millions
of dollars of back taxes and fines on MCI Worldcom's Brazilian
unit, even though it had promised the company there would be no tax
liability.
</P>
<P>
   RISING YEN RESTRICTS SONY PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Sony reported a 3.1 percent quarterly profit gain, to $445
million, but said it would have to cut costs because the yen's
climb caused operating profits to slide 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PROMOTING BANGLADESH ABROAD
</P>
<P>
   Iftekhar Chowdhury, Bangladesh's representative to United
Nations agencies in Geneva, finds his days filled and grueling as
he tries to insure that his struggling homeland partakes in the
fruits of globalization. Even so, he is willing to take on more
work; he wants to become a deputy director general of the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR WHO QUIT JOINS TALK MAGAZINE
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Wallace, who resigned from St. Martin's Press after a
flap over a biography of George W. Bush, agreed to join Tina
Brown's Talk Magazine as editorial director.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMWORKS SIGNS BRITISH DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks SKG entered into a long-term affiliation with Aardman
Animations, a British studio, to produce four feature-length films
in stop-motion clay animation style.
</P>
<P>
   Natwest Plans Takeover Defense &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National Westminster Bank, seeking to thwart a $34 billion
takeover attempt by the Bank of Scotland, said it planned to sell
assets that could raise $6.6 billion. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   Stock Promoters Shot to Death &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two partners in a stock promotion who were found shot to
death Tuesday in a Colts Neck, N.J., mansion were linked to illegal
stock promotions and may have been killed to be silenced, according
to the Monmouth County Prosecutor.
</P>
