<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATE28-COX     10-27 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore, Bradley offer specific answers in conflict-free debate
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ With barely a hint of confrontation or even
serious disagreement, Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore
offered voters a first impression of themselves as just thoughtful
guys during an hourlong nationally televised forum Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions from the audience at Dartmouth College, they
dealt with topics ranging from gay marriages to health care, from
school safety to East Timor. Questions were specific and for the
most part, so were the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attempted to be the more engaging, asking each questioner
about their family or job, while Bradley appeared less rehearsed
and more thoughtful _ at one point when asked about leadership, he
used Woodrow Wilson and Mikhail Gorbachev as examples.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the opening question about the questionable
personal conduct of President Clinton, the vice president said he
was as disappointed as anyone. Calling Clinton, ``my friend,'' Gore
said he had a responsibility to show leadership during the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A woman asked Bradley about the military's don't ask, don't tell
policy toward gays, forcing them to keep their sexual orientation a
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support gays being able to serve openly in the military. If
gays can serve openly in the White House, in Congress, in the
courts, in the Treasury Department ... why can't they serve in the
military?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he would support a legal designation for domestic
partnerships of gay couples. Gore said he supports such a
designation but would oppose calling it a marriage because it is
not the same as marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was asked to explain why he left the Senate in 1996, a
point often noted by Gore. Bradley explained that he wanted to get
``outside of Washington'' and ``have a dialogue'' with the voters.
That experience, he said, proved to him that he is ready to become
president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore challenged Bradley's plan to spend up to $65 billion on
health care programs. He said Bradley's plan is far more expensive
than Bradley has admitted. Bradley insisted that his economic
advisers have given a realistic cost estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a nip at Gore, Bradley said his vision is that, ``If
you're going to do this, you ought to deal with the big problems
and you ought to have big solutions to big problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's forum also marked the start of a new campaign for
Gore. When he entered the race earlier this year, Gore strategists
saw Bradley as little more than an annoyance on the way to the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bradley has become a formidable foe tying Gore in polls
in Iowa and New Hampshire, with one new poll, done by Quinnipac
College in New Hampshire, showing Bradley leading 47 percent to 39
percent. Gore hoped to use the forum to convince voters here and
supporters around the country that he understands the mistakes his
campaign has made and is ready to aggressively fight for the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters were seeing Bradley for the first time and Gore's
strategists are hoping that the impression Bradley made was that he
is less presidential than Gore. Gore tried to take command early
when, while the two men sat on stage waiting for the show to start,
he encouraged the audience to ask questions off the air. Then, when
the forum ended, the last words were from Gore inviting the
audience to stay and ask more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Republicans gather for their forum here with the
notable absence of Texas Gov. George W. Bush. He will appear on
local television to explain to New Hampshire voters that he skipped
the event because he wants to be with his wife when she receives an
award from Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   His rivals accuse Bush of snubbing New Hampshire voters. ``He's
thumbing his nose'' at them, said Dan Schnur, spokesman for Arizona
Sen. John McCain, who has been gaining on Bush in some polls.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans took advantage of the Democratic forum to air
commercials before and after the event poking fun at both
candidates, with one actor ending the ad with this line, ``who
spends more? That's the only debate between Bradley and Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
