<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE DOW GROWS MORE YOUTHFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 28:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dow'' will shed a remarkable number of pounds and years by
next Monday. That is when the Dow Jones industrial average _ the
yardstick by which the public most often tracks changes in stock
prices _ changes composition. Four companies will be added to the
index of stock prices of 30 major businesses; four will be removed.
Gone will be Union Carbide and Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber,
manufacturers of tangible goods, which have been part of the Dow
for more than 60 years. Entering will be the high-tech superstars
Microsoft and Intel, makers of software and computer innards.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the changes in the Dow made by the editors of The Wall
Street Journal over the past few years have followed the same
pattern: Substitute young stars in the technology, finance and
other service sectors for the heavy-manufacturing stars of
yesteryear. In the past eight years alone, 11 of the 30 positions
in the Dow average have been changed. Texaco and Bethlehem Steel
were dropped. Hewlett-Packard and Walt Disney were added.
Typically, the new companies were lighter and younger.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the changes, the Dow is hardly representative of the
U.S. economy, new or old. It excludes utility and transportation
companies because they are tracked by other averages published by
Dow Jones &AMP; Co. Also, the Dow includes stock prices of only
so-called blue chip companies _ major, successful companies that
are expected to remain industry leaders. The goal is to have an
``average'' that represents the leading companies, not some amalgam
of all companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the skewed selection process, movements in the Dow track
overall stock prices surprisingly well over extended lengths of
time. Over the three-, five- and seven-year periods before July 1,
the Dow rose 94 percent, 203 percent and 231 percent respectively.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, a broader average that
includes many more technology and financial stocks, rose by
comparable amounts _ 104 percent, 209 percent and 236 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 and other broader-based indexes are used by most
financial analysts to judge the performance of stocks in general
and of specific mutual funds or stock pickers. But when announcing
financial news, the 103-year-old Dow remains the first and often
the only yardstick. It may not be the most representative
yardstick, but it is changing to keep pace with the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
