<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: DOWN TO THE WIRE
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. George J. Mitchell began the last days of his
eight-week- old effort to salvage the sinking peace accord, with
frosty relations between rival parties thawing but no breakthrough
reported. ``No one should underestimate just how important are the
next few days,'' said Peter Mandelson, the new British secretary
for Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: JOURNALIST'S VICTORY
</P>
<P>
   A Belfast journalist, Ed Moloney, won a legal battle when
Northern Ireland's lord chief justice, Sir Robert Carswell, threw
out a court decision ordering him to give the police notes of a
1990 interview with a former Protestant paramilitary man charged in
the 1980 murder of a Catholic human rights lawyer. The killing
attracted international attention because of charges that the Royal
Ulster constabulary may have helped the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: LORD LUCAN OFFICIALLY DEAD
</P>
<P>
   Lord Lucan, a high-living British aristocrat who disappeared 25
years ago after his children's nanny was bludgeoned to death in his
Belgravia home, has been declared officially dead by the High
Court. The court acted so that his will can be put into effect. The
mystery of his disappearance has produced reports of sightings of
him in Australia, the Netherlands, Ireland and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: COMMUNIST APPEALS
</P>
<P>
   Egon Krenz, East Germany's last Communist leader, went before
the highest criminal court to appeal a 1997 conviction for his role
in East Germany's shoot-to-kill policy at the Berlin wall.
Repeating his argument that a united Germany has no legal basis for
trying him, he insists his six-and-a-half-year jail sentence is
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: CRAXI DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   Politicians fiercely debated whether to allow former Prime
Minister Bettino Craxi, a fugitive from justice, to seek medical
care in Italy after heart trouble landed him in a hospital in
Tunisia. Former Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti requested clemency
for Craxi, and Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said it was up to the
prosecutors. Prosecutors say a Milan tribunal will have to decide.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ZERO SLUSH FUND
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo has not asked the Congress, controlled
by opposition parties, to appropriate any money in Mexico's 2000
budget for the secret slush fund traditionally assigned to
presidents to spend at their discretion. The size of the fund has
been decreasing since 1993, when a Congress controlled by the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party set aside $660 million
for secret expenditures by Carlos Salinas in his last year in
office.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN GROUP BARRED
</P>
<P>
   Christian Solidarity International, a Swiss group that has had
its accreditation withdrawn by the United Nations for buying the
freedom of thousands of Sudanese slaves, criticized the decision by
saying the move was led by ``repressive regimes'' like Sudan. ``It
does the U.N. no credit to support the efforts of a regime that is
committing a clear pattern of crimes against humanity,'' said Hans
Stuckelberger, the group's president.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Yugoslav conscientious objectors and draft
resisters who refused to serve in Kosovo may now face trials in
military courts, Amnesty International said in a report. The rights
group said many of the 23,000 soldiers or others who would not
fight in Kosovo may have been responding to NATO leaflets dropped
around Belgrade in April urging Serbs to resist.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: TERRORISTS TIED TO ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Ephraim Sneeh, the deputy defense minister, said in an interview
that a Palestinian terrorist group, Islamic Holy War, had for the
first time attacked Israelis inside Lebanon. He said a mine
explosion in southern Lebanon, in which no one was wounded, showed
cooperation between the Palestinian group and the Lebanese-based
Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
