<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0631 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-ANALYSIS     10-27 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TAKES FIGHT TO BRADLEY DURING FIRST JOINT APPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 A News Analysis   
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore took the fight to former New Jersey Sen.
Bill Bradley during their first side-by-side tryout before American
voters Wednesday night, by doggedly challenging his rival's
financing for an ambitious health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   During the nationally televised ``town meeting'' in which New
Hampshire voters divided 24 questions between the two rivals for
the Democratic presidential nomination, Gore and Bradley agreed on
far more than they disagreed about.
</P>
<P>
   Both endorsed greater civil rights for homosexuals and lesbians,
although Gore opposed legalizing marriages between partners of the
same sex. Both endorsed campaign finance reform. Both endorsed
steps to target specific health care problems, with Bradley vowing
steps to help provide care for Alzheimers' patients and Gore
promising to work ``toward parity'' to treat mental illness on a
par with physical illness.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate attacked the other during the hour-long
encounter, though they looked for opportunities to criticize the
other's policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore zeroed in on questions about how Bradley would finance his
health-care plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are we are going to finance the plans?'' Gore asked in the
opening minutes of the two candidates' first side-by-side
appearance. ``The numbers have to add up. That's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has proposed a plan, costing about $65 billion a year,
to provide health insurance to almost all Americans, including the
45 million people without insurance this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big problem,'' Bradley said. ``And it needs a big
solution to that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bradley's proposal would consume the entire projected
$1.2 trillion federal budget surplus over the next ten years,
robbing the federal government of the chance to ``save Medicare,''
the federally subsidized senior citizens' health insurance program
that benefits almost 40 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's criticisms, leveled at Bradley's plan on at least three
occasions during their joint appearance at Dartmouth College in
Hanover, N.H., finally got a rise out of Bradley, who left the
Senate in 1996 after 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I just want to make one clarification,'' Bradley said
in response to an unrelated question. ``On the cost of the health
care plan, we each have our own experts. I dispute the cost figure
that Al has used.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bradley ducked at least one opportunity to take a
shot at the Clinton-Gore administration, when he was asked to
comment ``on the behavior of the '96 Clinton-Gore campaign as it
relates to fund-raising?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley replied: ``I think there were obviously some
irregularities that have been addressed. I'm not going to get into
the details at this stage of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's repeated appeals for the chance to serve as president
contrasted sharply with Bradley's laid back, deliberate manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise you, give me a chance to roll up my sleeves and go
to work on this,'' Gore said at one point, referring to mental
health care coverage. ``This is one that I will fix for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore went out of his way to engage the questioners, asking about
their families, telling a joke, making humorous asides. At one
point he told the vice president of a local labor union, ``That's
an important position, incidentally.''
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the debate, Gore seemed eager to tell a
questioner that he understood ``the disappointment and anger that
you feel toward President Clinton, and I felt it myself,'' adding:
``I also feel that the American people want to move on and turn the
page and focus on the future and not the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore mentioned his service in Vietnam; he cited his endorsement
by the AFL-CIO, the National Education Association and the American
Federation of Teachers. Gore also cited his opposition to the
school voucher program once supported by Bradley; he outlined far
greater readiness to intervene in foreign ethnic wars that did
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was less imploring. He stated his policy positions in a
straight forward way as he moved easily around the stage, with the
ease of a former NBA basketball star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lack of vigorous disagreements Wednesday night was
anticipated, based on the fact that the two Democrats agreed on
most issues most of the time during the eight years they shared
together in the Senate, before Gore was chosen by Bill Clinton to
join the Democratic ticket in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   During those years, liberal organizations such as Americans for
Democratic Action and the AFL-CIO's political action arm found that
Gore and Bradley voted to support their organizations' priorities a
majority of the time.
</P>
<P>
   More conservative organizations found that Gore and Bradley
failed to support their organizations' priorities most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce found that Gore supported its position
on an average of 33 percent of the votes it selected over the four
years ending in 1990. Bradley voted for the organization's business
priorities on 27 percent of the selected votes used to rate
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The independent National Journal, which conducts annual ratings
of lawmakers' voting records, found that Gore voted the liberal
position on economic issues 92 percent of the time compared to
Bradley who voted that way 84 percent of the time. Gore adopted the
liberal position on social issues 81 percent of the time compared
to Bradley who took that position 74 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy issues, the National Journal study in 1990
found that Gore voted for the liberal position on 64 percent of the
selected votes. Gore voted the conservative position on 35 percent
of the selected votes. Bradley voted the liberal position on 75
percent of the votes; he voted the conservative position on 20
percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
