<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0632 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DEATH-CONGRESS-1STLD-     10-27 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL OUTLAWING DOCTOR-ASSISTED SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS year to 1997 in 6th graf; MOVES up graf about prospects
in Senate to 3rd graf from 7th graf; CLARIFIES administration's
position in 8th graf; ADDS details of Oregon's referendums in 11th
graf, ADDS ``stated'' to 23rd graf; ADDS 2 grafs at end with
details of House bill) 
(ATTN: Ore., Okla., Ill., Wash., Conn.) (rk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alarmed by an Oregon law allowing
physician-assisted suicide, the House of Representatives passed a
bill Wednesday that would make it a federal crime for doctors to
prescribe drugs to help terminally ill patients end their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 271-156. Seventy-one Democrats joined 200
Republicans in supporting the legislation. Twenty Republicans, 135
Democrats and one independent voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill, introduced in the Senate by the assistant
Republican leader, Don Nickles of Oklahoma, has 31 co-sponsors, but
has not reached the floor. &UR;  &LR; Supporters say they are confident
because most Republicans and some Democrats are likely to back the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Like many state laws that ban assisted suicide, the House bill
makes a sharp distinction between the use of prescription drugs to
control pain and the use of such medications to hasten death.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says that the use of controlled substances to alleviate
pain or discomfort is a ``legitimate medical purpose,'' even ``if
the use of such a substance may increase the risk of death.'' But
under the bill, a doctor who prescribes drugs ``for the purpose of
causing death'' would be subject to criminal penalties _ 20 years
in prison for prescribing the drugs most commonly used to aid a
suicide, the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Oregon law, which was enacted in October 1997
following a statewide referendum, doctors may, in some
circumstances, prescribe drugs to enable terminally ill patients to
end their lives. In June 1998, Attorney General Janet Reno said the
federal government would not take action against Oregon doctors who
assist in a suicide and fully comply with the procedures of the
state's law, the Death With Dignity Act.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed Wednesday by the House would, in effect,
overrule Reno. It says that in deciding whether to issue or revoke
a doctor's license to prescribe potentially dangerous drugs, known
as controlled substances, the attorney general shall not recognize
any state law permitting assisted suicide or euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department told Congress last week that it opposed
physician-assisted suicide but disliked provisions of the House
bill that would ``interfere with state policy-making in a
particularly heavy-handed way.'' The White House shares that view,
although it did not issue an official statement of administration
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the House bill said that Congress had authority to
legislate on this issue because it can regulate the use of
potentially dangerous drugs. The bill would amend a 1970 federal
law, the Controlled Substances Act, which sets uniform national
standards for the control of morphine and other narcotics. The use
of hallucinogens, stimulants and depressants is regulated under the
same law.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from Oregon expressed outrage at the legislation,
saying it was the height of hypocrisy for conservative Republicans
_ usually staunch advocates of states' rights _ to overturn a law
twice approved in referendums by the voters of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon law was first approved in 1994, 51 percent to 49
percent, but was promptly put on hold amid great legal dispute,
with the Roman Catholic Church leading the opposition. In 1997, the
state's voters backed the law again, this time by 60 percent to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats and some Republicans said the bill would put
federal drug agents in hospital rooms to judge the intent of
doctors prescribing pain-relief medicines in the final days of
patients' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill, led by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said
they were trying to protect the sanctity of life by forbidding
doctors to prescribe drugs for the purpose of hastening death.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the bill promoted the uniform application of federal
drug laws. ``Oregon,'' he said, ``decided to change the
time-honored professional purpose of medicine and give doctors the
option to serve no longer as healing forces, but as social
engineers, messengers of death. Doctors are authorized by the
Oregon law to put down the stethoscope and pick up the poison pill
and assist in the execution of their patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., said Congress was arrogantly
setting standards for the practice of medicine. ``We, the great
board of medicine in the sky, will decide what goes on between
doctors and patients'' in the last days of life, said McDermott, a
psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Wu, D-Ore., said: ``This is a day of shame for the
U.S. Congress. In addition to overturning Oregon's law, this bill
authorizes the Drug Enforcement Administration to second-guess
physicians all across America, and its effect on pain management
will be devastating. Few, if any, members of Congress even read the
Oregon law they voted to overturn.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill said that technically it would not
overturn the Oregon law. But, they said, it would severely hamper
patients' ability to invoke the state law, because doctors could
not legally prescribe lethal doses of controlled substances.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson of Connecticut, a Republican who voted
against the House bill, said, ``DEA agents will have to decide
whether the doctor's purpose was to alleviate pain, even at the
risk of death, or to hasten death.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a physician who supported the House
measure, insisted, ``This bill does nothing to disturb the proper
doctor-patient relationship in Oregon.'' A doctor who would take a
patient's life ``no longer has an ethical right to care for that
patient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report on the first year of its assisted-suicide law,
Oregon said that 15 people ended their lives with lethal
medications in 1998. Thirteen had cancer, one had a chronic lung
condition and one had congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association supported the House bill and
supports Nickles' bill too.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Yank D. Coble, secretary-treasurer of the association, said
the bills would provide ``a new and important statutory protection
for physicians prescribing controlled substances for pain,
particularly for patients at the end of life.'' The AMA has long
opposed assisted suicide, on the ground that it is ``antithetical
to the role of physician as healer.''
</P>
<P>
   The stated purpose of the House bill, as stated in the
legislation, is ``to promote pain management and palliative care
without permitting assisted suicide and euthanasia.'' Palliative
care alleviates pain and distress, but is not meant to hasten death
or cure disease.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill provides federal money to train doctors and other
health care professionals in methods of alleviating pain. The
government would also encourage research on how to care for the
terminally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of abortion strongly supported the House bill. Burke
J. Balch, director of medical ethics at the National Right to Life
Committee, said his group opposed abortion and assisted suicide
because of ``our concern for the vulnerable and powerless _ in one
case, unborn children; in the other case, people with disabilities,
older people, poor people, people at the margins of society, who
are at risk of being coerced into euthanasia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
