<SLUG> BC-RAC-BREEDERS'-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT DOESN'T SCARE EUROPEANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thanks to the Europeans' surprising enthusiasm and
a wagering-rules change, Breeders' Cup handicappers might have more
horses than ever to choose from this year.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred twenty-eight horses have been ``pre-entered'' for
the Breeders' Cup Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park _ including 22
Europe-based horses, who will be asked to brave the Florida
humidity, blamed for foreigners' failure to win a race when the
event was held in that state in 1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   With six of the eight races overflowing their 14-horse limits,
among them the new fillies-and-mares turf race, this shapes up as
one of the most hotly contested of the 16 Breeders' Cups. The
pre-entry lists will be whittled down and starting fields will be
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans include Daylami, a contender for the Breeders' Cup
Turf. Breeders' Cup president D.G. Van Clief Jr. attributed the
Europeans' eagerness to try again at Gulfstream to well-advertised
improvements in the air conditioning in the track's quarantine barn
and a policy change permitting turf workouts in the cool early
mornings.
</P>
<P>
   The turf course, flooded by Hurricane Irene, was scheduled to
reopen this morning to allow Breeders' Cup horses already on the
scene to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds up to a very deep _ frankly deeper than we expected _
European contingent,'' Van Clief said Wednesday. ``We've had what
we feel is a tremendously strong response to the Breeders' Cup
championship this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the response reflects the popular assessment that most
Breeders' Cup races are wide open following a spate of injuries to
top horses in the spring and summer and a rash of upsets in the
autumn prep races.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very contentious races where people think that
with the right trip on the right day, they can win it,'' said D.
Wayne Lukas, trainer of a record 13 Breeders' Cup winners.
</P>
<P>
   Longshot bettors won't have to worry about coupled entries
reducing their choices and odds. Gulfstream officials are waiving
the rule requiring horses with common ownership to race as a joint
wagering interest.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas pre-entered seven horses _ Cat Thief (Classic), A Lady
From Dixie (in the Distaff), Surfside and Cash Run (Juvenile
Fillies), Natalie Too (Filly and Mare Turf), and High Yield and
Millencolin (Juvenile).
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert dominates the contenders lists with General
Challenge and River Keen (Classic), Silverbulletday (Distaff),
Chilukki (Juvenile Fillies), Tuzla (Mile), Forestry (Sprint) and
Forest Camp and Captain Steve (Juvenile).
</P>
<P>
   At Santa Anita:!off! With the Breeders' Cup Classic drawing
California-breds General Challenge and Budroyale, Saturday's
California Cup Classic is left with seven horses and no star.
Baffert-trained Del Mar Gray and jockey Alex Solis are 8-5
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Fields for the 10-race Cal Cup card, a $1.275 million showcase
for state-bred horses, were announced Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
