<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORNING-NET-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWENS CORNING GOES TO COURT OVER A FAKE INTERNET MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This much is known: A lawsuit was filed this week in
federal district court in Manhattan. But no one knows who was sued.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual case was brought by Owens Corning, the building
products company best known for its pink fiberglass insulation. In
the lawsuit, filed on Tuesday, Owens Corning says it was libeled by
an unknown person purporting to be the company's chairman, who
posted a message on an Internet bulletin board maintained by Yahoo
and devoted to discussion about the company.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed against ``John Doe,'' claims the fake message
hurt the company's reputation with stock analysts and traders on
Wall Street, as well as the company's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The message is written in the name of the company's chairman and
chief executive, Glen H. Hiner, who appears to respond to earlier
criticism from shareholders. In one place, the message quotes him
as making critical remarks about shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   In another, it quotes him as saying, ``So what if I have padded
the board with my cronies.'' It also quotes Hiner as saying that
Owens Corning, which has defended thousands of lawsuits from people
over exposure to asbestos products that the company once made, has
``the fix in with 88 percent of the plaintiffs' attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, which was posted at 4:54 p.m. on Sept. 26, drew
angry responses from shareholders, the suit said, who apparently
believed it was genuine.
</P>
<P>
   The case is one of a number of John Doe suits that have been
brought by companies that contend that their reputations were
damaged in anonymous Internet messages, said Floyd Abrams, the
lawyer who specializes in First Amendment issues.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, who said he was not familiar with the Owens Corning suit
and was speaking only generally, said some companies appeared to be
using the civil legal process to silence their critics,
particularly employees who might be posting the anonymous messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been happening a lot in the last eight or nine months,''
Abrams said. ``It's often been the case that the only purpose of a
number of these lawsuits has been to find out the identify of the
critical employee.''
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers for Owens Corning, William I. Sussman and Nelson A.
Boxer, declined to elaborate on the lawsuit, except to say that it
was not filed to stifle dissent but rather, as Boxer put it,
because ``someone anonymously went on the Internet, on the bulletin
board, purporting to be the CEO and making derogatory statements
about the company's stockholders and how the company's being run.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company ``never has had any strategy about trying to
stifle any kind of discussions and public statements on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, Yahoo, like other companies that run such
bulletin boards, was immune from suit.
</P>
<P>
   An official with Yahoo, Mike Riley, a senior producer, said he
could not comment on the specific case but that generally, Yahoo,
under its strict privacy policy, ``will not release any identifying
information about our users without their consent, unless we're
legally compelled to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Such compulsion, he said, ``usually comes in the form of a
subpoena.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-EL-AL-BOEING-SPI &LR;      10-27 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EL-AL-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL AL SPLITS ORDER BETWEEN BOEING, AIRBUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Airbus Industrie appeared last night to have won what
industry analysts called a major victory over The Boeing Co. when
Israel's national airline announced that it would buy widebody
planes from both airplane manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   El Al has an all-Boeing fleet and the fierce competition for the
latest order had been closely watched on both sides of the Atlantic
to see if Airbus could break Boeing's monopoly in Israel, despite
intense U.S. political pressure on the Jewish state, which receives
about $3 billion annually in U.S. foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   After a late-night meeting of its board, state-owned El Al said
through a spokesman that it had decided to buy three Boeing 777s
and also planned to buy three or four Airbus A330s.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus order still needs final approval, an El Al spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means another Boeing market has fallen to the advancing
Airbus hordes,'' said Richard Aboulafia, senior aerospace analyst
with the Teal Group in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``This leaves one traditional Boeing market _ Japan. That's it.
When Japan falls, protect the Fatherland, it's invasion of the home
turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Peter Jacobs of Ragan MacKenzie said the El Al order
further shows the considerable strides that Airbus has made with
loyal Boeing customers. British Airways last year bought Airbus
planes for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime Airbus can get its foot in the door of a customer that
does not have Airbus planes, it opens up great potential for Airbus
down the road, even if the order is only for one or two planes,''
Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   El Al spokesman Nachman Klieman said the board decided to split
the order because the 300-seat 777 is more suitable for long
flights, while the 250-seat Airbus A330 can be used on shorter
routes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Boeing and Airbus made considerable concessions to El Al as
they maneuvered to win the competition, which has unfolded over
several months. El Al's decision was originally set for early
spring but has been postponed repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to steeply discounting their planes, Boeing and
Airbus agreed to give Israeli companies business worth 50 percent
of the value of the orders. These are known as ``offset''
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The two airplane makers made revised 11th-hour offers Monday,
just hours before the board was scheduled to meet. Airbus, which
had previously said it would provide provide offsets worth 35
percent, raised it to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The board postponed the Monday meeting so it could take more
time to study the revised offers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also announced over the weekend that it would team with
Israel Aircraft Industries to convert 757 passenger planes to
freighters. That deal, worth about $120 million to the Israeli
company, was not linked to the El Al order.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known how much of a discount Airbus and Boeing offered
El Al on their respective planes.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus senior vice president John Leahy, who has been the
European planemaker's chief salesman in Tel Aviv for the El Al
order, expressed satisfaction with the deal:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely happy with the deal. But we are a lot happier
with the new partnership that was formed today with El Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Alan Mulally, also issued
a statement, saying, ``We are extremely pleased that El Al has made
a decision in favor of the Boeing 777.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulally had made a second trip to Israel in recent days to pitch
Boeing's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Al has conducted a very rigorous competition evaluating all
aspects of the commercial products to make sure that they made the
best business decision, Mulally said in the statement. ``We look
forward to the first Boeing 777 delivery to El Al in February
2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Klieman said the $400 million order for the three Boeing 777s is
a done deal, but the order for the Airbus planes still needs final
approval by company management. That could take a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The overall order is larger than the three or four planes El Al
had been expected to buy this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to evaluate our cash flow as well as the economics of
the destinations these planes (the A330s) would serve,'' Klieman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The first Airbus planes will be delivered in 2003, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus order is worth between $250 million and $400 million,
depending on how many planes El Al buys and the maintanance
agreements, an Airbus spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Klieman said the 777s would replace Boeing 747-200s while the
A330s would replace Boeing 767s.
</P>
<P>
   El Al has 13 747s in its fleet and six 767s. Some of those 747s
are the -400 model, which is the biggest and newest jumbo jet that
Boeing makes. El Al also flys Boeing 737s and 757s.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus lost an El Al deal in 1997 after Boeing reportedly
undercut it at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy, the Airbus executive, was quoted by Bloomberg News this
week as saying the European consortium was prepared to take a loss
to break the Boeing monopoly with El Al.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Airbus becomes a single corporate entity, profitability
will matter much more,'' said Aboulafia, the industry analyst.
``Right now, it's grab market share while you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Boeing Chairman Phil Condit told analysts
that Boeing has had to walk from some recent competitions with
Airbus rather than make unprofitable deals.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have applauded Boeing's commitment to the bottom line,
but they also are worried about the trend that has seen Airbus win
order after order from airlines that were loyal Boeing customers.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is far ahead of Boeing this year in orders for new
planes. Airbus has so far captured about 70 percent of the 1999
firm orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing faces something of a dilemma,'' said Jacobs of Ragan
MacKenzie. ``It does not want to sell airplanes at huge discounts,
but from another perspective it cannot allow Airbus to continue to
penetrate what has been sole Boeing customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, Airbus cannot continue to sell its planes at
grossly reduced prices ... But if airlines are choosing Airbus
planes because they view them as the better product, then Boeing
has some other fundamental problems that it will need to address.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
