<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAY-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tenacity not new for Gray
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jim Gray has compiled an impressive body of work as a
TV sports reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta resident's resume includes stints with ESPN and CBS
and two with NBC. Gray's experience since graduating from the
University of Colorado in 1981 includes many major sporting events:
Olympics, Super Bowl, NBA Finals, heavyweight boxing title fights,
the Masters and the men's NCAA basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But after an interview Sunday with Pete Rose, Gray is facing the
toughest challenge of his career.
</P>
<P>
   For showing tenacity in pursuing the Mike Tyson-Evander
Holyfield ear-biting story in 1997, Gray won a Special Individual
Achievement Emmy Award.
</P>
<P>
   For showing tenacity in trying to force Rose to admit to
gambling on a night when baseball celebrated its greatest players,
Gray has won the scorn of many viewers nationwide. In a career that
has been mostly highs, Gray has hit a low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Situations like this do not have real long life spans. Things
tend to calm down,'' said Mike Pearl, Turner Sports executive
producer who was Gray's coordinating producer when the two were at
CBS. ``After the Series is over, things will smooth over, and
everybody will move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, 40, is married. He first moved to Atlanta before the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Denver, where he played tennis in high school. He
first showed interest in broadcasting while attending Colorado
University. His first TV job was as an intern at Denver's KUSA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't set on a broadcasting career,'' he told the
Rocky Mountain News several years ago. ``But the opportunity and
support were there, so I took advantage of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first jobs Gray held after leaving Colorado with a
degree in journalism was in Philadelphia while Rose was with the
Phillies. Gray worked for PRISM, a regional cable network, in
1981-83 as an evening sports anchor and host of pregame shows on
the 76ers and Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   He left PRISM in 1983 and spent a year working as an associate
producer on an Olympics film before joining ESPN as its West Coast
Bureau Chief in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Gray reported on ESPN's coverage of such events as the America's
Cup, the NBA and the Super Bowl, but his breakthrough came on Oct.
30, 1987, when he was the first to reveal that Rams Hall of Famer
Eric Dickerson had been traded to the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   That scoop by Gray caught the eye of NBC, which hired him in
1988 to be a reporter on its pregame pro football show, ``NFL
Live,'' and for the Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   His first departure from NBC was not amicable. ``I got a call at
4:45 a.m. on an April morning in 1989 from (the) executive
producer,'' he told the Rocky Mountain News. ``His message: I was
being replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacement was O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Gray was hired by CBS to work on its pregame pro
football show, ``The NFL Today.'' It was during Gray's four-year
run with CBS that the big-time assignments began to come in
bunches.
</P>
<P>
   When CBS lost the NFL, he returned to NBC in 1994 and was
assigned to virtually every major event the network had, the
highlight being his exemplary work on the night of the Olympic Park
bombing at the Atlanta Games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He also gained some notice at the 1995 NBA All-Star Game, when
he interviewed Charles Barkley about Barkley's comment about
``hating white people.'' Barkley claimed his comments were taken
out of context and playfully gave Gray a kiss during the interview.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Gray also has worked for Showtime on
its boxing coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's a fine reporter, and, as evidenced, he's a fearless
reporter,'' Showtime president Jay Larkin said. ``If you don't take
risks, the level of achievement is mediocrity. Sometimes, it
backfires. But I think it's a compliment, not a detriment, that
he's willing to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
