u s BC-GRAY-REAX-COX     10-27 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAY-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gray boycott ends
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers and Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees apparently decided to back off their
boycott of NBC's Jim Gray, because manager Joe Torre and second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch granted him interviews Wednesday for the
pregame show.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had said it would not change Gray's role after Game 3 hero
Chad Curtis refused to talk with him, and the network stood by that
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to the Yankees and everything will be fine,'' NBC
vice president Ed Markey said. ``Jim will be in the dugout and talk
to them on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The boycott had forced NBC to move Craig Sager from the Braves
to the Yankees on Tuesday in order to get interviews for its
postgame show on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't enjoy doing it,'' Sager said. ``It felt
uncomfortable, but you have to do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday night's game, Gray sat in the New York dugout
beside Fox Sports anchor Keith Olbermann. Noticing several
reporters moving toward him, Gray smiled evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to hear here, guys,'' Gray said. Asked if that
should be interpreted as ``no comment,'' Gray smiled again and
said, ``I'm just having a conversation with Keith.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann appeared to try to help Gray deal with the growing
contingent of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm changing jobs again,'' joked Olbermann, who has moved from
ESPN to MSNBC to Fox in the past two years. He then added, ``I'm
not trying to steal Jim's thunder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead,'' Gray interjected swiftly. ``This is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, about 15 reporters were pressing in on Gray, who
politely listened to a few questions. He offered virtually the same
response to all: ``I'm just getting ready for Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would address the controversy again, he smiled a bit
more tightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already addressed everything I'm going to address on the
air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
