<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DOES THE LITTLE ATTACKING IN JOINT CAMPAIGN ENCOUNTER WITH
BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS Bradley's position on East Timor in 7th graf; ADDS 3 grafs at
end with Gore staying to answer questions.) (rk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore, in his first televised
encounter with former Sen. Bill Bradley Wednesday night, pointedly
but gently pressed his rival to defend his costly proposals that he
warned would ``shred the social safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a panoply of issues, the two candidates for the
Democratic presidential nomination agreed more than they disagreed
as they appealed to liberal primary voters for stepped up financing
on mental health, special education and environmental measures and
for more stringent laws protecting homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore occasionally disparaged Bradley's stands on health
care, school vouchers and foreign affairs, Bradley refused to be
ruffled or prodded into responding during an hourlong Town
Hall-like forum at Dartmouth College. Instead, Bradley spoke
broadly about his own proposals and _ in an subtle suggestion that
Gore does not offer big ideas _ said the presidency is about ``big
solutions to big problems'' and ``about dreaming and trying to
fulfill those dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the moments when Gore tried to put Bradley on the
defensive, the event was rather amicable. The two rivals, who for
years served together in the Senate, chatted amicably as they sat
side by side on stools and referred to each other as ``Bill'' and
``Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore, confronted by polls in this state showing that
Bradley has a slight edge, sought to undermine his challenger by
criticizing his proposals as excessively costly. The vice president
presented himself, by contrast, as more fiscally responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Before even 10 minutes had passed, Gore condemned Bradley's
health care proposal, asserting that it would cost ``more than the
entire surplus over the next 10 years.'' He said: ``You're going to
shred the social safety net _ so the cost is way excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, Bradley calmly refuted Gore's criticism.
``I want to make one clarification,'' he said, adding, ``I dispute
the cost the cost figure that Al has used.'' And he made no
apologies, saying of his health care plan, ``It's a big problem,
and it needs a big solution to that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore did not stop. Referring to Bradley, he said, ``If the
entire surplus is spent, there's no new money for education.'' He
took a jab at Bradley for supporting school vouchers on a limited
basis. He also questioned Bradley on foreign policy saying, ``I
think we were right to go into East Timor _ Bill disagreed with
that.'' Bradley later said he had agreed with the administration's
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was put on the defensive himself in the first question from
the audience. He found himself forced to defend President Clinton
after the scandals of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the disappointment and anger that you feel toward
President Clinton and I've felt it myself,'' he said. ``I also feel
that the American people want to move on and turn the page and
focus on the future and not the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring Gore's critiques, Bradley pressed his own stands on
issues such as gay rights. He drew perhaps the biggest round of
applause of the evening when he called for changing the 1964 civil
rights act to include homosexuals and for allowing gays to openly
serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think it's important that we can talk about gay
Americans and realize they are our neighbors, our bosses,'' he
said. ``They are no different in many ways than all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, reflecting a looser style on the campaign trail in recent
weeks, was particularly aggressive Wednesday night. He repeatedly
sought to connect with questioners by asking them about their
families. He also jumped off his stool often and strolled toward
the questioners in the audience behind and in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking an informality not customary for the vice president,
Gore acted very much like the insurgent. He asked the audience to
begin questioning him even before the event began _ and he made a
point before the end to announce that would stick around to chat
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was far less aggressive, but he appeared comfortable on
stage. In some ways, his serious, calmer demeanor was more fitting
of an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   The event Wednesday night, billed as a ``town meeting,'' was not
a traditional debate because the candidates did not have an
opportunity to directly question one another. Instead, Gore and
Bradley were quizzed by voters selected in a lottery by the Nelson
A. Rockefeller Center at Dartmouth College.
</P>
<P>
   But it was arguably the most critical hour thus far in the
Democratic competition because it was the highest profile event
featuring Gore and Bradley on the same stage _ and in the state
that will hold the first primary, on Feb. 1. The event, televised
live nationally by CNN and in New Hampshire by WMUR, drew hundreds
of reporters _ the most of any Democratic event of the campaign
season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At several points, Gore sought to show that Bradley was
proposing programs that would spend more money than is available in
the federal surplus. At one point, a woman asked Bradley if he
would work to ensure that the federal government pays its full
share for educating disabled students, as required under law.
Bradley said he would, then added that he would also seek to
finance a scholarship program that would place 60,000 new teachers
into disadvantage areas each year.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore was then asked what he would do to end violence in
schools, he did not answer the question right away, but instead
returned to Bradley's previous remarks. ``If the entire surplus is
spent, then there is no money left over for new initiative on
education,'' Gore said. ``The numbers have to add up.''
</P>
<P>
   On his next question, about the proliferation of nuclear
weapons, Bradley responded to Gore's attack, saying that his
proposals would not eat up the entire surplus. ``We each have our
own experts,'' Bradley said. ``I dispute the cost figure that Al
has used.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that he, like Bradley, did not support legalizing gay
marriages, but would endorse extending the same legal rights to gay
and lesbian partners that are now held by married couples. But he
said he opposed Bradley's idea of expanding the Civil Rights Act of
1964, adding that he thought most gay rights and civil rights
leaders agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   On education, one questioner, a teacher, asked how to change the
school system, saying there was a crisis in the schools in part
because the nation spent money on ``smart bombs'' not on ``smart
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that the most important ingredient in improving the
schools was a spirit and a ``willingness to try things that might
break through.'' But apart from doubling the funding for Head
Start, he was not specific, saying he wanted to create the kind of
spirit that Presidential Franklin D. Roosevelt did in overcoming
the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Asked a similar question, Gore again sought to cast himself as
more fiscally responsible, saying, ``Some problems will require
more money, but it's about standards, accountability and reforms.''
He went on to say that he had been endorsed by the national
teachers unions, but still favored ``tough future testing for new
teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a jab at Bradley, Gore added that one experiment he opposed
was using vouchers, which Bradley has supported.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Gore, the forum got off to an unusual start. Twenty
minutes before the event was scheduled to begin, the two candidates
came onto the stage, adjusting their mikes and getting comfortable
in their wooden stools while the moderators were still backstage.
Suddenly, Gore, playing the master of ceremonies, walked to center
stage and said to the audience, ``Why don't you all ask us some
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   A person in the crowd asked about how the two candidates would
overcome the fiercely partisan relationship between the White House
and Congress. In a lengthy answer that went well beyond the 90
seconds that would be allowed during the actual forum, Gore
recalled how Thomas Jefferson had run what he called a
``terrifically partisan'' campaign in 1800, but then had cordial
relations with Congress after taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Following his answer, Gore turned to Bradley, who looked a
little surprised, and said, ``Bill?'' Bradley followed with a
discussion of how a healthy dose of civility would reduce
partisanship in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the televised session, Bradley left the stage but
Gore stayed in the hall to answer more questions. With sweat
streaming down his face, he was surrounded by scores of people and
answered their questions briskly.
</P>
<P>
   To a man who asked about trade relations with countries accused
of humanitarian abuses, ``We've got to work for a ban on child
labor around the world,'' Gore said. To a biologist who asked about
the teaching of creationism, Gore said: ``I am strongly opposed to
the teaching of creationism in the schools. It is against the
Constitution.'' He said it could be taught in religion classes, but
not in science classes. ``No state should be allowed to do it, no
school district should be allowed to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   After 90 minutes, Gore finally stopped talking and left the
stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
