<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      10-27 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: THE SURPRISE POSSIBILITY OF A DIGNIFIED DEMOCRATIC
RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With DEMS-DEBATE) 
(js) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic presidential candidates on Wednesday
night discussed important, complicated issues in their first joint
event and invited voters to judge them not for campaign jabs but by
their earnest concerns about problems from health care to
homosexuals' rights to campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a secret meeting, scheduled against the fourth
game of the World Series, and so the ratings for the town meeting,
broadcast by WMUR in Manchester, N.H., and nationally by CNN, will
probably be minuscule. The scheduling seemed odd since the
electorate constantly complains to reporters and pollsters that
neither candidates nor news organizations pay attention to issues.
</P>
<P>
   But since Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley
have committed themselves to a series of these meetings, a
dignified campaign for their party's nomination on Wednesday night
became, if not a certainty, then surely a distinct possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's format did not invite detailed discussion, and of
the many issues covered, health care was the subject on which they
came closest to engaging each other directly. In discussing their
health care proposals, Gore said Bradley's was too expensive.
Bradley said that it was not as expensive as Gore thought, but that
``it's a big problem and it needs a big solution.''
</P>
<P>
   For the subject to be examined seriously, Gore's suggestion that
future debates focus on particular topics seemed apt.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates played to a larger perspective than their
questioners, New Hampshire citizens chosen by lot with questions
approved by the broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took a fairly narrow question on energy conservation and
gave a broader answer, saying: ``We, in our country, have a lot of
work to do. Global warming is a real problem. Air pollution is a
real problem. Water pollution is a real problem. We've got to clean
up the toxic waste sites. And you know, a president of the United
States who is committed to cleaning up the environment and fighting
for all of the families that now suffer with asthma or other health
problems because of the dirty environment _ a president can make a
huge difference.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bradley declined an invitation to criticize the Clinton-Gore
administration over its campaign fund-raising, saying merely that
there had been ``irregularities.'' Instead, he said that in order
to change the system, the public had to be aroused and so did civic
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a president that is going to make campaign finance
reform one of the top three or four or five issues,'' he said,
``because he recognizes how it is connected to our ability to
insure more Americans, to our ability to reduce child poverty. From
my perspective there is no issue that is as linked to other issues
as campaign finance reform. That's why it is an imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   And when asked about civil rights for homosexuals, each answered
the specific question and went on to talk about human dignity.
Bradley said homosexuals should be allowed to serve in the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Then he said: ``It's important that we can talk about gay
Americans and realize that they are our neighbors, they're our
bosses. They're no different in many ways than all of us. And we
have to get to a time in America where we can see beneath skin
color, eye shape, or sexual orientation, to the individual because
that is when we are going to be able to achieve the dignity that I
think America stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he opposed same-sex marriages, adding: ``I think that
the story of our country is in part an unfolding of the American
dream with a deeper meaning in each generation. It's a mystery how
Thomas Jefferson could write the words of our Declaration and own
slaves. It's a mystery how the founders in Philadelphia could write
our Constitution and not allow women to vote. But we have taken the
inner meaning and power of our founding documents and the spirit of
America and breathed new life into them in each new generation. And
the time has come for gays and lesbians to be recognized within the
circle of human dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Most joint appearances get interesting when sparks fly.
Wednesday the most intriguing moments came at the end, when each
man was asked to define presidential leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Each answered in terms of past presidents. Gore cited Abraham
Lincoln, who could ``assert values and elevate those values so that
people buy into them and base their decisions on those values.'' He
said Franklin D. Roosevelt was the ``finest example of articulating
a vision _ of how we could get through the Depression and win World
War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bradley cited Jimmy Carter for ``absolute integrity'' and
Woodrow Wilson for an ``ability to see the future before it's
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And in what may have been the most thoughtful comment of the
evening, the former senator cited the last president of the Soviet
Union. He said Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``saw that the world must
change and had the courage to make that change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
