<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Oct. 26,
about criticism of Republican members of Congress by Richard C.
Holbrooke, the United States representative at the United Nations,
over foreign aid and overdue payments to the organization,
misspelled the given name of the spokesman for the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, which has been involved with both issues. He
is Marc Thiessen, not March.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred imprecisely to the penalty on the
United States if it fails to meet a Dec. 31 deadline for payments
to the United Nations. While it will lose its vote in the General
Assembly, it will not formally lose its seat.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HOLBROOKE-LOBBY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Oct. 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Oct.
20, about Mr. Holbrooke's efforts to persuade Congress to make the
overdue payments misidentified the committee headed by
Representative David Dreier, Republican of California. It is the
House Committee on Rules, not the subcommittee on rules and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICH-SCHOOLS-NYT (moved on Monday, Oct. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Oct. 25,
about a study of school choice programs in Michigan misstated the
affiliation of the authors. They are professors at Michigan State
University, not the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-NYT (moved on Monday, Oct. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Oct. 25,
about AT&AMP;T's third-quarter earnings misstated the recent
performance of its consumer long-distance telephone unit. While its
revenue has declined, profit margins have increased recently, not
fallen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
