<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TOURCHAMPIONSHIP-     10-27 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURCHAMPIONSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The sun will rise and shine. Birds will chirp. Squirrels will steal
munchies from unsuspecting fans. And at 8:39 this morning, the
first shot of the 1999 Tour Championship will be fired.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officially, it will start like every other golf tournament
starts. But from that moment on, it will be unlike any event before
it or, hopefully, in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a celebration of Payne Stewart's life and the first tiny
steps of ensuring his memory is there for generations of future
golfers to admire and respect.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly a lot more than mere golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not playing golf, I don't know how else we are able
to honor Payne's life,'' PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem said
Wednesday. ``If we're not playing, what forum can we use to remind
people about Payne and what he was all about?''
</P>
<P>
   The golfing community will come together on the beautiful
dew-draped grounds at Champions Golf Club today with Stewart first
and foremost in everybody's thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Three days have passed since the Learjet in which he was
traveling crashed. There remains an uncomfortable, awkward feeling
throughout the ranks of players, fans and officials at the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But golf will go on. Or, at least, the tournament will.
</P>
<P>
   Today will start what will become a long list of tributes to
Stewart. A brief memorial service on the first tee will be held at
7:45 a.m. Tom Lehman will eulogize Stewart and deliver a prayer. A
lone bagpiper will stroll down the first fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people question whether we should be playing this
tournament,'' said Davis Love III. ``I questioned should we play
golf this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the best thing the tour can do is to show its support for
Payne and his family. And we're going to show our support a lot
better being out here playing than we would have if we were all off
with our own families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got ideas of how this tournament should go. But
the main thing is being together. If we're together, we can do the
right things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne's memory is going to live on through golf. We have to
keep playing. We can shed a lot of light on Payne's life this week
that we couldn't if we didn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's easy. The ceremony this morning figures to be a
teary-eyed affair. And a swell of emotions normally is not the best
way to prepare for a round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   But the players agree the short commemorative service will be
appropriate. Then, after 27 holes are played today, most of the
players at the tournament will board a fleet of chartered aircraft
bound for Orlando, Fla., for a memorial service Friday morning at
the church where Stewart was a member, along with his wife, Tracey,
and their two children.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, the players will return to Houston and the
tournament will resume with 27 holes Saturday and an 18-hole finale
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Coping continues to be the main aspiration of all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels different being here,'' Love said. ``At first, I
really didn't think we should play. And it doesn't feel right when
you're grinding out there on the range. It doesn't feel right when
you're laughing about something in the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``This event is going to have some weird things going on.''
</P>
<P>
   One clear story line is that the players are committed to
playing the event. But Love also wondered just how players will
respond after the trip to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is, once we get to Orlando and see Tracey and the
kids, am I going to want to come back and play golf?'' Love said.
``I don't know. I think that some of the guys may feel that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be very, very difficult to go. I would
be surprised if everybody did go. Going and spending some time with
the family in November and December might be even more important.
Hopefully, we can draw some inspiration from it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Love, who finished third at the Tour Championship the last
time it was at Champions in 1997, believes by being together today,
the players are doing the most therapeutic thing they can do while
also honoring their friend and competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for us to come out and run into guys and hug guys
that need to be hugged and cry with the guys who want to cry,''
Love said. ``Go ahead and get your grieving process started. I
think that's an important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton, the defending champion, echoed Love's thoughts that
the atmosphere at Champions is anything but that of a normal PGA
Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly has been a different feel around here this
week,'' said Sutton, 41, a year younger than Stewart. ``I think the
one thing that this challenges us to think about is how short life
really is. I almost feel like I lost a family member.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year or so, I guess you might say we took some
pride in the fact that we were coming back at the age that we are
at. We were being competitive, and he'd say to me, `Let's win one
for the old guys.' Although Payne and I don't want to admit we are
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton admitted that concentrating on golf won't be the main
issue this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those situations in life where you are asked to
prioritize,'' he said. ``And I think the priority here is not this
golf tournament but what has happened to us as a tour with the loss
of Payne, the loss of a friend and what Tracey and the kids are
going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll all be putting our best foot forward, and there
will be a winner on Sunday night. But there is a greater priority.
So I'm not really worried about how I focus or don't focus this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   This tournament will not be about individuals trying to compete
and be the best this week. It will be about playing for Payne.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a friend gets taken in a tragedy like Payne has been, you
are reminded of how short life really is,'' Sutton said. ``So all
the people you haven't told you love lately, you'd better tell
them. And you'd better live your days like you mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   And for 29 PGA Tour pros, today marks the start of building an
emotional monument to one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne Stewart's memory will live on as a golfer and as a
father,'' Love said. ``And, now, as a legend that was taken too
early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
