<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CORRIDOR TO MIDEAST PEACE  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, October
28:
</P>
<P>
   The opening this week of the first ``safe passage'' corridor
between the Palestinian-ruled Gaza Strip and the other main areas
of Palestinian administration, on the West Bank, may have lacked
the political drama of earlier steps on the road to Middle East
peace. But it was a crucial advance.
</P>
<P>
   Building a lasting peace will require finding ways to meet the
economic needs of the Palestinians without compromising Israeli
security. The corridor, which will allow Palestinians living in
crowded and impoverished Gaza to cross Israel to seek new
opportunities in the more prosperous West Bank, shows how this can
be done. Its long-delayed opening raises hopes that a final peace
agreement can be worked out as early as next year, the goal set by
Israel's Prime Minister, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been much movement on other bargaining issues
between Israel and the Palestinians since both sides embraced that
one-year target in early September. Street clashes have erupted in
Bethlehem, and security officers from both sides confronted each
other in Jerusalem Tuesday over arrangements for protecting
Britain's foreign secretary when he met with Palestinian leaders.
But uneven progress is to be expected as Barak and the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, wrestle with the sensitive remaining issues.
Six months after Barak's election, he has not flagged in his desire
for a speedy completion of the talks. Next week Barak, Arafat and
President Clinton will meet in Norway, and new understandings could
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Under the safe-passage agreement, Palestinians need only a
magnetic travel permit, which is good for a year and looks like a
driver's license, to make unlimited trips between Gaza and the West
Bank. Most will make the 27-mile journey by bus, but private cars
are permitted as well. No stops inside Israel are permitted, all
baggage is X-rayed and the permits are scanned by Israeli and
Palestinian security officers at either end of the corridor to spot
potential terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   First promised four years ago and then revived in the September
peace agreement, the system missed its scheduled starting date but
finally went into operation on Monday. For the million Palestinians
who until now had been virtually trapped in Gaza's jobless economy,
it is the most tangible benefit so far delivered by the Oslo peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
