<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPS-NYT &LR;      10-27 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S PLANE CRASH EVOKES PAINFUL MEMORIES FOR DAVIS LOVE III  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Davis Love III lost his father in a plane crash 11
years ago. When Payne Stewart was killed in a plane crash Monday,
it was a shock to everyone in the golf world, but for Love it
stirred painful memories. It was the sudden loss of another person
who had been dear to him, a Ryder Cup teammate, someone he
respected and admired.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Tour Championship begins Thursday at Champions Golf
Club here, forgive Love if his mind drifts elsewhere, to thoughts
of his father, to thoughts of Stewart. It was a struggle for Love
just to enter the tournament. Until Justin Leonard and Ben Crenshaw
telephoned on Tuesday and persuaded Love to come, he was still
grieving at his home in Georgia, convinced that he wouldn't play
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Love arrived at the course Wednesday morning, still shaken, but
drawing strength from his peers. On Monday, he believed the
tournament should have been canceled. By Wednesday, he had a
different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting at home thinking, `It doesn't seem right to play
golf,''' he said. ``People were questioning if we should play. But
after being here today, it is good to hug the guys that want to be
hugged, and cry with the guys that want to cry. It is part of the
process, and it is good for us to be together. We can shed light on
Payne by playing that we couldn't if we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Love was 24 in 1988 when his father, Davis Love Jr., was killed
in the crash of a small plane near the Jacksonville, Fla., airport.
Love's father was one of the country's most respected golf
instructors, and to this day people approach Love and reminisce
about his father, telling Love how proud his father would have been
to see him having become one of the world's top players.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable moment of Love's career occurred at the 1997
PG.A Championship, when a rainbow appeared over the 18th green at
Winged Foot Country Club as Love prepared to sink the winning putt.
It was like a signal from heaven, but Love was unable to share the
moment with his father face to face. Now, Love is concerned about
how Stewart's two children, 13-year-old Chelsea and 10-year-old
Aaron, will react to life without their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can help Aaron and Chelsea understand eventually
that the memories of their father will be fun,'' Love said. ``He
will live on in golf, but he will live on as a great father.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament schedule has been altered to allow players to
attend Stewart's memorial service Friday morning in Orlando, Fla.
The 29-man field in Houston will play 27 holes both Thursday and
Saturday, and 18 holes on Sunday. Chartered planes to Orlando have
been provided for players, their wives and their caddies on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a brief memorial service Thursday morning on
the first tee here before the tournament begins. Tom Lehman will
lead a prayer, and a single bagpipe player will walk down the first
fairway and play ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how many players from Houston would attend
Friday's service in Orlando, but most of them, including Love, plan
to go.
</P>
<P>
   Players practiced at the course Wednesday and tried to focus on
golf amid many reminders of Stewart, with flags at the course
flying at half-mast and flowers hanging in front of the parking
space that had been reserved for him. Players were uncertain how to
act, or what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This challenges us to think about how short life really is,''
said Hal Sutton, the tournament's defending champion. ``Although
Payne wasn't a family member of mine, I almost feel like I lost a
family member. Payne and I have been competing against each other
for 22 years. Because our names were so close together, we were
always lockered beside one another. When we were parking in
alphabetical order, we were parking beside one another. Every time
I look at his locker this week, it causes distress in my insides.''
</P>
<P>
   Love feels the same way, but he hopes to summon enough strength
to finish the tournament, which has a $5 million purse, with
$900,000 going to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since my dad passed away, I have had a tough time going
to funerals,'' Love said. ``Once I get to Orlando, am I going to
want to come back here? I don't know. Hopefully, we will all get
that inspiration to come back and be ready to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
