<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ABORTION RIGHTS IN PERIL  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Oct. 28:
</P>
<P>
   This week's federal appeals court decision upholding statutory
bans on so-called partial birth abortion in Illinois and Wisconsin
is a serious assault on the reproductive freedom guaranteed women
under Roe vs. Wade. The sharply divided 5-4 opinion by the 7th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals conflicts with the decision only last
month by the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals striking down
similar bans in Nebraska, Arkansas and Iowa. Thus the stage seems
to be set for a Supreme Court showdown on the roiling partial birth
issue. Surely the nation's top court cannot stand aloof when an
anti-abortion statute similar to one found unconstitutionally vague
and burdensome in Iowa is narrowly upheld weeks later in
neighboring Wisconsin, posing a threat to doctors of life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Although billed as narrow prohibitions of a rare late-term
abortion procedure, the proliferating partial birth laws all
contain language that could be read to forbid the abortion
procedures most commonly used before fetal viability, the period in
which the Supreme Court has held that abortions are protected by
the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   To navigate around this problem, the 7th Circuit majority
resorted to gimmickry. First it declared that the laws were not
unconstitutionally vague. Then, in a contradictory move, it issued
``precautionary'' injunctions to forbid enforcement of the statutes
outside what the majority defined as their core prohibition until
state courts have a chance to clarify the statutes through criminal
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in dismissing arguments that the bans place an undue
burden on women's right to choose abortion, the majority brushed
aside reputable medical testimony about the need for a health
exception. They also ignored the real-world impact of the statutes
in deterring physicians from performing abortion procedures that
the majority concede are constitutionally protected. In an
impassioned dissent, the circuit's chief judge, Richard Posner, a
Reagan appointee, wrote, ``What physician would be fool enough or
hero enough to risk a criminal prosecution in order to explore the
precise meaning'' of the broadly worded ban?
</P>
<P>
   The profoundly flawed 7th Circuit decision has at least
crystallized the idea that this fight is about far more than a
single late-term abortion procedure. It is about the continuing
vitality of the Supreme Court's wise decision in Roe to keep
politicians from interfering with what should remain women's
private medical decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-TOURCHAMPIONSHIP-     10-27 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS AT TOUR CHAMPIONSHIP GRIEVE FOR STEWART, HIS FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The roar of jet engines was an eerie sound from the
bright autumn sky above Champions Golf Club Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The ghostly rumble of airplanes flying to and from Houston's
George Bush Intercontinental Airport triggered mass introspection
during the aftermath of Payne Stewart's untimely death.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time U.S. Open champion and five others died Monday
after an accident during a scheduled flight from Orlando, Fla., to
Dallas. The Learjet ran out of fuel after a four-hour flight and
slammed nose-first into a field near Mina, S.D. All on board might
have been dead or unconscious prior to the crash due to a loss of
pressure, government investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about how many times we've all flown on private
airplanes and how many times we've gotten into that private
airplane and didn't know anything about that airplane or anything
about the pilots in that airplane,'' said Hal Sutton, a PGA Tour
member and Stewart's teammate on last month's U.S. Ryder
Cup-winning team. ``I think about how many times I've put my family
into a situation like that, and it's just tragic that Payne had to
be an example for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA considered canceling this week's Tour Championship for
the top 30 players on its money list, commissioner Tim Finchem
said. Davis Love III admitted his reluctance to attend until a
conversation with Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting at home thinking, `It doesn't seem right to play
golf. It doesn't seem right to do anything other than try to do
something for the Stewarts,' '' Love said. ``I really think some
people were questioning should we play. I questioned should we play
golf this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Others shared Love's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to think about playing a tournament,'' John Huston
said. ``It doesn't seem worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Leonard convinced Love that fellowship with one another
would be the beginning of healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for us to come out and run into guys and hug the
guys that want to get hugged and cry with the guys that want to
cry,'' Love said. ``Go ahead and get your grieving process started.
I think that's the important thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``... It's good for us to get out here in our atmosphere where
we're more comfortable doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, 29 men will attempt to navigate 72 holes _ 27 Thursday and
Saturday and 18 on Sunday _ despite heavy hearts for their fallen
friend and his surviving family. There will be no play Friday here
or at the Southern Farm Bureau Classic in Madison, Miss., out of
respect for Stewart's memorial service, scheduled for 11 a.m. EDT
in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Players will wear ribbons in memory of Stewart this week, and
Stewart's family will receive the $80,000 check that the 30th-place
finisher would have earned, Finchem said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a brief memorial service scheduled for 7:45 a.m.
Thursday on the No. 1 tee at Champions Golf Club. Tom Lehman,
another of Stewart's Ryder Cup teammates, will lead the prayer. A
lone bagpiper will walk down the fairway to conclude the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Finchem expects ``in the range of 100 players'' to attend the
service in Orlando, but no one could answer whether all 29 players
scheduled to play at the Tour Championship will attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people _ and I'm one of them _ who don't do
well in situations like that and try to avoid them,'' Love said.
``Ever since my dad passed away, I've had a tough time going to
funerals or services. I think guys are going to have to decide
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my biggest issue is once I get to Orlando and see
(Stewart's wife) Tracey and those kids, am I going to want to come
back here? I don't know. I think that some of the guys may feel
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   No number of birdies or eagles will alleviate the heartache
experienced this week, and that pain will make it difficult for all
to focus and grind through this event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about that all day long, and I think the
only answer that I have to that question is that this is one of
those situations in life where you're asked to prioritize,'' Sutton
said. ``I think the priority here is not this golf tournament, but
what has happened to us as a tour with the loss of Payne, the loss
of a friend and what Tracey and the kids are going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll all be putting our best foot forward, and there
will be a winner on Sunday night, but there is a greater priority.
So, I'm not really worried about how I focus or don't focus this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Stewart and their two children, 13-year-old Chelsea and
10-year-old Aaron, remain the focus of those prayers and thoughts.
Finchem met with Tracey on Tuesday in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will just say, as you might suspect, that she is very
strong,'' Finchem said. ``She is so positive in her love for him
that in some ways that seems to be giving her strength to deal with
it all from my perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Love understands this tragedy better than most. Love's
father, Davis Love Jr., died along with club professionals Jimmy
Hodges and John Popa in a November 1988 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very hard,'' Love said. ``I can't say how Tracey
Stewart feels or Aaron or Chelsea. Everybody handles things
differently, but I think our whole family and anybody that has lost
a loved one or relative or friend in any type of accident knows a
little bit how they're feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton suggested one way that Stewart's friends could remember
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kidded Payne all my life about his knickers, but just as
a tribute to him,'' Sutton said, ``I think it would be kind of neat
if we all wore knickers on Sunday. I don't know if that's possible
or not, but it would be kind of neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's space in the parking lot remains empty, yet
well-wishers have left flowers there in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends of mine at home said, `How are you going to get on an
airplane on Friday? Doesn't that scare you?''' Love said. ``I've
been dealing with that for over 10 years. Sure, you think about it
every time you get on an airplane, but I like Tiger Woods' line.
Something about you can't ride a bike 50 miles to work just because
you were in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a part of our lives, and things happen. I basically just
told my kids, `Hey, we put a lot of faith in machines, and they
break sometimes.' And you know, you can't live your life scared.
And you know, when your time to go is there, sometimes it's not
what we choose. But in the end, somehow it turns out best. Right
now, it's hard for us to see that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
