<HEADLINE>
FORMER TOP EDITOR AT ST. MARTIN'S TAKES JOB WITH TALK MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert B. Wallace, the former editor in chief of St.
Martin's Press who resigned abruptly two days ago, has a new job.
After a breakfast-time wooing Wednesday morning by Tina Brown, the
editor in chief of Talk Magazine, Wallace, a veteran of both ABC
News and Rolling Stone magazine, decided to join Talk as editorial
director.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's resignation came five days after St. Martin's recalled
a biography of George W. Bush, ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and
the Making of an American President'' from bookstores across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing house said that it no longer trusted the author,
J.H. Hatfield, because it learned that he had a criminal record,
which included a conviction 11 years ago for a botched
murder-for-hire scheme targeting Hatfield's then-boss.
</P>
<P>
   Senior executives at St. Martin's, which is owned by
Verlagsgruppe Georg von Holtzbrinck, said that Wallace had
approached John Sargent, the company's chief executive, over the
weekend and said he would resign if Sargent did not ask for the
resignation of Thomas L. Dunne, the editor in chief of the separate
St. Martin's imprint that published the Hatfield book.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said that Wallace had chafed at the fact that he did
not oversee Dunne's fief of nine editorial employees.
</P>
<P>
   In resigning, Wallace said he did not want to be associated with
the Dunne imprint and had been kept out of the loop on the book.
St. Martin's denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said Wednesday he did not want to discuss St. Martin's.
</P>
<P>
   Talk magazine, after the burst of publicity generated by its
first issue and an interview with Hillary Rodham Clinton, has faded
as a topic for the talk-show circuit. Two staff editors, including
the managing editor and the features editor, have left in recent
weeks, citing Ms. Brown's penchant for editing stories until the
last available minute. The magazine is a joint venture of the
Hearst Corp. and Miramax, a subsidiary of the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   A Talk spokeswoman, Hilary Bass, said that the appointment of an
editorial director would not affect the editorial structure of the
magazine, or the responsibilities of the executive editor, David
Kuhn. She said that Kuhn's responsibilities were focused on Talk
Media, a development company of which he is a vice president, and
that Wallace would serve as editorial director for the magazine
alone, a position that addresses the long-term editorial vision of
the magazine and that has been handled thus far by Ms. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace said he was comfortable with the vagaries of a
start-up magazine; as an editor at Rolling Stone, he worked on the
start-ups of Family Life and Men's Journal. However different the
environment at Family Life magazine may be from Ms. Brown's Talk,
Wallace said, ``I understand that growing pains are a part of the
business.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
