<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARILYN-AUCTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDDING SHOWS AUCTION IS AN ICON'S BEST FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS total amount of bids in 2nd graf; ADDS price for famous dress
in 3rd graf) (ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With deep-pocketed bidders competing to outspend one
another, the carefully preserved baubles and treasures of Marilyn
Monroe went up for auction Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at Christie's auction house in Manhattan applauded as
spirited bidding carried the prices of Monroe's belongings into the
stratosphere, well beyond what the auction house had estimated. The
winning bids totaled $5,030,000.
</P>
<P>
   The final item in the sale, the dress she wore at Madison Square
Garden when she sang ``Happy Birthday'' to President Kennedy on May
19, 1962, went for $1.15 million, plus commission.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Adlai E. Stevenson described that show-stopper by
remembering that Monroe was ``dressed in what she calls `skin and
beads.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see the beads,'' Stevenson added.
</P>
<P>
   Auctions have become a popular way to dispose of belongings that
celebrities' heirs no longer want. In the last couple of years,
fans have paid handsomely for the not-necessarily handsome discards
of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, Leonard Bernstein and Academy
Award-winning actresses _ everything from dog-eared sheet music to
furniture to old LPs to grand pianos to necklaces to evening gowns.
</P>
<P>
   The latest indication of how much people will pay for
celebrities' possessions began when Lord Hindlip _ the chairman of
Christie's International and the auctioneer who gaveled away 79
dresses belonging to Diana, princess of Wales, in 1997 _ faced the
standing-room-only crowd Wednesday night in the sale at Rockefeller
Center. Among those in the audience were the actress Stephanie
Seymour, Tony Curtis and Massimo Ferragamo, the chairman of the
Ferragamo shoe company, who wanted to buy back a pair of red
stiletto heels that the company made in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good form of reinvestment,'' said Ferragamo, who said
he wanted the shoes for the company's museum in Florence. ``The
estimate on those shoes was 1,000 times more than what the original
price was. Plus, Marilyn Monroe is an icon for all the reasons I
don't need to go into.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ferragamos got the shoes with a winning bid of $42,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the bidding began, Ferragamo settled into a stiff chair in
the 1,000-seat sale room _ a room filled through a lottery among
would-be bidders whose first purchase was the dictionary-thick
catalog, which cost $85 ($95 by mail). Christie's installed 100
telephone lines to handle prospective buyers who were not in the
room for the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were there clutched copies of the catalog, which
provided a full-color look at what Nancy Valentino, the curator,
called ``a capsule of an American life.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a famous life, and the capsule was well preserved for 37
years in climate-controlled storage rooms. Monroe apparently never
threw anything away, so everything was on sale _ the glittery gowns
and the used furniture. Her dining-room table has the scratches of
a hard life in small apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a major saver,'' Ms. Valentino said. ``The way she
took care of her possessions really reflects her attitude toward
money. She came from a very poor childhood and never forgot that,
as opposed to people who make it big and throw everything out. We
were able to identify stuff from as far back as 1950. Most people
would get rid of it and buy new things.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bidders did not seem to mind the wear and tear on things
Monroe had touched, sat in, played, wore or waved. Lot 7, the blue
jeans she wore while hanging from the side of a train in ``River of
No Return,'' sold for $37,000. A black-and-white photograph of Joe
DiMaggio went for $9,000. Her wedding ring from DiMaggio, a
platinum band with 34 diamonds (one is missing), sold for $700,000,
much more than Christie's estimate of $30,000 to $50,000. Her white
lacquered baby grand piano, which originally belonged to her
mother, Gladys, went for $600,000. (Prices do not include the
auctioneer's commission.)
</P>
<P>
   Christie's had expected her Bible _ with, as the sale catalog
put it, ``a few pencil markings in the text,'' just like her movie
scripts _ to sell for $2,000 to $4,000. It went for $33,000. Her
Union Prayerbook for Jewish Worship sold for $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's had valued the sleeveless Jean Louis cocktail dress
that she wore in ``The Misfits'' at $20,000 to $30,000 _ triple the
estimate for the film's script, by Husband No. 3, Arthur Miller. On
page 20 of the script, where Monroe's character said: ``I didn't
want children. Not with him,'' she penciled in a notation, ``Like
with J.D.'' Christie's speculated that she was referring to Husband
No. 2, DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Time after time, slides flashed on a screen at the front of the
room, showing off another batch of earrings, brooches or keepsakes.
There was her parchment nomination for a Golden Globe Award (for
``Some Like It Hot'' in 1959) sold for $30,000. This was followed
by the statuette she received when she won the award on March 8,
1960, which went for $125,000. Thursday, the compact she was
carrying that night will go on sale. Whoever buys it will also get
her acceptance speech typed on a card that fitted inside (``I'm
moved-thrilled'').
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
