<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MISGUIDED SHELTER REFORM  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Oct. 28:
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers remember vividly when homeless women with children
were sleeping in Grand Central Terminal and violent, mentally ill
people were a regular hazard on the streets. New York City has made
a great deal of progress by coaxing these people into shelters,
where they get help with drug addiction, mental problems and the
domestic calamities that caused their lives to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Giuliani administration is preparing to require all
able-bodied homeless people to work for their shelter, an extension
of the policy of requiring all welfare recipients to work for their
aid. The new policy appears abrupt and unduly punitive to the most
down-and-out residents of the city as cold weather approaches. From
a civic standpoint, it seems self-defeating to drive people onto
the streets, recreating the conditions so rightly deplored just a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter system holds about 7,000 single men and women, many
of them with drug or mental problems or other disabilities, and
about 5,000 families that include about 9,000 children. Some
three-quarters of the shelter residents receive welfare _ which
means that most of them already have workfare jobs. Of those not on
welfare, many work but remain in shelters because they earn too
little money to pay rent.
</P>
<P>
   Under current state policy, welfare recipients lose their
benefits if they fail to meet workfare requirements. The program
now proposed by the Giuliani administration would compound the
penalty by denying the welfare recipient shelter as well. Once a
homeless mother was ejected, child welfare officials could even
remove the children and put them in foster care to keep them off
the streets. However, a state court ruling in 1997 enjoined the
city from seeking foster care for homeless children ``solely based
upon a lack of housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most New Yorkers support the idea of requiring welfare
recipients to work in exchange for benefits. But even supporters of
workfare are startled by a plan that might force homeless people
back onto the streets and allow the city to usurp the role of
parent. Experience has shown that homeless people can get back on
their feet with close guidance, social service help and work skills
that many of them so desperately lack. Any plan that cuts against
this approach is a bad idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
