u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS &LR;      10-27 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY SPAR POLITELY, BUT VP IS CRITICAL OF CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore moved quickly Wednesday
in the first nationally televised joint appearance of the
presidential campaign to distance himself from President Clinton's
White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore's first questioner from the audience only alluded
to the Lewinsky affair, without mentioning Clinton by name, the
vice president jumped in with a specific denunciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the disappointment and anger that you feel toward
President Clinton _ and I felt it myself,'' said Gore, who seemed
to want to get the statement out as early and clearly as possible
to a purely political audience.
</P>
<P>
   But he apparently hoped to get past the problematic period and
its impact on his campaign. ``I also feel that the American people
want to move on and turn the page and focus on the future and not
the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's unexpectedly
strong challenger, sat nearby on a tall stool and did not comment
on the Monica Lewinsky scandal or Gore's response.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley only tepidly engaged when one of his questioners asked
him to comment on the financing of the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were obviously some irregularities that have
been addressed,'' Bradley said, after acknowledging the opening he
had been given with a grinning sideways glance at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the hourlong ``town meeting'' on the Dartmouth College
campus, was a polite, straightforward answer session by the
Democratic contenders to two dozen questions from audience members
who were picked by lottery. The inquiries had been screened by
sponsors CNN, which carried the event live, and WMUR-TV, the main
New Hampshire commercial station.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose uneven campaign had the most at stake, tried to work
in as many policy differences as possible with Bradley, but it was
far from the confrontational approach that has marked several of
the vice president's debates over the years. The sharpest exchanges
were gently couched disagreements over the cost of Bradley's more
comprehensive health-care proposal.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore relied heavily on his capacious memory to throw in
facts and figures, Bradley's emphasis was on a warm empathy to go
with the public policy pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his hip three-button gray-green suit and blue shirt,
was hot, in contrast to the self-assured, laid-back cool of
Bradley, who wore a blue suit typical of the staid attire Gore has
forsaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``My overall sense is that Gore tried a little too hard to
connect,'' said independent political analyst Stuart Rothenberg.
``It was pretty obvious what he was doing, it was so artificial.
Bradley's nonpolitician approach seemed more genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   The session, in Dartmouth's Moore Theater, was the first major
face-off between the two Democratic contenders and comes about
three months before the first major test of the 2000 presidential
campaign, the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24. The New Hampshire primary
is eight days later on Feb 1.
</P>
<P>
   As Bradley steadily moved up on Gore in national polls, and
pulled ahead in New Hampshire surveys, the vice president began to
challenge his former Senate colleague to weekly debates. Earlier,
Gore not only had been disinterested in debates but also refused
even to mention Bradley by name.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley have agreed to at least six more debates before
the New Hampshire primary, some of which will allow a more direct
one-on-one approach that will test the candidates' mettle under
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential contenders, except Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the GOP front-runner, will make a similar joint appearance
Thursday night during a 90-minute national telecast (8-9 p.m. EDT,
on CNN).
</P>
<P>
   Bush's challengers were amazed to learn Wednesday that debate
sponsor WMUR-TV has agreed to give the governor a live solo
interview on the evening news before the GOP engagement, which he
refused to join.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who also ducked a Republican debate in New Hampshire last
week, is skipping Thursday night's event because he said he wanted
to attend a Dallas dinner where his wife, Laura, will be honored by
her alma mater, Southern Methodist University. Bush aides said the
governor is to conduct the interview from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Wednesday in Iowa what he wanted voters to take from
his absence Thursday, Bush said: ``That I love my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor asked
for the interview because, ``he wanted to let the people of New
Hampshire know why he would not be in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic debate came as new polling showed Bradley's lead
in New Hampshire growing as national surveys continued to suggest
he may be more electable over a Republican than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic candidates included a direct appeal to voters in
New Hampshire, historically the site of the first primary of the
quadrennial presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Once a question arose about the cost of Bradley's health-care
plan, each candidate used several pieces of other 90-second answers
to return to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his plan, which guarantees health care to children
and opens a federal medical insurance system to the poor, would
cost $50 billion to $65 billion a year and would be financed by the
growing federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose health-care plan is smaller, moved quickly over a
question about juvenile diabetes to claim Bradley's proposal would
cost $1.2 trillion over 10 years and eat up all the projected
surplus _ leaving no funds to shore up the Medicare system as the
baby boom generation reaches retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost is way excessive,'' Gore said, draping his rejoinder
over two subsequent answers. ``Medicare cannot be an
afterthought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have our own experts,'' Bradley later replied. ``I
dispute the cost figures Al used.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also some subtle differences in how the candidates
handled emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called for homosexuals to be allowed to serve openly in
the military. Even though the next question to Gore was also about
gay rights, he did not defend the Clinton administration's ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy that keeps homosexuals closeted while in
military service _ nor did he repudiate it.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley proposed amending the 1964 Civil Rights Act to include
sexual orientation as a protected category, but Gore pointed out
that civil rights groups favored a less dramatic approach to
provide legal protection for gays.
</P>
<P>
   When asked specifically about recognition of gay marriage, Gore
pointed out that both he and Bradley were opposed to formal state
sanction of same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore said he backed legal protection, such as
contractual rights, for same-sex couples, ``I favor protecting the
institution of marriage as it has been understood, between a man
and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' answers to most of the questions followed
long-scripted responses that are delivered almost daily as they
campaign across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In replying to a question on health maintenance organizations,
Gore turned to one of his favorite campaign trail jokes, about the
HMO administrator, who when he approached the Pearly Gates was told
by St. Peter that he could come in _ but stay only three days.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also chose to deal lightly with a seemingly serious
question about the biggest mistake of his political life by
replying that he had chosen his words poorly when he seemed to
claim he had invented the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley came closest to being challenged on personal motives by
a question asking why he left the Senate in 1996 _ when, as Gore
has suggested, he should have stayed and help fight the Republican
majorities in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time for me to move on,'' said Bradley, who detailed
his subsequent efforts as a professor, businessman and campaign
finance reform advocate. Bradley's campaign strategists are
convinced voters will not hold it against their candidate _ or
anyone's _ for leaving Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
