<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-WITHOUT-BORDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SILICON VALLEY TO SOMALIA: A HELPING HEART THAT SEES NO
BORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RANDY KENNEDY    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You can take your pick of heart-stopping stories to
introduce Joelle Tanguy. This one takes place in Somalia, with the
barrel of an AK-47 resting against her throat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tanguy, 40, is the executive director of the U.S. wing of
Doctors Without Borders _ or Medecins Sans Frontieres _ the
Paris-based humanitarian group that won the Nobel Peace Prize this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But before she took an office job, she was living what Doctors
Without Borders calls the ``blue bag life.'' She had walked away
from a great job in Silicon Valley in 1989, had canceled her lease
and signed on with the group as a logistics specialist. She had no
home, no salary and no possessions beyond what she absolutely
needed, jammed into one of the bright blue duffel bags that have
become the group's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, she was in Mogadishu, where she spent five months. And
as the city began to come apart, with battles mounting between
United Nations peacekeeping troops and Somali clan leaders, it fell
to Ms. Tanguy (pronounced Tahn-GHEE) to pull her people out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closing of the mission was very hard,'' she recalled the
other day in her spartan office on the edge of Manhattan's Garment
District. ``You had local people losing their jobs. And everybody
who lost their jobs there either had a Kalashnikov or an AK-47 or
had a brother who had one.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Labor negotiations in this country can be tough,
but labor negotiations in Somalia were quite interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, as she stared down the Somali worker on the
trigger end of the rifle, she does not remember being exceptionally
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain. It's very unexplainable in a
newspaper,'' she said. ``Probably I was a second, a split-second,
away from being dead. I don't know. But I was feeling very
comfortable there. I didn't believe he would do it. I guess I had
to believe that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason people get angry is because they are afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tanguy is 5 feet tall and speaks softly, with a thick,
lilting French accent. You could almost call her bubbly. So it is
hard to imagine her facing down gunmen or standing her ground in a
room full of angry Somali warlords or building bridges over
refrigerator-sized potholes with planks she carried atop her car.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably also hard to imagine that she can tell these
stories without sounding just like all the battle junkies and
adrenaline addicts she has so often met and hated in the world's
war zones. But it takes coaxing to get her talking about herself,
mostly because she is worried that she will send the wrong message
about Doctors Without Borders.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she is worried that the Nobel Prize citation _ which
called the volunteers ``fearless and self-sacrificing'' _ will send
the same wrong message. And her true message is: no cowboys or
cowgirls need apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want any martyrs or heroes,'' she said. ``When you
walk into a war zone, you have to do it with your brain cells in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tanguy, who grew up in a suburb of Versailles, the daughter
of an aeronautics technician, had no pedigree for this kind of
life. Her parents have never taken an overseas trip, and they
wonder to this day ``how come there was such a spontaneous
generation of a traveler in such a sedentary family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She once or twice saw me on television with the bombing in the
background, my mother did,'' Ms. Tanguy said. ``I was actually for
many years trying to prevent her from knowing where I was. I would
say I was in Kenya when I was in Somalia. I would say I was in
Croatia when I was in Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   But ever since she was 25 and, as a successful Stanford
University business school graduate, took a ``sabbatical'' from her
job, her parents knew she was a lost cause. She left to travel
alone for a couple of months in India. A couple of months turned
into 18, and India turned into most of Asia. When she was asked how
her company felt about such an extended sabbatical, she laughed.
``Oh no, no. I quit. I knew that I would find a job when I came
back. It was such a natural thing to me at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   She loved traveling, but it started to make her feel complacent
the way that making computers and a lot of money did. She visited
Pakistan during the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan, and watched
as the Russians tried to ``how do you say, get the fish by
destroying the fish tank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a tourist, and you would see people who are asking
 &UR; you &LR;  for medicine. They're interested in whether in your backpack
you wouldn't maybe have something to cure them. And you start to
realize, `I'm having a fantastic time, and I'm discovering the
world, but I'm a bit of a useless part of that world.'''
</P>
<P>
   After five years of almost continuous field work for the group,
from Armenia to Zaire to Bosnia, Ms. Tanguy, ``with lots and lots
of hesitation,'' decided that she needed to ``take a sabbatical
from her sabbaticals.'' She accepted the job in New York, where she
coordinates the farflung work of about 120 medical volunteers a
year. She found an apartment in the East Village and signed her
first lease in five years.
</P>
<P>
   She says cryptically that she is still trying to have a personal
life. But if you had called her any time over the last year and a
half, chances are you would not have found her home. She has been
to Kosovo three times, most recently this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't live without having my chance at a blue bag every once
in a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
