<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PLAYER ADVISES COWBOYS' IRVIN TO QUIT NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Nobody around the Dallas Cowboys' Valley Ranch
headquarters would offer career advice to Michael Irvin on
Wednesday. But at the same time, nobody would seem to be surprised
if Michael Irvin retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decision that a lot of players, at some point or
another, have to make ... as to whether or not going out and
playing is worth the risk,'' Troy Aikman said. ``Michael may very
well be faced with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith, the third member of the so-called ``Triplets'' who
formed the cornerstone of the Cowboys' three Super Bowl
championship teams this decade, was asked about his concerns over
the Cowboys wide receiver coming back. Or even if Irvin will come
back after being diagnosed with cervical stenosis _ a narrow spinal
canal that could leave him paralyzed if he takes another hit like
the one that knocked him out of the game at Philadelphia on Oct 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question,'' Smith said. ``Obviously, Michael
definitely needs to do what is best for him and his family. Mike
knows we all want him back. Now he has to figure out whether or not
he wants to go back out and risk (his long-term health), and
whether or not he feels he can play up to his capabilities without
hindering himself mentally, more so than physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Denver, Broncos linebackers coach Frank Bush, given
a diagnosis 13 years ago of the same genetically narrow spinal
canal as Irvin, had four words of advice for the Cowboys' all-time
leading receiver:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut it down, Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, 33, is scheduled to undergo magnetic resonance imaging
for a second time Thursday. Cervical stenosis was first diagnosed
in Irvin when he had an MRI after the injury in Philadelphia. With
a narrow spinal canal, there is no cushion to keep the bone from
putting pressure on the spinal cord when jarred. The condition
increases the potential for a hit similar to the one he suffered
against Philadelphia _ or even one not as severe _ to cause
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who also suffered swelling in his cervical spine after
the hit, has said he will gather as much information as possible.
As to the question of whether to play again, Irvin ``should be able
to make an intelligent decision within the next couple of weeks,''
said his agent, Steve Endicott.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones described Irvin's cervical stenosis,
which is an unchanging condition, as ``more the issue'' than the
swelling at two places in Irvin's spinal column.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also said, ``There's a possibility that there is not going
to be a definitive (medical) conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, no one in the medical field had even tried to
advise Irvin to retire. Irvin was not at Valley Ranch on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who speaks from experience, has been told by spine
specialists that, if trauma is experienced again, calcium build-up
inside the spinal canal of a cervical stenosis patient can make an
already-narrow space even narrower, causing numbness and possible
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told if you have had (numbness) once, the next time can
be even worse,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose promising pro career with the Houston Oilers
abruptly ended in 1986 as a 23-year-old linebacker who had made the
NFL all-rookie team in '85, received four medical opinions _ all
the same. He tried to find a neurosurgeon who would tell him that
it was OK to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush never played again, just as Green Bay cornerback Tim Lewis,
now secondary coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers, never played again
after being given a diagnosis of cervical stenosis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was injured in a 1986 Bears-Packers game on ``Monday Night
Football'', one night after Bush was injured in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In all three cases _ Bush, Lewis and Irvin _ this genetically
narrowed spinal canal, a condition they all share, would not have
been detected if they hadn't received neck injuries that required
examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell (Irvin), `Shut it down, Michael.' That would be
the smart thing to do,'' Bush said. ``He's had a great (12-year)
career. You're not going to play this game forever, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has been examined by a spine specialist in Philadelphia
and in Dallas by Dr. Drew Dossett. He has been encouraged by the
Cowboys to get all the second opinions that he wants, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The MRI taken Thursday will be compared to the MRI taken Oct.
11, in Philadelphia, one day after Irvin was taken by ambulance to
a downtown trauma unit. Irvin lost feeling in his hands and his
legs for more than 15 minutes after the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, now 36, enjoys what he calls ``a normal life'' without any
numbness or any weakness in any of his extremities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I haven't hit anybody, either,'' said Bush, who
remembers reading about Irvin's injury and thinking, `Oh no, I'll
bet he's got what I got.' It's going to be real shaky if he tries
to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Following doctor's advice, Bush gets a checkup on his cervical
spine every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that doctors are afraid of the calcium that can
build up right where the spinal cord and the spinal canal collide,
if you ever get jarred,'' Bush added. ``The calcium is the body's
way of healing, but this calcium can cause numbness. I was told if
you have had it once, it can only be worse the next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cervical stenosis is not life-threatening; it's
lifestyle-threatening if you continue to play. I know Michael Irvin
is considered an old football player, but he's still a young man.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
