<DOCNO> NYT19991027.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0815 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLD-SERIES-ART-     10-27 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLD-SERIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SWEEP SERIES WITH A 4-1 VICTORY OVER THE BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens was traded to the Yankees on the first
day of spring training, and on the last day of the World Series he
became a Yankee. He and his teammates heard all year how the team
wasn't as good as the record-setting Yankees of 1998, but when it
came to achieving any team's ultimate goal _ winning the World
Series _ the Yankees, and Clemens, were every bit as good.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens shut out the Atlanta Braves into the eighth inning on
Wednesday night and the Yankees went on to win, 4-1, at Yankee
Stadium, clinching a four-game sweep and the Yankees' 25th
championship of the century, their third title in four years. The
Yankees' victory on Wednesday night was their 12th straight in the
World Series, tying a record.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera, the Yankees' closer, was named the most valuable
player of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was on the mound in the ninth inning when Atlanta's Keith
Lockhart hit a high pop fly to left field. As soon as the ball went
into the air, the Yankees began moving out of their dugout and
catcher Jorge Posada raised both arms and started rushing toward
the mound. Rivera waited until the ball fell into the mitt of left
fielder Chad Curtis, then raised his arms, turned and fell into the
arms of Posada.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, whose father had passed away earlier in the day,
ran in from right field, pausing to stop at second base and step on
the bag superstitiously before joining his teammates near the
mound. Many of the Yankees appeared to be near tears as they
hugged.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens finished warming up in the bullpen, stepped among the
monuments and pressed his right palm against the bronze image of
Babe Ruth, then walked across the Yankee Stadium field, fans
roaring when they saw him. It was a blustery fall night, the
evening moon was red-orange; this is Clemens' favorite time of
year, and this was the day he had been waiting for, Yankees Manager
Joe Torre said before the game, ``for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before Clemens scaled the mound to start the game, third
baseman Scott Brosius handed him the baseball and said something to
him; then Derek Jeter jogged in, with his perpetual half-grin,
added a few words of wisdom and slapped Clemens on the backside
with his glove. Clemens blew on his clenched right fist to warm his
hand, stood on the mound and stared in for the sign, peering
underneath his cap and over his black glove.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had been conquered by his own adrenaline repeatedly this
year, mostly in the early innings, when he would struggle to throw
strikes. Right away, the lead-off batter, Gerald Williams, fought
Clemens to a full count _ before Clemens fired a low fastball below
Williams' wild swing. Bret Boone grounded out to shortstop, and so
did Chipper Jones. Three up, three down.
</P>
<P>
   This was what the Yankees envisioned when they traded for
Clemens, a pitcher in command. During the regular season, Clemens
averaged 17.7 pitches an inning, but he would average less than 13
an inning in the first five innings on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   All season, Clemens had his catchers provide multiple signs for
him, even when there were no runners on base, and sometimes it
confused them. On Wednesday night, Clemens changed that, and Posada
gave him one sign at a time, rather than three. He kept his
fastball down in the strike zone, mixing in a particularly
hard-breaking split-fingered fastball and an occasional slider.
Great stuff.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz, the Atlanta pitcher, also had great stuff, but the
Yankees, as they do better than anybody else, gnawed at him, taking
pitches, spraying foul balls _ 18 in the first three innings _ and
driving up his pitch count quickly: Smoltz threw 75 pitches in the
first three innings, and reached three-ball counts on 10 of the
first 18 hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had runners at first and second and nobody out in
the second inning and could not score, as Posada, Ricky Ledee and
Brosius all took fastballs over the outside corner. But Chuck
Knoblauch reached first on an infield single to lead off the third,
and Jeter spanked a broken-bat single to right, Knoblauch sprinting
to third and pulling into the base standing. The Yankee Stadium
crowd of 56,752 boomed aloud, and in the Braves' dugout, Atlanta
Manager Bobby Cox could be seen shaking his head slightly; there
was no score, but it felt as if the conclusion was foregone.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill struck out, with Jeter stealing second, and the Braves
intentionally walked Bernie Williams. Bases loaded, one out. Tino
Martinez then turned on a fastball, pulling it hard toward first
base. Ryan Klesko, the Atlanta first baseman, waved his glove at
the ball, which bounded off his wrist and rolled into short right
field. Knoblauch scored and Jeter followed, taking the last steps
toward home plate with his right fist raised. Two batters later,
Posada stroked a single to right, and Williams rambled homeward
safely. The Yankees' lead was three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had found a groove by then, throwing comfortably,
freely. Clemens had been injured while pitching in Boston 12 days
ago, receiving treatment on his lower back after he was knocked out
at the outset of the third inning; teammates believe the reason he
would not disclose he was hurt is that he did not want to appear to
be making an excuse. Whatever ailed him apparently was no longer a
problem, for he blistered the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was keeping his fastball and split-fingered fastball
low, he was getting an unusual number of groundballs: 15 of the
first 21 outs were on grounders, four others were on strikeouts,
and with each subsequent out, the fans at Yankee Stadium began
smelling the championship. Their cheers were louder, and Clemens'
energy increased.
</P>
<P>
   When Brosius rushed in to field a bouncer and then throw to
second nicely for an out, Clemens had pumped a fist and pointed at
Brosius. Keith Lockhart led off the fifth inning and Clemens fell
behind Eddie Perez, three balls and no strikes; this was the one
moment all night when the Braves appeared to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez eventually chopped a grounder to Brosius, who threw to
Knoblauch, who avoided Lockhart's slide and threw perfectly to
first. Clemens screamed aloud _ ``Yeah, Bro!'' _ and stalked around
the mound, jabbing a finger first in the direction of Brosius, and
then Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fell while covering first base with two outs in the
eighth inning, when the runner Walt Weiss ran over his leg, and
Clemens came away limping. But as he tested the injury, Yankees'
fans cheered with each of his throws, louder and louder; they
wanted him to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens surrendered another hit, however, and once Torre emerged
from the dugout to relieve him, the cheers for Clemens began and
they peaked as Torre took the ball from him and sent him to the
dugout with a pat on his back. He had surrendered four hits and
just one run in his seven and two-thirds innings, walking two and
striking out four. Flashbulbs popped, everybody in Yankee Stadium
was standing and roaring and Clemens was moved to take off his cap,
wave both hands. Roger, Roger.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' bullpen took over, one run scoring before Rivera
relieved. The end was in sight now. All year, Clemens heard that he
was not as good as David Wells, maybe not good enough for the
Yankees. But he drove them over that finish line that seemed so
distant so often this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
