<HEADLINE>
OREGON CONSIDERS CHALLENGE IF ASSISTED-SUICIDE LAW IS OVERTURNED
</HEADLINE>
   (With DEATH-CONGRESS) 
(rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Elected officials in Oregon raised the possibility
Wednesday that they would mount a constitutional challenge to any
federal measure that tried to overturn state law allowing
physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Their reaction followed passage in the House of a bill that
would prohibit doctors from prescribing drugs to help terminally
ill patients end their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor views the bill as a roundabout way of undermining
Oregon's law,'' said Jon Coney, a spokesman for Gov. John
Kitzhaber, a Democrat. He said the governor would consider a legal
challenge, which could eventually send the issue to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Some state lawmakers indicated that they might be willing to
back that approach, but wanted to wait to see whether the Senate
and the president go along with the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Such a challenge would appear to be an uphill one. The
constitution generally provides that federal laws supersede those
passed by the states, said David Schuman, Oregon's deputy attorney
general. But he said officials were exploring other means to
involve the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a states'-rights issue,'' Schuman said,
``and the question would be: Is the regulation of the medical
profession something that Congress can do, or is that something
that's reserved for the states?''
</P>
<P>
   The State Senate's majority leader, Gene Derfler, a Republican,
also said Wednesday that he would support a legal challenge.
``Whether you like it or don't like it,'' he said of
physician-assisted suicide, ``the states should have the ability to
make those choices.''
</P>
<P>
   A final decision on any form of legal challenge by the state
would be up to Kitzhaber, a doctor who has done battle with the
federal government before, over the state's strategy, developed in
the early 1990s, to ration some forms of medical treatment to
provide care for more people.
</P>
</TEXT>
