<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PONDER HOW TO ADJUST IF IRVIN DOESN'T RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ As ``Life Without Michael Irvin'' goes into its
third week, Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman is left to
ponder along with everyone else:
</P>
<P>
   What if this isn't temporary?
</P>
<P>
   Can Aikman find the same comfort zone with Raghib ``Rocket''
Ismail as he enjoyed for more than 11 seasons, through three Super
Bowl championships and 14 playoff games with Irvin as his favorite
target?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocket and I have gotten more and more comfortable together,''
Aikman said. ``But Rocket and I probably won't play 11 years
together. And he's a different kind of receiver than Michael. You
tend to have more of that kind of (quarterback-receiver) rapport
with a possession-type guy like Michael, as opposed to a real
big-play threat like Rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has a genetically narrow spinal canal, a condition known
as cervical stenosis, which was detected three weeks ago after he
underwentmagnetic resonance imaging in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith momentarily broke away from the serious nature of
what is being considered a career decision facing Irvin to speak
directly to his fallen teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These eight- and nine-man fronts ain't no joke,'' said Smith,
who has a 2.3-yard average over the past two games. ``You need to
come back. You need to just stand out there on the field. You used
to tell me, `Just stand up back there. Don't get off the field.'
Well, I need you to (draw) some double-coverage again.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith lost his smile, adding, ``On a serious note, Michael has
to do what is best for him and his family. He can only do that by
listening to the advice of the doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Those at Valley Ranch put Irvin's quality of life above
football. But there is a void with Irvin gone, and it's being
experienced now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing pains,'' Aikman called it. ``Clearly, we're better
when Michael is playing. We would like not to be inconsistent, but
when you have a lot of young players you're depending on ... it
lends itself to inconsistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Receivers Jason Tucker, Jeff Ogden and injured Wane McGarity
(who has a dislocated shoulder but should return next month) are
all first- or second-year players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you ever replace a Michael Irvin,'' coach Chan
Gailey said. ``You only hope that others step up and allow you to
diversify to make up for his absence.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
