<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-STEREOHOW-PC-MUSIC-SI     10-27 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEREOHOW-PC-MUSIC-SIDEBAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TURNING YOUR COMPUTER INTO A TURNTABLE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
T urning your desktop PC into a full-blown music jukebox requires
an investment in time, money and at least a small degree of
computer know-how.
<P>
   Yet it's getting easier. For one thing, major computer-makers
are packaging some new home computers with all the software and
hardware you need.
</P>
<P>
   But even if your PC comes with all the components, you still
need to know how to run the jukebox software and where all the
cords and plugs go.
</P>
<P>
   Most computers bought within the past few years should have the
basic hardware _ an audio card, a decent set of speakers, a CD-ROM
drive and a lot of free space on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a Pentium III, 450-megahertz computer to play
MP3s,'' said Michael Robertson, CEO of MP3.com, a Web site that has
become the top Internet portal for digital music news and
information.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some additions that will help you build a deluxe
music machine right on your desktop:
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are downloading songs off the Internet or simply
copying _ a process called ``ripping'' _ music tracks from CDs you
already own, you need digital music software.
</P>
<P>
   The type of program you want depends on your end purpose. Some
programs are better at copying and playing songs, while others are
better at organizing music and transferring tracks to a portable
player. You may need to use more than one program.
</P>
<P>
   In general, though, jukebox software lets you copy songs from a
CD, using the computer's CD-ROM drive, into digital files stored on
your computer's hard drive. Music also can be downloaded from the
Internet, usually already in MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   All jukebox software supports the popular MP3 audio-compression
format, which can squeeze a WAV file used on CDs to about one-10th
of its size by taking out some parts of the audio spectrum not
heard by the human ear. So a four-minute, 50-megabyte song on a CD
will turn into a 4-megabyte MP3 file.
</P>
<P>
   Some jukebox software also supports Microsoft's competing
Windows Media audio compression technology and Liquid Audio Inc.'s
proprietary Liquid Tracks digital audio format.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Converting music can take about 50 to 60 percent of the time
it takes to play the song or CD. But once the songs are in the
computer, you can organize them by genre, such as jazz, rock or
classical. Or you can create a playlist of favorite songs by one
artist, say your favorite ``thin Elvis'' tunes, while skipping
tunes he recorded in his ``fat Elvis'' days.
</P>
<P>
   You also can create playlists of songs to fit your mood _ an
hour's worth of jazz for relaxing, two hours of rock for exercising
or six hours of various genres to play in the background during a
party.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, whose site at www.mp3.com rates and reviews jukebox
software, said MusicMatch Jukebox and RealJukebox are the standouts
of nearly 20 programs available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's seems to be a two-horse race,'' said Robertson, whose
site rates and reviews digital music software.
</P>
<P>
   Both are available for download from those companies' respective
Web sites, www.musicmatch.com and www.realnetworks.com, in free
versions, which can encode songs in ``near CD-quality'' MP3 format,
or enhanced $29.95 versions that allow you to step up to sound
quality that matches that of CDs.
</P>
<P>
   MusicMatch has just begun reaching out to more mainstream
consumers by marketing a shrink-wrapped version at retailers like
CompUSA, Best Buy and Staples. The boxed version also includes a
cable, to connect the computer's sound card to standard RCA jacks
in a stereo amplifier.
</P>
<P>
   Digital music fans like Drew Lynn of Venice, Calif., say they
also use WinAmp, the Internet's most popular MP3-player shareware,
because it is a Windows-based program that organizes songs in the
same way Microsoft Word documents are dragged and dropped into
files.
</P>
<P>
   Other jukebox programs are better at specific tasks. RioPort
Inc.'s Rio Audio Manager, for example, was designed to download
music into the Diamond Rio PMP 500 portable MP3 player. The
company, which spun off this week from S3 Inc., is working to make
the Rio Audio Manager better at organizing music.
</P>
<P>
   And if you fancy yourself an amateur disc jockey, there's a
program called PCDJ PHAT made by a small Florida firm called
VisioSonic Ltd. PCDJ PHAT, which stands for ``Pretty Hot and
Tight,'' allows you to mix songs in the same way a real DJ spins
together songs by hand-spinning and scratching vinyl records on a
turntable.
</P>
<P>
   HARDWARE
</P>
<P>
   Here's where it could get expensive; although, at minimum,
playing back songs on your computer's speaker system is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   A set of new computer speakers and subwoofers costing between
$100 and $200 gives a fuller, richer sound, MP3.com's Robertson
said.
</P>
<P>
   But you also could plug your computer's sound card to your
stereo system with a standard set of RCA cords and a
mini-plug-to-RCA adapter.
</P>
<P>
   This may be easy if you have a computer and stereo system in the
same room. If not, and if you don't want to drill holes in walls, a
Seattle company called X10 Ltd. (www.x10.com) sells an $88 wireless
connector called MP3 Anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Using an FM radio frequency, the MP3 Anywhere beams the music
signal from your PC to your stereo amplifier, and it comes with a
remote control computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   If you find the audio quality not up to CD standards, Creative
Labs Inc. has introduced Sound Blaster Live MP3-Plus. The firm,
based in Milpitas, Calif., says the $99 sound board boosts and
enhances stereo signals from MP3-encoded files. It comes with RCA
output jacks and software that creates mood-setting psychedelic
shapes and colors that move and groove on the computer monitor in
time with the music.
</P>
<P>
   Also, SRS Labs Inc. of Santa Ana, Calif., has introduced WOW
Thing, a $29.95 translucent blue box that enhances high- and
low-audio signals from MP3 and other digital audio files.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get going, it's easy to start filling up your hard
drive with songs, which creates the need for buying a bigger drive.
A few companies have popped up to offer virtual space.
</P>
<P>
   Myplay Inc. of Redwood City, Calif., for example, offers 250
Mbytes of free storage space for MP3 fans, hosted on its server,
plus the ability to listen to music playlists from any
Internet-connected computer and to share music with friends.
</P>
<P>
   New devices eventually may come on the market to make it even
easier to listen to computer songs. Wade Meyercord, chief financial
officer of RioPort Inc., said his company is working with partners
to develop a way to connect stereo systems directly to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something you will see in the not-too-distant future,''
maybe within the year, Meyercord said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
