<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-YANKEES28-     10-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-YANKEES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final game of decade tells the story of the '90s
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major-league baseball in the 1990s came to a fitting
end Wednesday night, with the rich getting richer and the poor
Braves showing the form that made them a team of heartbreak in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees are World Series champions for the third
time in the past four years, while the Atlanta Braves are
disappointed again.
</P>
<P>
   For all the time and energy the Braves have spent making this
such a storied season _ not to mention the previous eight _ it took
them only four games against the Yankees to watch it all swept
away, the last in a 4-1 loss Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees claimed their 25th World Series title overall
_ the best for any sports franchise _ the Braves made their
quickest exit in any of their 18 postseason series this decade and
probably their most painful.
</P>
<P>
   It came with a sick symmetry for John Smoltz, who started Game 7
of the 1991 World Series loss to the Twins. The sting of that loss
seemed innocent enough at the time but would become the Braves'
trademark in the four World Series losses to follow, two now to the
Yankees. The 1995 championship over the Cleveland Indians is the
only consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz pitched well Wednesday night, as Braves starters
seemingly always do in October, and lost, as Braves teams so often
do in October, without much semblance of an offense behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to put up one last offensive fight, the Braves instead
made a hero out of Roger Clemens, the only Yankee pitcher who'd
been vincible this postseason after a season of shortcomings. But
making his first World Series start since he played for the Red Sox
in the 1986 World Series, Clemens dominated the Braves lineup,
allowing only two balls out of the infield through the first seven
innings, on hits bKlesko and Keith Lockhart, and left to a
Yankee Stadium ovation after giving up his first back-to-back hits
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and two strikes against him, Bret Boone chopped a
single between the middle infielders to score the Braves' first run
and cut the lead to 3-1. But the Yankees called on closer Mariano
Rivera, who hadn't allowed a run since July, to retire Chipper
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones worked the count to 2-2, and just missed a double down the
first base line before grounding out to Luis Sojo to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Braves got any more comeback ideas, they got a raw
reminder of where they were and who they were playing when Jim
Leyritz homered off Terry Mulholland with two outs in the bottom of
the eighth. Leyritz, whose Game 4 three-run homer sparked the
Braves World Series collapse against the Yankees in 1996, rekindled
a Yankees fan celebration that's been going on for the better part
of five days.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz's was a fitting story to end the Braves season, as he
embodies so much of what the 1999 Braves were about _ bruised but
rarely beaten. But he and the Braves learned Wednesday night that
the best they could come up with despite their steady stream of
injuries and setbacks this season wasn't near enough against the
best in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Showing the Yankees the three-quarters arm angle he adopted to
pitch with a sore elbow, and the will that registered 95 mph on the
radar gun, Smoltz took his turn at the Yankee lineup, which had
rallied to win in the late innings of Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't bother waiting in this one, using a three-run third
inning to put the heat on the Braves and erase an otherwise
dominating effort from Smoltz, who had a World Series career-high
11 strikeouts in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz had allowed a pair of baserunners with nobody out in the
second inning and escaped by striking out the last three hitters,
all looking.
</P>
<P>
   But he was victimized by some more poor Braves defense an inning
later, as the Yankees used what were scored a couple of infield
hits on grounders off the gloves of Walt Weiss and Ryan Klesko to
mount a three-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch reached on an infield hit to Weiss, and Derek
Jeter lined a single to right and stole second. Smoltz walked
Bernie Williams to load the bases with one out and bring up Tino
Martinez. He grounded a ball toward first, where Klesko had planted
his glove in the dirt and watched the ball hop up and off his arm
into shallow right field, allowing both Knoblauch and Jeter to
score.
</P>
<P>
   Then with two outs and a 3-2 count on Jorge Posada, Smoltz
surrendered a line drive to right for an RBI single and the 3-0
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
