<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEREO-PC-MUSIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW HARDWARE, SOFTWARE TURNS PCS INTO JUKEBOXES  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
M ike Tatum says he's a big music fan, not a computer geek.
<P>
   Yet with a little work and some relatively inexpensive software
and hardware, Tatum has turned his computer into a central
component of his home stereo system.
</P>
<P>
   Tatum, business development director for an Internet startup in
San Francisco, uses ``music jukebox software'' to play and organize
MP3 music files stored on his computer hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   And he bought an $88 wireless transmitter to beam the music from
the computer to his stereo amplifier so he can listen to the songs
on his big speakers instead of his lower-quality PC speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Tatum, 28, exemplifies a fast-growing trend of music fans who
have found that computers have more musical talents than just the
ability to play back CD recordings. The desktop PC in Tatum's San
Francisco apartment has become an all-in-one appliance that can
play, record, store and organize music from a variety of sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late at night when I was doing e-mail or doing work and wanted
to listen to music, I used to have to get up and load a CD, when
all I wanted to do was listen to the MP3s I already had on my
computer,'' Tatum said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tatum plays his MP3s &LR;   &LR; with the same ``full stereo effect''
he has listening to CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the idea of using a personal computer as a stereo
component was popular only among a small but growing Internet
fringe _ techno-savvy high school and college students who were
copying and sharing digital MP3-formatted songs through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But interest in digital music has been shooting to the top of
the charts. ``MP3'' has surpassed ``sex'' as the most-searched term
on the Web. Software-makers have responded with ``music jukebox''
programs, while computer-makers have embraced musical features as a
way to sell computers.
</P>
<P>
   Music-jukebox software evolved from shareware programs that
recorded, played and organized audio files into MP3 or other
digital formats. Jukebox software has become faster and easier to
use and incorporates other features, like support for several
audio-compression formats, links to Internet music databases and
the ability to tune in live Internet radio programming.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hewlett-Packard said it will sell a new line of home
PCs that come with MusicMatch Jukebox software and some free
MP3-formatted songs from Internet site eMusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of being able to try out music and download it is
obviously catching the consumer's eye, and we're just trying to
make it as easy as possible,'' said Tom Anderson, HP home products
marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people will pay for a computer (just because it)
has music capability built in, but I think it will be a
tiebreaker,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp. also has started tuning into the computer
music market with an advertising campaign highlighting new PCs with
preinstalled MusicMatch software and big 37-gigabite hard drives,
which if used only for music would be large enough to store about
10,000 MP3-formatted songs.
</P>
<P>
   One Dell print ad depicts a distraught youth with a messy pile
of CDs at his feet and the tag line: ``I want a PC that will make
my stereo fear for its life.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer-makers hope that music fans will be lured by the
way jukebox software can personalize their music.
</P>
<P>
   Like the colorful, coin-operated 45-rpm and 78-rpm jukeboxes of
old, software jukeboxes can store a large library of music in MP3
or other audio formats. The computer jukebox organizes digital
music files copied from CDs or downloaded from the Internet by
title, artist, genre or other personal preference.
</P>
<P>
   Songs can be played in any order on the computer, burned into a
CD-ROM or transferred into a portable handheld device.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Lynn, a vocalist with a Southern California band called 40
Watt Domain, has culled about 500 favorite tunes from his
collection of 1,000 CDs and converted them into MP3 files stored in
his laptop. Instead of lugging the CDs everywhere, he just brings
the laptop or downloads some favorite tunes into a handheld MP3
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``My computer is functioning as an additional stereo system
right now,'' Lynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn is considering buying an inexpensive computer to act as a
music server. ``Someday, the stereo components are going to have a
connection to a network so you can download and have the stuff go
right into the stereo.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Lynn admits, ``there are a lot of steps you got to go
through, but once you get it dialed in, it doesn't seem like it
takes a lot of time at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worth the hassle, he said, ``to be able to take music where
you want to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
