<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORYCHIPS-PC-PRICES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 RISE IN CHIP PRICES NOT EXPECTED TO HIT PCS  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Will rising memory prices push up the cost of new PCs during the
holiday shopping season?
<P>
   Probably not, most industry watchers say, but discount offers
might be a little less tempting, and users who demand gobs of extra
RAM will pay a lot more than they would have last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that prices for computer memory, after falling
precipitously last year and through the first half of this year,
bounced back this summer and then spiked still further in the wake
of last month's earthquake in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, however, they have begun to settle, and barring
some new natural or man-made disaster, that trend should continue
for the rest of the year, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Dell Computer, the No.1 PC manufacturer in the
U.S. market, warned that higher RAM prices would cut into its
profits for the current quarter. The manufacturer, based in Round
Rock, Texas, also said it would reduce the amount of memory in some
of its standard PC configurations.
</P>
<P>
   That announcement triggered fears that other PC-makers would
either follow suit or raise their prices to compensate for the
higher cost of maintaining their current memory configurations.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, no other major PC-maker has followed Dell's
example, and most observers don't expect them to. Not only have
prices begun to recede from their September highs, but the supply
of RAM chips is expected to increase during the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to Nathan Brookwood, principal analyst at
Insight 64, a technology research firm in Saratoga, the phenomenon
that drove prices down so far prior to this summer's run-up _ an
excess of memory-manufacturing capacity, even in the face of strong
PC sales _ remains.
</P>
<P>
   The problem over the summer, he said, occurred because RAM
prices dropped so far in the first half of the year that memory
manufacturers had little incentive to deliver the product. Some of
them slowed down their production lines or shifted them to other
types of semiconductors that carry higher profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   When PC sales during the summer turned out to exceed
expectations, there was little inventory available to meet the
demand. That caused prices to rise, and that, in turn, persuaded
memory manufacturers to step up production.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry can't increase memory output overnight: It
takes two to three months, Brookwood said, from a ``wafer start'' _
the first step in the production process _ until chips are ready to
ship to customers. So over the summer, even as memory-makers were
stepping up production, the shortage increased.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's earthquake in Taiwan compounded the problem, even
though less than 15 percent of world memory production occurs
there. The semiconductor fabrication plants where memory is made
suffered no structural damage from the temblor, but power was out
for a week, and even after it was restored some machines required
recalibration and repair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, chips made from the extra silicon wafers first
started in the summer are beginning to reach the U.S. market.
That's why prices have settled back in the past few weeks. Because
output is expected to continue increasing this fall, further price
drops are likely, even though PC sales remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   PC vendors, who typically sign three-month contracts with their
RAM suppliers, still may face price increases when renewing these
arrangements, and that creates a continuing temptation either to
reduce the amount of RAM they install as standard equipment or to
raise the prices they charge for their systems.
</P>
<P>
   The latter strategy, however, will be difficult because the PC
market remains intensely competitive, and depending on their
contracts, some manufacturers already are seeing their costs settle
down.
</P>
<P>
   Decreasing standard RAM configurations _ the strategy Dell
adopted _ seems easier, but if it's carried too far, users might
rebel because cutting memory below today's prevailing standard, 64
megabytes, could have a noticeably negative effect on system
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Computers store program code and data they're currently using in
RAM, from which it can be read quickly. When there's no room in
RAM, such data has to be read from the computer's hard drive _ a
much slower process.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the news of Dell's plans to cut standard RAM amounts
elicited a strong response from a little-known organization called
the Council on Computing Power, which this week distributed a press
release warning consumers of the dire effects of reduced RAM,
especially in memory-intensive applications such as digital photo
editing.
</P>
<P>
   The council also noted that Windows 2000, a new Microsoft
operating system for business computers that's now expected to
reach users in February, will require a minimum of 64 megabytes,
and most beta testers have said it really requires 128 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   The Council on Computing Power, though it describes itself as
``a nonprofit organization dedicated to helping consumers get the
most out of their PCs,'` turns out to be a trade organization of
RAM manufacturers _ not exactly an unbiased source on this issue.
But the group bolsters its position _ explained at
www.rammatters.com and www.computingpower.org _ with test data from
Ziff-Davis' Testing and Analysis Group, and most computer experts
agree that the point is well taken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
